<HEADLINE>
BRAIN SURGEON DENIES THAT HE MADE MISTAKES WHILE OPERATING
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By JENNIFER STEINHAUER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Brandishing medical textbooks and x-rays, his voice
choked with anguish, the Staten Island neurosurgeon accused by the
State Department of Health of operating on the wrong side of a
patient's brain and other medical blunders Wednesday night
vehemently denied nearly every allegation made by the department.
</P>
<P>
   In a lengthy interview in a Manhattan coffee shop, Dr. Ehud
Arbit, accompanied by his wife and lawyer, categorically denied
that he committed any of the medical errors cited in a State Health
Department report issued on Monday. He contended that he is the
target of a few disgruntled hospital workers who have systemically
tried to destroy his career for reasons he said he cannot fathom.
</P>
<P>
   ``The atmosphere in our hospital is so poisonous,'' said Arbit,
a thin, soft-spoken man, ``and this kind of malicious behavior has
been exercised not only against me but other doctors as well.''
</P>
<P>
   He added: ``In my opinion, there were no aberrations in any of
these operations.''
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, the state cited Staten Island University Hospital for
40 violations and fined it $80,000 for failing to monitor Arbit.
The fine was the stiffest imposed on a hospital in the state in 15
years.
</P>
<P>
   The state issued its report after interviewing various hospital
workers, outlining five operations that were performed by Arbit
where its investigators concluded serious medical errors were made.
</P>
<P>
   In the most serious case, according to the report, state
investigators found that Arbit failed to take CAT scans into the
operating room where a 54-year-old patient with brain and lung
tumors awaited surgery. The report states that as a result, Arbit
made an incision on the left cerebellum, only to be told by a
physician's assistant that she recalled that the tumor was on the
right side. The report goes on to say that Arbit told the
physician's assistant that he did not see a tumor on the left side,
so he decided to proceed with his work on the right.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an outrageous lie,'' Arbit said, denying any
conversation of the sort with the assistant.
</P>
<P>
   Pointing to the X-ray of the patient, Johnnie Artis, a Staten
Island security guard who died a few days after his operation,
Arbit said that the tumor area covered both sides of the brain, and
added that he had created a sort of door on the back of the
patient's head in which the point of entry was not relevant. To
buttress his point, he referred to a neurology textbook that shows
the procedure as he says it was performed.
</P>
<P>
   In another case, a 21-year-old patient with a brain tumor was
left to bleed excessively, the state said. The doctor switched from
performing a biopsy, which was not proving effective, to brain
surgery, catching other staff members off guard and ill prepared.
Because the anesthesiologist had not anticipated more than a
biopsy, he had not prepared to replace large quantities of blood,
the report said. Arbit countered that he was only an assistant in
the procedure, called in at the last minute by another doctor who
was foundering, and that the bleeding was in fact not excessive.
</P>
<P>
   A third case involved a patient requiring spinal surgery. An
anesthesiologist and a physician's assistant told Health Department
investigators that Arbit's hand slipped and lacerated the patient's
spinal cord, leaving her partly paralyzed, a charge that
particularly outraged Arbit and his wife, Dr. Rose Varon, who put
her head in her hands when discussing the charge.
</P>
<P>
   Not only was the patient not paralyzed, but he did not sever her
cord, Arbit said, and had he done so in that particular type of
surgery, it would have been medically impossible for her to be
paralyzed. ``There was some pressure on the spinal cord,'' he said.
``I never slipped. There was no laceration.''
</P>
<P>
   In another instance, the state found that the doctor and his
staff failed to perform the proper follow-up blood work on a
62-year-old patient, which Arbit said was also unfounded.
</P>
<P>
   In the final case, state investigators said that a patient
complained of weakness in her hands after an operation. A CAT scan
revealed loose screws on a plate that had been implanted in the
patient's spine along the back of the neck, the state noted. Arbit
failed to replace the screws properly, the state said, at one point
asking a representative from a medical equipment company his
opinion on whether he thought the plate was positioned correctly.
</P>
<P>
   While Arbit said that a screw had indeed come lose, he insisted
that he corrected the problem easily and that the patient was no
worse for wear. ``I totally deny asking the assistance of this
gentleman,'' he said in reference to the medical representative,
who are commonly present during operations as technical support.
</P>
<P>
   Arbit said Wednesday night that a physician's assistant and at
least one anesthesiologist have been complaining about him, without
merit, to hospital administrators ever since he arrived at the
hospital. One anesthesiologist, who he would not identify, follows
him around with a chart and takes constant notes, he said
</P>
<P>
   These findings are particularly damaging to Arbit, who was chief
of neurosurgery at Memorial Sloan-Kettering Cancer Center until
1995, when he mistakenly operated on the healthy right side of the
brain of the mother of an Indian movie star. A cancerous tumor had
been found on the left side of her brain. Arbit was fired from
Sloan-Kettering. The state gave him one year's probation in that
case.
</P>
<P>
   Staten Island University Hospital opened its doors to the
doctor, who has written hundreds of articles in peer reviewed
medical journals and is the editor of a textbook on neurosurgery.
His case is being reviewed now by the state's office of
professional conduct.
</P>
<P>
   Arbit's lawyer, Anthony Scher, said Wednesday night: ``The
release by the department of health is ridiculous and distorted and
we believe we will win.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
