<HEADLINE>
SCHOOLS' REPAIR TAB EXPLODES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By CHRIS MOESER AND ROBBIE SHERWOOD  
 c.2000 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
(PHOENIX) - The condition of Arizona's schools is worse than
imagined.
</P>
<P>
   The tab to repair dilapidated schools under the court-mandated
Students FIRST program could hit $1.5 billion, a figure more than
10 times higher than initial estimates.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like finding the house you've saved up for your whole
life is built on a toxic waste dump and you have to clean up the
whole site,'' said Senate Appropriations Chairman Randall Gnant,
R-Scottsdale.
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers have downplayed estimates for school repairs, but many
at the Capitol, including Gnant, have quietly been preparing for a
potential financial crisis. Gnant puts the figure in the $1.5
billion range.
</P>
<P>
   That's quite a leap from Superintendent of Public Instruction
Lisa Graham Keegan's initial $175 million estimate to bring schools
up to minimum standards two years ago. Earlier this year, as
technicians descended on schools to assess the conditions, the
School Facilities Board in charge of the repairs began floating a
projected price tag in the $900 million neighborhood with the
potential to go much higher.
</P>
<P>
   Philip Geiger, executive director of the facilities board,
cautioned that there was no way to tell until the mandated survey
of schools in need comes back, probably in April.
</P>
<P>
   If the price tag is as high as Gnant expects, it will be too
much money to use state-issued revenue bonds, a plan Gov. Jane Hull
favors.
</P>
<P>
   ``That means we're going to have to seek an additional revenue
source,'' Gnant said. ``I don't think anyone in their right mind
would say we can get that out of normal revenues.''
</P>
<P>
   Translation: a tax or some other designated money source.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't see any other way they're going to meet that challenge
even if our economy continues to do well,'' Gnant said. ``The
problem is no one in government likes to look beyond the next
election.''
</P>
<P>
   Officials from the governor's office said they are aware of the
swelling projections and are looking at ways to come up with the
money.
</P>
<P>
   ``The governor understands that it's going to take significant
additional resources to get the job done, and we're looking at a
lot of ways to do that,'' said Jaime Molera, the governor's chief
lobbyist. ``But she's not going to back off her commitment to make
Students FIRST work.''
</P>
<P>
   As for borrowing money to build the schools, Hull disagrees with
Gnant's assessment that it can't work.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bonding for long-term debt is a sensible thing to do,'' Molera
said. ``Any form of government and private corporation would do the
same thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Even if the money were there next year, there would be no way
logistically to pay for all the fixes at once. Instead, the state
would more likely spread the improvements beyond the negotiated
2003 deadline to fix the schools, Gnant said.
</P>
<P>
   But Tim Hogan, an attorney for the Center for Law in the Public
Interest who brought the suit that prompted Students FIRST, warned
against watering down the standards or delaying action. Hogan
believes the school construction standards are already too weak and
called the 2003 deadline ``non-negotiable.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We negotiated and bargained for 2003 _ that was five years out
at the time,'' Hogan said. ``We always told the Legislature this
would be an expensive proposition.''
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers chose to ignore school repairs even though Arizona has
been in a state of sustained prosperity, Hogan said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not like somebody's been trying to conceal this,'' he
said. ``It's been a case of intentionally ignoring it.''
</P>
<P>
   Hogan said the revenue bonding approach makes ``some sense.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Chris Cummiskey, D-central Phoenix, agreed, saying it may
be the only politically feasible way to come up with the money.
``Even the most ardent opponent of bonding will have to reconsider
his position,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Geiger, too, thinks that revenue bonding is an attractive
option. And, despite the potential setbacks, he said Students FIRST
is working better and quicker than the old system.
</P>
<P>
   More than $700 million in new construction has already been
approved through Students FIRST, resulting in 66 schools.
Individual school districts holding bond elections to build the
same number of schools would have taken longer, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The bottom line, Geiger said, is the program must be funded. And
lowering standards to build anything less than adequate schools is
not an option, though he does feel the 2003 deadline is
unreasonable.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're going to have to do some later.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Reach the reporter at Chris.Moeser(at)ArizonaRepublic.com or (602)
444-8069. &QL; 
 &QL; 
The tab to repair dilapidated schools under the court-mandated
Students FIRST program could hit $1.5 billion, a figure more than
10 times higher than initial estimates. &QL;
</P>
