<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: THE RELIGION WARS 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Thursday, March 2:
</P>
<P>
   In 1960, having assured Southern Protestants that he would not
take his orders from the Church of Rome, John F. Kennedy became the
country's first Catholic president, and for the next 20 years
Americans comfortably assumed that sectarianism had been taken off
the political table. In the 1976 campaign, Jimmy Carter added
``born again'' to the political lexicon. But it was not until
Ronald Reagan allied himself with the Christian right in 1980 that
religious leaders began to assert a larger role in American
politics in general and the Republican Party in particular.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. John McCain has now chosen to attack some of those leaders
as ideological despots. Although he has withdrawn an earlier
characterization of them as ``evil,'' he continues to insist that
they are exerting an unhealthy influence on the GOP. Gov. George W.
Bush has fought back, and the result is that religious skirmishing
has assumed a prominence that many voters find disturbing.
</P>
<P>
   As most people now know, the origins of the fight lie in Bush's
visit to Bob Jones University, a reactionary South Carolina
institution that espouses anti-Catholic views and opposes
interracial dating. In the Michigan primary, McCain's campaign
forces used the visit to suggest that Bush was anti-Catholic. When
McCain then delivered his broadside in Virginia against the
religious right, Bush responded that McCain was pitting one
religion against another.
</P>
<P>
   All of which makes it important to keep one's eye on the
essential point _ namely, that McCain is trying to deliver a
message about the religious right that cannot be dismissed, as Bush
is trying to do, as intolerance on McCain's part. The essence of
that message is that the Christian right wing is as much a
political force as a religious movement, and that its leaders have
exercised a bullying influence within the Republican Party. They
also use bloc voting and substantial financial resources to single
out politicians in both parties who do not share their
religion-based views on abortion and school prayer.
</P>
<P>
   In labeling Pat Robertson and Jerry Falwell ``agents of
intolerance,'' McCain is accusing them of using their religious
following as a weapon of political intimidation. And he is saying,
in effect, that he is sick of it. He has seen his party and its
platform held hostage to the religious right in two successive
elections, and he has seen it go down to defeat both times.
</P>
<P>
   So far, this bold argument and the harshness of his language
have hurt McCain among the more conservative Republican voters. He
is hoping that it will help him among independents and in the New
York primary. But even if it does not, he will have made a point to
his fellow party members that badly needed making. The emergence of
the religious right as the enforcers of the GOP has skewed the
party's nomination process and its issues base and eroded the
spirit of tolerance that Americans rightly celebrated after the
1960 election.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
