<HEADER>
A4177 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-MCCAIN-1STLD-WRITETHR     03-02 1186
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCCAIN-1STLD-WRITETHRU-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MCCAIN APOLOGIZES FOR CHARACTERIZING FALWELL AND ROBERTSON AS
FORCES OF EVIL 
</HEADLINE>
   (SUBS to insert 2 new grafs after original 3rd graf to clarify
reason for apology; rewrites 6th graf to pick up insert; rewrites
9th graf for clarification.) 
 (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(af/js) 
 By FRANK BRUNI and ALISON MITCHELL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Under growing fire over his recent attacks on
leaders of the Christian right, Sen. John McCain Wednesay
apologized for remarks he had made the day before in which he
characterized Pat Robertson and the Rev. Jerry Falwell as forces of
evil. He said those remarks were intended as a joke.
</P>
<P>
   Repeating that he ``disagrees with the political message and
tactics'' of Robertson and Falwell, McCain added in a prepared
statement, ``I do not consider them evil, and I regret that my flip
remark may have mistakenly created that impression.''
</P>
<P>
   ``In my campaign,'' he said, ``I often joke about Luke
Skywalker, evil empires and death stars. It was in that vein that I
used the phrase yesterday.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain's apology focused on remarks he had made on his campaign
bus that amplified on a speech he gave on Monday, calling Robertson
and Falwell ``agents of intolerance.''
</P>
<P>
   Talking on the bus the next day, he said: ``To stand up to the
forces of evil, that's my job, and I can't steer the Republican
Party if those two individuals have the influence they have on the
party today.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain issued the apology shortly after his most prominent
supporter on the Christian right, Gary L. Bauer, harshly criticized
him for his recent attacks on Falwell and Robertson, and suggested
that the attacks could cost him the Republican nomination.
</P>
<P>
   Bauer, a staunch opponent of abortion who endorsed McCain after
ending his own candidacy for the presidency, insisted that he was
not withdrawing his endorsement. But, he said in an interview
``there is no way that any candidate can get the presidential
nomination if there is a perception that the candidate is hostile
to voters concerned about the breakdown of values.''
</P>
<P>
   The senator's apology late Wednesday was a clear reflection of a
campaign suddenly on the defensive after losing three contests the
day before to Gov. George W. Bush. And with the race possibly
hanging on the results of next Tuesday's contests in more than a
dozen states, McCain can ill afford to have his campaign consumed
by controversy.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, by contrast Wednesday, was clearly buoyed by his lopsided
victories in Virginia, Washington State and North Dakota, telling
an audience in suburban Atlanta, ``You might notice I walked in
with a little spring in my step.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush said the results in those states brought him, ``a step
closer to ending the Clinton era in Washington, D.C.'' And through
a cross-country campaign day that brought Bush from Georgia to
Missouri to California, he put a heavy emphasis on his signature
theme of education, an issue with broad appeal to the kinds of
moderate voters who will be important in California and New York.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas governor also moved to press his advantage over McCain
in California, announcing that he would participate in a debate
there in person to underscore his commitment to one of the most
critical states in next Tuesday's primary.
</P>
<P>
   But as it has for days in the Republican campaign, religion
continued to occupy a central spot in the day of Bush and McCain.
</P>
<P>
   At a town hall meeting in Riverside Wednesday morning McCain
sought to assure voters that his harsh comments recently about both
Robertson and Falwell were not an indictment of all Christian
conservatives in the Republican Party.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are talking about a couple of individuals,'' McCain said.
``The overwhelming majority of people who are members of the
Christian right are good and decent people. I think they've been
led astray by a couple of individuals that, very frankly, have done
some things which I find reprehensible in American politics.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush continued to hammer McCain for phone calls the senator's
campaign had made to Catholic voters alerting them to Bush's South
Carolina appearance at Bob Jones University, which forbids
interracial dating and whose leaders have espoused anti-Catholic
views.
</P>
<P>
   ``John ought to be ashamed of running that kind of campaign,''
Bush said. ``It's going to backfire on him.''
</P>
<P>
   In a sign that the Bush campaign is still working to minimize
any damage done with Catholic voters by McCain's broadsides, the
crowd sitting as a backdrop to Bush Wednesday morning near Atlanta
included a woman prominently at the governor's side who held a
placard saying, ``I'm Catholic and I'm for Bush.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush took the opportunity to criticize the leader of the Nation
of Islam, Louis Farrakhan, but not the leaders of the religious
right whom McCain, in a fiery speech Monday, had branded along with
Farrakhan as ``agents of intolerance.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Louis Farrakhan preaches hate,'' Bush said. ``Louis Farrakhan
is a hateful person.'' He said Farrakhan preached an ``anti-Semitic
message.''
</P>
<P>
   Bauer also talked about Farrakhan in criticizing McCain, saying
it was wrong for the senator to mention him and the Rev. Al
Sharpton in his criticism of Robertson and Falwell.
</P>
<P>
   ``The comparison of these respected conservative leaders to the
demagogic race-baiter Al Sharpton and the anti-Semitic Louis
Farrakhan was unfounded and unwise,'' Bauer said. ``Such rhetoric
serves only to divide the party and plays into the hands of the
liberal elite to falsely depict Christian conservatives as
intolerant extremists.''
</P>
<P>
   Bauer's criticism of McCain Wednesday came as somewhat of a
surprise, given the fact that he stood near McCain in Virginia
Beach on Monday as he delivered the speech in which he attacked
Robertson and Falwell. And he later commented on the speech without
distancing himself from it.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, he explained: ``I didn't get a chance to see that
speech until it was too late to do anything about it. It had
already been passed out to the press.'' McCain's aides challenged
the statement, saying that Bauer not only reviewed the speech in
advance but added a paragraph to it.
</P>
<P>
   Bauer said he was not pressured by fellow Christian
conservatives to disavow McCain's remarks. ``I just think that
Senator McCain's larger message, which is pro-life and pro-family,
is getting lost in this controversy between him and Robertson.''
</P>
<P>
   Talking with reporters on his campaign bus Wednesday afternoon,
McCain insisted that he stood by the speech he gave on Monday and
that he apologized only for his remarks suggesting that Falwell and
Robertson were having an ``evil influence'' on the Republican
Party.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not changing any of my speech,'' he said. ``I'm sure that
Gary and I will have an understanding about the speech and what was
intended and what was intended by my remarks yesterday. It was a
light-hearted attempt at humor and sometimes it isn't interpreted
that way.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
