<SLUG> BC-BKC-OKLAHOMA-TEX-A&AMP;M-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OKLAHOMA STARTS FAST, EASES BY TEXAS A&AMP;M
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MIKE JONES 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLLEGE STATION _ Having fallen prey to unforeseen events here
last season, Oklahoma need not have been warned about possible
pitfalls that await the inattentive in the confines of Reed Arena,
the Aggies' January ambush of Oklahoma State notwithstanding.
</P>
<P>
   But the Sooners could have taken Texas A&AMP;M with one eye open
last night.
</P>
<P>
   Holding as much as a 21-point lead in the first half and
surviving a mini-Aggies run in the second by hauling out their
3-point arsenal, the 21st-ranked Sooners (23-5) easily handled A&AMP;M,
77-59. The victory kept them in the running for a first-round bye
in next week's Big 12 tournament at 11-4, a game up on Kansas
(10-5) and Missouri (10-5), who play each other in the league's
last regular-season game in Lawrence, Kan., on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were definitely concerned about this game,'' OU forward
Eduardo Najera said. ``We knew they were going to be ready. But if
we were also ready I knew we would win this game. That's why I
wanted to get us a big lead in the first half so we could relax and
have some fun.''
</P>
<P>
   Najera was a workhorse in the first half. When coach Kelvin
Sampson called him to the bench for a breather with 1:40 left after
he had hit three consecutive mid-range jump shots, he had 17
points. So did the Aggies.
</P>
<P>
   ``Eduardo kind of took the game over,'' said A&AMP;M center Aaron
Jack, back in the lineup after missing the Texas game on Saturday
with a viral infection. ``But he's a great player and that's what
great players are supposed to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Najera finished with 20 points. Bernard King led the Aggies
(7-19, 3-12) with 15.
</P>
<P>
   A&AMP;M caused the Sooners some concern, turning up their defensive
pressure and cutting a 40-19 halftime lead to 51-41 when Jerald
Brown hit a 3-pointer with 11:55 to play. But with the Aggies in a
zone, Sampson sent Tim Heskett into the game. He hit a 3-pointer
from the left corner to stop an 8-0 run and after an Aggies bucket,
guard J.R. Raymond followed suit. When Heskett sank his second trey
in less than four minutes, Oklahoma was back up, 60-45, and A&AMP;M
never again threatened.
</P>
<P>
   The Sooners now turn their attention to Saturday's Bedlam II
match at Oklahoma State.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got to get back, relax and then get focused because
that's a big game for us,'' Najera said. ``We have to go in there
with a win mentality.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
