<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: ANOTHER DAY OF GUN VIOLENCE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Subs for rewriting) (sw) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Thursday, March 2:
</P>
<P>
   It just keeps getting more senseless. On Tuesday a first grader
in Michigan shot and killed a 6-year-old classmate. On Wednesday an
adult gunman in Pennsylvania shot a worker at his apartment
building, then fired on customers at two fast-food restaurants,
killing two people and wounding three. He fled into a nearby office
building before finally surrendering. These new eruptions of
violence, coming just a day apart, only confirm the urgency of
solving the nation's gun problem.
</P>
<P>
   Gun tragedies have a devastating effect on individuals, families
and communities. But in a larger sense the entire nation is
victimized when parents must fear little children toting revolvers
to elementary school to shoot other children, and a routine lunch
trip to McDonald's can end in bloodshed when a deranged person with
a gun goes on a rampage.
</P>
<P>
   The need for stronger gun control laws has never been plainer.
But as President Clinton aptly said on Wednesday, the nation's
elected leaders have not done all they can ``to keep these guns
away from criminals and children.'' He called on Congress to
approve gun safety legislation languishing in a House-Senate
conference committee before lawmakers begin a long recess at the
end of next week. In light of this week's events, it hardly seems
an unreasonable request.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
