<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-BRADLEY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORE, BRADLEY TONE DOWN SNIPING IN DEBATE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By CRAGG HINES 
and BENNETT ROTH 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ In what was probably the final debate of the fight
for the Democratic presidential nomination, Al Gore and Bill
Bradley adopted a newly conciliatory tone Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   They attempted to paint a bright picture of how they would be a
more tolerant chief executive than either major Republican
contender.
</P>
<P>
   The face-off came as Bradley, winless against Gore, faces
questions about how long he realistically can remain in the race.
Bradley has pledged to stay in the fight at least through the mass
of primaries coming Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Few delegates have been selected so far, Bradley said in the
debate, and Tuesday ``is takeoff day for me.'' Although the two
Democrats in earlier debates had sniped and snapped at each other,
they seemed to find an unusual amount of common ground in support
of gay rights, judicial activism and the need for federal oversight
of police misconduct.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley and Gore dueled briefly again about how conservative the
vice president's record was as a member of the House and Senate.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has evolved. I'm glad he has evolved,'' Bradley said of
Gore's move to firmly support abortion rights. But, Bradley said,
Gore's seeming inability to deal with past votes and positions ``is
relevant to consideration'' by voters.
</P>
<P>
   Both Bradley and Gore praised recent criticism from Republican
contender John McCain, a senator from Arizona, of religious right
leaders Pat Robertson and Jerry Falwell, who are supporters of the
Republican front-runner, Gov. George W. Bush of Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``The far right has gone too far time after time after time on
social issues and has tried to dominate this country with their
particular viewpoint,'' Bradley said. ``I think it's important to
resist that. I've always resisted that. ... I've never voted in
ways that they wanted. And I would be very emphatic in saying that
religion should not be a part of politics.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore said he agreed with McCain on issues such as campaign
finance reform and reigning in ``big tobacco,'' but the vice
president noted that McCain and Bush oppose most abortion rights
and ``neither had the guts to speak out against the Confederate
flag'' atop the South Carolina statehouse.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Republican party today is in the midst of an identity
crisis,'' Gore said with quiet glee. ``They're trying to figure out
who they are.''
</P>
<P>
   Immediately before the debate, Gore won the endorsement of the
Rev. Jesse Jackson, a civil rights leader who twice has sought the
Democratic nomination. Speaking to reporters at the debate media
center, Jackson, with Bradley in mind, said: ``At some point we
have to fold our tents and create a bigger tent.'' Jackson said the
vice president, a Tennessean, had ``steadfastly shunned the
demagoguery in the South'' arising from the flying of the
Confederate flag over South Carolina's capitol.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley lost to the vice president in the Iowa caucuses, New
Hampshire primary and, on Tuesday, in a nonbinding presidential
preference vote in Washington state that the former senator had
hoped would resuscitate his campaign. Instead, he lost to Gore by a
margin of about 3-1.
</P>
<P>
   Gore made it clear that he would let Bradley make up his own
mind about leaving the race.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm talking to the voters, not to him,'' a sweat-soaked Gore
called out as he jogged along a Pacific Ocean beach in Santa Monica
with daughter Kristin.
</P>
<P>
   Despite their belief that the nomination effectively will soon
be Gore's, the vice president's top advisers have cautioned him
against appearing too confident or cocky. Gore and Bradley left
immediately after the debate for overnight flights to New York, the
second-biggest prize in the mass of primaries on Tuesday. Answering
questions from undecided California voters, Internet users and
reporters, the two Democratic contenders covered a range of issues:
</P>
<P>
   _ Gore said he would nominate Supreme Court justices who see the
Constitution as ``a living and breathing document.'' Bradley said
his nominees could not be ``someone locked into an original
interpretation.'' Both answers would put them far to the left of
either Bush or McCain.
</P>
<P>
   _ Both, although opposing same-sex marriages, criticized a
measure that will be on the California ballot Tuesday to define
marriage as the union of a man and woman. Both Democrats supported
domestic-partnership arrangements in which same-sex couples could
have legal rights of married people. Gore called the initiative
facing voters a ``mean-spirited wedge.''
</P>
<P>
   _ In the wake of police corruption cases in Los Angeles and
brutality incidents in New York, both Democrats expressed support
for an increased federal role in overseeing local law enforcement
agencies.
</P>
<P>
   In the wake of Bradley's defeat in Washington, a state where he
had put in almost a full week of campaign time and poured tens of
thousands of dollars into television commercials, his aides engaged
in the rankest rationalizations. Bradley spokesman Eric Hauser said
that while the campaign was ``a little disappointed,'' he contended
that ``the energy, the enthusiasm'' from Washington state would
``carry us forward very assertively'' into the busiest week of the
primary season.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley, a former professional basketball star, put on his game
face as he prepared for the debate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mark Twain put it best when he said, `Reports of my demise are
greatly exaggerated,''' Bradley said. ``We're going on to March 7.
We're moving fast.''
</P>
<P>
   He promised a spirited campaign in several states with primaries
next week, including New York, Massachusetts and Maryland. But Sen.
Bob Kerrey, a Nebraska Democrat and one of Bradley's few
congressional supporters, said that beneath the political spin his
former colleague was realistic and ``knows that it's going to take
a miracle for him to win.''
</P>
<P>
   Another ranking adviser was quoted as saying that Bradley would
withdraw from the race if he fares poorly again Tuesday. Bradley's
outlook for several of those contests, including the biggest, in
California, is not much better. A new Los Angeles Times poll of
likely Democratic voters in the Golden State showed Bradley
trailing not only Gore 54-11 percent but also lagging McCain, who
had 20 percent support in the Democratic sampling, and tied with
Bush, who also drew 11 percent support from Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   In a bid to prove that he was serious about pressing on for at
least another week, Bradley began to air four new television
commercials in a snappier, more urgent black-and-white format. He
also taped a five-minute national spot to air Thursday night on
CBS. A new Spanish-language ad targeted Hispanic voters in
California.
</P>
<P>
   The California debate, broadcast nationally by co-sponsor CNN
and held in an auditorium at the headquarters of co-sponsor Los
Angeles Times, came eight days after Gore and Bradley engaged in
the most raucous face-off of either party during the presidential
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   From the stage of the Apollo Theater in New York, the two
Democrats traded political jabs. To a continuing chorus of boos and
catcalls from the audience in the venerable theater in the heart of
Harlem, Bradley said Gore was a conservative when it came to
abortion rights, gun control and federal tax treatment for
segregated private schools, and the vice president responded by
contending Bradley was ``desperate'' and willing to divide the
party for personal political gain.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY XXXX &QL; 
$$$
</P>
</TEXT>
