<HEADER>
A4185 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u p BC-DEMOCRATS-DEBATE-BOS &LR;      03-02 1292
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEMOCRATS-DEBATE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRADLEY, GORE HOLD GENTLEMANLY DEBATE IN CALIFORNIA
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB HOHLER AND SUSAN MILLIGAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Vice President Al Gore and former New Jersey Bill
Bradley Wednesday night waged their final debate before the crucial
round of Democratic primaries Tuesday with a breezy give-and-take
that belied the underlying tension between them and the enormity of
the stakes.
</P>
<P>
   Gore and Bradley resisted nearly every opportunity over 90
minutes to criticize each other on the hot-button issues that
sparked fiery skirmishes between them in earlier debates.
</P>
<P>
   The turnabout came as Gore entered the forum with a large lead
in the polls after weeks of brutal infighting. The debate's mild
tone denied Bradley the ``miracle'' breakthrough that his top
supporters predicted he would need to help keep his wounded
campaign alive past Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   With Gore wary of appearing overconfident or condescending and
Bradley striving not to look desperate or petty, the two spent
almost as much time jabbing themselves as they did each other.
</P>
<P>
   Gore even sought the high ground when confronted with a question
that is reverberating within the Democratic Party: Should Bradley,
winless in the first four contests and apparently fading fast, pull
out of the race?
</P>
<P>
   With apparent disdain, Gore replied, ``One of the things Senator
Bradley and I agree on . . . is that we prefer to get questions on
substance rather than process. The purpose of a campaign is also
for us . . . to have an ennobling, educational, revealing
discussion about all of the problems we face.''
</P>
<P>
   Bradley, for his part, said only 250,000 voters have
participated in the Democratic contest to date, compared to the 8.5
million who will be eligible to vote next week. And he insisted he
will continue fighting at least through Tuesday, which he called
``the kickoff day for me.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore scored a coup before the debate when the Rev. Jesse L.
Jackson, entered the media center to announce his endorsement of
the vice president. Jackson called Gore ``the most qualified and
experienced candidate in a generation.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson's endorsement was another blow to Bradley, who argues he
is more attuned to minority concerns than Gore and better suited to
address them.
</P>
<P>
   The debate, hosted by the Los Angeles Times and CNN, was the
ninth between the candidates and provided viewers who will cast
ballots in 16 Democratic contests Tuesday the last chance to
examine the candidates through an unfiltered lens.
</P>
<P>
   But rather than savaging each other, as they did in their recent
showdown at the Apollo Theater in Harlem and previous forums, the
two devoted considerable time to praising their wives, discussing
Internet technology and teaming up for attacks on the Republican
presidential candidates.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the candidates took some of the harshest shots of the
campaign at themselves. Bradley, in describing the role his wife,
Ernestine, would play if he were president, cited her willingness
to challenge him, particulary when he is performing below her
expectations.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's the one who tells me, you're terrible,'' Bradley said.
``She's told me that a few times in this campaign, I must say.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore, who has been widely ridiculed for once suggesting that he
invented the Internet, poked fun at himself for the misstatement.
And Bradley refrained from piling on.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was waiting in the campaign to make that joke about you
inventing the Internet,'' he said. ``I'm glad you did it and not
me.''
</P>
<P>
   And Gore and Bradley, time and again, professed their agreement
with each other's positions rather than strive to point out
distinctions.
</P>
<P>
   Only near the end of the debate did the two men criticize each
other, and then only after they were pointedly provoked into doing
so by one of the panelists.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about his past attacks on Gore's voting record on gun
control and abortion, Bradley took the bait, though he kept his
comments tame.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you run for president, your record is important. And that
is precisely what I was saying when I pointed out those aspects,''
Bradely said. ``He has evolved. I'm glad he has evolved.''
</P>
<P>
   But ``if you are consistent on matters of principle, that is
relevant,'' the former senator added.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley has accused Gore of opposing legal abortion, because he
voted as a congressman against Medicaid funding for abortions for
poor women and writing to a local constituent that abortion is
``arguably the taking of a human life.''
</P>
<P>
   Bradley also has gone after Gore for being weaker, in the past,
on gun control.
</P>
<P>
   Gore stated simply that he is in favor of abortion rights and
wants to ``take on'' the National Rifle Association.
</P>
<P>
   But Bradley kept going and attacked Gore for voting ``five
times'' for tax-exempt status for schools that discriminate.
</P>
<P>
   That comment made Gore bristle for the first time during the
debate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sorry you brought that up, because I thought we disposed
of it in the last debate,'' said an irritated Gore. The vice
president insisted he had voted against an amendment that backed
quotas, and ``I oppose quotas,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Gore has been using the issue of Bob Jones University, which
does not allow interracial dating, to paint the Republican
candidates as weak on civil rights. The vice president was clearly
annoyed that the issue had been turned against him, if only very
briefly.
</P>
<P>
   The two spent most of the debate, however, agreeing with each
others' opinions. Both said they opposed Proposition 22 in
California, a measure that would specifically outlaw gay marriages.
</P>
<P>
   Both Gore and Bradley said they do not support gay marriage in
the traditional legal sense, but do back a ``domestic partnership''
law.
</P>
<P>
   Both candidates expressed some approval of comments made by
Republican contender John McCain, a senator from Arizona, railing
against the preachings of right-wing Christian leaders.
</P>
<P>
   ``The far right has gone too far. Religion should not be part of
politics,'' Bradely said. Gore was more measured in his comments.
``I agree with the speech as far as it went,'' he said of McCain's
statements.
</P>
<P>
   Both debaters voiced concern for the plight of disabled people
and financially strapped members of the military. Both defended
their separate meetings with the Rev. Al Sharpton, noting that the
New York clergyman is seen as a leader by many blacks.
</P>
<P>
   Both men also said they would appoint Supreme Court justices who
would interpret the Constitution as a living, breathing document,
implying that they would name jurists who support the Roe v. Wade
decision legalizing abortion rights.
</P>
<P>
   Gore pointed out that Kate Michelman, president of the National
Abortion and Reproductive Rights Action League, was in the
audience. The group endorsed Gore, much to the frustration of the
Bradley campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier Wednesday, Bradley shrugged off his dismal showing in
the Washington state primary, saying, ``Mark Twain put it best when
he said, `Reports of my demise are greatly exaggerated.' We're
going on to March 7, and we're moving fast.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore had an unusually light schedule, heading to the beach in
the morning for a leisurely jog with his daughter Kristin. Asked if
he thought Bradley should withdraw from the race, Gore said, ``I'm
campaigning in California. I'm talking to voters, not to him.''
</P>
<P>
   Bradley limited his public schedule to a stop at a health center
in a predominantly Latino neighborhood, where he renewed his call
for a comprehensive overhaul of the health care system that would
provide access to coverage for every US citizen. Of the 44 million
Americans without health coverage, he said, 11 million are
Hispanic.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-02-00 0021EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
