<HEADER>
A4193 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-REPUBS-TV-NYT &LR;      03-02 0764
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REPUBS-TV-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH MUFFS LETTERMAN'S LATE NIGHT OPPORTUNITY 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By CARYN JAMES   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ When Gov. George W. Bush showed up by satellite on
``Late Show with David Letterman'' on Wednesday night, he was
smiling, good-natured, prepared to laugh at himself. Imagine, then,
what a comic flop he had to be to elicit groans and boos from the
audience, as he did with jokes about Letterman's recent heart
surgery.
</P>
<P>
   With Letterman sitting on stage in New York and Bush in a
conference room in St. Louis, there was a slight satellite delay
between the questions and answers, which had the effect of making
Bush look a little slow on the uptake. That was the last thing he
needed, since the point of the appearance was to send the message:
I am not a pinhead (to use one of the typical Letterman
descriptions of him).
</P>
<P>
   Late-night shows allow candidates to present their most casual,
engaging guises, and are so important to campaigns that while the
Letterman show had Bush on Wednesday night, Sen. John McCain
appeared on ``The Tonight Show with Jay Leno'' and both
overshadowed a Democratic debate on CNN.
</P>
<P>
   But the Letterman show offers the biggest risks and rewards,
because appearances are preceded by weeks of barbs, and a guest
shot can be transforming. Bush's job was to make his image seem
smarter than usual. That didn't happen.
</P>
<P>
   His approach sometimes eerily echoed that in the early debates.
He was slow to ad-lib; at times he offered one-word answers then
stared blankly into the camera. (Letterman asked if he was tired of
jokes about flunking a pop quiz about world leaders. ``Nah,'' said
the governor, and stared.) He forced in canned lines. He only had
five minutes and obviously had a few jokes he was determined to
cram in.
</P>
<P>
   Other lines sounded as if they came off the top of his head, and
they were scary. When Letterman asked exactly what Bush meant by
his often repeated phrase, ``I'm a uniter not a divider,'' the
governor said, ``That means when it comes time to sew up your chest
cavity, we use stitches as opposed to opening it up.'' The audience
booed; Letterman looked baffled; the camera turned to his producer,
Rob Burnett, who shrugged as if to say, ``I don't know what it
means either.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush understood the ground rules: that he was there to laugh at
himself. So he forced in a self-deprecating gimmick. ``I've morphed
on your show from a boob to a dweeb,'' he said, and created a
priceless photo by holding up a T-shirt that read ``Dweebs for
Bush,'' which he said he would like to give Letterman in person.
</P>
<P>
   A face-to-face showdown would have been better all around. There
was so little dynamism in the satellite conversation that at one
point Letterman was looking down at the desk.
</P>
<P>
   And though you can't blame the satellite for everything, the
delay did almost bury Bush's one sharp comeback. ``Who likes
interns better, you or John McCain?'' Letterman asked. It was hard
to hear Bush answer, ``It's the wrong party.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush will get some second chances soon. He will appear in person
on some future Letterman show, and is to be on ``The Tonight Show''
on Monday. As McCain's appearance on ``Tonight'' proved, where
Letterman and his audience appreciate self-mockery, Leno helps a
guest puff himself up. He introduced his guest as ``Arizona senator
and a war hero.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, voters can only hope both candidates get better writers
before a State of the Union address comes their way. McCain did a
bad Leno impression, joked about sleeping in the lucky shoes that
helped him win in New Hampshire, and said he and Jesse Ventura had
something in common because McCain wore a feather boa around the
Senate. He did get in the serious information that he will not join
the Reform Party. And he mentioned the ``iron triangle'' of
Washington power he is fighting. That phrase is familiar from news
coverage, but may be fresh to ``Tonight'' viewers, which is part of
the purpose of such appearances. How well such information
registers is a different question.
</P>
<P>
   In the ``Tonight'' manner, McCain was smooth and congenial. The
actress Neve Campbell, the first guest, had talked about her
bunions; McCain expressed concern and plugged universal health
care.
</P>
<P>
   On the riskier Letterman show, Bush went up in flames. But the
important thing was that he showed up at all. He proved he could
take a joke and that he knew, in response to the Letterman pop
quiz, who is president of the hair club for men. With the media
stakes so high, only a loser would have ducked the question.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
