<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-02 00:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4206 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a BC-DEBATE-DEMOCRATS_SFCH     03-02 1026
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEBATE-DEMOCRATS_SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 GORE, BRADLEY ENGAGE IN LOVEFEST IN LATEST DEBATE  &HT;     By JOHN WILDERMUTH and LYNDA GLEDHILL 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ In a Los Angeles debate that was more lovefest
than showdown, Democrats Al Gore and Bill Bradley spent 90 minutes
Wednesday night trying not to say anything bad about each other.
</P>
<P>
   For Bradley, the debate was almost a white flag, recognizing
that his campaign is likely to end next Tuesday when California and
15 other states choose their delegates.
</P>
<P>
   Even before the debate, rumors were swirling that Bradley was
getting ready to abandon his shot at the Democratic nomination,
forcing the former New Jersey senator to publicly deny that his
campaign was just about over.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm looking at next Tuesday as takeoff day,'' Bradley said
during the debate. ``I'm in here to change the political process,
to appeal to people as Americans and human beings.''
</P>
<P>
   But with polls showing Gore far ahead in California and
elsewhere, Bradley backed off the scorching comments he had aimed
at the vice president earlier in the campaign.
</P>
<P>
   When he talked about gun control, for example, he argued that
the country ``needs a leader committed to this every day he's in
office,'' but gingerly stepped away from his previous charges that
Gore could not provide that leadership.
</P>
<P>
   Gore also avoided the red-hot rhetoric that marked last month's
debate at Harlem's Apollo Theater. Time after time, the vice
president answered ``I agree with that'' when Bradley talked about
issues like campaign finance reform, civil rights and gun control.
He also backed away from chances to take a whack at the New Jersey
senator, body shots he had been willing to throw as recently as
Wednesday during a campaign appearance in the Los Angeles suburb of
Cudahy.
</P>
<P>
   When he talked about ways to help the disabled last night, Gore
mentioned the need to continue the Medicaid program and left it at
that. But in almost every campaign appearance he makes, he takes
pains to mention that Bradley wants to dump Medicaid and replace it
with a subsidy system Gore says is inadequate.
</P>
<P>
   The unspoken ceasefire in the campaign's barrage of charges and
countercharges delighted the vice president's backers.
</P>
<P>
   ``This shows we disagree with Republicans, not with each
other,'' said Chris Lehane, a spokesman for Gore.
</P>
<P>
   In many cases, Gore passed over Bradley's challenge to blast
John McCain and George W. Bush, the two GOP candidates for
president.
</P>
<P>
   When asked about the Christian right, for example, Gore said
that both Republicans were in the pocket of extremists.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Republican party today is in the midst of an identity
crisis,'' he said. ``Both (McCain) and Gov. Bush are in favor of
taking away a woman's right to choose,'' refused to come out
against flying the Confederate flag over the South Carolina capitol
building and ``are in the hip pocket of the National Rifle
Association.''
</P>
<P>
   Bradley's debate stance wasn't surrender, but tactics, said one
Bradley staffer.
</P>
<P>
   ``People watched Bill Bradley (tonight) and they saw that he's a
man of substance and integrity,'' said Dana Spurrier, a spokeswoman
for the former senator.
</P>
<P>
   Lost in the often-harsh give and take of the campaign has been
the fact that Gore and Bradley are far more alike than different.
</P>
<P>
   Both came out against California's Proposition 22, which would
outlaw same-sex marriage, but both also said they opposed gay
marriage and preferred domestic partner rules that would provide
the same legal rights.
</P>
<P>
   Proposition 22 is ``mean-spirited,'' Gore said. ``It's time to
leave people alone because of the way God made them.''
</P>
<P>
   The two men also came out in favor of increasing the number of
H-1B visas available, which would open the way for more highly
skilled immigrants to come to the United States to work in the
high-tech industry.
</P>
<P>
   The question of civil rights brought the most heartfelt
responses last night.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley called for a ban on racial profiling at federal agencies
and a requirement that local police agencies report of the racial
background of the people they arrest.
</P>
<P>
   The Amadou Diallo shooting case in New York shows how deeply
racial profiling has penetrated, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``A wallet in the hand of a white man is a wallet, but a wallet
in the hand of a black man is a gun,'' Bradley said.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley and Gore both refused to condemn the Rev. Al Sharpton, a
controversial New York clergyman who has a history of disputes with
both city officials and the Jewish community.
</P>
<P>
   Sharpton represents many black people who feel they have been
discriminated against, Bradley said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The question is how do the voiceless get a voice,'' he asked.
``Sometimes it takes someone who rubs part of the people the wrong
way to focus attention.''
</P>
<P>
   Minutes before the debate, the Rev. Jesse Jackson endorsed Gore,
saying that he was ``fully aware of the unfinished business of the
economic health'' of the society and was positioned to continue the
nation's economic growth.
   Jackson had been courted by both candidates.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the day, Bradley had to answer questions about
whether his campaign is taking on water after a crushing defeat in
Washington on Tuesday, a state where he had spent a lot of time and
money.
</P>
<P>
   At a brief press conference, Bradley quoted Mark Twain and said
the reports of his demise are greatly exaggerated.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last night was a disappointment,'' Bradley said. ``At the same
time the delegate count is still the same _ 41 to 27. We're going
on to March 7. ... We're still in the race. We're working hard and
I feel good.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite widespread reports that senior advisors have been urging
Bradley to quit, he said there were ``zero who said I should drop
out.''
</P>
<P>
   After the debate, Gore refused to suggest that Bradley was
surrendering and leaving him with the Democratic nomination.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't take a single vote for granted, much less a single
primary or caucus,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Both men left California immediately after the debate and
declined to say whether they would return to campaign again before
Tuesday's primary.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
