<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OSTLER-COLUMN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STEAMY READING AT THE CHECKOUT
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By SCOTT OSTLER 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &LR;   &LR;  SAN FRANCISCO _ Today: My sex change operation: Five minutes to
a new me!
<P>
   The plan today was to write about Muni or the rain, but I was
standing in the checkout line at the supermarket and happened to
notice that all anybody (women at least) cares about is sex.
</P>
<P>
   Here's a sampling from the covers of women's magazines:
</P>
<P>
   -- ``Sexecstacy: Make-him-throb moves so hot he'll sweat when he
hears your name'' (Complete Woman)
</P>
<P>
   -- ``50 tricks for outstanding orgasms/NC17 seductive
moves/applause-worthy foreplay'' (Glamour)
</P>
<P>
   -- ``Supersize your sex life/ take home 10 tasty tips from the
world's lustiest lovers'' (Cosmo)
</P>
<P>
   -- ``Your sex life: How often/How good/How orgasmic'' (Marie
Claire)
</P>
<P>
   -- ``The great vibrator hum-off'' (Jane)
</P>
<P>
   -- ``Deeply personal quiz: How sexually satisfied are you?''
(Self)
</P>
<P>
   -- ``New! Sex column/Surprise him tonight'' (Redbook)
</P>
<P>
   Believe it or not, there were a couple headlines I'm too
embarrassed to reprint here.
</P>
<P>
   Men's magazines aren't like this. We men don't need any sex tips
or quizzes. Our sex lives are already supersized.
</P>
<P>
   We don't phone up a buddy and say, ``Hey, how'd you score on the
deeply personal quiz in Motor Trend? My rating was `a quart low.'
''
</P>
<P>
   It's good to know what women are thinking about, but shouldn't
these magazines be kept in a curtained-off section of the market or
newsstand, with an armed guard checking IDs?
</P>
<P>
   Kids don't need to see this stuff. Frankly, neither do guys. It
makes us feel cheap, like playthings or lab rats.
</P>
<P>
   As for my sex-change operation: I think the technical medical
term is vasectomy. Read all about it in my first-person account in
Modern Hombre _ ``Cool Hand Dr. Luke: He cut me off at the pass.''
</P>
<P>
   BIG NEWSPAPER merger, sort of:
</P>
<P>
   Chronicle photographer Carlos Avila Gonzalez was zipping down
880, ran into traffic ahead so he slowed, then traffic behind ran
into him, in the person of a reporter for the San Jose Mercury
News.
</P>
<P>
   But this isn't news. When it comes to getting the story, the
Merc is always right behind us.
</P>
<P>
   MYSTERY TRAIN demystified:
</P>
<P>
   Technically, there is no train from SFO to downtown S.F.,
despite notification in Korean Air's in-flight magazine.
</P>
<P>
   But having flown in and out of SFO only a few hundred times, I
was not aware that there  &UR; is  &LR; a free shuttle from SFO to the
Millbrae Caltrain station, and then a $2 train to the Caltrain
station in SoMa, 4th and Townsend, a trip of 29 minutes or less, no
stopping for traffic.
</P>
<P>
   'STICK JR.? Will the Giants' new ballpark be windy?
</P>
<P>
   Karen Knowles-Pearce has been sailing out of the South Beach
yacht harbor near the new ballpark for 10 years, and she says wind,
every day of the summer during the afternoons, is guaranteed, or
double your money back.
</P>
<P>
   Karen's baseball season weather prediction: Less fog at the new
park than at the 'Stick, warmer temperatures. ... But no wind? Why
do you think people park their sailboats there?
</P>
<P>
   WELCOME TO San Francisco. Give me your wallet and your watch.
</P>
<P>
   There has been at least a mini-rash of recent robberies of tour
vans and buses.
</P>
<P>
   The bad guys work fast, are very efficient and well-organized.
Palace of Fine Arts, Golden Gate Bridge, Cliff House. ... Tourists
get out for a quick look around, return to find their bus picked
clean.
</P>
<P>
   It's not right. How can we rip 'em off legitimately if someone
steals all their traveler's checks?
</P>
<P>
   IT'S FUNNY, says author Michael Gross, that there are three Baby
Boomers running for president who are hated by all Baby Boomers,
and one non-Boomer running who is admired by the Boomers.
</P>
<P>
   So we're a confused lot; sue us.
</P>
<P>
   Or maybe we know that we can't respect anyone who did what we
did. Or we know that they know too much.
</P>
<P>
   Gross sorts out Boomer confusion and angst in his new book, the
quietly titled ``My Generation: Fifty years of sex, drugs, rock,
revolution, glamour, greed, valor, faith and silicon chips.''
</P>
<P>
   The book chronicles 19 zany Boomers, many of them from right
here by the bay, like the guy who invented LSD and helped give the
Grateful Dead its edge.
</P>
<P>
   One reviewer said the book ``is certain to induce a wave of
nostalgia among (Gross') peers.''
</P>
<P>
   But what if we get seasick?
</P>
<P>
   SPEAKING OF BOOMERS, the German Christian Democrats, notes
eagle-eyed Ed Epstein, have elected a new leader:
</P>
<P>
   Fred Merz!
</P>
<P>
   Actually it's Friedrich, but everyone calls him Fred, I'm sure.
</P>
<P>
   This means that Ethel Mertz is the party's First Fraulein.
</P>
<P>
   It's strange, despite Ethel Mertz's huge influence on American
culture, nobody names their daughter Ethel anymore.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe it's the $2-per-gallon stigma.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-02-00 0100EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
