<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-02 01:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4210 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a BC-MCCAIN-LOSANGELES-SFC     03-02 1032
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCCAIN-LOSANGELES-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MCCAIN GETS HERO'S WELCOME IN SOUTHERN CALIFORNIA'S LITTLE SAIGON
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By CARLA MARINUCCI 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &LR;   &LR;  WESTMINSTER, Calif. _ Sen. John McCain, who recently caused a
controversy with his use of ethnic slur to describe his Vietnamese
captors, got a hero's welcome in the nation's largest
Vietnamese-American community Wednesday night, telling his audience
of 1,500 ``This is a community that epitomizes what America is
about.''
<P>
   McCain was met in the business community of Little Siagon, which
is part of the city of Westminster, with sidewalks crammed with a
cheering throng people waving the red and yellow flag of Vietnam
and the stars and strips with many of the women and children in
colorful native dress. Many of the people credited McCain with
freeing them from re-education camps after the fall of South
Vietnam in 1975.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are proud of your contributions,'' McCain told them at a
rally last night. ``I praise you.'' The Arizon senator was flanked
on stage by nearly a dozen Vietnamese POWs and he appeared
emotional as he introduced them.
</P>
<P>
   There was no mention of the controversy last week in which he
referred to his Vietnamese torturers as ``gooks.'' But many
Vietnamese in the crowd said they understood the term in reference
specifically to particular guards who held in a POW camp for more
than 5 1/2 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was in prison 18 years, '' said Tam Nguyen, who served in
the South Vietnames Special Forces. ``I want McCain for
president.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain was on a three-day barnstorm through California with five
days to go before the crucial California primary.
</P>
<P>
   Making other news, he backtracked on strong statements he
uttered Tuesday, when he called televangelists Pat Robertson and
Jerry Falwell ``forces of evil'' within the Republican Party.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about those comments Wednesday, McCain suggested he was
only resorting to a common and humorous ``Star Wars'' campaign
analogy that he has used in recent weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``In my campaign, I often joke about Luke Skywalker, evil
empires and death stars,'' he said in a written statement. ``It was
in that vein that I used the phrase yesterday (Tuesday).
</P>
<P>
   ``While I disagree with the political message and tactics of
Rev. Falwell and Robertson, Mr. (Bob) Jones and other
self-proclaimed leaders of the Christian right, I do not consider
them evil, and I regret that my flip remark may have mistakenly
created that impression. ... I have always welcomed the support of
millions of religious conservatives who share my convictions ...
and our Judeo Christian values.''
</P>
<P>
   While he was waiting to go on the air for a live broadcast of
``Hardball'' with Chris Matthews, McCain told The Chronicle he was
deeply ``bothered'' that his offhanded bantering with reporters,
which he does constantly aboard his ``Straight Talk Express'' bus,
was misinterpreted Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   In the wake of Tuesday's defeats in the Washington and Virginia
primaries and North Dakota's caucuses, McCain's abrupt turnaround
appears to reflect increasing pressure on his campaign to round up
GOP voters in California and to secure a win in the Super Tuesday
primaries next week.
</P>
<P>
   GOP front-runner George W. Bush was quick to criticize McCain
for his remarks about Robertson and Falwell, attributing his
victories in Washington and Virginia to voter rejection of ``the
politics of pitting one religion against another.
</P>
<P>
   ``This campaign is winning, and we're doing it the right way,''
the Texas governor said, ``uniting our party without compromising
our principles, expanding our base without destroying our
foundations.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain's turnabout Wednesday was the second time this week that
he has felt obligated to clarify previous remarks.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, after announcing that he would skip Thursday night's
debate with Bush, McCain reversed himself and said he would rework
his schedule to participate via satellite. The CNN-Los Angeles
Times debate will be broadcast at 6 p.m. on CNN.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, McCain apologized for referring to the prison guards
who tortured him in a Vietnamese POW camp as ``gooks.''
</P>
<P>
   His comments about Robertson and Falwell were made during a
three-day blitz of California. Riding with reporters on his bus
Tuesday, McCain, when asked about his previous criticisms of the
two televangelists, said, ``I'm willing to take on the forces of
evil. ... That's my job.''
</P>
<P>
   The senator was specifically asked what he found objectionable
in the actions of the two Christian leaders. ``I'm talking about
the evil influence ... they have exercised over the Republican
Party,'' McCain said. ``They've driven us to the extreme right. ...
I blame them for setting a tone of exclusivity, and intolerance,
and bigotry.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet, despite the turnabouts and apologies, McCain maintains an
upbeat outlook on his chances in California and is drawing huge,
wildly enthusiastic crowds.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm excited, I'm enthusiastic, I'm hopeful,'' he said. ``Yes,
I need to win California. Yes, it's a critical state. California
has enormous impact on the nomination, and I need to win. I think
we can win.''
</P>
<P>
   After addressing a cheering crowd of about 1,400 in Riverside,
McCain said polls show that ``we're within single digits in
California'' and gaining a percentage point a day among GOP voters.
</P>
<P>
   Many who turn out to see him, often holding his book, ``Faith of
My Fathers,'' say they have not voted Republican for years _ or
have never aligned themselves with a GOP candidate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a Democrat for 71 years _ and I'm a Republican for the
first time this year,'' said World War II veteran Jack Cullari of
Hemet. ``He's a leader. There's no comparison with Bush.''
</P>
<P>
   But McCain faces a daunting task in the nation's most populous
state. Even though he appears to be winning the popular vote in
California _ and gaining support among independents and Democrats _
recent polls show him lagging 15 to 20 percentage points behind
Bush among Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   And only the Republican votes will count toward the awarding of
California's treasure chest of 162 GOP delegates, according to the
rules of the state's winner-take-all blanket primary.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
