<HEADER>
A4211 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NY-POLICE-SHOOTING-1S     03-02 0915
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-POLICE-SHOOTING-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNARMED MAN KILLED BY OFFICER JUST BLOCKS FROM WHERE DIALLO DIED
</HEADLINE>
  (SUBS 2nd graf to add location of shooting and confirm that victim
was unarmed;adds new 3rd graf to note that victim had been arrested
Friday in a Diallo protest;deletes orig. 3rd graf and adds new
grafs 4, 5 with details on protests after the shooting;rewrites
original 4, 5th grafs to add details;inserts new 9th graf, with
info on Rivera's gun; After graf bgng `At 10 p.m.' deletes all
orig. copy and subs to CORRECT number of victim's arrests,   add
details on shooting, with quotes from witness and state officials,
and background on Rivera.) 
 (nk) 
 By ANDY NEWMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A 23-year-old unarmed man was shot dead by a
plainclothes police officer Wednesday night after a struggle in a
Bronx apartment building just three blocks from where Amadou Diallo
was killed last year, the police said.
</P>
<P>
   The man, Malcolm Ferguson, who the police said was on parole for
a drug conviction, was shot once in the head, at about 6:30 p.m.,
and declared dead at the scene at 1045 Boynton Ave. in the
Soundview section, said John Scanlon, the Police Department's chief
of patrol. Scanlon said Ferguson was unarmed.
</P>
<P>
   Ferguson, the police said, was one of two protesters arrested in
the neighborhood last Friday after the four officers who shot
Diallo were acquitted of murder and manslaughter charges.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday night, dozens of protesters, still angry at last
week's acquittal of the four officers who shot Diallo, gathered
behind police sawhorses near the building after the shooting. Some
carried signs denouncing police brutality and confronted a squadron
of officers, some clad in helmets and other riot gear.
</P>
<P>
   Officials from the mayor's office, the Bronx borough president's
office and the Police Department, along with elected officials,
went to the block to quell any potential for violence. There was
one arrest, for throwing a bottle at police officers.
</P>
<P>
   Scanlon said five housing officers who were part of an anti-drug
unit had been traveling to a public housing unit in the Soundview
section of the Bronx, but as they passed by the building at 1045
Boynton Ave., they noticed ``some movement in the hallway that drew
their attention.
</P>
<P>
   ``The officers went to go into the hallway, and one individual
bolted up the stairs,'' Scanlon said. Officer Louis Rivera ran
after him, the chief said.
</P>
<P>
   ``At some point, on the second-floor landing, there was a
struggle,'' Scanlon continued. ``The officer's firearm discharged
and the individual succumbed.''
</P>
<P>
   Blood was found on Rivera's gun, indicating that Ferguson was
shot at very close range, Scanlon said.
</P>
<P>
   At 10 p.m., Scanlon said that no weapon had been found on
Ferguson, but that there was ``a continuing investigation for
weapons and other evidence.''
</P>
<P>
   The police found six packets of heroin wrapped in cellophane
tucked into Ferguson's pants, the chief said.
</P>
<P>
   Ferguson, who relatives said lived in the South Bronx, had been
arrested nine times since 1994, the police said. On two occasions,
he had his parole revoked, and he was on parole until April 3 for
selling drugs, the police said.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the protesters said that the shooting of Ferguson, like
that of Diallo, happened in large part because he was black.
Scanlon said that the officer who shot Ferguson was Hispanic. Of
the other four officers in the unit, one was white, two were black
and the other Hispanic.
</P>
<P>
   A witness, Modesto Rodriguez, said that the plainclothes
officers who went into the building were not easily identifiable.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw two guys with hoods go into the building,'' said
Rodriguez, 23, referring to the police. ``They didn't look like
cops. They looked like brothers.''
</P>
<P>
   In his four-and-a-half years on the force, Rivera had never
fired his gun, said Deputy Chief Thomas P. Fahey, a police
spokesman. ``He's squeaky clean,'' Fahey said.
</P>
<P>
   Rivera was the subject of one excessive-force allegation, but he
was exonerated, Fahey said. ``He was the wrong cop in that
complaint,'' the chief said.
</P>
<P>
   A senior police official said that Rivera had made 120 arrests
and described him as a ``very active police officer.''
</P>
<P>
   By 10 p.m., the neighborhood was largely blocked off. A phalanx
of officers in riot gear stood behind barricades as helicopters
circled overhead and floodlights illuminated the intersection of
Boynton and Watson Avenues. Dozens of detectives and other law
enforcement officials milled in and out of 1045 Boynton, a
four-story brick building on a narrow street.
</P>
<P>
   The protesters, mostly teenagers, held up signs that included
slogans like ``No justice NYPD got away with murder.'' At one
point, many of the group held up their wallets and chanted ``don't
shoot,'' a reference to Diallo, whose wallet was mistaken for a gun
by the officers who shot him.
</P>
<P>
   Elected officials also came out to try to keep the peace.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's such a tragic situation for this community, which has had
such a loss'' said state Sen. Larry Seabrook. ``Even if the
individual who expired committed a crime, it's too much to take at
this time. He was still an unarmed civilian.''
</P>
<P>
   Norman Siegel, the head of the New York Civil Liberties Union,
who arrived shortly after the shooting, said that the police had
changed their story.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were not told there was a scuffle,'' Siegel said. ``I was
told initially that he was running from the cop.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
