<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-02 01:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4213 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-HKN-STARS-FLYERS-TEX     03-02 0743
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-STARS-FLYERS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STARS DEFEAT FLYERS BY SHOWING CUP FORM
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JENNIFER FLOYD 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ Gentlemen, the Stanley Cup race may just have grabbed a
favorite in the Stars. Or, at least, as close to a favorite as
you're going to get in this wide-open season.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is ``the'' top team,'' Philadelphia coach Craig Ramsay
said after watching his Flyers lose to them, 2-0, last night at
Reunion Arena.
</P>
<P>
   In case anybody forgot, the Stars have reminded them during the
past 11 days. They've played and defeated three serious Cup
contenders in Colorado, Detroit and Philadelphia. They've done so
in impressive fashion, too.
</P>
<P>
   A solid, all-around performance was employed against the Flyers.
The defense was stingy. The usual suspects like Mike Modano were
forces. The youngsters like Brenden Morrow were anything but
intimidated. The goalie... Well, Ed Belfour was his usual
dominating self.
</P>
<P>
   And the Stars are beginning to look more and more like the team
that won it all last season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think we've gotten credit for winning the first one,''
Stars defenseman Darryl Sydor said. ``For us to get respect, we got
to win it again, and we feel like we can do it. ... Obviously, with
playing the good teams and doing well, we have the confidence that
we can get it done.''
</P>
<P>
   Neither team was at 100 percent or anything really close. The
Flyers were without big-name, big-game players Eric Lindros (back),
Keith Primeau (ribs) and defenseman Ulf Samuelsson (shoulder). The
Stars were without Joe Nieuwendyk (shoulder) and Jere Lehtinen
(ankle).
</P>
<P>
   With 1:27 remaining in the first period, the injury factor
became even. Stars defenseman Richard Matvichuk had to be helped
from the ice after Flyers winger Keith Jones tripped and rolled
under him, upending the defenseman and spraining the medial
collateral ligament in Matvichuk's left knee. Matvichuk didn't
return to the game. The defenseman will be evaluated again today,
but Stars coach Ken Hitchcock said he wasn't expected to miss more
than seven to 10 days.
</P>
<P>
   ``It really could end up being day to day depending on how he
comes in'' today, Hitchcock said.
</P>
<P>
   And while Stars Lite vs. Diet Philly was a little less sexy, it
was no less exciting.
</P>
<P>
   The game had everything. Physical play, big saves, exciting
scoring chances and plenty of Belfour.
</P>
<P>
   He earned his fourth shutout of the season, stopping all 25
shots he faced.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was good when he had to be good,'' Hitchcock said. Flyers
goalie Brian Boucher didn't have such a good game, allowing two
goals on 16 shots.
</P>
<P>
   At 5:02 of the third period, Stars center Aaron Gavey picked
defenseman Zarley Zalapski's pocket. He poked the puck toward
Philadelphia's goal. His shot wasn't the hardest or the best, but
bounced in off the pads of a diving Boucher for a 2-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``Actually, I think I was going five-hole,'' Gavey said. ``I
don't know where it really went. When I looked back, I saw it
slowly making its way over the line. I was just praying it was
going to keep going.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Zalapski: ``I won't be doing that next time. It's a blatant
kind of play where a guy poke checks you and goes in uncontested.
Those just aren't good plays. It's so close that one or two things
that happen like that changes the course of a hockey game.''
</P>
<P>
   The ``one or two things'' happened with Zalapski on the ice.
</P>
<P>
   A Zalapski snafu also led to the Stars' first goal. After Modano
poked the puck away at the blue line, Morrow beat Zalapski to the
puck. Morrow couldn't beat Boucher, but he pushed the puck to
Modano on the left side, and Modano did. Modano's goal, at 6:10 of
the second period, was really all the Stars needed.
</P>
<P>
   Belfour made sure of that. He looked as good if not better than
he did early in the season. He had to be, too. The Flyers certainly
had their chances. A few point blank ones included.
</P>
<P>
   ``They had some good chances in the game,'' Belfour said. ``It's
definitely nice when they get those chances and you come up with
the saves.''
</P>
<P>
   Yes, the Stars sent a message to the rest of the league in the
past 11 days.
</P>
<P>
   Not only can you not count them out. They might just be the
favorite.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, if you want to have a chance to win in the playoffs
you have to beat the good teams because those are the teams that
stay the longest in the playoffs,'' Stars center Guy Carbonneau
said.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
