<SLUG> BC-BKC-CSUN-WEBERSTATE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NORTHRIDGE ROUTS WEBER STATE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CHRIS BRANAM  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ A total effort translated into total domination
Wednesday night for the Cal State Northridge men's basketball team.
</P>
<P>
   Could this be the end of the Matadors' recent frustration?
</P>
<P>
   CSUN carried the momentum of a thrilling win last weekend into a
blowout of old nemesis Weber State Wednesday night, 76-62 in front
of a season-best 1,401 fans at Matador Gym.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't want to do anything special, we just wanted to come
out and put the effort into it,'' said junior center Brian Heinle,
who had 16 points, eight rebounds and six assists. ``We're playing
hard on the defensive end and on the offensive end we're playing
really unselfish.... We've been waiting for a while now to get
everyone on the same page.''
</P>
<P>
   That was obvious from tipoff to the final buzzer against the
Wildcats, who dropped into a fourth-place tie with the Matadors at
9-6 in the Big Sky. Forget about never trailing; Northridge never
let WSU get within 12 points in the second half.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe CSUN (17-9) sent a signal to defending Big Sky champion
Weber State (also 17-9). With one regular-season game left, these
teams most likely will meet in the first round of the conference
tournament next week.
</P>
<P>
   ``We played scared and we played soft,'' Weber State coach Joe
Cravens said. ``I didn't think we played hard or competed. We
played softer than a baby's behind all night. It's all about heart
and effort and we showed little of either one.''
</P>
<P>
   CSUN showed both. The lingering effects of Saturday's 79-78 win
over Portland State, which the Matadors rallied from 17 points down
with 7 minutes left, were evident in the first half. Northridge
took a 26-9 lead with 9 minutes, 31 seconds left before halftime.
</P>
<P>
   ``We defended well tonight,'' CSUN coach Bobby Braswell said,
referring to WSU's 23.1 percent shooting in the first half. ``We
played 40 minutes of good, hard basketball. The focus was just
phenomenal.''
</P>
<P>
   Weber State forward Harold Arceneaux, the favorite to repeat as
the Big Sky's MVP, had a game-high 27 points. But he made only 10
of 24 shots and he had six turnovers. Eddie Gill, the Wildcats'
all-conference point guard, was 4 of 12 from the field and had six
assists, four less than CSUN point guard Markus Carr.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we play hard, we can be a pretty good basketball team,''
Braswell said.
</P>
<P>
   Carr said: ``That was Northridge basketball. We weren't worried
about anything other than Northridge.''
</P>
<P>
   CSUN hosts Sacramento State (9-17, 3-12) Saturday night in its
home finale. The Matadors have an outside shot at tying third-place
Montana, which has two tough road games (Portland State and Eastern
Washington).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-02-00 0153EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
