   &UR; BUSINESS DAY _ (Moved in ``f'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   IMF-U.S. (Washington) _ When President Clinton pledged this week
to block a German finance ministry official from assuming the top
post at the International Monetary Fund, in effect vetoing the man
the 15-nation European Union had collectively chosen for the job,
he seemed to risk a diplomatic confrontation across the Atlantic.
What really happened, Clinton administration officials and some
European diplomats say, is that Clinton agreed to confront Germany
in a way that European countries applauded but were unwilling to do
themselves. By Joseph Kahn.
</P>
<P>
   AZERBAIJAN-U.S. (Washington) _ Pro-Armenian activists have kept
Azerbaijan on a United States blacklist since 1992 _ the only
former Soviet republic to be punished in this way _ thanks to a
well-coordinated lobbying effort by Armenian- Americans and a
strong coalition of Armenia supporters in Congress. But the
Azerbaijanis are pushing back. President Aliev himself has engaged
in face-to-face lobbying, and some high-powered hired professionals
are working behind-the-scenes. And big oil has been acting quietly
on Azerbaijan's behalf. By Marc Lacey.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo has been sent to NYT graphics clients.)
