</P>
<P>
   NY-VILLAGE-HOUSE (New York) _ Like many people who meander
regularly through the storybook streets of the West Village, Tom
Fontana had always wondered about the strange house on 13th Street
near Eighth Avenue. Set at the end of a row of brownstones, with
its elegant Moorish window arches and stepped gable, the
three-story brick house looked like a reproduction of a
17th-century Dutch guild hall. But the formal front doors and a
chunk of the ground floor had been hacked away. By the time that
Fontana _ the television writer and mastermind of ``Homicide'' and
``Oz'' _ first stumbled upon house, in the 1980s, it looked as
though it had been through a bummer of a trip. By Nancy Hass.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photos [NYT6,7,8) has been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   COLLECTING (Undated) _ It was a night like any other. Until I
knocked over the two and a half foot tall Finnish glass candle
pedestal, designed by Oiva Toikka in 1964. It stood in my living
room behind the Florence Knoll sofa. I paid $1,600 for it two years
ago at the Triple Pier Expo, a collectibles show in New York. The
purchase broke the ceiling on my expenditure for glass, ever. It
smashed into loose change in seconds. But that was only the
beginning of the crisis. By William L. Hamilton.
</P>
<P>
   LEWITT-MURAL (Undated) _ Last fall, Carole and Dick Cline were
looking for something to hang over the fireplace in the sitting
room of their new home, which overlooks a golf course near Chicago.
The couple's art consultant, Deborah Lovely, brought by a few
paintings but none that worked with the couple's antique furniture
and multicolored rug, Cline said. Then Ms. Lovely suggested a Sol
LeWitt mural _ a ``wall drawing'' in the artist's parlance. By
Christmas, the couple had something to match the rug: a geometric
drawing in diluted inks applied with sponges, covering two walls of
their sitting room _ about 250 square feet. They just didn't have a
chance to meet LeWitt. By Fred Bernstein.
</P>
<P>
   GARDEN-Q&AMP;A (Undated) _ Garden questions answered. By Dora
Galitzki.
</P>
<P>
   ITALY-DOORS (Undated) _ Leave it to Italians to solve a design
problem homeowners didn't know they had: clunky doors. Try
achieving a sleek and modern interior while dealing with throwback
terms like doorjambs and thresholds, lintels and hinges, much less
carved paneled doors. It's enough to make a minimalist swoon. By
Julie Iovine.
</P>
<P>
   FLOWER-SHOW (Undated) _ The snowdrops are blooming and the
species tulips are popping up. Some mornings, the air is balmy and
the sun has that golden light that says, ``Spring!'' And you put on
a lighter coat and freeze to death by the afternoon, when the
winter wind blows up again. That's the signal to get on the train
and head for your favorite flower show _ to wallow in woodland
gardens impossibly blooming with dogwoods and shadbush; to bury
your nose in acres of orchids, to drool over English gardens
stuffed with blue delphiniums you could never grow. By Anne Raver.
</P>
<P>
   HOME-IMPROVEMENT (Undated) _ The Home Improvement column. By
Edward Lipinski.
</P>
