<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-02 02:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4238 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BBN-ASTROS-WARD-HNS &LR;      03-02 0928
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-ASTROS-WARD-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CARLTON THOMPSON  
 c. 2000, Houston Chronicle  
KISSIMMEE, Fla. _ The Internet has become one of the greatest
sources of trade rumors, most of which are unfounded.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The name of Astros outfielder Daryle Ward popped up recently in
connection with Yankees reliever Ramiro Mendoza. A year ago, Astros
general manager Gerry Hunsicker might have considered such a deal,
but a year ago the Astros had a totally different opinion of Ward.
</P>
<P>
   The club always has known Ward could hit; that much has been
impossible to overlook. What the Astros were uncertain about was
whether he could play any position other than first base, which
belongs to Jeff Bagwell as long as he wears an Astros uniform.
</P>
<P>
   Ward answered that question last season when he made a
commitment to playing the outfield and became the Astros' every-day
left fielder down the stretch. It did wonders for his value around
the league, not to mention the Astros' estimation of him.
</P>
<P>
   ``We certainly were willing to discuss (trading Ward) a year
ago,'' Hunsicker said. ``It's hard to say too many people are
untouchable these days, but he's close to it. Ward is getting
greater recognition because of what he did last year at the
major-league level.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the perceptions from a lot of organizations were
similar to ours from a year ago, mainly that this was a kid who
could hit but his defense was a question mark, and there aren't too
many 23- or 24-year-old designated hitters around.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was minimal interest a year ago, but I think that has
changed now that he has demonstrated that he can play defense, and
he certainly has demonstrated that he can hit at this level.''
</P>
<P>
   For all the strides Ward has made in the outfield, it's his bat
that still gets everyone's attention. Astros hitting instructor Tom
McCraw has called Ward the best young hitting prospect with whom he
has worked. In 125 games split between Class AAA New Orleans and
Houston last season, Ward hit .346 with 36 homers and 95 RBIs. He
had eight homers and 30 RBIs in 150 at-bats with the Astros.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros certainly don't want to lose that type of thunder
from the left side of the plate, particularly with Bagwell eligible
for free agency after the 2001 season.
</P>
<P>
   ``That makes me feel good, because it lets me know that I'm
getting credit for the hard work that I've put in to become a
better defensive player and a better all-around player,'' Ward said
of his near-untouchable status.
</P>
<P>
   Although Ward's defense has improved, he's still not on the same
level as Moises Alou, Roger Cedeno and Richard Hidalgo _ the three
players who will form the Astros' regular outfield alignment.
Because manager Larry Dierker places great emphasis on defense,
Ward will enter the season as the Astros' fourth outfielder and
their primary lefthanded power source off the bench.
</P>
<P>
   Inevitably, Dierker will pick his spots to use Ward, who hit
seven of his eight big-league homers against righthanders last
season. Exactly when Ward's opportunities will present themselves
is still unclear.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have no idea,'' Dierker said. ``He's not one of our top
three defensively. But we also have to score, and the other corner
outfielders (Alou and Hidalgo) are righthanded, so he may get to
play a little _ pinch-hit, mostly _ or he may get to play (a lot).
It's going to make for some hard decisions lineup-wise, because the
other guys aren't going to want to come out.''
</P>
<P>
   In an ideal scenario, the Astros would prefer to have Ward, 24,
playing every day in the big leagues or in the minors. But the
reality is that Dierker needs a bat like Ward's on the bench. Ward
hit .320 with two homers and four RBIs in pinch-hit appearances for
the Astros in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   ``I watched guys like Billy Spiers, Jack Howell, Stan Javier and
Dave Clark,'' Ward said. ``As long as I continue to learn, I think
I can do pretty well as a pinch hitter. I'm not going to complain.
I'm in the big leagues having fun, so there's nothing to complain
about. I feel like I can help this team. Whether it's coming off
the bench or playing every day, I'm going to do my best to help the
team.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some guys run into trouble when there's not a spot for them,
and they moan and complain. They don't focus on what they have to
do and concentrate on the season that's ahead of you. There are
people constantly watching you, and you have to keep your head up,
enjoy the game and just play baseball. That's what I try to do.''
</P>
<P>
   While it appears Ward will be the odd man out in the Astros'
starting outfield, Hunsicker believes there will be plenty of
opportunities for the young slugger.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's unrealistic to think you're going to get through the
season with three outfielders,'' Hunsicker said. ``It never works
out that way, because of injuries, off years, pitching matchups,
etc. The fact he did a commendable job in the outfield has
furthered his cause.
</P>
<P>
   ``To his credit, he worked hard at his defense and made himself
into an acceptable outfielder, and now we can consider him as a
legitimate outfield candidate as well as a backup first baseman.
</P>
<P>
   ``He'll have to wait his turn and take the opportunities that
come to him, which will be when Alou and Hidalgo get rest against
certain tough righthanded pitching matchups. That's how I see it to
start the season, anyway.''
</P>
<P>
   But as evidenced by the 16 times the Astros used the disabled
list in 1999, how the lineup looks at the beginning of the season
can be quite different come September.
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
