<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-02 02:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4243 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BKN-OLAJUWON-HNS &LR;      03-02 1027
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-OLAJUWON </SLUG>
 -HNS  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JONATHAN FEIGEN  
 c. 2000, Houston Chronicle  
Hakeem Olajuwon might not have feared the worst, but it did cross
his mind. Instead, he got the best news possible about his
continued tendency to run out of breath faster than he can run.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Olajuwon's three days of tests uncovered a minor, treatable and
common condition that might allow him to return to the court as
soon as tonight, when the Sacramento Kings visit the Rockets.
</P>
<P>
   Olajuwon is suffering from a reactive airway disease that
restricts the flow of air through his bronchial passages during
heavy exercise. The condition, which has caused Olajuwon's lungs to
spasm, is similar to exercise-induced asthma.
</P>
<P>
   With the diagnosis, Olajuwon knew neither his age nor his
conditioning could be blamed for his lack of stamina and that the
condition that has caused his problems should be temporary.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you listed the 100 things it could have been, this is the
one you'd have made the No. 1 (most favorable) choice,'' Rockets
team physician Jim Muntz said. ``It doesn't bother him in his daily
life. And it's easily treated.''
</P>
<P>
   Olajuwon, 37, has suffered from anemia and in 1997 was diagnosed
with atrial fibrillation. But tests revealed no signs of those
problems, and Muntz said Olajuwon's lung capacity was determined to
be greater than it was four years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was very happy with all the tests that were done,'' Olajuwon
said. ``My heart is in good condition. It isn't anything related to
that. I was just trying to find out what is the problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was so happy to discover it (Olajuwon's health) wasn't
normal. I was thinking I wasn't in shape. But instead of getting
better, it was getting worse. When they ran all these tests, I
wanted to find that out. Thank God, I'm very healthy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to detect the problem. This can't be normal. How can
you be winded every time you go up and down (the court)? I cannot
be that out of shape, because I know I've been training so hard
just to play. Something must be wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   Olajuwon will be treated with medication taken via an inhaler.
There are also inhalers available to treat symptoms should they
continue during games or other especially stressful activities, but
they could cause a recurrence of other problems Olajuwon has had in
past years. Thus, doctors will limit the treatment of the condition
itself.
</P>
<P>
   After going through Wednesday's practice, Olajuwon said he
already felt better after beginning treatment with an inhaler and
that he plans to play tonight. Team physician Walter Lowe said he
would have to examine Olajuwon after today's shootaround before
giving him the OK to play. The Rockets are listing Olajuwon as
questionable.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it would be right to have him back out there if
we have to treat these symptoms continually through games,'' Lowe
said. ``I would, and I think the other doctors treating him would,
like to see him responding to the medication he takes, able to
bring his exercise level back up, to be able to train the way he
needs to to play and then be on the court. Whether that is tomorrow
or not remains to be seen.''
</P>
<P>
   Unlike many asthmatic conditions, this one is so treatable that
a cure is expected relatively quickly. Rockets forward Carlos
Rogers treats a bronchial condition with inhalers before every
practice and game. Though Olajuwon said learning of Rogers'
condition helped put him at ease, Olajuwon's treatment is expected
to be short-term.
</P>
<P>
   ``I found out it is very common, not something that is major,''
Olajuwon said. ``It will take a month or two weeks and be cured.
That's what I'm hoping.''
</P>
<P>
   It is uncertain whether the condition was caused by
anti-inflammatory medication Olajuwon has been taking for about
eight years. He recently changed his anti-inflammatory medication
and was taken off of it this week.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dream has been worried about an anti-inflammatory he's been
taking,'' Lowe said. ``It (his condition) can come from allergies.
It can come from pollution. It can come from having a cold. We're
probably never going to be able to tell where it came from.
</P>
<P>
   ``The good news is it's treatable. In the exercise world, these
lung problems are really common with kids through adults. It is
something that can come out of the blue when you were perfect two
weeks before, and now you've got it for a while. It is something
you can treat for a little while, it will go away, whatever the
stimulus was is gone, and now you're off your medication.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a whole lot of different medicines to use for this. We
have to see how Dream responds to these medications. I think
(within) four, five days, we ought to know whether the treatment
Dr. Muntz and the pulmonary guys have him on are going to work or
whether we change him to other things. Now we're in the stage we
know what's going on. Then we have to find out what medicines are
going to work for him. And then we're going to have to see him in
action on the court to see if he can get to where he needs to be to
play.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we want to see him doing really well before he plays.
Dream is going to want to play. There's no question about that. But
we really want to see him breathing the way he needs to before he
plays.''
</P>
<P>
   Coach Rudy Tomjanovich said he would be cautious about returning
Olajuwon to the court. Olajuwon,who is averaging 11.4 points and
6.6 rebounds this season, had 21 points and nine rebounds in a
113-111 overtime loss to the Spurs on Feb. 20. But he struggled
with exhaustion in the next three games.
</P>
<P>
   He played 28 minutes in Charlotte on Feb. 22, totaling six
points and five rebounds. He played 23 minutes against the Nuggets
on Feb. 24, scoring 10 points and grabbing six rebounds. He had six
points and six rebounds in 13 minutes against the Lakers on Sunday.
He skipped Monday's game against the Clippers to begin tests in
Houston.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have to admit I'm concerned,'' Tomjanovich said. ``Dream has
been great. He really wants to do the right thing and all that. We
just have to make sure he doesn't put himself in jeopardy in any
way.''
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
