<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-02 02:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4244 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-OLY-SKATING-GARDINER-     03-02 0735
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-SKATING-GARDINER-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JODY GOLDSTEIN  
 c. 2000, Houston Chronicle  
She looks like an athlete _ 5 feet 7 inches of solid muscle.
<TEXT>
<P>
   But if forced to guess, most people would be hard-pressed to
come up with her sport. She could be a basketball player,
volleyball even. She could run track or play soccer.
</P>
<P>
   But Baytown's Andrea Gardiner probably looks least like what she
is _ one of the top figure skaters in the country.
</P>
<P>
   In a sport where how an athlete looks is nearly as important as
how she performs, the 19-year-old isn't letting preconceived
notions limit her accomplishments. She recently returned from
senior nationals in Cleveland, where she exceeded expectations with
her best-ever finish _ fifth place _ only 1{ years after returning
to the ice following a hip fracture. That finish makes her an
alternate for the world team.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole competition was just awesome,'' Gardiner said. ``I
did what I came to do _ skate well and prove to everyone that I'm
here.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the crowd was so into her performance that she received
a standing ovation. But when the scores were announced, they were a
bit disappointing. The crowd reacted with boos.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was my first year back, so I expected the scores to be
low,'' Gardiner said. ``Now that I've watched the tapes, I
understand.''
</P>
<P>
   The solid showing earned her a trip last week to the Four
Continents competition in Japan, where Gardiner finished ninth in
the short program and seventh in the long for eighth place overall.
</P>
<P>
   Both competitions were breakthroughs for Gardiner, who is
working to reclaim a top reputation after time off the ice.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole goal this year was to have a positive experience
with skating again,'' coach Becky Dever said. ``That was as much as
I hoped right away. I never expected her to be as successful as she
has been right away because of the political side of skating. But
last week showed that Andrea is very much on the right path.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, Gardiner won the junior nationals at the age of 16. She
wasn't a prodigy like Houston's Tara Lipinksi, who was 14 at the
time and already known internationally. But Gardiner was proving to
be a top talent with a seemingly limitless future.
</P>
<P>
   All of that was cast in doubt in July 1998 when doctors
discovered a hip fracture. Gardiner did not suffer a sudden injury
on the ice. The bone apparently just snapped because of constant
pressure and stress, the doctors explained to her. She was out for
half the year and returned to the ice at senior nationals one year
ago, when a poor showing left her in 16th place. It was time to
make a decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd healed enough to skate, but I was not mentally prepared,''
Gardiner said.
</P>
<P>
   She hired former top skaters Dever and Kitty Carruthers to serve
as co-coaches and rededicated herself to the sport she had missed
so much in her absence.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Skating) had become a very stressful environment for her,''
Dever said. ``The poor kid was a mess. We worked, most importantly,
on her mind. She needed positive reiteration. It's almost like
parenting.''
</P>
<P>
   For the past 11 months, Gardiner has made the nearly 2{-hour
round trip five or six days a week to train at the Aerodrome in
Sugar Land, and the initial results showed in Cleveland. The next
major goal will be to make the Olympic team for the 2002 Winter
Games at Salt Lake City.
</P>
<P>
   She will be competing against some talented up-and-coming
skaters. Like in gymnastics and tennis, ice skaters seem to get
younger each year. But women like Gardiner could have an edge,
Dever said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're running into an area in skating where the quickness of
the little ones is very appealing to the eye,'' Dever said. ``And
to the sponsors and agents. But it's important to the sport to have
women represent them at the senior level. They're not going to give
away the whole pot of gold to the little girls even if they are
spitfires out there.''
</P>
<P>
   Which is a word that could be used to describe Gardiner as well.
While not a spitfire in appearance, she certainly is in attitude.
</P>
<P>
   ``On the first day that she got home from nationals, she was
already setting her goals for next year,'' Dever said. ``She's back
on the international team. She earned her right to be there. That,
in itself, is a tremendous stride, and her future possibilities are
really endless.''
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
