<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-02 02:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4247 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BBN-LOPEZ-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      03-02 0736
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-LOPEZ-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
John P.Lopez
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; c. 2000, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
KISSIMMEE, Fla. _ The Doctor has become the Insurance Man.
</P>
<P>
   No longer is Dwight Gooden the overpowering kid with the
flamethrowing right arm, but the fallback plan if things don't go
exactly as planned.
</P>
<P>
   No longer is he the dominator, staring over the brim of his
glove and intimidating even the game's biggest sluggers, but merely
the battling veteran hoping to find a place among the fellas.
</P>
<P>
   It's the way Gooden has embraced this prime-of-life career
change of sorts that says something about him. It says he has grown
up. It says he has found humility and perspective where once there
was ego and a feeling of invincibility.
</P>
<P>
   The difference in Gooden's outlook on baseball and life has been
clear every day at the Astros' spring-training camp, where he has
spent long hours putting in extra work, running sprints, doing
situps, signing autographs and fitting in with his new teammates.
</P>
<P>
   At 35, Gooden has seen his once-bright star go the way of the
heat on his once-virtually untouchable fastball, which is to say
it's simmering somewhere on the back burner.
</P>
<P>
   Where once there was a bigger-than-life swagger and so much
money and acclaim so soon that it all became too much, now there is
the hope of simply earning an honest day's pay for an honest day's
work.
</P>
<P>
   There is balance in his life in every way. And it is impossible
not to hope that the friendly, grounded Gooden has found a home at
a place where the only star he wears is on the bill of his Astros
cap.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was 19, I didn't realize everything I had,'' Gooden
said. ``I thought it would always be there. Maybe I didn't
appreciate it the way I should have.''
</P>
<P>
   The happy ending of Gooden's story would be his entering Astros
camp and suddenly regaining some semblance of his once-amazing
stuff. But that hasn't happened.
</P>
<P>
   Gooden is battling hard to find a place in the rotation, and his
progress has been slow. Good days have been followed by mediocre
ones.
</P>
<P>
   In a simulated game Monday afternoon, Gooden looked strong.
Astros manager Larry Dierker said Gooden's ball was livelier than
he had seen since camp began.
</P>
<P>
   But Wednesday in the same situation, Gooden was knocked around
as much as he set down bats.
</P>
<P>
   ``My arm was tired, but I knew that was coming,'' he said. ``I
know this time of year you have to break down your arm and then
build it back up.''
</P>
<P>
   The Doc realizes he has come to the point in his career where he
must cure himself. And if he does, it would remedy many questions
for the Astros' pitching staff.
</P>
<P>
   Over the first five years of his career with the Mets, Gooden
was by many accounts the most dominating pitcher in the game. Only
once in those first five years did he win fewer than 17 games or
strike out fewer than 175 batters _ a 15-7 year with 148 strikeouts
in 1987.
</P>
<P>
   He was pivotal in the Mets' World Series championship season of
1986. In 1985, when he went 24-4 at age 20, he was the youngest
player ever to win the Cy Young Award and also the youngest ever to
win 20 games.
</P>
<P>
   But over the past five years with the Mets, Yankees and Indians,
only once did Gooden win more than nine games or strike out more
than 88, going 11-7 with 126 strikeouts in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   A year ago with the Indians, Gooden found himself shuffled back
and forth from the bullpen, confused and frustrated the whole way,
and finished 3-4 with a 6.26 ERA.
</P>
<P>
   It was time for Gooden to redefine his game. And where better to
look to do that than with the Astros, where the clubhouse
atmosphere is relaxed and laid back, like Gooden? The starting
pitching staff also is in a state of transition, with Mike Hampton
gone, Scott Elarton recovering from surgery, and Shane Reynolds and
Jose Lima the only sure things.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm getting a chance here, and that's all I can ask for right
now,'' Gooden said. ``I don't have to be so much crafty as just
have the location and command of the pitches. When I was younger
and I fell behind in the count, everybody in the stadium knew what
was coming next _ the fastball. I can't do that now. I have to be
more than that.''
</P>
<P>
   Progress has been slow. But there has been some. The Astros need
Gooden as much as Gooden needs the Astros. The Doctor is out. The
Insurance Man is in.
</P>
<P>
   It's impossible not to hope this match works.
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
