<SLUG> BC-RAMPART-COPS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
L.A. POLICE DEFENSIVE, BLAME THEIR TOP BRASS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JASON KANDEL  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR; LOS ANGELES _ Police patrolling the city's streets in the hours
after a devastating report decried a culture of ``mediocrity'' in
the LAPD and expressed mixed but passionate sentiments over the
findings.
</P>
<P>
   Many defended the maligned command staff, others argued a few
bad apples were causing the entire Los Angeles Police Department's
reputation to rot, and still others placed the blame squarely on
the top brass.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a chief who is anti-cop,'' said Officer Kathy Simpson,
a 14-year veteran of the department, assigned to the West San
Fernando Valley. ``The brass needs to be changed. It's all politics
up there.''
</P>
<P>
   At issue is a nearly 400-page report, released Wednesday, that
found no evidence of widespread corruption within the department
but argued mediocrity was flourishing at every level.
</P>
<P>
   Officer Ray Barron said most of the officers he works with are
good people. He argued that the Rampart scandal is isolated.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our supervisors are very professional,'' he said. ``But it's
like any job. There are people you like working for and with, and
there are some people you don't like working for or with.''
</P>
<P>
   The report was issued after corrupt-cop-turned-informant Rafael
Perez told investigators that he and other dirty cops in the
Rampart Division framed suspects, stole evidence and shot unarmed
residents. He agreed to talk in exchange for a lighter sentence for
stealing cocaine from an evidence locker.
</P>
<P>
   Supervisors and the rank and file across Los Angeles received
copies of the report and were briefed about it at roll calls
Wednesday afternoon before heading out to their posts.
</P>
<P>
   The Board of Inquiry report, which was given to the Police
Commission on Wednesday, found that Rampart supervisors rarely
challenged officers' incident reports, even if they were
far-fetched.
</P>
<P>
   Among its findings, the report stated, ``This scandal has
devastated our relationship with the public we serve and threatened
the integrity of our entire criminal justice system.''
</P>
<P>
   Barron disagreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a positive reception from the public,'' he said. ``You
can't put a blanket statement over all of the department. Nobody
likes stereotyping.''
</P>
<P>
   According to the report, officers at Rampart were free to bend
or break rules to make more arrests. But Officer Estancio Rosales
countered that he had never been roughed up by cops in the 20 years
that he grew up in the Rampart area.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's isolated,'' he said. ``There are some bad apples. Society
is not perfect.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-02-00 0214EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000302.0043 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-02 02:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4263 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-OUT-MOUNT-LADN     03-02 0709
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OUT-MOUNT-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HE IMMORTALIZES PRIZE CATCHES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RICH HAMMOND  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Robert Munoz has heard fish stories from all over
the world, and believe it or not, every one of them is true.
</P>
<P>
   For the past 25 years, fishermen from Tarzana to Tokyo have put
Munoz in charge of producing replicas of their prized catches.
Munoz, and others like him, bucked the trend of mounting the actual
fish, known as skin mounts, in favor of creating molds that lead to
longer-lasting trophies.
</P>
<P>
   Fishermen have two options in immortalizing their catches. They
can bring the actual fish or several clear photos of it to Munoz,
or they can purchase one of his many premade species.
</P>
<P>
   ``Business continues to be great,'' Munoz said while taking a
break from his mostly one-man operation in Baldwin Park. ``I don't
even need to advertise, and I get customers from all over the
world. Germany, Italy, Taiwan, Japan, Spain ... it's really
amazing.
</P>
<P>
   ``And it's all word of mouth. I will do work for one guy and he
will go home and show five of his buddies, and it just keeps
spreading from there.''
</P>
<P>
   Businesses such as Munoz's help promote the idea of catching and
releasing fish. Anglers can experience the thrill of bringing in a
catch, and with Munoz' help they can create a lifelike replica even
though they threw back the catch.
</P>
<P>
   Munoz works on approximately four fish per day, which includes
making the mold and painting. He charges an average of $11 per
inch, although the figures vary based on the type of fish. He
continues to accept orders for skin mounts, although the demand is
much smaller than it used to be.
</P>
<P>
   ``It took awhile for this way to be accepted,'' Munoz said.
``For a long while, a lot of the old-timers thought skin mounts
were the only way to do it. They didn't say that (making a mold)
couldn't be done, but nobody knew how.''
</P>
<P>
   Munoz, then in his early 20s and working for a taxidermist, set
out to create a mold from which he could replicate any species of
fish, a task that proved both expensive and time-consuming.
</P>
<P>
   ``Back in those days, we had to buy gallons of whatever material
we wanted to try and just experiment with it,'' Munoz said. ``I'll
never forget when I figured out that first mold, I was so excited.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had been working on it for six or eight months, and one day
I worked on one and then fell asleep. I woke up three or four hours
later, opened up the mold and it was perfect.''
</P>
<P>
   The popularity of skin mounts continued to fade over the years,
not just because of the conservation movement but also because the
skin mounts tended to peel.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem is, people put them up in their living room or
whatever, and their heating and air conditioning systems cause a
lot of problems,'' Munoz said. ``The oil in the skin tends to
expand and contract depending on the temperature, and that causes a
lot of problems.''
</P>
<P>
   Munoz follows a pattern for customers who seek a custom mount,
one that is often filled with pitfalls.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of times people will just bring in a picture, one
picture, and expect an exact duplicate, and that's just not
possible,'' Munoz said. ``A lot of people have a bad picture, maybe
because the fish is in bad shape, and when I show them what the
fish is supposed to look like, they don't believe me.
</P>
<P>
   ``When somebody actually brings a catch into the store, the
first thing I look at is the condition of the fish, to see if it
has any scars or marks or anything. If it's a good candidate for a
replica, I can do it, or I suggest that they just buy one that I
already made.''
</P>
<P>
   Buying a premade mount allows the customer to have his fish
instantly, rather than waiting several weeks. Munoz has his
22-year-old son, Robert Jr., working in the office with him, and at
age 47 he is starting to wonder what the future will hold for his
company.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really wanted to hire a painter a couple years ago, but I
just couldn't find the right person with the passion for the job,''
Munoz said. ``There are other methods out there to be mastered, but
they will take several years to figure out. I'm still having fun
with this though and the orders keep coming in.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-02-00 0214EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
