r s BC-OUT-HIKE-LADN     03-02 0442
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OUT-HIKE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HIKERS SHOULD ALWAYS BE PREPARED FOR BAD WEATHER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEITH LAIR  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The weather on a recent Saturday was perfect and
it had Dave Smail worried.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a gorgeous day,'' said Smail, who is one of the
directors of the L.A. County Sheriff's San Dimas Mountain Search
and Rescue Squad. ``It was definitely a day to be concerned about.
People see it as a gorgeous day and decide to go hiking. They're
not expecting bad weather.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, the weather forecast - sunny days with overnight clouds
and early morning rain Sunday - held true. But what if the weather
changed? It's not an unlikely scenario; forecasts can change in a
matter of hours, especially in the Southern California mountains.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people knew it was supposed to rain Sunday, but if a
group went Saturday and the weather forecast changed in the
afternoon, they wouldn't know about it,'' Smail said. ``It's a
concern for us.
</P>
<P>
   ``On Sunday, it was raining and the temperature had dropped.
Monday, it was even colder and the snow level was down to 3,500
feet. Things like this happen more often than not.''
</P>
<P>
   A lot of those day-trippers, Smail and others say, might take
just water and lunch. If the sun is shining and it's warm, they
might even leave the jacket in the car. They might be anglers who
hike up the West Fork of the San Gabriel River for early-morning
fishing, armed with only fishing gear, a snack and jacket.
</P>
<P>
   But what if the weather changes? The clothing gets wet, there's
no protection and it gets cold in a hurry. The hiker is suddenly
prone to hypothermia. Being exposed to the elements eventually
causes illogical thinking, loss of body temperature and can lead to
death.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our main concern is to get people out safely and the weather
at this time of the year is a concern,'' Smail said.
</P>
<P>
   The team was successful in helping rescue four hikers in the
Angeles National Forest above Glendora on Tuesday. They had camping
gear and were prepared for the inclement weather, though. They were
found when rescuers say they spotted flashlight signals. Among the
10 items recommended by Smail, and other groups, for hikers is a
flashlight.
</P>
<P>
   Smail points out that food is not on the list.
</P>
<P>
   ``Water is,'' he said. ``You can go several days without food.
It's not an essential. But water is.''
</P>
<P>
   Another essential, especially at this time of the year, is
protective clothing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even a trash bag,'' Smail said.
</P>
<P>
   With a hole cut on top for the head, trash bags are ideal for
protecting hikers from rain and wind.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-02-00 0216EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000302.0045 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-02 02:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4265 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BKN-LAKERS-GRIZZLIES-     03-02 0694
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERS-GRIZZLIES-REWRITE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAKERS STREAK MARCHES ON
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(OPTIONAL: Adds quotes, details) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ March arrived and the march continued, though
mostly in stop-motion action.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-four hours removed from their ballyhooed battle in the
Pacific Northwest, the Los Angeles Lakers returned home Wednesday
for a date with considerably less sizzle, and certainly none of the
intrigue of their just-completed victory over rival Portland.
</P>
<P>
   And though the Vancouver Grizzlies tried to provide their own
sort of drama, of the upset variety, it was a short-lived notion.
The Lakers marched over their overmatched opponent to their 13th
consecutive victory, 103-91, at Staples Center.
</P>
<P>
   Coupled with the previous 16-game winning streak, this latest
string means the Lakers (47-11) are once again tilling new ground.
This is the longest pair of double-digit streaks a Lakers team has
had in one season.
</P>
<P>
   Such achievements don't come without the occasional junk game.
This was one of them as the listless Lakers, sapped by a night of
tension and hype, couldn't put the Grizzlies (18-39) away until
late in the third quarter.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think one of the things young teams learn ... is that you
accommodate highs and lows of a basketball season,'' coach Phil
Jackson said. ``After playing a game to an excited crowd last
night, we were somnolent out there in this game. We were walking
wounded, in our sleep.''
</P>
<P>
   That was evident in the way Kobe Bryant missed 13 of 22 shots
(but still finished with a game-high 27 points), in the way
Shaquille O'Neal collected fouls in bunches (fouling out late in
the fourth quarter) and in the way Glen Rice (eight points) never
really found a rhythm.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of our legs were heavy,'' Bryant said.
</P>
<P>
   But O'Neal, newly crowned NBA player of the month for February,
was effective between fouls, making 11 of 17 shots to finish with
25 points, 17 rebounds, five assists and five blocked shots. Bryant
found his energy late, scoring 19 in the second half.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't take this team lightly or feel like this was any
less of a game as far as our opponent,'' guard Derek Fisher said.
``This is the toughest game of the two, really, because it's easy
to get yourself going and bring your `A' game against a team that
everybody's been talking about the matchup, and a team that you've
been battling with all year for the NBA's best record....
</P>
<P>
   ``I was proud because our effort was there,'' Fisher said.
``Things weren't necessarily clicking, but like I've said a million
times this season, these are games that the four years that I've
been here, we could have easily found ourselves on the losing end,
because we weren't playing our best game. But we still found a way
to grind it out.''
</P>
<P>
   They did it with another inspired effort from the bench. Robert
Horry scored 10 points, leading a 32-point effort from the
reserves. And the bench finally put the Grizzlies away.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers hadn't led by more than six points and were only up
by a point late in the third when O'Neal went to the bench with his
fifth foul. Then the Lakers hit four consecutive 3-pointers, from
Brian Shaw, Horry, Rick Fox and Bryant, to take a 77-69 lead into
the fourth.
</P>
<P>
   Travis Knight's putback jam and another 3-pointer from Fox made
it a double-digit lead, 82-71, less than three minutes into the
final period, and the Grizzlies never got close again.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our second unit is giving us the energy we need to play with
teams now, as we get into this, hard days, a lot of games and a lot
of travel, and we need the energy of this team to be picked up from
the players coming off the bench,'' said Jackson, named NBA coach
of the month for February.
</P>
<P>
   For fourth-quarter excitement, fans had to settle for a couple
of spiffy Bryant dunks and Fisher's flying leap over the $1,000
courtside seats - complete with a foot to actor Jon Lovitz's head -
to save a ball.
</P>
<P>
   ``We did like we usually do, we played down to the talent of our
competition,'' O'Neal said. ``However, we gutted it out and got a
win.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
