<SLUG> BC-WHEELS-ALUMINUM-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUPERIOR INDISTRIES MAKES MARKET INROADS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JASON TAKENOUCHI 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR;   &UR; L &LR; OS ANGELES _ Superior Industries International Inc.
announced Wednesday that it has won an initial multimillion-dollar
order from Mitsubishi Motor Manufacturing of America Inc.
</P>
<P>
   The Mitsubishi order is latest new contract for Superior, a Van
Nuys- based supplier of aluminum wheels and other vehicle
components. The company has recently added DaimlerChrysler and
Rover to a customer base that includes General Motors and Ford.
</P>
<P>
   The contract with Mitsubishi could be worth up to $10 million,
according to Jeff Ornstein, Superior's vice president and chief
financial officer.
</P>
<P>
   But the initial value pales in comparison its long-term
potential, said Doug Christopher, an analyst with Los Angeles-based
Crowell, Weedon &AMP; Co. The wheel contract may pave the way for more
work in the future as Superior builds a relationship with
Mitsubishi, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's another customer added to their growing list of
customers,'' Christopher said. ``It's a start.''
</P>
<P>
   Ornstein agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We expect that the add-on business would be significantly
larger than the original contract,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Superior has already begun shipments of aluminum road wheels to
Mitsubishi's facility in Normal, Ill. The wheels will be used for
two 2001 model cars.
</P>
<P>
   Superior stock closed Wednesday at $23.88, unchanged from
Tuesday's close.
</P>
<P>
   Christoper said Superior's stock has gotten little respect
despite the company's strong earnings and solid balance sheet.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the dominant company in the industry. The company is
in an excellent position,'' he said. ``Unfortunately in this
market, no one really cares about the traditional businesses.''
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
