<SLUG> BC-PREZ-DEBATE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORE AND BRADLEY LOCK HORNS IN LOS ANGELES DEBATE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DOMINIC BERBEO 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ In a Los Angeles debate that could be the last
between Democratic presidential hopefuls Al Gore and Bill Bradley,
the two opponents switched course Wednesday by striking a friendly
tone and setting themselves apart from the Republican candidates on
issues like abortion, campaign reform and gun control.
</P>
<P>
   ``Both Gov. Bush and Sen. McCain are as anti-choice as you can
get,'' Vice President Gore said, referring to the two Republican
candidates. Knowing that is important to voters because the next
president will likely be called upon to nominate three judges to
the country's highest court, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley, a former New Jersey senator, said that, if elected
president, he would appoint Supreme Court judges who interpret the
Constitution with contemporary considerations.
</P>
<P>
   ``The new conservatism is the same as the old conservatism,'' he
said, adding that he would make it a top priority to uphold the
historic court decision of Roe v. Wade, which legalized abortion.
</P>
<P>
   The debate was seen as a last prayer for Bradley to breathe new
lifU!B &QC; jsnn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-02-00 0827EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000302.0052 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-02 10:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4350 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k BC-KLEINBERG-COLUMN05-CO     03-02 0672
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KLEINBERG-COLUMN05-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: Extra! Extra! Coupons in here!
 &HT;    (For release March 5, 2000.)
 &HT;    By Howard Kleinberg
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Several decades ago, our newspaper's advertising director
suggested to me that we run a streamer across the top of the front
page advising readers that there were coupons in that edition worth
$200. A hidebound traditionalist, I rejected his idea and, instead,
put something of news value across the top _ or at least what I
believed to be news value.
</P>
<P>
   That my newspaper _ The Miami News _ eventually went out of
business speaks volumes about my reader judgment. While we in the
newspaper game believe news is what sells _ that's what our
detractors also claim: ``They're just doing that to sell
newspapers'' _ it may not be the case.
</P>
<P>
   Things such as discount coupons, entertainment news and sports
seem to be in a position of domination at many newspapers across
the country. It's also showing in news magazines as well, or
haven't you seen entertainment-skewed Time magazine lately?
</P>
<P>
   What's the bigger sell: A story that state contractors are using
substandard materials or that Kathy Lee Gifford is leaving her
morning show? What's of greater interest to readers: That the
county's homeless shelter is flat broke, or that there's a bunch of
coupons inside the paper?
</P>
<P>
   Several Sundays ago, my local newspaper ran a streamer on its
front page, advising readers that coupons within the paper _ in an
inserted booklet from a national drug chain _ were worth over $500
in savings.
</P>
<P>
   That the newspaper used part of its front page for promoting
advertisements is an issue between the various departments of the
newspaper, and its publisher. The sad truth likely is that more
readers turned to that coupon-filled booklet than to the editorial
page.
</P>
<P>
   One of my earlier editors would insist that a ``woman's
interest'' story appear on Page 1 every day because, he said, women
made the decisions about what newspaper to have delivered to the
house. The problem was that I never could define what was ``woman's
interest.'' Judging by many I know today, it very well could be the
stock market.
</P>
<P>
   Inasmuch as federal authorities have recently announced plans to
clamp down on advertising claims by long-distance telephone
companies (I never believed them anyway; not the 10 cents, not the
unlimited calls stuff), I set out to see what was with this claim
of $500 in coupons in the paper.
</P>
<P>
   Surely I have better things to do, but I felt compelled. How
much did I have to spend to save $500 in a drugstore? So I leafed
through the 236 coupons in the booklet; not once but twice, all the
time tapping on the adding machine.
</P>
<P>
   Fully half the coupons did not give the price of the item, just
noted that it was 25 percent off or 25 cents off. The other ads had
the regular price and the price with the coupon. It was those that
I added up.
</P>
<P>
   It came to $1,770.25. That's what I would have to spend.
</P>
<P>
   Mind you, that's the total of only about half; do we double it
for those that did not include the price?
</P>
<P>
   I doubt that anyone saved $500 with coupons at the drugstore
that week, or ever intended to. This booklet was discounting
everything from phone cards to condoms to laxatives to hair spray _
no discounts on prescription drugs by the way.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody could take advantage of the full savings offered by these
coupons; who needs ALL that stuff? But the aggregate total of its
value made for a good streamer headline.
</P>
<P>
   ``Man bites dog'' or ``Headless woman in topless bar'' seem to
have become outmoded by reader tastes and journalistic drift. Now
the big news is that there are coupons in the paper worth more than
$500 in savings.
</P>
<P>
   And I understand why it is happening. They're just doing it to
sell newspapers.
</P>
<P>
   (Howard Kleinberg, a former editor of the Miami News, is a
columnist for Cox Newspapers. His e-mail address is
hkmiami(at)aol.com.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-02-00 1024EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000302.0053 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-02 10:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4351 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k BC-TEEPEN-COLUMN05-COX     03-02 0557
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEEPEN-COLUMN05-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: The impetus behind McCain's right jab
 &HT;    By Tom Teepen
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Don't make too much of John McCain's dramatic disavowal of the
tele-reverends Pat Robertson and Jerry Falwell.
</P>
<P>
   The gesture was at least as much a matter of personal pique _
the two and their allies trashed McCain in South Carolina _ as it
was a principled assertion of political realignment.
</P>
<P>
   Not that the act wasn't brave after its fashion. Falwell and,
latterly, Robertson especially have been bully boys in the GOP for
years, using their presumed moral suasion openly, and wielding
their control of church-bidden voters less overtly, to pull the
party into an agenda that blends political conservatism and
Protestant fundamentalism.
</P>
<P>
   The resulting hybrid movement has fielded a partisan infantry
for the party _ some 20 percent of its reliable electorate by most
counts _ but at some cost.
</P>
<P>
   In elections where all else was equal, the muddle of dogma and
right-wing politics has lost the party more at the polls than it
has won.
</P>
<P>
   A shakeup that stopped that tail from wagging the dog would be
painful to the GOP at first but healthy for it in the long run,
just as the comparable change was when the Democratic Party
recaptured its own center by taking back the veto power it had
granted its fringes in the '70s.
</P>
<P>
   But while McCain claims to be after a similar move for his
party, that is less than certain.
</P>
<P>
   The McCain campaign recruited its erstwhile rival, Gary Bauer,
longtime head of the Family Research Council, and while he was
excoriating Robertson and Falwell, McCain went out of his way to
praise, among other religious-right figures, James Dobson, mogul of
the sprawling Focus on the Family operations.
</P>
<P>
   In truth, except that Falwell and Robertson are more lurid and
Dobson and Bauer have managed to fly just under most media radar,
there is little to choose between Dobson-Bauer and
Robertson-Falwell.
</P>
<P>
   All are of a piece with the Christian-nation movement, either
advocating it or fellow-traveling with those who do. The aim is to
turn public policy and law into what Christian conservatives deem
the logical civil version of Scripture.
</P>
<P>
   Even as he dumped on the two televangelists, McCain emphasized
his solidarity with much of the evangelical political agenda _ his
commitment to outlaw nearly all abortions, to fund vouchers for
religious schools, to harass Internet pornography and more.
</P>
<P>
   McCain is certainly right to argue for a Republican Party that
is more Lincoln than Robertson, a party comfortable with religious
diversity rather than sullenly tolerant of it. But as we've seen
over the course of his jump-up, jack-in-the-box candidacy, politics
is intensely personal with John McCain.
</P>
<P>
   It is very much an open question whether McCain was just doing
pay-back to Robertson and Falwell or whether he is girded for a
battle that would extend beyond this political season to build a
party that would continue to welcome religious conservatives but
would slip its thralldom to the political preachers who swank
around in their name.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Teepen is national correspondent for Cox Newspapers. He is
based in Atlanta. E-mail: teepencolumn(at)coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
