<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Presidential race like a poker game
 &HT;    By Arnold Garcia
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ People who have been around politics usually
know better than to make predictions. Politics, after all, is about
people, and people are quite unpredictable.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than engage in prophecy, the experienced political
watcher often will speak in hypothetical. Since Gov. George W.
Bush's defeat in New Hampshire, some folks around here are using
poker slang in assessing his situation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he'd better look at his hole cards,'' said one,
meaning taking stock of the cards the other players can't see and
deciding then whether to call, raise or (gulp!) fold.
</P>
<P>
   It's not at all likely the governor will fold his presidential
campaign, though challenger John McCain is teaching him a poker
lesson or two.
</P>
<P>
   Bush is still given good odds to win, but the stroll to the
nomination that people were predicting six months ago didn't
materialize.
</P>
<P>
   And that is emboldening some around here to do the ``I could
have told you so'' routine, but not too loudly.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, there is some hypothetical talk about the prospect of
the Republican presidential nomination being decided at the
convention. Just imagine what a return to the thrilling days of
yesteryear that would be.
</P>
<P>
   The last time a convention had any suspense to it was the 1960
Democratic convention in Los Angeles that produced the
Kennedy-Johnson ticket. Since then, however, nominations have been
decided long before the delegates set foot on the convention floor.
</P>
<P>
   If it is a convention scenario, then you're talking about a real
poker game where anything can happen. It could even be that Bush
has to take a look at the prospect of becoming a vice presidential
candidate or inviting McCain to join the ticket.
</P>
<P>
   We are, of course, just speaking hypothetically.
</P>
<P>
   Too many people have too much invested in Bush to give up
easily. The motives for those investments vary. Some have made
assumptions about Bush vacating his office and what happens then.
</P>
<P>
   It hasn't been that long ago that people were talking about who
moves where when Bush leaves for Washington. Lt. Gov. Rick Perry
would become governor, which would leave his post open to a
hypothetical contest between Comptroller Carole Keeton Rylander,
Land Commissioner David Dewhurst and Sens. David Sibley (R-Waco)
and Teel Bivins (R-Amarillo).
</P>
<P>
   And hypothetically speaking, such a scramble would create
opportunities for advancement to fill those offices, which in turn
would open other doors.
</P>
<P>
   But that speculation has been cooled by McCain's show of
strength. It's a tough game and getting tougher as McCain and Bush
wrestling for control of the betting. Bush got raised in Michigan
and McCain is raising again in the March 7 Super Tuesday primaries.
</P>
<P>
   The governor's hole cards aren't bad. His record as Texas
governor has a little something for everyone. He made public
education a priority, he engaged in foreign policy, and overall he
made good appointments to the judiciary.
</P>
<P>
   The reason Bush was presumed to be way ahead was his presumed
ability to duplicate his crossover appeal in Texas on a national
basis. What he and his backers are learning again is that they play
poker differently in a national race.
</P>
<P>
   Bush is still given good odds to win the nomination. It just
isn't as easy as people thought it was going to be.
</P>
<P>
   Arnold Garcia is the editorial page editor of the Austin
American-Statesman. He can be reached at agarcia(at)statesman.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
