<HEADER>
A4370 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k BC-MCNEELY-COLUMN03-COX     03-02 0787
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCNEELY-COLUMN03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Is the honeymoon over?
 &HT;    By Dave McNeely
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ The ``Doonesbury'' cartoon for Tuesday was a
sign. Sen. John McCain, the former prisoner of war who disrupted
Gov. George W. Bush's smooth ride to the Republican nomination, may
be starting to have his paint peeled.
</P>
<P>
   Doonesbury, which had ignored McCain's insurgent campaign until
the day before, pondered McCain's mystical popularity. The
occasionally daffy Cricket has gone to work in conservative
McCain's anti-establishment campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's odd,'' she admits, ``is that I don't actually agree
with him on anything. But I'm drawn to his candor and independence
and quirky charm.''
</P>
<P>
   Garry Trudeau's cartoon is not exactly representative of the
press corps covering the McCain campaign. But the fact that
Trudeau, who has depicted former Vice President Dan Quayle as a
feather and George W. as a cowboy hat (with no cattle), finally is
dealing with McCain is just the latest evidence that McCain is
coming into the sights of The Dragon.
</P>
<P>
   That's the name veteran journalist Ross Ramsey, editor of the
Texas Weekly political newsletter, gives to the intense media
scrutiny that can suddenly focus on a presidential candidate who
becomes a front-runner or major contender. Paul Begala, who
co-managed Bill Clinton's first presidential campaign, calls it The
Laser _ because it is so hot and searing that it can melt almost
anyone.
</P>
<P>
   The press can fawn _ witness George W. last year, Clinton in
1991 _ and McCain has been its recent darling. His
stream-of-consciousness openness on his ``Straight Talk Express''
campaign bus _ ask me anything _ impressed reporters used to a
stiffer distance.
</P>
<P>
   George W. had undergone scrutiny about allegations of drug use
and National Guard favoritism. But last year the former first son
also enjoyed star treatment from national reporters, including a
seven-part series in The Washington Post last summer, and was
featured on the covers of major news magazines. He thought he had
survived.
</P>
<P>
   Until New Hampshire. Bush's canned, rote remarks and distance
from reporters raised the question: Does he have The Right Stuff?
McCain's strong upset victory won him the magazine covers. Then,
because of Bush's response in South Carolina, The Dragon focused on
his campaign tactics _ particularly his appearance at
fundamentalist Bob Jones University.
</P>
<P>
   But in recent days, the Bush campaign's recurrent claim that
McCain's ``Straight Talk Express'' is guilty of recurrent moving
violations has been accompanied by increasingly critical press
scrutiny.
</P>
<P>
   Just a few of the columns and stories include:
</P>
<P>
   _ Scott Greenberger in the Austin American-Statesman, about the
backlash McCain created among Asian Americans by his use of the
term ``gooks'' to describe his North Vietnamese captors.
</P>
<P>
   _ Nicholas D. Kristof's report in The New York Times Sunday on
McCain's returning from Vietnam and dumping his wife, a former
model who had been seriously injured in a car accident. He then
married a 25-year-old former cheerleader whose beer baron father
helped McCain become a congressman from Arizona a year after moving
there.
</P>
<P>
   _ Congressional Quarterly, which put a smiling McCain on the
cover of a recent issue with the headline, ``If he's so popular,
why do senators hate McCain?''
</P>
<P>
   _ Boston Globe columnist Ellen Goodman, who wrote incredulously
about swooning Democrats who think Ralph Nader isn't liberal enough
yet are ditching Bill Bradley to vote for McCain. What's up?
</P>
<P>
   ``They don't agree with McCain on anything but campaign-finance
reform,'' Goodman writes. ``They're pro-choice, he's pro-life.
They're pro-gun control, he's pro-gun. They're in favor of a
nuclear test ban; he's opposed. They're for strong environmental
protection; he's not. But, hey dude, he's a stand-up guy with a
good sense of humor.''
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Cohen of FAIR (Fairness and Accuracy in Reporting), a
left-of-center national media watch group headquartered in New
York, recently wrote that McCain had co-opted the objectivity of
the boys and girls on the bus.
</P>
<P>
   ``A big part of McCain's appeal to elite journalists is Vietnam
guilt,'' Cohen opined. ``Many baby boomer reporters were
well-connected collegians who dodged the war. In McCain they see a
hero, someone who didn't evade the war and who bravely survived
brutality in captivity.'' So they hold their punches.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff, that may be changing. The Dragon may be focusing its fire.
</P>
<P>
   Dave McNeely writes about politics for the Austin
American-Statesman. You may contact him at
dmcneely(at)statesman.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
