<HEADER>
A4372 &Cx1f; tad-z
r t BC-TRAVEL-EUROPE03-COX     03-02 1157
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-EUROPE03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    London bridge is going up
 &HT;    By Cheryl Blackerby
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ You usually can't go wrong with sightseeing in London.
</P>
<P>
   Even the most jaded traveler can't resist the Changing of the
Guard at Buckingham Palace or the spot where the ax beheaded
unlucky royals at the Tower of London, or Madame Tussaud's Wax
Museum, where you can see how much shorter you are than Bill
Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   And now there's the new British Airways London Eye, which looks
like a humongous Ferris wheel. (Unlike the Ferris wheel, it has
enclosed motorized passenger capsules positioned on the outside of
the wheel structure, and it is supported by an A-frame from only
one side.)
</P>
<P>
   ``Americans should like it because they like rides,'' said one
passenger.
</P>
<P>
   I had to admit it _ I liked it.
</P>
<P>
   The new Millennium Bridge, the first pedestrian bridge to be
built across the Thames since the 18th century, is scheduled to
open in the spring but looks to be running behind schedule like its
sister millennium project, the London Eye.
</P>
<P>
   Londoners are a bit touchy about the Eye, which was an
embarrassment on New Year's Eve when the whole world got to see it
standing there, broken, a monument to other things in the United
Kingdom that are hard to fix.
</P>
<P>
   But they do like to talk about something else that's new, the
Millennium Dome, the world's largest structure of its kind,
covering 130 acres.
</P>
<P>
   It opened for the New Year's Eve celebration but has attracted
far fewer people than expected since then, less than half the
number projected.
</P>
<P>
   ``It takes all day to see it,'' some moan. ``What is it
anyway?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Boring.'' ``Expensive.''
</P>
<P>
   People I talked to were so outspoken about it that I didn't go.
I didn't have the time anyway, but I want to see if it's truly as
bad as that.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the problem may be the name of the exhibitions _ The
Greatest Show on Earth _ which doesn't really say what it is. In
fact, it doesn't have dancing elephants or acrobats.
</P>
<P>
   What it does have are 14 themed zones ``examining the choices
facing humankind at work, rest and play in the 21st century.''
Exhibits will close at the end of the year. Walk, don't run.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, there are West End theaters, the Tower Bridge, Thames
River cruises, the Changing of the Guard (ask at your hotel about
days), parts of Buckingham Palace that will open to the public in
August, the Changing of the Horse Guard, and shopping on Bond,
Regent and Oxford streets.
</P>
<P>
   The easiest way to see the sights is from the top of a
double-decker sightseeing bus, wind in your hair and Westminster at
your feet.
</P>
<P>
   IF YOU GO
</P>
<P>
   Information: Call (800) 462-2748 or drop by a tourist office in
London such as the one at Victoria Station.
</P>
<P>
   Hotels: I like the Lime Tree Hotel. It's only three blocks from
Victoria Station and the bus station, and a nice stroll to
Harrod's, Buckingham Palace, Hyde Park, St. James Park and more.
</P>
<P>
   Sightseeing buses: Ask at your hotel about the nearest stop. Or
buy tickets at the Tourist Office at Victoria Station.
</P>
<P>
   ATHENS' NEW RIDE: THE SUBWAY
</P>
<P>
   Dandelions grow in the crevices of ancient rocks on the side of
the Acropolis, and sparrows chirp in the olive and pine trees.
</P>
<P>
   It feels like early spring, cool not cold, and the climb up the
marble steps is exhilarating.
</P>
<P>
   The rewards at the top are wonders of the ancient world _ three
ancient temples built in the fifth century B.C. including the
glorious, marble-columned Parthenon, a testament to the golden age
of Pericles.
</P>
<P>
   A Greek school class sat in front of the building, and hands
were raised as children eagerly answered the teacher's questions.
No bad behavior on this field trip.
</P>
<P>
   A trickle of tourists _ a nice change from the crowds of summer
_ roamed the ancient buildings, their video cameras recording every
step of the way.
</P>
<P>
   Close to the Parthenon is the site of the legendary contest
between Athena and Poseidon, and the Erechtheum, a shrine to Athena
and the twin deity Poseidon-Erechtheus. Six support columns on the
south side were carved in the shape of maidens, or caryatids. (The
real ones are in the museum.)
</P>
<P>
   On previous trips here, I've hired guides, who usually are
stationed at the entrance to the Acropolis, and it's worth the
small fee to help bring the monuments to life. (Talk for a few
minutes first to make sure he or she speaks English.) But on this
trip I carried a guidebook and took my time to admire the temples
and the city stretched to the horizon beyond.
</P>
<P>
   Another way to see the Acropolis is the Sound and Light Show at
night. You sit on the terrace on the west side of Phillopappou
Hill, where ancient Athenians met in democratic assembly, and one
by one, the ancient buildings are spotlighted and their stories are
told.
</P>
<P>
   Most of Athens' ancient sites, and there are many, are within
walking distance of the Acropolis. But you need to spend several
days here to see them.
</P>
<P>
   I stayed at the foot of the Acropolis in the Plaka, the oldest
quarter in the city, where cars are not allowed on most of its
narrow, winding stone streets. If you get lost you can always look
up to get your bearings.
</P>
<P>
   Many people speak English, and if they don't, they are still
extremely helpful. I asked a woman for directions to a certain
street and she took my arm and walked with me for a block to point
out the way.
</P>
<P>
   At night you'll have a hard time finding a bad meal. At many
small restaurants you can go into the kitchen and point out what
you want. I could go to Athens and be content to do nothing but
eat.
</P>
<P>
   After dinner, I took the funicular up Mount Lycabettus, which is
exhilarating too. If you're afraid of heights, just don't look
down.
</P>
<P>
   At the top, you can walk around, get ice cream in the cafeteria
and enjoy a spectacular view of the city _ and the Acropolis.
</P>
<P>
   Standing in Syntagma Square in the heart of Athens, you can see
the Acropolis towering above the city.
</P>
<P>
   But for the newest attraction, you have to go below ground.
</P>
<P>
   Walk through glass doors in a small building near the Parliament
side of the park and take an escalator down.
</P>
<P>
   You'll see the city's new subway station, which opened early
this month. At first glance, the cavernous room looks like a
museum: gleaming marble floors, ancient pottery and statues behind
glass cases, dramatic lighting.
</P>
<P>
   Take another escalator, and you'll find the ticket counters and
subway maps, and take still another escalator and you'll see the
new red subway trains.
</P>
<P>
   There's only one main line, but it sure beats driving on the
streets above.
</P>
<P>
   IF YOU GO:
</P>
<P>
   Hotels: The Electra Palace Hotel has a rooftop bar, next to a
small swimming pool, that offers an outstanding view of the
Acropolis. Room rates are about $100. There are many small inns and
inexpensive pensions in the Plaka.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
