<HEADER>
A4373 &Cx1f; tad-z
r t BC-TRAVEL-LONDON03-COX     03-02 0561
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-LONDON03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    London from the ground up, up, up!
 &HT;    By Cheryl Blackerby
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ A big wheel is churning out big excitement in London,
but the ``Eye'' isn't all that's the talk of the town. The world's
largest observation wheel is supposed to open March 3, delayed from
New Year's because of mechanical problems. Other ``big'' events:
The completion of the new Millennium Bridge, set for spring, and
the Millennium Dome, which is already open. And the Blair baby, due
in May, has tourists all aflutter. Who says London is stodgy?
</P>
<P>
   WHEEL OF FORTUNE
</P>
<P>
   From many places in London, including the prime minister's
residence, you can see the world's largest ``observation wheel.''
At the top, riders have 25-mile views.
</P>
<P>
   The London Eye was supposed to open New Year's Day, but because
of a ``clutch problem'' in one of the capsules, it won't open until
March 3.
</P>
<P>
   The enclosed glass capsules each hold 25 people. The wheel moves
at ``walking pace,'' slowly and silently. I took a ride on a test
run, and I could see the Thames winding through neighborhoods,
Buckingham Palace, Hyde Park and even Windsor Castle.
</P>
<P>
   And is that the queen getting into a helicopter at the palace?
Maybe another royal. Take binoculars. (Or you can rent them at the
London Eye ticket counter.)
</P>
<P>
   THE BLAIR BABY
</P>
<P>
   A baby is coming to No. 10 Downing St. Prime Minister Tony Blair
and his wife, Cherie, are expecting in May.
</P>
<P>
   In London, some people think it's a bit unseemly. Mrs. Blair is
45. ``It is rather LATE, don't you think?'' commented a matron in a
restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   Others are more excited. That's the foremost thing in the minds
of the tourists gathered outside the couple's residence. ``Do they
know if it's a boy or girl?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Will she still work?''
</P>
<P>
   ``They look quite happy.''
</P>
<P>
   I LOVE LONDON FOOD
</P>
<P>
   I may be the only one in the world who loves to eat in London.
They have nouveau pub cuisine, but go for the real thing at a real
pub _ bangers (sausages) and mash (potatoes), Yorkshire pudding,
shepherd's pie (who could resist ground beef with mashed potatoes
on top?) and hot scones with clotted cream.
</P>
<P>
   And what I really love is fish and chips _ cod and potatoes
fried, then doused in malt vinegar and wrapped in paper. The grease
will drip to your elbows.
</P>
<P>
   You might want to skip the kidney pie. It has a flavor all its
own.
</P>
<P>
   CHANGING GUARDS: TWO FOR THE SHOW
</P>
<P>
   When the guards at Buckingham Palace in London go to work, they
could just say, ``Here I am, cheerio.'' But that wouldn't be any
fun for the tourists, so the guards put on a display that attracts
thousands of people, complete with a brass band and a drum section.
This is the best free show in town.
</P>
<P>
   In Athens, the soldiers who guard the Tomb of the Unknown
Soldier next to the Greek Parliament don't have a band, but they do
wear the kind of uniform that is sure to draw a crowd _ short
skirts and pointy red shoes. The guards, called evzones, do some
high kicks and a Michael Jackson-like moon walk that makes their
rubber-soled shoes squeak on the marble courtyard.
</P>
<P>
   Hard to picture either one of them seriously guarding the queen
or Greek Parliament. Instead of shooting the enemy, they could just
throw a tuba.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
