<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-02 11:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4374 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k BC-YOUNG-COLUMN03-COX     03-02 0694
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YOUNG-COLUMN03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Ride Bush's tails? GOP school board member tells Bush tales
 &HT;    By John Young
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ You say that dentists aren't known for living
dangerously. Meet San Antonio dentist Bob Offutt. He needles George
Bush without Novocain.
</P>
<P>
   Offutt is a state school board member. He's a Republican. He has
an opponent, retired teacher Dan Montgomery, in the March 14
primary. No Democrat is running.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than spend his free time campaigning for himself, in
recent weeks Offutt spent time campaigning against Bush. The Steve
Forbes campaign flew Offutt and former board member Donna Ballard
to New Hampshire and Iowa to tell Republicans how wrong Bush is
about education.
</P>
<P>
   In these days when the GOP establishment criticizes John McCain
for talking out of school, Offutt hasn't just been talking. He's
been sky-writing.
</P>
<P>
   What's he saying? He says that Bush is for centralized control
over local school policies despite words to the opposite. Offutt
says Texas' policy that ultimately will pin student promotion in
grades 3, 5 and 8 to a state basic skills test is a harbinger,
under a G.W. Bush presidency, of federal control.
</P>
<P>
   Not that it will cause conservatives to wince, but Offutt has a
point. The increasing emphasis on the Texas Assessment of Academic
Skills means more state control over what teachers do.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, Offutt, who is considered the leader of the
conservative wing of the school board, has his own inconsistencies
if local control is his aim. Board conservatives are aching to
regain control over content in state textbooks, something the Texas
Legislature took away with Bush's blessing, giving school districts
more textbook choices.
</P>
<P>
   The right wing of the school board has been at war with Bush and
the Legislature essentially from the start. In Montgomery, Offutt
faces a foe who has support from key GOP players in District 5,
including State Sen. David Sibley and State Rep. Kip Averitt.
District 5 includes McLennan, Bell and Coryell counties.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, a dilemma for Republicans. In many ways Offutt could be
considered the party's hero. He recruited a slate of fellow social
conservatives to run for the state school board. They included a
home schooler and others who kept their children out of public
schools. Whether by stealth, voter apathy or organization, Offutt's
quest produced what often has been a controlling faction. That
faction has clashed with the governor and lawmakers over curriculum
standards and textbooks.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters credit Offutt with pushing for explicit state
curricular guidelines and phonics-based reading materials. Bush and
the Texas Education Agency made adjustments to the state curricular
guidelines after conservatives charged that the guidelines were too
``fuzzy.'' Offutt and supporters don't think TEA went far enough.
</P>
<P>
   Montgomery supports Bush's school policies and accuses the
Offutt wing of ``splitting the party in two.''
</P>
<P>
   The conservatives on the board have opposed Texas' participation
in the Goals 2000 program of federal education aid to states. They
say it is a Trojan horse for federal takeover. Montgomery calls
such concerns overwrought and unfounded.
</P>
<P>
   The retired teacher and basketball coach, now in Fredericksburg
as a sales representative for Transwestern Publishing Co., said
he's been astounded by efforts of conservative groups to get him on
the record about social issues that don't relate to the school
board, such as abortion, gun control and same-sex marriages. While
calling himself conservative, he said, ``I won't demagogue social
issues.''
</P>
<P>
   On Offutt's missions to New Hampshire and Iowa, Montgomery said,
``He didn't say anything good about Forbes. He denigrated
everything Bush has done.''
</P>
<P>
   That puts Offutt in an uncomfortable spot with the ``education
governor'' sitting a few lines above him on the primary ballot. On
March 14 we find out if the DDS has drilled too deep.
</P>
<P>
   John Young is opinion page editor of the Waco Tribune-Herald.
E-mail: jyoung(at)wacotrib.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
