<HEADER>
A4379 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-MOVIES-MYDOGSKIP03-CO     03-02 0536
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-MYDOGSKIP03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Filmmaker's pet project shows a lot of heart
 &HT;    By Jim Luksic
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ ``My Dog Skip,'' based on author Willie Morris'
memoirs about his childhood dog, is coyly labeled a ``true story''
_ meaning we're again at a filmmaker's mercy to distinguish truth
from embellishment. In this case, the responsible party is Jay
Russell, who directs the mournful, coming-of-age tale with utmost
care. Almost too much.
</P>
<P>
   Our starting point, according to the voiceover narration _ a
technique so prevalent it now seems mandatory _ is the summer of
1942 in Yazoo, Miss., (home of ``10,000 souls and nothin' doing.'')
Willie (Frankie Muniz) is the lone child of protective dad Jack
(Kevin Bacon), a veteran, and adoring mother Ellen (Diane Lane).
</P>
<P>
   Next-door neighbor Dink (Luke Wilson) doubles as Willie's best
friend and the town's star athlete; he's also heading off to war.
(We could do without the patriotic, momentous slow-motion effect
that captures Dink's farewell.) The boy's loneliness is cured by a
birthday gift, the title terrier (wonderful shot, from inside the
wrapped cage, of the kid's reaction). Skip soon helps Willie meet
beautiful classmate Rivers (Caitlin Wachs), who appreciates his
qualities _ unlike the trio of neighborhood paper tigers: Big Boy,
Henjie and Spit.
</P>
<P>
   The leisurely narrative is given a shot in the arm when a foray
into the local cemetery exposes two bootlegging thugs. Another plot
turn, and it's a doozy, involves the once infallible Dink; his
return home will test Willie's maturity. Our little hero, it comes
to light, demonstrates more backbone than his pushy peers do.
</P>
<P>
   Too often Russell takes liberties, such as with the
fife-and-drum anthemic score, rarely muting it. Perhaps true to
life, Skip proves to be as much a nuisance as a joy. This type of
soap lingers throughout, softening the impact of life's hard
knocks. (The kid's introduction to playing football recalls too
readily a scene in ``Forrest Gump.'')
</P>
<P>
   Spotlighting the loyal canine, something the mistitled ``A Dog
of Flanders'' inexplicably neglected, seems altogether sensible
herein. A deer-hunting incident portends a later development that
hits closer to home. There's also a nice, subtle point about
animals being oblivious to racial segregation.
</P>
<P>
   It's fair to question why such sizable stars as Bacon and Lane
are bumped to the margins for a considerable chunk of time. But the
affable Muniz, star of TV's ``Malcolm in the Middle,'' holds his
own amid the nostalgia. The actor looks quite the throwback
himself.
</P>
<P>
   Behind the lens Russell harbors a knack for milieu, with a
distinct evocation of time/place, lovingly shot in warm, bright
golden hues. And the movie doesn't fall prey to Hollywood's
compulsion to spring nonstop entertainment and gimmicks upon us.
</P>
<P>
   When all is said and done, there's no debating ``My Dog Skip''
has its heart in the right place. Whether the tale justifies a
major motion picture is another matter. Its stilted machinations
and sticky-sweet nature would seem ideal for an after-school
television special.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
