<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-CHRISTIAN03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Woman shares faith through books
 &HT;    By Christine Moran
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROCKY MOUNT, N.C. _ As the plane went down, Janice Gravely
prayed for a miracle. Her husband, Edmund, sat unconscious in the
pilot's chair, the victim of a fatal heart attack. Gravely radioed
for help, but no one replied. In a moment of panic, she unknowingly
broke two-way contact with the ground. No one could respond because
no one knew what frequency she was on.
</P>
<P>
   Gravely tried to fly the plane, but she didn't have any
experience as a pilot. The plane went down in a patch of woods. The
crash should have killed Gravely, but she survived and today shares
her story.
</P>
<P>
   In 1990, just eight years after the crash, Gravely published an
autobiography titled ``Won't somebody help me!'' She begins the
book by recounting the day of the crash. She goes on to share her
story about how a young woman from Los Angeles came to live in
Rocky Mount.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wrote the book because there were so many opportunities to
tell my story but so little time,'' Gravely said. ``I thought I'd
be able to include many more details in a written account of my
life. I also wanted to bring glory to God for all he has done and
continues to do for me.''
</P>
<P>
   Gravely's faith in God grew after the plane crash. She has
always been a woman of faith, however. Gravely has four children,
two boys and two girls. Her youngest child was diagnosed with
leukemia when she was 9 years old. By the power of God, Gravely
believes her child was healed.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Lord walked with us through our daughter's ordeal,''
Gravely said. ``We watched her endure years of chemotherapy. We
also watched the Lord heal her.''
</P>
<P>
   Gravely didn't put the pen down afterthe first book was
written. A divine inspiration prompted her to write another book.
</P>
<P>
   Gravely's second book, ``Ground Level Christianity,'' was
published in 1999. It's a collection of true stories she gathered
from people she knows, most of whom live in Rocky Mount.
</P>
<P>
   ``The stories illustrate the principle of Christianity,''
Gravely said. ``I think people can learn more from these real life
stories than they can from a 20-minute sermon. The book truly is a
lesson on life.''
</P>
<P>
   Gravely doesn't know what the future holds, but she said she is
looking forward to it. She'll go wherever the Lord sends her and do
whatever it is he needs her to do.
</P>
<P>
   For now, though, she said she couldn't be happier living in
Rocky Mount, surrounded by her children and her grandchildren.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
