<HEADER>
A4383 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-BOOKS-FISHING03-COX     03-02 0676
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-FISHING03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    McGuane avoids the faults of many fish stories
 &HT;    By Scott Hiaasen
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ What is it about fishing that compels so
many people to write about it? It could be that moments spent on
the water seem, to the fisherman, magnified in their beauty and
drama. Or it may be that no one who takes fishing seriously ever
gets to spend enough time doing it, so we must sublimate with fish
stories. Armchair anglers make an insatiable audience.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, most writing about fishing isn't very good. The
lowliest is of the how-to variety _ anecdotes of 30-fish days
preceding sponsor-heavy tips on how to clean out a lake.
</P>
<P>
   The more narrative efforts tend to be overwrought variations on
``The Old Man and the Sea,'' wherein our sport matches wits with a
quarry so cunning or large that the battle becomes epic. The story
usually climaxes with an epiphany along the lines of, ``catching
the fish isn't everything.''
</P>
<P>
   Luckily, a few writers have the talent and intellect to avoid
these pitfalls, and perhaps none is better than Thomas McGuane.
</P>
<P>
   In ``The Longest Silence,'' a collection of 33 essays on fishing
written over 30 years, McGuane takes us from the streams of
Michigan to the shallow banks of the Florida Keys to the salmon
rivers of the Arctic Circle.
</P>
<P>
   At nearly every bend, he manages to give the sport a fresh
perspective, to be thoughtful without being trite, sincere without
being precious. McGuane approaches his fishing with discipline and
reverence, but he knows that once you're out on the water, it's as
much about folly and luck.
</P>
<P>
   What McGuane wants most from his fishing may best be illustrated
by what's absent from his stories. He does not tangle with the
feisty largemouth bass, a fish so democratic in its distribution
that it has spawned professional tournament circuits inviting
anglers to dress like shuttle astronauts. Nor does he spend manly
hours straining his back against the giant blue marlin of Hemingway
lore.
</P>
<P>
   McGuane's ethic is summed up best in the title story, about his
lonely, obsessive treks through the Keys back country, trying to
catch the wariest of saltwater fish, the permit, on a fly:
</P>
<P>
   ``What is most emphatic in angling is made so by the long
silences _ the unproductive periods. For the ardent fisherman,
progress is toward the kinds of fishing that are never productive
in the sense of the blood riots of the hunting-and-fishing
periodicals.''
</P>
<P>
   In this vein, McGuane fishes almost exclusively with a fly rod.
His favorite fish, like the permit, are famously uncooperative, and
his angling destinations exceedingly remote. He is searching for a
perfect moment, and he's willing to spend fruitless days on the
water to find it.
</P>
<P>
   Taken as a travelogue, you can watch, page by page, as callous
civilization and environmental apathy chase McGuane farther and
farther away: away from the Winnebago-lined trout streams of
Paradise Valley in Montana, away from the Jet Ski drone of the Key
West flats.
</P>
<P>
   He finds great salmon fishing in Russia and Iceland, and
steelhead in British Columbia, but he wryly notes that he wouldn't
have had to go so far had America not allowed its own rivers _ once
the most abundant _ to be strangled.
</P>
<P>
   For the most part, however, McGuane avoids the didactic, and
there are many flashes of the dark wit that marks his novels, such
as in one essay when a trout runs downriver with all but the last
coil of line on his reel: ``It was like literature! He paused long
enough for me to consider how wonderful life could be when it had
great literature-style items, such as coincidence and fate and
elegant ironies. Then, in that moment of anti-magic, when
literature is converted to the far more familiar aspects of the
land in which we actually live and breathe and spend our days, the
great trout turned and straightened my hook.''
</P>
<P>
   See? Sometimes catching the fish isn't everything.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
