<DOCNO> NYT20000302.0064 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-02 11:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4384 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-YOUNG-HARRYPOTTER03-C     03-02 0522
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YOUNG-HARRYPOTTER03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The truth about Harry
 &HT;    By Roz Young
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ I was impressed some months ago when ``Harry
Potter and the Sorcerer's Stone'' rose right to the top of the best
seller list and stayed there for weeks and weeks. It was soon
joined by three other Harry Potter books.
</P>
<P>
   The stories about Harry Potter are children's stories, but who
is laying out cash to keep them at the top of the list? The
parents.
</P>
<P>
   Why are they doing it? It's a fad. ``If your child has the Harry
Potter books, then my child must have them, too,'' say the mothers
and fathers.
</P>
<P>
   Before I bought a Harry Potter book, I told myself that after
all, there are many fantasy books ostensibly for children that have
become classics because they say something to adults about
selfishness, mindlessness and cowardice, as in the ``Oz'' books,
madness and injustice in ``Alice,'' stupidity, intellectual
trickery and simple-mindedness and enchantment in ``Pooh.''
</P>
<P>
   I remember as an 11-year-old the delight I felt when one day
Eeyore was standing in his part of the forest looking at some
sticks on the ground. Piglet came to see what he was looking at.
Two of the sticks touched at one end but not the other and the
third stick was laid across them. ``Do you know what this is?''
asked Eeyore.
</P>
<P>
   ``No,'' said Piglet.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an A.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh,'' said Piglet.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not O, A,'' said Eeyore severely. ``Do you know what A means,
little Piglet?''
</P>
<P>
   ``No, I don't.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It means Learning, it means Education, it means all the things
that you and Pooh haven't got. That's what A means. People come and
go in this forest and they walk to and fro, saying `Ha Ha!' But do
they know anything about A? It's just three sticks to them. But to
the Educated, it's a great and glorious A.''
</P>
<P>
   I was delighted because along with Eeyore, I knew what A meant.
</P>
<P>
   You can read all the Harry Potter books from now until Sunday
and not find characters like Eeyore and Piglet.
</P>
<P>
   ``The purpose of reading,'' said William Safire the other day in
our newspaper, ``once you get the hang of it, is not merely to
follow the action of a plot but to learn about characters, explore
different ideas and enter other minds.'' He is right. Grown-ups who
buy the Harry Potter books for their children but read them for
themselves find the books are written to entertain children, which
is laudable, but have nothing to say to adults.
</P>
<P>
   J.K. Rowling, author of the Harry Potter series, won the prize
for the best children's books. But the top literary prize went to
Irish poet and Nobel Laureate Seamus Heaney for a translation of
``Beowulf.'' This is as it should be, and we say bully for the
committee of judges who were not seduced by the publishing record
of all time into giving the Harry Potter books the top prize. On
the other hand, how many will read Harry Potter and how many will
read ``Beowulf''? The answer is disquieting.
</P>
<P>
   Roz Young is a columnist, author, historian and lifelong
Dayton-area resident.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
