<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-02 11:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4386 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-BOOKS-CONSPIRACY03-CO     03-02 0928
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-CONSPIRACY03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Author intent on making impeachment story a good guys/bad guys
tale
 &HT;    By George Bennett
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Compared to that other bestseller about
presidential libidinousness and mendacity _ Ken Starr's steamy
``Referral to the United States House of Representatives'' _
Jeffrey Toobin's Starr-bashing impeachment saga is both better
written and more pithily argued.
</P>
<P>
   Toobin has an eye for telling detail and an ability to connect
the far-flung dots of a complex story with a droll narrative style.
He's both authoritative and succinct when discussing the legal
system's takeover of the political system or the history of sexual
harassment law.
</P>
<P>
   But ``A Vast Conspiracy'' ultimately disappoints. In his zeal to
bury Starr and other Clinton pursuers under an avalanche of damning
facts and anecdotes, Toobin minimizes the president's
responsibility for his near downfall. The result isn't as one-sided
as the independent counsel's 1998 bodice-ripper, but there's a
Starr-ish imbalance.
</P>
<P>
   Toobin, whose ``The Run of His Life'' was the definitive O.J.
Simpson trial book, isn't exactly an apologist for President
Clinton (``dishonesty and self-pity ... are among the touchstones
of his character,'' he writes). But he's intent on making the
impeachment story a good guys/bad guys tale. So Clinton gets a
white hat.
</P>
<P>
   ``(The) most astonishing fact in this story may be this one: in
spite of his consistently reprehensible behavior, Clinton was, by
comparison, the good guy in this struggle,'' he says early in the
book.
</P>
<P>
   Toobin's bad guys are the stock characters of a James Carville
rant: Clinton-haters, right-wing fanatics, book deal-seeking
opportunists, zealous prosecutors and the sex- and scandal-obsessed
media.
</P>
<P>
   He skewers the bad guys with devastating details and vigorous
skepticism. But with Clinton's enablers and apologists, Toobin
tends to be softer and more credulous.
</P>
<P>
   We're treated to a meticulous retracing of the calls and faxes
and meetings between Linda Tripp and literary agent provocateur
Lucianne Goldberg and their accomplices. Even a staunch
anti-Clintonite would have to find Toobin's portrait of a scheming
Tripp more plausible than Tripp's own ``I am you'' self-martyrdom.
</P>
<P>
   But as unsympathetic a character as she was, a complete picture
of Tripp and the swirl of controversy around her should at least
mention the Pentagon's leaking of Tripp's confidential personnel
file _ certainly a revealing example of the good guys' ability to
get down and dirty.
</P>
<P>
   Toobin's principal bad guy, Starr, is depicted convincingly as a
prosecutorial novice whose lack of instinct leads him to substitute
group think for his own judgment. This translated into an obsession
with projecting ``toughness,'' and it led to PR blunders (such as
making a First Amendment martyr out of Clinton attack dog Sidney
Blumenthal) and critical strategic disasters (such as failing to
wrap up an early immunity deal with Monica Lewinsky).
</P>
<P>
   He's less sure of Starr's ideological underpinnings, but he's
certain there's something dangerous there.
</P>
<P>
   Toobin describes Starr as a ``committed political conservative
who stood outspokenly opposed to Clinton on virtually every
controversial issue of the day'' and _ in the very next paragraph _
as someone who ``was no ideologue himself, (but) he had always
surrounded himself with them.''
</P>
<P>
   If there's a middle-aged man with an unenlightened attitude
toward women in this saga, Toobin maintains it's the hymn-singing
prosecutor rather than the skirt-chasing president.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 29 attorneys who represented Starr's office before the
grand jury, Toobin reports, 25 were men. Out of 121 sessions with
witnesses before the grand jury, women led the questioning only six
times.
</P>
<P>
   It's noted that a female prosecutor wasn't personally
congratulated by Starr after some Whitewater convictions while her
male colleagues were. And while Starr heard everyone out in his
protracted office deliberations, Toobin says, ``at the end of the
process, ... one thing remained the same in any organization Starr
had led: he followed the advice of men.''
</P>
<P>
   In contrast to this rap sheet of gender crimes, Toobin reaches
to find something more than middle-aged randiness in the
president's relationship with the star-struck intern.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a peculiar way, one could see that Clinton cared for Monica
Lewinsky,'' Toobin writes of the president's videotaped deposition.
``He generally gave an embarrassed smile when he spoke of her, but
there was, if not gallantry, a kind of affection as well.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to talking on the phone with congressmen while
receiving Lewinsky's ministrations, the president ``had listened to
Monica complain about her parents.''
</P>
<P>
   That's multi-tasking.
</P>
<P>
   Some philandering can be seen as betraying a deep-seated hatred
of women, Toobin notes, but Clinton ``was not a misogynist.'' In
fact, Toobin finds, Clinton displayed ``in other circumstances, his
clear respect and admiration for women.''
</P>
<P>
   This vaguely gallant, affectionate respecter of women behaved
shabbily, Toobin concedes, but didn't deserve the venomous excesses
of his enemies. Even without the gallantry bit, the American public
and the political system arrived at more or less the same
conclusion.
</P>
<P>
   The legal principle behind this, Toobin notes, is called
``proportionality.'' It's too bad ``A Vast Conspiracy'' doesn't
have more of it.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
