<HEADER>
A4387 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-EYMAN-ON-BOOKS03-COX     03-02 0455
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EYMAN-ON-BOOKS03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    George W. bio reissued by Soft Skull
 &HT;    By Scott Eyman
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ For all those who missed out on the
first printing, the St. Martin's Press disaster of last year,
``Fortunate Son,'' the cut-and-paste biography of George W. Bush
written by an ex-felon, has been reprinted in paperback by an
outfit with the unpromising name of Soft Skull Press.
</P>
<P>
   This was the book, you will remember, that alleged that Bush was
arrested for cocaine possession in 1972 but had the arrest expunged
because of his family's connections. Soft Skull told Publisher's
Weekly that the author, one J.H. Hatfield, had proved to their
satisfaction that his sources existed.
</P>
<P>
   Also resurfacing, but without the echoes of shame and ignominy,
is Ellery Queen, created 70 years ago by two cousins named
Frederick Dannay and Manfred Lee. ``The Tragedy of Errors''
contains the last Ellery Queen novel, as well as six uncollected
short stories. Half the book is taken up by tributes to the two men
by family, friends and current mystery writers. For more
information, contact Crippen and Landru, P.O. Box 9315, Norfolk, VA
23505.
</P>
<P>
   ROCK ON ...
</P>
<P>
   The Grateful Dead, or what's left of them, have formed Grateful
Dead Books and issued ``Spirit Into Sound'' by drummer Mickey Hart,
who also doubles as editor-in-chief. Grateful Dead books will be
predominantly marketed through the band's Web site, www.dead.net,
which receives a million hits a month.
</P>
<P>
   The imprint will issue a book called ``Art of the Dead'' next
year, and ``Spirit Into Sound'' will be reissued with an
accompanying CD next spring. They'll also be reprinting Hart's
first two books ``Drumming at the Edge of Magic'' and ``Planet
Drum.''
</P>
<P>
   WELLES, HOUSMAN AND CO. ...
</P>
<P>
   Tim Robbins based his recent, botched film ``Cradle Will Rock''
on a chapter from ``Arena,'' a memoir by Hallie Flanagan, the
remarkable woman who ran the Federal Theater Project in the '30s.
``Arena'' has been out of print since 1992, but Limelight is
bringing it out again soon, with an introduction by Robbins
(nothing happens in this country without a celebrity's endorsement
...).
</P>
<P>
   ``Buena Vista Social Club'' is a paperback companion to the
wonderful documentary about Cuban musicians that spawned a
soundtrack CD that sold 800,000 copies. With text by director Wim
Wenders, the book will include all the lyrics to the songs as well
as photos shot during the production by guitarist Ry Cooder and his
son.
</P>
<P>
   QUOTE UNQUOTE ...
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we ought to read only the kind of books that wound and
stab us.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Franz Kafka
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
