<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-02 11:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4391 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-VIN-DIESEL03-COX     03-02 0903
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIN-DIESEL03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Timing, talent fuel Vin Diesel's success
 &HT;    By Dave Larsen
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Vin Diesel's career is firing on all cylinders.
</P>
<P>
   The muscular, clean-pated actor stars in two films, ``Pitch
Black'' and ``Boiler Room,'' that opened simultaneously last month
to good reviews and better-than-expected box office sales.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Pitch Black,'' Diesel played Riddick, a murderous convict
charged with safeguarding the lives of spaceship passengers who
crash-land on a remote planet inhabited by deadly nocturnal
creatures. USA Today's Susan Wloszczyna called him ``the best
reason to root for a bad guy since Arnie in the original
`Terminator'.''
</P>
<P>
   The gravel-voiced New York native displayed a different side in
``Boiler Room,'' donning an expensive suit to play a fast-talking,
foul-mouthed millionaire stock broker.
</P>
<P>
   ``The last weekend was amazing,'' Diesel said from Los Angeles,
seven days after the Feb. 18 opening of both films. Their
synchronous arrival was a coincidence, he said. ``No one expected
that. No one probably wanted that.''
</P>
<P>
   It turned out well for Diesel, who earned raves for two
dissimilar roles.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it was really lucky in that respect,'' he said. ``That
people were able to see such a diversity within the opening weekend
if they wanted to. That really worked to my advantage.''
</P>
<P>
   The 32-year-old actor first came to attention as
Italian-American Pvt. Carpazo in Stephen Spielberg's Academy
Award-winning film, ``Saving Private Ryan.'' Spielberg created the
role for Diesel after seeing ``Multi-Facial,'' a short film that
Diesel wrote, directed, produced, financed and starred in that
screened at the 1995 Cannes Film Festival.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Diesel provided the voice for the title character of
the award-winning animated family feature ``The Iron Giant.''
</P>
<P>
   The son of a father who taught theater and an astrologist
mother, Diesel was raised in Manhattan. His real surname reportedly
is Vincent. His first name remains undisclosed.
</P>
<P>
   He chose the sci-fi thriller ``Pitch Black'' for his first
starring vehicle because of Riddick's character arc, ``and the fact
that he's so incredibly multidimensional.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a superhero of sorts,'' Diesel said of the role, which
required him to go mano a alien with bat-winged, razor-jawed
monsters. ``He's an antihero. He's a character that reminded me of
some of those heroes that I had. The `Mad Max' character and the
`Terminator' character and all these fun characters that empowered
me as a kid.''
</P>
<P>
   The film's character-driven approach appealed to Diesel.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought that `Pitch Black,' the overall script, offered a
relatively new approach to sci-fi filmmaking _ or at least an
approach that was nostalgic of those great films in the past,'' he
said. ``Because this film didn't rely _ even while we were shooting
the film, we weren't relying solely on the special effects. We
wanted to create a film that could stand on its own, independent of
the creatures and the sci-fi element.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Pitch Black'' opened at No. 4, earning an impressive $13.4
million in its opening weekend. ``The film had the highest
per-screen-average last week over every other film,'' Diesel said,
proudly. ``So the studio is super-excited about that.''
</P>
<P>
   The ``Alien''-inspired thriller remained in the top 5 its second
weekend, earning $7.1 million.
</P>
<P>
   Shot for $25 million, ``Pitch Black's'' success puts Diesel in
the high-octane fast lane.
</P>
<P>
   Hollywood is governed by the numbers, the actor said. ``Pitch
Black's'' strong opening and high per-screen-average makes him
suddenly viable for starring roles.
</P>
<P>
   ``Boiler Room,'' an independent film that premiered at this
year's Sundance Film Festival and opened at No. 8 with $6.7
million, may keep him from being typecast as an action hero.
</P>
<P>
   ``I did the `Boiler Room' job for a bunch of reasons, but the
fact that I was wearing a suit definitely was a bonus,'' Diesel
said. ``Because that directly contrasts that formidable character
in `Pitch Black.' It adds a nice balance, I think.''
</P>
<P>
   Hollywood has deluged him with offers, but with them comes more
pressure to choose the right role. ``I already am very selective,
but I think with this in mind, I have to be that much more
selective,'' he said. ``Especially because longevity in this career
is something that you have to work at.''
</P>
<P>
   Diesel recently wrapped production on ``Knockaround Guys,'' due
in November, in which he stars opposite John Malkovich, Dennis
Hopper and ``Saving Private Ryan's'' Barry Pepper.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all play gangsters,'' he said. ``It's about these gangsters
that end up in Montana.''
</P>
<P>
   Diesel is preparing several projects as a writer-director,
including ``Doormen,'' based on his experience as a nightclub
bouncer. His feature debut, ``Strays'' _ which he wrote, directed,
produced and starred in _ competed at the 1997 Sundance Film
Festival.
</P>
<P>
   But with his career shifting into overdrive, Diesel plans to
stay in front of the camera.
</P>
<P>
   ``This will definitely give me more clout to produce films
and/or direct them,'' he said. ``But there are a lot of good
projects out there that I may go into starring in first. You can
always direct. You can direct when you're 50. So I've got to kind
of take advantage of all these great roles now.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
