<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000302.0072 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-02 11:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4394 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k BC-GLASS-COLUMN-$ADV05-C     03-02 0593
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLASS-COLUMN-$ADV05-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: THE SEARCH FOR CYBERSOULS
 &HT;    Moving in (k) commentary and (f) financial categories for
release
 &HT;    Sunday, March 5.
 &HT;    By ANDREW J. GLASS
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The other day, Gerald Levin waxed rhapsodic over
the future of the Internet. Levin heads Time Warner, an old-line
media company seeking to reinvent itself by hooking up with America
Online, a hot ticket to cyberspace.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be hard for me to exaggerate the implications of the
Internet revolution,'' Levin told senators at a hearing called to
review the pending mega-merger.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the first time in our human history,'' Levin said, ``we
have at our disposal a universal, limitless connection that no
government, no corporation or centralized agency can control
because every user has the ability to publish and to offer
something new.''
</P>
<P>
   OK, I'm persuaded. You can even read reports online that peg the
Time Warner-AOL deal as little more than a bloated stock play. But
you needn't be a Wall Street bear or a Rust Belt technophobe to
ponder whether this revolt could stand a reality test.
</P>
<P>
   Take the guy who auctioned off a kidney on eBay last year. The
bidding topped out at $5.7 million before the auctioneers put a
halt to it because there's a federal law against trafficking in
human organs.
</P>
<P>
   Moving to a higher plane, a few days ago an 18-year-old Canadian
hopped on eBay to sell his soul. But the spoilsports canceled that
caper as well, arguing it's impossible to prove that his soul
actually exists.
</P>
<P>
   If it did, a natural buyer would be ``The Unholy Trinity,'' an
outfit based in Beverly Hills, which owns ``devil.com'' as an
Internet domain name. Those folks haven't done much with their $35
buy, completed in 1995 when only 19 million souls used the
Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Nowadays there are more than 200 million. ``That number,'' Levin
predicts, ``will cross one billion by mid-decade, led by AOL's
easy-to-use consumer-friendly service.''
</P>
<P>
   That's also persuasive. As Steve Case, Levin's would-be partner
put it, ``anyone with access to a computer and a modem can visit
any one of our 800 million Web sites, in just about every language,
covering every topic you could imagine.''
</P>
<P>
   But does our soulful world truly need a site such as
speakersdirect.com, which lets people select a celebrity, make an
offer online and carry him or her off in a virtual shopping cart?
</P>
<P>
   If it does, then there are at least four reasons why I would
book Case _ although his name has yet to appear in the glitterati
cyber-roster.
</P>
<P>
   First, since he lives nearby, I'd save on travel fees. (Booking,
say, Jeffrey Archer, the British novelist, who is listed, could set
you back $9,600 for a first-class ticket from London.)
</P>
<P>
   Second, since Case's stock portfolio is already worth billions,
his patter might be quite reasonably priced. (To book Archer
requires anywhere between $50,001 and $75,000.)
</P>
<P>
   Third, since Case has volunteered to let Levin run the combined
company, he might have more time on his hands to give a speech _
between, that is, appearances to defend the soul of the merged firm
before wary lawmakers.
</P>
<P>
   And fourth, the speakers' site can be easily plugged into an AOL
start page, further simplifying the bidding process. Proposed AOL
keywords: Enough already.
</P>
<P>
   Andrew J. Glass is a Washington-based columnist for Cox
Newspapers. His
</P>
<P>
   e-mail address is aglass(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
