<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-02 11:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4406 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-BBN-ROCKER-COX     03-02 0686
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-ROCKER-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Rocker rejoins Braves, meets with teammates, reads apology
 &HT;    By Carroll Rogers
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Kissimmee, Fla. _ John Rocker arrived for spring training today
and began the process of patching up his strained relationship with
his coaches and teammates.
</P>
<P>
   Rocker met with his teammates for a half-hour today after his
suspension was reduced by baseball arbitrator Shyam Das on
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, he addressed the media for three minutes, reading a
copy of his apology that ran in today's Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Rocker, appearing in his batting practice uniform, read his
statement, which was hand-written on the back of a Braves roster,
and then left, leaving Braves' General Manager John Schuerholz to
answer questions of the 100 or so reporters gathered at the
basketball fieldhouse at the Disney sports complex.
</P>
<P>
   Rocker's statement ended with: ``I feel the arbitration process
was a fair one and I will respect and abide by its results. At this
point in time, I want and need to focus on helping my team. I
recognize that this situation will not simply go away, but please
understand that I will have no further comment on this matter.''
</P>
<P>
   Rocker then joined the rest of the Braves on the field for the
first time since the World Series. He played catch with fellow
reliever Rudy Seanez.
</P>
<P>
   His arrival came a day after arbitrator Das cut the reliever's
suspension in half, ruling he should sit out the first 14 days of
the regular season for his offensive statements regarding gays,
minorities and foreigners.
</P>
<P>
   Schuerholz discussed the clubhouse meeting between Rocker and
his teammates, saying, ``In this clubhouse, there are a lot of very
good leaders, and I think their influence in this situation will be
very helpful.''
</P>
<P>
   Schuerholz characterized the team's feelings: ``In their minds,
it has been fairly dealt with and fairly resolved in the
clubhouse.''
</P>
<P>
   He said the decision by Rocker to read a statement and take no
questions ``was John's preferred format, and he felt comfortable
with this.''
</P>
<P>
   Rocker can pitch in a game as early as April 18, against the
Phillies at Turner Field, as opposed to the May 1 date originally
imposed by commissioner Bud Selig.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves met for 40 minutes regarding Rocker after their
workout on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's what I've said all along, and it seems to be the case
with other guys, which is I forgive him for what he said,'' Tom
Glavine said before the meeting. ``We'll have to see how things go
from here on out. He still has a lot of bridges to mend. We said
we're willing to give him the opportunity, so we'll see what
happens. We'll see what he does with it.''
</P>
<P>
   Rocker, who saved 38 games last season, might not be in the
clear yet. Schuerholz hinted Wednesday that Rocker still might be
traded. When asked whether Rocker would return to his role as
closer April 18, Schuerholz said, ``If John regains his
effectiveness and remains with us, he'll have a very good chance to
be our closer.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll all be better off to get him in here and deal with the
initial onslaught now and be done with it, rather than four weeks
from now,'' Glavine said.
</P>
<P>
   Schuerholz acknowledged that other teams had expressed interest
in Rocker. Among those is believed to be Montreal, who would send
the Braves closer Ugueth Urbina and a pitcher for Rocker and
starter Bruce Chen.
</P>
<P>
   Rocker, who agreed to terms with the Braves on Tuesday for a
one-year deal believed to be worth $350,000, had his fine reduced
from $20,000 to $500.
</P>
<P>
   Selig was angry about both reductions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I disagree with the decision of Arbitrator Das,'' Selig said
in a statement. ``It does not reflect any understanding of or
sensitivity to the important social responsibility that baseball,
an institution that has endured for more than 100 years, has to the
public. It completely ignores the sensibilities of those groups
maligned by Mr. Rocker and disregards the player's position as a
role model for children.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
