A4435 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-HYACINTH03-COX     03-02 0445
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HYACINTH03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    PERUVIAN FLY MAY BE CALLED TO HYACINTH WARS
 &HT;    By JEFF NESMITH
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A tiny Peruvian fly, so small it could perch on the
head of a pin, is being studied as a possible recruit in the war on
imported water hyacinths.
</P>
<P>
   So far, U.S. Department of Agriculture scientists are unwilling
to bring the fly to the United States. Further tests will be
required to confirm indications it feeds on nothing but hyacinths,
said entomologist Ted D. Center of the agency's Aquatic Plant
Control Research Unit in Fort Lauderdale, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   ``It looks very promising at this point,'' Center said Wednesday
in a telephone interview.
</P>
<P>
   Dense mats of water hyacinths infest hundreds of ponds, lakes
and streams throughout the south from Texas to the Carolinas, plus
California and Hawaii. They damage water quality, block boat travel
and clog water pumping stations.
</P>
<P>
   In Florida alone, more than $5 million is spent every year
spraying herbicide on floating aquatic plants, primarily hyacinths.
</P>
<P>
   Native to South America, water hyacinths can spread when parts
of a colony break off and sprout in new areas. Entomologists,
assuming that areas where the plant originated would have the
largest number of its natural enemies, reasoned that upstream
reaches of the Amazon River basin would be a good place to look.
</P>
<P>
   Exploring Amazon tributaries in Peru last year, they found a
flourishing collection of hyacinth eaters and collected hundreds of
samples in a week. The collection included the current candidate, a
previously undiscovered species from a group of insects known to
entomologists as Thrypticus.
</P>
<P>
   The insect is being studied in cages in Argentina, the
department's Agricultural Research Service announced Wednesday.
After adults breed, hordes of their offspring start digging into
the hyacinths' stems, Center said.
</P>
<P>
   Another insect from Peru, a small ``plant hopper,'' also is
being studied in Argentina, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The USDA released three species of hyacinth-eating insects in
the 1970s. Although these bugs are helping to reduce hyacinth
spread, ``we need more, we need better,'' Center said.
</P>
<P>
   He estimated it will be three years before entomologists feel it
will be safe to release the new flies in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Hyacinths produce lush leaves and beautiful blue-to-lavender
flowers, which have often been brought home by tourists. That's
apparently how the plant reached the United States in the late 19th
century.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Nesmith's e-mail address is jeffn(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
