<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRIVIA-Q&AMP;A-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LET'S CAUCUS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROGERS CADENHEAD 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: What was the exact vote count for each of the candidates in
the Iowa caucuses? I've heard under 2,000 people voted on the
Democratic side.
</P>
<P>
   _ D.K., Arlington, Texas
</P>
<P>
   A: Neither party has released exact vote counts for the
caucuses, which are tabulated in a more informal manner than
primary voting.
</P>
<P>
   Out of 61,000 people who voted in the Iowa Democratic party
caucus this year, 63.4 percent voted for Al Gore and 35.0 percent
for Bill Bradley.
</P>
<P>
   On the night of the Iowa caucus, the Democratic Party released
the delegate count for each candidate rather than vote totals:
1,269 for Gore, 698 for Bradley and 33 uncommitted out of 2,000
total delegates.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people want to turn the Iowa caucus into a primary,''
said Kim Warkenten, executive directory of the Iowa Democratic
Party. ``People elect a certain number of delegates in each
precinct.''
</P>
<P>
   There were around 86,300 votes cast in the Iowa Republican
caucus, with George W. Bush receiving 41 percent, Steve Forbes
receiving 30.5 percent, Alan Keyes 14.3 percent, Gary Bauer 8.5
percent, John McCain 4.7 percent and Orrin Hatch 1 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Can you tell me what Clark Howard's latest book is and
whether he is still writing?
</P>
<P>
   _ L.J., via the Internet
</P>
<P>
   A: Crippen and Landru is publishing Howard's first short-story
collection in April: ``Challenge the Widow-Maker and Other Stories
of People in Peril.''
</P>
<P>
   If you can't find the book at area stores under ISBN
1-8859-4139-0, you can order it from Crippen and Landru for $18.50
at Box 9315, Norfolk, VA 23505, or the Web site
www.crippenlandru.com.
</P>
<P>
   Howard, 66, has written more than 20 novels and true-crime
nonfiction books, winning the Edgar Allan Poe and Ellery Queen
magazine awards for his short stories. You can write to him at Box
1527, Palm Springs, CA 92263.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Where can I write to Jim Dougherty, the first husband of
Marilyn Monroe?
</P>
<P>
   _ M.D., via the Internet
</P>
<P>
   A: You can write to him at Box 157, Sabbatus, ME 04280,
according to the president of the Marilyn Remembered fan club in
Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Dougherty, who wrote ``The Secret Happiness of Marilyn Monroe''
in 1976, spoke at a club meeting about five years ago, group
President Greg Schreiner said.
</P>
<P>
   Monroe was 16 and Dougherty was 21 when they married on June 19,
1942. He joined the Merchant Marine and was sent overseas in 1944,
and they divorced in 1946 shortly after she began modeling.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's been married twice since then _ both times happily
married _ and was a policeman in different areas of the country,''
Schreiner said. ``He supposedly has another book to be published
soon.''
</P>
<P>
   (Rogers Cadenhead writes a trivia column for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. He can be reached at the Star-Telegram, Box 1870,
Fort Worth, Texas 76101; or by E-mail at trivia(at)prefect.com.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com)
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-02-00 1206EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
