<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; Thursday, March 2, 2000 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; EDITORS: &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Hearst News Service will file these stories for Friday. If
you have questions, please call Tim Spence at 202-298-6920.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (``HNS'' appears in all sluglines.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   NY-GROWTH (Albany, N.Y.) _ For the first time in more than four
decades, New York state outpaced the nation in job growth, and much
of upstate New York shared in the trend, Gov. George Pataki
reports. By JAY JOCHNOWITZ.
</P>
<P>
   GAY-MARRIAGE (San Francisco) _ Opponents of Proposition 22, the
anti-gay marriage initiative on the California ballot Tuesday, are
going for the jugular with an explosive new TV ad that compares
supporters of the measure with a fringe group of gay-haters from
Kansas. BY CAROL NESS.
</P>
<P>
   CANDIDATE-PORN (Houston) _ A Republican candidate for state
</P>
<P>
   representative wrote and appeared in a soft-core adult film
featuring women jogging naked through a Houston neighborhood. By
JULIE MASON.
</P>
<P>
   FREE-INMATE (Houston) _ U.S. District Judge David Hittner orders
state officials to make a decision to free or retry death row
inmate Calvin Burdine within five days. Hittner threw out his
conviction last year because his attorney had slept through much of
the trial. The state failed to bring charges against Burdine, and
he has petitioned for release. Burdine, 46, has been on death row
for fatally stabbing his roommate. By DEBORAH TEDFORD.
</P>
<P>
   ANNA-NICOLE-SMITH (Houston) _ The trial in which Anna Nicole
Smith is claiming she is owed half of her deceased billionaire's
husband estate is postponed until Sept. 1 because of an appellate
court ruling Wednesday. By RON NISSIMOV.
</P>
<P>
   SF-BAY-STUDY (San Francisco) _ Nearly a century ago, the
steamship Albatross patrolled the far reaches of wild San Francisco
Bay, collecting and classifying marine life as part of a nationwide
scientific mission. It was the first major study of bay life. Now,
the prestigious California Academy of Sciences is launching a much
larger endeavor, this time a four-year $800,000 study to map the
nearly 1,000 underwater species that inhabit the bay. By JANE KAY.
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLES (``l'' category)
</P>
<P>
   NOVELIST-FAME (Albany, N.Y.) _ From F. Scott Fitzgerald and
Truman Capote on down, the shelves are stacked high with the
biographies of writers who grabbed the brass ring only to watch it
turn into a noose. ``The thing is not to take it very seriously,''
says novelist Michael Ondaatje, speaking by phone from his home in
Toronto. ``(Fame) can do a lot of damage.'' Ondaatje knows what
he's talking about: His 1992 novel, ``The English Patient,'' hit
the literary equivalent of the trifecta. By CASEY SEILER. (For
release Sunday, March 5.)
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS/FINANCE (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   EXAMINER-LAWSUIT (San Francisco) _ A federal judge has
rescheduled a hearing on a lawsuit that seeks to block the Hearst
Corp., owner of the San Francisco Examiner, from purchasing its
larger morning rival, the Chronicle. U.S. District Judge Vaughn
Walker moved the hearing on the suit brought by former mayoral
candidate Clint Reilly from March 23 to April 13. By THE SAN
FRANCISCO EXAMINER.
</P>
<P>
   BANANA-WAL-MART (San Francisco) _ The chief executive of Banana
Republic, which is owned by San Francisco-based Gap Inc., is
leaving the specialty retailer to become the head of Wal-Mart's
online division. By VICTORIA COLLIVER.
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BKC-CAREY (San Francisco) _ When freshman Jamie Carey joined the
Stanford women's basketball team last fall, coach Tara VanDerveer
gave her a bit of friendly advice: ``I like a big lineup, so you'd
better play well.'' Carey didn't blink, and she has played well.
She's been a season-long starter despite her youth and the fact
she's a relative midget at 5-feet-6. By DWIGHT CHAPIN.
</P>
