</HEADLINE>
  
 WHAT THE NEW PRESIDENTS OF RUSSIA and THE USA WILL HAVE TO LEARN  
 &HT;     (This has already moved to clients of Mikhail Gorbachev's
distinguished monthly commentaries. To publish as a ``separate
buy'' article, please contact your New York Times Syndicate sales
representatives: 
 &HT;    (--U.S. and Canada: DEBRA WEYDERT in New Jersey at
1-732-390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697. 
 &HT;    (--Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942. 
 &HT;    (--Latin America: ANA PENA in New York, 310-798-0970; fax, By MIKHAIL GORBACHEV  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    In Russia, the March 26 presidential election offers no
alternatives. It seems that Vladimir Putin, the acting president,
has an obvious advantage. I know Putin. He is an intelligent and
serious man. But to hold any position on him, it is necessary to
see more: who he relies upon and in what manner he works and which
goals he sets. As yet, none of this is clear.
 &HT;    I make no secret of the fact that I regret that former Prime
Minister Yevgeny Primakov pulled out of the race.
 &HT;    I had spent two years trying to persuade everyone and myself
that he would be the best choice for president. Primakov is well
known in Russia and the West and that is a very important
qualification.
 &HT;    More importantly, if Primakov, whom I have always supported,
were participating in the election today, at least he would pose an
alternative. But Primakov was unable to withstand the ordeal of
what the Kremlin-controlled media did to him during the
parliamentary election campaigns _ the blatant smear tactics. We
must call things by their names: His knees simply gave way.
 &HT;    Now, from my knowledge of all the candidates in the race, I
would say that critical questions must be asked of all of them,
primarily Putin. Nothing is known about the foundations of his
program. But as to the issues, and what must and must not be done,
certain things are quite clear.
 &HT;    First, dictatorship is impossible in Russia anymore under any
regime in the Kremlin, Putin's or anybody else's. This is the point
everyone raises, the question I am always asked, especially by
people in the West: Is it possible that Russia will turn back? No.
 &HT;    What I would say is that a system of effective authority is
needed, that law and order are needed; but that such an imperative
should not be confused with a dictatorship.
 &HT;    Today's political leaders are being confronted with new problems
for which they are unprepared and have no solutions _ not only in
Russia but also in the West. The confrontation of opposing blocs
has ended, the Warsaw Pact organization has dissolved and many new
independent states have appeared. We have lost the system of
relations that previously held the world together and organized it,
however defective that system was.
 &HT;    As yet there is no good replacement. We now have ``goods'' that
seem as threatening as evils. For example, freed from the threat of
a nuclear nightmare that hung over everyone's head during the Cold
War, and freed from the discipline imposed by each of the rival
blocs during that time, every country finds that it now possesses a
certain new freedom of action. And yet nowhere, despite this
``freedom,'' do we see nations fostering truly genuine democratic
and peaceful international relations.
 &HT;    The United States viewed the end of the Cold War as essentially
the removal of obstacles on the road to achieving longstanding
goals of American policy. Even though the United States spoke about
a new world order, it essentially meant a continuation of its own
policies. The existing order in world economic affairs was
essentially to Washington's liking.
 &HT;    And so, in this new century, while the Cold War on the whole has
passed into history, its legacy and many of its elements have
persisted, although in changed form. We still have the concept
that, somehow, the West ``won'' and Russia ``lost.'' No wonder,
with such viewpoints, the two ``partners'' are not closer than they
are.
 &HT;    Both Russia and the United States are on the eve of presidential
elections, but there is fear and tension. What does Washington have
in store for us? ask Russians who have become disappointed with the
West's promises and fiercely loyal to their own heritage. In turn,
the West tries to analyze whether Putin, or some other successor to
former President Boris Yeltsin, will be the new Stalin, and foment
war.
 &HT;    We wonder, so long after the Berlin Wall has come down, why the
fact that the world has become pluralistic is not a greater cause
for celebration and respect and trust. Instead, the idea of various
``dangers'' coming from the East is expressed in Western
publications and sometimes in the speeches of Western political
leaders.
 &HT;    Still, Russia will not go back.
 &HT;    It is true that instead of the euphoria of 1989-90, a certain
pessimism has set in. In Russia and the former republics, any
leftover memories of that ``new world order'' are being considered
either a myth or a utopian idea.
 &HT;    But for an authoritarian or totalitarian system to flourish, as
we in the Soviet Union very well knew, there must be more _
something more sinister than disappointment. There must be closed,
secretive behavior relative to the outside world. When a regime
tightens the reins on its own population and uses any form of
coercion it desires, one result is that it will choose
confrontation as the most comfortable foreign policy.
 &HT;    And so it will be incumbent upon the two new presidents _ those
of Russia and the United States _ to raise to a qualitatively new
level the kind of international dialogue that played an
irreplaceable role in ending the Cold War. Without democratization
of international relations, we cannot arrive at any new, genuinely
peaceful world order.
 &HT;    Our people must hold the politicians precisely to these goals.
 &HT;     c.2000 Mikhail Gorbachev  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Mikhail Gorbachev is the author, most recently, of the
best-selling ``On My Country and the World.'' He won the Nobel
Peace Prize in 1990. Gorbachev now lives with his daughter and
granddaughter in Moscow and heads the Gorbachev Foundation, a
social-policy and global environmental think tank. He also founded
Green Cross International, a Zurich-based global
environmental-lobbying group. Gorbachev was the last leader of the
Soviet Union; he resigned in December 1991 when Boris Yeltsin came
to power.) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ---------------- &QC;
</P>
