<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-SHAUGHNESSY-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BASEBALL JUSTICE AWAITS AN APOLOGY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN SHAUGHNESSY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT MYERS, Fla. _ He is everyone's burden, the scourge of
baseball and we have wasted too many words on him already.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta reliever John Rocker said stupid words to a national
magazine in December and drew a whopping suspension from Baseball
commissioner Bud Selig. Wednesday, an arbitrator cut the suspension
in half, reduced Rocker's fine from $20,000 to $500 and ruled that
the pitcher can report to spring training immediately.
</P>
<P>
   And so there will be more words spilled as Planet Rocker crashes
into the Kissimmee, Fla., swamp. Just think what it'll be like when
the Braves play their first series in New York at the end of June.
Anyone care to ride the No. 7 train to Shea with John Rocker?
</P>
<P>
   It's no surprise that the arbitrator shaved two weeks off
Rocker's sentence. Deep down, Selig probably expected this ruling,
but now Bud gets to walk around saying he did his best to punish
Rocker in the name of social responsibility.
</P>
<P>
   But the sentence isn't about the money or the suspension.
Rocker's punishment follows him everywhere. He has become a
prisoner of his own racist/sexist/xenophobic/homophobic remarks.
Going to New York is going to be hell for him, and his toughest
challenge awaits in his own clubhouse _ a place populated by the
teammate he called a ``fat monkey,'' and numerous ``foreigners'' he
insulted in his ridiculous rant.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves held a players-only meeting Wednesday after the
ruling came down. Brian Jordan predicted that today will be just
another day at the office and Tom Glavine said teammates were
prepared to forgive the 25-year-old lefthander. Randall Simon _
target ot the ``fat monkey'' remark _ said he could make peace with
Rocker if the reliver makes a personal apology. In Arizona, Tony
Gwynn told ESPN that he wouldn't be surprised if one of the Braves
``gets in his face.''
</P>
<P>
   Rocker is expected to address his teammates en masse, then hold
a press conference. His representatives, the Hendricks Brothers, no
doubt spent Wednesday night helping him prepare his remarks.
</P>
<P>
   Some Red Sox veterans commented on what it'll be like for Rocker
when he walks into his clubhouse.
</P>
<P>
   Pedro Martinez said, ``They know him well enought to know about
his apology. You're gonna see it. If he joins the Braves Friday and
you see an empty space where he is sitting and you see everybody
skipping away from him when he eats, they don't trust him. They
don't want him around. But if they welcome him back and accept him
the way he is, he probably means his apology.''
</P>
<P>
   Veteran Mike Stanley added, ``I'm sure they'll set up some kind
of meeting where he can address Randall Simon among others. It's
going to be tough to repair in his own clubhouse, never mind what
he's going to have to do around the country. I remember what it was
like for guys who crossed the picket line. They had a hard time
finding a guy to play catch with. And as a player, you don't want
to have anybody say you have the same opinions this guy has. You
don't want to appear that you're friends with him.''
</P>
<P>
   John Valentin, who has been with the Sox longer than any active
player, said, ``He has to deal with his teammates. He's going to
have to apologize to all of them and hopefully they can deal with
it and it will pass. But he's going to pay for those remarks for
the rest of his life. I'm hoping it doesn't hurt baseball.''
</P>
<P>
   It's going to be a zoo in Kissimee. The Rocker problem just
won't go away and Selig admits concerns about the pitcher's safety.
</P>
<P>
   Every thinking American (and some who don't think, but just call
talk radio) has an opinion about Rocker and his punishment. Many
have expressed disappointment with the arbitrator's ruling. At
least one Atlanta official has called for the Braves to trade
Rocker. The ever-despicable Players Association continues to lobby
for Rocker and said the penalty should be further reduced.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, when ranking offenses committed by professional
athletes, it's hard to find the proper place for Rocker's rant. Was
it worse than Marty McSorley hack attack? Worse than Wil Cordero
beating his wife or Darryl Strawberry failing a drug test (Straw
got a year)? The NFL has two players awaiting trials for murder,
but John Rocker and his words are on the lips of the fandom.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Rocker has committed no crime. It's never been against
the law to say stupid things.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he really means his apology, that's good enough,'' said
Martinez. ``We're not God. We don't have the right to judge. If he
comes to Dominican ever, and I have a chance to welcome him to the
Dominican I would do it. Maybe he doesn't know any other way to
express himself. Maybe nobody taught him. I know he's big enough to
know what's good and bad . . . I'm not standing up for him. Make
that clear. I'm just not one to judge.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Dan Shaughnessy is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
