<HEADLINE>
E-SERVICE FIRM LOOKS TO BREAK AWAY FROM THE PACK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVEN SYRE AND CHARLES STEIN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Breakaway Solutions has made all the right moves in its brief
life as an Internet success story.
</P>
<P>
   The Boston company lined up blue-chip venture backers, had a
successful IPO, watched its stock take off like a rocket, pulled
off a major merger, and created its own venture capital fund, all
in nine months. Whew.
</P>
<P>
   Now comes the hard part. Breakaway has to find a way to
distinguish itself from the pack.
</P>
<P>
   When it comes to the Internet, Wall Street is still in the Lake
Wobegon stage: every company is above average. That will pass. As
in any maturing business, some companies will emerge as winners;
others will fall behind. The list of losers will be a long one, in
part because Wall Street has financed so many competitors.
</P>
<P>
   Consider the space that Breakaway plays in, usually referred to
as e-consulting or e-service. Companies in this field are busy
getting corporate America on the Web. They help clients with
strategy, branding, and the complicated technical issues involved
in becoming a serious e-commerce player.
</P>
<P>
   Analyst Mark D'Annolfo covers this turf for the investment bank
of DB Alex. Brown. He says there are 15 companies already on his
radar screen, with another 15 waiting in the wings to go public in
the next few quarters.
</P>
<P>
   ``The opportunity in this field is not a secret,'' agreed Randy
Mehl, an analyst with Robert W. Baird.
</P>
<P>
   Can Breakaway find a way to break away and become a leader in
e-service?
</P>
<P>
   Gordon Brooks says it can. The chief executive of Breakaway
insists his company has a very different focus than most of its
rivals. The competition has targeted strictly big customers, the
Fortune 500 or their international equivalents.
</P>
<P>
   Brooks isn't knocking that decision. When a Ford or a General
Motors decides it needs a Web operation, the dollars spent on
consulting will be huge. ``These guys are hunting elephants,''
Brooks said of his rivals.
</P>
<P>
   Breakaway is after smaller game: medium-sized companies and
emerging firms, most of them dot-coms. Its clients have names like
eRisks.com, JobDirect.com, and VerticalNet. Many of Breakaway's
clients are dot-coms financed by Internet Capital Group, a
Pennsylvania company that owns 40 percent of Breakaway.
</P>
<P>
   Brooks says emerging companies have different needs than the
giants. They need more hand-holding, for one thing. They also want
a consultant who can handle everything from soup to nuts. Breakaway
bills itself as a full-service provider. It does strategy,
implementation, and something few of its competitors do: hosting.
</P>
<P>
   For a fee, Breakaway will take over the Web operations for a
client and run them at one of its own computer centers. Unlike
consulting, where the paychecks stop when the job ends, hosting
involves a long-term relationship. ``We like the fact that it
represents a stable revenue stream,'' said David Smith, a money
manager at Loomis Sayles.
</P>
<P>
   Breakaway fans, Smith included, also like the company's
experienced management team. Brooks was an executive at Cambridge
Technology Partners, a big consulting firm. Many of Brooks's
deputies were founders of their own Internet start-ups.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts also applaud the speed with which Breakaway has come
out of the chute. In January, the company acquired Eggrock
Partners, a Concord consulting firm with a similar mission. The
$252 million deal gave Breakaway more clients, more offices, and a
leg up on late-starting rivals.
</P>
<P>
   ``The deal put us a year ahead of schedule,'' crowed Brooks, who
knows that in the world of the Internet, getting there first counts
for an awful lot.
</P>
<P>
   In a critique of Internet companies he wrote last year, Warren
Buffett said that not all fast-growing businesses will prove to be
good investments. The key, he said, ``was determining the
competitive advantage of any given company and above all the
durability of that advantage.''
</P>
<P>
   Does Breakaway have an advantage that will last as rivals, big
and small, invade its turf? So far, Wall Street seems to think it
does. The stock, which debuted at 14 in October, traded Wednesday
at 124 1/8. That translated to a market value of about $2 billion _
not bad for a company that had $10 million in sales in its most
recent quarters.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts concede the stock has had a big run-up, and they would
not be surprised to see it take a break for a while. Still, most
are bullish on Breakaway's long-term prospects; most have a buy
rating on the stock.
</P>
<P>
   Brooks thinks Breakaway is different enough and fast enough to
keep a step ahead of the pack. We'll check back sometime to see if
he's right.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
The Red Herring
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Chalk up another win for the new economy.
</P>
<P>
   Sycamore Networks, a Chelmsford, Mass. firm that went public
last fall, Wednesday blew past Gillette Co. to become the
Massachusetts company with the second-greatest market value.
</P>
<P>
   Sycamore ended the day with a market cap of nearly $40 billion,
compared to Gillette's $37.6 billion. Never mind that in the most
recent quarter Sycamore had sales of $29 million, about 1 percent
of Gillette's sales of $3 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Sycamore's optical networking products are hot; Gillette's razor
blades and batteries are not.
</P>
<P>
   With a market cap of $120 billion, EMC Corp., the Hopkinton,
Mass. maker of storage systems, remains the market-value leader in
Massachusetts. EMC moved past Gillette last year.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Steven Syre and Charles Stein can be reached by e-mail at
boscap(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
