<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HANDYMAN-HOTTON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE SEPTIC TANK QUANDARY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER C. HOTTON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. I just moved into a house that has a septic system, with the
usual septic tank and leaching field. Such systems are new to me.
How often should they be pumped out?
</P>
<P>
   PAUL BAMBERY, Acton, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. How often? It depends on whom you ask, and how many peple
there are in the family. And, there is little agreement. People who
pump out septic tanks for a living suggest doing it once a year.
Others say that is ridiculous, a ploy to get more work, and suggest
every four or five years. Some say you can go 10 years and beyond.
</P>
<P>
   Who's right? They all are; at least they are not technically
wrong. So, compromise. If the system is working properly, have it
pumped every three to five years. Or, do what many septic tank
owners do: Wait until it backs up, which may take many years. The
handyman does not think the latter is a good idea; it happened to
him once, and he does not want it to happen again.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. My walnut plywood paneling has been up for 30 years and still
looks good, but the veneer is coming up a bit in the vertical
grooves. How can I fix it?
</P>
<P>
   HAROLD WHITE, Boxford, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. If the veneer is the full thickness of the plywood, the
paneling needs to be renailed. If the veneer is very thin, you can
apply a bead of adhesive caulk to the groove and press the veneer
back. You can buy most caulks in brown and other colors, and you
should be able to find a near match to the walnut paneling. I find
that PhenoSeal, widely available in hardware stores, is the best.
It is slow to set, but once it does, it holds like a tiger.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I had a white maple hardwood floor installed last spring. Now
there are small openings between the boards, large enough that I
can get a credit card through. The varnish broke at the joints, and
the lines are black. Is there anything I can do to improve this
situation?
</P>
<P>
   TONY CORDEIRO, Arlington, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. Live with it, or have the floors sanded and refinished and
hope for the best. Some hardwood floors open up for no apparent
reason, but there always is a reason. It often happens when the
boards have excessive moisture in them and are at their largest
dimension when they are laid. Also, your boards may have been laid
immediately upon delivery, and not stored in the house for at least
two weeks for them to assume the same moisture as the house. After
your boards were laid, they behaved nicely, until autumn, when they
began to dry out and shrink, causing the separation and the varnish
to break at each joint. I cannot account for the black lines,
except to guess they are simply shadows on the sides of each board.
</P>
<P>
   If you want to have the boards taken up and relaid tight, wait
until next winter, when they are at their dryest and smallest. With
luck, they will stay tight longer than they did originally.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I am looking for a small corner medicine cabinet. I have
looked in a few places, without success. Are there any around?
</P>
<P>
   BARBARA McGURL, Belmont, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. There are a few around, including one that I found in the
Renovators catalog. It may be too big (30 inches high and 22 wide)
for your purpose, but it is the only one I could find. Call
800-659-2211. Another possible source for a corner cabinet is Yield
House.
</P>
<P>
   Your only other option is to build one. The hardest part about
that is the various angles the frame and trim boards must be sawn
at. Come to think of it, the handyman built a corner cabinet that
came out fairly decent, he doesn't mind saying. The point is, if he
can do it, you certainly can.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I had a forced hot-air furnace installed in the attic. Where
can I find a humidifier that will go on the furnace but will not
freeze in winter?
</P>
<P>
   C.B., High and dry
</P>
<P>
   A. The furnace is well insulated, as it should be, being in the
attic, but I don't think a humidifier can be insulated well enough
to keep it from freezing.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, I don't think it is a good idea to put a furnace in the
attic. No matter how well insulated it is, you cannot insulate
against an open flame, and the uninsulated flame will make the
attic warm, which can lead to ice dams in winter, and resulting
leaks in the house. You are better off, in my opinion, with a
furnace in the basement big enough to heat the whole house, or a
furnace in the living space, a closet, etc. Some people feel that
if the attic is big enough and well ventilated, a furnace there is
all right. I disgree.
</P>
<P>
   As for a humidifier, I suggest a console appliance, one that
will handle a whole floor. With such a console, you can keep an eye
on it, judge how much water you are introducing into the house, and
keep the water sweet and suitable for humidifying.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Globe Handyman on Call Peter Hotton will answer reader questions.
Write him at the Boston Globe, Boston, Mass., 02107, or e-mail him
at hotton(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
