<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JAPANESE-LIGHTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OF LOVE AND NORTHERN LIGHTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By COLIN NICKERSON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   YELLOWKNIFE, Northwest Territories _ Winter sojourners used to
be nearly as rare as flamingos in this frigid outback. And then the
Japanese suddenly decided that there is nothing hotter than
nuzzling beneath the pulsating glow of the aurora borealis, even
with the mercury tickling 30 below.
</P>
<P>
   It's the call of romance as much as the fantastic show of the
northern lights that's bringing Japanese visitors by the thousands
to this gold-rush settlement in the coldest months of winter, even
though, for many of these travelers, the romance seems to occur
mainly in the imagination.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is where I dreamed my fiance would bring me,'' said Keiko
Sugihara, 27, cheerfully conceding: ``Except I have no fiance, or
even a boyfriend. So I came with some other office ladies.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, it's the idea that counts _ and the spectacle.
</P>
<P>
   ``The lights are very romantic,'' Sugihara said. ``And there is
the excitement of a frozen wilderness.''
</P>
<P>
   A decade ago, the number of Japanese coming to the Northwest
Territories in the dead of winter was too small to bother counting,
certainly no more than a few dozen. Now they're pouring in by the
jetload. This season _ the prime time for viewing aurora borealis
extends from December through March _ more than 10,000 will have
descended on Yellowknife (pop. 17,500).
</P>
<P>
   The northern lights are shimmering displays of light that dance
across the night skies when the earth's magnetic field interacts
with charged solar particles and gases in the upper atmosphere.
It's a sight to behold, but jaded Yellowknifers are far more amazed
by the arrival of so many Japanese _ and refuse to believe the
visitors have come simply to oooh and aaahh.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, no, no. Not sightseeing!'' said Lam Pham, a
Vietnamese-born taxi driver by now completely local in his bemused
regard for the Japanese hordes. ``They come to make love in the
snow.''
</P>
<P>
   Yellowknifers are adamant that Japanese believe a child
conceived in the open air under the aurora will enjoy great
fortune. So they journey to Canada's north, year-round denizens
insist, to, well, procreate in the snowdrifts. That, almost every
Yellowknifer will rush to tell you, explains the tourist rush.
</P>
<P>
   It's a tale told with gusto and shocking detail.
</P>
<P>
   Except no one is more shocked by it than the Japanese
themselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``They think _ no! That's crazy!'' gasped Yumiko Sato, 30, an
airline safety supervisor from Osaka. ``In the snow? At these
temperatures? How weird. Are we polar bears?''
</P>
<P>
   Yet Japanese, with giggles and grins, call the territory a
``romance destination.'' And gritty Yellowknife does seem to
attract surprising numbers of honeymooners and sweethearts,
although the tourist ranks also include plenty of standard-issue,
Nikon-wielding sightseers of all ages.
</P>
<P>
   Sato arrived with beau in tow, explaining matter-of-factly:
``Oh, yes, we wanted a special place so he can propose to me.
Tonight, I think.''
</P>
<P>
   In any event, the Japanese are fast putting their mark on a
mining town more used to prospectors, bush pilots and _ as
territorial capital _ bureaucrats posted from Ottawa. These days,
the saloons are stocked with sake and Sapporo beer, cafe menus come
printed in Kanji characters, and shopkeepers greet browsers with
calls of ``konnichi-wa!''
</P>
<P>
   Tour outfitters are reveling in the aurora boom.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our business is up more than hundredfold,'' said Jared Minty,
operations manager for Raven Tours Ltd., which caters primarily to
Japanese tour groups and which vigorously markets the northern
lights in Japan.
</P>
<P>
   `It's extrordinary,'' he said. ```For Japanese, the night view
from Yellowknife is the eighth wonder of the world.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Yellowknife is among the best places on the planet for
watching the otherworldly arcs playing hundreds of miles into the
blackness. (Others are in Alaska, Norway, Finland, and Labrador.)
Tour operators say that visitors have a more than 90 percent chance
of catching the view, although clouds can cause serious
disappointment and sometimes _ even on clear nights _ the lights
fail to show.
</P>
<P>
   ``Still, because of atmospheric conditions, there are better and
more regular sightings here than at the North Pole,'' said Minty of
Raven Tours.
</P>
<P>
   Keiko Sugihara made the journey with three office pals, all from
Kyoto and all outfitted in white thermal boots and heavily
insulated red parkas and snowpants. The effect was more Michelin
Man than Versace, but the young women seemed delighted to look so
rugged.
</P>
<P>
   For sure, they'd need the padding on this bitter night in which
they bundled aboard buses with scores of other Nihonjin for the
bumpy 30 mile ride to Prelude Lake, an icelocked expanse offering
vast panoramas of night sky.
</P>
<P>
   The Japanese are not the most demonstrative of folk. But as
eerie curtains of green, violet and white light rippled across the
northern heavens, shrieks and moans and ecstatic cries rolled over
the stunted spruce taiga.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's so great! Oh beautiful!'' shouted Hiro Ototake, 29, a
pharmacist from Otsu who'd flown to Yellowknife with his new bride,
Emiko, for a bracing subarctic honeymoon.
</P>
<P>
   The couple alternated between tight embraces of each other and
tightening their parka hoods into the tiniest of apertures from
which their noses glowed and their eyes gleamed happily.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just the most romantic place I can imagine,'' said Emiko,
who, like many Nihonjin on the excursion, also wore a surgeon's
mask over her nose and mouth. ``So my lungs don't freeze.''
</P>
<P>
   The brutal cold is just part of the grand adventure.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you come to the far north in winter, you want to experience
the intensity of the Canadian climate,'' said Hiyoshi Abe, 51,
editor of a trade magazine for the metal industry.
</P>
<P>
   Most Japanese spend only three days in Yellowknife before
heading back, during which time they feast on caribou stew, trundle
across the tundra on dogsleds, splurge on Inuit carvings and _ with
belly-shaking hilarity _ pose for snapshots beside the two very
basic outhouses at Prelude Lake. The waterless facilities seem to
astound the highly urban guests.
</P>
<P>
   The northern lights have occupied a special place in the
Japanese heart for centuries and figure in the nation's folklore.
The spectacle was once routinely visible from the island of
Hokkaido, but a slight shift in the magnetic North Pole and a
not-so-slight increase in pollution have made the aurora
exceedingly rare even in northernmost Japan.
</P>
<P>
   ``Japanese people have a reverence for nature, even though few
of us live close to nature,'' said Abe. ``So to travel such a great
distance to see these lights seems reasonable. In that sense, it's
certainly a journey of love.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-02-00 1315EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
