<DOCNO> NYT20000302.0110 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-02 13:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4541 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-MEDIA-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      03-02 0862
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEDIA-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RIGHT-WING VOICES IN DISHARMONY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK JURKOWITZ  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Day after day, conservative talk radio star Rush Limbaugh rails
against Republican insurgent John McCain, assailing the traitorous
``McCain Mutiny'' as a remnant of the moderate ``Rockefeller-Ford
wing of the party.''
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere on the dial, however, another syndicated talk host
with equally conservative credentials _ G. Gordon Liddy _ is
backing the Arizona senator. ``What we really need is a mensch,''
says Liddy. ``And McCain is a mensch.''
</P>
<P>
   If the McCain-George W. Bush fight has triggered a civil war
inside the Republican Party, it has also fractured any sense of
unity among the conservative media. While the mainstream press is
widely accused of being too enamored of McCain, the Arizona
senator's candidacy has created a fault line in the media debate on
the right, generating disbelief, passion, and plenty of arguments
among ideological allies.
</P>
<P>
   At The Weekly Standard, publisher William Kristol and senior
editor David Brooks wrote a story embracing McCain's bid as a
``political phenomenon with potential appeal to the country as a
whole.'' Fred Barnes, the magazine's executive editor, attacked
McCain for not ``acting like a regular Republican.''
</P>
<P>
   The Republican race for president ``certainly is dividing The
Weekly Standard. No doubt about that,'' says Barnes, who also
cohosts ``The Beltway Boys'' on the Fox News Channel. ``It is
easily the most divisive thing in a Republican race that I can
remember.''
</P>
<P>
   And the battle rages. The editorial pages of two right-leaning
tabloids _ the Boston Herald and New York Post _ enthusiastically
endorsed McCain. The editorials in the conservative Washington
Times, clearly favoring Bush, cuff McCain around regularly.
</P>
<P>
   In the editorial pages of The Wall Street Journal, a column by
Paul Gigot disdainfully comparing McCain to Jimmy Carter was
situated right next to one by Dorothy Rabinowitz conjuring up warm
comparisons between the senator and Harry Truman.
</P>
<P>
   CNN analyst and Weekly Standard writer Tucker Carlson, who
admires McCain, recently returned to his office after an absence to
find scores of e-mails attacking his fondness for the senator.
</P>
<P>
   The media war over McCain and Bush, he says ``sort of divides
along the following lines _ those who like to see the finger given
to the Establishment and those who don't.''
</P>
<P>
   It's tempting to see the Bush supporters as representing the
buttoned-down conservative Establishment and McCain fans as the
wilder and crazier rebels.
</P>
<P>
   Herald editorial page editor Rachelle Cohen refers to the
pro-Bush view as ``the sort of Wall Street Journal . . .
business-page kind of conservatism.'' (The Journal's rock-ribbed
editorial page makes no secret of its dislike for McCain.)
</P>
<P>
   ``To some Republicans, there is the Bill Kristol Weekly Standard
crowd,'' counters Helle Bering, editorial page editor of The
Washington Times. ``They've been looking for an alternative to the
Republican Establishment for a long time.''
</P>
<P>
   R. Emmett ``Bob'' Tyrrell Jr., editor in chief of The American
Spectator says the rancorous warfare among conservatives ``is a
sign of some sort of psychological disorder.'' Both candidates, he
says, are ``propounding principles and policies that are certainly
within the mainstream of conservative,'' politics.
</P>
<P>
   But Spectator executive editor Wlady Pleszczynski, who recently
wrote a piece on the magazine's Web site accusing McCain of
seducing the media, is ``annoyed by a lot of this (McCain support).
He's a very smooth-talking, schmoozy fellow.''
</P>
<P>
   At its core, the debate among conservative media types seems to
mirror the broader disagreements in the electorate. Bush supporters
feel more comfortable with his policies while McCain fans think
character trumps ideology.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have issue differences with McCain,'' says Liddy. ``Nobody
cares. What they want is a real man.''
</P>
<P>
   The Herald's Cohen sounds the same note. ``Having looked this
guy in the eye, we said `we really like this guy,' '' she says.
</P>
<P>
   Citing differences on tax policy and campaign finance reform,
National Review editor Richard Lowry says, ``We have a lot of
problems with where (McCain's) positioned himself . . . I think
McCain has never had deep political convictions.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I have trouble understanding the McCain appeal,'' echoes
Barnes. ``On domestic policy, he's one big fuzzball.''
</P>
<P>
   Above the fray, however, are a few notable conservative voices
that are sitting this one out.
</P>
<P>
   ``One is not a conservative's dream. The other is just a flub,''
says The (Manchester) Union Leader's editorial page editor,
Bernadette Malone Connolly. ``For those of us in the ivory tower,
there's a problem.''
</P>
<P>
   And MSNBC and radio talk host Oliver North blames both
candidates for a nasty, mudslinging campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``A pox on both their houses,'' he says. ``My advice to both of
them is to cool it.'' In this campaign, North adds, ``I'm one of
those guys in the religious right that's agnostic.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Mark Jurkowitz covers the media for The Boston Globe.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
