<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONGO-CEASEFIRE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONGOLESE PERSEVERE AGAINST WAR'S RAVAGES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KURT SHILLINGER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   GOMA, Congo _ There is church on Sundays.
</P>
<P>
   Otherwise Mama-Eleye Balize passes her days in the monotony of
surviving. The 25-year old works in a crowded marketplace grinding
cassava roots into flour. The hut where she works is filled with
sweet odors of rot from a nearby garbage heap. Flour dust powders
her eyebrows and high cheekbones, so that her face looks like the
image in a photographic negative.
</P>
<P>
   Balize's life fits the portrait of a people trampled by ethnic
hatred, greed, and thirst for power _ the scourges that fuel the
ongoing war in Congo. A young mother of three children under the
age of four, she earns maybe $5 a week.
</P>
<P>
   Her husband has been jobless for two years. The family eats only
one meager meal of beans and corn a day.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't allow myself to be tired,'' Balize says, her infant
pulling at her breast, unsated. She can't produce enough milk. ``If
I get tired, there won't be food.''
</P>
<P>
   Six foreign armies and nine rebel factions wage a war of
multiple fronts and confusing subplots, violating their own
cease-fire and pillaging Congo's mineral treasures. The United
Nations makes modest plans to intervene, while the ordinary people
of this vast country endure with improbable grace.
</P>
<P>
   The Congolese have weathered colonialism, dictatorship,
invasions, rebellions and counterrebellions. Their economy has
collapsed. Light bulbs are scarce, AK-47s ubiquitous. Yet those
with jobs rise daily to work, even though they have not seen wages
in months or years. And those without jobs rise to look for work,
forming hopeful crowds daily outside the compounds of foreign
relief organizations and the few factories still operating.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the central paradox of Congo: No one has been paid in
two years, but everyone is still alive,'' said Alexandre
Liesbekind, a senior representative of the International Committee
of the Red Cross. ``In French there is a good word _ pauperization.
That is what's happening to the population.''
</P>
<P>
   Nineteen months after the outbreak of fighting, the war in Congo
has stalled and splintered. Rebel movements backed by Rwanda and
Uganda have marched halfway across the country from the east, while
the Congolese military, backed by Zimbabwe and Angola, holds the
west. Neither side seems capable, or particularly driven, to push
for total victory.
</P>
<P>
   The instability has encouraged numerous smaller conflicts and
freestyle pillaging. Two related ethnic groups in the northeast,
the Hema and Lendu, have been slaughtering each other over land.
Rebel and government forces from neighboring Burundi have taken
their war across the border into southeastern Congo. Nearly all the
foreign forces are hauling off timber, diamonds, gold, and precious
ores.
</P>
<P>
   Into this climate the UN Security Council last week agreed to
deploy a small mission to monitor the cease-fire signed by the
belligerents last July in Lusaka, Zambia. But that decision has not
made people here any more optimistic about peace. The operation
will bring in just 5,537 observers and protection forces in a
country roughly the size of western Europe. The four sites where
the force will deploy are separated by vast expanses of
impenetrable rain forest.
</P>
<P>
   The tiny force will have no power to impose sanctions for
cease-fire violations or disarm rebel factions that have not signed
the Lusaka accord. With such a limited mandate, regional security
experts worry it will only solidify the current de facto partition
of Congo.
</P>
<P>
   ``The operation is totally meaningless,'' said Patrick
Mazimhaka, chief peace negotiator for neighboring Rwanda. ``It
would take three years minimum to begin disarming and separating
the armies and factions under a meaningful UN military operation.
We have to set up centers to collect arms, create buffer zones, and
supervise repatriation. The answer is greater engagement.''
</P>
<P>
   Rwanda's stance does not bode well for the peacekeeping effort's
success, because the tiny nation's security concerns lie at the
crux of the war.
</P>
<P>
   After the 1994 genocide in Rwanda, when extremist Hutu killed
roughly 800,000 people, the majority of them members of the rival
Tutsi people, the killers fled into vast UN refugee camps just
outside Goma in eastern Congo. Most of the refugees were
repatriated in 1996 and the camps closed, but an unknown number of
Hutu militias, known as interahamwe, and former Hutu soldiers fled
into the bush.
</P>
<P>
   These forces, estimated to number in the tens of thousands, were
never disarmed. They carried out repeated cross-border killing
sprees against Tutsi, prompting Rwanda, with Uganda's help, to
launch back-to-back wars against its giant neighbor: the first in
1996 against then-Zairean dictator Mobutu Sese Seko for harboring
the Hutu extremists; then again in 1998 against Congo's president,
Laurent Kabila, for doing the same. Although Rwanda signed the
cease-fire last year, it won't drop its guard until Hutu extremists
in exile are disarmed and repatriated.
</P>
<P>
   Through the gloom of povery and war, however, some light shines
through.
</P>
<P>
   After repeated violations by all sides, the warring parties in
Congo agreed last week to hold themselves to the Lusaka cease-fire
as of March 1. Whether they do will determine how soon the UN
peacekeeping force arrives. And Kabila's most important ally,
Zimbabwean President Robert Mugabe, is under serious pressure to
retire after voters delivered a stunning rebuke in a referendum two
weeks ago, partly in response to Mugabe's costly military adventure
in Congo, where he has sent 11,000 troops to Kabila's defense.
</P>
<P>
   But the primary obstacle to peace remains the interahamwe and
former Hutu soldiers, and there is no solution in sight. Many have
been integrated into the Congolese and Zimbabwean armies, as well
as the rebel forces fighting against the Tutsi-led government in
Burundi. And as long as they have the means to wage war, Rwanda
won't stand down.
</P>
<P>
   ``What can we do? Our job is not yet done in Congo,'' said
Mazimhaka, Rwanda's negotiator. ``Our job is to bring our people
back, hopefully without their guns. We have to dig in deeper.''
</P>
<P>
   What does all this have to do with the price of beans in
Mama-Eleye's marketplace? Actually, quite a lot.
</P>
<P>
   Set on the black volcanic northern shore of Lake Kivu, Goma sits
at the crossroads of this, Africa's most complicated war. Its
people's story is a chronology of woes that has brought destitution
even to those who were once prosperous.
</P>
<P>
   Kasuku wa Ngexo was a wealthy man a few years ago. He had three
farms in the rolling hills outside Goma where 6,000 cattle and 250
horses fattened themselves on kikuyu grass and clover. He produced
cheese, butter, and beef. He also had a tea factory in town and a
game lodge in the nearby Virunga mountains, where tourists could
see elephants and chimpanzees.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't poor,'' he said. ``I'm broke now.''
</P>
<P>
   The destruction came in waves. Hordes of Rwandans poured through
this border town after the genocide in 1994, prompting the United
Nations to establish huge refugee camps. The refugees stole cattle
and set up butchering sites inside the camps, according to reports
by the UN High Commissioner for Refugees. So did soldiers hired to
run security in the camps.
</P>
<P>
   The first war started in 1996. As Kabila's rebels, backed by
Rwanda and Uganda, advanced, Mobutu's troops fled, looting cars,
houses, and factories. Extremist Rwandan Hutu joined the mayhem.
Two years later it happened again. The second war started, and this
time Kabila's troops pillaged as they fled.
</P>
<P>
   There were 450,000 cattle in the Goma area six years ago,
according to the local farmers cooperative. Today the herds are
gone. Lost too are 200,000 goats, 200,000 sheep, 100,000 pigs, and
hundreds of horses. Eighty percent of the wildlife in Rwindi
national park has been slaughtered, including elephants and hippos.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the cars in town are gone, most of the factories idle.
Hotels are bankrupt, owed hundreds of thousands of dollars in
unpaid bills by the Rally for Congolese Democracy, the main rebel
faction based here. Banks are broke. Farther out, farms lie fallow,
coffee plantations neglected. No tourists come. Until the Rwandan
Hutu go home, people here say, it is too dangerous to rebuild.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Goma hums with its own economic illogic. No one seems to
have money, yet everyone survives by selling things to each other.
</P>
<P>
   Yvonne Kabuo peddles bananas at the marketplace, not far from
Mama-Eleye's flour hut. Like everyone who sells produce here, she
travels to another town 50 miles away, twice a week, to buy
bananas. She barely makes enough to cover her transport costs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Life is very hard,'' she said, her forehead tightening into a
deep cleft.
</P>
<P>
   ``True,'' Ngexo shrugged. ``But you have to be optimistic. It's
my country. I'm a Congolese.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
