<HEADER>
A4547 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l BC-CAMPUS-BREADTH-2TAKES     03-02 1367
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAMPUS-BREADTH-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
888-603-1036.)  
 TRIO OF COURSES SHOW THE DEPTH OF TODAY'S CAMPUS OFFERINGS 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-ART-BOS  
 (ART ADV.: Photos are being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 888-346-9867 or (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOSEPH P. KAHN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ What do Duke Ellington, Alan Greenspan, and Aristotle
have in common? Genius, yes. (We'll grant Al some leeway here.)
Beyond that, each is a featured player in a popular course being
offered on a Boston campus this semester.
</P>
<P>
   One course is 30 years old and imaginatively combines community
service with classroom study. Another is a year old and like its
subject, the stock market, could scarcely be trendier. A third is
brand new and stylishly untrendy: a course on early American jazz,
taught by a Mozart scholar.
</P>
<P>
   The courses, chosen not entirely at random, sample the variety
and popularity of what's being taught at area colleges at any given
time.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Literature and Arts B-80: The Swing Era
</P>
<P>
   Examines American jazz from the early 1930s to bebop. Considers
sociological issues and the relationship of swing-era jazz to
classical music and popular song, to place swing's achievements
into a broader historical and musical perspective.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what I call a mean tune!'' Robert Levin shouts out over
the closing bars of ``Hocus Pocus,'' a 1934 Fletcher Henderson cut,
featuring the incomparable Coleman Hawkins on tenor sax. Levin then
fires up a CD dub of a Louis Armstrong recording he inherited from
his father, a jazz buff.
</P>
<P>
   For the next hour, the perpetual-motion Harvard prof cannot seem
to stand _ or sit _ still. Bouncing over to the piano, Levin bangs
outs a Bach prelude followed by some Jelly Roll Morton licks.
Strutting around the Sanders Theatre stage in front of 560
students, he dips his shoulders and wags his fingers in classic
hepcat style to a peppery clarinet solo by Buster Bailey. Close
your eyes and you can almost smell the Cotton Club circa 1937.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're figuring out what makes this music tick as well as
connecting to it emotionally,'' Levin tells his audience, a mixed
bag of Harvard students and AARP types who are auditing.
</P>
<P>
   For Levin, a classically trained keyboardist who studied with
Nadia Boulanger, ``The Swing Era'' represents a chance not only to
branch out into more of a pop-music idiom but to expose a younger
generation, in a serious and scholarly way, to the recordings he
grooved on as a kid in Queens, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   ``The simple reason I'm doing this is that I'm crazy about the
music,'' says Levin, whose piano-thumping lecture style has been
packing them in all semester. ``But that's not reason enough. The
fact is, this is the first truly mass popular music in US history.
I want students to get a real insight into the aesthetics of swing,
the way they'd view a painting in a fine arts course or read a poem
in a literature class.''
</P>
<P>
   The course benefited from an early buzz around campus, in part
because Levin also teaches a popular course on chamber music and is
famous for his energy and showmanship. For most of the students in
L&AMP;A B-80, Bix Beiderbecke and Benny Goodman belong as much to
ancient musical history as Beethoven and Liszt do. But as they're
learning, American music didn't start with Jimi Hendrix and Miles
Davis.
</P>
<P>
   Hannah Trierweiler, a freshman from Denver, was initially drawn
to Levin's course because it fills a core requirement. ``I listen
to mostly KISS-108 stuff,'' says Trierweiler, ``but not a lot of
jazz. This looked like fun, though. Levin is pretty quirky, too. He
dances around a lot.''
</P>
<P>
   Katherine Bolton, a junior from Alabama, grew up near New
Orleans listening to '60s and '70s rock. Now, she digs
jazz-influenced groups like Phish. ``I wanted to understand the
background more,'' says Bolton, who concedes that Levin's use of
terminology is ``tough to follow at times.''
</P>
<P>
   The heart and soul of Levin's lectures are close audio analyses
of classic swing tracks. Lectures on Goodman and Ellington
incorporated repeated playings of ``King Porter Stomp'' and ``Mood
Indigo,'' performed by different bands with different arrangements.
Like any good jazzman, though, Levin is an inveterate improviser. A
discourse on Ellington's recording of ``Take the A Train,'' for
instance, segued into a brief history of the Manhattan subway
system.
</P>
<P>
   Says Levin, ``My secret goal is to build students' listening
libraries, the way others bought `Rubber Soul' or `Born in the
USA.' Because once you've got these recordings, you'll listen to
them. I'm on a cultural crusade here.'' Move over, Bruce.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PL 088-089: Person and Social Responsibility (PULSE)
</P>
<P>
   Course requirements include 10 to 12 hours per week of community
service. In light of classic philosophical and theological texts,
students address the relationship of self and society, the nature
of community, the mystery of suffering, and the practical
difficulties of developing a just society.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   All things being equal, there is almost no chance Kristin
Kusmierz would have crossed paths with Michael Brady during her
college years. Or wanted to. Kusmierz is a BC junior from North
Kingstown, R.I. Brady is a 44-year-old, HIV-positive substance
abuser from Scituate who never went to college and who is ``pretty
much on my last chance right now,'' Brady says.
</P>
<P>
   BC's PULSE course is nothing if not a great equalizer, though.
And so one day last week, Kusmierz and Brady took a stroll together
around Shattuck Hospital in Jamaica Plain, where Brady is a patient
in the Living and Recovering Community program (LARC) and Kusmierz
works as a student volunteer through the Victory Programs agency.
The two found more in common than either might have dreamed of four
months ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was not like a conversation between a college student and a
dope fiend,'' Brady recalled afterward. ``We talked about the
virus, about substance abuse and her maybe going into human
services after she graduates. It's nice to hear what a student has
to say to someone who's been on the street for 30 years.''
</P>
<P>
   Kusmierz nodded. ``To actually see people living with the virus
teaches you more than any book can,'' she said, seated in a cramped
hospital conference room with two fellow PULSE students and half a
dozen LARC patients. ``In class, we focus on how to live your life,
how to develop a system of meaning that builds a community. It's
much easier to internalize something when you read it and see it.''
</P>
<P>
   Kusmierz is one of 300 BC students enrolled in the program this
year, continuing a tradition established in 1970. In weekly section
meetings, students discuss writings by Aristotle, Rousseau, and
Locke along with contemporary authors like Charles Taylor and
Jonathan Kozol. They also keep detailed journals, diaries that
often provoke soul-searching examinations of what personal and
social responsibility truly mean.
</P>
<P>
   The course has seldom been more popular. About 150 students were
turned away this year for space reasons, despite the heavy reading
load and community-service requirement. Program director Donald
McMenamin says word of mouth is his best recruiting tool.
</P>
<P>
   ``The kids hear from other students who say it's the most
important course they've taken at BC,'' says McMenamin. ``They
start out thinking they're going to change the world, and they
leave realizing how much they've been changed by it.''
</P>
<P>
   In class, McMenamin and his colleagues push students to relate
what they're reading to issues they've encountered in the field.
Thus a recent discussion of Taylor's ``The Ethics of Authenticity''
prompted McMenamin to ponder the relationship between the
individual and society, asking students if there were anything like
a shared definition of the American Dream.
</P>
<P>
   ``Does your concept of the dream correspond to that of the
people in the placement agencies where you work?'' he inquired.
``If the good life is going to be achieved,'' he argued, ``all the
voices must be at the table. If we exclude some of those voices, we
risk impoverishing our notion of what is authentic.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
