<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-02 13:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4553 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-HIPHOP-TEACHER-BOS &LR;      03-02 1055
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HIPHOP-TEACHER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLASS LETS TEENS ANALYZE THE MESSAGE BEHIND THE BEAT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SANDY COLEMAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Poet Corey Cokes is standing in a classroom at New
Mission High School, rocking, moving side to side, sweeping and
swooping slender hands as he fires off rhythmic messages in poems:
</P>
<P>
   The ``n'' word is not a name to let loose on your own people, he
tells them in ``Trainspotting.''
</P>
<P>
   People and things are not always what they appear to be, he lets
them know in ``Snapshot,'' touching on the abuse of his mother he
witnessed as a child:
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(poetry style) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   sistah Sarah's mascara, well, it ran away with tears
</P>
<P>
   you see, for years she has maintained that
</P>
<P>
   miss congeniality smile while in denial of her man's hands
</P>
<P>
   at work she's a wife, a mother &AMP;
</P>
<P>
   a professonal...liar.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(end poetry style) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Students at the school in the city's Roxbury neighborhood sit so
still and quiet, a cough coming from down the hall sounds like
thunder in here. They breathe in Cokes's words like fresh air,
learning the lessons teacher Damon Smith has been trying to get
across in his hip hop class.
</P>
<P>
   Words are power. You can make them hurt. You can make them heal.
Cokes does both as he rages against racism, black self-hatred,
domestic violence and taking life at face value.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's very critical of what he sees. I want students to stop
and be critical,'' said Smith, who created the hip hop class _
``Beats, Rhymes and Life'' _ taking the name from an album by
former hip hop group A Tribe Called Quest.
</P>
<P>
   Smith, who owns more than 300 hip hop CDs, has been an avid fan
of the music since the late 1970s when it emerged, rooted mainly in
break dancing, graffiti expression and deejaying. That was long
before the genre became today's consumer-driven cultural phenomenon
shaping everything from speech patterns to fashion.
</P>
<P>
   And because hip hop has become such an intregal part of the
lives of youths, Smith developed the class a year ago to engage
students and teach them about writing, politics, communication,
consumerism and anything else that fits.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their world revolves around that,'' said the 27-year-old
teacher. ``They connect very well to the music. . . . I wanted my
students to be really critical of this culture and not just take it
and accept it blindly.''
</P>
<P>
   Samaria Johnson, 18, was doing just that.
</P>
<P>
   Before the class, she didn't really think about the lyrics of
songs. ``If I was in the car or something, I would know the words
but I wasn't hearing,'' said Johnson, who signed up for the class
to get a better understanding of how hip hop affects society.
</P>
<P>
   The class, which requires students to pick apart lyrics and
analyze them, has taught her to dig deeper beyond the groove of a
good beat. ``We'll listen to a song, and we have to have evidence
for why we like a song,'' Johnson said. ``We can't just say I like
Tupac. We have to say I like the bass line or the lyrics, or
whatever.''
</P>
<P>
   Stephen Ruggs, 15, has been playing around with a microphone and
rap lyrics since he was 5 years old. He draws smiles from
classmates because he constantly talks about an album he will
someday make. Smith's class was a natural draw, he says, a chance
to take a serious look at a hobby. And, besides ``my parents,
they're old. They've got those old jams.''
</P>
<P>
   But, old jams also have a place in Smith's lesson plan. He opens
the course using Marvin Gaye's ``Mercy Mercy Me'' and ``What's
Going On,'' to show students the timelessness of some words and
music.
</P>
<P>
   He knows the next question he throws out will spark strong
reactions: Will hip hop last as long?
</P>
<P>
   Over the course of several weeks, students will try to answer
that question through a variety of assignments, including writing
at least six papers. They dissect song lyrics, explore songs that
best represent their lives, and discuss who are the top 10 hip hop
artists and why.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of our students don't necessarily like to write,'' said
Smith. ``Students in the hip hop class choose to be there and they
know there is a heavy writing piece to it. So, it's an avenue for
them to open up. . . . Rather than writing about `The Grapes of
Wrath,' I have them writing about a song by Jay-Z.''
</P>
<P>
   It's working said 17-year-old Marc Auguste, who writes gospel
raps. ``If I have to write about something, I have a better chance
of putting work into it if I'm interested. And I'm deep into this
class.''
</P>
<P>
   But, Smith admits it doesn't work for all students. There are
those who don't pass because they don't want to write. But, ``they
love to talk about it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Conversation drives the class.
</P>
<P>
   Recently, the topic was on the role of women as artists and
people in the hip hop world.
</P>
<P>
   To fuel debate, Smith shows a video of Rah Digga and Busta
Rhymes singing ``Dirty Harriet,'' which featured a powerful,
shotgun delivery and plenty of the buttock-shaking, breast-baring
women who have become a staple in many videos.
</P>
<P>
   Smith then opens the conversation by having students read the
lyrics of a 1987 Slick Rick song, ``Treat Her Like a Prostitute,''
to show how not much has changed when it comes to degrading women
in music.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's trying to say you don't have to treat no chick like a
queen unless you got to know her,'' said Auguste, adjusting the
black knit cap on his head.
</P>
<P>
   ``He could have said it better, but I agree with the message,''
adds Johnson. ``You have to get to know someone. He's giving a
message my mother would give. . . . I think he's just saying don't
give a girl your all. . . . I wouldn't treat a guy like he's the
king of the earth until he deserves it.''
</P>
<P>
   Sitting on a table before a dozen students, Smith asks: ``Are we
looking at women with even a baseline of respect? In this song, is
Slick Rick talking about a select group of women or all women? . .
. This is from 14 years ago. Now is a new day. We have Lauryn Hill.
We've got Eve. But, where do women fit?''
</P>
<P>
   ``When I look at it,'' responds Johnson, ``it's just like
society. What is the role of women in society? It's a society
issue.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith agrees. ``Hip hop is kind of a mirror of society. But, it
could be different. It should be different. Why isn't it? Because
we're not critical enough.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
