<HEADLINE>
&HT;     JUDGE RESCHEDULES HEARING ON NEWSPAPER MERGER 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ A federal judge has rescheduled a hearing on a
lawsuit that seeks to block the Hearst Corp., owner of the San
Francisco Examiner, from purchasing its larger morning rival, the
San Francisco Chronicle.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. District Judge Vaughn Walker moved the hearing on the suit
brought by Clint Reilly, an unsuccessful candidate for mayor, from
March 23 to April 13 due to scheduling conflicts, according to the
office of Joseph M. Alioto, who is Reilly's lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   Hearst has announced plans to buy the Chronicle for a reported
$660 million and merge it with the Examiner if a buyer for the
afternoon newspaper cannot be found. Reilly's suit contends that
such a merger would result in higher advertising and subscription
rates and thus harm consumers. It also claims the purchase would
violate federal antitrust laws.
</P>
<P>
   Hearst has denied those contentions and claims the proposed
merger of San Francisco's two dailies would benefit consumers by
boosting competition between newspapers in Bay Area suburbs and
between electronic media. Gary Halling, Hearst's lawyer, has asked
the court to dismiss the lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   The April 13 hearing will be on Reilly's request that Walker
enter a preliminary injunction barring Hearst's purchase of the
Chronicle, pending a full trial.
</P>
<P>
   Hearst is trying to sell the Examiner and says it has had
several inquiries. Reilly has expressed interest in buying the
paper and has met with Hearst executives to discuss it, Alioto
said.
</P>
<P>
   Hearst's proposed purchase of the Chronicle was announced in
August and has been under review by the antitrust division of the
U.S. Department of Justice since then. The two newspapers operate
under a federally approved joint operating agreement, through which
they share publishing expenses but maintain separate news
operations.
</P>
</TEXT>
