<HEADLINE>
ONLINE SLEUTHS GET SCOOPS BY FOLLOWING A PAPER TRAIL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PATTI HARTIGAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Blame it on Bill Bastone and Danny Green. They're the guys who
busted Rick Rockwell, the (maybe) multimillionaire who married a
stranger in front of (really) 23 million viewers. They're the ones
who dug up a restraining order filed against Rockwell years ago and
posted it on the Internet. They're the muckrakers who forced Fox to
cancel the rebroadcast of ``Who Wants to Marry a
Multimillionaire,'' disappointing the one or two of us who missed
it the first time around.
</P>
<P>
   Hey, if Western civilization is about to crumble because of a
made-for-television marriage, we ought to be able to watch the
foundation fall, if only in reruns.
</P>
<P>
   But if it's any consolation, Bastone didn't see the show,
either. ``I'm a little upset myself,'' admits Bastone, who is the
cofounder of www.thesmokinggun.com. When he isn't chasing down
incriminating evidence on possible millionaires, Bastone is an
investigative reporter for The Village Voice. His beat: the Mob.
When you run around in circles like that, you dig up a lot of juicy
documents that never make it into the paper.
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, Bastone and his pal Green, a freelance writer
based in New York, have amassed piles of rib-tickling,
face-reddening documents. In April 1997, they launched the Smoking
Gun Web site, a repository for dirt about celebrities, sports
stars, dead presidents, and _ well, why not? _ J. Edgar Hoover.
It's part gossip column, part police log, part political journal.
And it's always entertaining. (Unless you're Martha Stewart or
Howard Stern, whose dirty linen has been aired on the site.)
</P>
<P>
   In this age of digital technology, the site genuflects to the
ink-smudged, coffee-stained paper documents buried in musty old
courthouses and county offices. It's also a paean to the drudgery
of investigative reporting. ``A lot of this work is about calling
courthouses and police departments and going through files and
Xeroxing,'' says Green. ``It's scut work, but it's fun to get
e-mail from Norway and Australia saying, `I love the site, but who
is Marv Albert?' ''
</P>
<P>
   Each piece of paper reveals some sort of secret: The Stewart
files feature a police report that depicts the Home Beauty Queen
swearing at some poor sap in East Hampton. In the Kirstie Alley
papers, the actress's ex-husband, Parker Stevenson, outlines his
case for spousal support in excruciating detail, down to the
marching bands and the exotic animals. (We'll leave that one to
your imagination.)
</P>
<P>
   Just the facts, sweetheart, just the facts. These guys don't
make up any of this stuff, and even if they can be accused of
raking muck, they don't post anything on the Web site until they've
verified its accuracy, 100 percent. So how did they get the (maybe)
multimillionaire scoop? Someone in Southern California dropped a
dime, and the fearless reporters had their ``guy in LA'' scour the
files at the LA County Courthouse. The guy eventually came up with
the restraining order, which depicts the not-so-happy husband as a
controlling brute. After they confirmed it was the same Rockwell,
they posted the document along with Rockwell's mug, I mean, head
shot. They have been deluged with e-mail from folks claiming to
have some connection with Rockwell and his erstwhile bride, Darva
Conger.
</P>
<P>
   But unlike other Internet startups, they haven't exactly been
flooded with buyout offers since they broke the story. ``No one has
arrived at our door offering riches, but they're welcome,'' says
Bastone, who doesn't let a day go by without filing a Freedom of
Information Act request.
</P>
<P>
   The two writers haven't bothered to request their own files from
the FBI, though. ``I'm afraid there wouldn't be a smoking gun
there,'' says Green, with a sigh.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   When they aren't investigating not-so-eligible bachelors, the
members of the Fourth Estate like nothing better than to gossip
about each other. Witness the enormous popularity of Jim Romensko's
Media News (formerly www.mediagossip.com), which was recently
acquired by the Poynter Institute, a journalsim school in St.
Petersburg, Fla. Well, now there's a fabulous parody of the media
gossip site, put together by a couple of comedians in the Big
Apple. The parody is at www.modernhumorist.com, which promises more
hilarity this spring. I say, bring on the humorists; let spring
begin.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Patti Hartigan's e-mail address is p(long
dash)hartigan(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-02-00 1323EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
