<SLUG> BC-WIRELESS-INTERNET-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IMAGINE A WORLD OF ALL WIRELESS, ALL THE TIME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER J. HOWE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW ORLEANS _ Sometime this spring, Scott Young's company will
throw out its office desk phones and join a small but growing group
of people who are going all-wireless for their telephone needs.
</P>
<P>
   Young's firm, PrairieComm of Rolling Hills, Ill., has one
unusually strong reason for switching its 120 employees from
landline phones to cell phones: It sells processing chips for
several leading cell phone makers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Part of it is an image thing,'' Young said in an interview at
the Wireless 2000 convention here. ``If we want to project
ourselves as a cutting-edge wireless company, this is a way to do
it.''
</P>
<P>
   But, he added, there are good reasons for any other company to
consider following suit. ``It's the advantage of being able to get
a call anywhere: In your office, in the elevator, walking out to
the parking lot, wherever,'' said Young, who said AT&AMP;T Wireless
officials have told him his company is their third Chicago-area
customer going all-wireless.
</P>
<P>
   Today, about 4 percent of the 86 million US wireless phone
owners use them as their exclusive phone, double the percentage
estimated in a study last June by the Yankee Group of Boston,
according to the Cellular Telecommunications Industry Association's
chief economist Bob Roche, whose group sponsored the three-day
convention that concluded Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Some people see a potential revolution in the making.
</P>
<P>
   Amid all the hoopla this week over announcements about wireless
Internet access and e-commerce deals, association president Thomas
Wheeler said what is known as ``wireline displacement'' is an
overlooked but promising trend for the industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we didn't have all this wireless Net news popping, I think
you would be hearing a lot more about the growing numbers of people
who are using their wireless phone as their only phone,'' Wheeler
said.
</P>
<P>
   Besides mobile professionals replacing their office phone with a
portable unit, industry officials see big markets emerging among
young people, college students and first-time homebuyers who expect
to move frequently.
</P>
<P>
   The idea of using a wireless phone as a landline replacement is
especially powerful internationally. In many countries, people face
months of waiting to get a landline phone and may have to pay, in
countries such as Finland and Japan, up to $1,000 for a wired
connection. In Egypt, a country where landline service is scarce
and installations plagued by delays, Vodafone AirTouch PLC has
signed up over 350,000 subscribers for wireless and found the
service generated a profit within just four months, Vodafone
chairman Chris Gent said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who would want a phone nailed to the wall when you can have it
in your hand?'' said Harvey White, chairman and chief executive of
Leap Wireless in San Diego.
</P>
<P>
   Leap, a spinoff from phone maker Qualcomm, of which White was a
founder, is launching a service in 17 American cities under the
Cricket Communications brand offering local phone service through
wireless technology. The cities include Pittsburgh, Denver, and
Nashville.
</P>
<P>
   First offered in Chattanooga, Tenn., the service gives people
unlimited local calling in their home area for $30 a month,
prepaid, on a $100 or $130 digital phone, but with no roaming
charges for calls outside the area.
</P>
<P>
   In just nine months, White said, Cricket has sold its service to
7 percent of potential customers in the market, of whom more than
60 percent use the wireless phone as their primary or sole phone.
Cricket officials have no current plans to enter the New England
market but say they are interested in finding opportunities in the
region. .
</P>
<P>
   David Friedman, marketing vice president for US Cellular, whose
markets include rural parts of northern Maine, New Hampshire and
Vermont, said there is a huge market for wireless to crack, given
that the average residential wireline customer uses the phone 1,100
minutes a month, compared to about 150 minutes for wireless.
</P>
<P>
   Put another way, of all the time Americans spend talking on the
phone, only 5 percent is now over wireless units, said G. Edward
Evans of Dobson Cellular Systems Inc.
</P>
<P>
   Ed Reynolds, president of Bell South Mobility in Atlanta, said
he thinks that ``secondary lines are the most vulnerable to being
replaced'' by portable phones. ``We're seeing young, mobile
customers who have cut the cord or, frankly, never had a cord.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If you had a teenager you used to get a second landline phone
for them,'' said Herschel Shosteck, a Wheaton, Md., industry
consultant. ``Now you get a wireless phone for the teenager and
keep the second line for your Internet use.''
</P>
<P>
   Shosteck said he sees evidence wireless phones are becoming
increasingly popular for college students who may live in four
dorms over four years and have summer jobs in different places.
With plans like AT&AMP;T's One Rate that offer 10 cents a minute for
wireless and long distance, ``the mobile phone number makes more
sense for them, and I think they will keep that as they grow up.
They're not going to give up their mobile phone just because they
have a house in the suburbs,'' Shosteck said.
</P>
<P>
   Some industry executives, however, caution there are clear
limits to how much ``wireline displacement'' there will be. James
P. Caile, Motorola's corporate vice president of marketing for
personal communications, said, ``If you're in a household of more
than one person, you need to provide some sort of communication
dedicated to the household, like if someone is just calling to
reach someone in the family,'' Caile said.
</P>
<P>
   To date, technology has been slow to develop for offering a
single number that can serve more than one wireless phone, although
Denver-based US West has pioneered a popular service that rings
both a home and mobile phone through one number.
</P>
<P>
   And Josh Kiem, a director of marketing with Motorola's personal
communications line, said, ``In other countries where there are
waiting lists for traditional phone service, (wireless replacement)
is happening. In the US, we have great landline service, so this
will probably be one of the last countries'' where wireless makes
serious inroads into traditional landline business.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
