u a BC-COMPUTERS-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      03-02 0829
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMPUTERS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EMULATION'S DUAL PERSONALITY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HIAWATHA BRAY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Journalism keeps you humble, if you're the sort of journalist
who puts his e-mail address at the bottom of the column. Readers
never hesitate to bring me up short.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, for instance, I talked about the copper transistors
being used in the hottest new microprocessors. A couple of
sharp-eyed fans caught the blunder. It's the connectors between
transistors that are made of copper, not the transistors
themselves. Good catch, guys.
</P>
<P>
   Others directed their fire at my main point: that the torrent of
new superfast processors will provide far more power than most of
us need. Several of you responded that we'll soon have
sophisticated new programs that will need all the computing cycles
we've got. One correspondent pointed me to one of the most
interesting examples, a remarkable bit of software called VMware.
</P>
<P>
   It's a variation on the not terribly new concept of the software
emulator, a computer program that makes one computer act as if it
were another computer.
</P>
<P>
   Emulation programs have long been used by engineers to help them
design new computer systems. But they've never been especially
popular with ordinary users, except among loyal fans of Apple
Computer Inc.'s Macintosh machines. Whatever its merits, the Mac is
a sort of technological Gilligan's Island, and many users are eager
for some way back to the mainland.
</P>
<P>
   So there are programs like SoftWindows 98 and Virtual PC that
let a Mac run Microsoft Windows programs. I tried SoftWindows over
a year ago on my iMac, but found it sluggish and frustrating.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, Connectix Virtual Game Station does a darn
good job of turning any late-model Mac into a Sony PlayStation
gaming console. I've just been playing the new Die Hard Trilogy
PlayStation game on my iMac, with the help of Virtual Game Station.
My performance is lousy; the computer's is superb.
</P>
<P>
   Emulators add an extra layer of software between the operating
system and the programs you want to run. So even the best of them
don't run as well as the systems they're trying to emulate. This is
particularly true when you're trying to emulate software that runs
on entirely different hardware. Windows programs are all written to
run on X86 chips, the design created by Intel two decades ago. To
make them run on a Mac, you need a layer of software that will make
a Mac's PowerPC processor run like a Pentium. It gets sticky.
</P>
<P>
   No surprise, then, that emulators aren't very popular with users
of Intel-compatible PCs. There's already a lot of good software
that runs ``natively'' on Intel-type processors. Why bother with
emulation?
</P>
<P>
   But there is the occasional good reason. Say there's a Windows
95 program that doesn't behave itself when running under
Microsoft's new Windows 2000 operating system. Or say you want to
use the GIMP, a powerful Linux graphic design program, without
having to convert your entire computer to Linux.
</P>
<P>
   One simple solution is dual-booting. You can set up a PC with
several operating systems, each stored in a different partition on
the hard drive. Then, at boot-up time, you can tell it which
operating system to load. Programs like V Communications Inc.'s
System Commander Deluxe were invented for this purpose. Or, you can
use LILO, a little utility that's built into Linux.
</P>
<P>
   But when you're booted into one operating system, you can't use
the others. It could be quite useful to run two or three operating
systems on the same computer at the same time. That's what VMware
was designed for.
</P>
<P>
   I'm running VMware on an IBM ThinkPad loaded with Microsoft's
Windows 2000. I can now pop open a window on the laptop and have
Red Hat Linux running inside, almost as fast as it does on one of
my dedicated Linux machines. And I can easily hop back and forth
between Linux and Windows applications. For instance, I cut a few
words out of this article, being written in Windows on Microsoft
Word, and pasted the words into WordPerfect, running under Linux.
</P>
<P>
   VMware runs on Windows NT and 2000, and on Linux. I'd love to
have something like this running on my Linux machines. Then again,
VMware costs $300 for the commercial version and $100 for personal
use. Maybe I'll wait for the completion of Wine, an ongoing project
to build a free Windows emulator for Linux. With Wine, I could do
all my serious work in Linux, then pop open a Windows
flight-simulation program, just for fun.
</P>
<P>
   Either VMware or Wine will require lots of extra processing
power for decent performance. A one-gigahertz processor with a ton
of memory and a fat hard drive ought to do nicely. The average user
certainly doesn't need this kind of rig, but for many of the people
who read this column, there's no such thing as too much computer. I
stand corrected.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Hiawatha Bray can be reached by e-mail at bray(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
