<HEADER>
A4571 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-BRITAIN-NAMES-$ADV04-     03-02 0729
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRITAIN-NAMES-$ADV04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    WHAT'S IN A NAME? FOR WOMEN IN THE CZECH REPUBLIC, IT'S 'OVA'
 &HT;    Moving in both (i) International and (l) Lifestyle categories.
 &HT;    For Use Sat., March 4 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By SHELLEY EMLING 
 &HT;    c.2000 Special to the Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Scan the entertainment sections of any Czech magazine or
newspaper and you'll find Julia Robertsova and Meryl Streepova, not
Julia Roberts and Meryl Streep.
</P>
<P>
   In Czech and other Slavic languages, the suffix ``ova'' is added
to the last names of all females. It's an ending long-ingrained in
the vernacular that quite literally means ``belonging to'' the
male, as in belonging to a woman's father or husband. (In English,
``ova'' is plural for ``ovum,'' a female egg cell.)
</P>
<P>
   It's enough to make any American feminist wince. But Europe _
and especially Central Europe _ has long fought against
American-style political correctness, a term often derided as
describing a tortured sensitivity resulting in ridiculous changes
to the language.
</P>
<P>
   But times are changing, even in post-Communist countries like
the Czech Republic, meaning the use of the suffix ``ova'' may soon
be over.
</P>
<P>
   Legislation recently proposed by the Czech Republic's Ministry
of Interior would enable a woman to remove the suffix from her last
name.
</P>
<P>
   According to government officials, the legislation is expected
to pass and could take effect by the end of the year. They insist
the impetus for the proposal is not a rise in complaints, but is
simply the result of a changing world in which women are seeking
more control.
</P>
<P>
   Eva Kavkova, who runs Relocation Management International, a
Prague-based firm that helps companies relocate to the Czech
Republic, said some women have started to consider the use of
``ova'' demeaning.
</P>
<P>
   ``But they use it reluctantly because they accept it as part of
life here,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   In general, language is not as scrutinized in Europe as it is in
the United States.
</P>
<P>
   In Britain, for example, people who deliver the mail are still
called postmen, even if they are women.
</P>
<P>
   And even though British Prime Minister Tony Blair often speaks
out in favor of women's rights, no one bats an eye that the female
members of Parliament belonging to his Labor Party are popularly
referred to in the press as ``Blair's babes.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the Czech Republic is even more traditional than
Britain.
</P>
<P>
   It is, for example, the kind of country in which high-level
female involvement in business or government is rarely encouraged.
</P>
<P>
   In the Czech Republic there are no women in the Cabinet, whereas
in Sweden, 12 of 20 Cabinet positions are occupied by women.
</P>
<P>
   But many post-Communist countries are introducing laws these
days to put them in line with the European Union, which they aspire
to join.
</P>
<P>
   In the Czech Republic, legislation to combat sexual harassment
was recently proposed following the publishing of a study by the
daily, Lidove Noviny, indicating that almost half of the country's
working women had been sexually harassed in the workplace.
</P>
<P>
   Zuzana Roithova, one of just nine female members in the
81-member Senate, said Czech women have been slow to push for more
rights.
</P>
<P>
   ``A good family life is more important to many than their
rights,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Women right's advocates said it's no surprise then that the
Czech government is just now considering giving women the option of
removing the suffix ``ova'' from their last names.
</P>
<P>
   ``Feminism is not so popular in post-Communist countries as it
is elsewhere,'' said Jirina Ciklova, founder of the Center for
Gender Studies in Prague.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I think this new proposal is a positive one and that, as a
result, many women, at least many of those from the younger
generation, will change their names,'' she added.
</P>
<P>
   Ciklova said, however, the change may not go over so well with
older women, who favor the suffix for making it immediately clear
whether someone is male or female.
</P>
<P>
   Even she agreed that some Czech names just won't sound right
without the ``ova.''
</P>
<P>
   For example, she pondered, ``Can you imagine saying Martina
Navratil, instead of Martina Navratilova?'' She certainly can't.
</P>
<P>
   (Shelley Emling, a former foreign correspondent, is now a
freelance writer living in London.)
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
