<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-02 13:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4577 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r s BC-BKW-CAREY-HNS &LR;      03-02 0526
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKW-CAREY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     STANFORD'S FRESHMAN STAR HOBBLED BY INJURIES 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (ATTN: Colo., Wash.)  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By DWIGHT CHAPIN  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   STANFORD, Calif. _ When freshman Jamie Carey joined the Stanford
women's basketball team last fall, coach Tara VanDerveer gave her a
bit of friendly advice: ``I like a big lineup, so you'd better play
well.''
</P>
<P>
   Carey didn't blink, and she has played well. Very well. She's
been a season-long starter despite her youth and the fact she's a
relative midget at 5-feet-6-inches.
</P>
<P>
   She has averaged just under 11 points a game and is leading the
team with 63 3-pointers, just a dozen off Vanessa Nygaard's school
record and five behind Jennifer Azzi's Cardinal freshman mark.
She's also 10th in the nation in 3-point shooting percentage.
</P>
<P>
   Even more impressive than Carey's numbers are her toughness and
her poise. From the moment she took the court against the U.S.
women's national team in the Cardinal opener, nothing has shaken
her.
</P>
<P>
   ``She takes care of the ball,'' VanDerveer said. ``She's smart,
makes good decisions, recognizes when things are open and when
they're not. She's really, really special.''
</P>
<P>
   There's just one problem. Carey hasn't been really, really
healthy for some time.
</P>
<P>
   She injured both her ankles during her junior year at Horizon
High School in Thornton, Colo., and they have never completely
healed. On Saturday, near the end of Stanford's win over
Washington, she went sprawling after tripping over a Husky player
and reaggravated a high left ankle sprain.
</P>
<P>
   Carey was in tears on the bench, and left Maples Pavilion on
crutches. She has remained on crutches this week, and her status
for the Cardinal's crucial road games at UCLA and USC Friday and
Sunday is very much in doubt.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't really know if she'll be able to play,'' team trainer
Mike Leahy said. ``It's day to day. We'll just have to wait and
see.''
</P>
<P>
   Carey, who has missed just one game this season, is being
cautious, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``The ankle was very painful when I hurt it again,'' she said.
``As a player, you always want to play, but I just have to wait and
see now, because it's hard to tell just how long it will take to
recover.''
</P>
<P>
   But VanDerveer, well aware of Carey's ability to bounce back,
said, ``Personally, I'm counting on her. It's nice to have an extra
day (a Friday game instead of the normal Thursday) for her to rest.
But if she's not basically 100 percent, she's not going to play.''
</P>
<P>
   VanDerveer blamed herself for not getting Carey out earlier from
Stanford's blowout win over Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was just stupid,'' the coach said. ``What makes it so bad
is that I've been a nervous wreck all year sitting on the bench and
worrying about whether I should leave her in or take her out. I had
Christina Batastini at the scorer's table waiting to replace her
Saturday, but I couldn't get her in before Jamie got hurt again.''
</P>
<P>
   Carey probably will be facing extensive rehabilitation and
perhaps surgery after the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Time will tell,'' she said, ``but that's not an issue right
now.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-02-00 1348EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
