<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SWARTZ-COLUMN-$ADV02-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COACH SAYS YOU NEED A TIME OUT  
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Thursday March 2)  
 By SUSAN SWARTZ   
 The Press Democrat, Santa Rosa , Calif.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   I understand paying someone who is meeting you at the gym and
worries about your hamstrings as much as you do.
</P>
<P>
   And I understand why it might be a good idea to have a personal
guide when shopping in order to keep the mother of the bride away
from leopard prints.
</P>
<P>
   There are many things about which someone else knows best.
Advisers are important. What would we do without that friend we can
call to ask, ``Tell me again why I wanted to be a blonde?''
</P>
<P>
   Now people are acquiring a personal coach, to help them organize
all aspects of their overwrought life. At first I wondered, why add
one more person to your life when you don't have time for the ones
already in it?
</P>
<P>
   Then I went to lunch with Lotty, a woman who used to never take
time to eat out. A self-described overworked overachiever, she
swears she's a new woman since gaining a coach whose goal is to get
Lotty's personal and professional life in balance.
</P>
<P>
   The aim of a professional coach is to help you figure out what
you want in your life and why in your attempts you've become
addled, snappish and no fun anymore.
</P>
<P>
   Lotty, who from all accounts used to be a lot of fun even after
she gave up motorcycles, said in the past few years all she's done
is work. She does a lot of her job at home and one of the problems
with that is there's no one to say ``You're losing it. Let's knock
off for a beer.''
</P>
<P>
   She generally gets up at 4:30 a.m. and goes to her computer
where she sits in her pajamas until 4:30 p.m. after which she pulls
on some clothes and then drives into town to the office.
</P>
<P>
   She said the main reason she sought out a coach, whom she
describes as a ``gorgeous brilliant MBA with diplomatic skills,''
was to get better at her job, which for all the time she spent at
it, never seemed to get done.
</P>
<P>
   Those who've watched this trend grow and who predict that
eventually as many of us will have personal coaches as personal
fitness trainers, say the coach is part consultant, therapist,
motivational speaker and paid friend.
</P>
<P>
   You would like to think we should be able to do this without
paying for it but apparently we can't.
</P>
<P>
   Lotty's coach honed in on the problem of her wanting to be queen
of the hop. She got Lotty to delegate responsibility, give up some
control and modify some of her expectations for herself and her
staff.
</P>
<P>
   But at the same time she told Lotty to play. And she gave her a
way to rationalize it.
</P>
<P>
   ``She said I was working much too hard and with my level of
stress I couldn't be efficient.''
</P>
<P>
   Lotty pays a bunch of money for that kind of wisdom. There's
something about advice that comes with a price tag. If your mother
says you're working too hard, she's just being mom, but if an
expert gives you permission to slack off and then says, ``that will
be $100,'' you listen.
</P>
<P>
   Here's one of Lotty's coach's tips for free. Give yourself one
hour every day to do something that is fun and good for you.
Because of the ``good for you'' part, that probably cuts out eating
a pizza, but maybe not. It certainly doesn't mean doing your taxes
while you're on the phone with a client and also keeping an eye on
CNN.
</P>
<P>
   Lotty now pencils in one hour of fun every afternoon. Maybe she
reads something for pleasure or listens to music. The other day she
took her dogs for a walk in the rain and reported, ``It was
wonderful.''
</P>
<P>
   Two people told me in the past week they've awakened at 3 in the
morning with heart pounding and panicked over how they were going
to finish a certain project. A friend says she feels like she has
one eye on one task and another looking at the next one. She's
working two jobs, looking in on ill parents, promoting a new book,
feeling guilty about not getting to yoga class and trying to enjoy
a new romance. It's not like these people want it all to go away.
</P>
<P>
   They're the kind who, if they won the lottery, would not give up
their planner, like the friend who, when she can't sleep, gets up
and starts writing a new novel.
</P>
<P>
   Or Lotty, who says, ``It's a huge job. I have so much to do. And
I love it.''
</P>
<P>
   Last weekend she went to San Francisco with friends. ``It was
just for fun,'' she said, ``something I would never have done a
year ago before I had my coach.''
</P>
<P>
   She's also carrying a smaller purse, which is only big enough
for her sunglasses, keys and some money. No room for a pager or
cell phone.
</P>
<P>
   Her coach has also told her it's time to start dating again.
</P>
<P>
   Yay, coach.
</P>
<P>
   (Susan Swartz is a columnist for The Press Democrat in Santa
Rosa, Calif. The Press Democrat is a member of the New York Times
Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
