<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-02 14:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4601 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-BKN-HOLLEY-COLUMN-ART     03-02 1025
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-HOLLEY-COLUMN-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
888-603-1036.)  
 A YOUNG STAR CONTINUES TO BRIGHTEN 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 888-346-9867 or (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL HOLLEY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Vince Carter's day began at 1 a.m. when, outside the
Boston Harbor Hotel, he received a symbolic embrace from a group of
fans anxious to see him before he went to bed. His day ended _ at
about 9:30 Wednesday night _ almost the same way it began. This
time, he literally found himself in the arms of fans after making a
shot that turned the FleetCenter into a strange chamber of echoes,
gasps, and Pitino rage.
</P>
<P>
   Carter made a 23-foot corner 3-pointer at the buzzer to beat the
Celtics, 96-94. As he shot over Adrian Griffin, the 6-foot-6-inch
Toronto Raptor fell into the crowd as the ball fell into the net.
He was mobbed by fans and teammates. On a night full of irony, you
could say that Carter received love in Boston, the kind of love
that Rick Pitino wants the city to share with his team.
</P>
<P>
   It's amazing what great players and their performances bring out
of people. Ten minutes after Carter's shot, Pitino stood at a
podium and said some words that he will surely regret. He lashed
out at the Boston media and ``some fans'' for negativity.
</P>
<P>
   ``Larry Bird is not walking through that door, fans,'' the coach
said. ``Kevin McHale is not walking through that door and Robert
Parish is not walking through that door. And if you expect them to
walk through that door, they're going to be gray and old.''
</P>
<P>
   What's interesting is that Pitino chose his words on Carter
Night. I think most Boston fans are smart enough and reasonable
enough to understand that the current Celtics don't have Big Three
capabilities. I would even argue that most fans would be less angry
about a 23-34 record if they had someone like Carter to watch for
41 home games a season.
</P>
<P>
   What they don't understand is how a coach with such a huge
contract can have such a weak record (78-111 in nearly three
seasons). They don't understand the skittish personnel decisions.
They don't understand playoff guarantees, followed by bad
basketball, followed by fan-directed anger.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish we had $90 million under the salary cap,'' he
continued. ``I wish we could buy the world. We can't. The only
thing we can do is work hard, and all this negativity that's in
this town sucks.''
</P>
<P>
   Pitino went on to mention Yaz, Cooz, Russell, and Rice. It was
sad to watch and listen to. It was insulting, too. Pitino has
nothing in common with the legends he mentioned. His situation is
different. He is being booed because he is not delivering what he
promised. When he arrived in Boston, the Raptors were worse than
the Celtics. His first team won 20 more games than the 1997-98
Raptors. Now, Canada will have a playoff team, leaving the Celtics
with the longest playoff drought in the Eastern Conference (five
seasons).
</P>
<P>
   Canada also has Air Canada, also known as the 23-year-old
Carter. As you can see, the second-year forward is an agitator on
several levels. If he repeats his performance Friday night in
Toronto, when the teams play again, Pitino just might announce his
resignation after the game. Carter may not be ready to fill the
league's vacant Jordan Suite, but the kid who grew up playing the
drums and saxophone is already a terrific player.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after Carter entered the FleetCenter, it was obvious
that it would be a weird night. The first clue was in the Toronto
dressing room. Reporters crowded the area, trying to catch a
glimpse of this powerful dunker. What they saw was a
serious-looking kid in glasses. It was Carter. It appeared that he
was more prepared to do a scholarly study on dunks rather than
actually throwing a few down himself.
</P>
<P>
   About an hour later he ran onto the court to applause. It was
6:45 p.m., 20 minutes before game time. You scanned the arena and
saw dollops of purple, mostly young people wearing Carter's
purple-and-black No. 15 Raptors jersey.
</P>
<P>
   When Carter ran onto the court for warmups, the first adoring
fan to shake his hand was Ryan Pitino, youngest son of Rick.
</P>
<P>
   The intensity would rise gradually from that moment until the
finish.
</P>
<P>
   First quarter: Carter opens the game with a reverse layup. In
less than a minute, he has 4 points. He tosses in a baseline
fadeaway . . . makes a 3 . . . makes a turnaround jumper over Paul
Pierce . . . puts in a finger roll that his young fans would label
sick and ill (those are compliments); it's a finger roll that will
remind his older fans of George Gervin.
</P>
<P>
   By halftime, Carter had 16 points. At times in the third and
fourth, he looked preoccupied. Dee Brown, who never left the bench,
knew better. The former Celtic attended college in Jacksonville,
Fla., which is close to Carter's hometown of Daytona. Brown is 31,
8 years older than Carter. But when Brown was in college,
``Everyone was telling me about this kid in Daytona. They were
telling me how good he was going to be. He must have been in the
seventh or eighth grade.''
</P>
<P>
   Fourth quarter: Only 3.2 seconds remain and the Raptors trail by
a point. Carter had 25 points. Not a noisy, gaudy 25. They were the
kind of 25 that could be soundtracked by one of the ballads he
plays on his sax. Carter dribbled in the corner against Griffin. It
looked as if he was taking too much time. No problem. He pulled up,
ignored the hand in his face, and made the long 3. He put his hands
on his hips after he made the shot as if to say, ``What next?''
</P>
<P>
   What's next? By next season, Carter will certainly be among the
NBA's top three players. And by next season, Pitino will certainly
crumble under the weight of what he calls negativity. Before the
coach leaves Boston, I hope he realizes that it was not media and
fan negativity that collapsed on him. No, the problem will be that
he raised expectations and wasn't strong enough to handle it when
his optimistic (and unrealistic) words tumbled on him like a
ferocious avalanche.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Michael Holley is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
