<P>
   POLITICS
</P>
<P>
   GOP-DEBATE _ Coverage of GOP debate from Los Angeles. (Sherman,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution/Herman, Austin American-Statesman).
25.
</P>
<P>
   MCCAIN _ Although John McCain has called Pat Robertson and Jerry
Falwell evil influences on the Republican Party, the Arizona
senator's voting record indicates he agrees with the Christian
right leaders on most issues. (Sherman, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 25.
</P>
<P>
   POL-TICKER _ A brief roundup of the day's campaign events,
pulled from Cox staff and wire reports. (Cox News Service) ETA: 6
p.m.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   COCKFIGHTING _ WASHINGTON _ Bills that would ban interstate
shipment of chicken for cockfighting are being voted on this week
in the House and a Senate committee, alarming Texas aficionados of
the sport. Opponents call cockfighting cruel, and it is legal in
only New Mexico, Oklahoma and Louisiana. Texans now take their
birds to the three neighboring states to fight. (Turay, Cox News
Service). 18.
</P>
<P>
   CORAL-REEF _ WASHINGTON _ A federal task force on new
initiatives to reduce the loss of coral reefs worldwide, recommends
setting aside 20 percent of U.S. coral reefs as ecological
reserves. (Lipman, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   EDUCATION-TAX _ WASHINGTON _ The Senate on Thursday was poised
to approve a bill extending and expanding several tax breaks for
educational purposes. Those most likely to become law would expand
tax breaks for businesses that donate used computer equipment to
schools and for teachers who buy extra supplies for their
classrooms . But they would have to first be attached to another
bill, because the bill's main provision is a Republican plan for
K-12 education savings accounts that President Clinton has already
vetoed twice. (Turay, Cox News Service). 15.
</P>
<P>
   HYACINTH _ WASHINGTON _ U.S. Department of Agriculture
researchers say they may have found a way to control the imported
water hyacinth, which chokes millions of acres of water from
Florida to the Carolinas, south Texas, California and Hawaii. A
tiny Amazon jungle fly that can be bred in captivity devours the
plant, and the USDA hopes to begin testing whether it is safe to
import. (Nesmith, Cox News Service). 17. WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   IRS-AUSTIN _ WASHINGTON _ An IRS source provides details of how
a courier without proper identification was entrusted with a $28
million deposit at the tax agency's processing center in Austin,
Tex. (Malone, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   MIDEAST-POPE _ JERUSALEM _ While welcoming Pope John Paul II,
Israel's chief rabbi Thursday said he expects the pontiff to ask
Jews for forgiveness for the way the Catholic Church handled the
Holocaust during World War II. A handful of anti-pope protesters
and a series of recent pope visit controversies highlight the
discomfort some Israelis feel about the 10-day trip to the Holy
Land later this month. Developing. (Kaplow, Cox News Service). 20.
WITH PHOTO.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Moving in (i) International and (l) Lifestyle categories.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   CITADEL _ Two old foes, The Citadel and the New York law firm
that spearheaded Shannon Faulkner's assault on the school's
males-only policy, are negotiating a gift of several hundred
thousand dollars on behalf of female cadets. One possible sticking
point: How would the South Carolina-supported military college
acknowledge the gift from Shearman &AMP; Sterling? With a plaque
honoring Faulkner, or the law firm? A talker that reveals lingering
resentment against Faulkner, but probably not enough to foul the
sensitive negotiations. (Burritt, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
