<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-GROWTH-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     PATAKI TAKES CREDIT FOR GROWTH SURGE 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By JAY JOCHNOWITZ  
 &HT;     c.2000 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ For the first time in more than four decades, New
York state outpaced the nation in job growth last year, and much of
upstate New York shared in the trend, Republican Gov. George Pataki
said.
</P>
<P>
   In sharp contrast to the state's miserable performance in the
mid-1990s when New York ranked 48th in the nation, the Empire State
took 7th place in 1999, according to state Labor Department
statistics unveiled Wednesday by Pataki, Lt. Gov. Mary Donohue and
state economist Stephen Kagann amid much fanfare at the Capitol.
</P>
<P>
   Not unexpectedly, upstate New York as a whole lagged behind the
state but still had a stronger job growth figure than the nation
did _ 2.5 percent compared with 2.3 percent for the United States.
The state rate was 2.9 percent, or about 199,500 jobs. The
strongest-performing area was Putnam County, at 6.4 percent. The
Albany-Schenectady-Troy area reached 3.3 percent.
</P>
<P>
   State officials could not say how the jobs translate into money
and whether there was a corresponding gain in wages and salaries.
Kagann said it is likely to be months before such detail is
available.
</P>
<P>
   He said, however, that it was unlikely that the state's job
growth could be as strong ``without it being very broad-based,''
including both full- and part-time jobs and a full range from
minimum-wage positions to high-paying manufacturing slots.
</P>
<P>
   While giving a nod to companies for creating the jobs, Pataki
took full credit for creating the climate that brought in the jobs,
pointing to a record of tax cuts and ``fiscal restraint.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to tell government that the policies that worked for
the last five years are going to work for the next three years,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Kagann, who claimed an economic forecasting model he developed
had predicted the exact state growth number months ago, supported
the governor's assertion. ``Not only do taxes matter, they matter a
lot,'' said Kagann, whose model predicts job growth as a result of
tax relief.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Pataki stood by his conservative budget forecasts for
next year, which the Legislature says are about $1 billion short on
the revenue side. ``The state's doing well, but it's not doing as
well from a revenue standpoint,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone was as impressed with the figures as the governor,
who several times expressed surprise at press questions focusing on
the lower-performing areas like Rochester (1.9 percent) and
Buffalo-Niagara Falls (1.8 percent).
</P>
<P>
   Calling Pataki's self-congratulatory announcement
``disingenuous,'' Assembly Speaker Sheldon Silver said New York
state was only now catching up with a national trend that he
credited to White House policies under President Clinton and Vice
President Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Silver, a Democrat, said that if the state under Pataki had
performed in recent years as well as states like Texas, California
and Florida did, it would have added one million more jobs since
1995. According to Pataki, the state gained nearly 663,000 jobs, a
9.6 percent increase, following a 5.9 percent decline from
1990-1994.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki was elected in 1994 and re-elected in 1998.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
