<SLUG> BC-TREK-CHARISMA-CARPENTER-IN-ANGEL-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A TOUCH OF CHARISMA: CHARISMA CARPENTER, ON THE SIDE OF THE
`ANGEL' 
</HEADLINE>
  (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to Inside Trek, a
weekly science-fiction column with color and black-and-white art.)
 (Includes a color slide and a black-and-white photo of Charisma
Carpenter in a scene from ``Angel.'') 
 By IAN SPELLING  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features.)  
 &HT;    It's usually a recipe for television disaster: Take a beloved
supporting character and turn him or her into a star.
 &HT;    Usually, it reveals that the same quirkiness that made the
character popular as a backup player is downright irritating in a
leading man or woman.
 &HT;    Every so often, however, it works.
 &HT;    Case study: ``Angel,'' which puts ``Buffy the Vampire Slayer''
bitch-goddess Cordelia (Charisma Carpenter) front and center. And
it does so to great effect, with each weekly episode revealing more
of what makes the character tick.
 &HT;    ``Cordelia was just this gratuitous, nasty person on `Buffy,'
especially at the beginning,'' Carpenter says, speaking by
telephone from a Los Angeles studio during a break at a photo
session. ``Towards the end, it got better.
 &HT;    ``Officially, with `Angel,' they had to give more life to the
character,'' she says. ``And they have. She's not nearly as mean
and biting or as quick to go for the jugular as she used to be _
but she's still got an edge, because we need to maintain that
entertainment element of her, her bluntness and way of telling the
truth.
 &HT;    ``On `Angel,''' Carpenter adds, ``we want her bluntness to ring
true, but she still has to be appealing and approachable enough
that the audience can identify with her. That's my challenge in
playing her.''
 &HT;    Cordelia, of course, is a fabulously frustrated actress, one
without a shred of talent. She's also frightfully unlucky in love
and working alongside that ever-brooding vampire, Angel (David
Boreanaz), at his fledgling detective agency.
 &HT;    When the popular WB series kicked off its freshman season last
fall, Glenn Quinn co-starred as Doyle, Angel's amiable guide.
Despite the genuine romantic sparks set off by Doyle and Cordelia,
Doyle soon bit the dust and was replaced by a familiar ``Buffy''
face, Wesley (Alexis Denisof), late of the Council of Watchers and
now both a free-lance demon-hunter and Cordelia's latest verbal
sparring partner.
 &HT;    Before his departure, however, Doyle passed on to Cordelia a
gift that keeps on giving: his visions of people in peril.
 &HT;    ``For Cordelia, the visions are a curse,'' Carpenter says, ``but
one of my favorite lines is a result of the visions. Angel was
brooding about something, and I approached him and said, `In case
you're wondering why my vein is doing the cha-cha ... '
 &HT;    ``Those kinds of lines are the funniest things to say,'' the
actress says. ``It's so much fun to have the visions, as the
character.
 &HT;    ``To act them is hard,'' she adds, ``because I hyperventilate
sometimes when I'm doing the vision scenes. It's like my body
believes that I'm really having a vision or some sort of seizure.
Sometimes I get so lightheaded that my whole body tingles. It's
weird.''
 &HT;    Weird? Carpenter plays a character who shares her home with a
ghost, is employed by a vampire with a conscience, experiences
bizarre visions and was impregnated by a demon _ and body tingles
are weird?
 &HT;    ``I only freak out and say `What have I gotten myself into?'
when they start wanting to slap prosthetics on me,'' the actress
says, laughing. ``I am not OK with that. I'm very claustrophobic _
I'm always asking my makeup artist to cut back on the makeup, and
I'm always threatening my hair stylist that I'm going to cut my
hair because it's so high-maintenance all the time, day in and day
out.
 &HT;    ``I'd rather have the extra hour of sleep than be in the makeup
chair with rollers in my hair, you know?'' Carpenter says. ``In a
way, I guess, I do ask `What have I gotten myself into?' But I am
so grateful that we have the crew we have, that we have the writers
we have, that our fans dig the show so much and that I have a
job.''
 &HT;    Even if that job does keep her hopping.
 &HT;    ``My publicist is waving at me frantically,'' Carpenter says.
``I think I've got to go.''
 &HT;    Before she does, however, the actress expresses one unfulfilled
desire: to see Cordelia get as physically lethal as she is deadly
with a snippy line of dialogue.
 &HT;    ``I want Angel to teach me how to fight,'' she says excitedly.
``Whenever there's a demon to fight, it's Angel and Wesley who go.
Growing up in Sunnydale, I've been around the Hell Mouth. I should
be able to take care of myself and not always be in peril.
 &HT;    ``I think it would be bad-ass if I was bad for one episode and I
got to kick butt,'' she says. ``That would be a dream. I'd love to
be a Faith type.'' 
 c.2000 Ian Spelling  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Ian Spelling is a New York-based free-lance writer.) &LR; 
 &UR; EDITOR: For further information on ``Angel,'' consult the WB
Website at www.thewb.com. And don't forget to visit The New York
Times Syndicate Website at http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for
information on Inside Trek and Sci-Fi and other features. &QL; 
 &UR; (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) &QL; 
 &UR; (She also has information on how to subscribe to Inside Trek, a
weekly science-fiction column with color and black-and-white art.)
 &UR; ------------------------------------------------- &QC;
