<HEADLINE>
888-603-1036.) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 888-346-9867 or (l and f coding)  
 THE TIBURON: THE LITTLE HUNDAI THAT COULD  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BILL GRIFFITH  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   If someone asked me to define the word ``funky,'' I'd have to
give them the old
``I-can't-put-it-into-words-but-I-know-it-when-I-see-it'' line. Or,
I'd say, ``the Hyundai Tiburon.''
</P>
<P>
   Because this truly is a funky little sports car.
</P>
<P>
   Even though there aren't a lot of them around, when one does go
by you tend to notice and ask, ``What was that, anyway?''
</P>
<P>
   And the two folks I've seen get out of them were . . . well,
they struck me as being on the funky side, too.
</P>
<P>
   And, besides being funky, they weren't tall.
</P>
<P>
   Tall people don't fare well in the Tiburon.
</P>
<P>
   Only by setting the driver's seat into a slightly reclining
position could I get the Tiburon to accommodate my 6-foot frame.
And it doesn't take a genius to figure out what happens when you
hit a big pothole.
</P>
<P>
   While I was preoccupied with my fit inside the car, my good
friend Jerry, a retired
machinist-turned-gunsmith-turned-clockmaker, was more interested in
the Tiburon's fit-and-finish. He lifted the hood and hatchback,
then ran his hands over the body panels and looked at the engine
and pronounced his judgment: ``Whoever made this car knew what they
were doing.'' High praise indeed from a man who was rebuilding
Lincoln, LaSalle, and Cadillac engines back in the '40s and still
machines parts to the 10,000th of an inch.
</P>
<P>
   My problems fitting into a vehicle aren't anything new. In the
past, I've gone into a Honda store prepared to buy a Prelude, a
Toyota store ready to buy a Celica, and a Saturn store ready to buy
a two-door coupe. In each case, sitting in the vehicle _ especially
if it was equipped with a sunroof _ proved impossible. Even
plopping into Audi's much-acclaimed TT coupe left me hunched over
trying to see overhead traffic lights through the narrow
windshield.
</P>
<P>
   Obviously, part of the problem is me, but part is with these
autos' designs. They are perfect fits for most folks under
5-feet-10.
</P>
<P>
   If the Tiburon fits you, however, it could be one of the neatest
buys on the market.
</P>
<P>
   It comes with a base price tag of $13,999 and a 10-year,
100,000-mile warranty (five years bumper-to-bumper and rust
perforation). In its favor, it also offers unique styling,
surprisingly good handling, a neat-but-not-luxurious interior, and
plenty of oomph from the 140 horsepower produced by its 2.0-liter,
4-cylinder engine.
</P>
<P>
   Our test version had a sunroof, big-time sound system, rear
spoiler, and leather accoutrements that pushed the price near
$17,000.
</P>
<P>
   But guess what? It's worth it.
</P>
<P>
   Think you can't drive a 5-speed manual? This is the smoothest
I've ever tried. The main reason is that the engine revs don't
immediately fall off when you ease off the gas to shift, allowing
the engine and transmission to meet smoothly in the next gear. I
always pride myself on smooth shifts but rarely have I found
seamless shifting so easy to accomplish.
</P>
<P>
   Lift the hatchback and there's room for several weeks' worth of
groceries, the dry cleaning, and whatever else you want to toss
back there. Lower the lid and it's all hidden by sheet metal and an
almost unnoticeable cover.
</P>
<P>
   Buzzing around town, which is what the Tiburon does best, you'll
get nearly 30 miles per gallon with great performance. It does
0-to-60 in 8.5 seconds, but the perceived quickness is even better
than that.
</P>
<P>
   From the driver's seat, looking over the hood is reminiscent of
sitting in a classic Triumph Spitfire. Then there was the color _ a
yellow that harked back to Chrysler's Super Bees of the late '60s.
</P>
<P>
   Or as the lady who rolled down her window in front of
Melrose-Wakefield Hospital when I popped out at a red light to slam
down the hatchback said:
</P>
<P>
   ``I love the color of your car . . . and I love the car. What is
it anyway?''
</P>
<P>
   Hyundai Tiburon. A name worth remembering.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Nice touches:
</P>
<P>
   --The handling was sensational on those occasions when I could
let it go on a winding road.
</P>
<P>
   --The square headlight coverage pattern was unique and seemed to
give this myopic driver outstanding night vision.
</P>
<P>
   --The wipers (front and back) gave clear, clean consistent
visibility in misty and greasy road conditions.
</P>
<P>
   Annoyances:
</P>
<P>
   --The cupholders pulled out of the front console and blocked
access to the radio controls and also put the cup's contents in
jeopardy of a flying fist during gear changes.
</P>
<P>
   --The driver's seatbelt and jammed in its guide.
</P>
<P>
   --For three days, every time I hit the right directional signal
at night, I also managed to turn off the headlights, making the
driver in front of me wonder why I was flashing my lights.
</P>
<P>
   --And I could not find a spot to put a turnpike toll ticket,
except under a strap on the sun visor.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
THE NUMBERS
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Base price: $13,999 &QL; 
Price as tested: $17,747 &QL; 
Horsepower/Torque: 140/133 lb.-ft. at 4800 rpm &QL; 
Wheelbase/Overall length: 97.4 inches/170.9 inches &QL; 
Width/Height: 68.1 inches/51.7 inches &QL; 
Curb weight: 2,633 lbs. &QL; 
Seating: 2 passengers &QL; 
SOURCE: Manufacturer
</P>
</TEXT>
