<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-02 14:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4630 &Cx1f; tab-z
r v BC-SLATE-ADVISORY-NYTSF &LR;      03-02 0441
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SLATE-ADVISORY-NYTSF </SLUG>
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; WHY DOES THE MEDIA TREAT THIS POLLSTER LIKE A GOD?
 &UR; A PENSIVE BRADLEY WRITES THE FINAL CHAPTER
 &UR; SUPREME COURT GUIDE TO DRUG-SMUGGLING AND BAG-SQUEEZING
 &UR; TIME TO CLOSE THE `APPRECIATED PROPERTY' LOOPHOLE
</P>
<P>
   The following articles from SLATE, the premier online magazine
of politics and culture, are available from The New York Times
Syndicate. To purchase these ``separate buy'' articles please
contact syndicate sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480)
</P>
<P>
   1. WHY DOES THE MEDIA TREAT THIS POLLSTER LIKE A GOD?, by Joshua
Micah Marshall
</P>
<P>
   A little-known independent pollster based in Utica, N.Y., John
Zogby rocketed to fame by correctly predicting the results of the
1996 presidential election. Like all religions, the cult of Zogby
relies on myths about his feats and denial about his failures.
Meanwhile, Meanwhile, pundits, reporters and chat show hosts now
routinely genuflect to him.
</P>
<P>
   850 words: Slugged BC-CULT OF ZOGBY-SLATE
</P>
<P>
   -------
</P>
<P>
   2. A PENSIVE BRADLEY WRITES THE FINAL CHAPTER, by Jacob Weisberg
</P>
<P>
   It is striking how un-desperate Bill Bradley sounds in the face
of imminent defeat. It may be explained by the strange quality of
interiority that has characterized his campaign from the outset.
Bradley has always viewed running for president as an opportunity
for personal growth and character development. He's staying in the
race for another week to achieve a sense of completeness as he
comes to grips with the experience. To put it a bit cruelly,
Bradley views his unsuccessful presidential campaign as a book that
needs a last chapter.
</P>
<P>
   800 words: Slugged BC-BRADLEY-SWAN-SONG-SLATE
</P>
<P>
   -------
</P>
<P>
   3. SUPREME COURT GUIDE TO DRUG-SMUGGLING AND BAG-SQUEEZING, by
Dahlia Lithwick
</P>
<P>
   The Supreme Court ponders whether you have a reasonable
expectation of privacy when you place your illegal drug stash in
the overhead compartment of a Greyhound bus. Here's a tip from
Justice Antonin Scalia: Buy hard luggage.
</P>
<P>
   1,400 words: Slugged BC-GREYHOUND-BUS-PRIVACY-SLATE
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   4. TIME TO CLOSE THE `APPRECIATED PROPERTY' LOOPHOLE, by Michael
Kinsley
</P>
<P>
   Is there any reason the government should care whether you give
a charity $10,000 of stock or $10,000 in cash _ care enough to
reduce your tax bill by two or three thousand dollars for choosing
to give the stock? None that I have ever heard. But it's the kind
of
</P>
<P>
   ridiculous ``arrangement'' that gets into the tax code
unintentionally and then can't be gotten rid of.
</P>
<P>
   700 words: Slugged BC-KINSLEY-GIFT-LOOPHOLE-SLATE
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-02-00 1450EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
