A4651 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a BC-SF-BAY-STUDY-HNS &LR;      03-02 0739
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SF-BAY-STUDY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     SCIENTISTS PLAN BIOLOGICAL HISTORY OF SAN FRANCISCO BAY 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By JANE KAY  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Nearly a century ago, the steamship Albatross
patrolled the far reaches of wild San Francisco Bay, collecting and
classifying marine life as part of a nationwide scientific mission.
It was the first major study of Bay life.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the prestigious California Academy of Sciences is launching
a much larger endeavor, this time a four-year $800,000 study to map
the nearly 1,000 underwater species that inhabit the deep, shallow
and tidal waters of the Bay.
</P>
<P>
   Out of it will come a new knowledge of the ecological health of
the Bay, say scientists, who hope to learn which places in
Carquinez Strait, Suisun Bay, San Pablo Bay and the central and
southern Bay are good habitat for marine life.
</P>
<P>
   The scientists also want to locate the problem areas _ now
muddier, warmer or more polluted than in previous decades _ so they
can recommend fixes.
</P>
<P>
   A big bonus of the study will be the first field guide published
by the academy of the Bay's vast array of fish, crabs and oysters,
down to the lowly worms that dig in the bottom muds.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't have a fundamental understanding of what native
species are here and where they occur,'' said Terrence M. Gosliner,
the provost and senior curator of the academy. ``We don't even know
what we're losing at this point because it's happening so rapidly.
We can't preserve our biological diversity if we don't know what we
have.''
</P>
<P>
   Scientists prize biological diversity, the number of native
species present in an ecosystem, because it means a flourishing,
dynamic Bay.
</P>
<P>
   Some native species, those that evolve over time like the
Sacramento River's chinook salmon and, on land, the California
clapper rail, don't live anywhere else on Earth.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a strong moral commitment to preserve the native
species,'' Gosliner said. ``Their preservation really tells us
about the health of the Bay ecosystem. Every time one of those
native species disappears, the health of the ecosystem diminishes
dramatically.''
</P>
<P>
   Since the academy was founded in 1853, its scientists have
discovered at least 10,000 species of plants and animals worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   The Albatross, under the auspices of the then-U.S. Fisheries
Commission, arrived in the Bay in 1912 and spent two years
collecting data. All of it has been published, and is available at
the academy, a nonprofit institution that receives city money to
operate the Steinhart Aquarium.
</P>
<P>
   As part of the study, all the information gathered in last 150
years by the academy will be placed on computers and be available
on line.
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, one-third of the Bay has been filled, destroying
the bulk of the wetlands that once provided habitat for aquatic and
land animals.
</P>
<P>
   Dredging, reducing the amount of fresh river water and
discharging toxic chemicals and sewage also have harmed the Bay's
marine life, the scientists say.
</P>
<P>
   The academy's core of 25 scientists intends to use the past
studies to portray a biological history of the Bay, where the
natives species lived, when the exotic species came and how they
all spread or diminished.
</P>
<P>
   The Bay has about 200 non-native species, some dumped
purposefully, some arriving in ship's ballast water or on hulls,
some coming on their own as ocean waters warm.
</P>
<P>
   From the Manila clams arriving in the 1940s to the Chinese
mitten crab, the green crab, the Asian clam and the New Zealand sea
slug of the 1990s, they compete for food and sometimes prey on the
natives.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Joining the study will be Andrew Cohen, a biologist at the San
Francisco Estuary Institute, and James Carlson, a marine biologist
at Williams College in Massachusetts, both experts in invasive
species.
</P>
<P>
   Compiling a list of Bay fishes will be John McCosker and Tomio
Iwamoto from the academy and Bob Lea, a biologist from the state
Fish and Game Department. Peter Moyle, a fisheries biologist at the
University of California at Davis, also will work on the study.
</P>
<P>
   Scientific teams from the National Ocean and Atmospheric
Administration will test the marine life for toxins. San Francisco
State's Romberg Tiburon Center will measure circulation. The Bodega
Marine Laboratory will monitor flow and currents.
</P>
</TEXT>
