<SLUG> BC-WASTE-$ADV05-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    FLAGGING WAR ON WASTE GETS ELECTION-YEAR LIFT
 &HT;    With WASTE-WATCHDOG and WASTE-EXAMPLES. For release Sunday,
March 5.
 &HT;    By JULIA MALONE
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ As John McCain struggles to win over a majority of
Republicans, his presidential drive may breathe new life into the
flagging crusade against waste in government.
</P>
<P>
   In the current a flood of federal revenue, many Republicans have
abandoned the vows of thrift taken when they won majority control
of Congress six years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Joining their Democratic colleagues last year, they packed
spending bills with highway projects, weapons contracts and museums
for their home districts. At the same time, congressional oversight
of the massive federal bureaucracy is considered spotty at best.
</P>
<P>
   Now McCain has built a constituency, in part, by rallying voters
who want a major overhaul, including curbs on special-interest
campaign contributions and the ``pork barrel'' projects that often
follow.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm in the military, and I know the Air Force was forced to
take C-130s they didn't ask for,'' said Don Meno, an Army colonel
who works at the Pentagon, as he left a McCain rally last weekend
in Alexandria, Va.
</P>
<P>
   The C-130s, transport planes that cost $60 million apiece, are
consuming scarce defense dollars, Meno said. Twenty of the aircraft
were ordered at the behest of Newt Gingrich when he was the
Republican House speaker. The planes are built by Lockheed Martin
in his Marietta, Ga., district.
</P>
<P>
   McCain has focused on the congressional ``pork'' issue and
tapped into the movement spawned by Texas billionaire Ross Perot.
In fact, a national survey by McCain's pollster, Bill McInturff,
showed that 24 percent of McCain supporters voted for Perot four
years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Marshall Wittmann, a resident scholar at the Heritage Foundation
and a McCain adviser, said the Arizona senator's position cuts
across party lines. ``I think that the attack on pork barrel
spending is part of a broader reform message that resonates among
the American people,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you talk about trillions or billions of dollars in
spending, that's too abstract,'' he said. But take a specific
project for a congressional district, such as studies of chicken
manure, Wittmann said, ``and people can comprehend that.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, McCain has had little success defeating programs in the
Senate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I mean, you could get trichinosis from the last couple of
budget bills that have been passed, from all the pork,'' Wittmann
said.
</P>
<P>
   The question is whether the public is outraged enough to take
action.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the public is upset with government'' and excess
spending, said James Thurber, a political scientist at American
University. But with a glut of revenues, the slower growth in the
size of government, and a thriving economy, people are otherwise
content, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think (the McCain critique) is an argument that goes
to as wide a population as it may have in the past,'' Thurber said.
</P>
<P>
   So powerful was the McCain reform message in the early going
that his rival, Gov. George W. Bush of Texas, repositioned himself
as ``the reformer with results.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush even attempted to turn McCain's anti-pork crusade against
him last week by airing ads knocking the senator for opposing some
breast cancer research. McCain responded that he had voted against
only those programs that circumvented the ``normal review process''
to divert funds to the districts of ``powerful'' lawmakers.
</P>
<P>
   That kind of spending is the glue that holds spending bills
together, said Thurber. He pointed to last year's highway bill,
which was expanded by 25 percent to include projects for almost
every congressional district.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, he said that Congress fails to monitor the way the
money is spent.
</P>
<P>
   ``The oversight is never fun on the Hill,'' Thurber said. He
graded both parties ``F'' for failing to systematically check up on
federal agencies.
</P>
<P>
   Wittmann offered a similar assessment of the congressional
record, but he argued that the public can be stirred by a reform
message such as McCain's.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a deep belief that politics as usual has to be
changed,'' he said. ``I think that sentiment is really animating
the American electorate.''
</P>
<P>
   Julia Malone's e-mail address is juliam(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
