<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WASTE-EXAMPLES-$ADV05-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    WASHINGTON WASTE LAMPOONED A to Z
 &HT;    With WASTE. For release Sunday, March 5.
 &HT;    By JULIA MALONE
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Some people scowl or shrug at what they see as
profligate spending of taxpayer dollars for marginal or ineffective
programs.
</P>
<P>
   Martin L. Gross does something else. The retired college
professor has made a second career out of combing through thousands
of pages of federal budget documents to discover exactly where
those dollars go.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could cut this government down by 30 to 40 percent in a week
and deliver twice as many services,'' boasts the author of several
irreverent books, including his latest, ``The Government Racket
2000,'' an ``all new'' expose of Washington waste ``from A to Z.''
</P>
<P>
   On his latest list:
</P>
<P>
   _ Lavish new federal courthouses costing as much as $218 million
(in Boston) or $86 million (in Jacksonville, Fla.). A government
audit of courtrooms found that they were used for trials only 27
percent of the time.
</P>
<P>
   _ More than $100 billion in gasoline tax money invested in the
``generally failed light-rail system.'' Gross cites transportation
expert Wendell Cox's estimate that the rail system has decreased
road congestion by only one-half of 1 percent.
</P>
<P>
   _ Special ``demonstration'' projects, costing more than $9
billion, added to last year's highway authorization bill by
lawmakers for their home states. Among the projects are $12 million
for a new visitor center in West Virginia, $4.4 million to beautify
Route A1A in Daytona Beach, Fla., and $4 million for a parking
facility in Peoria, Ill.
</P>
<P>
   _ More than $4 billion a year for 127 different programs in 15
different agencies, all with the same aim of helping teenagers.
``The answer is to combine the 127 programs into four,'' he writes,
and save ``at least $3 billion.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Defense funds may be low and Air Force ranks reduced, but
Andrews Air Force Base, Md., added a third golf course ``mainly''
for federal civilian employees and members of Congress.
</P>
<P>
   _ The federal program to allow people to ``adopt'' wild horses
to save them from starvation on the western plains has a humane
ring to it, but the cost to taxpayers has been $250 million. A
review by the Associated Press revealed that some owners pay the
$125 adoption fee, wait the required year and sell the ponies to
slaughterhouses for $700 each.
</P>
<P>
   Julia Malone's e-mail address is juliam(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
