<DOCNO> NYT20000302.0163 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-02 15:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4668 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-WASTE-WATCHDOG-$ADV05     03-02 0489
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WASTE-WATCHDOG-$ADV05-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    NATION'S TOP WASTE-WATCHER CONFRONTS EUPHORIA OF SURPLUSES
 &HT;    With WASTE. For release Sunday, March 5.
 &HT;    Eds: Repeating a story first moved Feb. 16.
 &HT;    By JULIA MALONE
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Finding waste in the government might seem about as
easy as finding sand at the beach.
</P>
<P>
   The problem for David M. Walker is that nowadays, the folks he
works for aren't very interested in all that sand.
</P>
<P>
   As comptroller of the United States, Walker has the sometimes
thankless task of heading the agency that is the investigating arm
of Congress. His General Accounting Office is the chief watchdog
for exposing waste and mismanagement throughout the federal
government.
</P>
<P>
   He has a staff of 3,275 of workers who churn out some 1,500
audits, investigations and testimonies each year on everything from
how much the Pentagon pays for screws to the solvency of the Social
Security system.
</P>
<P>
   But currently, a deluge of budget surpluses has undercut some of
the urgency of his work.
</P>
<P>
   When Walker presented a list of 61 potential reforms and program
eliminations to the Senate Budget Committee a few weeks back, some
senators didn't wait to hear him speak before they launched into
spirited defenses of their pet projects.
</P>
<P>
   ``That hearing illustrated the difficulty of making some
changes,'' Walker said philosophically in an interview later.
</P>
<P>
   An impeccably attired 48-year-old whose wire-rimmed glasses and
orderly office fit the image of the nation's top auditor, he
pointed out that he only makes suggestions. It's up to the
lawmakers to accept them.
</P>
<P>
   ``After all, we work for 540 politicians, and they must be
accountable to the American people,'' he said. ``Reasonable people
can and do differ.''
</P>
<P>
   The former partner and global manager in Atlanta for the
accounting firm Arthur Andersen, Walker systematically studied the
terrain during his first 15 months on the job. Last month he
announced his plan to streamline his 77-year-old agency's $378
million annual operations, setting off grumbling within the ranks.
He keeps his staff on their toes by showering them with e-mails,
starting around 6:30 in the morning.
</P>
<P>
   He has also met with almost every member of Congress, not to
mention the secretaries of waste-plagued federal departments.
</P>
<P>
   Still, with the economic boom, Congress and the executive
agencies may not be very receptive to the comptroller's findings.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes he's going to feel like a skunk at a picnic and
sometimes he's going to feel more popular, but that's his job,''
said Paul C. Light, director of governmental studies at the
Brookings Institution, a Washington research center. ``And he's got
to keep hacking on it and hacking on it and hacking on it.''
</P>
<P>
   Julia Malone's e-mail address is juliam(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
