<P>
   &UR; FEATURE Stories &LR;  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   TV-OLD-VALUES (Undated) _ Despite its high-tech set and clanging
music, ``Who Wants to be a Millionaire'' offers the veneer of a
return to comfy old values, to the days when quiz shows were king
and people pulled together to cheer on their champions. Even its
immense success is a throwback, uniting the country in a way that
is nearly impossible in this age of 500 channels and fragmented
audiences. Fox's ``Who Wants to Marry a Multimillionaire?'' was
typical of the network in putting the sleaziest possible spin on a
trend, as it reveled in the caveman ethos of the marriage contest.
But both the benign quiz show resurgence that ABC's ``Millionaire''
has led (several clones and counting) and the blatant sexism of the
Fox show are symptoms of a deeper retro impulse. By Caryn James.
(Moved). &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BRUCE-WILLIS-FILMS (Undated) _ If Bruce Willis feels
``unappreciated,'' to quote his character from ``Die Hard,'' it's
easy to understand why. ``The Sixth Sense,'' the twist of an
otherworld thriller, was one of the biggest hits of 1999. The movie
has earned six Oscar nominations, including deserved acknowledgment
of young Haley Joel Osment and Toni Colette, as the mama lion whose
belief in her tormented son is steadfast. Yet Willis's considerable
effort in that film went unnoticed by the Academy. By now, he may
feel that the most memorable line from ``The Sixth Sense'' _ ``I
see dead people'' _ refers to the way Oscar voters feel about him.
By Elvis Mitchell. (Moved).  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FILM AND VIDEO &LR;  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   WESTERN-FILMS (Undated) _ Two movies set in a once-renowned, now
rarely visited, arena will open this year. Next month, Miramax will
release ``Texas Rangers,'' starring the television pinups James Van
Der Beek and Ashton Kutcher, among others, as wet-behind-the-ears
recruits in Stetsons and bandoliers who take on a band of
renegades. Disney's ``Shanghai Noon,'' starring Jackie Chan as a
19th-century Chinese man trailing a Chinese princess in the
American West, follows in the summer. By Graham Fuller. (Moved). &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SHANDLING-ALIEN-FILM (Hollywood) _ Garry Shandling plays an
alien in the movie ``What Planet Are You From?'' _ his character
has been sent to impregnate an Earth woman and bring back the child
as part of a plot to take over the universe _ he has been shorn of
the outward appurtenances of manhood and reduced to wearing a
Freudian clip-on. This mechanical apparatus produces hydraulic
whining noises during lovemaking, though most of the whining in the
picture still comes from Shandling. It is all about him, after all.
The film, directed by Mike Nichols, also stars Annette Bening and
John Goodman as a sort of jumbo Javert who is onto the scheme. It
opened Friday. By Bruce Newman. (Moved).  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THEATER &LR;  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BOYD-GAINES-THEATER (New York) _ Boyd Gaines emerged from his
dressing room after a matinee of ``Contact,'' famished and drained.
He apologized for the time he had taken in collecting himself. It
is fortunate that Gaines did not make a persuasive enough case
against himself, for his moving performance as Michael Wiley, the
highly successful if suicidally lonely New Yorker of the show's
title piece, is one of the most emotionally rewarding facets of
``Contact.'' That his face is familiar to regular theatergoers _ he
won Tony Awards in 1989 and 1994 for ``The Heidi Chronicles'' and
``She Loves Me'' _ deepens the audience's own contact with the
production. The play being so popular has moved to the Vivian
Beaumont theater, where it is in previews before officially
reopening on March 30. By Peter Marks. (Moved). WITH PHOTO. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   DEBORAH-YATES-THEATER (New York) _ From the moment she enters in
that arresting yellow dress, it is clear that what is happening is
not just another striking theatrical performance. It is the
uncommon but unmistakable emergence of a star. In the new Lincoln
Center dance-play, ``Contact,'' reopening at the Vivian Beaumont
Theater after a sold-out run at the Mitzi E. Newhouse, Deborah
Yates dares you to take your eyes off her. And not just because she
can fly through the air without an upswept blonde strand slipping
out of place or because she makes complex swing combinations look
as easy as the box step. It is because Yates commands the stage
with an authority that never seems arrogant, combining a playful
grit with an elegant grace that makes you want to know more about
her. By Robyn Pogrebin. (Moved). WITH PHOTO. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PORGY-AND-BESS (Undated) _ ``Porgy And Bess'' comes to the New
York City Opera this week, so it is a good time to celebrate the
man largely responsible for the opera's resilience: DuBose Heyward,
the author of the 1925 novel ``Porgy.'' Of course there are those
fabulous Gershwin tunes, but no other Gershwin show has proved
revivable, and in no other Gershwin show do the songs embody
dramatic characters, even when sung out of context or played
without the lyrics. By David Schiff. (Moved). WITH PHOTO. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   FLEA-THEATER (New York) _ Until recently, the 80-seat Flea in
Manhattan has been thought of mainly as an Off Off Broadway
theater. Its productions have included Mac Wellman's ``Infrared,''
``Chere Maitre,'' starring Irene Worth, Rudy Stern's Theater of
Light and ``Benten Kozo,'' a Kabuki play, which won an Obie. Now it
is becoming known downtown as a dance venue hoping to give some
competition to more established spaces like P.S. 122, Dixon Place,
the Joyce SoHo and the Kitchen. This month the Flea is presenting
``Get Up! Two,'' a free festival of short dances by more than 15
choreographers that will run Tuesday nights at 8:30 through March
21. By Kevin Giordano. (Moved). WITH PHOTO. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AMERICAN-SHOWS (London) _ When it comes to theatrical invasions,
there is a new one here worth signaling: the influx of American
shows, several of them in their original productions. Think of it
as a long-overdue attempt to redress what some might call a
theatrical imbalance, because the traffic, of course, generally
heads the other way. On Broadway, some kind of history was made
last spring when eight English or Irish stagings _ including those
of several American plays, ``The Iceman Cometh'' for starters _ all
opened within 10 weeks. By Matt Wolf. (Moved). &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CLASSICAL MUSIC &LR;  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   DALLAS-SYMPHONY (Undated) _ Tell a New Yorker that the symphony
orchestra in Dallas, Texas, is 100 years old, and the reaction will
probably be surprise. The Dallas Symphony Orchestra would like to
change that. True, being 100 years old in Dallas is a little
different from being 100 years old in, say, Philadelphia (where the
orchestra is celebrating its centennial this year, as well). The
DSO's history has followed a rollercoaster track of highs and lows.
By Anne Midgette. (Moved). WITH PHOTO. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SCIARRINO-MUSIC (New York) _ ``Recitativo Oscuro,'' the title of
the concerto by Salvatore Sciarrino that Maurizio Pollini will play
this week at Carnegie Hall, with Pierre Boulez and the London
Symphony, is consistent with others in this composer's recent
output, where ideas of night and darkness often lurk. But the
embodiment of such ideas here is far more incisive, more vehement
and, indeed, louder than has been usual for Sciarrino. By Paul
Griffiths. (Moved).  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   LONDON-SYMPHONY (Undated) _ Pierre Boulez's four concerts with
the London Symphony Orchestra at Carnegie Hall in Manhattan
beginning Friday are, in their way, the closing of a book. The
title of this book might be ``An Age of Exploration,'' and we have
been turning its pages for about 100 years. There will be new
pieces by Salvatore Sciarrino, Peter Eotvos, Olga Neuwirth and
George Benjamin, but none will offer groundbreaking methodology or
send music into some unexplored orbit. They will make sounds,
maneuver in time and hope that we like what we hear. By Bernard
Holland. (Moved).  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SHOSTAKOVICH-MUSIC (New York) _ The full houses and rapturous
critical response that greeted the Emerson String Quartet's recent
Shostakovich cycle at Alice Tully Hall gave further evidence that
Shostakovich, a giant of 20th-century music, may yet be accorded,
in the 21st, the recognition long withheld out of irrelevant
geopolitical and musico-political concerns. Now the Emerson's
wonderful performances of all 15 quartets are available in a
Deutsche Grammophon recording. By Richard Taruskin. (Moved). &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SHANGHAI-SYMPHONY (Shanghai, China) _ Last year the Shanghai
Symphony Orchestra, as it has been called since 1953, celebrated
its 120th anniversary. As the nation's oldest symphony orchestra,
it has done more to promote the development of symphonic music in
China than any other institution. Its claim to the title ``best
orchestra in the Far East,'' bestowed in the 1930s, is long past.
But if judged on the basis of perseverance and dedication in the
face of seemingly insurmountable odds, the Shanghai Symphony stands
alone. By Sheila Melvin and Jindong Cai. (Moved). WITH PHOTO. &QL; 
 &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   &UR; POP MUSIC &LR;  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   CARNAVAL-BRAZIL (Salvador, Brazil) _ Carnaval in Salvador, the
state capital of Bahia, is purely a street carnaval, different from
the Folies Bergeres-like televised festivities that take place in
Rio de Janeiro. The music played on top of the trio eletrico _ it's
usually the popular new Brazilian samba-reggae or axe music _ has a
direct relationship to the street and takes part in a kind of
natural selection: each year carnaval starts with dozens of songs
written specifically for the festivities, and by the end of the
week that repertory has been narrowed to a handful. The trio
eletrico is the medium, and the street decides. By Ben Ratliff.
(Moved). WITH PHOTO. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   DYLAN-MUSIC (Undated) _ When Bob Dylan was an acerbic young folk
singer warning that the times were a-changin', one change he
probably did not envision was that he would become a darling of the
high-art world. Yet last fall, nearly 40 years after he made his
first records, Dylan was declared one of the greatest artists of
the 20th century by Andrew Motion, the British poet laureate. And
now the composer John Corigliano, commissioned to write a song
cycle for the soprano Sylvia McNair's Carnegie Hall recital on
March 15, has produced ``Mr. Tambourine Man: Seven Songs of Bob
Dylan,'' a 35-minute song cycle. By Allan Kozinn. (Moved). WITH
PHOTO. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   CARNIVAL-MUSIC (Undated) _ Carnival dances in this weekend
across the Caribbean, South America, southern Europe and that
splendid cultural biosphere, New Orleans. From now through Fat
Tuesday, carnival's first paradox is that it ties profane delights
to the church calendar, wrapping up before Lent begins on Ash
Wednesday. By Jon Pareles. (Moved).  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ART &LR;  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   CHARLES-ATLAS-ART (New York) _ In the last 30 years, Charles
Atlas has created scores of videos, films, performances and set and
lighting designs for opera, theater and dance. This Friday through
April 1 he returns to the Kitchen, in Manhattan, where he first
performed a short dance in a 1974 series that also featured the
artists Joan Jonas and Hannah Wilke. His current appearance is as a
video-installation artist with two new works, ``As If You Like It''
and ``10,'' both of which will fill the walls of the Kitchen's
large second-floor gallery with digitally altered patterns of
mesmerizing movement by elaborately costumed performers. By Michael
Rush. (Moved). WITH PHOTO. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   TURKEY-ART (Istanbul, Turkey) _ There is bad news for anyone
planning to visit Turkey this year. The velvet-lined case that
houses the country's most famous artifact, the glittering Topkapi
dagger, will be empty. Nor will visitors be able to see the curved
battle sword that hung from Sultan Mehmet the Conqueror's hip when
his army captured Constantinople in 1453, or the inlaid
ebony-and-ivory throne from which the vast Ottoman Empire was once
ruled, or the dazzling emerald-studded turban decoration that awed
visitors to the court of Sultan Ahmed I in the 17th century. The
good news, however, is that these objects and more than 200 others,
some of which have never before left the Topkapi Palace, will be
missing because they will be on tour through the United States.
They are part of one of the most ambitious exhibitions of Ottoman
treasures ever assembled. The exhibition, called ``Palace of Gold
and Light: Treasures From the Topkapi, Istanbul,'' opened on
Wednesday at the Corcoran Gallery of Art in Washington. By Stephen
Kinzer. (Moved). WITH PHOTO. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   RENZO-PIANO-ARCH (Paris) _ Renzo Piano chuckled as he remembered
how he and Richard Rogers were ``young boys, really young and quite
bad boys'' in 1971 when they won the architecture competition for
the Georges Pompidou Center with a design that they considered a
parody of technology. Even now, at 62, Piano, a good-natured
Italian, seemed amazed that France allowed two young foreigners _
he was 33 and his British partner was 37 _ to challenge the sober
18th-century stone facades of eastern Paris with an immense
metallic structure variously described (by its critics) as a
refinery or an ocean liner and (by its architects) as ``a Jules
Verne spaceship that can't fly.'' The Pompidou Center, which opened
in 1977, proved immensely popular and today it (italics)is(end
italics) a monument. Piano in turn made his name and collected
architectural honors, including the highly regarded Pritzker Prize
in 1998. By Alan Riding. (Moved). WITH PHOTO. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
