<HEADER>
A4677 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r f BC-BIZBOOKS-REVIEWS-TEX     03-02 0938
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZBOOKS-REVIEWS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MANAGEMENT CONSULTANT'S THIRD WORK TRIES DIFFERENT ANGLE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TERESA McUSIC 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Like a dog biting your pants leg, James Champy just won't let
go.
</P>
<P>
   First, the management consultant invents reengineering with his
book, ``Reengineering the Corporation.'' He tells us to go through
every process, every procedure, every traditional
way-it's-always-been-done system and tweak it until it runs faster,
smoother and more profitably. His book hits bestseller status,
coins a buzzword and, with his consulting work, starts a corporate
movement.
</P>
<P>
   A few years later, Champy sees that even though many are trying
his ideas, few are implementing them as he had hoped, so results
are mixed. Out of frustration, he blames management for poor
performance and writes ``Reengineering Management'' to contend that
the concept isn't flawed; only those trying to manage it are.
</P>
<P>
   Now he presents good management from a different angle. Champy
is writing about good and bad managers, and how they came to be. He
cites successful leaders and hopes to nurture the potential of
others.
</P>
<P>
   One gets the feeling that he's trying to create the type of
manager necessary to implement his ideas _ to prove that those
ideas work.
</P>
<P>
   Building strong leadership is the premise behind ``The Arc of
Ambition: Defining the Leadership Journey'' (Perseus Books, 272
pages, $26).
</P>
<P>
   This work is well-written, although many of the same people _
Michael Dell, Ray Krok, Steve Jobs _ are analyzed and highlighted
as they are in hundreds of management books.
</P>
<P>
   The difference is the cohesion with which these people are tied
to the ideas presented. The book is thought-provoking, not just
another string of bios.
</P>
<P>
   Another difference is that many of the subjects _ Cesar Chavez,
Nelson Mandela, William Jefferson Clinton _ don't pop up in your
typical management/leadership books. They add an interesting
dimension to the ideas on defining leadership.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the credit for this fresh air _ perhaps most of it _
must go to Champy's co-author, Harvard Business School Professor
Nitin Nohria. The work has an international insight that Nohria
likely brought to the table. It also has a classical feel. In one
paragraph, the authors hail the life of English Romantic poet John
Keats, in the next, Starbucks founder Howard Schultz.
</P>
<P>
   And although scholarly, the book contains a good dose of the
real world.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ambition started out as a pedestrian notion derived from the
Latin word `ambitionem,' meaning to walk around soliciting votes,''
Champy and Nohria write. ``But its reality can be fierce and its
results momentous.''
</P>
<P>
   The authors contend that ambition can be traced in an arc that
rises and falls in stages. Those stages include:
</P>
<P>
   - See what others don't. Among those who did so are Dell, John
Mackey and the Wright brothers.
</P>
<P>
   _ Follow a steadfast path. Case studies include George Lucas,
Mandela and Sam Walton.
</P>
<P>
   _ Seize the moment. Leaders who did so include Krok, Robert
Johnson and Martin Luther King.
</P>
<P>
   _ Temper ambition. This means setting goals while ensuring
disciplined execution. Those who didn't include Clinton and Alfred
Dunlap.
</P>
<P>
   _ Inspire with a greater purpose. Among the examples: Chavez,
Mohandas Gandhi and Monsanto's Robert Shapiro.
</P>
<P>
   Other stages of ambition include not violating values, keeping
control by giving it up, changing or dying, and leaving gracefully.
Names from Abraham Lincoln to Peter Lynch are included in this
group.
</P>
<P>
   Surprisingly, the book works, despite its well-worn theme. Maybe
good management can't be overanalyzed.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Jacket blurbs
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   ``The 75 Greatest Management Decisions Ever Made ... and 21 of
the Worst''
</P>
<P>
   By Stuart Crainer
</P>
<P>
   AMACOM, $24.95
</P>
<P>
   This is a fun read, looking at management from a
sometimes-offbeat perspective. Business and management writer
Stuart Crainer goes back in history _ all the way back to 100 B.C.
in Thebes at one point _ to uncover great management decisions.
Most examples are a bit more recent, from Michael Dell selling PCs
directly to consumers to the Grateful Dead allowing fans to tape
their concerts. Crainer offers lively examples of excellent
management decisions and how they affected our lives.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   ``The Secret of a Winning Culture: Building High-Performance
Teams''
</P>
<P>
   By Larry E. Senn and John R. Childress
</P>
<P>
   Leadership Press, $25
</P>
<P>
   A Harvard Business Review study found that 75 percent of
managers polled were unhappy with change initiatives at their
companies. Larry Senn and John Childress suggest that most
corporate changes are focused on the operational and technical side
and ignore the human side. Their book focuses on the best way to
communicate with employees about the changes many companies are
facing.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   ``The New Working Woman's Guide to Retirement Planning: Saving
and Investing Now for a Secure Future''
</P>
<P>
   By Martha Priddy Patterson
</P>
<P>
   Penn, $19.95
</P>
<P>
   Only about 10 percent of U.S. women expect to receive retirement
benefits, and those who do will usually get half of as much as
their male colleagues, writes attorney and KPMG Director Martha
Priddy Patterson. That fact alone will have many wanting to buy
this book. Patterson, who specializes in employee benefits law,
writes that women must build retirement funding separate from an
employer or Social Security. She explores the various avenues.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Teresa McUsic reviews business books for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the
World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
