<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-02 15:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4680 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r l BC-NOVELIST-FAME-$ADV05-     03-02 0660
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NOVELIST-FAME-$ADV05-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     AUTHOR OF `ENGLISH PATIENT' TURNS ATTENTION TO TROUBLED
HOMELAND 
</HEADLINE>
  
 &HT;     (For release Sunday, March 5)   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By CASEY SEILER  
 &HT;     c.2000 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ From F. Scott Fitzgerald and Truman Capote on
down, the shelves are stacked high with the biographies of writers
who grabbed the brass ring _ fame! money! Hollywood! _ only to
watch it turn into a noose.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing is not to take it very seriously,'' said novelist
Michael Ondaatje, speaking by telephone from his home in Toronto.
``(Fame) can do a lot of damage. But if one has a certain intent
that's private when you're working, it certainly helps.''
</P>
<P>
   Ondaatje knows what he's talking about: His 1992 novel, ``The
English Patient,'' hit the literary equivalent of the trifecta. An
alternately grim and lyrical tale of love during wartime, the book
received adulatory reviews (including a Booker Prize), earned solid
sales and _ miracle of miracles _ inspired a faithful film
adaptation that dominated the 1996 Academy Awards.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was very lucky to go through the filmmaking process with
people who were both talented and honorable,'' said Ondaatje, who
discussed Anthony Minghella's film after a screening Wednesday
night at the State University of New York at Albany.
</P>
<P>
   Ondaatje, 56, is married to the nonfiction writer Linda
Spalding.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd much rather talk about the film than about myself,''
Ondaatje said, ``so (the film's success) affords me a nice kind of
disguise.''
</P>
<P>
   Even before ``The English Patient,'' Ondaatje had been exploring
fame as a theme in his work. His 1976 fact-based novel ``Coming
Through Slaughter'' describes trumpeter Buddy Bolden's descent from
musical acclaim to madness and obscurity. (``There are no prizes,''
the book concludes darkly.)
</P>
<P>
   ```Slaughter' was a book about the dangers of fame, and I feel
much the same way today,'' Ondaatje said.
</P>
<P>
   In the intervening years, the writer's work has gone global. He
revisited his native Sri Lanka in the 1982 family memoir ``Running
in the Family.'' His 1987 novel ``In the Skin of a Lion''
reimagined the boomtown industry of his adopted Toronto; several
characters from that story traveled to Italy for ``The English
Patient.'' Ondaatje's four collections of poetry include ``The
Cinnamon Peeler'' and ``Handwriting.''
</P>
<P>
   Slated for release May 1, Ondaatje's new novel, ``Anil's Ghost''
(to be published by Knopf), returns to Sri Lanka. But instead of
the lush colonial years depicted in ``Running in the Family,''
Ondaatje has set his story against a modern landscape of political
unrest and officially sanctioned violence.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not sure which was more difficult,'' Ondaatje said. ``With
`Running in the Family,' there's always the danger of encountering
relatives ... but one kind of feels able to describe your own
stories, as long as you're going about it with a generous spirit.''
</P>
<P>
   But for Ondaatje, the sense of obligation is stronger when he's
creating a fictional character. ``You're more responsible in
fiction,'' he said. ``You're entering someone else's world
entirely.''
</P>
<P>
   He's gearing up for another kind of obligation: the forced march
of pre-publication interviews and book tours.
</P>
<P>
   ``The readings, I enjoy _ I'm not an antisocial type of
person,'' he said. ``But I think writers are an odd mix of hams and
the warily private. Don DeLillo is a very private person, but then
he writes a 600-page book. It's a very curious thing.''
</P>
<P>
   After the success of his last novel, Ondaatje understands the
publishing world's expectations for this one.
</P>
<P>
   ``Strangely, that hasn't bothered me,'' he said. ``I think I was
able to turn it off when I came back to writing. I feel very good
about this book, (but) I don't think it's going to have anything
like the success of `The English Patient.'
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not necessary to hit that kind of grand slam again.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-02-00 1533EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
