<DOCNO> NYT20000302.0177 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-02 15:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4696 &Cx1f; taf-z
r l BC-TIGHTS-FIGHT-FLAB-(NE     03-02 0613
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TIGHTS-FIGHT-FLAB-(NEW-SCIENTIST)-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PATENTED PANTYHOSE CLAIM TO BANISH CELLULITE  
 (FOR RELEASE THE WEEK OF MARCH 6, 2000)
</HEADLINE>
   (This article from the London-based science and technology weekly
NEW SCIENTIST is free for use for New York Times News Service
clients. Please send clippings to the New York Times Syndicate at
122 E. 42nd St., New York, N.Y. 10168 or fax clippings to
212-499-3382.) 
 By BARRY FOX  
 Copyright 1999 New Scientist  
 (Distributed by New York Times Syndicate)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Could a pair of tights beat cellulite?
</P>
<P>
   Victoria's Secret, a U.S. lingerie chain, has filed a patent
covering a treatment for cellulite using chemically impregnated
pantyhose tights. The company claims the pantyhose can treat
cellulite _ the unsightly ``orange peel'' fatty deposits that some
women develop beneath the skin of their thighs and buttocks. It is
not yet known if the company plans to launch a product using this
technology.
</P>
<P>
   The European patent (EP 955 043) was filed by Victoria's Secret
of Reynoldsburg, Ohio, a company that runs 800 stores in North
America. But the company has refused to confirm whether or not it
intends to launch a product using the technology. In fact, it has
so far refused any comment.
</P>
<P>
   The patent covers a treatment for cellulite using ``hose
material that is worn tightly on the skin.'' It says a compound
called theophylline acetate (THA) _ previously administered orally
to treat bronchial disorders such as asthma _ is bonded to nylon
with an organic polymer called PEI, which is usually used as an
adhesive in inks and dyes. The THA is doped with silantriol, a
silica-based compound which Victoria's Secret says has been shown
to ``increase the penetration of certain chemical compounds that
are not easily passed into the skin.''
</P>
<P>
   The PEI binds strongly to the THA and silantriol when the tights
are not being worn. But when they are clinging tightly to human
skin, sweat is released, the pH of the fabric rises, and friction
with the skin generates heat. This breaks the ionic bonds with PEI,
allowing THA and silantriol to permeate the skin. To work, the
tights must be worn for at least three 8-hour days. Washing the
tights with a light detergent does not affect the chemicals.
</P>
<P>
   Victoria's Secret does not explain how the chemicals remove
cellulite. Susan Jebb, a scientist specializing in human nutrition
at the Medical Research Council in Cambridge, has investigated many
slimming aids, including creams for rubbing on cellulite. She is
skeptical about claims that chemicals can help.
</P>
<P>
   ``The general view is that it is the massage that helps, not the
cream,'' Jebb says. ``But when women pay a lot for creams, they are
more likely to use them.''
</P>
<P>
   In its patent, Victoria's Secret reports that a dozen volunteers
wore the tights for 30 days. The firm says measurements confirmed
by ultrasound scans have shown a 2- 5-centimeter reduction in the
circumference of volunteers' thighs.
</P>
<P>
   It also claims that volunteers' thighs appeared smoother, with
less fatty tissue on the hips. Formerly tight jeans, it reports,
``felt baggy and loose.''
</P>
<P>
   But Jebb cautions: ``Short-term size reduction in the thighs
tells nothing about the long-term reduction of body fat.''
</P>
<P>
   It's not clear why Victoria's Secret is so reluctant to discuss
its plans for the technology. But if the tights do go on sale, the
end results might finally settle the burning question: Is it the
chemical content of a slimming cream or massaging it in that
accounts for any reduction in thigh size?
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (This article is excerpted from New Scientist, a weekly science
and technology magazine based in London.) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-02-00 1537EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000302.0178 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-02 15:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4707 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-PLANET-FILM-REVIEW-NY     03-02 1224
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PLANET-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`WHAT PLANET ARE YOU FROM?': POWER AND ABILITIES FAR BELOW THOSE OF
MORTAL MEN 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds.: Production notes are at end of review.) 
(jt) 
 By ELVIS MITCHELL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``What Planet Are You From?'' represents a breakthrough of sorts
for Garry Shandling. He couldn't be less of a commitophobe than his
character is here. He's out to impregnate a woman and marry her,
the polar opposite of the fearsome, paranoid creeps he's played on
television and in stand-up routines.
</P>
<P>
   But as soon as the woman he finds gives birth to a son, he has
to disappear. So not everything has changed, although this time
he's leaving because he's an alien whose mission is to find a woman
to bear him a child he can take back to his home planet. One of the
things that remains the same is that whenever Shandling exposes
that picket fence expanse of teeth, something's wrong; he looks as
if the fading memory of a bad smell lingers.
</P>
<P>
   The inhabitants of his planet ``are a product of cloning,'' says
the on-screen text at the beginning of this uneven comedy. ``Their
reproductive organs have shrunk and disappeared. They have no
emotions.'' They also have no women and are all clad in gray,
brushed-wool Nehru jackets, the kind of outfit Keenen Ivory Wayans
would wear if he became an airline pilot.
</P>
<P>
   The mission gives Shandling a chance to be direct, although his
come-ons are the product of instructions you would hear in a more
enlightened infomercial. The pick-up lines he uses, given to him by
Graydon, his leader (Ben Kingsley, who delivers every line with a
quince-jam affect), are on the order of ``Your footwear is quite
stylish.''
</P>
<P>
   When he arrives on Earth after transporting himself onto a plane
that's still in flight and causing so much trouble no one bothers
to ask where he came from, he takes the name Harold Anderson and
goes to work as a loan officer at a bank. He's not picky about
women, although his bank co-worker Perry (Greg Kinnear) is so
sleazy and desperate that Harold's insistent come-ons are innocent
by comparison. The womanizing Perry is so self-absorbed that his
features sag with boredom whenever someone else opens his mouth,
unless he sees a way to take advantage of the conversation.
</P>
<P>
   Perry cruises for dates at Alcoholics Anonymous meetings, to
which he takes Harold. Susan (Annette Bening), a recovering
alcoholic who has passed through a number of careers and
boyfriends, catches Harold's eye. She's now a freaked-out real
estate agent, a profession that has become Bening's on-screen
specialty, although she's much saner here than she was in the same
job in ``American Beauty.'' This movie feels cold when she's not on
screen; she's so much the emotional center of ``Planet'' that her
resemblance to the Columbia Pictures logo comes to mind.
</P>
<P>
   The blend of cravenness and manipulation that fuels office
politics _ part of the story mechanics of Shandling's ``Larry
Sanders Show'' _ becomes a motif here. Several observations play
out in the film, chief among them that people talk past one
another, and no one is really listening. Harold, the outsider, is
the only one who takes in what other people say, if only so he can
try to make sense of it.
</P>
<P>
   There's a lot of Shandling in this movie, which isn't
surprising, since he is one of its writers. The combination of fear
and spirituality that can be found if you pay close attention to
his work surfaces throughout ``Planet.'' At a climactic point
Harold muses ruefully, ``It's through conflict that we learn about
ourselves,'' the kind of thing you'd expect to hear if Emily
Dickinson ran a group-therapy session.
</P>
<P>
   The movie clears space for Shandling to work the room. Sitting
at a bar and commiserating with a fellow drinker, he sails into a
riff about aliens that sounds like a bit he would do sitting next
to David Letterman. He finds a way to squeeze somestand-up into
the picture, just so the experience of acting in a movie isn't
totally alien to him.
</P>
<P>
   It fits that he would write a romantic comedy about another race
seeking world domination from the alien's point of view. Harold is,
in the end, just a guy trying to please his boss. His travails
include the organ with which he has been fitted to do his job,
which makes as much noise as aircraft landing gear when activated.
And it is activated a lot.
</P>
<P>
   ``Planet'' has an almost beatific fastidiousness. It's as if
someone took a dust cloth and a bottle of Clean to Phoenix, the
film's setting, before the director, Mike Nichols, and his crew set
foot in the area. (With its wide-open desolation, Phoenix works as
the place an alien would find inviting.)
</P>
<P>
   The film is droll and organized; in their meticulousness,
Nichols and Shandling are a little too much in sync. Even the
schtickiest elements are free of mildew; when Linda Fiorentino, as
Perry's vampy wife, shows up, the va-va-voom drumbeat that
accompanies her is so muted that it has a world-music feel to it.
Nichols stages the movie with a languid deadpan, so that
Shandling's slight remoteness isn't jarring; it becomes a piece
about small-scale reactions to the absurdity of the everyday. The
set-up allows ``Planet'' to leer at women and then ridicule that
impulse.
</P>
<P>
   It has also cannily been structured as an ensemble work, a
series of set pieces in which the characters react to Harold's
plainspokenness. The boldness comes from the cast as the
characters' apparent rationality unravels scene by scene. The
masterly John Goodman is a relentless FAA investigator whose zeal
to uncover the truth plants entirely the wrong idea in the head of
his wife (Caroline Aaron), and her patience is dwindling. Judy
Greer is a seemingly normal flight attendant whose anxieties emerge
as Harold gets to know her better. Nichols' instinct for casting is
a boon; the talented and watchable cast also includes Richard
Jenkins.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually the flakiness of Earthlings infects Harold as he
spends more time among them; he can't trust himself anymore. It's
``The Man Who Fell to Earth'' played for laughs. Unfortunately,
``Planet'' is just as cold conceptually. Shandling has developed
into a fine actor over the years, but he's finnicky and brittle
here. Nichols drapes his own dry imperiousness over the script, and
the result is a romantic comedy without a romance. This movie wants
to be sweet and dark at the same time, but it is as distant as a
planet's satellite.
</P>
<P>
   Rating: ``What Planet Are You From?'' is rated R (Under 17
requires accompanying parent or guardian). It includes alien sexual
apparatus, nudity and adult language related to Shandling's
mission.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `WHAT PLANET ARE YOU FROM?'
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Mike Nichols; written by Garry Shandling, Michael
Leeson, Ed Solomon and Peter Tolan, based on a story by Shandling
and Leeson; director of photography, Michael Ballhaus; edited by
Richard Marks; music by Carter Burwell; production designer, Bo
Welch; produced by Nichols, Shandling and Neil Machlis; released by
Columbia Pictures. Running time: 115 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Cast: Garry Shandling (Harold Anderson), Annette Bening (Susan),
Greg Kinnear (Perry Gordon), Ben Kingsley (Graydon), Linda
Fiorentino (Helen Gordon), John Goodman (Roland Jones), Caroline
Aaron (Nadine), Judy Greer (Rebecca) and Richard Jenkins (Don
Fisk).
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
