<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-CSNY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REUNITING FOR THE ROCK OF AGES 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By BRUCE WESTBROOK 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   To quote his Byrds song ``Renaissance Fair,'' David Crosby
sometimes looks around these days and says, ``I think that maybe
I'm dreaming.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm the happiest guy you're gonna talk to today,'' Crosby, 58,
said earlier this week.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm kind of amazed I'm alive, let alone doing this well,'' he
said. ``So yeah, it's all very good.''
</P>
<P>
   Life is good in large part because Crosby _ a veteran of rock's
highs and lows since the '60s _ is sober and strong and playing
with his old friends in a reunion tour of Crosby, Stills, Nash &AMP;
Young, the early rock supergroup.
</P>
<P>
   He and Stephen Stills, Graham Nash and Neil Young launched the
tour Jan. 24.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL; 
CSNY have a Monday date at Compaq Center in Houston.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(END OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Crosby promises their fans about 30 songs in three hours, not
counting an intermission.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're still real excited about playing music,'' he assured.
``We still want to crank it up and rock. We still have pretty much
the same value systems we've had all along and stick up for the
same kind of things.''
</P>
<P>
   It's not as if any of the four ever went away. All have had solo
successes, and Crosby is even an author, having written about rock
stars' political activism in ``Stand and Be Counted'' (Harper,
$25), new in stores.
</P>
<P>
   He's also part of the rock band CPR (along with Jeff Pevar and
Crosby's long-lost son, James Raymond), which will finish a new
album after the CSNY tour ends in April.
</P>
<P>
   So it's not as if Crosby needed a reunion. Already a two-time
member of the Rock and Roll Hall of Fame (with the Byrds and CSNY),
he's one of rock's greatest living icons _ though the ``living''
part was often in jeopardy.
</P>
<P>
   A longtime drug-abuser, Crosby reached a turning point when he
spent a year in the Texas Department of Corrections during the
mid-'80s on a drug and weapons arrest. There, he endured an
agonizing ``cold turkey'' withdrawal from drugs.
</P>
<P>
   After his release, Crosby spent a short time at a halfway house
in Houston and joined Nash at a show at a local club before
returning to his home in California.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, he's had 14 years of drug-free living.
</P>
<P>
   ``Being in Huntsville (Texas), I think, probably saved my
life,'' he said. ``That's where I quit drugs.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a very hard way to do it, but I don't regret it at all.
It was necessary. I was in terrible shape until that.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet going straight wasn't enough. Crosby wouldn't have survived
without a liver transplant in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Nash also has had travails. Last year he broke both legs in a
boating accident. When the CSNY tour was announced in October, Nash
was in a wheelchair.
</P>
<P>
   ``But Graham's doing great now, man,'' Crosby said. ``Our
biggest problem is to get him to slow down. He's got this `it's
only a flesh wound' attitude.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was hurt bad, no question. But he's a brave guy who doesn't
want to admit he's in pain, and he works really hard.''
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, CSN have recorded and toured together much more
than CSNY. Young didn't join until after CSN's self-titled debut
disc in '69, followed by CSNY's ``Deja Vu.''
</P>
<P>
   Both were huge hits, but the group splintered in the mid-'70s,
embarking on solo projects and occasional blends such as Crosby and
Nash's joint recordings.
</P>
<P>
   Apart from some brief reunions, CSNY has remained apart, never
touring again until now.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a rare event, man, and you don't want to miss it,''
Crosby said.
</P>
<P>
   Having Young back on stage brings ``a completely different
energy,'' Crosby said. ``It's like sticking your finger in a wall
socket. Whooo!
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not that we weren't energetic without him. But Nash and
me by ourselves, Neil on his own, Stephen with his blues band _
those have a completely different chemistry.
</P>
<P>
   ``CSNY brings out stuff in all of us that only that combination
can bring out.''
</P>
<P>
   That's not to say CSNY doesn't still play acoustic songs, buoyed
by their trademark rich vocal harmonies, as well as some non-CSNY
material.
</P>
<P>
   ``On this tour, we go as far back as Buffalo Springfield,''
Crosby said, referring to Stills and Young's '60s band. ``We do
`For What It's Worth' and `Mr. Soul,' sometimes.''
</P>
<P>
   So far no Byrds songs have taken flight, ``but I'd love to try
`Eight Miles High' with these guys,'' Crosby said.
</P>
<P>
   There are no solo sets. ``About as far as it goes is Nash and I
do (CSN's) `Guinevere,' just the two of us,'' Crosby said. ``We'd
love to do more solo stuff, but then it'd be a four-hour show.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides, they also play new songs from CSNY's ``Looking
Forward'' album.
</P>
<P>
   ``We love playing new material,'' Crosby said. ``It's not that
we don't love playing the old stuff. We do. But the new stuff keeps
us alive and moving forward. We don't wanna be like a jukebox.''
</P>
<P>
   The band members compiled their joint and solo songs before the
tour, finding more than 900 between them. They whittled those down
to 50 or 60 for the road, spread over different nights.
</P>
<P>
   One omission fans have noted so far is the CSN hit ``Suite: Judy
Blue Eyes.'' But Crosby said the song will pop up on tour, ``I
guarantee it.''
</P>
<P>
   He doesn't see this as CSNY's last hurrah. He'd love it if the
group stuck together.
</P>
<P>
   ``In our 50s, all family guys, are we too old to rock 'n'
roll?'' Crosby asked. ``Look at Chuck Berry, who's about 10 years
older and can rock anybody off the stage. I don't know where you
can draw a line.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I figure is, I'll do it until it's not fun, and I'm
having a blast.''
</P>
<P>
   His personal life isn't bad, either. Within a short span in
1995, Crosby's wife, Jan, gave birth to a son, Django, and he met
James Raymond, a son whom he put up for adoption when he became a
father in his youth.
</P>
<P>
   The day after their meeting, Raymond's wife gave birth to
Crosby's first grandchild. That's not to mention the two children
born to Julie Cypher, partner of rocker Melissa Etheridge, with
friend Crosby as sperm donor.
</P>
<P>
   Fans had speculated the dad was Brad Pitt or other young stars
until Crosby's identity was revealed in January _ to the surprise
of many.
</P>
<P>
   ``I get some kidding about that still, but I think it's calming
down,'' he said. ``I see the kids pretty regularly. We're all
friends, and they're great kids.''
</P>
<P>
   As for whether his rock 'n' roll ``family'' will continue, he
won't predict. ``But my guess is there's a chance,'' Crosby said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now we're making some of the best music I've heard in my
life, and everybody seems to be having a blast. Things have
changed, and they haven't. It's still powerful: It's very good, and
I love it.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY XXXXX &QL; 
$$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
