<SLUG> BC-NEXT-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`THE NEXT BEST THING': OH, YOUR DADDY'S GAY, AND YOUR MAMA'S A
YOGI 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: Production notes at end of review) 
(jt) 
 By STEPHEN HOLDEN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Something happens to Madonna when she stops singing, dancing and
posing and is forced to play a screen character who speaks in
plain, everyday English. The extraordinary drive that made her a
world-famous entertainer becomes stifled, and the personality that
wafts off the screen is a curt, cool cookie who, even in misty-eyed
moments, conveys traces of a sour self-absorption.
</P>
<P>
   In ``The Next Best Thing'' Madonna is paired with her pal, the
English actor Rupert Everett, who exudes a different sort of chill.
(He often suggests a grown-up Little Lord Fauntleroy on the verge
of a tantrum, his curved lower lip dipping into a petulant scowl.)
But if the chemistry they stir up is closer to dry ice than fire,
it's genuine in its way. It is the shared knowledge of two
narcissists who have been around the block often enough to be able
to puncture each other's own romantic illusions without wincing.
And at his liveliest, Everett displays a flouncing comic flair that
brings out Madonna's playful side.
</P>
<P>
   In the movie, directed by John Schlesinger from a screenplay by
Thomas Ropelewski, Madonna and Everett portray less exalted
versions of themselves trading remarks that suggest a sharpened
variant of their desultory banter in a recent Vanity Fair cover
story.
</P>
<P>
   Madonna is Abbie Reynolds, a Los Angeles yoga teacher who has
been romantically burned too many times by men who have used those
dreaded words ``It's me, not you'' to wriggle out of relationships
that have lost their zing. Everett is Abbie's gay best friend,
Robert Whittaker, an aging Hollywood party boy and live-in gardener
at the estate of two wealthy older gays who spend afternoons
arguing about whether Ethel Merman or Betty Hutton was the
definitive Annie Oakley.
</P>
<P>
   In its early scenes ``The Next Best Thing'' shows promise as a
sophisticated screwball comedy about romantic love, parenthood and
sexual orientation in contemporary Los Angeles. But about halfway
through, the story takes a disastrous turn and heads away from
comedy into the land of suds and sorrow. Any psychological
credibility the movie has built up is quickly dissipated, as it
turns into a stumbling, poor man's ``Kramer vs. Kramer.''
</P>
<P>
   The movie is smartest when it is examining the stresses on a
complicated friendship that turns momentarily erotic with fateful
consequences. After the funeral of a mutual friend who died of
AIDS, Abbie and Robert get wildly drunk and have sex in a scene
that cleverly parodies a Fred Astaire-Ginger Rogers dance sequence.
Although they experience some morning-after tension, the incident
is quickly forgotten until Abbie discovers she is pregnant. Robert,
on receiving the news, almost faints on the spot but recovers his
equilibrium. And with great enthusiasm the two friends decide they
should live together and bring up the child.
</P>
<P>
   As Abbie and Robert go about telling their friends the news, the
movie becomes a shrewd comic barometer of social attitudes in
contemporary Hollywood. In the niftiest moment of farce, Robert
helps Abbie get revenge on Kevin (Michael Vartan), a boyfriend who
has just dumped her, by posing as his flamboyantly effeminate
lover, visiting the recording studio where Kevin works and
embarrassing him in front of his colleagues.
</P>
<P>
   But the movie takes the first of many wrong turns when it
abruptly cuts from Abbie's delivery of their son, Sam (Malcolm
Stumpf), to six years later, when Sam is an adorable boy who is
just beginning to ask his parents ticklish personal questions.
Until then, we are led to believe, everything has been just peachy,
with the three living in bugs-in-a-rug bliss. Sam is that ludicrous
Hollywood fantasy, a model child who never gets sick, never loses
his temper and loves everybody all the time.
</P>
<P>
   Trouble arrives in the form of Ben (Benjamin Bratt), a hunky New
York investment banker who strolls into Abbie's yoga studio one
day, takes a lesson and quickly falls in love with her. Robert
becomes increasingly miffed as Ben plays daddy to Sam during their
picture-postcard beach outings. And when Abbie and Ben announce
their plans to marry, the question of Sam's future becomes a
bitterly divisive issue.
</P>
<P>
   At this point the movie throws in a plot twist that makes the
question of custody 10 times knottier. It also suddenly changes our
perceptions of Abbie by demonizing a character the movie had
presented as a likable good sport. The movie's remaining shreds of
credibility are destroyed once Ben makes some inexplicable career
decisions. Only Hollywood could dream up an investment banker who
looks and sounds like a macho street fighter but speaks in the
warm, fuzzy vocabulary of a New Age guru. (He actually talks about
taking sick companies and making them well.)
</P>
<P>
   Although one can only surmise how the movie went wrong, ``The
Next Best Thing'' plays like a film whose creators feared at one
point that the story was too small and familiar, and frantically
cooked up some extra plot to add narrative juice. The moment the
movie loses its lighthearted spirit is the moment it loses touch
with reality.
</P>
<P>
   Rating: ``The Next Best Thing'' is rated PG-13 (Parents strongly
cautioned). It includes sexual situations, frank sexual dialogue
and partial nudity.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `THE NEXT BEST THING'
</P>
<P>
   Directed by John Schlesinger; written by Thomas Ropelewski;
director of photography, Elliot Davis; edited by Peter Honess;
music by Gabriel Yared; production designer, Howard Cummings;
produced by Tom Rosenberg, Leslie Dixon and Linne Radmin; released
by Paramount Pictures. Running time: 107 minutes. This film is
rated PG-13.
</P>
<P>
   Cast: Madonna (Abbie), Rupert Everett (Robert), Benjamin Bratt
(Ben), Illeana Douglas (Elizabeth Ryder), Michael Vartan (Kevin),
Josef Sommer (Richard Whittaker), Malcolm Stumpf (Sam), Lynn
Redgrave (Helen Whittaker) and Neil Patrick Harris (David).
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-02-00 1604EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
