<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-02 16:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4729 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u e BC-VIDEO-REVIEW-HNS &LR;      03-02 0899
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIDEO-REVIEW-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S TAYE DIGGS AT HIS `BEST' 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By BRUCE WESTBROOK 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   `THE BEST MAN'
</P>
<P>
   Think of this as a black ``The Big Chill,'' with former college
classmates reuniting years later, this time for a wedding in
Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   As is the case in ``Chill,'' contrivance dictates that almost
everybody has become wildly successful, from a TV director (Nia
Long) to a superstar jock who's getting wed (Morris Chestnut) to
Harper, an author who is the title character (Taye Diggs).
</P>
<P>
   Harper is basking in his first book deal for a novel that's a
thinly veiled account of their college days. Its release isn't due
until after the wedding, but advance copies fall into his friends'
hands.
</P>
<P>
   They quickly seize upon their surrogates in the book, with
messy, confrontational results _ especially when the groom realizes
his bride slept with his best man during school days.
</P>
<P>
   What ensues is a romantic comedy with unpleasant tangents, such
as the groom's fiercely violent temper tantrums, for which the film
has too much tolerance.
</P>
<P>
   Manhattan also is depicted as a strange other world. Instead of
the diverse city we know it to be, it's populated almost
unanimously by black men and women who have every speaking part in
the film, down to the tiniest bit player.
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Malcolm Lee (cousin of Spike Lee, who produced), the
cast is superb, especially Diggs, the charismatic lover of ``How
Stella Got Her Groove Back.''
</P>
<P>
   This is a much meatier part as he desperately tries to disarm
the emotional bombs of his book and as he's torn between his
longtime girlfriend and a seductive former classmate (Long).
</P>
<P>
   You might say that Harper is the one waiting to exhale _ at
least until he can get his friends hitched.
</P>
<P>
   Rating: 3 stars.
</P>
<P>
   1999, R, Universal, CC, VHS priced for rental, DVD $24.98 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   `AN EXTREMELY GOOFY MOVIE' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   This direct-to-video Disney effort is ambitious and surprisingly
good.
</P>
<P>
   Like most Disney movies made for video, it's a sequel to a
theatrical hit, in this case 1995's ``A Goofy Movie,'' which made
$35 million.
</P>
<P>
   Again, the creaky old character of Goofy is immersed in
relatively hip and contemporary sensibilities, thanks to his
teen-age son, Max.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Goofy is a constant embarrassment to Max. Yet he
prevails via good-hearted doggedness, despite being prone to
pratfalls (much like the late Jim Varney's Ernest character).
</P>
<P>
   Here, Max is off to college, and Goofy suffers from empty-nest
syndrome _ and losing his job. So he enrolls in Max's college
himself (an unforgivable intrusion, but without it there's no
movie).
</P>
<P>
   On campus, ``Extremely Goofy'' tries to have it both ways,
keeping Max very much a kid while advancing him toward adulthood.
</P>
<P>
   The chief kid-bent is making Max a champion skateboarder.
Defying an arrogant upperclassman, he competes in extreme sports at
this college, where students don't seem to have graduated to cars
yet.
</P>
<P>
   On the more savvy side, the film offers charming coffeehouse
scenes with a sassy Beat poetess (voiced by Vicki Lewis of
television's ``News Radio'').
</P>
<P>
   Having its hopelessly dated dad doesn't deter the film's lively
spirits. At college, Goofy sparks disco-era nostalgia as he
partners in dance with a librarian voiced by Bebe Neuwirth.
</P>
<P>
   Pauly Shore gives voice to Max's impish pal, while Jason Marsden
and Bill Farmer return as the voices of Max and Goofy,
respectively.
</P>
<P>
   The animation is fluid, and the backgrounds are handsomely
detailed. The song score also is strong, with Pat Benatar covering
Timbuk 3's ``The Future's So Bright, I Gotta Wear Shades''
andBritish trio Cleopatra giving a new spin to ``Right Back Where
We Started From.''
</P>
<P>
   The material also is on a soundtrack album called ``An Extremely
Goofy Movie Dance Party.''
</P>
<P>
   Rating: 3 stars.
</P>
<P>
   2000, G, Disney, CC, VHS $24.99, DVD $29.99 &UR;  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; `STIGMATA' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   This ``Exorcist'' wannabe bristles with visual dazzle but bogs
down in cliches and a murky narrative.
</P>
<P>
   Gabriel Byrne plays a troubled priest whose bosses at the
Vatican seem even more corrupt than those of ``Godfather III.''
</P>
<P>
   Byrne travels to the United States to investigate a stigmata
phenomenon, in which a young Pittsburgh hairdresser (Patricia
Arquette) suddenly and inexplicably suffers the same wounds Christ
had on the cross, with nail holes erupting on her wrists and lash
marks on her back.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the priest also should investigate why Pittsburgh
suffers from constant, drenching rains throughout the film.
</P>
<P>
   It's so rainy that you might also brand the film as a ``Blade
Runner'' wannabe.
</P>
<P>
   Or you might simply call it all wet.
</P>
<P>
   It's certainly violent, albeit in a highly stylized way that
substitutes bloody eye candy for true terror. In effect, this is an
overblown music video geared toward gore-heads.
</P>
<P>
   As such, it's quite mindless, making no attempt to justify its
bizarre metaphysics.
</P>
<P>
   Arquette's affliction _ somehow transmitted by a relic she
received in the mail _ owes less to stigmata than to the demonic
possession of ``The Exorcist,'' a truly horrific film that dared to
make sense.
</P>
<P>
   Rating: 1 1/2 star.
</P>
<P>
   1999, R, MGM, CC, VHS priced for rental, DVD $24.98 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
VIDEO RATINGS &QL; 
4 stars _ Excellent &QL; 
3 stars _ Good &QL; 
2 stars _ Fair &QL; 
1 star _ Poor &QL; 
 &QL; 
