<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-02 16:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4730 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u e BC-FILM-NEVE-CAMPBELL-HN     03-02 1172
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-NEVE-CAMPBELL-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
QUEEN OF `SCREAM' GETS SILLY 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By LOUIS B. PARKS 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ She may reign as the current Queen of ``Scream,'' but
Neve Campbell hopes her horror-movie fans will be laughing at her
soon.
</P>
<P>
   In the extremely silly ``Drowning Mona,'' whihc opens this
weekend, Campbell trades both her dramatic persona from Fox's
``Party of Five'' and her terrorized teen-turned-fem-avenger in the
hit ``Scream'' film series for something considerably lighter and
ditzier.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Drowning Mona,'' Campbell, 26, plays the
eager-to-be-married Ellen. Her fiance, Bobby (Casey Affleck), is
one of several suspects in the death of Mona, the town's crabbiest,
most unpopular resident (Bette Midler).
</P>
<P>
   It's a kooky role _ one Campbell loved playing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Absolutely!,'' she said, the first of many times she used that
word during the next half-hour. ``(It was) a lot of fun and really
light. I laughed a lot. It was fun to play someone really
ridiculous.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, Campbell's Ellen, while no rocket scientist, is among
the brighter residents of the small town of Verplanck, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mona'' co-stars Jamie Lee Curtis, as a waitress who wears
miniskirts with sneakers and smokes while serving food, and Danny
DeVito, the local sheriff who is also Ellen's dad. (The town's so
small, sleepy and second-rate that the sheriff's official car is a
battered subcompact.)
</P>
<P>
   However much fun she had goofing around on the set _ ``The film
is so absurd and ridiculous that you cannot take it seriously in
any way,'' she said _ Campbell admitted she had her doubts about
trying something so different from the roles that have turned her
from struggling Canadian actress into Hollywood star.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really scary straying from the things you know and people
like you doing,'' she said. But she insisted the work is more
important to her than fame.
</P>
<P>
   ``To be able to grow is important to me, above and beyond my
career.
</P>
<P>
   ``As an actor, you're always growing. When I'm 80 years old, if
I'm still acting or still alive, I'll still be learning and
growing. That's a process, and you have to keep that moving no
matter what people want to keep you as.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL; 
In person, Campbell looks younger than her age, but her attitude
and dress are mature and subdued. Her dark hair (with one slightly
auburn streak) is pulled back.
</P>
<P>
   A bulky grey turtleneck sweater and heavy wool skirt add some
softness, and a little diamond clip and antique earrings lend a
touch of class.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(END OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Despite her youth, Campbell is a seasoned veteran. ``Party of
Five'' is in its sixth (and rumored to be last) year. Campbell had
done several films before the original ``Scream'' in 1996 led to
fame. Since then, she has had the two hit Scream sequels and the
cult bad-girls film ``Wild Things.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been working professionally since I was 15, for 11
years,'' she said. Before that, she was a dancer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was a classical ballerina; that was my first career. That's
all I thought about and never thought about acting at all.''
</P>
<P>
   She trained at the National Ballet School in Toronto, where she
grew up. But she had a rough time. In recent years, she has blamed
her time there for the physical aches and pains she lives with,
including arthritis and hip problems. She finds acting ``much
easier.''
</P>
<P>
   ``With dance, you're in the classroom every day, and you're
constantly struggling and aware of the competition, where _ for me
at least _ as an actress, I'm not struggling to become better than
someone next to me. I'm struggling to become better than I was the
day before, which feels a lot better.''
</P>
<P>
   Campbell was surprised when she found out ``Scream 3'' and
``Drowning Mona'' would come out so close to one another, but she
figures it won't make much difference.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are very different kinds of characters in different kinds
of films for different audiences. So I think it's OK.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Fox has not said ``Party of Five'' will end after this
season, that's what Campbell expects. With Miramax announcing that
``Scream 3'' is the last of that series (we'll see), she would be
left without her two mainstays.
</P>
<P>
   No problem, she says.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know what, (the show's) been fantastic for me. ''Party of
Five's`` the reason I got into the States, and it's been my first
big thing here, and it's been a way for me to use my (acting)
muscles every day, which is great. ''Scream`` was fantastic and had
great success and really helped me career-wise.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I'm elated to kind of empty the cup, so I can fill it
again. The last six years have been insane. The most I've had off
is two weeks each year. Every time I have a hiatus, I did one or
two films. This time I was doing ''Scream 3,`` ''Drowning Mona``
and ''Party of Five`` at the same time. That was insane.''
</P>
<P>
   She already has her next film lined up, working for independent
film director Alan Rudolph (``Choose Me,'' ``Trouble in Mind'') on
a movie in Berlin called ``Investigating Sex.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's, like, a no-money, lots of fun, actor's piece, which I'm
really looking forward to. It's going to be really experimental and
creative.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have anything planned after that. If I want to take a
break, I'll do that.''
</P>
<P>
   When the conversation turns, or rather attempts to turn, to her
private life, Campbell handily deflects the thrust.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm trying to keep stuff like that out of the press. I'm just
at a place where that's (only) for me.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we first become famous we feel like we have to be
absolutely honest about everything. I'm not saying I'm being
dishonest right now, but we feel the need to give our hearts to
everybody, and say this is who I am. But you end up affecting your
loved ones, your family members. You have to learn not to do
that.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, Campbell married aspiring actor Jeff Colt, but the
couple divorced in 1998. And although she comes from Toronto, her
mother and older brother, Christian, also an actor (``Trick'') live
close by in Los Angeles. Her father and younger brothers still live
in Toronto.
</P>
<P>
   On the set of ``Drowning Mona,'' Campbell found herself paired
with Affleck, who has one of the leads in the movie although his
relative-newcomer status didn't warrant top billing. She did share
with him what she's learned about the business and fame.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't going to be condescending and say this is what you
do,'' Campbell said. ``I just talked to him about my own
experiences and how I've responded in different ways.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're kind of in different places because I've been doing
(''Party of Five``) so my face has been out there in public a
little bit more than Casey's.''
</P>
<P>
   So, does that mean she feels old and wise now? The silliness of
the question surprises and tickles her. She giggles as she answers.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know what, I felt old and wise five years ago, and I look
back, and I knew nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY XXXX &QL; 
$$$
</P>
</TEXT>
