<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-02 16:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4732 &Cx1f; tad-z
r s BC-GLF-GARYNICKLAUS-COX     03-02 1795
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-GARYNICKLAUS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Gary Nicklaus is a hunter, fisherman, outdoorsman, pet lover
and. . .he golfs too.
 &HT;    By Alan Tays
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Florida _ Showing off the grounds of the
Jupiter home he shares with his fiancee, Heather McDonough, Gary
Nicklaus points out the nesting boxes he made for wood ducks, a
once-threatened species, and marvels at the female wood duck's
penchant for flying almost full speed into the nesting box's entry
hole.
</P>
<P>
   Inside the house are the mounted heads of seven game animals
killed by Nicklaus. There are two whitetail deer, a mule deer, a
warthog, a kudu (a species of African antelope), an impala and a
sable antelope. Roaming the house are two more-fortunate animals:
Chili, the couple's 4-year-old female boxer, and Hugo, their
1-year-old Maine coon cat.
</P>
<P>
   In the driveway on a trailer is a 19-foot Action Craft flats
fishing boat. ``That was the present I bought for myself right
after I got this,'' Nicklaus says, pulling out a money clip that is
the first tangible evidence of what he does for a living.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, Gary Nicklaus _ hunter, fisherman, outdoorsman, fiance, pet
owner _ also plays golf.
</P>
<P>
   This year, at the age of 31, he finally has made it full time to
the stage his father, Jack, dominated for almost three decades. In
December, on his ninth attempt at making it through PGA Tour
qualifying school, he shot a 63 in the final round at Doral to earn
his Tour card.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is what it's all about,'' he says, holding out the money
clip that signifies PGA Tour membership.
</P>
<P>
   Two ``things'' come with being Gary Nicklaus: ``the Sports
Illustrated cover thing'' and ``the Jack's son thing.'' So let's
get them out of the way early.
</P>
<P>
   At the age of 16, Gary appeared on the cover of the March 11,
1985, Sports Illustrated dressed in tennis shorts and a golf shirt,
hitting practice balls. ``The Next Nicklaus,'' the headline read.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember the day it came out,'' said Toby Harbeck, Gary's
golf coach at The Benjamin School. ``We had it in the car and we
were driving to a match and he was looking at it and shaking his
head. I said, 'What are you shaking your head about?' He said,
'This is not the way it was supposed to be.' It was supposed to be
an article about the whole family. It ended up being all about him.
I know Jack wasn't very pleased with Sports Illustrated, because it
put a lot of pressure on Gary.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a great honor to be on the cover,'' Gary said last
month, ``but I had not any merit to be there. I mean, Tiger, he won
three U.S. Juniors, three U.S. Amateurs, and I don't know how old
he was the first time he got on the Sports Illustrated cover, but
he wasn't 16.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a lot of attention that I really didn't want. I was a
sophomore in high school; my wants and desires were not to be a
public figure at that age. It was more to go fishing and chase
girls and do whatever sophomores in high school do.''
</P>
<P>
   Gary's oldest sibling, brother Jackie, 38, the first ``Next
Nicklaus,'' thinks the SI cover ``turned his attention away from
golf. I think it kind of spooked him a little bit. He understood
that there was an expectation for Gary now, and he spent a lot of
time with his friends at college and enjoyed his college life at
Ohio State.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The SI cover thing,'' of course, was all about ``the Jack's
son thing.'' And Gary's take on that subject is ...
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been his son for 30 years and I've had a lot of attention
everywhere I've gone,'' Gary told reporters in December during his
father's annual ``State of the Bear'' address. ``If I have not
learned to deal with it, then I've got a serious problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``Definitely I want people to recognize me as Gary Nicklaus. But
if I go out and win the Grand Slam this year, I'm still Jack
Nicklaus' son.''
</P>
<P>
   But enough about Golden Bears. It's Gary we don't know jack
about. What kind of a guy is he?
</P>
<P>
   He's a tool guy _ ``pretty much a Home Depot and a Craftsman
guy.'' He's been that way since he was a kid. Both his mother,
Barbara, and sister, Nan O'Leary, say the young Gary was constantly
taking things apart, but not putting them back together.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like to fix things,'' Gary said. ``I've got my tool bench
out there (in the garage) with probably a pretty impressive
collection of tools for a person who isn't in the profession of
doing that.''
</P>
<P>
   You picture him dialing an 800 number after watching an
infomercial for the latest and greatest in screwdrivers or ratchet
sets.
</P>
<P>
   ``No,'' he said with a laugh, ``but I do fall prey sometimes to
other infomercials,'' pointing to a rotisserie cooker on the
counter. Gary, by the account of Heather, Nan and Barbara, is a
pretty fair cook, too.
</P>
<P>
   At Ohio State, where Gary followed his father, even pledging at
the same fraternity, Phi Gamma Delta, he met McDonough. She was a
freshman and he was an upperclassman. They met in a hospitality
tent at his father's Muirfield Village Golf Club. ``I asked her
out, we had a good time and then she dumped me,'' Gary said,
teasing Heather. Gary went on to marry his high school sweetheart,
Jill Moffitt, but their two careers (Jill is a dancer who toured
with Madonna and danced in the Broadway show Cats) proved
incompatible and they divorced.
</P>
<P>
   Gary and Heather, who grew up in Cincinnati, began dating again.
With Heather working in Miami, where she is director of special
events for the local chapter of the American Red Cross, their
careers don't get in each other's way.
</P>
<P>
   Gary also met Rob Sample at Ohio State. Sample, the Golden Bear
Golf vice president in charge of the Nicklaus-Flick Golf Schools,
roomed with Gary for a year. He remembers Gary as an excellent
student, a fan of Buckeyes football and Jimmy Buffett and a great
guy to have around when a party was being planned. ``He was always
there to help out,'' said Sample, who also calls Gary ``the best
friend anyone could have. If I needed him now, he'd drop everything
and be there.''
</P>
<P>
   That kind of support can be extended to strangers, too. After
winning The Office Depot Father-Son tournament in Naples, Gary and
two friends came upon a couple with a flat tire. They fixed the
flat, prompting the couple to write a thank-you letter that was
published in the Naples Daily News.
</P>
<P>
   The one question that keeps coming up about Gary's golf game is
this: Did it come too easily? Did he work hard enough at it? Did
tool benches or flats boats or wood ducks or Ohio State football
games get in the way too often? Are any of those things the reason
it took him nine trips to qualifying school before he graduated?
</P>
<P>
   ``You're looking at it as Gary (taking) nine years to qualify
for the PGA Tour,'' Jack Nicklaus said. ``I think Gary has tried to
qualify for the PGA Tour realistically (only) the last three years.
I don't think his golf game was capable of qualifying for the PGA
Tour until the last two or three years.''
</P>
<P>
   Jack thinks Gary made a breakthrough when he committed to
playing the European Tour in 1998 and the Nike Tour in 1999. ``That
elevated his ability to play golf,'' he said. ``You can't get
better unless you play.''
</P>
<P>
   Not playing well, however, almost led Gary to give up playing.
During one trip home from Europe after some bad performances, ``I
talked to my dad and said, 'I'm going to finish out the European
Tour, but after that, I don't think I'm going to play anymore. What
opportunities are there within Golden Bear and within our
organization?'''
</P>
<P>
   Gary's game improved when he returned to Europe, and he forgot
about quitting.
</P>
<P>
   Gary gives Jack credit for offering advice without being _ no
pun intended _ overbearing. ``As I've gotten older,'' Gary said,
``he has tended to let me do things my own way. He's still my dad,
and he still likes to make sure he's there for me. If there are
things he thinks I might want his advice on, he'll let me know.''
</P>
<P>
   It's Jack, Gary says, who subscribes to Mark Twain's
observation: ``When I was a boy of 14, my father was so ignorant I
could hardly stand to have the old man around. But when I got to be
21, I was astonished at how much the old man had learned in seven
years.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He used to always say that about how smart his father got when
he got older,'' Gary said of Jack and Jack's father, Charlie
Nicklaus. ``I've always thought (Jack) was pretty smart.''
</P>
<P>
   Gary pinpoints his breakthrough as the final round of Q-school
in December at Doral. He was on the bubble, not a sure thing to
make it without a spectacular final round.
</P>
<P>
   ``I played solid all week,'' he said, ``but when I got to the
final round it was like, all right, this is why I've spent the last
2 1/2 years on the European and Nike tours. It was weird, because
all of a sudden I had this sense that I belonged here.''
</P>
<P>
   On the first hole, he hit ``a perfect tee shot, a perfect second
shot to about 4feet and made the putt for birdie. ``There was
absolutely zero nerves the entire day.''
</P>
<P>
   Gary says there are a couple of things he might do differently
over the past nine years. ``If I had separated my play time from my
work time and managed my time a little better, I probably would
have been out there (on Tour) a little earlier,'' he said. ``If you
have time to do something, then fine, but don't take time away from
your practice to do the fun things. Wait until you get home. Play
hard when you get home, but work hard when you're on Tour.''
</P>
<P>
   Harbeck sees Gary as a take-charge guy, a quality he displayed
right from the beginning of their relationship, when Benjamin
needed a golf coach. ``He said to me after his first year, 'Why
don't you coach golf?''' Harbeck said. ``I said, 'I don't know
anything about golf.' he said, 'I'll teach you everything you need
to know.'''
</P>
<P>
   Gary has made the cuts in half of the six events he has played
this year. ``I've just got to start putting better,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever happens, Gary always will have the satisfaction of
knowing he made it to this level on his own. ``He showed a lot of
guts to me in the second qualifier when he shot 68 the last round
when he was on the bubble and when he shot 63 in the last round of
the final qualifier,'' Jack said. ``It's not something his dad can
do. He's got to do that for himself.''
</P>
<P>
   A few years after the Sports Illustrated story, Harbeck read a
letter in the magazine referring to fathers and sons who had been
on SI covers. Gary and Jack weren't mentioned, and Harbeck wanted
to correct the error. But he also added another thought. ``I also
said you'd hear the Nicklaus name again,'' he said, ``and it
wouldn't be Jack.''
</P>
<P>
   Al Tays writes fro the Palm Beach Post. He can be reached at
altays(at)pbpost.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
