<HEADER>
A4740 &Cx1f; tad-z
r t BC-FESTIVALS05-COX     03-02 0766
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FESTIVALS05-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    10 great warm-weather Southern festivals
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, March 5.
 &HT;    By Paula Crouch Thrasher
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QR;  53rd Annual Festival of Houses and Gardens. Charleston, S.C.,
March 16-April 15. This monthlong series of self-guided afternoon
and evening candlelight tours features about 150 private homes in
11 historic neighborhoods and gardens abloom with spring flowers.
The event is complemented by Lowcountry Plantation Oyster Roasts at
Drayton Hall on March 27, April 4 and 12. 843-722-3405.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  18th Annual International Cherry Blossom Festival. Macon,
March 17-27. A concert by the Beach Boys, a hot-air balloon fest
and a Matsuriza Japanese drum performance highlight the 500 events
that celebrate the blossoming of nearly a quarter-million Yoshino
cherry trees. Also popular are tours, concerts, theatrical
performances, parades, art and a carnival. 912-751-7429,
www.cherryblossom.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Biltmore Estate Festival of Flowers. Asheville, N.C., April
1-30. Signs of spring burst forth at George Vanderbilt's grand
French chateau-style estate in the Blue Ridge Mountains during this
annual event. Elaborate Victorian floral arrangements fill the
house, and garden paths are alive with color. Live music on
weekends completes the celebration at the historic Biltmore Estate.
1-800-289-2961.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  31st Annual New Orleans Jazz and Heritage Festival. New
Orleans, April 28-May 7. The good times roll as this festival
showcases the culture of Louisiana with an open-air Heritage Fair
featuring 12 stages of music, Cajun and creole food (along with
international fare) and traditional and contemporary crafts. Expect
lots of jazz, gospel, Cajun and zydeco and headlining performances
by Dr. John, the Allman Brothers Band, Allen Toussaint, Erykah
Badu, Sting, the Wailers, Buckwheat Zydeco, Bela Fleck, Irma
Thomas, Lenny Kravitz, Jimmy Cliff, the Neville Brothers, the
Temptations, Ani DiFranco and King Sunny Ade &AMP; His African Beats _
to name just a few. Also, evening concerts and educational
workshops. 504-522-4786.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Memphis in May International Festival. Memphis, May 1-31.
India is in the spotlight for this year's festival. All of May
becomes a party on the Mississippi during this annual spring fling.
Also part of the event are the Beale Street Music Festival,
International Week, World Championship Barbecue Cooking Contest and
Sunset Symphony. 901-525-4611.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Prater's Mill Country Fair. Dalton, May 13-14. A barn-red
1850s gristmill on the banks of Coahulla Creek is the centerpiece
of this festival that features 200 arts and crafts exhibitors,
traditional music, country cooking, heritage exhibits and
children's activities. The mill operates during the festival, and
you can take home a bag of freshly ground cornmeal. 706-275-6455.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The 24th Annual Spoleto Festival USA. Charleston, S.C., May
26-June 11. The 17-day festival includes 126 events in opera,
music, theater and dance. Says general director Nigel Redden:
``This year's Spoleto Festival is a journey that spans centuries,
from the 18th century with Gluck's gripping masterpiece, `Iphigenie
en Tauride,' to the present with the premiere of a new version of
Bright Sheng and David Henry Hwang's `The Silver River'; from
Verdi's investigation of love, honor and duy in `Luisa Miller' to
Brecht's biting comedy `Mother Courage and Her Children.'''
843-722-2764 or www.spoletousa.org.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Riverbend Festival. Chattanooga, June 9-17. The revitalized
downtown on the banks of the Tennessee River rocks for nine days
with 100 musical artists on five stages, sporting events, family
activities, fine arts, food and fireworks. 423-265-4112 or
www.chattanooga.net/cvb.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  51st Annual Fiesta of Five Flags. Pensacola, June 7-17.
Florida's largest and oldest festival honors Spanish conquistador
Don Tristan de Luna, who founded Pensacola in 1559. Since then,
five flags have flown over the city _ Spanish, French, British,
Confederate and American. Events include a concert in Seville
Square, parades, de Luna landing re-enactment, sand sculpture
contest and the Fiesta Krewe Ball. 1-800-874-1234.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  City Stages. Birmingham, June 16-18. The acts for this year's
outdoor music festival have not been announced, but you can count
on lots of great entertainment on 16 stages or performance areas in
Linn Park and surrounding streets downtown. 205-251-1272 or
www.citystages.org.
</P>
<P>
   Paula Crouch Thrasher writes for the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
