<DOCNO> NYT20000302.0189 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-02 16:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4743 &Cx1f; tad-z
r t BC-SOUTHEAST-INNS05-COX     03-02 1982
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOUTHEAST-INNS05-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Southern inns to build a dream on
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, March 05.
 &HT;    By Paula Crouch Thrasher
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   A really great inn is more than somewhere to spend the night. It
is a warm place where you are pampered and fussed over _ in short,
made to feel like a welcome guest. The inn might be country cozy or
elegantly upscale. Here are some old favorites and new discoveries
from recent travels _ and a few we're dreaming of visiting.
</P>
<P>
   FIVE OLD FAVORITES
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Gastonian, Savannah, Ga. The elegant 17-room inn on East
Gaston Street, two blocks from Forsyth Park, is two 1868 Regency
Italianate mansions connected by a green and tranquil courtyard.
Sumptuously decorated and filled with fine English antiques and a
Waterford chandelier in the dining room, the home is a showplace of
elegance and good taste. Speaking of good taste, breakfasts are
gourmet Southern repasts, afternoon tea is served with
complimentary wines, and cordials await in the parlor at night.
Innkeeper Anne Landers, a former Atlantan who bought the inn in
1996, presides with meticulous attention to details. Rooms, all
with working fireplaces, are appointed with Oriental carpets and
antiques (some are upper-crust English in character, while others
are pure Americana), and most feature Jacuzzis. Turndown service
includes pecan pralines and white linen floor mats beside the bed.
$295-$350. Information: 1-800-322-6603 or www.gastonian.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Balsam Mountain Inn, Balsam, N.C. The best feature of this
comfortable 50-room inn, opened in 1908, may be the two-level
veranda on which one can rock and relax, gazing at surrounding
mountains. In 1990, innkeeper Merrily Teasley began restoration of
the neoclassical Victorian structure perched on a hilltop. Inside
are restored hardwood floors, bead board walls, antique wicker and
Victorian trim. A double-sided fireplace in the spacious lobby
keeps the place cozy in winter. Rooms feature bentwood or painted
iron beds piled with down comforters (but no TVs or phones). Some
baths have antique claw-foot tubs. A full breakfast is included;
lunch and dinner are available. $90-$150.
</P>
<P>
   1-800-224-9498 or www1.aksi.net/(tilde)cmark/balsam.htm.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Kendall Manor Inn, Eufaula, Ala. This elegant
bed-and-breakfast _ lovingly restored by Barbara Lubsen and her
husband, Tim _ is one of the crown jewels in a town that boasts
more than 700 architecturally significant structures dating to
1836. The National Register home two blocks from downtown is a
favorite stop on the annual Eufaula Pilgrimage (coming up April
7-9). Staying at Kendall Manor Inn is like stepping back a century
_ but with queen and king beds, telephones with dataports, heat and
air conditioning, indoor plumbing and a television (if you want one
brought to your room). Built by cotton magnate James Turner
Kendall, the home was completed in 1872. Architectural highlights
include the ruby-red Czechoslovakian glass sidelights for the
massive front door, Italian marble mantels and French gold-leaf
cornices and mirror frame in the front parlor. A carved walnut
staircase leads to the second floor. Topping it all is an
arch-windowed belvedere that provides vistas for miles. $99-$129.
334-687-8847.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Inn at Merridun, Union, S.C. Affable innkeepers Peggy and Jim
Waller and their yellow tabby, J.D., personify Southern
hospitality. Their 1855 Greek Revival inn _ a National Register of
Historic Places property with stately Corinthian columns _ is
secluded on nine woodsy acres off a busy highway. The Wallers are
gourmet cooks whose talents are apparent at the bounteous
breakfasts, highlighted by blueberry pancakes for ``dessert,'' and
elegant candlelight dinners at additional cost for overnight guests
by reservation only. Each of the five distinctively decorated
bedrooms has a private bath, including Lucy's Garden Retreat with a
Jacuzzi tub. $79-$119. 864-427-7052.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Casablanca Inn, St. Augustine, Fla. Listed on the National
Register of Historic Places, this 1914 Mediterranean Revival home
in the oldest American city's historic district offers panoramic
views of Matanzas Bay and traffic _ some of the horse-and-carriage
variety _ along Avenue Menendez. Guests take breakfast on the
porches that catch the breeze from the bay. Rooms are decorated
with antiques and some have Jacuzzis _ but no TVs or phones.
Bicycles are available at no cost to guests. Special touches
include a never-empty plate of homemade cookies and a help-yourself
fridge stocked with soft drinks and beer. Read about the resident
ghost on the Web site, www.casablancainn.com. The inn is within
walking distance of St. Augustine's historic attractions and
restaurants. $89-$199. 1-800-826-2626.
</P>
<P>
   FOUR RECENT FINDS
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Cypress Inn, Conway, S.C. The 12-room Cypress Inn on Elm
Street is the only B&AMP;B in the historic district, and its location
overlooking the Waccamaw is ideal: The Riverfront Tennis Center is
across the street, and next door is Conway Marina, where you can
rent canoes and paddleboats. Although modern, the three-story inn
evokes the 19th century. The rooms, decorated with antique
furnishings and designer fabrics and wall coverings, feature
Jacuzzi tubs. The front porch, lined with rockers, overlooks a
small private marina. Pitchers of lemonade and iced tea await
guests. $95-$140. 1-800-575-5307
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Pensacola Victorian, Pensacola, Fla. This restored Queen Anne
Victorian _ with hardwood floors and paneling and sparkling
chandeliers _ was once the dream home of ship captain William
Hazard Northup. Each of the four bedrooms has a different
decorating scheme. The location is within walking distance of the
Seville Historic District, with its living history village, and
downtown, which has been revived with trendy boutiques, art
galleries and restaurants on Palafox Street, the main north-south
corridor, and surrounding streets. Innkeeper Barbee Major's hearty
breakfasts include egg-based casseroles, waffles and a wonderful
broccoli and chicken quiche. Rates $65-$100 through March 31;
$75-$120 April 1-Nov. 1. 1-800-370-8354 or
www.pensacolavictorian.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Applegate Bed and Breakfast, Dillsboro, N.C. Your hosts Andree
and John Faulk will make you feel like a favorite cousin come for a
long overdue visit. A footbridge over Scott's Creek links inn
guests with 30 or so shops in the village and excursions on the
Great Smoky Mountains Railroad. Sumptuous breakfasts are served on
an enclosed patio. After breakfast, John cranks up his restored
1949 John Deere tractor to take guests on a hayride. Eight smartly
decorated rooms and suites. And a sweet mutt named Punky. $70-$90.
828-586-2397.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Red Rocker Inn, Black Mountain, N.C. Yes, there really is a
red rocker. Actually, there are several, along with swings and
gliders. This 17-room country inn run by the Lindberg family _
Margie and Carl and sons Derrick and Brian _ is known not only for
its just-like-Grandma's comforts but for its family-style dining.
Folks gather for home cooking by Derrick Lindberg and sinful
desserts by his wife, Elizabeth. One evening, entree choices
included pork tenderloin, pot roast, chicken with asparagus and
hollan-
</P>
<P>
   daise and fried trout. Before dinner Derrick welcomed us all,
described the evening's repast and said a blessing. The feast is
$16.95 (dessert extra), by reservation only. Rooms are $85-$145.
1-888-669-5991 or www.redrockerinn.com.
</P>
<P>
   FIVE WE'RE
</P>
<P>
   DREAMING OF
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Gideon Ridge Inn, Blowing Rock, N.C. The village _ perched at
3,990 feet _ is a charmer, with attractive shops, antique galleries
and inviting restaurants. Set on five wooded acres with seasonal
gardens, the inn features stone terraces with old wicker, a library
with massive stone fireplace and a breakfast room with original
art. Breakfast might be cornmeal pancakes, Smithfield ham sausage,
sauteed apples and Vermont maple syrup. For afternoon tea, there
are freshly made sandwiches, scones, shortbread and such, plus Earl
Grey tea. $115-$260. 828-295-3644 or www.ridge-inn.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Woodlands Resort and Inn, Summerville, S.C. At this elegant
resort on 42 private, wooded acres, ``quintessential Southern
hospitality'' (as the brochure boasts) comes at a price. Rooms cost
$295-$350 a night. Guests are treated to a pampering atmosphere,
gorgeously decorated rooms (plush robes and fresh flowers await), a
highly rated restaurant featuring the creations of chef Ken
Vedrinski, a full-service spa, swimming pool, tennis courts and
bicycle and jogging trails. It's the only AAA five-diamond hotel
and restaurant in the state. 1-800-774-9999 or
www.woodlandsinn.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  John Rutledge House Inn, Charleston, S.C. A member of Historic
Inns of America, this National Historic Landmark was built in 1763
by Rutledge, a signer of the Declaration of Independence. It bears
the Mobil four-star pedigree for its posh accommodations and
service, including afternoon wine and sherry, nightly turndown
service with chocolates, and breakfast of freshly baked pastries
served in your room. The three-story structure features intricate
ironwork and an elaborate interior with carved Italian marble
fireplaces and inlaid floors. There are 15 rooms and four suites in
the main house and two carriage houses. $185-$365. 843-723-7999;
www.charminginns.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Fearrington House Restaurant and County Inn, Pittsboro, N.C.
Winner of five AAA diamonds for both lodging and dining, the
restaurant and country inn anchors a bustling village center of
shops and services. Black-and-white Galloway cows graze in the
pastures. Each room is decorated with antiques, original art and
luxurious fabrics; marble vanities, heated towel racks and
individual sound systems cater to personal comfort. Several rooms
offer fireplaces and Jacuzzi tubs. Distinctive touches include
ecclesiastical doors used as headboards, canopied beds and pine
flooring from a workhouse along the Thames. $175-$350 (includes
afternoon tea and gourmet breakfast). 919-542-2121 or
www.fearrington.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Christopher Place, Newport, Tenn. The 14,000-square-foot
Colonial-style mansion on 200 acres at the edge of Great Smoky
Mountains National Park was built in 1976 as a private residence
and converted to an inn in 1994. Vacations magazine recently named
it one of the country's 10 most romantic inns. On the grounds are a
heated pool, tennis courts, fitness center and hiking trail.
Inside, there's a library, parlor with grand piano and a billiards
room. Eight spacious rooms; $150 to $300.
</P>
<P>
   1-800-595-9441 or www.christopherplace.com.
</P>
<P>
   READER'S CHOICE: LODGE ON GORHAM'S BLUFF
</P>
<P>
   Sally Stewart Mohney of Vinings recommends the Lodge on Gorham's
Bluff in northeast Alabama. The inn has six double rooms with
private baths and fireplaces. $120-$175 a night includes full
breakfast and snacks. Evening meals extra; dinner is served nightly
and is open to the public. Reservations required. 256-451-3435 or
www.gorhamsbluff.com.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Lodge features porches and balconies that overlook the
Tennessee River and a magnificent mountain backdrop,'' Mohney says.
``The innkeepers, the McGriff family, think of everything in terms
of simple comfort. From the bed linens to triple-milled soaps to
the assortment of reading materials, everything in our cozy but
spacious room was choice. In one of the three downstairs sitting
areas (full of plump, comfortable chairs and sofas) were tidy
shelves of select books as well as an extensive video library. And
the food! Tender filet mignon with garlic mashed potatoes for
dinner; fluffy eggs, homemade biscuits and warm bread pudding
drizzled with peach compote for breakfast. Gorham's Bluff offers
the ultimate cocooning weekend.''
</P>
<P>
   Paula Crouch Thrasher writes for the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
