<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-02 16:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4745 &Cx1f; tad-z
r t BC-BIGEVENTS05-COX     03-02 2041
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIGEVENTS05-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Much to see, do in South in 2000
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, March 5.
 &HT;    By Paula Crouch Thrasher
 &HT;    and Howard Pousner
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALABAMA
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Birmingham: The 50th Birmingham International Festival, a
series of exhibits and events at venues around the city, is
highlighted by the Salute to Native Americans Street Festival in
Linn Park downtown April 14-16. Native American performers will
share their culture through storytelling, music, dance, sports,
arts demonstrations and children's activities. Rita Coolidge, who
is of Cherokee descent, is the headliner for the April 15 evening
concert. 205-252-7652; www.bifsalutes.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Boaz: The Boaz to Montgomery 20th Annual Alabama Wagon Train
leaves Sand Mountain Saddle Club in Boaz on Wednesday and ends its
trek March 15 at Garret Coliseum in Montgomery, site of the 43rd
Southeastern Livestock Exposition. A national event with
participants from 40 states, the Alabama Wagon Train is one of
America's largest. The train goes through five counties and covers
165 miles. 256-593-9488.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Gadsden: ``Jerusalem's Gate,'' a Passion play written for
Gadsden's millennium celebration, will be performed at Mort Glosser
Amphitheatre, April 17-18 and April 20-22. 256-442-2003.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Huntsville: Panoply, Huntsville's festival of the arts, will
be held in Big Spring International Park downtown April 28-30. This
year's event is part of the yearlong ``Celebration of the Arts &AMP;
Sciences,'' in recognition of rocket scientist Werner Von Braun.
The annual event features a visual arts show, a choreography
competition and a variety of performances. 256-519-2787.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Montgomery: The Alabama State Capitol is the site of
``Alabama, My Home: A Celebration of Rural Schools and
Communities.'' The April 28-29 event celebrates the nationally
recognized educational innovations of 25 rural Alabama communities.
Exhibitions and demonstrations of student work by Alabama's
emerging filmmakers, lyricists, authors, playwrights, photographers
and journalists. Hear blues, gospel choirs and old-time fiddlers on
two outdoor stages, listen to storytellers from across the state,
and sample fried fish or barbecue. 205-348-6432.
</P>
<P>
   GEORGIA
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Augusta: The Phinizy Swamp Nature Park opens April 22 on 1,100
acres of swampland seven minutes outside the city. The park offers
nature lovers a chance to see bald eagles, blue herons,
red-shouldered hawks, otters, alligators and bobcats in natural
habitats. Boardwalks and trails lead past bald cypress groves,
natural wetlands, streams, river scars and an oxbow lake.
706-828-2109.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Dawsonville: Thunder Road U.S.A., a $15 million motor sports
attraction, is opening in the fall in the hometown of NASCAR great
Bill Elliott. The facility will be the official Georgia Racing Hall
of Fame and will celebrate 50 years of motor sports and automotive
history in the state. The initial phase is 40,000 square feet. A
10,000-square-foot exhibit area and banquet hall is planned.
706-216-7223; www.thunderroadusa.com.
</P>
<P>
   KENTUCKY
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Louisville: ``Imperial China: The Art of the Horse in Chinese
History'' will be on display May 1-Aug. 31 at the Kentucky Horse
Park. This is the first exhibition to explore the role of the horse
in more than 3,000 years of Chinese history and culture. With 300
artifacts on view, the exhibit illuminates the horse's significance
in art, warfare, leisure activities and sport. 1-800-568-8813, Ext.
231; www.imh.org
</P>
<P>
   /imh/china/.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Louisville: Opening night at Louisville Slugger Field is April
12. The $26 million facility will be home to the Louisville
RiverBats, the Cincinnati Reds' AAA team. 502-367-9121;
www.batsbaseball.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Louisville: The 126th Kentucky Derby runs May 6, culminating
the monthlong Kentucky Derby Festival. Churchill Downs will unveil
a dramatic entrance, and Derby-goers can learn more about ``the
greatest two minutes of sports'' at the newly renovated Kentucky
Derby Museum. Information: 502-636-4400 (Derby); 502-637-7097
(museum); 502-584-6383 (festival).
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Paducah: The American Quilters Society National Quilt Show is
April 13-16. More than $100,000 in cash prizes will be awarded.
270-442-8856; www.aqsquilt.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Pikeville: After more than a century of peace, descendants of
the Hatfields of West Virginia and the McCoys of Kentucky will face
off once again _ this time on a softball field June 10. The game is
part of the first national reunion of the famous feudin' families.
The families will have separate private dinners June 9, then the
public is invited to join the clans downtown June 10 for food, arts
and crafts, music, games and children's activities. Special
exhibits, walking tours and bus tours to feud sites will be
available. The reunion weekend concludes June 11, with a
reconciliation prayer breakfast and memorial service at the
Buskirk-Matewan Bridge. 1-800-844-7453. www.real-mccoys.com.
</P>
<P>
   SOUTH CAROLINA
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Charleston: The South Carolina Aquarium, opening May 19, will
host 62 exhibits housing 10,000 animals and 5,000 plants indigenous
to South Carolina. The $69 million aquarium, located on the edge of
the Charleston harbor near downtown, will display and interpret the
state's diverse aquatic habitats, from rushing mountain streams
through rivers, lakes and salt marshes out to the depths of the
Atlantic Ocean. 843-720-1990; www.scaquarium.org.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Myrtle Beach: The almost 20,000-square-foot Butterfly Pavilion
will open in June at Broadway at the Beach. The focus of the
attraction will be an 8,640-square-foot aviary featuring thousands
of North American butterflies representing 60-70 species.
843-679-0999.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Myrtle Beach: The Myrtle Beach Pavilion Amusement Park is
adding a 3,800-foot roller coaster, the Hurricane, expected to open
in April. 843-
</P>
<P>
   913-5200.
</P>
<P>
   NORTH CAROLINA
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Raleigh: The North Carolina Museum of Arts and Sciences _
opening April 7 with a two-story waterfall and four floors of
exhibits, live animals and hands-on programs _ will be home to a
112 million-year-old meat-eating Acrocanthosaurus, better known as
the ``Terror of the South.''
</P>
<P>
   1-877-462-8724.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Raleigh: The centerpiece of Festival Rodin, April 16-Aug. 13,
is an exhibition of more then 130 well-known works by Rodin at the
North Carolina Museum of Art. The exhibition includes sculptures
such as ``The Thinker'' and ``The Kiss'' and works ranging from
intimate studies to monumental creations. The festival includes
Broadway shows, intimate theater, concerts, dance performances plus
special programs at area museums. 1-877-627-6346 or
www.festivalrodin.com.
</P>
<P>
   TENNESSEE
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Nashville: Opry Mills, the 1.2 million-square-foot shopping
and entertainment complex built on the site of the Opryland USA
amusement park, will open May 11. 615-884-7310; www.oprymills.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Memphis: The Memphis Rock 'n' Soul Museum opens April 29 a
half block south of Beale Street. The inaugural exhibit is the
Smithsonian Institution's ``Rock 'n' Soul: Social Crossroads,''
which examines the history of Memphis' music and its impact on
cultural change. The exhibition is on long-term loan.
1-800-263-6744; www.memphisrocknsoul.org.
</P>
<P>
   The museum is inside the new Gibson Guitar Factory, which is
scheduled to open in early May. The two attractions, while housed
in the same facility, are separate. For information about Gibson
plant tours, call 1-800-444-2766.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Pigeon Forge: Dollywood will open its $3 million Dreamland
Forest, featuring a 15,000-square-foot treehouse _ America's
largest _ on April 15 in celebration of the park's 15th year.
865-428-9400; www.dollywood.com.
</P>
<P>
   VIRGINIA
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Hampton Roads: OpSail 2000, the largest tall ship and maritime
event in history, is June 16-20. A flotilla of 150 tall ships,
character vessels and military craft from nearly 20 countries will
be making its way up the east coast from Puerto Rico to New York
Harbor for the country's 224th birthday celebration. The visit will
be celebrated with waterfront festivals, attractions and special
events throughout the area. A highlight will be the 12-mile parade
of sail on June 16 from Virginia Beach to Norfolk, Portsmouth and
Chesapeake. 757-441-2940.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Natural Bridge: Members of the Monacan Indian Nation have
begun constructing an authentic 18th-century Monacan Indian village
to be completed in 2002. Meanwhile, beginning April 1, an
interpretive history center will be in place to complement the
ongoing village construction. 1-800-533-1410.
</P>
<P>
   FLORIDA
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Orlando: Discovery Cove, opening July 1, is a
reservations-only experience where people can swim with dolphins
and stingrays, feed exotic birds and snorkel among thousands of
tropical fish. 1-877-434-7268; www
</P>
<P>
   .discoverycove.com. Meanwhile, on June 1, Kraken, a
``floorless'' roller coaster, will open at SeaWorld Adventure Park.
1-800-423-8368; www
</P>
<P>
   .seaworld.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Orlando: ``Men in Black Alien Attack'' opens April 1 at
Universal Studios Escape. The interactive theme park ride is billed
as the world's first life-size ride through a video game. Will
Smith will re-team with Rip Torn as they reprise their roles as
Agent Jay and MIB Director Zed, leading hardy bands of
guest-trainees as they take up arms to save the Earth from
intergalactic terrorists. 1-800-447-0679; www.uescape.com or www
</P>
<P>
   .universalstudios.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Orlando: Gatorland, the Alligator Capital of the World, has
just opened ``50 Years of Great Tales,'' an exhibit featuring
crocodilian snapshots and memorabilia from a half century of
visitors. 1-800-393-5297.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Lake Worth: The Palm Beach Institute of Contemporary Art
opened Saturday in a landmark 1939 art deco movie house. The
inaugural exhibition, ``Making Time: Considering Time as a Material
in Contemporary Video &AMP; Film,'' features cutting-edge examples of
video art by emerging artists as well as works by Andy Warhol, Nam
June Paik and Bruce Nauman. 561-582-0006; www.palmbeachica.org.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  St. Cloud: Forever Florida opens its 5,000-square-foot visitor
center with a restaurant, nature-based gift shop and audiovisual
room on April 22. The 4,500-acre wildlife preserve features
self-guided horseback rides, bicycle trails and coach tours of wet
and dry savannas, flatwoods, creeks and hammocks. 1-888-957-9794;
www
</P>
<P>
   .foreverflorida.com.
</P>
<P>
   MISSISSIPPI
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Jackson: The new Museum of Natural Science, located on 300
acres adjacent to the Pearl River in LeFleur's Bluff State Park,
opened Friday. Natural objects and live animals tell the story of
``Mississippi's Web of Life'' through educational exhibits. The
73,000-square-foot facility includes an aquarium system with nearly
100,000 gallons of water and more than 200 species of native fish,
reptiles, amphibians and aquatic invertebrates. A 1,700-square-foot
greenhouse terrarium with a 20,000-gallon aquarium is home to fish,
turtles, alligators and native plants. More than 2 1/2 miles of
nature trails wind through the woods where more than 3,000 native
trees, shrubs and vines have been planted. 601-354-7303.
</P>
<P>
   LOUISIANA
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  New Orleans: The National D-Day Museum will open June 6, the
56th anniversary of the Normandy invasion. Located in the Warehouse
Arts District, the 70,500-square-foot museum will be the first of
its kind to tell the story of the U.S. amphibious operations around
the globe in World War II. The heart of the museum will be the
D-Day collection purchased from the St.-Lo La Musee de la
Liberation in Normandy, including German vehicles, sentry boxes and
weapons. The museum includes four state-of-the-art interactive
historical and educational exhibits. 504-527-6012.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  New Orleans: Jazzland Theme Park is set to open in May with
six themed sections, including Mardi Gras, Pontchartrain Beach,
Cajun Country, Jazz Plaza, Kids' Carnival and Gospel Gardens. The
140-acre park, located 20 minutes from downtown at I-10 and I-510,
will feature roller coasters, theme rides, music, shows and lots of
food. 504-242-0220; www.jazzland2000.com
</P>
<P>
   Paula Crouch Thrasher and Howard Pousner write for the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
