<DOCNO> NYT20000302.0192 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-02 16:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4748 &Cx1f; tad-z
r t BC-FAMILY-DESTINATIONS05     03-02 1348
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FAMILY-DESTINATIONS05-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Southeastern destinations sure to promote family fun
 &HT;    Eds:Embargoed for Sunday, March 5.
 &HT;    By Paula Crouch Thrasher
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DESTIN, FLA. _ ``The world's luckiest fishing village'' reels in
not only anglers but families who bask in the sun on sugar-white
beaches, splash in the Gulf of Mexico's clear emerald waters and
queue up to feast at tried-and-true seafood haunts such as Harbor
Docks. Families flock to attractions such as the Track Recreation
Center with go-carts, bumper boats, bumper cars and minigolf;
Rollin' Wheels Skate Center; and the ever-funky Big Kahuna's, an
entertainment complex that includes a water park, a 54-hole
minicourse with jungle theme, Little Kahuna's Kiddieland, go-carts
and Grand Prix track. When you've tired of the beach, you can spend
hours at Morgan's Family Entertainment Center at the Silver Sands
Factory Stores. Morgan's is a two-story complex with dining on the
lower level (wood-fired pizzas, rotisserie chicken and baked goods)
and a fantasy playland with a Jules Verne theme just up the
escalator. Plus, the family will enjoy sailboat cruises,
glass-bottom boat excursions and deep-sea fishing. Information:
Emerald Coast Convention and Visitors Bureau at 1-800-322-3319 or
www.destin-fwb.com.
</P>
<P>
   HILTON HEAD
</P>
<P>
   ISLAND, S.C.
</P>
<P>
   From ankle to toe, this foot-shaped island is packed with fun
things to draw families. For starters, 12 miles of beaches are the
main draw. Several stables offer guided tours, and some have
special kids' packages and pony rides. Plus, there are ample
opportunities for golf, tennis and water sports. Families also
enjoy the popular dolphin cruises offered by several tour
operators. A good starting point is the Hilton Head Island Chamber
of Commerce Welcome Center on U.S. 278, on the way into town.
Accommodations run the gamut from motel rooms under $100 a night to
weeklong stays in beachside condos for $1,000 and up. For hungry
kids, you can't beat Crazy Crab in Harbour Town and Crabby Nick's
on U.S. 278. Information: Hilton Head Chamber of Commerce,
</P>
<P>
   1-800-523-3373 or www
</P>
<P>
   .hiltonheadisland.org.
</P>
<P>
   NEW ORLEANS
</P>
<P>
   The Big Easy is an easy-to-like family destination with the
fabulous Aquarium of the Americas, the Audubon Zoo (see the rare
white alligators), riverboat excursions on the mighty Mississippi
and the terrific Louisiana Children's Museum. And it's not hard to
avoid the sleaze of Bourbon Street; you'll be pooped by dark
anyway, after a day of activities. Kids get caught up in the scene:
wolfing down sugar-dusted beignets and hot chocolate at Cafe du
Monde, watching street performers in Jackson Square, riding the St.
Charles streetcar and taking horse-drawn carriage rides through the
French Quarter. Expect to pay at least $100 (and potentially far
more) for a room. Le Richelieu, Hotel Provincial and Holiday Inn
Downtown-Superdome are reliable, moderately priced choices. Your
dining options are endless. Kid-friendly restaurants include the
Court of Two Sisters (go for Sunday jazz brunch), the moderately
priced Gumbo Shop on St. Peter Street, just off Jackson Square, and
Ralph and Kacoo's on Toulouse. Information: 504-566-5011, New
Orleans Metropolitan Convention and Visitors Bureau; www
</P>
<P>
   .neworleanscvb.com or www.neworleans.com.
</P>
<P>
   HUNTSVILLE, ALA.
</P>
<P>
   You don't have to be a rocket scientist to figure out the appeal
of this space-age destination where rocket boosters that put men on
the moon were developed. The U.S. Space &AMP; Rocket Center is just the
place for would-be astronauts and their families. You can see Imax
shows about space, take a guided bus tour of NASA's Marshall Space
Flight Center and get a close look at the real Apollo 15 module
that hauled men to the moon. The rocket center spans the distance
between sci-fi space fantasy and sophisticated NASA reality, with
more than 60 interactive exhibits and 1,500 pieces of space
hardware. Downtown Huntsville has a variety of moderately priced
hotels close to the center, including the Radisson Suite Hotel,
several Holiday Inns, Hilton, Marriott and Ramada. Many offer
suites and family specials, with separate bedrooms for children and
parents, for $80 to $120 per night. The center's Galaxy Food Court
serves moderately priced hamburgers, grilled chicken sandwiches and
other American foods. Space center information: 256-837-3400;
www.huntsville.org, www.ussrc.com.
</P>
<P>
   CHATTANOOGA
</P>
<P>
   The much-anticipated carousel in Coolidge Park is merrily
spinning 'round on the north shore of the Tennessee River. The
carousel's hand-carved and painted menagerie include a horse, fish,
giraffe, cat, elephant and frog. Across the river are the Tennessee
Aquarium, where the exhibit ``Venom: Striking Beauties'' opens
Friday, and 3-D Imax Theatre, where ``Dolphins'' opens April 1.
BellSouth Park, the new home of the Chattanooga Lookouts minor
league baseball team, also opens April 1 in the riverfront area (on
the hill behind Imax). Nearby, the Southern Belle Riverboat plies
the river from Ross' Landing. Just up the street is the Children's
Creative Discovery Museum. Little boys (and their dads) will love
the International Towing &AMP; Recovery Museum. The all-suite Residence
Inn by Marriott is right in the middle of the action. Hungry? Fun
restaurants in the vicinity include T.G.I. Friday's and Cheeburger,
Cheeburger. Round out your stay with visits to the Chattanooga Choo
Choo (you can even spend the night in a restored Pullman car, and
there's an indoor pool at the Choo Choo Holiday Inn). Close-by
attractions include Rock City, Ruby Falls and the Incline Railway.
Free shuttles run daily from the Choo Choo to the aquarium.
Information: 1-800-322-3344 or www.chattanooga
</P>
<P>
   .net/cvb.
</P>
<P>
   JEKYLL ISLAND
</P>
<P>
   Even the name sounds like fun. Once the playground of the rich
and famous, now the historic island is an affordable haven for
families. Even in summer (high season), it is possible for a family
to stay on the beach for less than $100 a night. And most
restaurants are reasonably priced and cater to families. In
addition to 10 miles of beach, you'll find Summer Waves Waterpark
(open daily Memorial Day through Labor Day), 63 holes of golf,
tennis courts, miniature golf, bicycle rentals (to explore 20 miles
of paved trails), horseback riding, fishing, dolphin tours and
sight-
</P>
<P>
   seeing. Be sure to tour the island's National Historic Landmark
District to learn about the days when it was a ``millionaires'
village.'' Trolley tours leave 10 a.m.-3 p.m. daily from the Museum
Visitors Center on Stable Road, where free exhibits describe
Jekyll's history. You can also clip-clop through the district in a
horse and buggy. Information: 1-800-841-6586 or
www.jekyllisland.com.
</P>
<P>
   FONTANA
</P>
<P>
   VILLAGE, N.C.
</P>
<P>
   Think of historic Fontana Village Resort as summer camp for the
whole family. The rustic and charming resort has a lakeside
swimming pool with water slide as well as an indoor pool, a marina
with boats to rent, fishing, 20 miles of maintained mountain biking
trails, minigolf and an activities center with equipment for
archery, badminton, tennis, volleyball, shuffleboard and
horseshoes. Stay at the 94-room Fontana Inn or one of the 200
cottages. Built in the early 1940s by the Tennessee Valley
Authority to house construction workers building Fontana Dam, the
town was turned into a sprawling family resort after World War II.
A visit to the 19th-century Gunter Cabin and Museum in the center
of the village offers a glimpse into bygone days. Lodging rates are
highest in summer: inn $79 and $149; cottages $89-$189 (the new
two-bedroom, two-bath cottages with fireplace and whirlpool are
$209). Peppercorn Restaurant in the Inn is a full-service
restaurant. The Village Cafe is great for a quick lunch. The
Peppermill Buffet House serves hearty mountain country cuisine
May-October. Information: 1-800-849-2258 or www.fontanavillage.com.
</P>
<P>
   Paula Crouch Thrasher writes for the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
