<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LENT-ADVISORY-NYTSF </SLUG>
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (To purchase this ``separate buy'' article from the New York
Times Syndicate please contact syndicate sales representative DEBRA
WEYDERT at 732-390-4480)
</P>
<P>
   `SMELLS AND BELLS' OF LENT CAN'T BE FOUND ON THE WEB
</P>
<P>
   By Diana Butler Bass
</P>
<P>
   It seems almost deviant to say so, but traditional church
appears to be making a comeback among computer-savvy baby-boomers
and Generation Xers. In contrast to the disembodied spirituality of
cyberspace, people seem eager for sensual religious experience _
kneeling, incense, bread and wine, congregational singing. The more
``smells and bells'' the better. Thus, the Internet actually
creates a need for human connection to the divine. The stuff of
traditional religion cannot (yet) be experienced over the Web. It
exists only in musty old buildings whose wood is scented with
decades of candle smoke. Those old buildings are sacred space,
places where the human and divine have touched for generations.
(Slugged LENT-WITHOUT-INTERNET-NYTSF)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-02-00 1627EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000302.0196 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-02 16:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4752 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w BC-CLINTON-GUNS-NYT &LR;      03-02 0559
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-GUNS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON URGES CONGRESS TO BREAK LOGJAM ON GUN CONTROL 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By MARC LACEY and ERIC SCHMITT    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Responding to two high-profile incidents of gun
violence this week, President Clinton said Thursday that he would
call legislative leaders to the White House on Tuesday to try to
``break the logjam'' on gun-control legislation that has been tied
up in Congress since last summer.
</P>
<P>
   But the situation on Capitol Hill showed few signs of bipartisan
cooperation. Frustrated Senate Democrats vowed to break off pieces
of the bottled-up legislation and add them as amendments to other
bills. In the House, Speaker Dennis Hastert, R-Ill., blamed
Democratic leaders for being the obstructionist ones and suggested
alternatives of his own.
</P>
<P>
   The House and Senate approved different gun-control bills after
contentious debates last year. Lawmakers in the two chambers,
however, deeply divided on the restrictions, have yet to reconcile
them in conference. The issue could become a prime issue in the
fall elections as Democrats, who generally support tighter
restrictions, criticize Republicans for not uniting behind the
president's approach.
</P>
<P>
   In convening a session at the White House on Tuesday, Clinton
sought Thursday to bring the issue of gun control to the forefront
following heightened public concern after the shooting death of a
six-year-old girl in Michigan by a classmate, as well as a
Pennsylvania man's shooting rampage that left two men dead and
three others wounded.
</P>
<P>
   ``These two incidents were very troubling, and they have
individual causes and explanations, and doubtless will require
individual responses,'' Clinton told reporters. ``But they do
remind us that there is still too much danger in this country, and
that for more than eight months now, Congress has been sitting on
the common-sense gun safety legislation.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also said that if a trigger lock had been installed on
the gun used by the Michigan boy, as the legislation calls for, the
incident might not have happened.
</P>
<P>
   The National Rifle Association, which Clinton criticized for
blocking reform, accused the the president of playing politics with
tragedy.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all politics,'' said Wayne LaPierre, executive vice
president of the National Rifle Association. ``These were horrible,
tragic situations. The president is trying to profiteer on
tragedy.''
</P>
<P>
   Seizing on the issue, Clinton interrupted two speeches devoted
to other topics this week to react to the shooting incidents in
Michigan and Pennsylvania. He said the deaths make the case for
legislation even more compelling.
</P>
<P>
   Describing his reaction to the shooting at the elementary
school, Clinton told NBC: ``As a parent, I was heartbroken, and
then I was angry. I thought how did this child get the gun in the
first place. What's a six year old doing with a gun?''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton acknowledged that gun control legislation would not
eliminate the problem of gun violence, which he said claims the
lives of 13 children every day. But he said tighter laws would
drastically reduce the problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is there a silver bullet that will solve it overnight? No,''
Clinton said. ``Can we save a lot of lives, including a lot of
children, 13 every day _ 13 funerals a day? You bet we can, and we
ought to.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-02-00 1629EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
