A4753 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-TV-PERKINS-COLUMN-TEX     03-02 1025
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-PERKINS-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DALLAS MOM IS TAKING OUT THE TRASH TV
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEN PARISH PERKINS 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Anyone with even a passing interest in television knows that Fox
is in trouble again, having pegged itself yet again as the network
most likely to put absolutely anything on the air as long as it
generates ratings.
</P>
<P>
   Talking to a Fox publicist recently on an entirely different
matter, I couldn't help but ask what it's like to work for the
network; whether, with all due respect, she didn't personally feel
drenched with the slime that seems to ooze out of the programming
brains of the company.
</P>
<P>
   She paused and said, sure, at times she feels like her superiors
are profit-mongers with no sense of integrity, dignity or class.
But, on the other hand, doesn't that cover all of television?
Aren't they merely trying to stay with the pack?
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps this was her way of defending the company that cuts her
checks, or justifying her contributions to sleaze-peddling. Or is
there a ring of truth to what she's saying?
</P>
<P>
   An e-mail came in the other day from a 37-year-old wife and
mother of four who lives in Dallas but works in Fort Worth. Anna
Donovan is a college-educated world traveler who recently plopped
down more than $200 to send her preteen children to a performance
of the Alvin Ailey American Dance Theater at Bass Hall in Fort
Worth.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's nothing worse than keeping young minds away from the
arts,'' she wrote. ``Dance, music, whether it's pop concerts with
the Backstreet Boys or the Dallas Symphony, it should all be there
for the taking, because it opens up the minds and more importantly,
the senses.''
</P>
<P>
   Her point is that television, while never considered an art form
among fine artists, is an art because of its ability to communicate
to the masses in a creative way.
</P>
<P>
   She ``uses'' television rather than ``watches'' it, she wrote,
and has tried to encourage her children to do the same. It's
working, she thinks, because, while their selections aren't always
what she'd like to them to be, their viewing hours are minimal, and
they watch shows that challenge their minds and their environments
instead of ``sitcoms where the only goal is a laugh no matter the
expense.''
</P>
<P>
   In a subsequent talk by phone, Donovan said she was happy that
her oldest son, who is 12, joined the condemnation chorus over
Fox's ``Who Wants to Marry a Multi-Millionaire?,'' and not because
questions surfaced about the so-called millionaire, but because the
program itself was so sexist and void of redeemable value.
</P>
<P>
   ``I also tell my kids that television is entertainment and it's
revenue-driven,'' she says. ``So certain choices are being made
based on that criteria. I mean, my son saying that this was
something that didn't lure him, I was pretty impressed. We escaped
that one, at least, because the battle is always to win out over
this evil intruder.''
</P>
<P>
   The evil intruder, actually, is commerce, which could be linked
to any industry. Like any business, no network is out to lose
money. But where should a line be drawn?
</P>
<P>
   I recall a conversation a few years ago at a Dallas hotel with
Jamie Kellner, who has had tremendous success getting The WB off
and running. He spent a great portion of an hour talking about
positioning and brand name and narrow-casting, saying that The WB
was the TV version of radio and that everyone _ NBC, CBS, ABC,
everyone _ ought to get on board if they were to survive what
television would become as we head into 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Kellner sounded like a businessman, not the head of a creative
entity who cared all that much about art.
</P>
<P>
   But for that matter, as the Fox spokesperson said, class is a
matter of perception. Maybe Fox merely gets caught because of its
rep.
</P>
<P>
   It was NBC that, on the night of David Letterman's comeback show
on ``Late Night,'' purposely scheduled Howard Stern, a media hound
who had ridiculed Letterman on his radio show. NBC considered it a
good counterprogramming move; others thought it was tasteless.
</P>
<P>
   And CBS? It aired a JonBenet Ramsey miniseries, ignoring the
fact that the murder case hasn't been solved and that there's
little to report other than innuendo. (The miniseries, as expected,
won its time period.)
</P>
<P>
   People used to complain that TV's problem was that it was
squarely aimed at the minds of 12-year-olds. Now, thanks to
Kellner's The WB, it seems aimed at the hormones of 14-year-olds.
</P>
<P>
   So we get wrestling and monster truck shows and series about
foul-mouthed rappers called ``Shasta McNasty,'' because UPN execs
are convinced those will draw young men and increase the network's
advertising rates.
</P>
<P>
   So what do you do, says the Fox publicist, when your competitors
are killing you in the ratings and your job is at stake? The ``high
road,'' as she put it, ``isn't going to pay the rent.''
</P>
<P>
   In a multiple-channel environment, and at a time when parents
are out of the home more than in it, leaving children alone to
watch what they please, we are raising a generation that will be
conditioned to think that tasteless reality programming is quality
TV. It's the old adage that if you only drink dirty water, you come
to think it tastes fine.
</P>
<P>
   As for Anna Donovan, she is convinced that television is this
intruding force that's more bad than good simply because it's
designed that way in the current competitive environment.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't give up on TV by watching whatever and letting our
children watch the trash,'' she says. ``TV as baby sitter is
cliche. But isn't that what happens when parents just give up on
trying to make TV good again by watching the tasteless stuff?''
</P>
<P>
   I can't say that a majority of parents have given up caring.
But, judging from the responses logged to this office shortly after
the ``Marry a Multi-Millionaire'' fiasco, they are certainly
growing weary of fighting the intruder.
</P>
<P>
   (Ken Parish Perkins is TV critic for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. You can call him at (817) 390-7862, or e-mail:
kpperkins(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
