<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-CRITIC-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXAS DEMOCRATIC STATE REPRESENTATIVE LABELS GORE A FRAUD
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service Clients) 
By JACK DOUGLAS JR. 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Texas State Rep. Lon Burnam has angered some
fellow Democrats by writing that Vice President Al Gore is a fraud
and a willing accomplice to foreign policies that have led to the
``rape, torture and mutilation of women and children across the
world.''
</P>
<P>
   Burnam, D-Fort Worth, made the assertions in a one-page
newsletter in which he endorses Bill Bradley over Gore as the
Democratic presidential nominee. Bradley's campaign disavowed any
involvement in distributing the letter and said some of Burnam's
comments are offensive.
</P>
<P>
   Burnam, in an interview on Wednesday, said he believes that Gore
is a fraud by claiming to work to protect the environment. Gore's
voting record while in the U.S. Senate, Burnam said, suggests
otherwise.
</P>
<P>
   Burnam did not elaborate in his newsletter when he described
Gore as an accomplice to criminal acts. But he said in the
interview that Gore must share the blame for atrocities committed
in Latin America, including the rape and torture of women and
children. Those crimes were committed by paramilitary groups
trained by Americans as part of a foreign policy supported by Gore,
Burnam said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bill Bradley stands head and shoulders above Al Gore, not just
in stature, but politically as well,'' Burnam wrote.
</P>
<P>
   A spokeswoman for Bradley said the candidate did not authorize
the letter, which was mailed as a political advertisement by
Burnam's campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Members of Bradley's national campaign headquarters are ``very
disturbed'' by Burnam's assertions, said Kristen Ludecke, Bradley's
deputy press secretary in West Orange, N.J.
</P>
<P>
   ``The mailing was not authorized by this campaign, and it is
certainly not a sentiment shared by Bill Bradley,'' Ludecke said,
adding, ``The language in the mailer is offensive.''
</P>
<P>
   A member of Gore's campaign headquarters in Nashville, Tenn.,
agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is classic political-attack literature that has no place
in a Democratic campaign,'' said Douglas Hattaway, a Gore
spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   ``Senator Bradley's supporters would do better to focus on
(Bradley's) positive record, rather than defame Al Gore,'' Hattaway
said.
</P>
<P>
   As co-chairman of the Bradley-for-president campaign in Tarrant
County (Fort Worth), Burnam said he mailed ``less than a thousand''
of the letters to Bradley supporters.
</P>
<P>
   Burnam, who is unopposed for a third term in office, said he
knew his written comments about Gore would upset members of his own
party.
</P>
<P>
   He said the newsletter was meant to wake up ``Democrats who are
complacent about what the Democratic Party is responsible for when
it comes to suffering in the Third World.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We are no better than the worst Republicans when it comes to a
lot of foreign policy issues,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Burnam said he will only support Gore if he becomes the
Democratic Party's presidential nominee _ and ``not a day before.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked about Burnam's assertions that Gore is partly responsible
for rapes and tortures, Russell Langley, executive director of the
Tarrant County Democratic Party, said: ``We certainly wouldn't go
along with that.''
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com)
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
