A4755 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-MIDEAST-POPE-0303-COX     03-02 0776
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIDEAST-POPE-0303-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    ISRAELI CHIEF RABBI EXPECTS POPE TO ASK FORGIVENESS
 &HT;    By LARRY KAPLOW 
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ Israel's chief rabbi Thursday said Pope John Paul II
should ask forgiveness for church silence during the Holocaust when
he visits later this month.
</P>
<P>
   The Pope is expected to visit Israel and the Palestinian areas
for six days beginning March 30. It will be his first trip here as
Pope, and the first trip here by any Pope since the mid-1960s.
</P>
<P>
   In recent weeks, a series of protocol squabbles concerning the
visit have highlighted age-old Jewish anxieties about the Pope and
Catholicism. Israel and the Vatican only established full
diplomatic ties in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Israel Chief Rabbi Israel Meir Lau said he welcomed the Pope and
said the frail 79-year-old pontiff has traveled the world
repeatedly condemning anti-Semitism. Lau, a Holocaust survivor from
Poland, said the Pope understands the horrors of the Holocaust
because he is also from Poland.
</P>
<P>
   But, Lau said the Pope's scheduled visit to Jerusalem's Yad
Vashem Holocaust museum should include a plea for forgiveness on
behalf of the Catholic Church.
</P>
<P>
   Lau referred to a 1998 church committee that renounced the
silence of individual Catholics during the Holocaust. Lau and other
Jewish leaders objected that the committee had not gone far enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``Asking for forgiveness at Yad Vashem will be more
satisfying,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He said the wartime Pope Pius XII had remained silent and
therefore ``stood in the blood'' of innocent Jews.
</P>
<P>
   ``To not deny the Holocaust means telling the truth,'' Lau said.
He said the 1998 committee was ``chapter one'' and that he was
``waiting for chapter two.''
</P>
<P>
   Wadie Abunassar, a spokesman for the Vatican's millennium
activities in the Holy Land, answered that Catholics should not be
repeatedly asked for apologies for the Holocaust.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think we should continue with apologies, apologies,
apologies,'' he said. ``We have to think of reconciliation. Real
reconciliation.''
</P>
<P>
   The Pope has labeled 2000 as a holy year, stressing repentance.
It is expected that he will offer at least limited church apologies
later in the month on several historical matters.
</P>
<P>
   Historic friction between Jews and Catholics has come up
frequently as Israel prepares for the Pope's pilgrimage. A small,
but vocal, minority has expressed objections to the papal visit.
</P>
<P>
   Even as Lau began his news conference Thursday, a handful of
extremists stood outside his offices with signs accusing the Pope
of being an anti-Semite.
</P>
<P>
   The protestors said they were related to the outlawed Kach
movement, a militant, anti-Arab group representing a tiny fringe of
Israeli society.
</P>
<P>
   But last week, more than 2,000 rabbis signed a petition asking
the Pope to respect the Jewish Sabbath, which runs from Friday
evening through Saturday evening, during his tour.
</P>
<P>
   Lau, also, called on the Pope to minimize his travel on the
Sabbath so that observant Jews among the Israeli police and
security will not have to work. He said, for example, the Pope
should not use a helicopter to travel from Jerusalem to Nazareth, a
two-hour drive away, so that pilots of air force escorts can get
the day off.
</P>
<P>
   Israeli officials reacted with outrage last month when the Pope
met with Palestinian Authority President Yasser Arafat. The two
approved an agreement between the Vatican and the Palestinian
Authority that Israelis interpreted as a challenge to Israeli
authority in Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the Israeli objections are similar to misgivings that
some Israelis had about hosting the thousands of Christian pilgrims
who came here for New Year's Eve.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts say that Jews have seen Christianity, often
Catholicism, used as the justification for anti-Jewish activities
from the Crusades a thousand years ago to modern times.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, some Muslims have expressed doubts about the papal
visit. Ibrahim Sarsur, head of a branch of the Islamic Movement in
Israel, said the Pope should issue an apology for massacres of
Muslims during the Crusades.
</P>
<P>
   But the Pope is using his visit as an opportunity to enhance
inter-faith relations with both Jews and Muslims. Father Peter
Vasco, a member of the seven-person council that oversees Middle
Eastern holy sites, said that the overall atmosphere is good.
</P>
<P>
   He downplayed the objections.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are isolated incidents,'' he said. ``Certainly, we're
not surprised at it. At the same time we realize it's not the
majority opinion of the Israeli people.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
