<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOLF-VIDEOGAMES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOT SHOTS GOLF 2 ELIMINATES USUAL PROBLEMS WITH VIDEO GOLF GAMES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MALCOLM MAYHEW 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   If there's one sport that vid-game companies still scratch their
heads over on how to make it cool for kids _ much less
knuckleheaded adults like me _ it's golf.
</P>
<P>
   It takes hours to figure out most golf games, even the
supposedly kid-friendly ones. Gotta line up the player just right.
Gotta aim just so. Gotta do some sort of mathematical equation to
make the guy hit the ball. Then, for some reason, I always wind up
missing it. Sorry, but I just don't have the patience. I like to
win every once in a while.
</P>
<P>
   That was what was so great about Hot Shots Golf, PlayStation's
very cool, very oblivious-user-friendly golf title from last year.
The sequel, Hot Shots Golf 2 (Sony for PlayStation, $40), is even
better.
</P>
<P>
   All the problems with the usual golf games are nonexistent here.
You don't have to know golf mechanics, don't have to be an engineer
to figure out what iron you wanna use, and an algebra lesson isn't
necessary to whack the ball.
</P>
<P>
   You do, however, have to wanna have fun. The characters are
funny and colorful and goofy, and the commentary's equally a hoot.
</P>
<P>
   But Hot Shots 2 is anything but dumb. The graphics, for example,
are as crisp and detailed as any golf PC game, and while the
courses aren't Tiger Woods material, they're challenging enough to
keep your mind boggled and your fingers blistered. Which is more
than I can say for most other golf games.
</P>
<P>
   Anyone who has ridden in a cab _ especially in New York _ knows
that, well, cabbies are just a different breed of people. A round
of applause for Sega for cleverly exploiting these guys with its
great new Dreamcast title, Crazy Taxi (Sega for Dreamcast, $50, all
ages).
</P>
<P>
   What we have here is one of the most original titles to come
along in a while _ and what makes it so cool is that it's so true,
to an extent. But I always have a better time playing a game that's
based on reality than a far-fetched game that features cat-eating
zombies.
</P>
<P>
   The object of Crazy Taxi goes something like this: You're a
hot-shot cabbie trying to make as much cash in one day as ya can.
To do this, obviously, you have to pick up as many fares as
possible, figure out where they wanna go and the shortest route to
get there, then drop 'em off at their destination; so it's not just
driving around knocking trash cans over, you've gotta be able to
read maps.
</P>
<P>
   That's not to say you don't get to trash stuff, because you do.
You'll probably get points slashed for it, but you can drive
through yards, hit other cars and terrorize pedestrians. Mmmmm,
hurts so good.
</P>
<P>
   (Malcolm Mayhew is a pop culture critic for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. You can call him at (817) 390-7713 or e-mail:
mmayhew(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
