<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-02 16:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4757 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r t BC-ORLANDO-THEMEPARKS-10     03-02 0844
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ORLANDO-THEMEPARKS-1000(2Takes)-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNIVERSAL STUDIOS ESCAPE TRIES TO MATCH THEME PARK STALWART DISNEY
WORLD
</HEADLINE>
 
(EDS: Accompanied by ORLANDO-ATTRACTIONS) (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CAROLYN POIROT 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ORLANDO, Fla. _ Among the guests crowding the floating dock of
the new resort hotel Portofino Bay, hoping to hitch a water taxi
over to the Universal Studios theme park, was a young boy, hopping
from foot to foot as he waited impatiently.
</P>
<P>
   ``So how do you think this place stacks up against Disney
World?'' an older man asked him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, Downtown Disney has more stuff for kids to do than
CityWalk, but I like the roller coasters better over here,
especially the Incredible Hulk,'' the youngster said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Hulk,'' my 13-year old daughter piped up. ``And the
beds.''
</P>
<P>
   Beds may seem a strange point of comparison _ if you haven't
seen the ones at Portofino Bay, the first on-site hotel at what is
now called ``Universal Studios Escape.''
</P>
<P>
   And if you haven't seen the luxurious Portofino _ not to mention
a 650-room Hard Rock Hotel slated for opening late this year, the
Islands of Adventure theme park that debuted last summer, and the
ever-expanding collection of nightclubs known as CityWalk _ you may
not not realize this about Orlando's Universal Studios Escape: The
park is giving notice they're ready to rival their more-established
neighbor, Walt Disney World, as a ``complete vacation destination.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, after spending years known as Orlando's ``other'' theme
park, Universal Studios now apparently intends to compete head-on
with Disney World, which has grown to include Magic Kingdom, Epcot,
MGM Studios, Animal Kingdom, Downtown Disney and 17 on-site hotels,
containing a staggering 27,000 rooms.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   But back to those beds. Each of Portofino's large rooms is
equipped with tall, wood-framed beds, covered with feathery white
duvets and soft, giant pillows. The first thing my daughter did
when we entered the room was jump into the middle of all that fluff
and announce that she wanted to take a nap. (She never takes a
nap.)
</P>
<P>
   As a mother, I worried about the pizza sauce she accidentally
dripped on one of those snow white clouds, and the fact that she
insisted on wearing the equally white pique bathrobe to Portofino
Bay's dramatic Roman aqueduct-style pool, complete with water slide
and a sand beach on one end.
</P>
<P>
   Other than the pool, however, this luxury hotel seems more plush
than playful. (Although the Hard Rock Hotel will be nearly as
expensive, it will have a more casual atmosphere; the third
Universal hotel, the 1,000-room Royal Pacific Hotel due to open in
summer 2001, will also be on the upscale side.)
</P>
<P>
   The Portofino has been designed to look like a village of softly
colored pink, tan and gold townhouses, built around a harbor.
Inside, crystal chandeliers grace the lobby, and deluxe rooms with
large tile baths and dressing areas with double marble sinks are
standard. It would be a perfect choice for any of the tens of
thousands of newlywed couples who make central Florida the
honeymoon capital of the world _ or business executives on expense
accounts.
</P>
<P>
   At the harbor, guests can catch a water shuttle headed for
CityWalk and the Universal theme parks. They can also choose to sit
at one of the tables out on the tile and brick-paved piazza at
Trattoria del Porto, eating brick-oven pizza or pasta and sipping
wine served from painted china crocks. Or, they might hoist a beer
at the Thirsty Fish tavern, where strolling musicians play
accordions and violins.
</P>
<P>
   We didn't eat at the more formal restaurants _ the gourmet
Delfino Riviera and the American Bar, where the specialties are
caviar, champagne and salmon _ but they looked very elegant,
despite no requirement for jackets or ties.
</P>
<P>
   Open only since mid-September, the 750-room luxury resort is
still a bit of a work in progress. A third pool, more gift shops
and a full-service spa were not yet open on our recent visit.
Restaurant service was slow this winter, and though the staff
seemed to want to be helpful, they were sometimes clueless about
such simple things as how late the pools were open and which park
had an early opening.
</P>
<P>
   Brand-new landscaping currently distracts from the scene. But,
given all that, in another year or two, the grounds will rival the
lush and always neat settings over at Disney.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the world's best-known theme parks are bound to spark
comparisons, especially when they are less than 20 miles apart.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just say Disney is more kid-friendly,'' my daughter insisted
when asked for help in comparing the two parks.
</P>
<P>
   Both theme parks offer exclusive guest privileges to those who
stay on site, including early admission to their theme parks,
special bus and boat transportation, charge cards that bill
everything back to your hotel, priority seating at select
restaurants and shows, and complimentary package delivery back to
your room (for all those heavy souvenirs you collect early in the
day).
</P>
<P>
   MORE
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Universal offers guests staying at on-site resorts
``front-of-the-line'' access to many of the most popular
attractions during the first hour of regular operations. Disney
offers the ``fast pass,'' a come-back-later deal that gives guests
with multiple day admission passes immediate entry at a designated
time if they are willing to come back in an hour or so.
</P>
<P>
   Disney also sells ``E-passes'' for $10, that allow on-site hotel
guests to ride many of the biggest and best attractions at Magic
Kingdom for three hours after the park closes _ and nearly empties
_ on certain nights. (Just in case you want to ``do Splash
Mountain'' seven times in less than an hour, like we did.)
</P>
<P>
   Other points of comparison include:
</P>
<P>
   Universal's Islands of Adventure's Jurassic Park River Adventure
is a lot like Disney's Animal Kingdom's thrill ride, Countdown to
Extinction _ except that you take a boat at Jurassic, a jerking and
careening jeep at the Kingdom. (Jurassic has the 5-story T-Rex, but
Countdown is more intense and scary in the dark; dinosaurs can jump
out at you and you could be destroyed by an asteroid at any
moment.)
</P>
<P>
   At Magic Kingdom, visitors ride through the hundred-acre woods
in a honey pot to join the adventures of Winnie the Pooh; at Seuss
Island, one of Universal's Islands of Adventure, you can follow the
adventures of the Cat in the Hat from a gently spinning sofa. Seuss
Island also has red fish and blue fish you can ride through the
air, much like you ride Dumbo the Flying Elephant over at Magic
Kingdom.
</P>
<P>
   Animal Kingdom's new whitewater-raft ride, Kali River Rapids, is
a round rubber raft ride that takes you through a rain forest with
waterfalls and through mythical ruins as well as the ruins of a
stripped logging camp, leaving you soaked-to-the-skin. Over at the
Islands, there is Popeye &AMP; Bluto's Bilge Rat Barges, a similar ride
that leaves you just as wet, at least from the knees down.
</P>
<P>
   Dudley Do-Right's Ripsaw Falls (Universal) and Splash Mountain
(Magic Kingdom) both take you on whimsical adventures before
plunging you over a tall, steep waterfall that's certain to soak
you through at the end. (While the big drops are comparable,
Dudley's scenery pales in comparison with the splendid Mountain.)
</P>
<P>
   A kid-friendly centerpiece of Downtown Disney, the entertainment
complex, is the gigantic Rain Forest Cafe. Universal's CityWalk
counters with Hard Rock Live Orlando, which has a 2,200-seat
amphitheater on the roof hosting nationally known artists.
</P>
<P>
   Both parks offer one really outstanding new ride.
</P>
<P>
   Disney's Rockin' Roller Coaster combines a smooth, high-speed
roller coaster with blasting rock music and flashing neon lights. A
stretch limo equipped with lots of stereo speakers whips you
through downtown LA traffic to the (very loud) tune of an Aerosmith
concert. The assault on your sense is such that I honestly did not
realize that we turned completely upside down three times until I
rode the Rockin' Roller Coaster a second and third time.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Universal's Amazing Adventures of Spider Man, billed
as ``the greatest ride ever built,'' is truly amazing _ the first
themed thrill ride to combine vehicles that whip you around, hurtle
you through space and drop you through the dark with startling 3-D
action and on-fire special effects. (The science of illusion works
magic when Spider Man comes swinging down from a tall skyscraper,
right into your lap.)
</P>
<P>
   Disney's IllumiNations, the laser show and fireworks at Epcot's
World Showplace, hasn't changed much for its millennium
celebration, but it still takes the prize for best special effects.
It's rivaled only by another Disney show, Fantasmic, a spectacular
new light show reflected off screens of spouting water.
</P>
<P>
   But for sheer spectacle, Disney can't match Universal's Cirque
du Soleil, the musical circus/theater. This show immerses you in a
surrealistic dream where gymnasts fly gracefully on colorful silk
scarves _ looking much more like birds than acrobats _ and soar off
trampolines impossibly fluid. Mime characters are both comic and
tragic here, and cycling clowns perform upside down and sideways on
an intricate, very-near-magical stage, that's inside a white circus
tent.
</P>
<P>
   So which park is for you? After four visits in five years, we
still favor Disney by a bit, but Universal is definitely moving up.
Let's just say they make an extraordinary package, and we aren't
close to getting our fill of any of them, yet. Guess, we'll just
have to keep going back.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
