A4769 &Cx1f; tab-z
w e BC-IVOR-ANNETTE-BENING-I     03-02 1248
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IVOR-ANNETTE-BENING-IN-WHAT-PLANET-ARE-YOU-FROM-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANNETTE BENING, AN OSCAR NOMINATION ... AND BABY MAKES THREE 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's Hollywood Stars
entertainment column.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to Hollywood Stars, a
weekly entertainment column with color and black-and-white art.)
 Includes black-and-white photos and color slides of Annette Bening
with Garry Shandling in a scene from ``What Planet Are You From?'' 
 By IVOR DAVIS  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    If you have trouble picking out Annette Bening at the Academy
Awards on Mar. 26, here's a tip: She'll probably be the only one
who brings a small suitcase.
 &HT;    ``If I went into labor pains, I'd go straight to the hospital,''
she says. ``And some friends suggested I ought to have my overnight
bag under my seat or have a medical team around me wearing tuxedos,
or at least sit among a bunch of actors who have played doctors in
movies.''
 &HT;    Yes, Bening is due to produce Baby Beatty number four on or
around that date. But even if she doesn't, it will still be a big
night for the Beatty clan: She's favored in the Best Actress stakes
for her over-the-top performance in ``American Beauty,'' while
husband Warren Beatty will receive the prestigious Irving Thalberg
Award, a tribute to his long career as a Hollywood star, producer
and director.
 &HT;    Bening hopes she makes it, because she's thrilled with the
success of ``American Beauty,'' a quirky suburban drama/black
comedy on which first-time director Sam Mendes spent a miserly _ by
today's budgets _ $15 million.
 &HT;    ``We all worked for virtually union scale (around $1,000 a
day),'' Bening says. ``We made it thinking only a few people would
ever get to see it, never in our wildest dreams imagining it would
do so well and become so hugely popular.''
 &HT;    ``Hugely popular'' it was, not to mention critically acclaimed
and, of course, Oscar-nominated, to the tune of eight nods
including Best Picture, Best Actor (Kevin Spacey) and Best
Director.
 &HT;    In person, Bening is less driven than the obsessive,
martini-guzzling real-estate agent she plays in the movie, and a
whole lot smarter. Prettier, too _ she is one of those women who
improves with pregnancy. Wearing virtually no makeup, she looks
serene and beautiful as she sits, dressed all in black with a black
pashmina shawl wrapped around her stomach, to talk about the
performance that might bring her an Oscar.
 &HT;    ``When I first read it I had some sort of intuitive
understanding of her,'' the actress says. ``I found it difficult
and challenging, yet this was a woman I sort of felt I knew or had
known. I grew up as a teen-ager in the California suburbs, and
maybe I babysat for her or saw her in the supermarket, or I had
been shown a house by her.
 &HT;    ``She was a woman trying to have it all, trying to live the
American dream,'' Bening adds. ``But, after shooting each day, I
made certain I didn't take her home with me. Then, after seeing the
film for the first time, I thought, `Oh God, is that who I really
am?'''
 &HT;    Her next film is a good deal more lighthearted. ``What Planet
Are You From?'' will open March 3, directed by Mike Nichols and
written by actor/comedian Garry Shandling, who also stars as an
alien who lands on earth, takes one look at Bening and announces,
``I want to sleep with you and get you pregnant.''
 &HT;    ``I read Garry's script and laughed out loud,'' Bening recalls.
``I loved it, and told Garry I'd like to be in the film. It's about
people trying to connect, and how we all desperately want to find
love and find a way to make a family _ and how tricky that is.''
 &HT;    Shandling is an old friend of Beatty's, which came in handy
during an extended honeymoon scene he shared with Bening.
 &HT;    ``I felt very comfortable doing the scene,'' Bening insists with
a broad smile. ``Garry says he called Warren for advice on how to
do the love scene, but if he did I wasn't aware of it. I giggled
through it the whole time, and Mike also kept giggling.
 &HT;    ``I've done other nude scenes, and directors usually clear the
set,'' she adds. ``On this one they invited everyone to watch, and
we did it on a bed on a high platform.''
 &HT;    As for the baby to come, Bening _ already the mother of
8-year-old Kathlyn, 5-year-old Ben and 3-year-old Isabel _ says
there won't be any sequels.
 &HT;    ``We've been married for eight years,'' she says, ``and this is
definitely my last child. I'm the youngest of four children, and
Warren and I always said we'd have more than two. But I know when
it's enough.''
 &HT;    If she makes it to Oscar night, she admits her thoughts will be
divided between the baby and the bauble. Her toughest competition
is likely to come from Hilary Swank, the virtual unknown nominated
for her tour-de-force performance as a woman disguised as a man in
``Boys Don't Cry.''
 &HT;    ``Hilary's performance was inspiring,'' Bening admits. ``But I
still want to win. Anyone who says they don't care about Oscar is
lying.''
 &HT;    Many actresses have expressed admiration at Bening's ability to
juggle motherhood with a thriving career, a trick which many others
have found difficult. She gives the credit to having a lot of help
at home _ including Beatty, who she says not only has never
pressured her to choose between career and motherhood, but also has
become a veteran diaper-changer.
 &HT;    Besides, she says, combining acting and mothering isn't as hard
as it would be if she were in most other professions.
 &HT;    ``I have a great job to have with kids,'' she says, ``because I
can stop and start and take large chunks of time off. I feel very
lucky that I can do both. I love my work, and my kids are
fantastic.
 &HT;    ``And I've had enough babies by now to know when it's physically
and emotionally right for me to start work again,'' she adds.
 &HT;    Her Oscar-night outing will be a bit unusual, Bening says,
because as a rule she studiously avoids public scrutiny when she's
pregnant.
 &HT;    ``But I'm enjoying the fact that my new movie is coming out,''
she says, ``and `American Beauty' is having such a wonderful second
life.''
 &HT;    And if she has to leave in the middle of the show, she says, her
husband will leave with her, Thalberg Award or no.
 &HT;    ``I would never have married a man who would not have been able
to make the right kind of decision in that situation,'' Bening
says. ``He'll be with me at the hospital.''
 c.2000 Ivor Davis  
<TEXT>
