<SLUG> BC-GAY-MARRIAGE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     GROUP FIGHTING ANTI-GAY INITIATIVE UNLEASHES NEW AD 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By CAROL NESS  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Opponents of Proposition 22 are going for the
jugular with an explosive new television advertisement that
compares support of the anti-gay marriage initiative with a
gay-hating fringe group from Kansas.
</P>
<P>
   ``Prop. 22 won't save a single marriage, but it will hurt gay
people. That's what it's intended to do,'' a voice-over says as a
small image expands to fill the screen.
</P>
<P>
   The ad shows a photo of protesters holding signs reading ``God
hates fags'' and ``Fags burn in Hell.'' The opponents of the
California ballot measure say the protesters are followers of the
itinerant Baptist minister Fred Phelps of Topeka, who frequently
demonstrates at gay parades and other events.
</P>
<P>
   ``No discrimination,'' is the message in the advertisement.
</P>
<P>
   ``The image you will see is jolting. It's meant to be. Prop. 22
is jolting to many Californians,'' said Mike Marshall, manager for
the campaign against what is known as the Knight Initiative. The
measure, which will appear on Tuesday's ballot, is sponsored by
state Sen. William ``Pete'' Knight, a Republican from Palmdale.
</P>
<P>
   ``When people vote yes, they are going to hurt someone they know
who is gay or lesbian,'' Marshall said.
</P>
<P>
   The Yes on 22 campaign responded by calling the new ad part of
an increasingly negative campaign waged by the opponents.
</P>
<P>
   ``Equating millions of Californians who believe marriage should
be kept as between a man and a woman with extremist groups from out
of state is grossly offensive and inflammatory,'' said Yes on 22
spokesman Robert Glazier.
</P>
<P>
   He called the tactic desperate.
</P>
<P>
   The new ad hit the airways in most California cities Tuesday
night in a late-campaign effort to sway support for the initiative.
Polls since October, including two new ones this week, have shown
that slightly more than 50 percent of Californians favor
Proposition 22, and slightly under 40 percent oppose it.
</P>
<P>
   Gay marriage is not legal in California or any other state, but
the initiative prohibit California from recognizing gay marriages
conducted in other states, should they become legal.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
