<P>
   MISSING-ATHEIST (San Antonio) _ Blood traces recovered from an
Austin storage unit have reinforced federal authorities' belief
that the militant atheist Madalyn Murray O'Hair and her two adult
children were dismembered there after being kidnapped and killed in
1995. The information is contained in documents filed in the U.S.
District Court at Austin. By JOHN MacCORMACK
</P>
<P>
   BONFIRE-PROBE (College Station, Texas) _ The commission
investigating last year's Texas A&AMP;M bonfire collapse that killed 12
people wants to double its $1 million budget. The commission also
wants to extend the time for completing its report until May 31. By
JOHN WILLIAMS.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MEANS-COLUMN (Washington) _ Civil rights activists have
campaigned to get rid of offensive reminders of slavery in recent
years, from the confederate flag that flies over the South Carolina
statehouse to the names on school buildings of historic figures who
owned slaves. Now the Declaration of Independence is under siege on
the grounds that its 1776 statement that ``all men are created
equal'' didn't include blacks (or women) at the time. But this
protest misses the forest for the trees. By MARIANNE MEANS.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT(``e'' category)
</P>
<P>
   FILM-NEVE-CAMPBELL (New York) _ She may reign as the current
Queen of ``Scream,'' but Neve Campbell hopes her horror-movie fans
will be laughing at her soon. In the silly ``Drowning Mona,'' which
opens this weekend, Campbell trades her dramatic persona from Fox's
``Party of Five'' and her terrorized teen-turned-fem-avenger in the
hit ``Scream'' film series for something considerably lighter and
ditzier. By LOUIS B. PARKS.
</P>
<P>
   MUSIC-CSNY (Undated) _ To quote his Byrds song ``Renaissance
Fair,'' David Crosby sometimes looks around these days and says,
``I think that maybe I'm dreaming.'' Life is good in large part
because Crosby _ a veteran of rock's highs and lows since the '60s
_ is sober and strong and playing with his old friends in a reunion
tour of Crosby, Stills, Nash &AMP; Young, the early rock supergroup. By
BRUCE WESTBROOK.
</P>
<P>
   VIDEO-REVIEW (Undated) _ A look at films ``The Best Man,''
``Stigmata,'' ``Random Hearts'' and a direct-to-video release from
Disney, ``An Extremely Goofy Movie.'' By BRUCE WESTBROOK.
</P>
<P>
   For Sunday:
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   THOMPSON-COLUMN (Washington) _ In the current campaign, the men
who would be president have been called such things as liars,
cheats, cowards and phonies. But such vitriol is nothing new. It is
part of a tradition that began in 1796 with the first presidential
clash between Thomas Jefferson and John Adams. By ROBERT E.
THOMPSON.
</P>
