<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-NUNN03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: Nunn still valuable to U.S. interests
 &HT;    (EDs: This is an editorial from Friday's Atlanta Constitution)
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Late last month in a ceremony little noticed outside
Washington, D.C., the State Department paid tribute to a man better
known for his association with the Department of Defense _ Sam
Nunn.
</P>
<P>
   The former Georgia senator and ex-chairman of the Armed Services
Committee received a high honor indeed, the Ralph Bunche Award for
Diplomatic Excellence, for exemplifying the traits of creativity,
leadership and character reminiscent of the venerated
African-American statesman.
</P>
<P>
   Nunn a diplomat? Yes, in the words of Undersecretary of State
Thomas Pickering, Nunn was a visionary in fashioning a bipartisan
consensus on Capitol Hill concerning national security issues _ an
achievement in diplomacy even though Nunn performed the feat on
U.S. soil. Also, Pickering pointed out, Nunn worked with State's
career officers to foster diplomatic readiness within the
department, because he thought that was no less important than
military readiness.
</P>
<P>
   Nunn raised some questions about seizing diplomatic initiatives
in his own remarks:
</P>
<P>
   ``Can we develop a preventive diplomatic fund in the State
Department that would allow millions to be spent in predictable hot
spots like Kosovo to prevent wars rather than waiting for billions
to be spent to fight wars? Should we lead a world effort to buy all
excess nuclear materials to head off the nightmare of nuclear
terrorism?''
</P>
<P>
   Those certainly seem like sound suggestions. Perhaps Nunn, in
his spare time away from his Atlanta law practice and Georgia Tech
professorship, could flesh them out for this or a future
administration. Inside the government or out, he's still a valuable
guy to have around.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
