A4777 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k BC-EDITORIAL-ROCKER03-CO     03-02 0338
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-ROCKER03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: Reduced penalty more suitable
 &HT;    (EDs: This is an editorial from Friday's Atlanta Constitution)
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Major League Baseball's new independent arbitrator
Shyam Das has lightened the penalty imposed on the Atlanta Braves'
John Rocker by Commissioner Bud Selig. That's just as well. The
original monthlong suspension and $20,000 fine were excessive.
</P>
<P>
   To put the fuss over Rocker in perspective, he didn't violate
league rules on drugs as a marginal New York Yankee outfielder did
(for the umpteenth time). He didn't poleax an opposing player and
put him in the hospital as a Boston Bruins enforcer did. Granted,
he embarrassed the baseball establishment, but that pales beside
the mortification of the NFL over the arrest of a Baltimore Ravens
linebacker in a double murder.
</P>
<P>
   Rocker just gave the world a piece of his mind, an unsavory
piece to be sure. His interview-tirade in Sports Illustrated was
puerile, insulting and spiteful, but he is entitled to express his
opinions freely. All the baseball people who were appalled by his
remarks were entitled to rebuke him, but Selig overdid it.
</P>
<P>
   It has become a mark of Braves players that they handle
themselves in an exemplary fashion, both on the field and off.
Rocker plainly let his teammates down on that score, but he is
young and immature, certainly not irretrievable.
</P>
<P>
   Characteristically, the Braves organization had the good sense
to arrange a diversity- and sensitivity-training session for its
players this week. Sad to say, Rocker couldn't take part.
</P>
<P>
   But now he can rejoin the Braves at spring training camp, no
doubt wondering how he, the prodigal, will be received. The best
object lesson he could get would be their tolerance and willingness
to forgive his gratuitous slurs.
</P>
<P>
   He'll need their solidarity when the season starts and the
Braves venture to hostile ballparks.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
