<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are considering for
the Page 1 of Friday, March 3. The N.Y. Times News Service night
supervisor is Pat Ryan; phone: (888) 346-9867; e-mail:
patryan(at)nytimes.com.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   PINOCHET (London) _ Gen. Augusto Pinochet was allowed to fly
home to Chile Thursday after Britain dropped extradition
proceedings against him and put an end to his 16 months of house
arrest in England. The decision to free the 84-year-old former
dictator was announced by Home Secretary Jack Straw, who told the
House of Commons that he was ending the complex legal and judicial
case because of the failing health of Pinochet. Four European
countries had been seeking the general's extradition, with Spain
wanting him returned to Madrid to stand trial on charges of torture
dating from his 17-year rule of Chile in which more than 3,000
people died or disappeared. By Warren Hoge.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-RIGHTS (Beijing) _ The United Nations' top human rights
official expressed deep concern here Thursday over what she called
a ``deterioration'' in China's human rights practices. Her critical
assessment comes less than three weeks before the major annual U.N.
meeting on human rights, starting on March 20 in Geneva, where the
United States is offering a resolution censuring China's rights
record. By Erik Eckholm.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``w'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   HSIA-TRIAL (Washington) _ A federal jury on Thursday convicted
Maria Hsia, a longtime political fundraiser for Vice President Al
Gore, on all five felony counts she faced for her role in arranging
more than $100,000 in illegal donations to Democratic candidates in
1996. Of that amount, $55,000 came in illegal donations to the
Democratic National Committee in connection with the vice
president's much-criticized 1996 visit to a Buddhist temple in the
Los Angeles area. By Neil A. Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   SOCSEC-EARNINGS (Washington) _ With Congress and the president
about to make a major change in Social Security, a look at the end
of income restrictions for Social Security recipients. By Peter T.
Kilborn. (1200 words)
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-GUNS (Washington) _ Responding to two high-profile
incidents of gun violence this week, President Clinton said
Thursday he would call legislative leaders to the White House to
try to ``break the logjam'' on gun-control legislation that has
been tied up in Congress since last fall. The House and Senate
approved different gun-control bills after contentious debates last
year, but lawmakers in the two chambers, deeply divided on the
restrictions, have yet to reconcile them in conference. By Marc
Lacey and Eric Schmitt.
</P>
<P>
   POLITICS
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``p'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   REPUBS-DEBATE (Los Angeles) _ Sen. John McCain in St. Louis and
George W. Bush in Los Angeles face off at 9 p.m. EST. By Alison
Mitchell.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   FINANCIAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``f'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   IMF (Washington) _ Developing. The International Montetary
Fund's 24 executive directors hold an informal poll to assess
support for the three official candidates to lead the agency. By
Joseph Kahn.
</P>
<P>
   PALM-IPO (San Francisco) _ Shares of Palm Inc. surged in their
trading debut Thursday, rising as high as $165 from an offering
price of $38 before retreating. Shares in Palm's parent, 3Com
Corp., declined, although 3Com still holds 94 percent of Palm after
the offering. By Lawrence M. Fisher.
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   NY-POLICE-SHOOTING (New York) _ An unarmed Bronx man who was
fatally shot by the police Wednesday night had a long criminal
history, Mayor Rudolph Giuliani said, as he took pains to say the
shooting should not be likened to the killing of Amadou Diallo. The
latest shooting, which took place two blocks from where Diallo was
killed, ignited another round of protests as intense as those over
the Diallo shooting. In both shootings, the police were in
plainclothes and were approaching a building at night, and in both
instances the people they killed were unarmed. By Robert D.
McFadden.
</P>
</TEXT>
