<SLUG> BC-NY-POLLS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 &HT;     POLLS GIVE McCAIN THE EDGE IN N.Y. PRIMARY  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By LARA JAKES  
 &HT;     c.2000 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ For the first time, presidential hopeful John
McCain is leading in all three major New York polls among likely
Republican voters as he and George W. Bush face off in the days
before the state's March 7 primary.
</P>
<P>
   McCain, 20 points behind Bush six weeks ago, now has a 6- to
7-point lead over the Texas governor in polls released Wednesday by
Zogby International, Quinnipiac College and the Marist Institute
for Public Opinion.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the first time,'' said Quinnipiac pollster Maurice
Carroll. ``McCain was like a blip on the screen just a few months
ago. What you've got is a (GOP) establishment versus this McCain
aura.''
</P>
<P>
   In all three polls, McCain's edge was above the statistical
margin of error among likely GOP primary voters. Marist had McCain
over Bush by a 51-44 percent edge; the poll was taken Feb. 28-29
and has a margin of error of 5 percentage points.
</P>
<P>
   Quinnipiac showed McCain at 47 percent to Bush's 40 percent, in
a poll done Feb. 22-28. That poll had a 6-point margin of error.
Zogby's daily tracking survey showed McCain at 44.1 percent and
Bush at 38.4 percent, with a margin of error of 4.5 percentage
points.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's forces responded with two new ads downstate focusing on
the environment and breast cancer. Bush's state chairman, Gov.
George Pataki, also took a swing at McCain, calling the Arizona
senator's voting record as ``anti-New York, anti-Northeast as
anybody's in the country.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a difficult fight, and we appreciate that,'' Pataki
added. But voters, he said, ``are going to take a look at the
candidates and come out and vote for Governor Bush because they'll
see that he has the record and the vision for America, and Senator
McCain does not. That's what it comes down to in an election.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush's radio spot on breast cancer features survivor Geri Barish
of Long Island. The ad marks the first time Bush has attacked
McCain for voting to cut federal funding for breast cancer
research, which was included in a 2000 appropriations bill.
</P>
<P>
   McCain's camp responded by blasting Bush for distorting the
senator's record of support for breast cancer research and said he
voted against funding that was part of a ``pork barrel'' package.
</P>
<P>
   Bush took a hit for the second ad, paid for by a group called
``Republicans for Clean Air'' and touting the governor's
environmental record in Texas. The Sierra Club pronounced the
television ad ``full of half-truths.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush spokesman Ari Fletcher said the campaign had nothing to do
with the ad.
</P>
<P>
   Among likely Democratic voters polled, Vice President Al Gore is
holding on to his comfortable lead over challenger Bill Bradley,
the former senator from New Jersey. In all three surveys, Gore
carried at least a 19-point edge.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-02-00 1651EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000302.0216 </DOCNO>
