<HEADER>
A4784 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l BC-CAMPUS-MUSIC-2ND &LR;  &UR; TAK     03-02 0834
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAMPUS-MUSIC-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-ART-BOS  
 (Repeating for all needing.)  
 BOSTON: ... is authentic.''  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Kusmierz noted that as people focus more on individual freedoms
and less on how their actions affect others, the dividing line
between haves and have-nots sharpens. ``As long as large segments
of society can't realize their definitions of the good life,'' she
said, ``programs like LARC will exist.''
</P>
<P>
   The voices heard around a hospital conference table last week
were authentic, all right, painfully so. Amid the sobering talk of
viral loads and T-cell counts, though, there was also laughter. And
that constituted a learning experience in itself.
</P>
<P>
   John Miller, a LARC patient from Dorchester, glanced at Richie
Moriarity, a sophomore from Maryland, and said that if he could
give these BC kids one gift, it would be ``an awareness of drug
addiction. Because there's always a line to cross, and I crossed
it. Once you cross it, you can't come back.''
</P>
<P>
   Moriarity smiled back. ``Being at BC gives you a warped sense of
reality,'' he said softly. ``Everyone there is fortunate. Everyone
has plenty of money. It knocks me off my feet every day I come over
here. It's like _ '' Moriarity glanced around the table _ ``hel-lo,
Richie. Welcome to the real world.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   EXP 88S: Understanding the Stock Market
</P>
<P>
   Students will begin to develop an understanding of and an
appreciation for the fundamentals of stock market investing, doing
so within the realm of larger social, demographic, political, and
economic contexts.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Who knows what a margin is?'' asks Timothy Stratford in a
basement classroom of Braker Hall. ``No one?''
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-nine students sit on their hands.
</P>
<P>
   ``OK,'' says Stratford, writing ``THE MAGIC OF MARGIN'' on a
blackboard. ``Now, the whole premise of what I'm about to tell you
is that you should never do it, but it's crucial to know about.'' A
hand goes up. ``Yes?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Alan Greenspan said today he was unconcerned about margins.''
</P>
<P>
   Stratford laughs. ``Did he say why?'' he asks, tapping the
board. ``OK, here's my concern,'' continues Stratford. ``It's
buying stock with money you don't have. It's the biggest disaster
you can do. Mutual funds do it because they can get in and out of
stocks quickly. You can't. Any questions?''
</P>
<P>
   Thus began week six of an unusual course offered by Tufts
University's Experimental College. Call it Greenspan 101. From
calculating interest rates to shorting tech stocks, the course aims
to demystify the Dow while equipping students with the basics of
portfolio building. Chaucer? Organic Chem? Forget about it. The
cheer you hear is tuition-strapped parents yelling, ``Finally, a
course with a return on investment!''
</P>
<P>
   Stratford, an ex-bartender who logged 17 years as a broker, was
likewise cheered when 200 students showed up for the course last
spring, six times the number he could accommodate.
</P>
<P>
   ``The ones who don't get in beg me for a seat.'' says Stratford,
now teaching the course for the third time. ``If I were a broker
and 180 prospective clients showed up, I'd be thrilled. But I'm not
trying to sell them anything here.''
</P>
<P>
   The students, most of whom admit they don't know NASDAQ from
NASCAR, must write brief application essays. ``Like learning to fix
my car and cook a turkey,'' wrote one, ``learning about the stock
market is one of those goals that I've had for a while but haven't
gotten around to addressing.'' Gushed another, ``I only know that
those mysterious numbers that flash by right before the commercials
on the national news excite me more than any other possibility in
my life.'' Ah, youth.
</P>
<P>
   Two students have brought parents to class. Drew Carlton, a
senior from Shaker Heights, Ohio, took the course last fall. An
experienced day trader, Carlton knew as much about Internet trading
as Stratford did, maybe more. Still, says Carlton, ``I liked it
because it's a lot more relevant than most college classes. This is
something everyone should know about.''
</P>
<P>
   Jennie Robin, a senior psychology major from Long Island, knew
nothing about investing before this semester.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm about to graduate, and I thought I'd better take one
course in something relevant,'' says Robin. Her midterm assessment?
``It's given me a basis for reading the business page every day,''
she says. ``Some things are still unclear, though, like inflation
and interest rates or _ '' join the club, Jennie `` _ what actually
moves the stock market up and down.
</P>
<P>
   If Stratford preaches anything, it's the value of patience and
discipline. Strategies like dollar cost averaging _ investing small
amounts consistently to capitalize on market fluctuations _ are
emphasized over picking the next hot dot-com stock or go-go mutual
fund.
</P>
<P>
   Says Stratford, ``Some of these kids want to make money, some
have parents who think this is good stuff to know, and some want to
walk into job interviews and not sound like idiots.'' He smiles.
``I'm here to help them all.''
</P>
</TEXT>
