<SLUG> BC-GAY-CLERGY03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Religious leader fighting for gay rights to speak at rally
 &HT;    By Kathy Whyde Jesse
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ The Rev. Mel White, the gay clergyman who last
fall met with the Rev. Jerry Falwell in an effort to bridge the gap
between gays and religious conservatives, will speak at a Dayton
rally March 11.
</P>
<P>
   The rally, sponsored by a coalition of local gay and lesbian
advocacy groups, also will include Dayton City Commissioner Mary
Wiseman, who last year led an unsuccessful attempt to amend the
city's anti-discrimination ordinance to include gays, the poor and
Appalachians.
</P>
<P>
   The Soulforce Justice Rally, at Faith United Church of Christ,
takes its name from White's national effort to promote nonviolent
gay advocacy efforts. It includes workshops, videos and a Web site,
www.soulforce.org.
</P>
<P>
   White, 60, a former ghostwriter for Falwell and Pat Robertson,
is a minister with the Metropolitan Community Church. In October,
after his meetings with Falwell at his church in Lynchburg, Va.,
Falwell pledged to tone down his anti-gay rhetoric, although he
still maintains that homosexuality is a sin. In November, White was
arrested outside a church in Nebraska, where he led a protest in
support of the Rev. Jimmy Creech, who was cut off from the United
Methodist Church for presiding at the union of a gay couple.
</P>
<P>
   The Dayton event has been organized by Faith Church, Parents and
Friends of Lesbians and Gays, the Dayton Lesbian and Gay Center,
and other churches that are supportive of the gay community.
</P>
<P>
   It comes on the heels of the December defeat of Wiseman's
amendment, and the realization that the gay community needs to
build bridges between the black community and the faith community,
according to Wiseman. Her amendment faced strong opposition by
black clergy.
</P>
<P>
   She has not ruled out proposing the amendment again, in a form
that might be more acceptable to its detractors. ``We continue to
try to keep the dialogue going,'' she said. ``We understand there's
a lot of work to be done.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
