<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-02 16:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4787 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l BC-BEEKEPING-HOBBYISTS-A     03-02 1496
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BEEKEPING-HOBBYISTS-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
888-603-1036.)  
 FOR ENTHUSIASTS, BEEKEEPING IS AN ESCAPE INTO SERENITY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating for all needing.)  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 888-346-9867 or (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LINDA MATCHAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   KINGSTON, Mass. _ Spring is hardly in the air, but bee school is
already up and, well, buzzing.
</P>
<P>
   Some 50 beekeepers and beekeeping wannabees have gathered at a
local community center for a session, ``The Life Cycle of the Honey
Bee.'' You can almost hear the hum in the air, the anticipation of
bee season, which begins in earnest next month when bees come out
of their hives and embrace spring.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm here to talk about our favorite insect, the honeybee,''
says the guest lecturer, Marshfield beekeeper Vicki McDonough.
Notebooks fall open and ballpoint pens click. Nobody says they
prefer the rival bumblebee, for example, or perhaps the yellow
jacket.
</P>
<P>
   No, in this crowd, honeybees R them.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, honeybees R a lot of people these days.
</P>
<P>
   While this particular bee school _ a seven-week introduction to
beekeeping _ is sponsored by the Plymouth County Beekeepers
Association, interest in beekeeping seems to be growing across the
country. County bee clubs in Massachusetts report rising
memberships. Subscriptions to American Bee Journal _ the
Illinois-based trade magazine for beekeepers _ are up.
</P>
<P>
   What's the attraction to bees? It's not an economic interest,
that's for sure. A serious nationwide problem with
honeybee-attacking mites over the last decade has discouraged many
professional beekeepers who were involved in beekeeping for honey
production or who managed colonies for crop pollination.
</P>
<P>
   Rather, more and more, ``it's people interested in doing it
recreationally,'' says Joe Graham, editor of the American Bee
Journal.
</P>
<P>
   They're people interested in what Howard Scott, who runs the
Kingston bee school and has published a small volume called ``Bee
Lessons,'' describes as ``the poetical wonder of bees.'' He's seen
folks who ``are tired of the rat race'' discover a meditative,
Zen-like quality in this hobby rooted in nature and the outdoors
and the community that bees create.
</P>
<P>
   One of Scott's students, Lou Eyster, runs an insurance agency in
Framingham and owns three hives at home in Norwell. Sure, the
honey's sweet, he says, but that's not why he raises bees. ``To be
honest, it's an escape,'' he says. ``It relaxes me. I'm fascinated
by the bees, and at the same time, you don't have to deal with a
lot of people. You go out there and watch them bring in the pollen,
and nobody bothers me.''
</P>
<P>
   Kim Hatton of Pembroke plans to start up two hives, not only to
pollinate her flowers and create more robust blooms but also
because, quite simply, she admires honeybees: ``I like the idea of
natural creatures that give something back by pollinating.'' With
their well-defined division of labor, their regal leadership, and
their furious work ethic, she says, honeybees have invented ``a
perfect society.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no handouts,'' she says. ``If you don't participate,
there is no point in having you.''
</P>
<P>
   Birgit Deweerd of Bedford, vice president of the Middlesex
County Beekeepers Association and a recreational beekeeper,
describes her infatuation with the insects in her self-published
book ``Let Me Tell You About the Bees'' and lectures about bees at
garden clubs and schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you know that if you move a hive a few inches to the side,
the bees won't find their way back?'' she asks. ``They are so
oriented to the original spot. If you know their way of life, you
can anticipate their behavior and treat them like a bunch of farm
animals.''
</P>
<P>
   Because of the informal nature of beekeeping, there are no
statistics on how many people are suiting themselves up in
protective bee veils and tending hives. You don't need a license to
be a beekeeper, just some basic equipment like a standard wooden
beehive, a single, all-purpose tool that pries open the hive cover
and pulls out the frames, and a package of mail-order bees.
</P>
<P>
   Beekeeping is not a particularly expensive hobby. For $46, you
can buy a package of 3,000 bees, including a queen, and a starter
hobby kit in a beekeeping catalog sells for $109.95.
</P>
<P>
   Nor is beekeeping time-consuming. Scott calls it ``the lazy
man's hobby'' because all an amateur beekeeper needs to do is
medicate the bees against mites and observe the hive now and then
to be sure the eggs are healthy and the bees thriving. ``The bees
do all the work,'' he says. ``You just go out in September and
extract the honey.''
</P>
<P>
   For many of today's beekeepers, tending hives and observing
honeybee activity is ``kind of a therapy,'' says Al Carl, chief
apiary inspector for the state of Massachusetts. ``It's a
back-to-the-earth thing,'' he says. With bees, ``You are dealing
with a population that is not going to say to you `Have a nice
day.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Gail Anderson-Dargatz understands this phenomenon so well she
has written a novel about it, ``A Recipe for Bees'' (Harmony
Books), which was published last month in the United States and a
year ago in Canada, where it was well received.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson-Dargatz is married to a beekeeper, and her novel
describes a character whose bees ``were more a calling than an
occupation,'' whose bookshelves were filled with ``books about the
art of beekeeping, the biology of bees, myths and legends
associated with bees.''
</P>
<P>
   She was surprised by how much the book's beekeeping passages
resonated with readers. ``When I was giving readings from my book,
there seemed to be a whole lot of people coming to see me who were
involved in beekeeping, and they spoke about it not in farming
terms but in poetic terms,'' she says in a telephone interview from
her home in British Columbia. ``They used a lot of metaphor, almost
as if I was discussing beekeeping with a poet. After all, handling
the hive is about engaging all five senses. On a winter's day when
the sun comes out, they fly out and look like these wonderful amber
jewels.''
</P>
<P>
   Scott, the freelance writer and small-scale beekeeper who
organized the Plymouth County bee school, is also taken with the
poetry of bees. ``Bee Lessons,'' which he published himself last
year, is an imaginative interpretation of things he has learned
from observing the insects, with 41 conclusions or bee lessons, as
he calls them. These include: ``It's satisfying to work for the
greater good''; ``By dividing up the work, more gets done''; and
``Produce more heirs than you need to insure survival.''
</P>
<P>
   Initially, Scott thought the book would do well at state fairs
and beekeeping meetings, but it turns out urban folks like it, too.
He printed 3,000 copies and ``I'm close to sold out,'' he says,
with many sales made at bookstores in Cambridge. To be sure, he
heard from one woman who acknowledged she bought it because its
bright yellow cover matched her kitchen. But more typical, he says,
is the feedback he got from a minister ``who called up and said,
`There are 50 sermons in this book.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Scott, 55, started keeping bees nearly 20 years ago, and now ``I
seem to have become the person I dreaded I'd become'' _ the
beekeeping equivalent, he says, of the railroad buff who can't stop
talking timetables.
</P>
<P>
   ``My excuse is I like it more and more,'' he says. ``Beekeeping
is a strange world and a different world, with all different values
and constructs.''
</P>
<P>
   He's a Wharton-trained economist who for a dozen years owned a
Quincy office supply business. There are many parallels, he says,
between the beehive and the business world.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is the way they all work for the good of the hive, for
example,'' he says. ``Bees actually wear their wings out in the
summer, and will sting when the hive is threatened, and die for
it.'' There is their strong sense of community, for example, their
industriousness, and their tendency to move around the corporation.
Every worker bee does many jobs during a lifetime, from cleaning
cells to processing honey to foraging for nectar and pollen. (Bee
Lesson 9: ``The best way to achieve job satisfaction is variety.'')
</P>
<P>
   Now, like most of his students, Scott's thoughts are turning to
spring. Once in a while, he goes to his backyard and puts his ear
to his hives to hear that reassuring faint hum that means his bees
have made it through the winter.
</P>
<P>
   ``Besides robins and croci, bees are an important sign of
spring,'' he writes in his book. ``Sightings of active bees
proclaim that the insects have made it through another harsh winter
and that the greening of the countryside will soon begin.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Bee Lesson 40: Ah bees, Ah life.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Most counties in Massachusetts have bee associations and bee
schools. For information, contact the Massachusetts Department of
Food and Agriculture's bureau of farm products and plant industry
at 617 626-1802.)
</P>
</TEXT>
