<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Guide gives a big boost to natural wonders of the Southeast
 &HT;    By Howard Pousner
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   When the National Fish and Wildlife Foundation published its
first Directory of Birding and Nature Festivals in 1995, it listed
about two dozen events. This year, the 76-page guide lists more
than 200 events nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   The growth, says Peter Stangel, director of the foundation's
regional office in Atlanta, mirrors mushrooming interest in birding
and nature.
</P>
<P>
   ``Festivals are a win-win for people and birds,'' he says,
referring to the knowledge festivalgoers gain about the natural
world that surrounds us and the festival proceeds that typically
benefit conservation.
</P>
<P>
   That's the case with the Florida Birding Festival and Nature
Expo in Clearwater, Fla., which has earmarked $20,000 in proceeds
to help Pinellas County secure Shell Key. The pristine, 180-acre
barrier island, at the mouth of Tampa Bay on the Gulf of Mexico, is
home to countless varieties of shorebirds.
</P>
<P>
   Here's the listing of upcoming Southeastern events from the 2000
directory:
</P>
<P>
   ARKANSAS
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  March 31-April 12, Bismarck: 11th Annual Beaks&AMP;Bills _
Feathers&AMP;Quills. Bird feeding programs, bird walks, evening
programs and lake tours. Contact: DeGray Lake Resort State Park,
501-865-2801; www.degray.com
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  June 10-11, Paris: Mount Magazine International Butterfly
Festival. Butterfly gardens, explanations of butterfly ecology and
life stages, wildflowers planting and a guided catch-and-release
session for all ages. Contact: Paris Area Chamber of Commerce,
1-800-980-8660; www.paris-ar.com
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Oct. 13-15, Bismarck: Autumn Avian Affair at DeGray Lake
Resort State Park. Bird feeding programs, bird walks, owl prowls
and lake tours to see wintering bald eagles. Call 501-865-2801;
www.degray.com
</P>
