<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONA-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`DROWNING MONA': CAUTION: FALLING YUGO ZONE AHEAD 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: Production notes at end of review) 
(jt) 
 By ELVIS MITCHELL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the pulpy comedy ``Drowning Mona,'' Bette Midler, as Mona
Dearly, looks a mess, with a dye job the color of Tang, similar to
the faded taffy hue of the Yugos that dot the front yards of
Verplanck, the tiny upstate New York town where the movie is set. A
series of crude shots _ some of which are very funny _that pop the
small cast of yokels right between the eyes, ``Mona'' is a dreary
crash of malapropisms and slapstick maimings wrapped very loosely
around a murder mystery.
</P>
<P>
   Mona is sent to her doom in a brakeless Yugo launched off a
mountain road. (Someone may have believed that ``Hurtling Mona''
wasn't as good a title.) Mona was meaner than a werewolf under a
full moon; she drew blood every time she opened her mouth. (Her
last name was a bad joke.) So many people in town dearly wished her
dead that even in this little burg there's no shortage of suspects.
</P>
<P>
   ``Drowning Mona'' is kind of a mystery, although the real
mystery is that anybody cares enough to find out who killed her.
Leading the investigation is Chief Wyatt Rash (Danny DeVito), the
constable with a keen interest in Broadway musicals. The film
reunites him with Midler, his ``Ruthless People'' co-star, but this
time around he's the only person who didn't want the victim dead.
(He seems to be the only reasonable person in town.)
</P>
<P>
   The real victims here are the characters, who've been impaled on
their own Herculean pursuit of bad taste. Three Dog Night songs
have been unleashed on the soundtrack, which must have been scored
by K-Tel record company.
</P>
<P>
   And there are more bad hair days than you'd see at a monster
truck rally. William Fichtner, whose turn as a voluble strong-arm
cop was one of the many acting high points in last year's film
``Go,'' is Mona's husband. His bravery as an actor is heartening.
</P>
<P>
   Fichtner's hair is teased into a gruesome tumbleweed; he wears
one of those '70s white-guy Afros with mutton-chop sideburns
obscuring the sides of his face. He must have taken his ladykiller
look from a Tom Jones album cover, or at the very least from
Engelbert Humperdinck. He regards everything with the same
intensity, including an episode of the television show ``Cops'' he
watches while being tongue-lashed by his wife. ``They've cornered
the shooter,'' he says, incredulously.
</P>
<P>
   The director, Nick Gomez, is working in a much more
conventionally structured narrative situation than he has in his
previous pictures (``New Jersey Drive,'' ``Laws of Gravity''). It's
not enough that the film is full of soiled white trash. Almost
everyone in ``Drowning Mona'' is dumber than he needs to be,
resulting in several different types of slack-jawed stumblebums.
</P>
<P>
   Marcus Thomas, who plays Mona's son, Jeff, is the film's most
idiotic character. Having lost a hand in a way that's as mysterious
as Mona's murderer, Jeff is seen at one point trying to strum a
guitar with his stump. The laughs can come fairly quickly, mostly
at Jeff's expense. Then there's Bobby Calzone (well played Casey
Affleck), Jeff's partner in a landscaping business in which Jeff's
participation comes mostly in the form of making fun of Bobby's
sensitivity, especially toward his fiancee, Ellie (Neve Campbell).
</P>
<P>
   Everything in the movie is treated as an object for gags, and
that includes the cast. The movie goes beyond antisentimentality,
really. This may be an efficient way to make a comedy, but it's not
heartless enough.
</P>
<P>
   Rating: ``Drowning Mona'' is rated PG-13 (Parents strongly
cautioned). It includes violence, angry adult language and cruelty
to small animals.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `DROWNING MONA'
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Nick Gomez; written by Peter Steinfeld; director of
photography, Bruce Douglas Johnson; edited by Richard Pearson;
music by Michael Tavera; production designer, Richard Toyon;
produced by Al Corley, Bart Roseblatt and Eugene Musso; released by
Destination Films. Running time: 90 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Cast: Danny DeVito (Chief Rash), Bette Midler (Mona Dearly),
Neve Campbell (Ellen), Jamie Lee Curtis (Rona), Casey Affleck
(Bobby), William Fichtner (Phil Dearly), Marcus Thomas (Jeff
Dearly) and Peter Dobson (Feege).
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
