<DOCNO> NYT20000302.0224 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-02 17:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4796 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-ANTIQUES-COLUMN-2TAKE     03-02 0673
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANTIQUES-COLUMN-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RARAE AVES: AUDUBON AT AUCTION 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By WENDY MOONAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``The climate in Scotland is very good for books,'' Francis
Wahlgren, the head of Christie's books department in New York, said
with a smile. ``It's damp and cold.''
</P>
<P>
   He was commenting on the the fine condition of four giant
volumes of John James Audubon's ``Birds of America,'' which had
been in a Scottish house since 1909 before being consigned to
Christie's.
</P>
<P>
   The leather-bound set is the star lot in Christie's March 10
sale, ``Important Natural History Books.'' It took Audubon 11
years, from 1827 to 1838, to publish the 435 hand-colored, etched
and aquatinted plates in these volumes.
</P>
<P>
   The set will be on view Saturday through Thursday, and even an
amateur can see that the color is vibrant and there has been little
deterioration.
</P>
<P>
   The set is known as a ``double elephant'' because of the size of
its sheets of thick rag paper: each sheet measures 39{ by 19{
inches.
</P>
<P>
   ``These were the largest single sheets produced at the time,''
Wahlgren said. Audubon insisted on this size because he wanted the
birds to be depicted life size. ``You can almost feel the feathers
on these birds,'' he said. ``These plates are the icons of
ornithology.''
</P>
<P>
   Bird books have been published at least since the 16th century,
but in terms of sheer artistry almost nothing can match Audubon's
``Birds of America,'' except, perhaps, Audubon's original
watercolors, which are in the permanent collection of the New-York
Historical Society.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was a master of brilliant color, detail and lifelike
movement,'' said Angela D. Mack, a curator at the Gibbes Museum of
Art in Charleston, S.C., who has organized a show of 42 original
Audubon watercolors from the society's collection, opening at the
Gibbes on March 31. ``Audubon is known for his innovative style of
combining a range of different techniques and mediums.''
</P>
<P>
   It was not easy for Audubon to sell his engravings in the early
1800s. Nor was it easy to buy them. His original clients had to
subscribe to a series to receive his bird plates, and they were
delivered in installments, five engravings at a time. Wahlgren said
a shipment usually included one very large bird, one medium-size
bird and three small birds.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a subscriber, you would have had to put in the equivalent
of $1,000, which at that time would have been a lot of money, for a
set, before binding,'' Wahlgren said. Each plate was meticulously
engraved after Audubon's watercolor drawings by William H. Lizars
of Edinburgh or by Robert Havell Sr. and Jr. of London. A few
colors could then be applied by aquatint, and the rest were
hand-painted.
</P>
<P>
   The man who ordered the four-volume set now at Christie's was
George Lane Fox of Yorkshire, England, a friend of the prince
regent whose greatest interests apart from birds were racing and
gambling. The Audubon set remained in his family until 1909 and
then went to John, Fourth Marquess of Bute, whose son is consigning
the present set.
</P>
<P>
   Other subscribers to the original edition included Charles X of
France, Queen Adelaide of Britain (wife of William IV), Earl
Spencer and several Americans: Daniel Webster, P.J. Stuyvesant,
John P. Wetherells and Henry Clay. Only about 200 double-elephant
sets were made; at least 70 have been destroyed. They rarely come
up for sale.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't seen a complete set in seven years,'' Wahlgren said.
``The last complete copy that came up for auction was in 1993 here
at Christie's, and it sold for about $3 million. The record price
for a full set is $4 million.'' The estimate for this set is $2
million to $4 million.
</P>
<P>
   Over the years double-elephant sets have been broken up, and
individual sheets are sold at art galleries for $2,500 to $150,000.
``Birds of America'' was later reissued in smaller-format volumes
known as octavo editions, some of which are also in Christie's
March 10 sale, at estimates a fraction of the double-elephant
set's.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   ``No copy surpasses the first,'' Wahlgren explained.
</P>
<P>
   Audubon was preoccupied with birds practically from birth.
</P>
<P>
   He was born in 1785 in Haiti, the son of a French captain who
was an agent for a French mercantile company and his Creole
mistress. Less than a year after his birth, his mother died, and
his father took him back to Nantes, France, to be raised by his
wife.
</P>
<P>
   He was legally adopted but received only a minimal education. He
spent most of his time collecting bird specimens in the countryside
for stuffing and drawing. He was a self-taught artist.
</P>
<P>
   In 1803 the family's fortunes declined. Napoleon was seeking
army conscripts, so Audubon, then 18, is said to have fled with his
father to America. They settled in Pennsylvania. In 1808 he married
the daughter of a wealthy neighbor and moved to Louisville, Ky. He
tried his luck as a merchant but failed.
</P>
<P>
   He became obsessed with the exotic birds he found in the
wilderness and devised a method to mount the birds on wires to draw
them in more lifelike poses.
</P>
<P>
   ``He propped them in positions they would never have had in
nature,'' Wahlgren said. ``But you do get a feeling of movement and
life in them.'' Audubon drew his birds out in the field, depicting
them on branches of native American plants. Both plants and birds
are identified in the plates by their Latin and common names.
</P>
<P>
   Occasionally he would add a view of the site, even an American
city, in the background. ``These were artistic decisions, and it
makes the compositions more interesting,'' Wahlgren said.
</P>
<P>
   In 1820 Audubon went bankrupt and left for Louisiana on a
flatboat. He worked as an itinerant artist, doing mostly portraits
and leaving his wife to support and raise their two sons.
</P>
<P>
   He seems to have come into his own as a painter of birds while
working in Mississippi and Louisiana, but he was unable to get his
work published in America. In 1826 he traveled to England to find a
publisher.
</P>
<P>
   Portraying himself as an American woodsman, he won support from
British ornithologists who admired his work and from titled
families who enjoyed listening to his lectures and seeing his
frontier costumes.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was a 19th-century romantic figure, creator of his own
myth, an artist-naturalist, an artist explorer, an
artist-publisher, an entrepreneur, a writer and an
environmentalist,'' said Holly Hotchner, a former director of the
New-York Historical Society's museum.
</P>
<P>
   In time he succeeded in selling subscriptions to his bird series
to the families in the great English country houses. Having secured
an engraver, he returned to America to continue drawing and
painting.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1830s he visited South Carolina, often staying with the
Rev. John Bachman in Charleston. Bachman's sister-in-law, Maria
Martin, helped him paint in the backgrounds.
</P>
<P>
   It is the 42 watercolors of South Carolina birds that the Gibbes
Museum will show later this month. Mack, the curator, said she
planned to show the original drawings next to a double-elephant
folio on loan from the College of Charleston so visitors can
compare the originals to the engravings.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted to show where the books come from,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-02-00 1706EST &QL; 
