u e BC-ALBUM-OF-THE-WEEK-NYT     03-02 0155
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ALBUM-OF-THE-WEEK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPOTLIGHT ON A NEW ALBUM 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By JOHN PARELES   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   AMEL LARRIEUX: ``Infinite Possibilities'' (Epic/550 Music).
</P>
<P>
   Undulating vamps, the glassy tinkle of electric piano and
playful phantom choruses surround Amel Larrieux on her debut album.
</P>
<P>
   Larrieux, who sang with Groove Theory in the mid-1990s, is part
of the high-minded pop-soul movement spearheaded by Erykah Badu and
Lauryn Hill.
</P>
<P>
   In songs she wrote and produced with her husband, Laru Larrieux,
she sings about ambition, loneliness, reclaiming self-esteem and
staying true to her soul; her syncopated phrasing links the songs
to jazz or gospel.
</P>
<P>
   But the sparse, coolly synthetic production _ some songs barely
state the beat _ places Larrieux's supple, girlish voice in an
inner domain that's all her own, where her prismatically multiplied
voice offers counsel and comfort.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-02-00 1706EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
