<DOCNO> NYT20000302.0227 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-02 17:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4805 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i BC-PINOCHET-ART-1000(2TA     03-02 1044
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PINOCHET-ART-1000(2TAKES)-(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRITAIN ALLOWS PINOCHET TO RETURN TO CHILE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
(js) 
 By WARREN HOGE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ Gen. Augusto Pinochet was allowed to fly home to Chile
Thursday after Britain dropped extradition proceedings against him
and put an end to his 16 months of house arrest in England.
</P>
<P>
   A Chilean military plane lifted off from Waddington Royal Air
Force Base in Lincolnshire at 1:10 p.m., just hours after the
decision to free the 84-year-old former Chilean dictator was
announced by Home Secretary Jack Straw.
</P>
<P>
   Straw told the House of Commons that he was ending the complex
legal and judicial case because of the failing health of Pinochet.
Four European countries had been seeking the general's extradition,
with Spain wanting him returned to Madrid to stand trial on charges
of torture dating from his authoritarian rule of Chile from 1973-90
in which more than 3,000 people died or disappeared.
</P>
<P>
   In letters to ambassadors of the four countries released
Thursday morning, Straw argued that the general's declining health
had produced a ``memory deficit'' that would have compromised his
ability to understand charges and direct his attorneys.
</P>
<P>
   ``With these impediments, Senator Pinochet would be unable to
follow the process of a trial sufficiently to instruct counsel,''
Straw said in his letter to the Spanish mission.
</P>
<P>
   ``He would have had difficulty in understanding the content and
the implications of questions put to him and would have inadequate
insight into this difficulty,'' the letter continued. ``He would
have difficulty in making himself understood in replying to
questions.''
</P>
<P>
   The Pinochet case will be remembered and cited long after its
swift and undramatic end Thursday. Its most significant legacy is a
fundamental change in international law that gives universal
jurisdiction to the prosecution of crimes that are considered human
rights atrocities.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has established beyond question the principle that those
who commit human rights abuses in one country cannot assume they
are safe elsewhere,'' Straw told parliament.
</P>
<P>
   Straw had first signaled his intention to make Thursday's move
in January after medical tests conducted by four British
specialists claimed that the general was unfit to stand trial.
Spain, France, Belgium and Switzerland challenged that finding, and
Straw was subsequently ordered by a three-judge panel of Britain's
High Court to send the four governments the records of the
examination.
</P>
<P>
   None of the governments or human rights organizations that had
mounted legal challenges to Pinochet's release pressed to bring an
appeal in the scant time available before Pinochet could leave
Britain.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   There was clearly an effort to get him out of the country with
as little attention as possible. A convoy of police vehicles and
motorcycle outriders escorted the limousine carrying the former
Chilean dictator from the suburban enclave south of London where he
had been living and sped the 150-mile distance to the airbase.
</P>
<P>
   Pinochet left the Surrey residential estate south of London by a
road that skirted the main exit, where protesters and the press
were camped out.
</P>
<P>
   In 5 a.m. darkness, the Chilean Air Force Boeing 707 that had
been parked at Brize Norton Royal Air Force Base in Oxfordshire
since late January flew unannounced to the Waddington field.
</P>
<P>
   In two decisions, the Law Lords of the House of Lords, Britain's
highest court, ruled that Pinochet was not immune from prosecution
even though he was head of state at the time that the alleged
crimes against humanity took place.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   To rights groups, the rulings that emerged in the Pinochet case
amounted to a coming of age for international law, a framework that
has gradually shifted from the notion that states do not interfere
in each other's affairs to a belief that human rights transcend
domestic jurisdictions. Amnesty International said Thursday that
the case represented the greatest advance for international law
since the Nuremberg trials.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a terrible disappointment for Pinochet's thousands of
victims that he will not face trial in Spain,'' said Reed Brody,
advocacy director of the New York-based Human Rights Watch, which
has been among the groups pursuing the case. ``But the very fact
that he was arrested and that his claim of immunity was rejected
has already changed the calculus of dictators around the world. The
Pinochet case signified the beginning of the end of their
impunity''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   That new principle has already seen its first application. Last
month, the former president of Chad, Hissene Habre, was arrested in
Senegal where he has been living in exile since 1990 and charged
with responsibility for political killings, torture and the
disappearances of opponents. The human rights groups that assembled
the evidence against Habre said they were drawing on the legal
precedent established in the Pinochet case.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Pinochet was originally arrested on Oct. 16, 1998, while he was
in a London clinic recuperating from back surgery. British police
made their surprise move in response to an application from a
Spanish judge, Baltasar Garzon, seeking Pinochet's extradition to
Madrid to stand trial on charges of genocide, torture, kidnapping
and murder in connection with the disappearance of 3,197 people in
the years after he seized power in a coup in 1973.
</P>
<P>
   Garzon, considered something of a maverick in the Spanish
judiciary, had gathered his evidence during an investigation into
the so-called dirty wars in Latin America in the 1970s. There was
no expectation at the time that his unorthodox move to arrest
Pinochet would succeed.
</P>
<P>
   The Spanish government, though forced by circumstance to pursue
the case, has shown little enthusiasm for the case from the outset,
and Spain's prime minister, Jose Maria Aznar, said Thursday that,
``I will respect Straw's decision.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Pinochet won his first legal battle to overcome the charges in a
ruling by the High Court, which upheld his claim to sovereign
immunity.
</P>
<P>
   But in a ruling that was to create the case's legacy, the Law
Lords later overturned that decision, saying that being a head of
state did not excuse crimes against humanity.
</P>
<P>
   The case returned to the House of Lords after one of the
original judges, Leonard Hoffmann., was found to have had an
association with Amnesty International, a party to the case.
</P>
<P>
   But the second Lords' decision, on March 24, 1999, was even more
emphatic on the principle than the first, although it drastically
reduced the number of charges, narrowing the scope to torture and
conspiracy to torture. The case then moved on to the validity of
the actual extradition order itself, which was upheld by a London
magistrate last October and remained under appeal with a hearing
scheduled for this March 20.
</P>
<P>
   In the one appearance in court that Pinochet was obliged to
make, on Dec. 11, 1998, he maintained the defiant attitude he had
adopted from the beginning, saying that he did not recognize the
jurisdiction of any court outside Chile to try him and that he was
innocent of ``all the lies of Spain.'' He later described himself
as ``England's only political prisoner.''
</P>
<P>
   At every hearing and court date, throngs of supporters and
opponents have angrily faced down one another from behind
barricades, trading taunts and jeers and displaying flags and
placards with accusatory slogans and pictures of missing friends
and relatives.
</P>
<P>
   For the past 15 months, the general has been living under 24
hour police custody with his wife Lucia in a rented mansion in one
of London's exclusive southern suburbs. He has had periodic visits
from Chilean supporters and other backers in this country, the most
visible and voluble of whom has been former Prime Minister Margaret
Thatcher.
</P>
<P>
   She has argued that rather than holding him in custody, Britain
should extend its gratitude to Pinochet for the support he gave the
country in 1982 during the Falkland Islands war with Argentina.
``His reward by this government,'' she told reporters Thursday on
the steps of her Belgravia home, ``was to be held prisoner for 16
months.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
