<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-02 17:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4810 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-TV-WEEKEND-NYT &LR;      03-02 1035
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-WEEKEND-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`IF THESE WALLS COULD TALK 2': THROUGH THE YEARS, WOMEN WHO LOVE
WOMEN 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: Production notes are at end of review)  
 (af)  
 By CARYN JAMES   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   With white hair pinned on top of her head in old-fashioned
braids, Vanessa Redgrave gives one of the most exquisitely
understated performances of her career as a lesbian bereft of her
house as well as her heart's love when her partner dies.
</P>
<P>
   Though Marian Seldes is only on screen for four minutes in this
first segment of the trilogy ``If These Walls Could Talk 2,'' she
is every bit as eloquent as the lover whose relationship remains a
social taboo in their day, 1961.
</P>
<P>
   And Chloe Sevigny, in the segment set in 1972, is also
mesmerizing as a radically different character, a shirt-and-tie
wearing woman ostracized by lesbian feminists at the local college
who think she is selling out to the male world. In this layered,
sophisticated performance, Sevigny does not act like a man, but a
woman acting like a man.
</P>
<P>
   These matchless performances soar above the movie's predictable,
agitprop writing and self-satisfied attitude. The film, about three
lesbian couples, is a sequel to HBO's 1996 trilogy about abortion,
which was far more powerful dramatically (and remains its
highest-rated original movie).
</P>
<P>
   Like its predecessor, ``If These Walls Could Talk 2'' concerns
women who live in the same house at different times. Yet as it
moves from the delicate Redgrave story to the more daring Sevigny
era and on to the present, in which Ellen DeGeneres and Sharon
Stone play a couple who want a child, each segment becomes more
didactic and proud of its very existence. It would be easier to
praise ``If These Walls Could Talk 2'' if the film weren't so eager
to praise itself.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, the best segment comes first. With her Valkyrie
stride and demure housedresses, Redgrave's Edith is a picture of
dignity. Seldes, better known for playing witty divas, creates a
rich character in just a few perfectly created scenes here. In a
Dutch-boy haircut and pants, her Abby is a sweet-natured
bird-watcher.
</P>
<P>
   The film opens with the women at the movies holding hands as
they watch the scene in ``The Children's Hour'' in which Shirley
Maclaine is horrified to realize she may, after all, be in love
with Audrey Hepburn. They walk home to the house they have shared
for 30 years and Edith makes tea while Abby fills a bird feeder in
the yard, creating a picture of such tender domesticity and
devotion that when Abby has a stroke and dies, viewers are likely
to feel the loss along with Edith.
</P>
<P>
   But that is when the episode, written and directed by Jane
Anderson (``The Baby Dance''), becomes blunt and begins to demonize
heterosexual society. Abby's nephew has inherited the house, which
was in his aunt's name, and Edith is cruelly dispossessed even
though she has paid half of the mortgage.
</P>
<P>
   The nephew's materialistic wife rushes through the house
claiming precious figurines of birds from Abby's collection. Their
young daughter is sympathetic to Edith, clumsily making the point
that bias is taught, not innate.
</P>
<P>
   But through it all, Redgrave is a wonder of restraint. Though
Edith keeps her anger under wraps, we can see on Redgrave's
impassive face how deep her pain goes. When she sings ``Bye Bye
Blackbird'' over the image of an empty room at the end, she has
earned this heartbreaking moment and the audience's understanding.
</P>
<P>
   That first segment works because viewers feel inside the
characters' lives as well as their house. The second and third
stories feel voyeuristic, and not only because there they include
detailed sex scenes. Psychologically, we are looking at these
people from the outside, peering in through the window.
</P>
<P>
   The 1972 segment makes the point that prejudice exists even
within minority groups. Michelle Williams of ``Dawson's Creek''
plays Linda, a college student who goes with her lesbian housemates
to a local bar, where they scorn Amy ( Sevigny) and other
masculine-looking women. It is unsurprising that Linda falls for
Amy and learns it's OK to be tolerant of other kinds of lesbians.
</P>
<P>
   But Sevigny is fascinating to watch in a role that is the flip
side of the one she plays in ``Boys Don't Cry.'' In that film (for
which she got an Academy Award nomination), she is a young woman
who falls for a woman masquerading as a man.
</P>
<P>
   Here she is in the male role, with men's clothes, a motorcycle
and slicked-back Elvis hair. But with her shoulders held up broadly
and her pelvis thrust out, her exaggerated body language makes it
clear that Amy is a woman, not a woman trying to pass as a man.
</P>
<P>
   The third episode, written and directed by Anne Heche, is
strained and precious, and so overshadowed by her highly publicized
real-life relationship with DeGeneres that the segment seems one
more move in their personal public relations campaign. DeGeneres
and Stone's characters visit a sperm bank, try to buy sperm over
the Internet and sterilize a turkey baster, yet never escape their
real-life personalities.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hate that I can't get you pregnant,'' DeGeneres says. She is
so smug and pleased with herself for saying it that the character
disappears. Stone acts giddy in a role that seems its own public
relations gambit: she is Sharon Stone the movie star lending her
clout to an enlightened cause.
</P>
<P>
   The sex scenes in these last two segments are calculated to draw
attention as they head toward that murky line between respectable
cable and cable-in-the-middle-of-the-night. But the point the film
tries to make in its heavy-handed way is not about sex. HBO has
been promoting ``The Sopranos'' with a tag line that suits this
film better: ``Family Redefined.''
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES &QL;
</P>
<P>
   `IF THESE WALLS COULD TALK 2' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   HBO, Sunday night at 9
</P>
<P>
   Written by Jane Anderson, Sylvia and Alex Sichel and Anne Heche;
Anderson, Martha Coolidge and Heche, directors. A Team Todd
production. Ellen DeGeneres, Suzanne Todd and Jennifer Todd,
executive producers.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: Vanessa Redgrave (Edith), Marian Seldes (Abby), Michelle
Williams (Linda), Chloe Sevigny (Amy), Sharon Stone (Fran) and
Ellen DeGeneres (Kal).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-02-00 1718EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000302.0231 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-02 17:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4811 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-CHINA-RIGHTS-450&AMP;ADD-     03-02 0835
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-RIGHTS-450&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.N. OFFICIAL CONCERNED ABOUT HUMAN RIGHTS ABUSES IN CHINA 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By ERIK ECKHOLM   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING _ The United Nations' top human rights official
expressed deep concern here Thursday over what she called a
``deterioration'' in China's human rights practices.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am concerned about three areas: freedom of expression,
freedom of religion and freedom of association,'' said Mary
Robinson, the high commissioner for human rights, at a news
conference following meetings with senior Chinese officials.
</P>
<P>
   Her critical assessment came less than three weeks before the
annual session of the U.N. Human Rights Commission, starting on
March 20 in Geneva, where the United States is offering a
resolution censuring China's rights record.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson declined to comment on the resolution. Her remarks here
may bolster the U.S. case, but the resolution has little chance of
passing, diplomats say, because China can muster a majority of
countries to oppose it as unwarranted meddling in its internal
affairs.
</P>
<P>
   In meetings Thursday with Deputy Prime Minister Qian Qichen and
other officials, Robinson presented her concerns about developments
over the last year and a half. These included the arrests and
lengthy prison sentences given to democracy advocates, what
Robinson termed ``a notable clampdown on religious expression,''
and the repression of labor organizers and the Falun Gong spiritual
movement.
</P>
<P>
   She gave the Chinese government a written report detailing
violations of international rights standards and listing numerous
individuals who have been imprisoned without fair legal procedures.
</P>
<P>
   At about the same time that Robinson spoke, the Foreign Ministry
said in a regular press briefing that only the people of China had
the right to judge whether their rights were worsening or
improving. ``The Chinese people are satisfied'' with the freedoms
they enjoy, said a ministry spokesman, Zhu Bangzhao, calling on the
high commissioner to cooperate with China ``on the basis of mutual
respect.''
</P>
<P>
   Robinson, a former president of Ireland, was clearly mindful of
China's prickliness and offered praise for what she called the
country's continued progress in ``economic and social rights'' and
efforts to improve criminal procedures. But she was frank in her
critique of China's record in the core freedoms and legal
safeguards enshrined in international declarations.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson had hoped for agreement this week on a long-discussed
program of technical cooperation with China, to study how its laws
and criminal practices can be brought into compliance with the two
international rights covenants that China has signed but not
ratified.
</P>
<P>
   No such agreement was announced Thursday, but Robinson said she
had been assured that the Chinese expect to sign on to the program
later this year.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Robinson said she was encouraged that China's parliament had
begun discussions about the International Covenant on Economic,
Social and Cultural Rights, which China signed in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   But she said no such progress was evident in the case of the
Covenant on Civil and Political Rights, signed in 1998, and warned
that China would have to make wide-ranging changes to bring its
legal practices in line with international standards.
</P>
<P>
   Among other needed changes, Robinson said, China's notorious
system of ``reform through labor,'' in which accused criminals and
opponents of the state are sent to labor camps for up to three
years without a trial or basic legal protections, would have to be
phased out.
</P>
<P>
   According to the government's own figures, as of 1997 some
230,000 people were held in such labor camps, and the government
has given no public sign that it would seriously consider
abolishing the system.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson said she had been alarmed to hear of proposals for a
new law to govern the reform-through-labor system, as though that
would raise its international legitimacy. ``Bad law can be a
tyranny,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson was in Beijing attending a U.N. workshop on human
rights in Asia. The Chinese press on Thursday featured the workshop
as a sign of progress and carried President Jiang Zemin's message
of congratulations to the forum in which he praised the global
development of human rights _ in keeping with the cultural
traditions and needs of each country.
</P>
<P>
   ``China has made tremendous efforts on the human rights front,
and it has achieved successes that have astonished the world,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, after the U.S. State Department in its annual rights
report castigated China for regressing last year, China issued its
own report on human rights violations in the United States like
racism and the mistreatment of prisoners.
</P>
<P>
   China's papers have prominently covered the controversial trial
in New York of police officers who shot to death Amadou Diallo, a
West African immigrant, and were acquitted of all charges.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-02-00 1719EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000302.0232 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-02 17:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4812 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e BC-TV-OLDANCHORS03-COX     03-02 1627
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-OLDANCHORS03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Today's anchors might be the last of their breed
 &HT;    By Diane Holloway
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ New millennium. New anchors. Count on it.
</P>
<P>
   The current troika of network anchors has reached the age when
most people think about retirement.
</P>
<P>
   None has indicated a desire to step down yet. All are energetic
news hounds. But sooner or later _ probably in the next five years
_ change will come for the first time in nearly two decades.
</P>
<P>
   An entire generation has grown up with Tom, Peter and Dan. It's
almost impossible to think of NBC, ABC and CBS newscasts without
them. Network news is so stamped with their personality and style
that a change at the top will fundamentally alter the broadcasts.
</P>
<P>
   ``The newscasts are very definitely personality-driven,'' says
Ken Bode, former NBC and CNN political reporter and now the dean of
Northwestern University's Medill School of Journalism. ``That's
part of the reason they've been kept alive. The anchors are the
essential brand of those programs, not the newsgathering or the
presentation.''
</P>
<P>
   And today's anchors have been around a long time, in most cases,
longer than their predecessors.
</P>
<P>
   The last anchor shake-up occurred in 1983, when Peter Jennings
became solo anchor of ABC's ``World News Tonight'' following Frank
Reynolds' death. That same year, Tom Brokaw took the reins of ``NBC
Nightly News'' after a brief partnership with Roger Mudd. The first
change in the current generation of anchors came in 1981 and was
the most profound. Walter Cronkite, the most trusted man in
America, departed a year ahead of schedule so that ``The CBS
Evening News'' could give Dan Rather the job. It was the end of an
era, a shift from avuncular to brash.
</P>
<P>
   That seismic shift, as dramatic as it was, successfully
established three new anchors, but it came at a time when
television news was a totally different beast. The evening
newscasts were the only game in town, reaching a whopping 72
percent of the viewing audience. CNN was in its infancy, and the
Internet wasn't a factor. Because of the dominance of network news,
it was easier for rising anchors to get the experience, credibility
and star quality they needed.
</P>
<P>
   Today there are three major cable news channels _ CNN, MSNBC and
Fox News _ and the combined network share of the audience for the
Big Three's evening news has shrunk to 46 percent. Internet news is
available in more than half of U.S. homes. With so many places for
viewers to get their news now, the influence of network news and
the people who report it has diminished, and nobody is emerging as
heirapparent to the anchors.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is hard now to establish the kind of unique role that Dan
had coming up at CBS,'' says Andrew Heyward, president of CBS News.
``We have some terrific people coming up through the ranks, but
becoming the dominant reporter of your generation, the way Dan did,
is not going to happen.''
</P>
<P>
   So, who are the designated successors? Surprisingly, nobody
officially and only one unofficially. A few years ago, NBC made no
secret of the fact that it was grooming Brian Williams to replace
Brokaw, now 60 and the youngest of the three. But then Brokaw,
nicknamed Duncan the Wonder Horse for his tireless work ethic,
either changed his mind or gently reminded his bosses he wasn't
ready to leave. Williams now anchors his own news program on NBC's
cable news outlet MSNBC.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have people coming up we feel very strongly about who would
be suitable heirs,'' says Bill Wheatley, vice president of NBC
News. ``Brian continues to get invaluable experience. He's
anchoring a high-quality national news program on MSNBC, and he has
been called upon numerous times to anchor for NBC.''
</P>
<P>
   But Williams is no longer the shoo-in he once was. Other names
bandied about include ``Today'' host Matt Lauer and ``Dateline
NBC'' host Stone Phillips.
</P>
<P>
   If the 68-year-old Rather decided tomorrow to take up fishing
fulltime at his Lake Travis getaway, who would replace him? White
House reporter and Sunday anchor John Roberts is the front-runner,
although not officially. Also mentioned are former White House
reporter Scott Pelley and Tim Russert, host of NBC's top-rated
Sunday morning program ``Meet the Press.'' Bryant Gumbel, anchor of
CBS's ``The Early Show,'' is a possible contender, too.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Friedman, executive producer of ABC's ``World News
Tonight,'' says that if Jennings were to quit today, ``Good Morning
America'' anchor Charles Gibson likely would get the nod _ although
perhaps not permanently. Gibson, as Friedman pointed out, is only
seven years younger than Jennings.
</P>
<P>
   ``There has been some grooming going on here, but there's still
time,'' Friedman says. ``Naming names makes it awkward, so I won't.
Besides, as smart as you are and hard as you try to plan these
things, it's never that neat. It's possible there are reporters
toiling away out there who will come to our attention and become
good anchormen.''
</P>
<P>
   If a woman is to join the next generation of network anchors,
ABC's Diane Sawyer seems the most likely candidate. After working
horrendous hours salvaging ``Good Morning America'' while
continuing her work on ``20/20'' at night, surely Sawyer deserves a
shot at the top job.
</P>
<P>
   However, Friedman was reluctant to confirm Sawyer as a
possibility, using the terms ``anchorman'' and ``anchor guy''
repeatedly. He says there's nothing wrong with having a woman
anchor, and viewers clearly like Sawyer. But he noted that Barbara
Walters' partnership with Harry Reasoner failed, as did Connie
Chung's brief tenure with Rather.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe when the time actually comes to make that decision, they
will consider a woman,'' says Barbara Cochran, president of the
Radio-Television News Directors Association in Washington. ``It
seems to me that any network executive looking at talent will see
women who are very compelling and who have substantial experience.
There's clearly a role for a strong woman. Look at the prime-time
newsmagazines and morning shows. They all have women anchors who
make huge contributions.''
</P>
<P>
   It may or may not be coincidence that the network news divisions
are presided over by men. Perhaps in the future, a woman will
occupy one of those top spots, which could increase the chances of
a woman becoming solo anchor.
</P>
<P>
   Although most news executives refuse to name names of possible
candidates, they readily tick off qualities they will look for in
the next anchors. First and foremost, they want reporting
experience and lots of it, although there is no longer an emphasis
on print reporting. Rather is the last anchor to start out in
newspapers. The networks do want anchors whose TV reporting
includes a wide range of beats and locations.
</P>
<P>
   ``That gives you an enormous background of knowledge, and that
adds to the credibility, which is so important,'' Friedman says.
``There's also the likability factor _ the feeling this is a decent
guy you'd like to talk to. I don't think blinding good looks is
critical. You just have to look decent and be a good
communicator.''
</P>
<P>
   You'd think since anchors are so important to the newscasts, the
networks would be training and promoting the next ones. The fact
that they aren't has led some to wonder if the newscasts themselves
are heading for extinction.
</P>
<P>
   ``When it comes time for Brokaw to retire, maybe they'll just
retire his jersey,'' says Northwestern's Bode. ``Maybe they'll say,
`We can't imagine continuing the broadcast without Brokaw, but we
do have MSNBC.' Brian Williams already has a show on MSNBC. They'll
have to examine very seriously whether there's any reason to
continue the network evening news.''
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, news executives think there will always be a
need for a dependable half hour that summarizes the day's events
and provides context.
</P>
<P>
   ``The newscasts aren't the overwhelmingly dominant voice they
once were,'' says CBS's Heyward. ``But there's still a strong need
for someone who can be the gatekeeper for all this information.
It's ironic that the same proliferation of choices that has eroded
the power of the evening news also has solidified the role, because
you need someone to make sense of it all.''
</P>
<P>
   Which is not to say the newscasts won't change. They've already
changed in the post-Cronkite era.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're no longer considered the broadcast of record,''
Heyward says. ``They've moved away from headlines and now place
much more emphasis on original reporting. Sameness once was almost
a virtue; now they all have to distinguish themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   And they do that with standing features like CBS's ``Eye on
America'' and ABC's ``Cutting Edge.'' But the format is virtually
the same on all three, including an overview of the day's news, the
standing features and a single longer story. Since CNN and other
cable news networks specialize in the digest news, broadcast
networks are moving toward fewer but longer stories.
</P>
<P>
   Might there be a truly dramatic, formula-busting change when the
next anchors arrive?
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, if not sooner,'' says ABC's Friedman. ``Somebody's going
to have to do it. ... It's a question of who's got the courage to
make the change, because you always lose in the short run, and then
you hope to hell you can build yourself back up and surpass where
you were.''
</P>
<P>
   But even with charismatic and richly experienced anchors,
network news is merely hanging on to a shrinking audience. With new
anchors, erosion is likely to worsen. In the past, the ratings
slide was temporary, but the next shift may be more profound. If
so, the next generation of viewers may have only a dim recollection
of the nightly news habit.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
