<HEADLINE>
UNIVERSITY SUSPENDS CLASSES TO PROTEST ARRESTS BY PALESTINIAN
FORCES 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 By JOEL GREENBERG   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ Students and teachers at Bir Zeit University, the
leading Palestinian academic institution in the West Bank, on
Tuesday suspended classes indefinitely to protest arrests of
students by the Palestinian security forces.
</P>
<P>
   The arrests followed an incident on Saturday in which a crowd of
protesting students threw stones at Prime Minister Lionel Jospin of
France during a campus visit.
</P>
<P>
   They were angered by remarks Jospin made in Israel in which he
called attacks by Hezbollah, the guerrilla group fighting to oust
Israeli troops from southern Lebanon, ``terrorist acts.''
</P>
<P>
   The stone-throwing incident embarrassed the Palestinian
Authority. Yasser Arafat, the Palestinian leader, apologized and
ordered an investigation.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday and Monday, Arafat's security forces rounded up dozens
of students in and around the university, setting up checkpoints on
approach roads and detaining suspected participants in the stoning
and others said to be active in campus political groups.
</P>
<P>
   Students who were later freed said that some detainees had been
beaten.
</P>
<P>
   After more student protests in West Bank cities against Jospin
and in support of the detainees, the Palestinian police chief, Maj.
Gen. Ghazi Jabali, banned demonstrations without prior police
approval.
</P>
<P>
   Fadel al-Khalidi, an official at Bir Zeit University's office of
student affairs, said 28 students remain in detention out of about
60 who were rounded up. He said students and teachers had suspended
classes until all are released, and that students were holding a
sit-in protest at the campus.
</P>
<P>
   The stone-throwing incident ``is an internal matter for the
university to resolve, without the intervention of the Palestinian
Authority's security forces,'' Khalidi said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The university will take the appropriate measures, but nothing
will be done until all the detainees are freed,'' he added. ``Those
students have the right to an education.''
</P>
<P>
   But Hind Abdeh, a spokeswoman for the Palestinian Preventive
Security Service in the West Bank, said agents had the right to act
because Jospin had been an official guest.
</P>
<P>
   ``The university belongs to the Ministry of Higher Education, so
it is natural that the authority should intervene,'' she said.
``The incident involved a guest of the Palestinian Authority.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
