<HEADLINE>
SPECIAL ATTRACTIONS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Some other Orlando additions worth noting:
</P>
<P>
   _Disney's Epcot: Several millennium additions make this park
worth a stop before the end of 2000.
</P>
<P>
   The Tapestry of Nations parade _ held twice daily at 6:30 p.m.
and 8 p.m. _ is a moving spectacle of 20-foot-high puppets that
float and bob to tribal rhythms. The puppets are archetypal _ some
are fluid as butterflies, others are solid and metallic; drummers
pound on giant wheels of time. It's all clearly about the passing
of the age _ and just a darned good time.
</P>
<P>
   The new Illuminations fireworks at 9 each evening offers a
global blast _ somewhat literally. The earth glows and twirls
around the lagoon while sprays of flares and lasers keep time to a
momentous symphony commissioned just for the show.
</P>
<P>
   The new Millennium Village is a mix of displays, foods and
shopping from around the world. Unlike the Epcot countries, which
were created two decades ago, the new displays sparkle with
technology. In Brazil, for instance, you hold up a paddle to drive
a boat on the Amazon; in Saudi Arabia you can catch holograms in
your hand; in Israel you can ``fly'' over Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
   _Holiday Inn Family Suites: This new 800-suite motel, near
Animal Kingdom and other Disney Parks, is the next generation of
the popular Family Fun Suites Holiday Inn introduced in Orlando a
few years back. With almost 500 square feet, these new suites are
more spacious, offering separate rooms for parents, plus a sitting
area with a pull-out couch and kitchenette. Facilities include two
pools and a small fitness center, and there are frequent shuttles
to Disney parks.
</P>
<P>
   Suite themes include cinema suites (the spare bedroom includes a
60-inch screen and two comfy recliner chairs with drink holders), a
sweetheart suite (one bedroom plus a spacious heart-shaped
whirlpool tub), a large one-bedroom residential suite with full
kitchen, and a business suite (the spare room is converted to a
large office with cherry desk furniture, fax-copier and white
board.)
</P>
<P>
   Rates start at $129. Information: (407) 387-5437;
www.hifamilysuites.com
</P>
<P>
   A special event at Universal Studios Florida is Mardi Gras 2000,
a 44-night festival running until April 1. It's the longest-running
Mardi Gras celebration outside of New Orleans and comes complete
with fancy floats and wildly dressed float riders throwing tons of
trinkets to the crowds. You'll also find music from popular bands
and Cajun-style food. It's included in the price of theme park
admission; for information, call the Mardi Gras hot line at (407)
224-5500.
</P>
<P>
   _NBA City: This first NBA restaurant, opened in September, is a
partnership between the National Basketball Association and Hard
Rock Cafe. Part of CityWalk at Universal Studios Escape, NBA City
combines interactive games, shopping (natch), basketball action via
video, and dining in an arena-style building. Dishes include
pizzas, pastas and steaks. Information: (407) 445-7622.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
