</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COCKFIGHTING03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    SENATE PANEL PASSES RESTRICTIONS ON FIGHTING COCKS
 &HT;    By ISMAIL TURAY Jr.
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Senate Agriculture Committee on Thursday
approved an amendment to the Animal Welfare Act that would ban the
interstate shipment of fighting cocks from states where the sport
is illegal.
</P>
<P>
   The committee approved the measure introduced by Sen. Wayne
Allard, R-Colo., on a voice vote. It now goes to the full Senate.
Similar legislation is pending in the House.
</P>
<P>
   The Humane Society of the United States sees the legislation as
a major step toward banning the sport in all 50 states.
Cockfighting is legal only in Louisiana, Oklahoma and New Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are very pleased with the outcome of this vote,'' said
Wayne Pacelle, senior vice president of the Humane Society. ``We
are that much closer to eliminating the federal loophole that
provides a smokescreen for illegal cockfighting in the 47 states
where the practice is outlawed by state law.''
</P>
<P>
   The anti-cockfighting legislation is ``hilarious,'' and Pacelle
is an ``obnoxious person who knows nothing about chickens,'' said
Tomas(cq) L. Booth, a breeder in Odessa, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``How are you going to enforce it?'' asked Booth, owner of
Tommy(cq) Club, a cockfighting pit in Hobbs, N.M. ``Are you going
to send FBI agents to the borders and send a guy to the pen? You
can't even fight the interstate shipment of drugs.''
</P>
<P>
   Booth said that even though cockfighting has been illegal in
Texas since 1907, he estimates there are eight pits and 24,000
people who engage in cockfighting in the state, with 85 in Odessa
alone. He said the pits get 80 to 90 entries per week, including
some submitted by law enforcement officers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are friends with those guys, we elect them,'' said Booth.
He said he has never engaged in cockfights in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Booth said cockfighters rent hotels, motels or bars to stage
tournaments on weekends.
</P>
<P>
   Depending on the size of the pit, Booth said, participants are
charged up to $500 to enter as many as seven chickens. Those with
the most successful cocks can win as much as $9,000 per night, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Booth said cockfighting is a ``good, wholesome family sport''
that George Washington and Abraham Lincoln were involved in.
</P>
<P>
   But opponents of cockfighting say it's a bloody, barbaric
practice.
</P>
<P>
   The cock's natural spurs are cut off and replaced with
razor-sharp 1-inch blades known as a gaffs, said Pacelle.
</P>
<P>
   The cocks are given stimulants to heighten their aggression,
Pacelle said, and are placed in the 16-foot-square pit.
</P>
<P>
   Like boxers, the chickens deliver blows with the gaffs and use
their wings to block attacks. When one of the chickens falls or
doesn't defend itself, it is put on its feet by a referee. A
knockout is declared when a chicken is unable to stand on its own
three times.
</P>
<P>
   The chicken's lungs or other vital organs are punctured during
the cockfights, Pacelle said. He said a chicken sometimes loses an
eye in a fight, and when that happens, the one-eyed birds are often
matched in a fight known as a blinker derby.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's possible that there are blinker derbies,'' said Booth.
``But it's very rare for their eyes to get poked out.''
</P>
<P>
   Booth said, ``I don't see you trying to ban boxing or football''
even though those are also barbaric and people are sometimes
killed. He added that in Texas, dogs that are not adopted are put
to sleep and burned in incinerators that people pay for through
taxes.
</P>
<P>
   ``My chickens don't have to worry about being golden brown or
extra crispy,'' Booth said. ``They can live to see their
offspring.''
</P>
<P>
   Ismail Turay Jr.'s e-mail address is ismailt(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
