<HEADER>
A4823 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-BOOK-NOTES02-COX     03-02 0689
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-NOTES02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Georgia writer finds France more friendly to noir works
 &HT;    By Don O'Briant
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Georgia writer Henry Joseph has not had much luck with American
publishers so far, but the French love him. Editions Gallimard, the
Paris company that published Albert Camus, has bought world rights
to six of Joseph's novels.
</P>
<P>
   ``My books are published in their Serie Noir collection,'' says
Joseph, 51, who lives on 19 isolated acres in northwest Georgia.
``The first two books, `Bloodwork: The New Rugged Cross' and
`Dinosaur Heaven,' got good reviews over there.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Bloodwork,'' the only one of Joseph's books published in the
United States, was released in 1994 by Gibbs-Smith. Now out of
print, the film rights have been optioned by My Girl Productions in
Florida. Carter DeHaven (``Hoosiers'') has been asked to develop it
as a feature film.
</P>
<P>
   Set in Georgia, ``Bloodwork'' opens with protagonist Jack Lee
finding his best friend hanging from a wooden cross and wearing a
crown of marijuana flowers.
</P>
<P>
   Next out in spring 2001 in France is ``The Well-Spent Death of
Eightball Barnett,'' which Joseph describes as a thriller about a
former political operative who retired under the stress of his own
guilt from a secret government outfit called The Unit. When he
learns he has a terminal illness, he sets out to right some of the
wrongs he has done under the guise of patriotism.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the action in the novels takes place in Americana, the
location of the expatriate Confederate colony in Brazil. Joseph
spent a year and a half in Brazil and a year in India doing
research, working construction jobs and ``chasing the brass ring of
realization.''
</P>
<P>
   Joseph is not the only author who had to go abroad to attract
attention in his native country. Atlanta writer Jim Grimsley's
first novel, ``Winter Birds,'' was published in Germany before
Algonquin Books bought the American rights.
</P>
<P>
   So why do the French like Joseph's novels more than American
publishers do? The French have always loved ``noir'' works, Joseph
says, ``and my books are pretty dark. For another thing, New York
publishing is dominated by corporate `suits,' which has led to an
even narrower middle-of-the-road stance, while my own work has
become more offroad. What I need to do here is to hook up with an
adventuresome editor.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  New award: Amazon.com has launched the PEN/Amazon.com Short
Story Award in collaboration with the PEN American Center. The
contest invites unpublished writers to submit original short story
manuscripts to compete for a grand prize of $10,000 and publication
at Amazon.com and in the Boston Book Review.
</P>
<P>
   The judging panel is composed of three PEN writers: David
Guterson, author of the award-winning ``Snow Falling on Cedars'';
Jamaica Kincaid, author of ``Annie John'' and ``Autobiography of My
Mother''; and novelist Sherman Alexie, author of ``The Lone Ranger
and Tonto Fistfight in Heaven.''
</P>
<P>
   Joining 16 other PEN literary honors, the PEN/Amazon.com Short
Story Award will be presented at the annual PEN Literary Awards
Ceremony on May 15 at Walter Reade Theatre in New York's Lincoln
Center.
</P>
<P>
   To participate, writers must be over the age of 18 and residents
of either the United States or Canada. Manuscript submissions must
be postmarked on or before March 24. Additional award information
and a complete set of rules can be found at
www.amazon.com/shortstory.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Nominations wanted: The Lindberg Awards Committee is seeking
nominees for next year's Stanley W. Lindberg Award, which
recognizes anyone who has contributed substantially to the literary
culture of Georgia through a lifetime body of work. Pat Conroy was
the first recipient of the award, established in 1999 in honor of
the late editor of the Georgia Review. Brief descriptions of
nominees and their work can be sent to Anne Johnson, Georgia Center
for the Book, 215 Sycamore St., Decatur, GA 30030.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  E-mail: dobriant(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Don O'Briant writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
