<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-WALLS-REVIEW-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PASSION AND PASSAGES WITHIN `THESE WALLS' 
</HEADLINE>
   By JOHN CARMAN  
 c.2000, San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   If these walls could talk, they'd probably be giggling instead,
along with Sharon Stone and Ellen DeGeneres in their lesbian sex
romp.
</P>
<P>
   Stone and DeGeneres dispense with their clothes and give viewers
equal parts passion and mirth in a bonfire of a sex scene Sunday
night, putting a celebratory exclamation point on ``If These Walls
Could Talk 2.''
</P>
<P>
   I see big numbers for HBO, and I hear VCRs churning, not
necessarily for the most correct reasons. The scene would be a TV
groundbreaker except for the fact that Chloe Sevigny (``Boys Don't
Cry'') and Michelle Williams (``Dawson's Creek'') have at each
other less than an hour earlier on the same program.
</P>
<P>
   Four years ago, HBO set a still-standing ratings record for its
original films with ``If These Walls Could Talk,'' about pregnancy
and abortion. This Sunday's show, executive-produced by DeGeneres,
is a trilogy of short films about lesbians and changing times.
</P>
<P>
   It would be a pleasure to say that ``If These Walls Could Talk
2'' is delightful, delovely and DeGeneres. But mostly it's
DeGeneres. She has become a gutsy, pioneering force in
entertainment since declaring her lesbianism and deciding to let
the hips fall where they may. Yet her talent usually runs a step
and a half behind her ambitions.
</P>
<P>
   The idea here is to set the three stories _ each with separate
casts, writers and directors _ in the same house, which happens to
be occupied by lesbians in 1961, 1972 and 2000.
</P>
<P>
   The first short film is written and directed by Jane Anderson
(``The Baby Dance''). Vanessa Redgrave stars as a retired
schoolteacher who has been living discreetly with her lifelong
lover (Marian Seldes) and whose world unravels cruelly when Seldes
falls from a ladder and dies.
</P>
<P>
   Redgrave is turned away from Seldes' hospital room because she
isn't ``family.'' Then, when Seldes dies, her patronizing nephew
and heir (Paul Giamatti) arrives with his smarmy wife (Elizabeth
Perkins) to claim the house Seldes shared for decades with
Redgrave.
</P>
<P>
   Next, Martha Coolidge directs a story written by Sylvia Sichel
and set in 1972. Williams plays one of four college coeds, all
lesbian feminists, who now rent the house. Williams' attraction to
a butch lesbian (Sevigny) provokes trouble with Williams'
roommates, who belittle Sevigny's masculine trappings. It also
provokes a sort of crisis of conscience for Williams.
</P>
<P>
   DeGeneres and Stone are a couple living in the house in 2000, in
a comedic segment written and directed by DeGeneres' off-screen
partner, actress Anne Heche. They want to have a baby. When Stone
begins to ovulate, DeGeneres giddily dashes to the sperm bank.
</P>
<P>
   Heche's pun-filled script is light as helium and seemingly
pointless. It barely makes any feints toward fleshing out the two
main characters. But aside from its dishy sex scene with all the
writhing flesh and interlocked limbs _ quick, is that body part
DeGeneres' or Stone's? _ the segment surely does count as
affirmation.
</P>
<P>
   Time has passed since Redgrave's troubles; there are still
references to discrimination in 2000, but the Stone and DeGeneres
characters are living confidently and happily. It's not for nothing
that the two stars rock out at the end, dancing rollickingly over
the closing credits.
</P>
<P>
   The 1961 story is more affecting. If it had been better
directed, it would have been genuinely moving.
</P>
<P>
   But Anderson isn't content with the worlds of repressed passion
in Redgrave's exquisite blue eyes. Instead she steers the segment
toward mawkishness, heavy-handedly demanding that the viewer feel
sorry for Redgrave's character. And you will, but you well might
resent being led to it by the nose.
</P>
<P>
   Coolidge's middle film is the best, the most complex and the
least self-conscious of the batch. The segment catches lesbianism
at a transitional time, with Williams' character realizing finally
that Sevigny must be herself _ coat, tie, slicked-back hair,
motorcycle and all _ rather than toe the feminist line.
</P>
<P>
   I don't know if butch often comes in as svelte a package as
Sevigny, but I do know that hers is the most beguiling performance
in all of ``If These Walls Could Talk 2.''
</P>
<P>
   This isn't butch as in masculine swagger. Sevigny's character is
quiet, utterly honest about who she is, and devastatingly sexy. The
backdrop is 1972, but there's something in Sevigny's sleek
self-assurance that smacks of 2000 more than the Stone-DeGeneres
silliness to come.
</P>
<P>
   There's also a romantic tension in the budding affair between
Sevigny and the naive Williams that ought to make this middle film
the real television trailblazer of the batch. When this pair reach
the sheets, the turn-on is too cool and too palpable to be about
the mere configuration of gender.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
