<HEADER>
A4826 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u k BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN$ADV05     03-02 1031
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN$ADV05-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     RUNNING FOR PRESIDENT: A NASTY BUSINESS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 &HT;     (For release Sunday, March 5)   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients  
 &HT;     By ROBERT E. THOMPSON  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The men who would be president and, therefore, the
world's most powerful head of state have been called liars, cheats,
bigots, cowards and phonies.
</P>
<P>
   Before the Gore-Bradley love feast in Los Angeles last week, the
major presidential contenders prefaced their attacks on one another
with such soothing phrases as ``my good friend'' or ``he's a fine
fellow.'' Then they blasted the heck out of them.
</P>
<P>
   Running for president is a ``nasty, nasty business,'' Jesse
Ventura said last week. And having been a professional wrestler
before he was elected governor of Minnesota, Ventura is an expert
on such enterprises.
</P>
<P>
   Ventura says the presidential hopefuls should cease besmirching
the character of their opponents and limit themselves to
discussions of the issues that divide them.
</P>
<P>
   Millions of Americans undoubtedly share that opinion. Of course,
many may derive a certain sinister pleasure from watching
presidential candidates rip one another to shreds. But most
probably recognize that their personal interests would be far
better served by an enlightened debate on such matters as taxes,
education, national defense, health care and America's stance in
the world.
</P>
<P>
   Yet in the televised Republican debates of recent weeks, George
W. Bush and John McCain often spent an inordinate amount of time
arguing over which of them has indulged more in negative
advertising. On the Democratic side, Al Gore and Bill Bradley
wasted an excessive amount of time on the same issue before last
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   When the candidates themselves have refrained from besmirching
the character of their opponents, their surrogates have lunged into
the breach with vicious condemnations of opposing candidates.
</P>
<P>
   McCain has blasted Bush for cowtowing to the religious right and
two of its patron saints, Pat Robertson and Jerry Falwell, and
indirectly accused the Democratic candidates of paying homage to
racially divisive activists Al Sharpton and Louis Farrakhan. Gary
Bauer, who has supported McCain since withdrawing from the
presidential race, now has asked him to apologize for his remarks
about Robertson and Falwell.
</P>
<P>
   But, in truth, Robertson also should apologize for his unsavory
campaign oratory.
</P>
<P>
   When the McCain forces ridiculed Bush for speaking at South
Carolina's Bob Jones University, whose policies are racist and
anti-Catholic, the Texas governor first cried foul and then wrote a
letter of apology to Catholic Cardinal John O'Connor in New York.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, voters in Michigan and Virginia claimed to
have received telephone calls from McCain activists accusing Bush
of being anti-Catholic. Those calls presumably were retribution for
the ones made by Robertson and other Bush advocates attacking
McCain.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley has asserted that Gore is dishonest and Gore has charged
that Bradley did little during his three terms in the Senate to
promote the causes he now champions.
</P>
<P>
   The Republicans repeatedly promise to end the ``Clinton-Gore
regime'' in Washington, thus seeking to link the vice president to
Clinton's unsavory sexual adventures that denigrated the presidency
and the White House.
</P>
<P>
   Where Bush once was expected to soar to the GOP nomination
without serious opposition, he now finds himself battling a
candidate whose direct manner of speaking has fired the imagination
of many Americans. McCain also has brought into the primaries
independents and Democrats who could provide the GOP with victory
in November.
</P>
<P>
   But the sinking of presidential contests into innuendo, gossip,
and lies is nearly as old as the republic.
</P>
<P>
   It is part of a tradition that began in 1796 with the first
presidential clash between Thomas Jefferson and John Adams near the
end of George Washington's tenure.
</P>
<P>
   In his book, ``Presidential Campaigns,'' Paul F. Boller Jr.
wrote: ``The first real presidential contest in American history
turned out to be exuberantly venomous. On both sides handbills,
pamphlets and articles in party newspapers denounced, disparaged,
damned, decried, denigrated and declaimed.''
</P>
<P>
   But Boller added that Adams and Jefferson remained on good terms
and did not take active part in the campaign of sleaze. Adams won,
but four years later Jefferson defeated him and was elected
president.
</P>
<P>
   In the campaign of 1804, when Jefferson sought a second term,
the Federalists asserted that he had made an attractive slave named
Sally Hemings his mistress and the mother of several of his
children. Jefferson did not publicly deny the accusation, but he
did do so in private letters to friends.
</P>
<P>
   If the DNA evidence we have today about Jefferson's possible
paternity of at least one of Hemings' children had been available
in 1804, he might have served only one term.
</P>
<P>
   In 1824, the fiery Andrew Jackson was denounced as an adulterer
and bigamist because he and his wife Rachel had married thinking
her first husband had obtained a divorce. He had not done so, and
that provided fuel for Jackson's many opponents. Once the first
husband did obtain a divorce, Jackson and Rachel were remarried.
</P>
<P>
   And so it has gone through the years. Abraham Lincoln, Franklin
D. Roosevelt, Harry Truman, Lyndon Johnson, Dwight Eisenhower,
Jimmy Carter and Ronald Reagan all have been subjected to brutal
attacks by their political enemies.
</P>
<P>
   In the present battle for the presidency, it should be
understood that Gore sometimes exaggerates his credentials but he
is not a liar, Bush is not anti-Catholic, McCain is as good a
Republican as Bush but wants to reform his party, and Bradley
distinguished himself in the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Elections permit the people to take part directly in choosing
the men and women who determine the fate of the republic. But the
quadrennial presidential pageant is the World Series, Super Bowl
and Kentucky Derby of politics, and its participants should not
descend into the gutter to gain votes and money.
</P>
<P>
   (Robert E. Thompson can be reached at 202-298-6920.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
