<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-MAP-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SIGOURNEY WEAVER TAKES CHARACTER DOWN COMPLEX PATH IN `MAP OF THE
WORLD' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By WILLIAM ARNOLD  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Alice (Sigourney Weaver), the heroine-narrator of the film
version of Jane Hamilton's 1994 novel, ``A Map of the World,''
tells us in its opening moments that we are about to witness a
woman's descent into a living hell. The boast turns out to be no
exaggeration.
</P>
<P>
   The over-stressed, under-appreciated wife of a Wisconsin farmer,
Alice hates her life from the start: Her oldest daughter is an
incomparable brat (``I don't even like her,'' she confides to a
friend), her mother-in-law (Louise Fletcher) is a meddler, and she
hates her job as nurse at the local grammar school.
</P>
<P>
   But things get considerably worse for her when the young
daughter of her best friend (Julianne Moore) is accidentally
drowned in the pond on Alice's farm while under her care, and the
crushing guilt Alice feels brings her to the raw edge of a nervous
breakdown.
</P>
<P>
   Then the trampy waitress mother (Chloe Sevigny) of a troubled,
possibly abused, little boy comes forward with the accusation that
Alice has been molesting her son; Alice is arrested (with bail set
so high she can't get out of jail) and suddenly finds herself in
the midst of a McMartin/
</P>
<P>
   Wenatchee-style witchhunt.
</P>
<P>
   What makes this film truly chilling is the fact first-time
feature filmmaker Scott Elliott and his writers somehow make every
step of this descent harrowingly believable, and somehow strangely
predestined by various quirks in Alice's character and her overall
dissatisfaction with her
</P>
<P>
   lot.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to Weaver's unflinching performance, Alice is, through
most of the film, as unique, fascinating and complex a woman
character as I've seen in a Hollywood movie in some time _
especially in the sequences when she finds that she actually likes
being in jail (``Haven't you ever wanted to be on a desert
island?'').
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, it all moves to one of those transcendent, happy
resolutions calculated to have us leave the theater feeling somehow
uplifted by Alice's ordeal. It's highly unconvincing, and a total
non sequitur to all the horror that's preceded it. This is a story
that, for honesty's sake, cries out for an ending as dark as that
of Strindberg's ``Miss Julie.''
</P>
<P>
   One more complaint: The film's many laudatory references to
Oprah Winfrey are also annoying. Granted, being chosen (as ``Map of
the World'' was) an Oprah Book Club novel is considered more
prestigious these days than winning a Pulitzer Prize. But is this
woman really so powerful now that authors and filmmakers feel
compelled to fill their work with cloying tributes to her glory?
</P>
<P>
   A Map of the World. Directed by Scott Elliott. Screenplay by
Peter Hedges and Polly Platt. Cast: Sigourney Weaver, Julianne
Moore, David Strathairn, Louise Fletcher. First Look Films. 127
minutes. Rated R for sexual themes.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
