<HEADER>
A4832 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-ISRAEL-ATTACK-ART-390     03-02 0967
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-ATTACK-ART-390&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
3 SUSPECTED TERRORISTS DIE IN CLASH WITH ISRAELI FORCES 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
(bl) 
 By WILLIAM A. ORME Jr.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ Israeli forces killed three suspected Palestinian
terrorists Thursday in a clash in an Arab town in northern Israel,
averting what Prime Minister Ehud Barak said was a plan ``to
sabotage the peace process'' with bomb attacks on Israeli
civilians.
</P>
<P>
   Explosions and gunfire punctuated a pre-dawn raid on a two-story
house in Taibeh, an Israeli Arab town southeast of Nazareth, where
authorities said a group of at least five Islamic militants from
the Gaza Strip were preparing explosives for use in Israeli cities.
</P>
<P>
   One man surrendered during the raid, but another two emerged
with weapons and a suitcase that exploded when it was hit by police
fire, according to a police account. The two men were instantly
killed in the explosion, according to the report. A police officer
wounded in the blast later had his foot amputated.
</P>
<P>
   A third man in the house was shot after opening fire on Israeli
troops some 12 hours later. Another may have escaped, but police
Thursday night were searching the ruined building for bodies.
</P>
<P>
   Police, reinforced by counter-terrorist army troops, surrounded
the house in a siege that lasted most of the day and was marked by
sporadic explosions and gunfire. The security forces sent dogs into
the house _ one was killed _ followed by a bomb-sweeping robot. The
stand-off ended when police smashed into the house with an armored
bulldozer.
</P>
<P>
   Sheikh Ahmed Yassin, the spiritual leader of Hamas, appeared to
corroborate the claim that the dead men belonged to his militant
Islamic group. ``The fall of the martyrs is not a loss, but a
victory for the movement and the Palestinian nation,'' he said in
an Israeli television report from Gaza City.
</P>
<P>
   Their willingness to risk death shows that ``the way is open for
the continuation of the jihad'' against Israel, Yassin said.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday's raid appears to provide further indications of the
increasing difficulties faced by Hamas in mounting terrorist
operations in Israel. As one Israeli general recently noted, 1999
was the first year in recent times without a single Israeli
civilian casualty from terrorism _ an achievement he attributed in
part to improved intelligence cooperation with the Palestinian
Authority. Israeli and Palestinian security forces have claimed
credit for foiling other alleged Hamas terror plots in the past
year.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Officials in the Palestinian Authority echoed Israeli charges
that the men were Gaza-based members of Hamas. According to Israeli
radio, Israeli police ``are investigating the possibility that they
had help from Israeli Arabs.''
</P>
<P>
   The Arab mayor of Taibeh said the occupants of the house arrived
recently and were not known to local residents. He convened the
town council Thursday to discuss a possible prohibition against
renting local properties to outsiders.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope that the Right won't use this to eviscerate the
residents of Taibeh,'' said Issam Asaweh, the mayor, speaking in
Hebrew to Israel Radio. ``We have no connection to this. All the
residents condemn this.''
</P>
<P>
   Thursday's incident took place against a backdrop of rising
tension between Israeli Arabs and the country's Jewish majority. In
a 60-53 vote Wednesday, the parliament endorsed an opposition
motion requiring any referendum on a withdrawal from the Golan
Heights to pass by an absolute majority of all eligible voters _
not just a majority of those who vote on the referendum. Backers
and opponents of the measure said it is intended to neutralize the
impact of Israeli Arabs, who represent some 10 percent of the
electorate and strongly favor a land-for-peace deal with Syria.
</P>
<P>
   In recent weeks, Arab members of parliament have engaged in
increasingly bitter exchanges on a wide range of other divisive
issues, from Israel's nuclear weapons program to Foreign Minister
David Levy's threat to respond in kind to cross-border terror
attacks harming Israeli children. Some Jewish lawmakers challenged
their Arab counterparts' patriotism, and questioned their right to
take part in the parliament of a Jewish state.
</P>
<P>
   Ahmed Tibi, one of 10 Arabs in parliament and a Taibeh native,
condemned both the apparent use of his home town as a terrorist
base, and suggestions from some in the Israeli right that
townspeople were implicated in the incident.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't know all the facts yet,'' said Tibi, referring to
reports that the men belonged to a Gazan terrorist cell. ``But if
it turns out that this is the case, they have made a big mistake,
for us, for themselves, and for the Palestinian cause.''
</P>
<P>
   Palestinians must recognize ``the special status'' of Israeli
Arabs as Israeli citizens and a vulnerable minority in a Jewish
state, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Taibeh lies in the heart of a primarily Arab region of northern
Israel, and its use as a Hamas base would represent further
evidence of a change in strategy for the radical Palestinian
dissidents. Hamas had long avoided compromising Israeli Arab
communities with terrorist activities or recruitment.
</P>
<P>
   But in September, two simultaneous abortive car bombs _ one in
Tiberias, killing the driver, and another in Haifa, killing the
driver and a passenger _ provided evidence of Hamas infiltration of
Israeli Arabs. Police said the bombs were intended for use on
public buses and had been prepared with the aid of Israeli Arabs
recruited by the Hamas office in Amman, which was shut down shortly
afterwards by the Jordanian government.
</P>
</TEXT>
