<HEADLINE>
`NEXT BEST THING' ISN'T MADONNA'S ACTING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By WILLIAM ARNOLD  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   At some point, Madonna is going to have to face the hard fact
that her particular stardom just doesn't translate well to
feature-length, narrative-based motion pictures. After 15 years of
trying, she still can't transcend her limitations.
</P>
<P>
   She's the queen of music videos, and she's been very effective
playing an extreme caricature of herself in films such as
``Desperately Seeking Susan'' and ``Dick Tracy'' _ and in the movie
version of ``Evita'' (essentially an album of music videos).
</P>
<P>
   But when she tries to play a normal, everyday human being _ as
she does in her latest splashy star vehicle, ``The Next Best
Thing'' _ she's fairly hopeless: not exactly terrible, but
noticeably weak, strained and unconvincing in scene after scene.
</P>
<P>
   She plays Abbie, a single, 40ish yoga instructor with a bad
romantic track record and a fiercely ticking biological clock who _
after one drunken fling _ finds herself unexpectedly pregnant by
her gay best friend, Robert (Rupert Everett).
</P>
<P>
   They move in together, have the child and become exemplary
parents and a more or less happy family _ except for the fact that
Abbie has no sex life, and finds herself unaccountably jealous of
Robert's brief sexual relationships with various men.
</P>
<P>
   Cut to six years later, and the rest of the movie deals with the
crisis that arises when Mr. Right (Benjamin Bratt) _ a handsome,
sensitive, affluent and incredibly straight investment banker _
comes into Abbie's life and this family unit is imperiled.
</P>
<P>
   In its defense, the movie has good intentions and the element of
surprise _ it's never quite clear where it's going at any given
point _ and noted veteran director John Schlesinger (``Darling,''
``Midnight Cowboy'') gives the proceedings a reasonably delicate
touch.
</P>
<P>
   Playing a slightly deeper version of his character in ``My Best
Friend's Wedding,'' Everett also steals almost every scene: he's
funny, self-deprecating and enormously sympathetic in the
distinctive way that's become his trademark.
</P>
<P>
   But Thomas Ropelewski's script is basically a piece of Hollywood
fluff: it trivializes the issues it raises, is rigidly dogmatic in
its political correctness (so, in the last act, Abbie becomes a
stock heavy) and it fails to find any real drama in the situation.
</P>
<P>
   The film also has the handicap of Madonna. You have to admire
her determination, and the vulnerability she exposes _ especially
in a scene that deals with her aging. But she just doesn't have the
kind of charisma that can carry a movie, and she always seems to be
trying too hard.
</P>
<P>
   The Next Best Thing. Directed by John Schlesinger. Written by
Thomas Ropelewski. Cast: Madonna, Rupert Everett, Benjamin Bratt.
Paramount. 107 minutes. Rated PG-13 for sexual references.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: C
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
