<SLUG> BC-CORAL-REEF03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    PANEL OUTLINES PLAN TO PROTECT CORAL REEFS
 &HT;    By LARRY LIPMAN
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ At least 20 percent of the nation's threatened
coral reefs should be declared ``no-take'' ecological reserves by
2010, a federal-state task force said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is absolutely critical that we act now,'' said D. James
Baker, administrator of the National Oceanic and Atmospheric
Administration and the co-chair of the task force, made up of 11
federal agencies, five U.S. territories, Florida and Hawaii.
</P>
<P>
   The plan calls for establishing ``no-take'' ecological marine
reserves in at least 5 percent of each major U.S. island group and
Florida by 2002, 20 percent by 2005, and 20 percent by 2010.
</P>
<P>
   Human activity in these areas would be restricted, and in some
cases prohibited. The location of the marine reserves would be
jointly set by the federal and local governments.
</P>
<P>
   About 10 percent of the world's coral reefs have been destroyed,
mostly by recent human contact. At the present rate, another 30
percent could be gone within 20 years and roughly 70 percent by
mid-century, Baker said.
</P>
<P>
   Whether the destruction is caused by anchors crushing the
fragile coral skeletons or pollution killing the microscopic
plant-like organisms that build them, the task force concluded that
since most of the threats are man-made, they can be reduced or
eliminated.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. coral reefs cover about 6,500 square miles, roughly the
size of Hawaii. More than 90 percent are located around U.S.
islands in the Pacific, and the remainder are located off Florida,
Texas and the U.S. island territories in the Caribbean.
</P>
<P>
   They are a source of tourism, fishing and _ increasingly _
pharmaceuticals.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you protect the coral reefs, you are protecting the
economy, you are protecting jobs,'' Baker said.
</P>
<P>
   In the Florida Keys, for example, the coral reefs are
responsible for about $1.2 billion a year in tourism-related
business such as diving tours, fishing trips, and hotel and
restaurant activity.
</P>
<P>
   Often called the ``rain forests of the sea,'' coral reefs are a
high priority for the Clinton administration, said George T.
Frampton Jr., acting chairman of the White House Council on
Environmental Quality.
</P>
<P>
   This year's budget includes $21 million for coral reef
protection, and President Clinton has requested $25 million for
next year.
</P>
<P>
   Greg DiDomenico, executive director of the Monroe County
Commercial Fishermen Inc., whose territory includes the Florida
Keys, said it was too soon to determine the impact of the marine
reserves.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it keeps us from fishing in areas where we have been
historically for 20 or 30 years, it will have a major impact, but
it depends on the places they're talking about,'' DiDomenico said.
</P>
<P>
   Larry Lipman's e-mail address is larryl(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
