<SLUG> BC-FILM-AGNES-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`AGNES BROWNE' DANCES TO A LIGHTER BEAT THAN `ANGELA'S ASHES' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By WILLIAM ARNOLD  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Anjelica Huston's big-screen directorial debut, ``Agnes
Browne,'' is a chronicle of an imperiled Irish family that could
almost be described as a benevolent, feel-good version of
``Angela's Ashes.''
</P>
<P>
   Like the earlier film, this one is a period piece whose title
character is a chain-smoking mother (Huston) of a large Irish brood
forced to cope with poverty, ignorance, loan sharks and the lack of
a husband.
</P>
<P>
   But while ``Angela's Ashes'' was as relentlessly bleak a view of
the Irish as has ever been put on celluloid, ``Anges'' has nothing
but affection for its characters and fondness for their quirkiness.
</P>
<P>
   Set in 1967 and based on a popular radio series and novel by
Brendan O'Carroll, it picks up Agnes' story as her husband has just
died and _ her widow's pension held up by bureaucracy _ she has to
go to the neighborhood loan shark, Mr. Billy (Ray Winstone), to pay
for the funeral.
</P>
<P>
   From here, the episodic script traces her struggles to make ends
meet as a street vendor, her various child-rearing problems, her
relationships with the Church and her Market Street Dublin
community, and her budding romance with a shy French baker (Arno
Chevrier).
</P>
<P>
   Huston's performance is winning, and she also does a more than
credible job of handling her other actors and situations _
especially Agnes' finely drawn friendship with her next-door
neighbor, Marion (Marion O'Dwyer), which is gradually shown to be
the most profound relationship of Agnes' life.
</P>
<P>
   The film's vision of Ireland is not exactly ``The Quiet Man,''
and we do catch glimpses of ugliness throughout the story, as well
as a certain ignorance of sexual matters that is more sad than
funny. But it balances this dark strain with humor, and many
instances of noble self-sacrifice and the kindness of strangers.
</P>
<P>
   The film's one drawback is that Huston can't quite bring off her
fairy tale ending involving the singer Tom Jones (with Jones
clumsily playing himself 33 years ago).
</P>
<P>
   It really doesn't work and almost seems to trivialize the story,
leaving us with the uncomfortable feeling that we've just viewed
some episode of a TV sit-com of the era.
</P>
<P>
   Agnes Browne. Directed by Anjelica Huston. Screenplay by John
Goldsmith and Brendan O'Carroll. Cast: Anjelica Huston, Marion
O'Dwyer, Niall O'Shea, Ray Winstone, Arno Chevrier. USA Films. 92
minutes. Rated R for language.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B-
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
