</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POL-TICKER03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    POLITICAL TICKER: Suiting up for the GOP debate
 &HT;    (EDs: A brief roundup of the day's campaign events, pulled from
Cox staff and wire reports.)
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Warming up for Thursday night's Republican debate in Los
Angeles, John McCain vowed to get past discord over religion and
turn to issues. An increasingly confident George W. Bush worked to
create a sense of inevitability. ``When I'm the nominee, I'm going
to set the tone for the party,'' he said. Thursday's debate is the
final GOP match-up before Super Tuesday, when voters in 13 states
choose Republican delegates. California is the largest prize. Bush
and Alan Keyes will be in person in Los Angeles; McCain plans to
participate via satellite from St. Louis.
</P>
<P>
   A LITTLE SPARRING BEFORE THE REAL THING
</P>
<P>
   George W. Bush and John McCain struggled for a late advantage
Thursday heading into the debate. McCain protested an ad suggesting
he opposes breast cancer research and called on Bush to ``get out
of the gutter.'' Bush said the ad only described a proposal on
McCain's own Web page, and added, ``It sounds like Senator McCain
is becoming increasingly angry as the campaign goes on.''
</P>
<P>
   LIKE OLD PALS UP THERE ON STAGE
</P>
<P>
   Throughout much of their 90-minute debate, Al Gore and Bill
Bradley reacted in striking contrast to their earlier encounters.
Bradley was remarkably subdued after months of aggressiveness, and
he and Gore expressed agreement on most issues and statements.
After coast-to-coast red-eye flights, both shifted their attention
to the East and New York's crucial primary next week. Gore boarded
an overnight flight to New York, to be followed by visits to
Maryland, Florida, Georgia and Massachusetts. Bradley also flew
east to campaign in New York, Connecticut, Maine and Rhode Island.
His campaign has virtually given up on California, where polls show
Gore with a massive lead.
</P>
<P>
   BRADLEY GOES UP AGAINST `ER'
</P>
<P>
   Bill Bradley will lay out his case for the presidency in an
unusual five-minute ad airing nationwide Thursday. The spot is
scheduled for broadcast on CBS at 10:54 p.m. PST and EST (9:54 CST
and MST).
</P>
<P>
   ``It's Bradley speaking personally to voters about his vision
for the country and the basis of his candidacy and why he would be
a better president,'' said spokesman Eric Hauser.
</P>
<P>
   OPENING A DOOR FOR THE NEXT GERALDINE FERRARO
</P>
<P>
   John McCain said Thursday that the time might be right for a
woman to serve in the White House. At a town hall meeting in
Riverside, Calif., McCain hinted that if he wins the GOP
nomination, he would consider a woman to be his running mate. ``It
would be very legitimate to have a woman vice president,'' McCain
said. ``And perhaps, in the next cycle, a woman president.''
</P>
<P>
   STRONG BONDS
</P>
<P>
   In what he called an emotional reunion, John McCain held a
colorful rally in a large and friendly Vietnamese community that
harkened back to McCain's term as prisoner of war. ``It was my
experience with you that was the defining period of my life,''
McCain told the Vietnamese crowd of about 1,000 in the ``Little
Saigon'' neighborhood. For Hinh Nong, the choice of whom to back in
the GOP presidential race is simple. ``We would still be in North
Vietnam without him,'' said Nong, who spent 18 years as a prisoner.
``There's a bond,'' said Tam Ngoc Ho, a prisoner for 13 years. ``He
was a prisoner like we were.''
</P>
<P>
   MCCAIN EVENT GETS MARINE ATTENTION
</P>
<P>
   Marine Corps brass were up in arms Thursday over a cordon of
color guards that participated in a rally for John McCain in
Bakersfield, Calif. McCain stood with a four-man Marine color
guard, all in uniform. But military personnel are not permitted to
participate in political campaigns. Gen. James Jones, the Marine
Corps commandant, reportedly is incensed. He feels the matter is
very awkward for the Corps, according to ABC News, because he
served as a liaison officer to the Senate and knows McCain
personally. There's no evidence of Pentagon involvement.
</P>
<P>
   JACKSON, MONDALE GOING WITH GORE
</P>
<P>
   Just prior to the debate, Jesse Jackson endorsed Al Gore.
Jackson said Gore was best able to help Americans continue the
longest period of economic growth in U.S. history. In Minneapolis,
1984 Democratic nominee Walter Mondale said Thursday that he
promised Gore his support recently ``and I guess I'm announcing it
now.'' Mondale plans to appear with Gore in Minnesota next week.
</P>
<P>
   NEXT TIME, PLAY A SAXOPHONE
</P>
<P>
   Stumping for votes on late-night talk shows, George W. Bush and
John McCain tried to entertain, but couldn't match Bill Clinton's
flashy 1992 musical appearance on ``The Arsenio Hall Show.'' Bush,
on David Letterman's show, and McCain, on Jay Leno's, attempted to
turn the comedic tables, but their efforts met with only lukewarm
results.
</P>
<P>
   GET THOSE PHONES OUTTA HERE!
</P>
<P>
   Before the Democratic debate began in cell phone-addicted Los
Angeles, moderator Bernard Shaw laid down the law to the in-studio
audience: Shut the devices off. A great stirring followed in the
audience, as dozens of people reached for their phones. Also on
Shaw's list of no-no's were pagers, signs, ``outbursts'' and
``demonstrations.'' There was one infraction, however: A cell phone
rang during the debate.
</P>
<P>
   ON SECOND THOUGHT, BAUER DOESN'T LIKE IT
</P>
<P>
   After first standing by him, conservative activist and former
presidential candidate Gary Bauer urged John McCain to retract and
apologize for critical statements about conservative religious
leaders Pat Robertson and Jerry Falwell. ``I must in the strongest
possible terms repudiate Senator McCain's unwarranted, ill-advised
and divisive attacks on certain religious leaders,'' Bauer said in
a statement. ``Senator McCain must not allow his personal
differences with any individual to cloud his judgment.'' McCain
said he was ``not backing away from the speech.''
</P>
<P>
   DIFFERENT EVANGELISTS, DIFFERENT RESPONSES
</P>
<P>
   One of the two religious leaders whom John McCain suggested was
among ``the forces of evil'' is coming to his defense. Jerry
Falwell told a television station in Roanoke, Va., that he doesn't
believe McCain ``hates Christians or hates anybody.'' But the
candidate was criticized by prison evangelist Charles Colson, whom
McCain had praised. In an opinion piece in the New York Times on
Thursday, Colson, a former Nixon White House aide, said by
``exploiting'' Bush's visit to Bob Jones University to gain
Catholic votes, McCain abetted Democrats who want to ``drive a
wedge'' between Catholics and evangelical Protestants.
</P>
<P>
   BE SURE TO KEEP SPENDING IN CHECK, OK?
</P>
<P>
   Except for George W. Bush, the presidential candidates will be
able to spend $40.5 million to seek their parties' nomination.
Candidates who receive federal funds must limit their spending;
Bush, who spent a record $50 million through Jan. 31, is not
accepting federal funds. The Federal Election Commission put the
primary campaign spending limit at $40.5 million, plus an unlimited
amount for certain legal and accounting expenses. Once nominated,
the candidates each will be able to spend $67.6 million on the fall
campaign. Bush, if nominated, is considered likely to accept
federal funds for the general election. The figures are based on
1974 limits, adjusted for inflation.
</P>
<P>
   MOVEMENT BACK TOWARD THE CENTER
</P>
<P>
   George W. Bush, already backed by an unwavering bloc of
conservative voters, has started to go after John McCain's base of
support, appealing to moderates and independent voters by
emphasizing the compassionate side of his conservative message and
stressing issues with broad appeal, such as education. By stressing
the more moderate elements of his agenda, Bush can appeal to more
middle-of-the-road Republican voters in New York and New England
while also beginning his campaign against Al Gore, the likely
Democratic nominee.
</P>
<P>
   HEADS THEY WIN, TAILS THEY WIN
</P>
<P>
   Thirty-two companies or individuals made six-figure donations to
both the Republicans and Democrats last year, with AT&AMP;T the leading
corporate contributor, the advocacy group Common Cause reported.
``They give this money for one simple reason,'' said Common Cause
president Scott Harshbarger, ``They want something in return.''
AT&AMP;T, which gave $555,350 to the Democrats and $761,908 to the
Republicans, has opposed efforts to open its cable lines to
competing Internet providers and has fought requests by the Baby
Bell operating companies to offer long-distance telephone service.
</P>
<P>
   WHAT DO WE DO WITH SEAT BELT LAWS?
</P>
<P>
   After a first-grade girl was shot to death in a Michigan school,
George W. Bush struck a delicate balance on the politically
sensitive issue of childproof trigger locks. ``I hope people use
trigger locks,'' he said. But he stopped short of actively calling
for such a measure. He questioned whether trigger-lock laws could
be enforced, and talked about ``trigger lock police knocking on
peoples' doors, saying, `Show me your trigger locks, please?'''
</P>
<P>
   GUNS AND MONEY AND HYPOCRISY CHARGES
</P>
<P>
   As fatal shootings in Michigan and Pennsylvania were capturing
headlines, the rival New York Senate campaigns of Hillary Clinton
and Rudy Giuliani, both supporters of gun control, accused each
other of hypocrisy on gun violence. She had accepted a $1,000
contribution from rap artist Sean ``Puffy'' Combs, who was charged
with gun possession after a nightclub shooting; he accepted a
$1,000 contribution from Charlton Heston, president of the National
Rifle Association.
</P>
<P>
   GUNS AND AIRPORTS AND CRIMINAL CHARGES
</P>
<P>
   Peter Malvey, 34, of Barrington, N.H., who described himself as
a bodyguard for Alan Keyes, was arrested at JFK Airport in New York
for carrying a gun without a proper permit. Officials said Malvey
was at an airline terminal and handed authorities a Glock
semi-automatic pistol. Malvey was arrested on unlawful possession
charges. Port Authority spokesman Steve Coleman said Malvey denied
he was carrying any other weapons, but a luggage search found
another pistol, 29 rounds of .40-caliber ammunition, and 109 rounds
of .223-caliber ammunition.
</P>
<P>
   WOMEN AND JEWS SWINGING TO GIULIANI
</P>
<P>
   A statewide poll in New York released Thursday said Rudy
Giuliani, riding support from white women and Jewish voters, has
taken the lead over Hillary Clinton. The poll from the Quinnipiac
College Polling Institute (3 percentage point margin of error) had
Giuliani ahead 48 percent to 41 percent. But Giuliani leads 51
percent to 37 percent among white women and 48 percent to 38
percent among Jewish voters.
</P>
<P>
   A REFORMER WITHOUT RESULTS
</P>
<P>
   Reform Party presidential hopeful Pat Buchanan says he would be
the only true reformer in the race for the White House if John
McCain's and Bill Bradley's campaigns fail. ``I think when Bradley
and McCain fade away, there's only one reform candidate in the
race,'' Buchanan said Thursday. ``There's only one Reform Party,''
he added. ``We will have an agenda of reform that is broader and
deeper than any we've seen this year.''
</P>
<P>
   Compiled by Ernie Freda from staff and news reports
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists, visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
