<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ART-NOTES-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHORT ITEMS ON THE ART WORLD 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Ohio)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(af) 
 By CAROL VOGEL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Check-In Time
</P>
<P>
   After the success of Metrotech, the office complex in downtown
Brooklyn, N.Y., known for its dedication to showcasing public art,
its developer, Bruce C. Ratner, is once more trying his hand at
creating environments that focus on contemporary art. This time
Ratner is installing art in two new Manhattan hotels opening this
spring.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have a burning desire to own art, but I like the idea
of art in public places,'' said Ratner, chief executive of Forest
City Ratner Cos., an affiliate of Forest City Enterprises, based in
Cleveland.
</P>
<P>
   Forest City Ratner Cos. have invested $5 million in buying and
commissioning new works by artists like Sol LeWitt, Tom Otterness,
Pat Steir and Kurt Kauper. As he did when planning Metrotech,
Ratner collaborated with the nonprofit Public Art Fund, which
organizes displays of art around the city.
</P>
<P>
   ``The idea was to create a model for other buildings and to
expand the audience for contemporary art,'' said Susan K. Freeman,
president of the Public Art Fund. She said visiting these hotels
would be like spending ``a day in a gallery.''
</P>
<P>
   Art will be everywhere: in each guest room and in public spaces
like lobbies, restaurants and corridors.
</P>
<P>
   For the Embassy Suites Hotel, at 102 North End Ave. in Battery
Park City, LeWitt has created an 11-story mural, 80 feet tall and
130 feet wide, that will dominate an atrium. Called ``Loopy Doopy
(Blue and Purple)'' it is one of the his wall drawings, this one of
undulating lines in cobalt blue and deep purple. The work, painted
on a series of 460 panels, was fabricated in a 20,000-square-foot
warehouse at the Brooklyn Navy Yard.
</P>
<P>
   Stier has been commissioned to create a series of murals for the
Embassy Suites. The largest will be at the ground-level entrance,
and she will also provide murals for the hotel's two restaurants.
The mural in the lobby will have a deep-red line tracing the
history of drawing from pre-Columbian markings through contemporary
graphics.
</P>
<P>
   Meeting rooms and guest rooms will have prints by artists
including Roy Lichtenstein, Frank Stella and Ellsworth Kelly.
</P>
<P>
   Art for the Hilton Times Square, at 234 W. 42nd St., has
purposely been selected for its theatricality, Freedman said. The
marquees for the hotel's entrances on 41st and 42nd Streets will
feature the work of Otterness, a sculptor whose works are among the
most popular at Metrotech.
</P>
<P>
   He is once again using his signature Lilliputian bronze figures,
which will appear to be trying to topple a giant clock that tips
precariously from the marquees toward the sidewalk. His
rambunctious characters continue inside the hotel, with a host of
bronze figures, from diminutive tourists to larger-than-life
moguls.
</P>
<P>
   The ground-floor entrance will feature large-scale photographs
of old Times Square theaters taken by Andrew Moore. The figurative
painter Kurt Kauper has been commissioned to create paintings for
the lobby and a restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   A number of artists have been asked to create prints for the
hotel rooms, including well-known names like Mary Heilmann and
Elizabeth Peyton and some lesser-known artists like Sara Sosnowy,
an abstract painter. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Off the Wish List
</P>
<P>
   Last month the National Gallery of Art in Washington announced
that it would exhibit works from the collection of Barney A. and
Pam Ebsworth, St. Louis collectors of American art. Ebsworth, who
retired as the chairman of the travel company Intrav, has donated
several works to the museum over the years. It was understood when
the exhibition was conceived that more donations would be
forthcoming.
</P>
<P>
   So it comes as no surprise that this week the gallery has
received three more works from Ebsworth's collection: paintings by
Charles Sheeler, Arthur Dove and Bob Thompson. His choice was based
on knowing what was on the gallery's wish list.
</P>
<P>
   ``Barney was sensitive to chose works that would be important to
our permanent collection,'' said Earl A. Powell III, director of
the gallery.
</P>
<P>
   The Sheeler, ``Classic Landscape'' (1931), is the first of his
oils to enter the museum's collection and one of his best-known. It
depicts a scene from the Ford Motor Co.'s River Rouge Plant near
Detroit, which the artist visited in 1927.
</P>
<P>
   The Dove work, ``Moon'' (1935), is that artist's second oil on
canvas for the gallery. And Thompson's ``Tree,'' painted during a
stay in Paris in 1962 and derived from Goya's 1799 etchings ``Los
Caprichos,'' will be the first of his works to enter the museum's
holdings. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Prize by Design
</P>
<P>
   The latest trend among museums seems to be giving prizes. The
Tate Gallery's Turner Prize in London was the first. Then came the
Solomon R. Guggenheim with its Hugo Boss Prize. Just last month the
San Francisco Museum of Modern Art chimed in with its Webby Prize
for Excellence in Online Art.
</P>
<P>
   Now the Cooper-Hewitt, the National Design Museum that is part
of the Smithsonian Institution, has announced that it will be
giving National Design Awards.
</P>
<P>
   The annual prizes will go to five recipients whose work
demonstrates extraordinary vision and contributes to the nation's
quality of life. Unlike the other prizes, these carry no cash
awards. Winners will be chosen from a jury that includes David
Kelly, co-founder of IDEO, the largest industrial design concern in
the United States; the architect Daniel Libeskind; and Martha
Stewart, the home-design guru.
</P>
<P>
   The museum has also appointed a nominating committee of more
than 250 leading design professionals and architects.
</P>
<P>
   The five awards will be divided into three categories: a
lifetime achievement award, a corporate achievement award and three
design achievement awards given to individuals or companies for
exceptional work. Winners and their work will serve as the basis
for educational programs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Design has been left behind over the years,'' said Kay
Allaire, a Cooper-Hewitt board member who is chairman of the
National Design Awards. ``We felt it was important to develop a
prize that would help give more national awareness to design.'' The
first winners are to be announced in November. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-02-00 1749EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
