<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Friday, March 3, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) 
(jt) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST
</P>
<P>
   Gusty winds from the northwest will continue to draw chilly air
from eastern Canada into the Northeastern States. Periods of snow
will linger in eastern Maine as ocean moisture circulates around a
slow moving storm center near Nova Scotia. Snow showers will dust
the high ground from the Adirondacks of New York to the Green and
White Mountains of New England. Farther south, most of the interior
Northeast will have a mixture of sunshine and some puffy cumulus
clouds. Sunshine will be ample across the Middle Atlantic States.
</P>
<P>
   A cool rain will fall north of a low pressure center as it moves
from the southern Mississippi Valley into the Tennessee Valley. The
steadiest rain will occur across southern Missouri and northern
Arkansas. A broken band of showers and a few strong thunderstorms
will form in the warmer, more humid air near the western and
central Gulf of Mexico coast.
</P>
<P>
   Dry weather will cover a large area from the east slopes of the
Rockies to the Great Lakes States. The day will begin with areas of
low clouds across the central Plains. Otherwise, plentiful sunshine
will boost temperatures far above the seasonal average across these
regions.
</P>
<P>
   Variable clouds and few showers will surround low pressure near
the southern California coast. The precipitation will be most
prevalent over the higher terrain where some snow may be mixed with
the rain. Farther north, the latest in a series of Pacific fronts
will send rain toward the Pacific Northwest Coast.
</P>
<P>
   Looking for Patterns
</P>
<P>
   Last month was the sixth warmest February on record at Amarillo,
Texas. Also on the list of Amarillo's six all-time warmest
Februarys are 1932, 1954, 1976 and 1999, suggesting a pattern of
about 22 years. History is replete with weather patterns, but most
eventually break down, depriving forecasters of a powerful tool. It
is curious to note that the pattern of warm Februarys at Amarillo
closely follows a rhythm of the cycle of solar maxima. Scientists
have long searched for reliable patterns of weather on earth that
could be directly linked to the cycles of solar output. The search
continues.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
