<HEADLINE>
SHORT ITEMS ON HOME VIDEOS 
</HEADLINE>
  (af) 
 By PETER M. NICHOLS 
  
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   `Eyes Wide Shut,' With Extras
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, Warner will release ``Eyes Wide Shut,'' Stanley
Kubrick's much-debated film about the outer reaches of sexual
jealousy, on tape and DVD. Videocassette is adequate for taking in
the glossy tribulations of Bill and Alice Harford (Tom Cruise and
Nicole Kidman) after Alice riles Bill with a tale of her lust for
another man and sends him reeling into the night on a round of his
own explorations.
</P>
<P>
   But there being practically no middle ground of critical opinion
when it comes to this film, the added features on the DVD version
($24.98) are interesting, at least to a point.
</P>
<P>
   In separate interviews Cruise and Kidman talk about Kubrick, who
died last March, and working on the film, which opened in theaters
in July. In a third interview, Steven Spielberg, who had nothing to
do with ``Eyes Wide Shut'' but occasionally discussed films with
Kubrick, makes some overall comments about the director and his
work.
</P>
<P>
   While the three don't get into much depth or stray from the
guarded critical straight and narrow, viewers are free to make
between-the-lines interpretations on such matters as Kubrick's
obsessive slowness _ for instance, his inclination to shoot some
scenes 50 times or more _ his supposed lack of interest in the
inner lives of his characters and his rather odd way with a story.
</P>
<P>
   Some critics felt the film was wooden. Cruise describes being
totally absorbed in his role, but he does fondly allude to the fact
that the shoot began to run on a bit (a year, in fact). ``Stanley
would say, `We have got to earn every scene with this character,
earn every single moment.' At times we just couldn't get it _ you
know, you don't have that fire burning that day.''
</P>
<P>
   The days were adding up. Cruise had a company to run, scripts to
assess, writers waiting. ``I said, `Stanley, I don't care how long
it takes, but I have to know, are we going to finish in six months?
This after six months.''
</P>
<P>
   Later he readdressed the issue. ``I said, `Tell me it's going to
be two years, Stanley, I don't care.''' Kubrick replied: `Don't be
ridiculous, Tom. If it takes that long, everything they say about
us is true.'''
</P>
<P>
   Kidman notes that scenes didn't always require 50 takes; Kubrick
could be fast. ``Stanley was always waiting for something to
happen,'' she said. ``Always looking for something that surprised
him or piqued his interest. It was about exploring all facets of it
so he could go into the editing room.''
</P>
<P>
   Frequently that was after many takes. ``He made sure he
discovered everything there was to discover in the material,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   Spielberg sums up. Kubrick films tend to grow on you, he said,
perhaps to remind viewers not to lock in their judgments about this
one. You have to watch them more than once. With Kubrick, craft was
paramount. ``Nobody could shoot a picture better in history,''
Spielberg says. But Kubrick stories could be frustrating. ``The way
he tells a story is antithetical to the way we are accustomed to
receiving stories,'' he said. Kubrick was always changing the form.
``He was a chameleon. He never made the same picture twice _
different genre, different period, different story, different risk.
The only thing that bonded them was craft.'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A Hundred and One Nights
</P>
<P>
   Conjuring grand allusions, Agnes Varda salutes 100 years of
movies with scores of clips from films and reflections from the
stars. For example, Marcello Mastroianni argues about bathtub
scenes with Michael Piccoli (left), who presides over the film in a
baronial chateau.
</P>
<P>
   One of the odder movie bits shows Robert De Niro floating along
in a swan boat with Catherine Deneuve to the tune of ``Sentimental
Journey.'' Nevertheless, Janet Maslin wrote in The New York Times,
``whenever Varda galls her audience with such fluff, all she needs
is a clip from `Pickpocket' or `The General' to make things
right.''
</P>
<P>
   1995. Winstar. $89.98; DVD, $89.98. 101 minutes. French with
English subtitles. No rating. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The Best Man
</P>
<P>
   Harper (Taye Diggs) is the kind of novelist who has his book
chosen by Oprah Winfrey's book club and floats in a candlelit bath
full of rose petals. Titled ``Unfinished Business,'' his novel has
a character closely resembling an old flame (Nia Long), whom he
re-encounters and has a tryst with in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Back home, his loyal love (Sanaa Lathan) stays true blue,
demonstrating that ``current movies about upscale black characters
have much more solid traditional values than ones about catty white
teen-agers'' (Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   1999. Universal $107.37; DVD, $24.98. 118 minutes. Closed
captioned. R. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A Dog of Flanders
</P>
<P>
   Missing no opportunity to oversentimentalize, Kevin Brodie's
adaptation of the children's tale by Ouida, set in 19th-century
Flanders, takes a poor boy named Nello (Jeremy James Klissner and
Jesse James) and his shaggy sheep dog, Patrasche, on a bumpy trip
to the realization that Nello may be a rich kid after all.
</P>
<P>
   After an unpromising apprenticeship hauling milk for his
grandfather (Jack Warden), Nello is taken in hand by the painter
Michel La Grande (Jon Voight), who sees artistic promise in the
lad. But a charge of arson and eviction into a blizzard don't make
the going easier in a film ``clogged with sticky-sweet pieties
cooed to saucer-eyed tots'' (Stephen Holden).
</P>
<P>
   1999. Warner. $19.98. 90 minutes. Closed captioned. PG. Release
date: March 7. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Sitcom
</P>
<P>
   Francois Ozon's film begins promisingly with the sounds of
screaming and gunfire disturbing the suburban calm. It seems the
Father (Francois Marthouret) is displeased with his surprise
birthday party. Through flashbacks we meet the Mother (Evelyne
Dandry), a fusser and fretter, and their son (Adrien De Van), who
declares himself gay, and daughter (Maria De Van), who has an
erotic encounter with a rat, jumps out a window and becomes a
paraplegic dominatrix. Though filmed with the look of a television
comedy, ``Sitcom'' can't conceal ``a sour streak that eventually
poisons its humor'' (Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   1999. New Yorker. $94.98. 80 minutes. French with English
subtitles. No rating. Release date: March 7. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Other new titles of interest, some of which may have had a
theater release, appeared on television or been on videocassette in
earlier editions. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A FINE ROMANCE and two other British television comedies, NO,
HONESTLY and COLD COMFORT FARM, are available in three boxed sets.
In the 1980s series ``A Fine Romance'' (three cassettes, $39.95,
225 minutes), a high-powered translator (Dame Judi Dench) and a
landscape gardener (Michael Williams, Dame Judi's husband) are
thrown together by a matchmaking sister and brother-in-law. Going
back a decade earlier, ``No, Honestly'' (three cassettes, $39.95,
175 minutes) matches an unemployed actor (John Alderton) and a
debutante and aspiring writer (Pauline Collins) who look back on
the rocky beginnings of their relationship. Adapted from Stella
Gibbons' 1932 satire, the BBC's 1968 ``Cold Comfort Farm'' (three
cassettes, $39.95, 135 minutes) stars Sarah Bedel as the orphaned
London urbanite who retreats to rural Sussex and undertakes to
salvage her Gothic agrarian relatives. Acorn Media. Information:
(800) 474-2277. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   THE FIRST WALTZ. Billy Corgan of Smashing Pumpkins, Cheap Trick,
the Bodeans and many others join the Nicholas Tremulis Band in a
concert to benefit homeless teen-agers. 1999. Palm Pictures.
$14.95, with profits going to the Neon Street Program for Homeless
Youth. Information: www.palmpictures.com. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   FROZEN. To protest repression, a Chinese performance artist
freezes himself to death in a block of ice. That's not pleasant,
but along with other acts of rebellion it is thought-provoking.
1998. Winstar. $89.98. 95 minutes. Mandarin, with English
subtitles. No rating. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-02-00 1754EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000302.0253 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-02 17:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4849 &Cx1f; tth-z
r e BC-FILM-SKIP-SPI &LR;      03-02 0489
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-SKIP-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TENDER `MY DOG SKIP' TUGS AT THE HEARTSTRINGS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By PAULA NECHAK  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Why does the South evoke such nostalgia? The film world has long
embraced its humid atmosphere, struggling to replicate a bygone
world _ culled largely from literature _ where there's not much to
do and nowhere to go yet there's danger and tension lurking beneath
the surface.
</P>
<P>
   Think of the film adaptation of Harper Lee's ``To Kill a
Mockingbird'' or the woeful cast of misfits in movies based on
Carson McCuller's ``The Heart Is a Lonely Hunter'' and ``A Member
of the Wedding.'' A gruff, comical friction and begrudging respect
lingered beneath the racial and class lines of ``Driving Miss
Daisy,'' while ``Fried Green Tomatoes'' cast a spell with its
eccentric characters, focusing on the wild moments at the town's
Whistlestop Cafe.
</P>
<P>
   Add a pet dog to the mix and the formula proves purely
irresistible. ``My Dog Skip'' is adapted from writer Willie Morris'
simple, elegant and understated memoir of a World War II-era
childhood in Mississippi.
</P>
<P>
   In it, he recounts the life lessons learned as an only child who
received ``an only dog,'' a Jack Russell terrier he names Skip, on
his ninth birthday. Together, beginning in 1942, the pair comb the
lazy town of Yazoo, where there were ``10,000 souls and nothin'
doin''' except reading the paper for news about America's role in
the war, going swimming, playing baseball and living an idyllic
life today's kids can only dream of.
</P>
<P>
   That's not to say that bookish, shy Willie (Frankie ``Malcolm in
the Middle'' Muniz) and Skip don't get into mischief. Indeed, for a
town as serene as Yazoo, much happens to the boy, to the
consternation of his gregarious mom (Diane Lane), taciturn dad
(Kevin Bacon) and Willie's friend and neighbor _ golden son and
athlete Dink Jenkins (Luke Wilson), who is about to ship out for
active duty.
</P>
<P>
   The film captures the pain of being alone, of failure, anger and
the illusions that shroud the glory of war as well as the code of
honor and ethics that surround the notion of heroism. More, it
shows in its inimitable, quiet way, the hard-won bonds of loyalty
and love that Skip teaches and which are, as Morris says in
voiceover, ``the most lasting.''
</P>
<P>
   ``My Dog Skip'' has its lapses, but it kept a preview audience
in tears. As a family film about a boy and his dog, it brings back
memories of ``Old Yeller,'' ``Big Red'' and ``The Incredible
Journey,'' which also taught kids about life, its hardships and
joys, and how important that first beloved pet can be. And it works
because it never tries to be more than the very personal memory
piece it is.
</P>
<P>
   My Dog Skip. Directed by Jay Russell. Written by Gail Gilcriest.
Cast: Kevin Bacon, Diane Lane, Luke Wilson, Frankie Muniz. Warner
Bros. 93 minutes. Rated PG for animal violence.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B+
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-02-00 1756EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000302.0254 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-02 17:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4851 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-STUDENT-MUSIC-ART-780     03-02 0837
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STUDENT-MUSIC-ART-780(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OH MOM, I'M SICK OF FUER ELISE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(jt) 
 By ANTHONY TOMMASINI    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Children taking piano lessons today can choose from
an extensive repertory of elementary-level pieces by the greatest
of composers. Bach and Schumann wrote volumes of such works, though
they had personal as well as pedagogical reasons to do so: both
were doting fathers. Lots of little minuets and dance pieces by
Mozart are ideal for children, which only makes sense: he composed
them when he was a child himself. Beethoven wrote quite a few works
for beginning-level pianists, though he may have been motivated
more by a chance to make extra money than by genuine affection for
children. Still, the Minuet in G and ``Fuer Elise'' have been
played by grateful youngsters ever since.
</P>
<P>
   The practice of providing pieces for students to play continued
in the 20th century with composers like Igor Stravinsky, Dmitri
Kabalevsky, Ross Lee Finney and Gyorgy Kurtag. Bela Bartok alone
composed a whole catalog of teaching pieces including six volumes
of ``Mikrokosmos,'' which begin with simple five-finger exercises
and progress to works of considerable difficulty.
</P>
<P>
   But few works by 20th-century composers are pegged to students
at an intermediate level. That void worried the composer Ellen
Taaffe Zwilich, who is very involved in music education. In 1997
while composer in residence at Carnegie Hall, Zwilich decided to do
something about it.
</P>
<P>
   She approached Judith Arron, who was then the executive and
artistic director of Carnegie Hall, and together they commissioned
10 international composers to write piano works of an intermediate
level. Those who accepted ranged from the imposing Serialist Milton
Babbitt to the composer known as Hannibal, whose music is steeped
in spirituals learned while working in the cotton fields of Texas
and drum rhythms assimilated while living in Africa.
</P>
<P>
   The pieces have just been published by Boosey &AMP; Hawkes as the
``Carnegie Hall Millennium Piano Book.'' The volume includes a CD
of all the works, performed by the pianist Ursula Oppens, a
champion of contemporary music. And Thursday night Oppens will
participate with four young conservatory student pianists in a
concert at Weill Recital Hall in which all 10 pieces will receive
their world premieres.
</P>
<P>
   The dearth of contemporary intermediate-level works has several
possible explanations. In earlier times amateur music-making
flourished even in middle-class households: if you wanted music in
your daily life you had to make it yourself. That once-vibrant
tradition has never recovered from the invention of the radio and
the phonograph. Another factor may be the increasing complexity and
specialization of 20th-century music, which has tended to put off
audiences and isolate composers.
</P>
<P>
   The void has made it harder for new music to reach people. In
the 19th century amateurs at home and students in conservatories
could immerse themselves in the music of their own time. Today,
after children practice their elementary pieces by Bach and Bartok,
they can generally turn only to earlier centuries for
intermediate-level works.
</P>
<P>
   Zwilich, who inaugurated several educational projects during her
tenure at Carnegie Hall, thought that addressing this ``vacuum in
the piano repertory'' was important.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have lost some noble traditions in our time,'' she said in
a recent telephone interview from her home in Florida. ``As
composers we ought to be able to speak to all different people,
including students and amateurs.'' Arron (who would die of breast
cancer in 1998) agreed completely and secured financial backing
from the Irving S. Gilmore International Keyboard Festival, with
additional support from the Mary Flagler Cary Charitable Trust.
</P>
<P>
   Arron and Zwilich recruited the composers, looking especially at
those who had ``never done this kind of thing before,'' Zwilich
said. Besides Babbitt, the roster includes brainy contemporary
masters like Elliott Carter whose works are known for their
difficulty.
</P>
<P>
   The other composers in this wildly varied ``Millennium Piano
Book'' are Wolfgang Rihm, the formidable German; Frederic Rzewski,
an American best known for his pummeling, virtuosic 50-minute piano
piece, ``The People United Will Never Be Defeated!''; John
Harbison, whose much-debated opera, ``The Great Gatsby,'' was
recently given its Metropolitan Opera premiere; two Chinese-born
composers, Tan Dun and Chen Yi; and Zwilich.
</P>
<P>
   While seeking diversity in composers, Zwilich adamantly avoided
stipulating just what constitutes an intermediate-level piano
piece. The resulting works range from the fairly playable, meaning
not overly taxing for the fingers and concentration, to the
considerably difficult.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Reflecting on the Millennium Book pieces recently in her Upper
West Side studio, Oppens conceded that some of them were quite
hard, Babbitt's in particular. ``It's a fancy, elegant and spiffy
piece, but it's difficult,'' she said. She pointed to four others
that would reasonably be considered of intermediate level by any
student pianist. Rihm's ``Zwiesprache'' is a set of five
meditative, languidly lyrical memorial pieces. Louis Andriessen's
``Image de Moreau'' is a Minimalistic swirl of chords and colors.
Harbison's ``On an Unwritten Letter'' alternates subdued chorale
passages with animated contrapuntal writing in two parts. And there
is Zwilich's ``Lament,'' written in memory of Arron.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was working on my Fourth Symphony, when the call came from
Carnegie Hall abut Judy's death,'' Zwilich said. ``I sat at my desk
and this thing poured out of me.''
</P>
<P>
   Though not challenging technically, she added, the piece is
challenging musically. The pianist must work hard to highlight and
project a slow-moving lyrical line that runs through the work. The
piece also calls for extensive use of rubato, that is, rhythmic
freedom; but the use of rubato has ``a structural meaning and is
not just an expressive indulgence,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Then there are works like Chen's ``Ba Ban,'' filled with
swirling figurations, and Rzewski's propulsive ``The Days Fly By,''
which make big effects through modest technical means. There is a
long tradition of such works. Quite a few Liszt pieces lie fairly
easily in the fingers but are calculated to impress. Summing up the
overall level of difficulty in the works, Oppens said, ``the
average is intermediate.''
</P>
<P>
   So, if most of the pieces in this collection are not going to be
played by children in the middle grades, they might be taken up by
college and conservatory students who have steered clear of
contemporary music because of the difficulty involved.
</P>
<P>
   In Thursday night's concert, Oppens will perform the works by
Harbison and Tan Dun. Four students who were selected through a
sort of uncompetitive competition will play the other eight.
</P>
<P>
   ``Carnegie Hall felt that a real competition would be
inappropriate and undoable,'' Oppens said. ``So, I paired the
pieces in groups of two and sent them to four conservatories and
asked each, by whatever means they wanted, to have two students
learn the pieces and submit tapes.''
</P>
<P>
   The tapes were listened to blindly. Those selected were: Ofra
Yitzhaki, an Israeli pianist pursuing a master's degree at
Juilliard; a Wisconsin native, Kuang-Hao Huang, who is doing
doctoral work at Northwestern University; Kozue Jinnouchi, the
bachelor of music program at the Eastman School of Music, and
Kirill Gerstein, who moved to New York six years ago from Russia
and is now a student at the Manhattan School of Music.
</P>
<P>
   Gerstein recently spent an afternoon at Oppens' studio being
coached in the Rihm and Carter works he will play Thursday night.
The title of Carter's ``Two Diversions'' suggests that the music is
supposed to be diverting. The notes and rhythms are undeniably
tough to master. The music could be called intermediate-level in
that each piece presents a straightforward musical challenge. The
first involves just two elements: a slow lyrical line that threads
through the piece and a contrasting fanciful line that continually
darts about. In the second piece two rather independent voices get
respectively faster and slower at the same time.
</P>
<P>
   ``To be honest,'' Gerstein said before playing the pieces for
Oppens, ``I did find the Carter to be not an easy thing to learn.
It was a good healthy challenge. I learned a lot in the process.''
</P>
<P>
   As he sat down at Oppens' piano that day, he placed on the music
stand a huge rectangle of cardboard on which the pages of the
score, in photocopied reductions, had been pasted so that he would
not have to deal with page turns. He called it his ``road map.''
</P>
<P>
   As he plays, it is clear to Oppens that the young pianist,
tackling his first Carter work, has studied its notes, rhythms and
structure quite carefully. He finds great color in the music. She
feels, though, that he is not making sufficient contrasts between
the two elements in the first Diversion.
</P>
<P>
   ''One line should be slow and steady,'' she explains. ``The
other should be as varied, operatic and imaginative as possible.''
Gerstein's overall tempo is a bit fast, she thinks. ``What you are
doing is real good,'' she adds, ``but it's worth making sure that
the tempi are perfect. The idea is to be exceedingly expressive
without doing things to the tempo itself.''
</P>
<P>
   To help him relax with the music, Oppens, a formidable
technician, offers some self-effacing encouragement. ``I can't
really hear counterpoint anyway,'' she said, ``so I just take turns
hearing each voice, and it works for the listener.''
</P>
<P>
   In another place, where she feels that Gerstein is a bit
constrained, she says, ``That's where I really try to let the hands
be separated and just hope that they will wind up in the same
place.'' Gerstein tries the passage again, and the difference is
striking. His playing is fanciful and the skittish lines finally
evoke the diverting quality of the title.
</P>
<P>
   To Carter, ``Two Diversions'' is an intermediate-level piano
piece. Expanding on why he had not written such works before, he
explained that composers in the highly experimental 20th century
had to labor hard to come up with a distinctive style. ``It's
difficult to write something simplified that represents your
style,'' he said. ``We try to find our own voice and sing;
sometimes we don't sing simply.''
</P>
<P>
   Gerstein found the effort of learning Carter's piece well worth
it. ``At first it was rather confusing,'' he said, ``but I find
that the more I play it and live with it, the more clarity it has
for me. Now it seems just a clean combination of different lines.
It seems to be simple, in a good sense.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   That Gerstein has come to that realization and is game to try
other, harder, contemporary works, seems an endorsement for the
Millennium Piano Book project. Zwilich has only one more hope:
``I'd be happy if every composer in the world would get this book,
say, `Gee, I could do better than that,' and sit down and try the
same thing.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
