<SLUG> BC-FILM-MONA-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`DROWNING `MONA' FINDS BOTH GOOD HUMOR AND BAD TASTE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By PAULA NECHAK  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   More and more nasty comedies _ whether about romance (the
terribly foul ``Love Stinks''), music (``Detroit Rock City'') or
something altogether different _ have been vying to topple Bobby
and Peter Farrelly's ``Kingpin'' and ``There's Something About
Mary'' from the top of the bad-taste throne.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the contenders are unredemptive, vile treatises on the
worst sides of human nature.
</P>
<P>
   The latest entry, ``Drowning Mona,'' scores high on nastiness,
but it has as many surprisingly funny moments as offensive ones.
</P>
<P>
   The film, directed by Nick Gomez, reunites Danny DeVito (whose
company also produced the film) and Bette Midler, who starred in
the 1986 hit ``Ruthless People.''
</P>
<P>
   Mona Dearly (Midler) is the most foul-mouthed, ill-tempered
resident of Yerplanck, N.Y., a town full of white trash, Yugo
drivers and bad haircuts. When her Yugo goes off a cliff and sinks
into the lake, drowning the much-loathed woman, the whole community
celebrates. ``I bet property values go up,'' chortles one, while
another quips, ``I've seen people more upset at losing change in a
candy machine.''
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, Police Chief Rash (DeVito) is called in to
investigate what appears to be a routine accident. But he soon
learns the car's brakes were sabotaged and the death was actually
murder. But since everyone either hated and/or feared Mona, he's
got scads of suspects.
</P>
<P>
   They include Mona's dumb-as-a-post, one-handed son Jeff (Marcus
Thomas), her cheating husband Phil (William Fichtner), diner
waitress Rona Mace (Jamie Lee Curtis) and, at the top of the list,
young Bobby Calzone (Casey Affleck). Bobby is Jeff's landscaping
business partner and harbors serious grudges against both Mona and
her ineffectual, lazy, beer-swilling son, who is about to drive
Bobby to bankruptcy. But Bobby is about to be married to Rash's
beloved daughter Ellen (Neve Campbell), who has her own reasons to
dislike Mona and Jeff.
</P>
<P>
   ``Drowning Mona'' sifts through the convoluted lives and
relationships of this group of misfits and, for its first
two-thirds, is quite funny and involving. But like most movies
these days, it doesn't quite know how to tie up its loose ends and
settles more for convenience than ingenuity.
</P>
<P>
   Drowning Mona. Directed by Nick Gomez. Written by Peter
Steinfeld. Cast: Bette Midler, Danny DeVito, Neve Campbell, Jamie
Lee Curtis, William Fichtner, Casey Affleck. Destination Films. 91
minutes. Rated R for language, violence.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-02-00 1801EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000302.0258 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-02 18:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4858 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-SAPIENS-FILM-REVIEW-N     03-02 0700
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SAPIENS-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`HOMO SAPIENS 1900': PERFECTING EUGENICS IS AS HARD AS PERFECTING
PEOPLE 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Production notes are at end of review) 
(af) 
 By STEPHEN HOLDEN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   There's something intrinsically creepy about the scientific
quest to create a new and improved human being, and ``Homo Sapiens
1900,'' Peter Cohen's unsettling documentary history of eugenics,
mercilessly zeroes in on exactly what that is.
</P>
<P>
   In turning people into laboratory specimens and using genetic
theory to try to breed superior strains of people, scientists play
God by making value judgments about the most desirable human
qualities, usually deemed to be measurable intelligence and
physical endowment.
</P>
<P>
   But the declaration of a hierarchy of human traits leaves those
decreed genetically inferior vulnerable to all sorts of abuses,
from sterilization to outright murder. And as the film makes
abundantly clear, eugenic theory has always been used to justify
the most virulent racism in the name of science. Societies usually
define the ideal human as having the physical characteristics of
the ethnic majority.
</P>
<P>
   ``Homo Sapiens 1900,'' which opens Friday in New York, is so
solemn that in many places it looks and sounds like a horror film.
Beginning with a scene from ``Frankenstein,'' it is filled with
ominous images of grim know-it-all doctors in white coats,
elaborate diagrams of family trees, and disturbing pictures of the
deformed and mentally ill, photographed to look like monstrous
biological mutations.
</P>
<P>
   Accompanying the images is a dry, authoritative voice-over
narration by Steven Rappaport, who delivers a fact-filled history
of the eugenics movement from its development in the 19th century
by Sir Francis Galton in England and Gregor Johann Mendel in
Austria to the recent past.
</P>
<P>
   The film's most appalling moment is an excerpt from a silent
film, ``The Black Stork,'' in which Dr. Harry Haiselden, an
American proponent of euthanasia, imperiously tells nurses in a
hospital which fragile newborn babies should be left to die.
</P>
<P>
   From its beginnings, eugenics has intrigued national leaders who
have adapted its theories to suit their political agendas. The
Soviet Union was the center of a shifting debate as to whether
acquired characteristics could be inherited. In its early years,
the brains of gifted artists, scientists and political leaders
(including Lenin) became the fetishized objects of scientific
study, the ideal being to create and produce a society of supermen
in only a few generations.
</P>
<P>
   But later, under Stalin, when the mass production of food and
supplies became an urgent priority, the more grandiose eugenic
theorists were brutally silenced, and the ideal Soviet citizen of
the future became an efficient, obedient cog in a smoothly whirring
machine.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, in Germany, perfect physical specimens who conformed
to classically defined stereotypes became the genetic goal. But
there, too, eugenic fantasy clashed with social policy. Nazi
Germany's idealization of the family ensured that the notion of
Aryan breeding farms for the production of a master race barely got
off the ground.
</P>
<P>
   In the United States the vogue for eugenics in the early 20th
century led to the enactment of compulsive sterilization laws in 20
states by 1907, but the vogue faded because the accompanying
culture was so reactionary.
</P>
<P>
   The filmmaker, whose 1989 documentary ``The Architecture of
Doom'' explored the relationship between aesthetics and violence in
Nazi Germany, is an outspoken opponent of eugenic science's ``dream
of a measurable man'' and argues that there is still no way to
program or predict actual human achievement.
</P>
<P>
   That may be so. But as modern genetic engineering gallops
forward with one breakthrough after another, the Frankensteinian
impulse to improve the species is as alive as ever. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES: &QL;
</P>
<P>
   `HOMO SAPIENS 1900'
</P>
<P>
   Written, edited, produced and directed by Peter Cohen; directors
of photography, Peter Ostlund and Mats Lund; music by Matti Bye;
released by First Run Features. Running time: 85 minutes. This film
is not rated.
</P>
<P>
   With: Steven Rappaport (Narrator). &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-02-00 1802EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
