<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COX NEWS SERVICE BUSINESS BUDGET
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   These business stories for release Friday, March 3, 2000, are
moving today to clients of the New York Times News Service.
</P>
<P>
   Stories are moving in the financial (f) category. Stories also
moving in lifestyle will be marked with (f, l).
</P>
<P>
   Separate budgets move daily with spot news, features, sports and
commentary.
</P>
<P>
   If you have questions or need a resend, please call CoxNet, the
Cox News Service, at 404-526-5456.
</P>
<P>
   CINNABON _ Cinnabon plans to roll out a new prototype at about
100 bakeries by the end of the year. At the same time, the AFC
division hope to sell between 30 and 50 units within the next five
years to franchisees. (Poole, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   WAFFLEHOUSE-BIAS _ A Waffle House manager in South Carolina is
suing the Atlanta based restaurant chain for racial basis. The
manager claims he was fired because he refused to fire black
employees at his restaruant in order to be reflective of the
population of the community. (Poole, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   BELLSOUTH-TAKEOVER _ BellSouth has been bandied about as a
possible takeover target for Deutche Telkom for months. Indeed,
it's US headquarters is in Colony Square, right across from
Campanile, BellSouth's hq. They have teamed up a number of times.
Where does DT's bid for Qwest (in which BS owns a 10% stake) and
U.S. West leave BellSouth? (Kanell, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
40.
</P>
<P>
   STOCKFRAUD-HEARING _ Peter Lybrand/Tosto, the guy who allegedly
ran a $12 million international stock fraud scheme out of a former
Madison dime store, has his bail hearing in NYC today. The Asst. US
Atty. will argue why he should be kept in jail until trial. Story
should have more detail about why he is a threat to flee or a
danger to the community. (Clothier, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
12.
</P>
<P>
   DELTA _ A spat between Delta and Northwest airlines over fares
listed in Priceline.com has grown into a running feud. Northwest
for several months has offered special low fares from Atlanta on
its own website, a protest to the fact that it can't do so on
Priceline because of an exclusivity clause negotiated by Delta. On
Wednesday the battle escalated when Northwest rolled out an ad
saying Delta ``won't allow Atlanta to receive competitive Priceline
fares.'' Delta has retaliated by offering specials on its website
on flights from Northwest hubs. (Thurston, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
