<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-02 18:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4863 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w BC-NUKE-SECURITY-HNS &LR;      03-02 0707
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NUKE-SECURITY-HNS </SLUG>
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; HOUSE PANEL BLASTS RICHARDSON ON NUCLEAR AGENCY &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; By JUDY HOLLAND &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; C.2000Hearst Newspapers  &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Republicans and Democrats on a congressional panel
Thursday criticized Energy Secretary Bill Richardson for what they
said was his failure to follow instructions on how to set up a new
agency that would be responsible for the U.S. nuclear weapons
program.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Floyd Spence, R-S.C., chairman of the House Armed Service
Committee, told Richardson that the reorganization was designed to
correct the ``confused lines of authority and reporting chains that
have troubled the department since the very beginning.''
</P>
<P>
   But Spence said Richardson has preserved much of the old system
even as he put together the staff for the new semi-autonomous
agency _ the National Nuclear Security Administration _ within the
department.
</P>
<P>
   Spence said he has ``serious concerns'' about Richardson's
decision to ``dual-hat'' Energy Department employees so they also
fill key positions in the new nuclear agency.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is my view that this (dual-hatting) approach is in direct
and clear violation of congressional intent,'' Spence said. He
added that he thinks Richardson intended to ``ensure that the
existing organizational structure, lines of authority and fiscal
and managerial practices of DOE remain intact.''
</P>
<P>
   Congress ordered the reorganization of the Energy Department
last fall after allegations that China had stolen sensitive nuclear
secrets because of poor security and mismanagement at weapons
laboratories run by the department. Congressional investigators
blamed confused responsibilities and lack of accountability within
the department.
</P>
<P>
   Richardson has resisted the reorganization on the basis that it
would reduce his authority.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Ellen Tauscher, D-Calif., the top Democrat on the special
House panel that oversees the reorganization of the Department of
Energy, said in an interview that Richardson has set up a
management structure that looks ``like Frankenstein's brain on
fire,'' adding: ``We want a simple channeling of authority.''
</P>
<P>
   She said Richardson's plan for the new nuclear agency is ``a
missed opportunity'' to alleviate 20 years of mismanagement of
nuclear weapons programs.
</P>
<P>
   She said the Energy Department's management of the nation's
nuclear weapons programs is a ``bureaucratic kudzu-laden tangle''
that has jeopardized ``our prize nuclear secrets.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Duncan Hunter, R-Calif., told Richardson that the
department's handling of the country's nuclear weapons laboratories
has been ``abysmal'' and that the new arrangement is going to
``degrade security.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You're still going to have a situation in which confusion can
reign,'' Hunter said.
</P>
<P>
   Richardson, responding that he did not intend to subvert the
legislation, said only 18 of the 2,014 employees of the new
National Nuclear Security administration hold positions in both the
nuclear agency and the Energy Department. They include attorneys,
field managers, members of a judicial board that resolves agency
disputes and a counter-intelligence official. Richardson said he
``firmly believes'' it is both efficient and legal for him to place
employees with overlapping authority in the new agency and in the
department.
</P>
<P>
   ``I intend to keep those dual-hatted employees where they are to
avoid duplication,'' Richardson said. ``I have to manage this
agency and I believe this is the best way to avoid duplication.''
</P>
<P>
   Tauscher told Richardson that six of the 18 people who serve in
double roles are ``actually the very top leaders of the new
organization. That is my concern, some of these people are very key
people and very significant players.''
</P>
<P>
   The intent of Congress was ``not to take the existing agency and
change the name and have them wink at us,'' she said later. ``It
was not our intent to have dual-hatting.''
</P>
<P>
   Richardson announced that he is recommending that President
Clinton nominate Air Force Gen. John A. Gordon as the first
director of the new nuclear agency for a three-year term.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Judy Holland can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at the e-mail
address Judy(at)hearstdc.com.)
</P>
</TEXT>
