<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-02 18:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4864 &Cx1f; tth-z
r e BC-FILM-PEOPLE-SPI &LR;      03-02 0420
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-PEOPLE-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`PEOPLE' SUCCESSFULLY MESHES HUMOR AND WAR-TORN BOSNIA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By PAULA NECHAK  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Yugoslav director Jasmin Dizdar's colorful first feature opens
in a burst of energy and never lets up.
</P>
<P>
   It's about melting-pot London and a group of residents whose
lives run parallel and perpendicular, no matter what their
ethnicity. The film refers comically and tragically to the war in
Bosnia and the refugees who land on the city's doorstep.
</P>
<P>
   Yet it has a vibrancy, offbeat optimism and hope despite its
subtext of prejudice, pain, isolation and death.
</P>
<P>
   The clashes between immigrants and the British are comically,
painfully and sometimes heartbreakingly observed.
</P>
<P>
   And there is a subversive strain at play under the vibrant and
colorful surface of the film.
</P>
<P>
   Its characters fight, get high, rebel and learn a lesson about
another way of life, sometimes falling into star-crossed love.
Dizdar elicits a messy, restless, bright and barmy look at the
world and its universal enlightening lessons.
</P>
<P>
   The inhabitants of the London melting pot include Griffin (Danny
Nussbaum), a teenager who is into drugs but gets a second chance
when a freak coincidence literally drops him into another world;
Portia (Charlotte Coleman), a doctor and daughter of rich political
parents, falls in love with poor Bosnian refugee Pero (Edin
Dzandzanovic); and Dr. Mouldy (Nicholas Farrell), a harried man on
the verge of losing his children to a disgruntled ex, finds
salvation in a Bosnian couple going through trauma over an unwanted
birth (the baby is the product of a war rape).
</P>
<P>
   Like the writer Hanif Kareishi (``My Son the Fanatic,'' ``My
Beautiful Laundrette''), Dizdar humorously compares and contrasts
extremes in economics and lifestyles and looks at the west through
the eyes of an outsider.
</P>
<P>
   He successfully meshes an enjoyably superficial romantic comedy
along the lines of ``Four Weddings and a Funeral'' with a
neo-realistic drama of war-torn Bosnia more reminiscent of
``Welcome to Sarajevo.''
</P>
<P>
   Dizdar never resorts to preaching and gives his characters the
chance to find a new hope as well as a new war in their battle for
a place and acceptance in a new world.
</P>
<P>
   Beautiful People. Directed and written by Jasmin Dizdar. Cast:
Charlotte Coleman, Charles Kay, Linda Bassett, Nicholas Farrell,
Rosalind Ayres. Trimark Pictures. 107 minutes. Rated R for
language, violence.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-02-00 1806EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
