<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-02 18:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4867 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a BC-MISSING-ATHEIST-HNS &LR;      03-02 0758
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MISSING-ATHEIST-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     NEW EVIDENCE SURFACES IN CASE OF MISSING ATHEIST 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By JOHN MacCORMACK  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ Blood traces recovered from an Austin storage unit
have reinforced federal authorities' belief that militant atheist
Madalyn Murray O'Hair and her two adult children were dismembered
there after being kidnapped and killed in 1995, according to a
federal court document.
</P>
<P>
   The document, filed in U.S. District Court in Austin, said
laboratory analysis of bloodstains ``resulted in the identification
of DNA of human origin'' that matched the DNA of ``two of the
missing Murray-O'Hair family members.''
</P>
<P>
   If true, the claim represents the first concrete evidence that
O'Hair, her son Jon Garth Murray and daughter Robin Murray O'Hair
were slain after they vanished from San Antonio in September 1995.
</P>
<P>
   In a lengthy affidavit filed last spring, federal investigators
accused three men _ David Waters, Gary Karr and Danny Fry _ of
abducting and killing the O'Hair family for $500,000 in gold coins.
And they have accused Waters and Karr of then killing and beheading
Fry, whose nude body was found on a Dallas riverbank two days after
the O'Hairs vanished.
</P>
<P>
   Karr has been charged in connection with the O'Hair
disappearance, but Waters has not. Neither man has been charged
with the death of Fry.
</P>
<P>
   However, Waters has been convicted of being in a felon in
possession of ammunition and of violating his probation on a state
theft conviction. He currently is in prison.
</P>
<P>
   While federal authorities have amassed a circumstantial case,
they have neither a witness to slayings of the O'Hairs nor bodies
to prove they are dead. Waters, who once worked for O'Hair, has
said the three disappeared as part of a long-planned getaway.
</P>
<P>
   The latest motion containing the new revelations was filed by
federal prosecutors in response to Waters' request for the return
of his personal property seized in the raid on his Austin apartment
last spring.
</P>
<P>
   The document also accuses Waters and Karr of collaborating in
other crimes, including the theft of guns and other property at an
Indianapolis home in July 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``The name, telephone number and e-mail address of this same
Indianapolis homeowner-victim was found in a spiral notebook during
the search of (Waters') residence on March 24, 1999,'' the motion
reads.
</P>
<P>
   It further says a .22-caliber pistol authorities say was found
in Karr's Detroit apartment in March 1999 was traced by its serial
number back to the homeowner in Indianapolis.
</P>
<P>
   In his motion for return of his property, filed from a Texas
prison, Waters lists hundreds of items taken from his residence
last spring, ranging from a pack of cigarette papers to a
serrated-edged knife.
</P>
<P>
   After months of deliberation, U.S. District Judge Paul Borman
threw out critical evidence Monday in a weapons case against Karr.
He ruled Karr had not given the police or federal agents permission
to search his Detroit apartment in March 1999.
</P>
<P>
   The police say they found two guns and charged Karr with being a
felon in possession of a firearm.
</P>
<P>
   Borman's ruling that the guns cannot be used as evidence may
lead to a dismissal of the charges, clearing the way for Karr to be
brought to Texas, where federal authorities are eagerly awaiting
his arrival to question him about the O'Hair and Fry cases.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there is no firearms case, I assume they'll try to bring
him to Texas. Practically speaking, he can't fight it,'' said
Karr's federal public defender, Richard Helfrick.
</P>
<P>
   The only delay may be an appeal of Borman's ruling. If the U.S.
attorney in Detroit does not appeal, Karr's next stop will likely
be Austin, where last year a federal grand jury indicted him in the
kidnapping and extorting of $500,000 from the O'Hair family.
</P>
<P>
   Karr has admitted what he maintains was a minor role in the
disappearance of the O'Hair family.
</P>
<P>
   Last spring he gave FBI agents a detailed map of a Hill Country
ranch, showing where the bodies of O'Hair and her children
allegedly were buried.
</P>
<P>
   However, a search of the site proved futile.
</P>
<P>
   Waters, who is serving two prison terms for other crimes, has
denied any role in the O'Hairs' disappearance.
</P>
<P>
   O'Hair gained fame when she carried her fight against prayer in
public schools to the Supreme Court, winning a case there in 1963.
She also founded and ran an atheist organization, the United
Secularists of America, which is located in Parsippany, N.J.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-02-00 1808EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
