u e       03-02 1045
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRASH-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`TRASH CULTURE': THE INTERSECTION OF HIGH AND LOW CULTURE 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Publication notes appear at end of review.) 
(DW) 
 By MICHIKO KAKUTANI   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In our culture of recycling, it's not surprising to learn that
``Clueless'' was based on Jane Austen's ``Emma'' or that
``Apocalypse Now'' was based on Conrad's ``Heart of Darkness.''
</P>
<P>
   In his addled new book, which traces the connections between
``canonical works of art'' and ``trash culture,'' the scholar
Richard Keller Simon adds to these well-known examples a host of
additional cases. He argues that ``Dumb and Dumber'' is ``a film
version of `Don Quixote' for kids,'' that ``Rambo: First Blood,
Part II'' is ``a contemporary variation on Homer's `Iliad''' and
that ``Seinfeld'' is a ``kinder, gentler'' adaptation of the
Etherege play ``The Man of Mode.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Star Trek,'' he asserts, is ``a contemporary variant on
`Gulliver's Travels,''' recapitulating Swift's ``inquiry into the
nature of civilization, the use of allegory, the elaboration of the
fantastic voyage, the problem of reason and emotion.'' ``Friends,''
he insists, is ``Much Ado About Nothing'' ``transplanted to a New
York City coffee shop, with Ross and Rachel as the inexperienced
lovers Hero and Claudio, Chandler as the witty Benedick, Monica as
the outspoken Beatrice, Joey as the worldly Don Pedro and Phoebe as
a generic Shakespearean fool.''
</P>
<P>
   Though Simon demonstrates a clever knack in ``Trash Culture''
for finding parallels between classic texts and contemporary works
of entertainment, he completely undercuts his thesis _ that ``we
are surrounded by stories that echo, repeat, revise and adapt the
entire history of literature'' _ by indulging in faulty logic,
self-serving omissions and absurd generalizations.
</P>
<P>
   Simon completely ignores the role that mythic archetypes and the
collective unconscious might play in explaining the persistence of
elemental stories throughout history: Jung does not figure in his
arguments at all, while Joseph Campbell is relegated to a single
mention in passing. He shrugs off the fact that essential aspects
of the human condition are obviously going to be addressed by
successive generations of artists and naively assumes that if two
texts share certain ingredients they must be related to each other.
</P>
<P>
   Simon makes the ludicrous argument, for instance, that talk
shows featuring Jerry Springer, Ricki Lake and Geraldo Rivera
frequently take their ``inspiration from Tennessee Williams, in
particular the tangled sexual dynamic acted out by Stanley
Kowalski, his wife, Stella, and her sister, Blanche Dubois in ``A
Streetcar Named Desire.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the talk show's great subject, the unrepentant male
stud surrounded by the women with whom he has had sex, without
regard for the consequences,'' Simon writes. ``In Williams' play
Stanley beats his wife and rapes his sister-in-law, while Stella
puts up with the abuse because she does not want to lose the great
sex and Blanche _ herself a sexual rule-breaker with a preference
for underage boys _ thinks she can control Stanley by flirting with
him.
</P>
<P>
   Some variant of this conflict plays over and over again on the
talk show circuit, where two sisters or three cousins or four best
friends or five girls in the neighborhood learn that they have been
sleeping with the same man who has betrayed them all.''
</P>
<P>
   Similarly obtuse interpretations are littered throughout ``Trash
Culture.'' Simon describes ``Sense and Sensibility,'' ``The House
of Mirth'' and ``Madame Bovary'' as ``cautionary tales and guides
for young women readers,'' then goes on to argue that they are
precursors to Cosmopolitan magazine, another guide for young women
that in his warped opinion also happens to be ``a brilliant
modernist text, what would have resulted if Marcel Duchamp had
thrown a hand grenade into the great courtship novels of the 19th
and 20th centuries, then pasted the fragments together.''
</P>
<P>
   In another chapter, Simon reduces ``Star Wars'' to ``a
commentary on the evils of our own side's war in Vietnam'':
``Luke's struggle with his father, who has gone over to the side of
the militaristic empire,'' he writes, ``reflects the experience of
many draft-age young men who struggled with their pro-war fathers
over the morality of the war.''
</P>
<P>
   As for Oliver Stone's 1986 movie ``Platoon,'' which does deal
with Vietnam, Simon regards it as ``a more brutal version'' of
``Henry IV, Part I,'' showing a young man, much like Prince Hal,
torn between two role models, ``a fanatical super warrior who lives
for bloodshed and a pleasure-loving fighter with no illusions about
the nature of war.'' Having thus linked the film with Shakespeare's
famous play, Simon goes on to mock Stone's own suggestion that he
based the movie on his own experiences as a soldier in Vietnam,
sarcastically commenting, ``as if he were Prince Hal!''
</P>
<P>
   Such stupefying failures of reasoning are exacerbated in this
volume by Simon's sloppy scholarship _ he identifies the author of
the classic book ``The Vision of Tragedy'' as William (instead of
Richard) Sewall _ and his penchant for making silly, willfully
provocative assertions. He announces that ``Star Wars'' appears to
have ``replaced the Bible as the urtext of our civilization'' and
hails The National Enquirer as ``postmodern tragedy, an
extravagant, minimalist celebration of the death of the subject
made available in collage or montage form.''
</P>
<P>
   In setting forth such absurd arguments, Simon is not bravely
staking out new territory, as he repeatedly says he is doing. After
all, there is little bias against popular storytelling in the
academy today, as he continually suggests: the intersection of high
and low culture has been a favorite topic among scholars for
decades, and treating ``trash culture'' texts as worthy subjects of
analysis has long been a favorite practice of deconstructionists.
All Simon is really doing in this book is recycling those familiar
arguments, and more often than not in a particularly inept fashion.
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PUBLICATION NOTES: &QL;
</P>
<P>
   `TRASH CULTURE: POPULAR CULTURE AND THE GREAT TRADITION'
</P>
<P>
   By Richard Keller Simon
</P>
<P>
   189 pages. University of California Press. Cloth, $40; Paper,
$15.95.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
