<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-COVERME-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AGENT MAKES HIS WORK THE FAMILY'S BUSINESS IN `COVER ME' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN LEVESQUE  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Unlike some kids, 11-year-old Chance Arno knows exactly what his
father does for a living.
</P>
<P>
   Exactly. Thus, on family car trips, he and his sisters play
back-seat games more intently than most. Instead of shouting
``blue'' when a blue car passes, they're apt to say: ``Late-model
Ford Mustang, female Caucasian, 28 to 32, brown hair, slight build,
cat lover.''
</P>
<P>
   The attention to detail makes Dad proud. He's Danny Arno: FBI
agent, lounge singer, devoted father. OK, unconventional father.
The sort who asks his 16-year-old daughter to get close to a
mobster's son so she can pump him for information, then goes all
conventional on her when he realizes how close she got.
</P>
<P>
   Consider it the downside of involving the wife and kids in the
family business. But the downside of not being involved is ickier.
To quote the philosophical adolescent, Chance: ``In the movies,
people die because they know too much. But in life, it's usually
the opposite.''
</P>
<P>
   So Danny not only tells his family what he does. He trains them
in what he does. It has been his mission ever since his partner and
his partner's wife were executed by the bad guys. Danny figures if
the woman had known her husband was infiltrating organized crime,
she'd have had a contingency plan.
</P>
<P>
   It might be a flimsy premise on which to hang a series, but
Shaun Cassidy, teen-heartthrob-turned-TV-producer, makes ``Cover
Me,'' premiering Sunday on USA Network, one of the more enjoyable
new shows of this or any season.
</P>
<P>
   Peter Dobson is part Elvis, part wack job, completely
captivating as Danny Arno. Think of him as the flip side of Tony
Soprano. And even though we're assured ``Cover Me'' is based on an
actual ``FBI family,'' it makes about as much sense as having the
low-fat topping on a hot-fudge sundae. But Dobson sells it
beautifully, like the law-abiding con man he plays. When taking a
family photo in 1984, he decides it's time to give Chance a piece,
so he puts his service revolver in the boy's hands. After Chance
accidentally ventilates Danny's overcoat, Danny instructs his son
in the subtler points of gunplay: ``When you do it again, empty
your load. Never let the other guy return fire. Otherwise, you'll
end up deader than vaudeville. Understand? Empty your load!
Attaboy. Kiss me. Now let's go to church.''
</P>
<P>
   It's not how every father would have handled the sitch. But
Danny Arno is different. Sort of like the guy at work who never
smiles. Mysterious. Scary. Odd. And Dobson, with a smirk and a
wink, makes it work. Besides, this is TV, where we go to escape
reality and embrace people like Barbara, Danny's wife, sometimes a
homemaker, sometimes a stockbroker, always whatever the job
requires. Always. Played with sexy devotion by Melora Hardin, she's
a bit Joan Severance, a bit Sela Ward: the mom from central casting
who can play all the parts. The kids _ Michael Angarano as Chance,
Antoinette Picatto as Ruby, Cameron Richardson as Celeste _ are
cute and typical siblings, until duty calls. Make that when Daddy
calls.
</P>
<P>
   Cover Me: Based on the True Life of an FBI Family. One-hour
drama series about an undercover FBI agent who involves his wife
and three children in his job. Starring Peter Dobson, Melora
Hardin, Cameron Richardson, Antoinette Picatto and Michael
Angarano. Premieres Sunday on USA Network. Parental guideline
rating: TV-14.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B+
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
