<SLUG> BC-IRS-AUSTIN03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    AUSTIN TAX CENTER HANDED $28 MILLION TO UNKNOWN COURIER
 &HT;    By JULIA MALONE
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Last fall, a courier arrived at the security gate
outside the Internal Revenue Service Center in Austin, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Although he was a substitute worker unknown to the IRS security
guards, the courier was allowed onto the grounds without being
asked for identification. Once inside the fence, he called the
processing center and an IRS employee came out to give him $28
million in checks, again without asking for his identification.
</P>
<P>
   As it turned out, the courier was legitimate, and he ferried the
deposit safely to the Federal Reserve Bank.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the incident was cited prominently at a congressional
hearing this week as the U.S. General Accounting Office issued a
sharply critical assessment of IRS operations.
</P>
<P>
   GAO associate director Gregory D. Kutz, who headed the tax
agency study, confirmed Thursday that courier episode occurred in
Austin in September while he was monitoring the tax service center.
</P>
<P>
   Security lapses are not new to the IRS. The GAO, which is the
non-partisan congressional watchdog agency, last year reported that
a district office in Dallas routinely handed over millions of
dollars in bank deposits to bicycle messengers.
</P>
<P>
   The IRS has tightened its policies since then, Kutz said. But,
he added, ``it's a big decentralized organization'' where policies
are ``difficult to enforce'' nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   Ed Roberts, chief of support services in Austin, said Thursday
that reforms were instituted soon after GAO informed officials
about the courier incident.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now we get i.d. badge numbers from the courier company and we
verify the driver has the i.d. badge and we match it against our
records,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   However, Austin IRS officials played down the risk that was
involved. ``That deposit, if it's not totally checks, it's almost
all checks, and they're all endorsed strictly for Internal Revenue
Service deposit,'' Roberts said.
</P>
<P>
   Diane Hall, chief of planning and analysis for the Austin
facility's submission processing center, said the courier who was
not asked for identification had the proper documentation for the
pickup.
</P>
<P>
   A year and a half ago, the Austin center was criticized by the
GAO for having no perimeter fence. One has since been installed.
</P>
<P>
   Julia Malone's e-mail address is juliam(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
