<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-02 18:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4874 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-THEATER-NOTES-NYT &LR;      03-02 1017
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THEATER-NOTES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHORT ITEMS ON THE GREAT WHITE WAY 
</HEADLINE>
  (af) 
 By JESSE McKINLEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   How About McGarden?
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The Winter Garden Theater won't be changing its name
after all.
</P>
<P>
   Gerald Schoenfeld, the chairman of the Shubert Organization,
which owns the theater, said Thursday that his company had ended
discussions with General Motors about changing the name of the
Winter Garden, home to ``Cats,'' to the Cadillac Winter Garden, or
some variation thereof, in exchange for corporate sponsorship.
</P>
<P>
   No explanation was given for the abrupt end to the discussions,
which had been continuing for about three years and which seemed to
be close to fruition.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement came just a day after the Roundabout Theater
Company announced it was selling off the name of the historic
Selwyn Theater, its new home, to American Airlines, a deal that was
greeted on Broadway with a mix of approval and skepticism. The
airline will pay $8.5 million (and, one would hope, a lifetime
supply of free peanuts).
</P>
<P>
   As for the Winter Garden, Schoenfeld offered no additional
comment, and a call to GM was not immediately returned.
</P>
<P>
   Vamoose, `Vanya'
</P>
<P>
   The new name notwithstanding, it's apparently taking a little
longer than expected to get the Selwyn _ er, the American Airlines
Theater _ ready for takeoff.
</P>
<P>
   The theater formerly known as the Selwyn, at 229 W. 42nd St., is
in the midst of a $21 million overhaul but nonetheless was
scheduled to open its doors on April 11 for the first preview of
``Uncle Vanya.''
</P>
<P>
   Now comes word that the construction isn't proceeding as quickly
as expected, and that the company is in discussions with the
Nederlander Organization to shift the run of ``Vanya'' to the
Atkinson Theater.
</P>
<P>
   Todd Haimes, the artistic director of the company, said that the
possible move was a precautionary measure to assure that the show
opens by the Tony deadline, which is May 3.
</P>
<P>
   A shift would not be completely unexpected; the company had
already delayed the opening once. Still, it is sure to be a
disappointment for the Roundabout, which had planned an array of
events around its opening. The timing, too, is not ideal, coming
just after the American Airlines deal.
</P>
<P>
   The prospective shift of ``Vanya'' is made possible by another
production decision: ``Enigma Variations,'' which opened on Feb. 24
in Toronto, will not come to Broadway this season. The production
had mainly favorable reviews in Toronto, but its producer, Emanuel
Azenberg, has decided to pass on bringing the show to the Atkinson,
where it was tentatively scheduled to open, opting instead to take
it to London. ``The economics over there are stultifyingly
different,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   London productions are generally much cheaper than those in New
York, owing to Broadway's famously steep labor and landlord costs.
Azenberg said he was considering a possible autumn run in the
United States.
</P>
<P>
   Welcome to the Club
</P>
<P>
   The staff of the Manhattan Theater Club can be excused for
feeling a little emotionally drained. In the last six weeks, after
all, it has closed one production (``Y2K''), transferred a second
to a commercial run (``Fuddy Meers'') and watched as the prospects
of a third (``The Wild Party'') were dashed by a round of sub-par
reviews.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Tuesday night's opening of ``The Tale of the Allergist's
Wife'' provided a spurt of invigorating energy for many at the
theater club. The play, an urban comedy by Charles Busch, received
a round of strong notices.
</P>
<P>
   Particular praise was saved for Linda Lavin, who plays Marjorie
Taub, the Sartre-quoting depressive at the play's center. It is a
character that this veteran New York actress says she understands
instinctively.
</P>
<P>
   ``This woman loves the drama of her life,'' Lavin said, adding
with a laugh, ``I know this woman.''
</P>
<P>
   The drama of Lavin's life may get even more high-stakes in
coming weeks. The reviews for ``Allergist'' have given rise to talk
of a longer run, with producers reportedly inquiring about two
mid-size Broadway houses where the current tenants are doing
moderate business.
</P>
<P>
   Whether those rumors pan out or not, Lavin is expected back on
Broadway next spring in rotating revivals of Neil Simon's
``Brighton Beach Memoirs'' and ``Broadway Bound,'' reprising her
Tony-winning turn as Kate Jerome, the narrator's long-suffering
mother. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Coming Attractions
</P>
<P>
   Two ambitious new additions to the spring schedule were
announced this week.
</P>
<P>
   Both are off-Broadway. At the New York Theater Workshop the
artistic director, James C. Nicola, said two newly rewritten works
by John Guare would be performed in repertory in May. They are the
plays formerly known as ``Gardenia'' and ``Lydie Breeze,'' first
produced in 1982 and both about the lives of a group of friends in
a 19th-century utopian commune.
</P>
<P>
   Neither was well liked back then, but after directing a
well-received version of both plays in Washington in 1983, Nicola
said he had become convinced that they constituted ``a 20th-century
American classic.''
</P>
<P>
   Now the plays are being combined into one cohesive five-hour
script, reworked by Guare, to be played over two nights, and
renamed ``Lydie Breeze, Part 1: Bulfinch's Mythology'' and ``Lydie
Breeze, Part 2: The Sacredness of the Next Task.'' (There will be a
quiz.)
</P>
<P>
   Another surprise reprise is under way at the Irish Repertory
Theater, where the artistic director, Charlotte Moore, announced
that ``Our Lady of Sligo,'' a hit at the Royal National Theater in
London in 1998, would arrive in April.
</P>
<P>
   The play, by Sebastian Barry, is part of a series of
biographical works about his family. The ``Lady'' in question is
Barry's grandmother, a part to be played by the Irish star Sinead
Cusack. Max Stafford-Clark will direct.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking from London, Cusack described the character as
``damaged and damaging,'' traits familiar to characters of many
recent Irish dramas. Why are her countrymen so ripe for humor and
pain? ``I think that's a universal condition,'' Cusack said. ``The
Irish are just more overt.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
