<HEADLINE>
LOVE REIGNS IN LESBIAN TRILOGY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN LEVESQUE  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   If only the people who hate homosexuals _ excuse me, who hate
homosexuality _ were forced to watch ``If These Walls Could Talk
2,'' maybe they'd realize they really have nothing to fear from
homosexuals. And, consequently, one thing less to hate.
</P>
<P>
   Four years after HBO looked at three women dealing with
unexpected pregnancies, Sunday's ``If These Walls Could Talk 2''
takes the same approach examining the lesbian experience: Three
short films about people living in the same house during different
time periods.
</P>
<P>
   The first, in 1961, involves two women deeply devoted to each
other for more than 50 years. But when one of them (Marian Seldes)
suffers a stroke and dies, the other (Vanessa Redgrave) encounters
a society that, while not exactly uncaring, cluelessly and
inexorably works to negate their special relationship at every
turn.
</P>
<P>
   The second film features Michelle Williams of ``Dawson's Creek''
as Linda, a college student living in the house with three lesbian
friends in 1972. Curiously, the friends, all radi-
</P>
<P>
   cal feminists, feel threatened and intimidated when Linda falls
for a woman with very masculine tendencies, played by
Chlo &UR; gfumlaut &LR; e Sevigny.
</P>
<P>
   Part 3 takes us to present day, with Fran (Sharon Stone) and Kal
(Ellen DeGeneres) sharing the house and desperately trying to have
a baby. Where the ``1961'' segment is sad and ``1972'' eye-opening,
``2000'' is mostly a hilarious capper to a sensitive trilogy that
deserves a wide audience, simply because we can all use an
occasional reminder that people who love are so much better off
than people who hate.
</P>
<P>
   If These Walls Could Talk 2. Ninety-minute anthology film about
lesbians living in three different time periods. Starring Vanessa
Redgrave, Michelle Williams, Chloe Sevigny, Ellen DeGeneres and
Sharon Stone. Sunday on HBO. Parental guideline rating: TV-MA.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: A-
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
