u i BC-RUSSIANS-AMBUSHED-BOS     03-02 0552
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIANS-AMBUSHED-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
12 DIE IN AMBUSH OF RUSSIAN RIOT POLICE IN GROZNY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID FILIPOV  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   EKAZHEVO, Russia _ Rebel fighters ambushed a column of Russian
riot police Thursday in Chechnya's ruined capital Grozny, killing
12 and wounding 31, a Russian television station reported.
</P>
<P>
   On a day when Chechnya's separatist president, Aslan Maskhadov,
vowed to keep fighting and promised a drawn-out and costly
conflict, Russian troops suffered their worst losses in Grozny
since driving out the rebels last month.
</P>
<P>
   Gunmen opened fire in broad daylight as the column moved through
a heavily guarded highway north of the center, Russian NTV
television reported. The station showed the bodies of several
soldiers on stretchers on a street in Grozny, and quoted a doctor
at a Russian field hospital as confirming the casualties. It gave
no information about rebel casualties in the attack.
</P>
<P>
   It was unclear how the rebels had been able to set up an ambush
in Grozny, where Russian police and troops conduct regular
house-to-house checks.
</P>
<P>
   ``They fired at us from all sides,'' a wounded Russian police
officer told NTV. ``We took up defensive positions and shot until
help came.''
</P>
<P>
   Russian troops interviewed in Grozny last week said that as many
as 500 rebels were still in the city, which was largely destroyed
by a two-month long siege and heavy fighting that ended when most
of the separatists retreated to the mountains in southern Chechnya.
</P>
<P>
   Russian troops closed Grozny in February to prevent rebel
fighters from moving in and out of the city. But the past few days
small groups of residents were allowed to go on foot to see what
could be salvaged from their homes.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, after federal troops seized the mountain town of
Shatoi, the last main separatist stronghold, Russian generals
declared victory in Moscow's five-month military campaign against
the rebels.
</P>
<P>
   But Defense Minister Igor Sergeyev urged his troops not to
relax, saying up to 3,000 diehard Chechen rebels would never give
up. The men in the Russian column attacked Thursday, made up of
riot police who had just arrived from Moscow, apparently failed to
heed the message.
</P>
<P>
   Maskhadov, in an interview on the Web site of US-funded Radio
Liberty, disputed Russian claims of victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``Out of 25,000 volunteers who took up arms, 23,000 remain,
23,500. The fighting will go on for a long time,'' Maskhadov said.
</P>
<P>
   Maskhadov also proposed holding peace talks with Moscow. But
Russia's Acting President Vladimir Putin, who has vowed to wipe out
the last Chechen rebel forces, dismissed the idea of talks with a
man Moscow accuses of aiding and abetting the kidnapping gangs who
terrorized the Caucasus region until Russian troops invaded
Chechnya in October.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before political talks with Maskhadov can start, we need to
resolve the criminal side of the matter,'' Putin said.
</P>
<P>
   Russia portrays its war in Chechnya as a struggle against
terrorists and bandits, but human rights monitors have accused
federal troops of abuses against civilians. Moscow Thursday said it
was inviting United Nations rights chief Mary Robinson to the North
Caucasus. Robinson has been one of the most vocal critics of
Russia's campaign.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-02-00 1824EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000302.0274 </DOCNO>
