<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-02 18:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4880 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-OIL-PRICES-540&AMP;ADD-NY     03-02 0939
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OIL-PRICES-540&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OIL MINISTERS AGREE PRODUCTION SHOULD INCREASE
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By ALAN COWELL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ With the high cost of oil and gasoline spreading alarm
through western economies, oil ministers from Saudi Arabia,
Venezuela and Mexico _ all among the world's major exporters _ met
here Thursday and agreed that production should be increased to
stabilize prices, but they declined to make firm commitments on the
timing or the amount.
</P>
<P>
   Oil market traders interpreted the absence of such commitments
as an indication that producers may not meet demands by the United
States and other oil-consuming nations for a substantial increase
in output.
</P>
<P>
   Oil prices, which have risen to nine-year highs in recent weeks
and jumped 4 percent on Wednesday, ended little changed Thursday on
the vague outcome of the oil ministers' meeting in London.The
London price of Brent crude for April delivery rose to $29.47 a
barrel before settling back to $29.22, up 10 cents. In New York,
oil for April delivery briefly rose to $32.15 a barrel before
retreating to settle at $31.69, down 8 cents.
</P>
<P>
   The Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries is to meet in
Vienna on March 27 to decide whether to increase production or to
maintain the present reduced output, as some exporters led by Iran,
Libya and Algeria are demanding.
</P>
<P>
   ``OPEC still has moderates and still has price hawks,'' said
Peter Gignoux, an oil analyst with Salomon Smith Barney here. ``We
still need to get a consensus'' for the Vienna meeting, he said.
``I think we are looking at high oil prices for a bit to come.''
</P>
<P>
   The Saudi oil minister, Ali Naimi, acknowledged Thursday that
``there is need for additional production. The issue is when and
how much.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Uppermost in our minds is to maintain stability in the
market,'' he said, but he refused to specify the likely scope of a
production increase. ``I think the number will be put forward when
we finish our consultation with all other members,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you are seeking the number, you are not going to get it
today,'' he told reporters. He also declined to say whether he was
aiming at a specific price level and would not comment on
suggestions that producers want oil prices in the United States to
sink below $25 a barrel. ``We are going to leave that up to the
market for now,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Delegates at the discussions here have said privately they
expect production to be increased next month by 1 million or 1.2
million barrels a day. The United States would like to see
production increase by 2 million to 3 million barrels a day.
</P>
<P>
   World oil consumption runs at around 77 million barrels per day
but, since OPEC agreed deep production cuts last March, production
has dropped to 75 million barrels a day. The shortfall of 2 million
barrels a day has tripled oil prices since December 1998, when they
had fallen to $10, the lowest in 12 years.
</P>
<P>
   Retail gasoline prices have reached an average of $1.421 per
gallon in the United States, the world's biggest oil-consumer, and
there is some expectation they will reach $2 by the summer driving
season, when demand is highest.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. energy secretary, Bill Richardson, who has just
returned to Washington after a visit to major oil producers has
called the rising prices and dwindling supplies a threat to global
economic growth.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   OPEC's production cuts are set to expire on March 31.
Historically, however, demand for oil falls in the second three
months of the year with the arrival of spring in the Northern
Hemisphere, and prices tend to weaken. That cyclical shift has
provided OPEC's hawks with the argument against increased
production.
</P>
<P>
   ``I accept that oil prices are high at the moment, but they will
fall in the second quarter when we expect demand to drop by 2.8
million barrels per day,'' said Hossein Kazempour Ardebili, an
Iranian oil ministry official. ``If we increase output while demand
is falling it will be detrimental to prices.''
</P>
<P>
   Iran has previously called for the OPEC production cuts to be
maintained through September and the official's remarks seemed to
signal continued deep division within OPEC about raising production
levels.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's clearly no decision taken yet,'' said Frederic
Lassere, an analyst at Societe Generale in Paris, who argued that
of the three oil-producers meeting here, Mexico was probably under
greatest pressure from the United States to increase output.
</P>
<P>
   Mexico is not a member of OPEC, which accounts for around one
third of worldwide oil production, but has agreed to cooperate with
the group's decision at its Vienna meeting later this month. ``An
increase in production is warranted'' because of a dramatic
increase in demand, the Mexican oil minister, Luis Tellez, said
Thursday. ``We believe there is a need for more oil in the
market,'' he said, but indicated that Mexico would prefer not to
break ranks while OPEC was seeking a broad agreement among its
members. ``We will wait to see this consensus before making our
independent decision,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The move to raise oil production won further cautious support
Thursday when Norway, another non-OPEC country that joined in last
year's production cuts, indicated that it backed a return to less
volatile prices. ``It is a goal that we should reach long-term
stability that is fair to both producing and consuming countries.
There is a danger when the price is very low and when it gets very
high,'' Marit Arnstad, the Norwegian oil minister, said in Paris
Thursday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-02-00 1824EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000302.0275 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-02 18:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4881 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e BC-MUSIC-REVIEWS03-COX     03-02 1383
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-REVIEWS03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    MUSIC REVIEWS: `Next Best Thing' soundtrack a pleasant surprise
 &HT;    By Staff Reports
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _
</P>
<P>
   POP
</P>
<P>
   Various artists
</P>
<P>
   ``THE NEXT BEST THING'' soundtrack
</P>
<P>
   Maverick
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B
</P>
<P>
   The ways in which Madonna will stir us up to get our attention
never cease to amaze me _ especially this time, when her pose seems
to be one of relatively uncharacteristic nonoffensiveness. Who
could object, after all, to a calm, respectful cover of the classic
``American Pie''?
</P>
<P>
   Well, just about every child of the 1960s and '70s who reveres
Don McLean's folksy original, probably. Madonna sings it as a lush,
danceable ballad in a hushed, breathy tone without regard to
phrasing or intent. It becomes less a pop-cultural coming-of-age
parable and more just a pretty song. Objections? None here; I never
liked ``American Pie'' anyway, and I appreciate that she brought
out the music in it.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, she shows she can assemble a pretty good soundtrack
disc (she executive-produced). She includes another pretty new song
of hers, ``Time Stood Still.'' She includes good cuts from Moby and
Groove Armada, a nifty remake of 10cc by female-fronted electronica
band Olive and an amusing little Euroditty from Manu Chao.
</P>
<P>
   However, the dignified centerpiece is ``Stars All Seem to Weep''
by up-to-date folksinger Beth Orton. Her red-wine voice reminds the
listener that she's the only artist on a record full of popsters.
Madonna, knowing this, might be even braver and smarter than we
thought.
</P>
<P>
   JAZZ
</P>
<P>
   Pat Metheny
</P>
<P>
   TRIO 99 &QR; 00
</P>
<P>
   Warner Bros.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: A
</P>
<P>
   It is an unassuming disc, this latest from guitarist Pat
Metheny, on break from his group to lead a trio. The CD comes in a
simple gray package, with plain typography and no liner notes. Its
only concession to vanity is the rainbow burst of color on the disc
itself. But even after a single listen, it's clear that the music _
the simpatico burst of creativity _ does not need fancy packaging.
</P>
<P>
   Arguably Metheny's most straight-ahead jazz album since 1990's
trio document ``Question and Answer,'' the new record spotlights
younger players Larry Grenadier (bass) and Bill Stewart (drums),
who bring a subtle edginess and a funkier take on their playing.
</P>
<P>
   Metheny charges out of the gate with a new original, ``Go Get
It,'' then steps back to offer a slower, more unusual take on John
Coltrane's ``Giant Steps,'' drawing out chords and expanding
spaces. Three more Metheny compositions follow before a clever
rendition of Wayne Shorter's ``Capricorn.'' Several songs later,
strong versions of two old Metheny-Lyle Mays compositions complete
``Trio 99 &QR; 00.''
</P>
<P>
   Stewart and Grenadier provide a thoughtful counterpoint to
Metheny, who plays no-frills jazz guitar _ it's almost as if he's
standing back to let the music discover itself. The album winds its
way through several moods and styles, showing a panoramic view of
the trio's range.
</P>
<P>
   ROCK
</P>
<P>
   Various artists
</P>
<P>
   ``WONDER BOYS'' SOUNDTRACK
</P>
<P>
   Columbia
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B
</P>
<P>
   None of these songs, with the exception of the new Bob Dylan
tune, ``Things Have Changed,'' needs much of a review to speak for
it. They have withstood the test of time and have gotten their due.
</P>
<P>
   The accomplishment here is the compilation. Together, the songs'
philosophical leanings intensify, creating a contemplative album
that looks at the challenges of love and life through a bittersweet
lens.
</P>
<P>
   ``Things Have Changed'' sets the tone, as it picks up the
swampy, blues feel from Dylan's last studio album, ``Time Out of
Mind.'' The song reveals a Dylan who is as at home with a groove as
he is with poetics. The album continues down a path of
self-exploration and earnest yearning with three older Dylan tunes
_ ``Shooting Star,'' ``Not Dark Yet and'' ``Buckets of Rain.''
</P>
<P>
   Other 1960s icons on the disc are John Lennon, represented by
``Watching the Wheels''; Buffalo Springfield (``A Child's Claim to
Fame''); Neil Young (``Old Man'') and Tim Hardin (``Reason to
Believe''). In his own way, each of these figures has struggled
with fame and redemption _ as the movie's central character must.
Van Morrison's ``Philosophers Stone,'' closing the album, is a
standout, as well.
</P>
<P>
   At the end, the selection of tunes suggests that the fight to
decipher the reasons behind the chaos of life may mean more than
the result.
</P>
<P>
   HIP-HOP
</P>
<P>
   Various artists
</P>
<P>
   Grammy Rap Nominees 2000
</P>
<P>
   RCA
</P>
<P>
   Grade: D-
</P>
<P>
   The compilation ``Grammy Rap Nominees'' is designed to cash in
on the popularity of big-name stars; as if you didn't hear Will
Smith's ``Wild Wild West'' enough last summer. ``Grammy Rap
Nominees'' contains 10 previously released songs that apparently
you're supposed to buy again.
</P>
<P>
   Irony surrounds this disc. At the Grammy ceremonies Feb. 23, the
big winner in the rap categories was Eminem, who took home awards
for Best Rap Album and Best Rap Song. He didn't even attend the
event, although the disc includes two of his songs (``My Name Is''
and ``Guilty Conscience,'' with Dr. Dre). The awards are annually
maligned as much as the Oscars, so for the folks behind the Grammys
to release albums is wildly funny: ``I know, let's get all of the
lame songs that we nominated and put 'em on CD.'' Whatever.
</P>
<P>
   There is also a companion disc out called ``Grammy Pop Nominees
2000.'' It pushes acts such as Ricky Martin, TLC, Lou Bega and, of
course, Carlos Santana.
</P>
<P>
   The only good thing about the Grammys and rap this year is is
that Smith didn't collect any statuettes. ``Big Willie'' has a way
of winning these things nearly every time he is nominated. The
Roots did win, so maybe there is justice.
</P>
<P>
   Or maybe not: This disc hasn't disintegrated yet.
</P>
<P>
   CHRISTIAN
</P>
<P>
   Jennifer Knapp
</P>
<P>
   LAY IT DOWN
</P>
<P>
   Gotee
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B
</P>
<P>
   With her big-label debut, ``Kansas,'' Jennifer Knapp deserved
the attention she received, including being named best new artist
by the Gospel Music Association. She provided a folk-rock passion
lacking from women in Christian music.
</P>
<P>
   Her second Gotee Records release, ``Lay It Down,'' whets the
appetite. The first radio single, ``A Little More,'' effectively
articulates _ without cliches _ the confusing truths of grace and
sin, and Knapp's vocal is appropriately thick with pain, longing
and hope. Still, though the arrangement starts sparsely with
acoustic guitar, strings swell into a distraction on the bridge.
Knapp doesn't need the musical emotional baggage.
</P>
<P>
   Her low-key backing vocals on the title track expose how easy
Knapp makes it seem. ``Usher Me Down'' is a great, completely
different worship song with a Chris Isaak musical feel. ``Into
You'' carves vivid imagery and contradictions in a straight-on
rocker.
</P>
<P>
   The inclusion of Shawn Colvin's ``Diamond in the Rough''
fittingly links Knapp with other rootsy women songwriters whose
vulnerability and strength coexist somewhat uneasily. For those
more attuned to Christian music, ``When Nothing Satisfies,'' penned
with Margaret Becker, makes a similar connection. Jennifer Knapp is
earning her place.
</P>
<P>
   HIP-HOP
</P>
<P>
   NATAS
</P>
<P>
   WWW.Com (Wicked World Wide)
</P>
<P>
   Grade: C
</P>
<P>
   It's easy for mainstream hip-hop fans to dismiss Detroit's Natas
for its heavy reliance on rock music. Acid rap, as made by Natas,
Kid Rock and Insane Clown Posse, deviates from the hip-hop norm,
which long has favored R&AMP;B. But Natas proves there is a place for
other genres in the dynamic world of hip-hop. Natas' 21-cut album
``WWW.Com'' (Overcore) must be treated like a buffet meal: Purists
may pass over many of the tracks, while some songs, including
``Oriental Spas,'' ``Levitation,'' ``Forever Fly'' and ``Funeral,''
merit a second helping. The best bits deserve to go beyond cult
following to gain mass appeal.
</P>
<P>
   R&AMP;B
</P>
<P>
   KEESHA
</P>
<P>
   KEEP IT REAL
</P>
<P>
   Grade: C
</P>
<P>
   Eight years after Mary J. Blige broke big, every record company
still wants another Mary J. Now Keesha tries with ``Keep It Real''
(RCA) and comes close, but no cigar. The record has run-of-the-mill
tracks and standard production. She's even got that tired,
single-name thing going. Maybe on her next one, she will give us
her full name.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
