<SLUG> BC-PINOCHET-RELEASED-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRITAIN ALLOWS PINOCHET TO RETURN TO CHILE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN CULLEN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ Seventeen months after he arrived for surgery in what
he thought was a friendly capital, former Chilean dictator Augusto
Pinochet left London Thursday a free but broken man, ending an epic
diplomatic and legal tug of war.
</P>
<P>
   The episode divided Britain and put despots worldwide on notice
that they can be held accountable anywhere for human rights
violations.
</P>
<P>
   Within two hours of the announcement by Jack Straw, Britain's
home secretary, that the 84-year-old Pinochet was too physically
and mentally feeble to be extradited to Spain to face torture
charges, the former dictator was bundled into a minivan at the
mansion where he had been held under house arrest for more than a
year. Under a police escort, he was whisked to a Royal Air Force
base in Lincolnshire, where he boarded a Chilean government jet
that had been waiting for him since January.
</P>
<P>
   Pinochet's supporters said the jet would arrive in Santiago, the
Chilean capital, Friday, when Pinochet is expected to check into a
military hospital.
</P>
<P>
   While insisting that Pinochet's condition meant he could not
receive a fair trial ``in any country,'' Straw said the former
dictator's arrest and the legal precedents that followed produced
``a landmark judgment in human rights law, whose impact has been
felt far beyond our shores.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The case,'' Straw told the House of Commons, ``has
established, beyond question, the principle that those who commit
human rights abuses in one country cannot assume that they are safe
elsewhere.''
</P>
<P>
   After more than a year of the legal drama, Pinochet's hurried
departure from Britain was something of an anticlimax. While a
handful of anti-Pinochet protesters demonstrated near the mansion
in Surrey and outside the air base, even those who had fought
fiercely to bring him to trial had resigned themselves to the
reality that Pinochet would be released.
</P>
<P>
   Straw said in January that he was inclined to release Pinochet
after a team of four doctors concluded he was too incapacitated to
defend himself. Even Pinochet's most implacable foes acknowledged
that the last seven weeks of legal wrangling, in which Straw was
forced to give the medical reports to Spain and three other
European countries that sought Pinochet's extradition, had only
postponed the inevitable.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we need to move on,'' said a crestfallen Luis
Macchiavello, a Chilean exile who was tortured during the Pinochet
regime and leads the Families of the Disappeared, which represents
relatives of some 3,000 people who died or vanished at the hands of
Pinochet's regime.
</P>
<P>
   Macchiavello said Pinochet's victims would now channel their
energy into getting him tried in Chile, where Pinochet faces 59
civil suits for murder and torture committed during and after the
1973 coup in which he seized power.
</P>
<P>
   They face an uphill struggle. Pinochet enjoys immunity from
prosecution in Chile because he was made senator-for-life under a
compromise that saw him step down as dictator in exchange for a
return to democracy.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's extremely doubtful he will be tried in Chile,'' said Jose
Miguel Vivanco, executive director of the Americas division for
Human Rights Watch, one of the groups that mounted a tenacious
legal battle to extradite Pinochet to Spain.
</P>
<P>
   But human rights activists like Vivanco insisted that Pinochet's
release in no way diminishes the precedent established in the fight
to hold the former dictator accountable for human rights violations
committed by his regime.
</P>
<P>
   Belgium's foreign minister, Louis Michel, whose country also
sought Pinochet's extradition along with France and Switzerland,
said the international community had shown that heads of state may
be held accountable outside their own nations and can no longer
rely on the principle of sovereign immunity to escape
accountability for acts of repression against their citizens.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have demonstrated that a dictator is not out of the reach
of justice,'' Michel said.
</P>
<P>
   It was a ruling by England's highest court, the Law Lords, that
Pinochet did not enjoy immunity as a head of state that is seen as
the most significant and lasting legacy of this convoluted legal
and diplomatic saga.
</P>
<P>
   Acting on a warrant issued by Baltasar Garzon, a crusading
Spanish judge, British police arrested Pinochet on Oct. 16, 1998,
as he recovered from back surgery in a London hospital. Just days
before his arrest, Pinochet had enjoyed cocktails at the home of
Margaret Thatcher, the former British prime minister who regarded
him as a friend and staunch ally of Britain during its 1982 war
with Argentina over the Falkland Islands.
</P>
<P>
   Pinochet was held for 17 months _ a month for every year of his
military dictatorship _ in a case that divided Britain and strained
its relations with Chile, which argued that Britain had no right to
intervene in what Chile called a domestic matter. While
conservatives like Thatcher admire Pinochet as a steadfast ally who
wrested Chile from the control of a pro-communist regime, he is an
object of hate to many British liberals who supported Salvador
Allende, the elected socialist president who was overthrown and
killed in a coup.
</P>
<P>
   Underscoring the strong emotions on both sides of the
ideological aisle, Straw was greeted with shouts of ``Shame'' in
the House of Commons as he explained his decision.
</P>
<P>
   As Britain's top law enforcement official, Straw, who as a
college student in the 1970s led protests against Pinochet, held
the power singlehandedly to send Pinochet to Spain or home to
Chile. He said he had received 70,000 letters and e-mails, nearly
all of which urged him to extradite Pinochet.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am all too well aware that the practical consequence of
refusing to extradite Senator Pinochet to Spain is that he will
probably not be tried anywhere,'' Straw said. ``I am very conscious
of the sense of injury which will be felt by those who suffered''
under Pinochet. But, he concluded, the medical evidence forced him
to let Pinochet go.
</P>
<P>
   Opposition leader William Hague said the government's decision
to authorize Pinochet's arrest, then to dither before eventually
freeing him, was a ``shambolic'' scandal that had tarnished
Britain's reputation and cost taxpayers more than $6 million. Straw
said the only bill tallied so far was a legal one of $2.2 million,
but he said it was too early to estimate how much had been spent
providing round-the-clock police protection for Pinochet.
</P>
<P>
   He said the government would review its extradition law to see
whether there was any way to make the process less prone to long
delays.
</P>
<P>
   Britain's High Court initially ruled that Pinochet was immune
from prosecution because he was a head of state when the crimes
were committed. But in the final appeal, the Law Lords ruled that
so-called sovereign immunity did not apply to cases of murder and
torture. That precedent-setting ruling, however, was set aside
because the judge who cast the deciding vote of the five-judge
panel had failed to disclose his association with Amnesty
International, one of the parties to the case. A different panel of
Law Lords then issued a similar decision.
</P>
<P>
   Straw then began formal extradition proceedings last April, but
they bogged down in a series of appeals. In the meantime,
Pinochet's health began to fail and he had a series of minor
strokes, leading Straw to ask a panel of doctors to examine him.
</P>
<P>
   Even if Pinochet had been extradited, tried, and convicted, he
would not have gone to prison because Spain prohibits the
incarceration of anyone over 75. Still, those who demanded that
Pinochet stand trial believed the sight of him in the dock would
serve as a powerful deterrent to other despots bent on using murder
and torture to control their citizens.
</P>
<P>
   Vicente Alegria, a Chilean exile here who helped organize vigils
and protests against Pinochet, spoke for many of the regime's
victims when he said they felt cheated by his release.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is seeing the compassion he never showed to his victims,''
Alegria said.
</P>
</TEXT>
