<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are planning for
Friday, March 3 Page 1. The NYT frontpage advisory, with layout
description, will move by 7:30 p.m. ET. The NYT News Service Night
Supervisor is Pat Ryan (888-346-9867).
</P>
<P>
   PINOCHET (London) _ Gen. Augusto Pinochet was allowed to fly
home to Chile Thursday after Britain dropped extradition
proceedings against him and put an end to his 16 months of house
arrest in England. The decision to free the 84-year-old former
dictator was announced by Home Secretary Jack Straw, who told the
House of Commons that he was ending the complex legal and judicial
case because of the failing health of Pinochet. By Warren Hoge.
</P>
<P>
   (Eds.: an early version of this story has moved and will be
updated.)
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   Reefer to: PINOCHET-REACT (Santiago, Chile) _ The reaction to
Pinochet's return, and a look at the legal situation for the former
dictator in his home country. By Clifford Krauss.
</P>
<P>
   AUSTRIA-HAIDER (Bad Kleinkircheim, Austria) _ To his supporters,
Joerg Haider's message has less to do with Nazi revisionism or
anti-immigrant vitriol than with market reform. It is about less
state. Deregulation. Sweeping privatizations. Reduced bureaucracy.
An end to the division of the spoils in Austria among members of
the long-dominant Social Democratic and conservative People's
parties. This is a popular view in Austria. About one-third of the
support that took Haider's Freedom Party into national government
in February for the first time comes from entrepreneurs,
particularly in the small companies that dominate the Austrian
economy. By Roger Cohen. 1,500 words.
</P>
<P>
   HSIA-TRIAL (Washington) _ A federal jury on Thursday convicted
Maria Hsia, a longtime political fundraiser for Vice President Al
Gore, on all five felony counts she faced for her role in arranging
more than $100,000 in illegal donations to Democratic candidates in
1996. Of that amount, $55,000 came in illegal donations to the
Democratic National Committee in connection with the vice
president's much-criticized 1996 visit to a Buddhist temple in the
Los Angeles area. By Neil A. Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   CHRISTIAN-RIGHT (Atlanta) _ It is hard to know how many Bob
Harrisons are out there. But each one is a nightmare for Sen. John
McCain. Harrison, a 60-year-old electrical engineer and a leader of
the choir at Atlanta's Mt. Paran Church of God, was once an
enthusiastic McCain supporter. He liked his heroic military
background. He liked his positions on education and health care.
And he liked his penchant for straight talk. ``I was really pulling
for him,'' Harrison said. ``He was the guy.'' That all changed this
week. Harrison, who considers himself a Christian conservative
voter, was deeply offended by McCain's attacks on Pat Robertson and
Jerry Falwell, whom the Arizona Republican described in a Monday
speech as ``agents of intolerance'' comparable to Louis Farrakhan
and Al Sharpton. ``I think he was out of line,'' Harrison said. Now
Harrison is leaning toward voting for Gov. George W. Bush of Texas
in Tuesday's Republican primary in Georgia. By Kevin Sack. (1400
words)
</P>
<P>
   CINDY-MCCAIN (Cincinnati) _ For months now, more than any other
presidential candidate's wife, Cindy McCain has been a regular on
the campaign trail. Through 14-hour work days, she is almost
constantly at her husband's elbow, smiling as she double-steps to
keep up with him in crowds, and nodding at just the right moments
during the speech she has heard hundreds of times. A profile by
Melinda Henneberger. (2000 words)
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   NY-POLICE-SHOOTING (New York) _ An unarmed Bronx man who was
fatally shot by the police Wednesday night had a long criminal
history, Mayor Rudolph Giuliani said, as he took pains to say the
shooting should not be likened to the killing of Amadou Diallo. The
latest shooting, which took place two blocks from where Diallo was
killed, ignited another round of protests as intense as those over
the Diallo shooting. In both shootings, the police were in
plainclothes and were approaching a building at night, and in both
instances the people they killed were unarmed. By Robert D.
McFadden.
</P>
<P>
   PALM-IPO (San Francisco) _ Shares of Palm Inc. surged in their
trading debut Thursday, rising as high as $165 from an offering
price of $38 before retreating. Shares in Palm's parent, 3Com
Corp., declined, although 3Com still holds 94 percent of Palm after
the offering. By Lawrence M. Fisher.
</P>
