<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-02 18:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4889 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k BC-EDITORIAL-CUP-BOS &LR;      03-02 0381
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-CUP-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW ZEALAND'S PRIZE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   For only the third time in its 150 years, the America's Cup has
gone to a non-American boat. For the first time, a foreign defender
_ New Zealand _ defended successfully. This year, also for the
first time, not even the losing boat was American.
</P>
<P>
   New Zealand's Black Magic won with grace and precision and
apparent ease, leaving Italy's Red Moon (Luna Rossa) and several
lessons in its wake.
</P>
<P>
   The Italian crew entered the finals in high hopes that may have
heeled over into overconfidence. They thought they had the faster
boat. And, after winning two tough series against 10 other
challengers, they felt a competitive edge. But their tactical
errors turned out to be the major difference.
</P>
<P>
   Moral: Hopes do not produce results unless matched by
performance.
</P>
<P>
   A larger lesson has to do with national pride. Sailing's
greatest prize is named for the boat that won the first race,
beating the English yacht Aurora and 14 other boats in a 60-mile
race around the Isle of Wight in 1851. The cup does not belong to
the United States, but the sense of mastery became so great as the
United States defeated 24 challengers that some began to feel it
did.
</P>
<P>
   When the first race was sailed, the British Empire was near its
peak, including major possessions on all six inhabited continents.
New Zealand had been added to the empire only 11 years earlier.
England was the world leader in large part because it had no
challenger as a maritime power.
</P>
<P>
   The United States at that time was gaining stature
internationally, but struggling for its soul domestically. The
Civil War was just a decade away.
</P>
<P>
   So, for more than a century after the American yacht prevailed
in England, national pride was palpable. One American writer in
1974 compared the cup to Mount Everest, Excalibur, and the Holy
Grail, calling it ``the most prized sporting honor in the world . .
. an object symbolizing power and invincibility.'' Today, America
is the world leader, but the America's Cup belongs in New Zealand.
</P>
<P>
   Moral: In this era of globalization, America has much to teach
and much to learn. Today, yachting and humility may be counted
among the latter.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-02-00 1835EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
