<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-02 18:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4891 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k BC-EDITORIAL-IMPLANT-BOS     03-02 0388
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-IMPLANT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAUTION ON BREAST IMPLANTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Through all the controversy about the safety of silicone-gel
breast implants, little attention was paid to the alternative,
saline implants. Lest anyone think this is because they have a
clean bill of health, the Food and Drug Administration is hearing
evidence this week of problems with these devices.
</P>
<P>
   The problems do not justify banning implants, but they do make a
strong argument for more research. Thursday's recommendation by an
FDA advisory panel that women be warned of the complications of
implants is supported by the data _ much of it compiled by the
manufacturers themselves. Surgeons must provide women with the
latest information about implants and then give them a waiting
period so they can consider the pros and cons at home and give
truly informed consent.
</P>
<P>
   Ideally, this kind of FDA hearing would have taken place 30
years ago, before the implants came on the market. But the FDA did
not gain authority to approve medical devices like this until 1976.
</P>
<P>
   In 1992, the FDA ruled that silicone-gel implants should be
limited to women who have had mastectomies and not used for
cosmetic breast augmentations because of many problems, including
leaks and infections. However, the FDA did not find that the
implants were causing systemic disease. Last year, the Institute of
Medicine confirmed that silicone implants did not cause major
diseases.
</P>
<P>
   As for saline implants _ saltwater in a silicone shell _ they
often rupture, deflate, or infect the breast tissue, requiring
repeat surgeries. They also make tumor detection by mammograms more
difficult. According to a study by implant-maker Mentor Corp., 9.2
percent of implants given women after a mastectomy rupture and
deflate within three years, and 24 percent of recipients suffered
breast hardening from scar tissue. For women undergoing breast
augmentation, the rate of complications was lower.
</P>
<P>
   But the manufacturers also point to data showing women are
highly satisfied with their implants, in spite of the difficulties.
That speaks to a demand the implants can fill. What's crucial is
making sure that women have valid data, preferably from impartial
sources, before choosing implant surgery.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-02-00 1838EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000302.0285 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-02 18:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4896 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k BC-EDITORIAL-GUNS-BOS &LR;      03-02 0369
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-GUNS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A TEACHABLE MOMENT ON GUNS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   America's children are more vulnerable to death by firearm than
any other industrialized country in the world. In 1996, 19 children
were killed by guns in England, none in Japan, 153 in Canada, and
5,285 _ that is not a typo _ in the United States. Every child's
death is tragic, but the murder Tuesday of a 6-year-old Michigan
girl by her schoolmate is an incident to galvanize public attention
on the woeful state of the nation's gun laws.
</P>
<P>
   A major reason for the shocking toll guns take is their
ubiquity. So long as there is a gun for everyone in America _ 200
million in circulation _ this country will top the grim charts of
deadly violence. Some states, including Virginia, Maryland, and
California, have laws restricting gun purchases to one a month. Gun
buyback programs are also a small step toward reducing the
country's arsenal of handguns.
</P>
<P>
   More immediately, action can be taken to keep the guns out of
the wrong hands. If Michigan had a child access protection (CAP)
law, as Massachusetts has, it would be easier to prosecute the
adults who neglected to keep the stolen .32 semiautomatic
inaccessible to the young boy. It may not have prevented this
particular tragedy, but a study by the Journal of the American
Medical Association found that CAP laws requiring loaded guns to be
stored in locked containers have reduced accidental gun deaths of
children by over 20 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Gun manufacturers must also bear some responsibility for the
Michigan crime. Instead of investing research dollars into new ways
to make their products more lethal or concealable, manufacturers
should work toward perfecting safety locks and identification
systems that can make sure the guns are fired only by their owners.
</P>
<P>
   Automobiles driven recklessly also kill plenty of children every
year. But every car in this country must be registered and every
driver licensed, and every gun and owner should be as well. Cars
are also covered by consumer safety laws, unlike guns. It strains
credulity that products designed to kill continue to be so poorly
regulated.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-02-00 1839EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
