<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-HEALTH-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HARVARD PILGRIM OFF LIFE SUPPORT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Harvard Pilgrim Health Care, which seemed on the brink of
collapse two months ago, will soon be out of receivership if the
Massachusetts Supreme Judicial Court accepts Thursday's
recommendation of Attorney General Thomas Reilly and Insurance
Commissioner Linda Ruthardt. The action is a tribute to the
recovery program being implemented by Harvard Pilgrim executives
and the confidence that receivership has given plan members in its
viability.
</P>
<P>
   While the short-term prognosis for the plan is improved, its
long-term prospects are far from clear, and the state will have to
examine whether health plans and the providers of care have
adequate resources to do their jobs.
</P>
<P>
   The beauty of Reilly and Ruthardt's approach is that it does not
require Harvard Pilgrim to be sold to a for-profit company, a
transaction that would have undermined the strong nonprofit culture
of health care in Massachusetts. And it also does not require
anyone to invest in the plan, whether through surplus notes of
dubious value to hospitals or contributions from Harvard University
or Ross Perot, whose company is revamping the Harvard Pilgrim
information system.
</P>
<P>
   The absence of any of these investors means that the plan is
heavily reliant on premiums from customers. Its survival depends on
retaining most of its members as it raises rates to pay off its
debts.
</P>
<P>
   Reilly and Ruthardt promise to continue their oversight of the
plan, which ought to insure there will be no surprises on the order
of the extra $34 million in losses uncovered in January. Neither
can do much to solve the basic problem of health care in
Massachusetts. Most providers think they are underpaid, even though
health care costs are extremely high. And hundreds of thousands of
people lack health insurance while the economy booms.
</P>
<P>
   The Cellucci administration was wise to establish four task
forces to explore a comprehensive approach. Their jobs are
formidable: to retain the nonprofit philanthropic orientation of
the system; develop policies that provide adequate compensation for
hospitals, physicians, and other providers; reduce the number of
uninsured; and make sure that the Harvard Pilgrim financial crisis
is never repeated. Formidable tasks, but essential.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
