<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-02 18:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4909 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u p BC-GORE-BRADLEY-HNS &LR;      03-02 0773
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-BRADLEY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRADLEY APPEALS TO DEMOCRATS IN COSTLY TV `INFOMERCIAL' 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By ALAN BERNSTEIN 
and JOHN W. GONZALEZ 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRIDGEPORT, Conn. _ Democratic presidential contender Bill
Bradley bought some precious national television exposure Thursday
to call the Democratic Party home to its roots.
</P>
<P>
   Campaigning Thursday in Connecticut, Bradley said he will
concentrate his weekend campaign on the northeast, where ``there
are states I can win.''
</P>
<P>
   But Gore, even though he seemed to be cruising as polls show him
leading in every Super Tuesday state, joined Bradley in that
region, pushing his education ideas in New York and Maryland.
</P>
<P>
   At an estimated cost of $1 million, Bradley used a five-minute,
``infomercial'' on CBS to take his appeal directly to voters across
the country. Several days ago, Bradley bemoaned the fact that he
has enjoyed little national television news coverage, following his
loss to Gore in the New Hampshire primary and the emergence of
McCain.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley and Gore have had two nationally televised debates in as
many weeks.
</P>
<P>
   In the ad, Bradley pressed his case for why the nation needs a
more committed alternative to the Clinton administration.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, the economy's good, but I don't think that's enough,'' he
said. ``It's no accident of history that we are discussing, in this
election today, the same issues that we talked about eight years
ago and four years ago _ and after each election, failed to use the
great opportunity given us by our economic prosperity; to teach the
young, care for the sick, clean the environment and heal the racial
divide.``
</P>
<P>
   Clinton won the presidential races four and eight years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley also said that if the Democratic Party is controlled by
special interests and strays from its mission to ``give voice to
the voiceless'' and represent all parts of society, ``then we have
forfeited the meaning, the reason, for the Democratic Party.``
</P>
<P>
   Gore read a storybook to P.S. 163's kindergarten class on
Manhattan's Upper West Side. Gore told a tiny, crammed room filled
with educators that he's determined to improve school facilities,
student-teacher ratios and teacher performance without burdening
local school districts with federal regulations.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to come here on the eve of the all-important New York
primary to reaffirm my top priority is education. If you entrust me
with the presidency, I will fight for you. I will fight for
revolutionary improvements in schools,'' Gore said.
</P>
<P>
   Aiming his fire at a general-election opponent, ``The Republican
candidates have both supported draining money away from public
schools at a time when more is needed. They seem to think that just
because New York schools begin with 'PS' that education is an
after-thought. It's not,'' he insisted.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, who enjoys strong union backing, said teachers are
unfairly portrayed as opponents of accountability in the classroom.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now that's a sensitive subject. Some in the public have the
misimpression that teachers and their organizations don't want to
see anybody ever get fired. But what they want is due process and
for protection against arbitrary or political personnel
decision-making,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Bradley advertisement, which competed with the top-rated NBC
show ``ER'' for viewers, could reach about 7 million voters across
the nation in advance of Tuesday's primaries and elections in 16
states, Bradley aides said.
</P>
<P>
   With Connecticut on the list of states that vote next week,
Bradley conducted a rally in Bridgeport a few hours before the
commercial was broadcast. Reflecting the relatively conciliatory
approach he took against Gore in a Los Angeles debate Wednesday, he
refrained from making the kind of aggressive attacks against Gore
that were a staple of Bradley's speeches just a few weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   And in interviews with local TV news crews here and in New York,
Bradley fended off suggestions that he will soon quit the race in
the face Gore's dominant lead in surveys of Democratic voters.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about his message to voters in Connecticut, Bradley said,
``Don't listen to the pollsters or the pundits. Vote your heart,
vote your conscience, vote for a new politics.``
</P>
<P>
   Saying that he doesn't plan to quit the race and is fighting
mightily for votes, Bradley invoked his career as a professional
basketball player in New York and senator from New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been in these places before, when nobody thought you can
do it, and I did it. So it doesn't bother me,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY XXXX &QL; 
$$$
</P>
</TEXT>
