<DOCNO> NYT20000302.0291 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-02 19:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4913 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-CITADEL03-COX     03-02 0748
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CITADEL03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Law firm that battled Citadel discussing gift
 &HT;    By Chris Burritt
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLUMBIA, S.C. _ Two old foes, The Citadel and the New York law
firm that led Shannon Faulkner's courtroom assault against the
males-only corps of cadets, are negotiating a sizable contribution
to help female cadets.
</P>
<P>
   The Citadel said Shearman &AMP; Sterling suggested a donation of
$300,000, a figure that both sides hope to nail down in a meeting
in Charleston a week from today. The negotiations raise a
potentially ticklish question. In exchange for the gift, would
Shearman &AMP; Sterling _ or Faulkner _ deserve a public
acknowledgement, such as an honorary plaque on the campus once
hostile to the prospect of women in the ranks?
</P>
<P>
   Here in Columbia, six Citadel graduates serving in the state
Legislature said they'd welcome Shearman &AMP; Sterling's contribution,
though two said they'd prefer it not celebrate Faulkner's
trailblazing role.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do not think Faulkner ever intended to go to The Citadel,''
said 1964 graduate James Battle, a Democratic representative from
Nichols. ``She went down there for the publicity.''
</P>
<P>
   Another Citadel alumnus, state Rep. Greg Delleney (D-Chester),
made that point bluntly. ``I do not think Shannon Faulkner did
anything to improve The Citadel,'' the 1974 graduate said.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Black, a Charleston lawyer who represented Faulkner, now
a high school teacher in Greenville, said she remains a target of
``persistent hostility'' because some alumni believe ``she
destroyed The Citadel.''
</P>
<P>
   After a bitter 2 1/2-year court fight, a federal judge ordered
The Citadel to admit her. In August 1995, she enrolled as the
school's first female ``knob,'' but faltered on the first day of
Hell Week and quit in less than a week.
</P>
<P>
   But it was a short-lived victory for The Citadel. The next
summer, after the U.S. Supreme Court ruled that Virginia Military
Institute's males-only policy was unconstitutional, The Citadel's
Board of Visitors reversed its ban on females.
</P>
<P>
   Black said Faulkner deserves recognition, or, he said, ``Women
who enroll will someday want to know what was wrong with Shannon
Faulkner.''
</P>
<P>
   Sixty-three women are now enrolled, and they have made The
Citadel a better college, said President John Grinalds, who arrived
at the school after the court fight.
</P>
<P>
   But neither the college nor Shearman &AMP; Sterling would discuss
how the law firm's gift might be acknowledged. In fact, both said
they hadn't given it much thought.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not going to make (a donation) or not make it based on
what it is called,'' Shearman &AMP; Sterling partner Henry Weisburg
said. ``There has been no discussion yet about apportioning
credit.''
</P>
<P>
   Citadel spokeswoman Patricia McArver said school administrators
are concerned that a public discussion might ignite old hostilities
and snarl negotiations over what the college and the law firm said
should be a symbolic reconciliation.
</P>
<P>
   Some legislators agreed it's time for a truce.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would certainly hope we could let the issue die and move
on,'' said state Rep. Gresham Barrett (R-Westminster).
</P>
<P>
   Noting that the school is trying to raise millions of dollars
for major renovations and expansions, Barrett, a 1983 graduate
said, ``A gift like that for The Citadel is welcome.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I am sure they can figure out how to accept that gift,'' said
state Rep. James Harrison, a Columbia Republican and a 1973 Citadel
graduate. ``I would hope they would readily accept a gift to the
college from any source.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I do not know why there would be any resistance,'' said
Allison Dean Wright, one of two women appointed as nonvoting
Citadel board members in 1997. She is running for an at-large,
voting seat on the Board of Visitors.
</P>
<P>
   Last fall, Shearman &AMP; Sterling initially suggested that its
gift, drawn from the legal fees it won in The Citadel case, go
toward women's scholarships, McArver said.
</P>
<P>
   But the college, figuring that $300,000 invested conservatively
would generate little money for scholarships, countered that the
gift might be used for women's locker rooms.
</P>
<P>
   ``We obviously are not in a position to turn $300,000 away,''
McArver said.
</P>
<P>
   Shearman &AMP; Sterling routinely donates the legal fees it wins in
cases, such as the one against The Citadel, in which it volunteers
its legal services for what it considers the public good, Weisburg
said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
