<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-02 19:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4921 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a BC-BONFIRE-PROBE-HNS &LR;      03-02 0999
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BONFIRE-PROBE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PANEL INVESTIGATING BONFIRE TRAGEDY AT TEXAS A&AMP;M SEEKS MORE FUNDS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Eds.: See optional ending) 
 
By JOHN WILLIAMS 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The special commission investigating the deadly collapse of the
Texas A&AMP;M University Bonfire now says it may need to spend $2
million to figure out the cause of the disaster.
</P>
<P>
   That amount is more than eight times what university officials
originally believed they would need to learn why the stack
collapsed Nov. 18, killing 12 people and injuring 27 others.
</P>
<P>
   The money will come from the university's investment fund _
money that typically is used for everything from emergencies to
travel expenses.
</P>
<P>
   State Rep. Ron Wilson, D-Houston, said spending that much money
``is excessive, beyond what probably is needed.''
</P>
<P>
   But even if that amount is needed, Wilson said, a commission
appointed by the school should not head the investigation. Instead,
the work should be done by an independent law enforcement agency,
he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If this was Texas Southern University and the same event had
occurred on that campus, it would be crawling with federal and
state and local officials looking at it,'' Wilson said. ``But A&AMP;M
has some politics on its side.''
</P>
<P>
   TSU is a largely black state university in Houston with about
7,000 students. More than 43,000 students attend Texas A&AMP;M at
College Station.
</P>
<P>
   State Sen. Steve Ogden, R-Bryan, whose district includes the A&AMP;M
campus, said Wilson is ``just flat wrong.'' Ogden is vice chairman
of the Senate Education Subcommittee on Higher Education.
</P>
<P>
   ``Trying to drag Texas Southern and the racial issue into this
is totally inappropriate,'' Ogden said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Secondly, A&AMP;M has no choice,'' he said. ``If they appoint an
independent commission and do not give them the assets they need,
it compromises the public perception.''
</P>
<P>
   In response to Wilson's comments, Texas A&AMP;M President Ray Bowen
released a statement that read:
</P>
<P>
   ``We share Representative Wilson's concern about the cost. We,
too, wish it didn't cost so much. We obviously wish, of course, the
tragedy had never occurred.''
</P>
<P>
   Wilson's comments came a day after special commission Chairman
Leo Linbeck Jr. informed school officials that another $1 million
might be needed to complete an investigation. He also said the
commission will miss the March 31 deadline set by Bowen. The new
goal is the first week of May.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to keep it at a high level of confidence so people are
sure we didn't leave anything out,'' Linbeck said. ``The gravity of
the tragedy and the injuries that ensued make it important that we
pursue the truth.''
</P>
<P>
   Last November, university officials appointed Linbeck to head
the special panel to determine why the 59-foot tower collapsed
before completion. The accident was the most tragic in the 90-year
tradition of the bonfire, which is burned before the annual
football game with the University of Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Documents released by the school indicated that on Dec. 5, A&AMP;M
officials expected to spend $225,000 on the investigation.
</P>
<P>
   In January, after talking with consultants, Linbeck estimated
the cost would be about $500,000 to hire four firms to determine
what happened.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, A&AMP;M regents said they would spend as much as $1
million for the investigation, but they wanted to sign off on any
expenditures above that amount.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, Linbeck told university officials the budget is
$1.67 million. However, he wants as much as $2 million needed.
</P>
<P>
   The money for the investigation is coming from university
investments, rather than tax dollars from the state's general
revenue fund. The university invests income from student fees and
other non-tax generated monies, and that income may be used for any
lawful purpose.
</P>
<P>
   In the days just after the tragedy, the school spent $292,000,
including about $90,000 to send students and administrators to
funerals.
</P>
<P>
   University regents have indicated they will approve the budget
increase Linbeck wants. The Houston construction magnate, who is an
alumnus of the University of Notre Dame, said the extra money
largely is needed to complete interviews with more witnesses and
officials.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the companies handling the investigation want
financial protection should they be dragged into any ensuing
lawsuits.
</P>
<P>
   Despite criticism from Wilson, other lawmakers who oversee the
state's second-largest university said they had no problem with the
$2 million figure or the fact that the school is investigating
itself.
</P>
<P>
   Texas Senate Education Chairman Teel Bivins said A&AMP;M is taking
the same approach that Johnson &AMP; Johnson did when the company faced
a scare that its product, Tylenol, was laced with cyanide.
</P>
<P>
   ``Johnson &AMP; Johnson spared no expense to investigate their
product and the company did everything in the open,'' Bivins said.
``It appears to me that Texas A&AMP;M is doing the same thing.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It is not the first time Wilson has spoken up about the Bonfire.
</P>
<P>
   In January, he said he would seek a bill in the 2001 Legislature
to allow victims and their families to sue the school for more than
the state-mandated cap.
</P>
<P>
   Under Texas law, governmental entities cannot be forced to pay
more than $500,000 to all those who suffered from anyone incident
the government is responsible for.
</P>
<P>
   No lawsuits have been filed.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, some associated with the school said Wilson was
getting even for a 1992 incident during which the Houston
legislator launched a fight against campus racism since an A&AMP;M
fraternity held a ``jungle party.'' That year, a student newspaper
depicted him as a small, black, yapping dog.
</P>
<P>
   Wilson has said there is no vendetta, though he can understand
why some might say that.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just believe that an independent law enforcement agency
would provide more accountability,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY XXXX &QL; 
$$$
</P>
</TEXT>
