<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOREST-ROADS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
US PROPOSES FOREST ROAD MAINTENANCE PLAN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROBERT BRAILE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In another sign of the greening of the US Forest Service,
Agriculture Secretary Dan Glickman Thursday proposed a plan to
repair and maintain heavily used roads and close lightly used ones.
The proposal affects 380,000 miles of roads in America's 155
national forests and 20 grasslands, including New England's prized
Green Mountain and White Mountain national forests.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the lightly traveled roads are little more than rutted
dirt trails built a half-century ago to enable logging trucks to
penetrate the dense, remote forests.
</P>
<P>
   Nationally, the US Forest Service faces an $8.4 billion backlog
in roadwork, because it gets only 20 percent of the funding needed
to maintain roads.
</P>
<P>
   The agency has recently come under intense pressure from
environmentalists, who say that increasing numbers of roads pose a
threat to forests.
</P>
<P>
   Hikers, bikers, snowmobile riders, and other outdoor enthusiasts
are increasingly using the roads. The White Mountains alone have
about 500 miles of road and receive 7 million visitors a year.
</P>
<P>
   To the dismay of timber groups and the delight of
environmentalists, Glickman and Forest Service chief Mike Dombeck
said Thursday that it is time for a change.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you have 380,000 miles of roads and an $8.4 billion
backlog, what do you do?'' Dombeck said. ``You put the shovel down,
stop digging deeper, and really focus on what the priorities and
needs of the people are.''
</P>
<P>
   Dirt roads can erode into rivers and streams, altering water
temperatures and flows, obstructing fish and wildlife, and causing
other ecological harm, say environmentalists. The roads also
potentially endanger growing numbers of drivers, because many roads
don't meet safety standards, environmentalists say.
</P>
<P>
   But a top timber industry group said the proposal would drive a
wedge between Americans and their forests by limiting access. It is
one of several proposals the agency has made recently that amount
to redefining its mission to preserve forests rather than enabling
the public to use them, the industry group said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're managing the forests for wilderness protection, and
that's not their mission,'' said Derek Jumper, a spokesman for the
American Forest and Paper Association.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's clear there will always be a place for roads in the
national forests,'' said Jay Watson, a Wilderness Society
spokesman. ``But it's high time the Forest Service put the brakes
on what has been a runaway road program, one that, with 380,000
miles, is now eight times the interstate highway system.''
</P>
<P>
   The proposal differs from President Clinton's proposal last
October to protect 40 million acres of forests from new roads.
Thursday's proposal only involves existing roads. Work on the
proposal began in February 1999, when Dombeck declared a moratorium
on road building and repair until a policy could be put in place.
It is expected to be finalized by Sept. 1, following a 60-day
public comment period that begins Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Forest Service wants roads it can be proud of,'' Dombeck
said. ``And right now, that's not the case.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-02-00 1918EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000302.0298 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-02 19:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4923 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i BC-AUSTRIA-HAIDER-2TAKES     03-02 0979
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUSTRIA-HAIDER-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR MANY AUSTRIANS, HAIDER'S APPEAL IS BLEND OF FREE MARKETS AND
FAMILY AID 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By ROGER COHEN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BAD KLEINKIRCHHEIM, Austria _ Here in the midst of
picture-postcard Austria _ pine-clad slopes, sun glistening on the
snow, rosy-cheeked families sipping mulled wine _ it is something
of a surprise to encounter Matthias Krenn and his modern political
theories.
</P>
<P>
   ``Political populism is just modern marketing,'' Krenn said
casually as he sat in the lobby of one of the hotels he owns. ``In
politics today, you have to sell your services like any other
product. So you listen carefully to what each person wants and
respond accordingly. That is why Joerg Haider is such a successful
political marketer.''
</P>
<P>
   Krenn, 40, is a hotelier from the southern province of
Carinthia, the heartland of Haiderism, and a representative figure
of the young entrepreneurs who have helped thrust Haider's
catch-all Freedom Party to power. While the world tends to see
Haider as a xenophobic rightist, based on statements he has made,
Krenn sees him as Austria's belated answer to Margaret Thatcher.
</P>
<P>
   For him, Haider's message has less to do with Nazi revisionism
or anti-immigrant vitriol than with market reform. It is about less
state. Deregulation. Sweeping privatizations. Reduced bureaucracy.
An end to the division of the spoils in Austria among members of
the long-dominant Social Democratic and conservative People's
parties.
</P>
<P>
   Krenn's is a popular view in Austria. About one-third of the
support that took the Freedom Party into national government in
February for the first time comes from entrepreneurs, particularly
in the small companies like the Krenn hotel group that dominate the
Austrian economy.
</P>
<P>
   ``To understand Haider, you must see that he's a late edition of
the neo-conservative wave that totally passed Austria by in the
1980s and 1990s,'' said Lothar Hoebelt, a historian sympathetic to
him.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, Austria's political system was long distinguished by
immobility. During three decades of Social-Democratic-led rule,
stability came before market reform, and state jobs were useful to
reward political loyalty. The state still owns the national
telephone company and main tobacco corporation; as such, it is now
a European anomaly.
</P>
<P>
   But a look at how Haider operates in Carinthia, where he won 42
percent of the vote in the regional election last year, suggests
that promoting the free market is merely one ingredient of his
heady brew.
</P>
<P>
   Haider quit Feb. 28 as leader of the Freedom Party but retained
his post as governor of Carinthia. The resignation was widely seen
as a maneuver to shield himself from any unpopularity the new
government may encounter.
</P>
<P>
   Take Thatcherism, add a dose of Robin Hood, some designer
labels, a touch of Austria-first bigotry, a dollop of straight talk
and fanatical physical fitness, and the seductive magician of
modern European politics emerges, a man who has taken his party
from 4 to 27 percent of the vote in the past 15 years.
</P>
<P>
   In downtown Klagenfurt, seat of Haider's regional government,
``Joergs Treff'' is a popular meeting place. In this Freedom Party
office, young people can surf the Internet or play video games on
computers provided by the governor. Posters plastered on the
windows show a baby brandishing a check for 5,700 Schillings, about
$407.
</P>
<P>
   A bubble from the baby's mouth reads: ``This check can be cashed
with Governor Haider.'' It is a reference to Haider's promise to
hand out monthly checks to mothers with small children in order to
strengthen the family and boost Austria's falling birth rate.
</P>
<P>
   So, the prophet of leaner government, more individual
responsibility and tighter state budgets is also the proponent of
an ambitious new program of state handouts? Well, yes, so it seems,
if that is what brings in the votes.
</P>
<P>
   ``The children's check cannot be financed,'' said Franz Pacher,
a businessman who is president of the Carinthian Chamber of
Commerce and who opposes Haider. ``It could cost as much as $175
million a year, or close to one tenth of the state budget. But of
course the promise has won him a lot of popularity.''
</P>
<P>
   In an interview, Haider said the program could be financed and
that the checks would be paid: ``You see, on the one hand I am a
kind of Margaret Thatcher pushing lean government and the end of
party influence. On the other, I am a new Social Democrat, pushing
family values and taking care of the smaller people against the
powerful.''
</P>
<P>
   He smiled his gleaming smile and added: ``That is why I like to
say that I am not to the left or the right of my opponents. I am
simply ahead of them.''
</P>
<P>
   Just how long Haider can stay ahead of the game, and continue to
appeal both to rising entrepreneurs and to the less privileged, who
like the look of his largesse, is the question now posed by the
Freedom Party's entry into government.
</P>
<P>
   Karl-Heinz Grasser, the 31-year-old national finance minister
and a home-grown Carinthian protege of Haider, is attempting to do
on a national scale something of what the party leader has done
locally.
</P>
<P>
   He has vowed to eliminate about 9,000 state jobs, sell off state
industries, raise the retirement age and reduce pensions for early
retirees in order to bring the budget deficit down to 1.7 percent
of Austria's total output from well over 2 percent. All doctrinaire
market-oriented policy straight out the textbook.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, Grasser wants to increase state support for
the family by extending fully paid maternity and paternity leaves
and by introducing other measures that Haider said would include
extending the promised ``child checks'' to a national level. That
would cost close to $3 billion _ about what the finance minister
has promised to cut this year in other areas.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to do it the American way,'' said Thomas Prinzhorn, a
prominent Freedom Party member of Parliament who owns a large paper
company. ``We're Austria's only free-market party. At the same
time, Haider feels passionate about the family and social justice,
so we have to balance these things.''
</P>
<P>
   The Haiderian ``balance'' appears to involve other elements.
Michael Stattman, a Klagenfurt businessman, said that when Grasser
was in charge of economic policy in Carinthia, he tried to impose
an ``Austrians-first'' principle on hiring for building sites in
the province. This angered some entrepreneurs, who faced the loss
of cheaper foreign labor.
</P>
<P>
   Prinzhorn has also made some notable anti-foreigner statements,
including a remark during the national election campaign last year
that foreigners in Austria were getting free hormone treatment from
the country's health services ``in order to increase their
fertility.'' He has since apologized.
</P>
<P>
   Max Hofmann, a leader of a business group supporting Haider
called the Circle of Freedom Party Enterprises, said there was
nothing xenophobic about such remarks or the party's approach to
business. Both simply reflected the fact that, in a small country,
``We can only invite in foreign people when we have enough work.''
</P>
<P>
   Hoffman, the owner of a central-heating business, said the
Freedom Party is a post-ideological party that wants to scale back
the state but also to appeal to workers.
</P>
<P>
   ``To think in terms of appealing either to workers or to
entrepreneurs is the thinking of the past,'' he said. ``There is no
more class struggle. There is only the joint interest of workers
and management in making Austria a good place to do business.''
</P>
<P>
   Up to now, Haider has been highly successful in promoting this
message. His support among entrepreneurs has been matched by strong
support from blue-collar workers who fear the loss of jobs to
foreigners and seem to feel more identification with Haider's
slickly marketed nationalism than with the socialism of old.
</P>
<P>
   In Klagenfurt, one catch phrase promoted by the governor is
``the Silicon Alps'' _ the slogan of several new technology
companies that have set up shop here. At the same time, Haider
loves to promote local folklore against ``cultural globalization.''
The clear idea is a very broad laptops-to-loden-coats political
appeal.
</P>
<P>
   For Pacher, the leader of the Klagenfurt Chamber of Commerce,
Haider is simply ``the master of disguises, the great European
illusionist.''
</P>
<P>
   But for Krenn, the hotelier, the Haider message is consistent:
``The old government was selling you tired wares badly. I'm selling
you new goods and I'm doing it well.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
