A4930 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-CINNABON03-COX     03-02 0505
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CINNABON03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Cinnabon creates new look; parent AFC makes more plans
 &HT;    By Shelia M. Poole
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Cinnabon International Inc. is rolling out its new
look nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   The Atlanta-based bakery chain, which was acquired by AFC
Enterprises in 1998, plans to remodel about 100 company-owned units
by the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We started remodeling the units to make them more attractive
and to keep us competitive,'' said Gerald Wilkins, chief financial
officer for AFC. The previous owner ``really had not done much to
re-image the concept,'' Wilkins said. ``It had gotten old and dated
and tired.'' He said it will cost about $60,000 to redo each
bakery.
</P>
<P>
   The new look is more contemporary, with extensive use of wood
tones and stainless steel. The blue and white tile remains.
Cinnabon spokesman Mallard Holliday said consumers said they wanted
more of a ``neighborhood bakery feel.''
</P>
<P>
   Other changes are in store for Cinnabon. Over the next five
years, the chain plans to sell between 30 and 50 bakeries to new
and current franchisees in areas that it considers to be
``remote.'' ``These locations are very difficult to oversee, which
causes the overhead to be abnormally high,'' Wilkins said. He added
the ``lion's share'' of those units are profitable but are
difficult to manage effectively.
</P>
<P>
   ``The previous owners embraced a development strategy that
really caused them to be far too spread out,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He said the company will use the proceeds to reinvest in markets
where Cinnabon has a stronger presence.
</P>
<P>
   Cinnabon, which had systemwide sales of $150 million in 1999,
has 382 bakeries in 41 states and eight countries. The company
plans to open 104 units this year, the bulk of which will be
franchised locations.
</P>
<P>
   Currently Cinnabon represents about 12.5 percent of AFC's
revenue.
</P>
<P>
   This week AFC released its results for the 1999 fiscal year. The
company reported net income of $12.1 million, which included a $2.4
million charge related to the loss from Chesapeake Bagel Bakery's
discontinued operations and the sale of its franchise system.
</P>
<P>
   Total revenue in 1999 was $707.1 million, vs. $605.6 million for
fiscal year 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Systemwide sales at AFC's 3,374 company-owned and franchised
restaurants, bakeries, cafes and whole and manufacturing operations
were $2.1 billion, compared with $1.8 billion for the same period a
year earlier. This was the first time in the company's history that
systemwide sales exceeded $2 billion.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to Cinnabon, AFC also owns Churchs Chicken, Popeyes
Chicken &AMP; Biscuits and Seattle's Best Coffee. Overall, the company
plans to open 450 new units this year.
</P>
<P>
   Wilkins said the company is still evaluating a public offering.
``Right now we don't see a favorable market environment.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We think that once we see that, we will be in a position to
go.'' He said it could happen as early as the fall.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
