<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WAFFLEHOUSE-BIAS03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Former manager accuses Waffle House of racial bias
 &HT;    By Shelia M. Poole
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ A former manager of a Waffle House restaurant in
Beaufort, S.C., is suing the Norcross, Ga.-based restaurant chain,
alleging he was dismissed for refusing to fire black workers and
hire whites.
</P>
<P>
   Jesse E. Gantt Jr., who has homes in Georgia and South Carolina,
accused the company of racial discrimination and unlawful
employment practices. The lawsuit was filed last month in U.S.
District Court in Atlanta and seeks unspecified monetary damages.
</P>
<P>
   Gantt was employed by Waffle House in management positions
between 1991 and 1998 in Georgia and South Carolina. Most recently
he was senior operator/franchisee trainee for the Beaufort
restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit said that Gantt's production numbers were
consistently above-average to excellent and he was often praised by
his supervisors.
</P>
<P>
   However, on or about Dec. 20, 1997, the suit claims that a
Waffle House area vice president visited the store.
</P>
<P>
   The suit contends that vice president looked around the
restaurant and said, ``Jesse, I will not have a black restaurant.''
</P>
<P>
   Days later he asked Gantt for a racial breakdown of the staff
and insisted that it match the demographic mix of Beaufort County,
which was 70 percent white and 30 percent black, according to the
suit.
</P>
<P>
   Gantt claims he was then ordered to change his employee base by
firing black workers and replacing them with whites until he
achieved a 70 percent to 30 percent, white-to-black mix.
</P>
<P>
   When Gantt resisted, he was told if ``you can't do this, I'll
get someone who can,'' the suit alleges.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit said the instructions were spelled out in a memo
that was sent to several high-ranking Waffle House executives,
including its chief executive and executive vice president.
</P>
<P>
   The pressure continued, and in the spring of 1998, Gantt was
fired for allegedly having an inappropriate relationship with an
employee he supervised.
</P>
<P>
   Gantt, who now owns and operates a restaurant in Beaufort,
denied the accusation.
</P>
<P>
   Waffle House spokesman Chris Jacobsen declined to comment on the
lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   However, Jacobsen said the company has a policy of ``zero
tolerance for any form of discrimination.''
</P>
<P>
   Kennan R.S. Nix, one of the attorneys who represents Gantt, said
he expected the company to fight the case.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no question that the company engages in widespread
patterns and practices of discrimination against African-American
employees, managers and customers,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In another discrimination case, a major Waffle House franchisee,
Northlake Foods, is being sued by five African-Americans customers
who claim a cook refused to serve them because of their race.
</P>
<P>
   Waffle House owns and operates 1,250 restaurants, mostly in the
Southeast.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
