<SLUG> BC-CRAY-TERA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SGI AGREES TO SELL ITS CRAY SUPERCOMPUTER BUSINESS TO TERA  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Wash., Calif., Minn. , Wis.)   By LAWRENCE M. FISHER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ SGI, formerly Silicon Graphics Inc., said
Thursday that it had agreed to sell its Cray supercomputer business
to Tera Computer Co. of Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   Terms were not disclosed, but analysts said there was little
doubt that Tera paid a fraction of the $740 million that SGI had
paid to acquire Cray Research Inc. in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   SGI shares closed at $9.875, down 25 cents apiece, on the New
York Stock Exchange. Tera shares fell $1.125, also to $9.875, on
the Nasdaq market.
</P>
<P>
   The sale of Cray at such a discount reflects both technology
trends and a shifting dynamic in the marketplace.
</P>
<P>
   Cray, once an icon of U.S. technological prowess and a national
asset for its deep involvement with the departments of Defense and
Energy, had already begun to slip from its perch before SGI
acquired it. Although Cray's huge supercomputers, which sell for as
much as $20 million, still excel at certain kinds of demanding
tasks, like simulating atomic explosions, they are increasingly
rivaled by machines based on microprocessors, like those used in
PCs, which cost much less.
</P>
<P>
   Cray's machines belong to a class of computers called vector
processors, so-called because they perform calculations on a long
series of numbers called vectors. Doing this at high speed requires
enormously powerful processors, which are built in small
quantities. In contrast, high-performance computing has
increasingly moved to parallel processing, in which lower-power,
lower-cost microprocessors are ganged to work on multiple
calculations at once. Cray also sells parallel systems.
</P>
<P>
   ``Basically, we don't see the vector business as a growth
business or a profitable business given the price/performance of a
product like that,'' said Kenneth Coleman, SGI's senior vice
president for sales and marketing. ``It's declining rapidly. It's
an industry phenomenon, not unique to Cray.''
</P>
<P>
   Cray is still attractive to Tera, which has sold just one
supercomputer since its formation in 1987. ``Cray has been the
pre-eminent supercomputer manufacturer,'' said Jim Rottsolk, Tera's
president and chief executive. ``We're a small company, just
entering the business, and being able to acquire the Cray operation
with a talented work force and its customer relationships, was, for
us, a no-brainer,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Tera will change its name to Cray to capitalize on the brand
awareness and reflect the importance of the acquired products,
which will contribute about $200 million a year in revenue to the
company. ``We have a different perspective than SGI,'' Rottsolk
said. ``It's true the market has been in decline, but that's
because there hasn't been a product to satisfy customer needs. We
believe we can expand and grow the market.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the Cray name, Tera is gaining about 775
employees in Egan, Minn., and Chippewa Falls, Wis., and the rights
to sell three lines of Cray supercomputers. Silicon Graphics is
retaining certain assets that will remain part of its
high-performance computer business. ``What we bought and what we
sold are not the same thing,'' Coleman said. ``We bought a company.
We're selling the vector business. Even in the Midwest, we will
have more people at SGI than Cray will have.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
