<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STOCKFRAUD-HEARING03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Figure in stock fraud case still in jail, looking for new lawyer
 &HT;    By Mark Clothier and Frances Katz
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Peter Lybrand, the alleged head of a $12 million
international stock fraud scheme based in a former dime store,
needs a lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   Attorneys for Lybrand, also known as Peter Tosto, were to have
told a federal judge in New York on Thursday why Lybrand should be
released on bail. Instead, a lawyer from the Manhattan firm Brafman
&AMP; Ross told a U.S. District judge that the firm will withdraw from
the case Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Lybrand, 35, is being held in a New York area jail until the new
bail hearing March 24. Assistant U.S. Attorney Joanna Hendon is
expected to ask that he be held without bail until trial.
</P>
<P>
   The extra time before the new hearing is to give Lybrand time to
find another lawyer and to give the lawyer time to learn the case,
said U.S. District Judge Theodore H. Katz, a chief magistrate judge
for the Southern District of New York.
</P>
<P>
   Lybrand is charged with manipulating stocks and defrauding
investors in three publicly traded companies, all while working and
living in Madison, Ga., an hour's drive east of downtown Atlanta.
He was arrested by the Federal Bureau of Investigation in New York
last week.
</P>
<P>
   Lybrand faces three counts each of securities fraud and lying to
the U.S. attorney's office, and one count each of perjury and
obstructing justice. The criminal fraud charges each carry a
maximum sentence of 10 years and $1 million or twice the proceeds
from the fraud. The remaining counts each carry a maximum fine of
$250,000 or twice the proceeds, and five years in prison. The
charges carry no minimum penalty.
</P>
<P>
   The Securities and Exchange Commission filed civil charges last
week as well.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
