<SLUG> BC-RETAIL-SALES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RETAIL SALES RISE IN FEBRUARY  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By LESLIE KAUFMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Even though the Federal Reserve raised interest rates, oil
prices increased and the stock market grew more volatile, American
consumers continued a record spending spree in stores in February,
a report showed Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Because of unusually mild weather, shoppers rushed to the stores
to buy their jean jackets and tropical print spring fashions early
and gave merchants a stronger-than-expected month. Sales in stores
open more than a year, a key industry measurement, rose 5.1 percent
in February, according to the Goldman Sachs retail composite index.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were enough factors that together they could have caused
the train to go off the track,'' said Jeff Feiner, a retail analyst
for Lehman Brothers, ``but consumer confidence has remained high,
and we are optimistic about the first quarter.''
</P>
<P>
   More good news came as the Commerce Department released its
first official estimate of electronic commerce retail sales, which
had previously been included with overall sales. The study found
that $5.3 billion worth of goods and services were sold online in
the fourth quarter of 1999. Although that number accounted for only
0.64 percent of the total retail economy of $821 billion for the
quarter, the data confirmed sharp growth in Internet commerce.
</P>
<P>
   The Commerce Department based its numbers on a survey of 12,000
Internet merchants who sold products as diverse as cars, furniture
and groceries. But the survey did not include travel services,
financial brokers and dealers and ticket sales, numbers that
consulting firms have often included in online predictions.
</P>
<P>
   February is not a significant month on the retail calendar,
accounting for only about 6 percent of sales in a year. As a
result, most analyst were not adjusting profit predictions for the
companies despite the better-than-expected results.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even though most of my companies have outperformed, I am not
changing earnings estimates,'' said George Strachan, a retail
analyst with Goldman, Sachs.
</P>
<P>
   In keeping with long-term industry trends, the retailers that
performed strongest last month were at opposite ends of the price
spectrum. On the luxury side were Saks Inc., whose sales rose 8
percent, and Neiman Marcus, which posted a gain of 11.2 percent.
Among the discounters, Costco continued its red-hot streak, with an
increase of 13 percent. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
