<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-RYAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LET'S PUT THE UNFORTUNATE ROCKER BEHIND US 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB RYAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAKE BUENA VISTA, Fla. _ John Rocker walked into a gymnasium
adjacent to the baseball field. He sat in front of a microphone,
read a 372-word general apology, and then departed.
</P>
<P>
   There was no immediate media probing. (He would later submit to
questioning from the Atlanta press only.) It was, said John
Schuerholz, the Atlanta Braves' executive vice president and
general manager, Rocker's choice not to take questions from the
national press. ``We neither discouraged him nor encouraged him
from doing anything,'' Schuerholz explained.
</P>
<P>
   OK, it would have been nice had Rocker satisfied the media mob.
He could have said, ``I'll deal with it this one time, and this one
time only.'' He could have said, ``Twenty minutes, and not a second
more.'' He did not. He read and ran.
</P>
<P>
   Excuse me for not feeling offended. Aren't we all just about
Rockered out, anyway?
</P>
<P>
   In his statement John Rocker apologized for the ``foul
language'' he used in the infamous Sports Illustrated article. ``I
was not raised that way,'' he insisted.
</P>
<P>
   He next apologized to AIDS victims and the assorted minority
groups he denigrated while taking his hypothetical trip on the 7
train. Pointing out that he has had various minority players as
house guests for periods ranging from two weeks to six months, he
said, ``As you can see, my actions do not support this racist
label,'' adding that ``My thoughtless words, however, do show that
sometimes I lack the understanding to see the problems others
face.''
</P>
<P>
   Finally, he apologized to the Atlanta organization, his manager,
and his teammates for the ``stress and confusion'' I have brought
on the Braves organization.''
</P>
<P>
   OK, fine. He did his public duty, even if it had the suspicious
rhetorical ring of an agent's prose and even if he didn't satisfy
those who apparently would have preferred he had been brought into
the room locked inside one of those Viet Cong cages. It was enough.
I'm not sure it would have been totally necessary to have him
answer an hour's worth of warmed-over
``Have-you-stopped-beating-your-wife?'' queries from righteous
media attack dogs.
</P>
<P>
   Of far more import was a meeting he had with the players and
coaches earlier in the morning. This is where his teammates looked
into his eyes and weighed the timber of his voice and decided
whether or not they would believe what he had to say. Those men are
his only meaningful judge and jury.
</P>
<P>
   And?
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he was very sincere, and I think he's sorry about the
pain and attention he has brought to the organization and the
team,'' said Brian Jordan, an African-American outfielder.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a good meeting,'' said Chipper Jones, a Caucasian third
baseman. ``Very positive. Guys got things off their chests.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody said what they had to say,'' explained Ozzie
Guillen, a Venezuelan shortstop. ``He said what he had to say. We
said what we had to say. Now we leave everything in the
clubhouse.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a productive meeting because we have so many good
veterans,'' declared Reggie Sanders, an African-American
outfielder. ``We have a lot of guys with good hearts. We're trying
to turn this into a positive situation.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We all forgive him,'' said Javy Lopez, a Puerto Rican catcher.
``We all gave him another chance. We are here to play baseball and
be a family.''
</P>
<P>
   If this is all a great collective acting bit, so be it. But
these are the only people whose opinions really count on this
matter, since they're the ones who have lived with him in the
clubhouse, busses, and planes the past three years. The fact is
they have a difficult time reconciling the John Rocker in the SI
article with the lovable goofball they know.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course, I was concerned when I read the article,'' said
Lopez. ``Everybody knows I'm a Puerto Rican. Those comments
included me. When I first heard about it, I just thought he was
reacting to the things that went on in New York during the World
Series. Then when I read it, I couldn't believe it. I thought he
was set up. But he wasn't. So I was confused.''
</P>
<P>
   Isn't it obvious that Javy's first instinct was correct? John
Rocker was getting back at the New York fans _ or, at least, he
thought he was _ when he went off on his 7 train riff. He was
extraordinarily foolish not to foresee the potential consequences
of his discourse.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the foolish rantings of a 25-year-old relief pitcher
should not materialize into a national issue. When are we going to
regain perspective? In a more reasoned world, people would have
looked at the Rocker quotes and said, ``I think I'll consider the
source.'' Why can't we learn to save our outrage for meaningful
occasions, like, when major presidential candidates refuse to
denounce a racist flag flying over a state capitol building?
</P>
<P>
   Instead, we have John Rocker's overturned suspension as the lead
story in some American newspapers. Said a somewhat exasperated
Schuerholz, ``This is a front-page story in a major national
newspaper over a man murdering four people in Pennsylvania in what
apparently is a racially-oriented killing.''
</P>
<P>
   It's not over, of course. People will have their fun with this
all season. ``It's a big step, but it will all take a while to calm
down,'' said Jordan. ``It won't happen today, or next week. In
every city there will be someone ready to light the fire.''
</P>
<P>
   Please don't forget that one reason the Braves are so willing to
reembrace John Rocker is the simple fact that he is very good at
what he does. They want him happy and content and just plain John
Rockerish. ``I want to see his focus,'' said Jones. ``I want to see
him run out of the bullpen the way he used to.''
</P>
<P>
   Guillen, age 36, sounds as if he would have been willing to live
with Rocker even if he (itals)didn't(unitals) think his apology was
sincere. ``He doesn't have to say he's sorry to anybody,'' he
growled. ``Just save 50 games, get me a ring, and make me some
money.''
</P>
<P>
   And this is a guy Rocker ripped for not making a play in Game 4
of the National League Championship Series. If he can get over it,
everyone else should, too. Acknowledge that the kid needs to do
some growing up, and then let's hunt around for something in our
society that's worth our legitimate outrage.
</P>
<P>
   That shouldn't be hard to do.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Bob Ryan is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
