<SLUG> BC-DELTA03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Northwest finds fault with Delta over exclusive Priceline fares
 &HT;    By Scott Thurston
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ A spat between Northwest and Delta airlines over the
availability of fares through Priceline.com has escalated into a
public feud.
</P>
<P>
   ``Have you heard what Delta is up to? Delta won't allow Atlanta
to receive competitive Priceline fares,'' Northwest complains in a
newspaper ad that appeared Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a Northwest problem, not an Atlanta customer
problem,'' responded Delta spokesman John Kennedy.
</P>
<P>
   For months, Northwest has fumed over its inability to sell seats
on Atlanta flights through Priceline.com, the name-your-price
Internet site.
</P>
<P>
   That's because Delta, the first major airline to participate in
Priceline.com, negotiated a clause that prevents other carriers
from offering seats to or from Atlanta at the site. The only
exceptions are nonstop routes between Atlanta and another carrier's
hub.
</P>
<P>
   The exclusivity clause was a savvy business deal, Kennedy said,
adding that Northwest is trying to manufacture a consumer issue.
</P>
<P>
   Delta sells ``thousands'' of tickets weekly through
Priceline.com, giving travelers good availability, Kennedy said. He
noted there are many other Internet sites where consumers can also
shop.
</P>
<P>
   But Northwest pricing executive Tom Bach said Delta's
Priceline.com sales on Atlanta routes are ``at generally higher
fares'' than users of the Web site get in other cities.
</P>
<P>
   ``It isn't a level playing field'' for either airlines or
consumers, Bach said, adding that none of the other airlines that
participates in Priceline.com has such protection for its hub
cities.
</P>
<P>
   Northwest is doing more than just complaining. Since November
it's run a fare sale on its own Web site, nwa.com, aimed
specifically at Atlanta fliers. Fares range from $98 to $218 round
trip.
</P>
<P>
   Delta, in turn, has retaliated with special fares on its Web
site, delta-air.com, for travelers in Minneapolis, Detroit and
Memphis _ Northwest's hubs.
</P>
<P>
   Priceline.com spokesman Brian Ek wouldn't comment on the terms
of Delta's contract, or on the dispute. ``We're not getting in the
middle of it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Delta's early participation in Priceline.com got it more than a
hometown advantage. Delta took warrants for 18.6 million shares of
Priceline stock, which later went public. Delta has since sold part
of its holdings, netting $711 million so far.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
