<SLUG> BC-DOUBLECLICK-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOUBLECLICK, ASSAILED ON PRIVACY ISSUE, BACKS DOWN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HIAWATHA BRAY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Stung by protests from Internet privacy advocates and a federal
investigation, Internet advertising firm DoubleClick Inc. has
halted its plan to use name and address data to track the online
activities of millions of consumers.
</P>
<P>
   In a frank admission that his company had blundered, DoubleClick
chief executive Kevin O'Connor said Thursday his company would not
use such data until the Internet industry and the federal
government establish firm guidelines to protect the privacy of
Internet users.
</P>
<P>
   ``I made a mistake by planning to merge names with anonymous
user activity across Web sites in the absence of government and
industry privacy standards,'' O'Connor said. He added that New
York-based DoubleClick had not yet begun the controversial
practice, despite press reports to the contrary. ``We commit today
that until there is agreement between government and industry on
privacy standards, we will not link personally identifiable
information to anonymous user activity across Web sites.''
</P>
<P>
   Marc Rotenberg, executive director of the Electronic Privacy
Information Center, hailed the policy shift.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think DoubleClick finally got the message,'' he said. ``It's
a step in the right direction.'' But the only satisfactory
solution, he said, is a federal law setting strict standards for
the use of data collected on the Internet, an unpopular idea among
Internet marketers.
</P>
<P>
   Esther Dyson, publisher of industry newsletter Release 1.0, also
helped establish the Internet privacy consortium TrustE. Dyson said
the DoubleClick announcement is intended to fend off the heavy hand
of government. ``The point they're trying to make is that
self-regulation in the market works, because, look, we stopped,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   But at the same time, O'Connor's words suggest to Dyson that
DoubleClick might accept some degree of government privacy
regulation. ``He's saying we need something. We need something
clear and explicit.''
</P>
<P>
   US Representative Ed Markey, who has long favored a federal
Internet privacy law, thinks major Internet companies may be coming
to the same conclusion. ``I think increasingly many in the industry
realize that it makes no sense for the best participants to
continue to protect the worst online companies,'' he said. The
large Internet companies already have good policies, he said, while
smaller firms are more likely to misuse personal data.
</P>
<P>
   DoubleClick's travails began last year, when the company spent
more than $1 billion to acquire Abacus Direct, a marketing database
firm with the names and addresses of millions of Americans on file.
DoubleClick announced a plan to combine this data with information
collected from users of various Internet sites. DoubleClick already
tracks the Internet surfing habits of millions of individuals, by
displaying advertisements on their Web browsers. These ads contain
identification tags called ``cookies'' that link to the user's
computer and enable DoubleClick to track their movements through
the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   But cookies have traditionally been anonymous _ DoubleClick and
other firms that use them don't know the identities of the people
being tracked. But with Abacus, DoubleClick planned to change that,
linking cookies with name and address information to build detailed
profiles of a user's tastes and interests.
</P>
<P>
   The goal was to create a database that would be worth millions
of dollars to marketers on or off the Internet. But consumer groups
and privacy advocates were outraged by the idea. Last month a woman
in California sued the company; the attorney general of Michigan
and the Federal Trade Commission both launched investigations.
</P>
<P>
   DoubleClick's woes continue to escalate. On Wednesday, Internet
home delivery service Kozmo.com announced it would no longer carry
advertisements linked to the DoubleClick system. The same day, the
AltaVista Internet search service announced it would limit the
amount of user information made available to DoubleClick. AltaVista
is owned by Andover-based CMGI Inc., which also owns Engage
Technologies Inc., DoubleClick's biggest competitor. Engage,
however, does not collect names and addresses of Internet users.
</P>
<P>
   And Thursday, the leading financial software maker Intuit Inc.
announced that DoubleClick ads on its Web site were inadvertently
sending personal information from users to DoubleClick. The problem
was caused by a bug in HTML, the coding method used to build Web
pages. There is no evidence that DoubleClick was collecting the
information being sent by Intuit. And the same information could
also be sent to other Internet advertising firms, not just
DoubleClick.
</P>
<P>
   But independent computer security specialist Richard Smith of
Brookline, Mass., who discovered the problem, said he began warning
DoubleClick in October that the privacy leak existed. Smith said
DoubleClick could have warned sites that displayed its ads so they
could fix the bug. But no action was taken. The story came out
because Smith discovered the bug on the Intuit site, and informed
that company of the problem. As for DoubleClick, ``They have got to
be more proactive than they have,'' Smith said.
</P>
<P>
   DoubleClick may not be hurt financially by delaying its
data-collection plan. Anthia Christian, analyst with William Blair
&AMP; Co. in Chicago, says revenues from Abacus' other database
businesses still make it a profitable investment for DoubleClick.
</P>
<P>
   DoubleClick stock rose $2.875 to close at $83.4375 on the Nasdaq
stock exchange.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
