<SLUG> BC-RUN-GARCIA03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Garcia makes late run to head of pack
 &HT;    By Mike Fish
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Donna Garcia never thought of herself as an Olympic
hopeful.
</P>
<P>
   Garcia had been a scholarship runner at the University of
Kentucky, but the bulk of her postcollegiate years have focused on
the 9-to-5 world. She traveled the back roads of Georgia and
Tennessee calling on grocers as account manager for Pepperidge
Farms. Her day job always came first.
</P>
<P>
   That's all changing.
</P>
<P>
   Almost out of nowhere, Garcia has developed into a major factor
in women's distance running. The 31-year-old Marietta, Ga.,
resident earned a spot recently on the U.S. team for next month's
World Cross Country Championships in Villamoura, Portugal. She is
one of only two women qualifying in both the 4K and 8K races.
</P>
<P>
   Garcia already had qualified for the Olympic trials in the 5,000
meters and, if plans go as scripted, she will do the same in the
10,000 meters. In April, she will take a break from her job to
pursue her Olympic dream in full.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm at a point where I need to give this running thing 100
percent of my time and see what I can do,'' Garcia said. She moved
near Atlanta three years ago and trains with Georgia State
Professor Dave Martin, a running guru.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can say I'll be a long shot going into the Olympic trials,
but stranger things have happened,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The next step comes Saturday in the USA Indoor Track and Field
Championships, where Garcia is entered in a strong 3,000-meter
women's field. This year's meet is short on big-name athletes, but
the 3,000 figures to be one of the more competitive races, with
Garcia and Amy Rudolph, Marla Runyan, Kathy Fleming and Blake
Russell.
</P>
<P>
   Her coach said he thinks her future will be in the longer 10,000
meters as she continues developing strength and endurance. Her
debut in that event is this spring.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's a real success story,'' Martin said. ``Like a lot of
postcollegiate runners, she got a job and started working her way
up the corporate ladder. But she continued to run and harbored an
interest in staying competitive. In every single race, over the
three years she has been running competitively, she has gotten
better and better.''
</P>
<P>
   Garcia began hitting her stride last year, running in her first
World Cross Country Championship and posting a 5,000-meter time of
15:57 to qualify for her first Olympic trials. Her goals got
grander. With a boost to her confidence, she started training
harder and thinking she could run with top Americans.
</P>
<P>
   ``So many things have changed for me,'' Garcia said. ``It seems,
every time I run, I'm running at a new level or new standard. I
look around and see the who's who of American distance running _
Regina Jacobs (36) and Libbie Hickman (35) _ and they're older than
me. It's inspiring.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
