<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STAPLES-EARNS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOT-COM SLIDE OVERWHELMS STAPLES' EARNINGS REPORT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHRIS REIDY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Staples Inc., the office-supply retailer, announced Thursday
that its fourth-quarter profits rose 27 percent.
</P>
<P>
   So what happened? Its stock fell sharply on the disclosure that
its small Internet business will run up much bigger losses this
year than previously estimated.
</P>
<P>
   As a brick-and-mortar retailer, Staples continues to turn in
impressive performances. But investors were spooked by news
that &UR;  &LR; the Framingham, Mass. company expects losses this year for
Staples.com to double to $150 million on expected sales of $250
million.
</P>
<P>
   Staples.com sales in fiscal 1999 were $94.3 million, only a
sliver of the company's total sales of $8.84 billion. Still, shares
of Staples stock fell 4 11/16, closing on the Nasdaq at 21 5/8.
</P>
<P>
   The company had been projecting losses for this year of $75
million for Staples.com, said PaineWebber analyst Aram Rubinson.
Doubling that projection was not what Wall Street wanted to hear,
he said.
</P>
<P>
   For the quarter that ended Jan. 29, Staples.com had a loss of
$9.8 million on sales of $43.1 million, compared with a loss of
$285,000 on sales of $7.8 million in the same period a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   Rubinson had nothing but good things to say about Staples'
traditional brick-and-mortar operation.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're a terrific retailer, one of the best around,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   But for the short term, Staples may find itself in a
click-and-mortar dilemma. The Net has spawned two types of
retailers. There are so-called pure-plays _ retailers that only
sell goods online. Then there are click-and-mortar businesses such
as Staples that sell goods online and in brick-and-mortar stores.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, big losses were almost a badge of honor for publicly
traded pure-play retailers. Though these upstarts produced oceans
of red ink, investors bid up their stock prices to lofty levels.
</P>
<P>
   Yet when traditional retailers dabble in the new economy of
e-commerce, they're now sometimes judged by the hard-eyed
arithmetic of the old economy. That's one reason why Staples plans
to issue a separate stock that tracks the performance of
Staples.com.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview with CNNfn, Staples chairman and chief executive
Thomas G. Stemberg expressed some frustration with how Wall Street
now seems to regard his company and the potential for Staples.com.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do think there are some analysts who don't fully appreciate
the long-term ramifications of significant moves on the Internet,''
said Stemberg.
</P>
<P>
   The company also said that the Staples.com work force should
grow from 140 to 300 employees this year.
</P>
<P>
   For the fourth quarter, Staples said its net income was $129.2
million. Fourth-quarter sales rose 25 percent to $2.59 billion. At
stores open at least a year, sales rose 10 percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
