<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FIDELITY-EARNS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIDELITY INVESTMENTS DOUBLES PROFIT IN 1999 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BETH HEALY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Fidelity Investments earned a record $1.01 billion last
year, more than doubling its 1998 profit, as surging online
investments helped push managed assets to nearly $1 trillion.
</P>
<P>
   The results mark a huge comeback for the nation's biggest mutual
fund firm after a disappointing 1998, when earnings slumped 17
percent. Fidelity attributed the gains to a jump in Web activity,
higher fund sales through brokers, and success overseas,
particularly in Canada and Japan, according to its annual report,
released Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Fidelity's revenues rose 31 percent, to $8.85 billion, twice the
growth rate in 1998. At the same time, Fidelity reaped cost savings
by driving more trading and customer service to the Web.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's very cost effective,'' said James Lowell, editor of
Fidelity Investor, an independent newsletter in Needham, Mass. He
suggested Fidelity's internal motto last year was ``to get our
customers onto the Web. That's clearly the mission.''
</P>
<P>
   Fidelity introduced its Powerstreet online brokerage last year,
which lets customers trade, track their investments, and access
news and research online. The number of Internet accounts at the
firm soared 71 percent last year, to 3.5 million.
</P>
<P>
   Assets in online accounts doubled to $269.2 billion. That was
five times the 20 percent growth seen in Fidelity's traditional
mutual funds, which totaled $351.1 billion at the end of 1999.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, the number of phone calls handled in
Fidelity's service centers decreased to 659.3 million from 680.1
million in 1998. That meant 3.1 percent fewer calls per day.
</P>
<P>
   In his letter to shareholders and employees in the annual
report, Fidelity chairman Edward C. Johnson 3d noted that fund
sales to individuals grew ``less vigorously'' than in the past. He
called the market for selling funds to individuals ``maturing and
highly competitive.''
</P>
<P>
   As the entire fund industry grapples with slower growth,
Fidelity is gunning to increase its share of online brokerage, to
compete with Charles Schwab &AMP; Co. and newer entrants such as
E-Trade. The popularity of online trading took off last year, as
investors were dazzled by unusually quick returns on technology
stocks.
</P>
<P>
   Fidelity customers did 78 percent of their trades on the Web in
1999, up from 64 percent in the prior year. And investors sent
55,417 trades per day to Fidelity, more than double the 21,561
trades executed per day in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   A strong, if up-and-down, stock market buoyed Fidelity's growth
last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just the market going up gives them more earnings,'' observed
Michael Lipper, founder of Lipper Inc., the Summit, N.J.,
fund-ranking firm. Indeed, not only does Fidelity earn more fees
with every dollar that comes in the door, but several of its stock
funds regained the old star power that wowed investors in the late
1980s and early 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-four of Fidelity's stock funds beat the benchmark
Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 Index. And there were many standouts. The
firm's Aggressive Growth soared 103 percent, while New Millennium
(closed to new investors) rose 109 percent. Growth Company jumped
79.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The performance of several hot funds overshadowed the fact that
Fidelity's funds beat only 50 percent of their peers in 1999, down
from 70 percent in 1998. Active managers across the industry beat
the indexes and posted strong returns.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson described last year as ``an environment that was less
than calm because of market volatility and increasing
competition.''
</P>
<P>
   In the Fidelity Capital group, where Fidelity starts and runs
new ventures, there were several big gains:
</P>
<P>
   --BostonCoach's revenues jumped 19 percent to $90 million.
</P>
<P>
   --Fidelity's Life Insurance Co. notched a record $2 billion in
sales for the year, for a total $16 billion under management.
</P>
<P>
   --Fidelity received a federal savings bank charter.
</P>
<P>
   In a nod to the success of COLT, the telecommmunications company
Fidelity Capital launched and took public, Johnson said the firm
had to be careful ``that we don't neglect our traditional
businesses even as new opportunities demand our energy.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
