<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-02 19:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4954 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-NFL-PATRIOTS-BOS &LR;      03-02 0374
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NFL-PATRIOTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NFL PAYS CONNECTICUT $2.4M TO SETTLE PATRIOTS CLAIMS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (f and s coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MEG VAILLANCOURT  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The National Football League paid Connecticut $2.4
million Thursday to settle any legal claims the state might seek
over the New England Patriots' hustle out of Hartford last year.
</P>
<P>
   Governor John G. Rowland said the money will allow the state to
recoup the legal and planning costs incurred during negotiations
with the team.
</P>
<P>
   ``I made the decision that instead of making up some number and
applying something for punitive damages or emotional stress . . .
the best thing to do was to ask for just the reimbursement for the
costs we incurred,'' Rowland said.
</P>
<P>
   While every team in the league will pay a share of the
settlement, NFL officials said the agreement absolved both the
league and the Patriots of any wrongdoing.
</P>
<P>
   As part of the agreement, Connecticut also returned a $2 million
letter of credit to the Patriots, which the state had been holding
since last spring.
</P>
<P>
   ``The state of Connecticut pursued its stadium proposal fairly
and we are pleased that all remaining issues have been resolved,''
NFL commissioner Paul Tagliabue said.
</P>
<P>
   As the Boston Globe reported last week, the settlement comes
almost a year after Kraft announced he was pulling out of a deal to
move his team from Foxborough to a publicly financed stadium in
downtown Hartford.
</P>
<P>
   Kraft signed an agreement to relocate in late 1998, but within
months it was clear there were serious problems in cleaning up the
polluted stadium site. Using a clause in the contact giving him a
penalty-free exit prior to May 1, Kraft backed out of the deal
April 30, 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after Kraft walked away from Connecticut, Bay State
lawmakers passed a bill giving the team $70 million in
infrastructure aid for a new Foxboro Stadium. The bill had been
pushed by the NFL and Boston business leaders.
</P>
<P>
   Massachusetts lawmakers and the Patriots insist they respected
language forbidding the team from talking with anyone else while
the contract was in force. Patriots spokesman Stacey James said
Kraft would not comment on the settlement.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-02-00 1948EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000302.0323 </DOCNO>
