<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-02 19:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4955 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u p BC-CAMPAIGN-REPUBLICANS-     03-02 0635
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAMPAIGN-REPUBLICANS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH-MCCAIN ENMITY GAP NOW 2,000 MILES WIDE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JILL ZUCKMAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ What a difference a few primaries make.
</P>
<P>
   Back before the first votes were ever cast, George W. Bush and
John McCain had only the warmest of words for one another. At
debates, they referred to one another as friends, and when they saw
each other they hugged. Never was a critical word exchanged.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just think I would make a better president,'' was the worst
that McCain could muster. Usually, he would say of his rival: ``I
think he's a very fine and decent person who's been a good
governor.''
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Bush repeatedly praised McCain as a hero. ``John
is a good man. I do think his story is compelling,'' Bush has said.
``He's a straight talker.''
</P>
<P>
   No more. Since they left New Hampshire behind, enmity has
replaced cordiality. Each man has a long list of grievances against
the other. And Thursday night, there was no hugging before the
debate, with the pair separated by about 2,000 miles, a gap that
was as much a metaphor for the state of their relationship as it
was a matter of geography.
</P>
<P>
   When asked this week about the status of the friendship, Bush
was cool and clipped: ``That's something I'll have to reassess
after the primary is over.''
</P>
<P>
   And though Bush called McCain to congratulate him on his victory
in New Hampshire, he ignored political etiquette and did not
congratulate McCain for winning primaries in Michigan and Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   McCain, however, called Bush after losing to the Texas governor
in South Carolina and after Bush won the Virginia primary. But
McCain said their most recent conversation was terse on Tuesday
night.
</P>
<P>
   McCain congratulated Bush, and Bush said ``thanks.'' End of
phone call. McCain shrugged his shoulders after recounting the
frosty reception.
</P>
<P>
   By all accounts, the relationship broke down as soon as the pair
arrived in South Carolina. A veteran, by the name of J. Thomas
Burch, Jr. stood by Bush's side and accused McCain -- a prisoner of
war in North Vietnam for five and a half years -- of abandoning
veterans and their concerns about Agent Orange and the Gulf War
Syndrome.
</P>
<P>
   ``He came home and he forgot us,'' said Burch, chairman of the
National Vietnam and Gulf War Coalition.
</P>
<P>
   It was an affront that angered McCain, who believed that Bush
should have repudiated Burch on the spot. ``I gave him a pass on
the National Guard and now he comes after me on this,'' McCain said
at the time, referring to Bush's stateside service during the war.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, on the other hand, reacted with outrage when McCain
launched a television commercial comparing him to President Clinton
and accusing him of breaking a handshake agreement not to run
negative ads.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do we really want another politician in the White House we
can't trust,'' asks the announcer.
</P>
<P>
   Said Bush: ``That's about as low a blow as you can get in the
Republican primary.''
</P>
<P>
   On a daily basis since, the back-and-forth continues to take on
an increasingly emotional tenor as every charge ratchets up the
palpable dislike between the two as they argue over phone banks,
push-polling, fliers and political ads.
</P>
<P>
   In the final days of the primary contest, there is little hope
of a let up. The Bush campaign began running a radio ad in New York
accusing McCain of opposing federal funds for breast cancer
research, which caused McCain, once again, to react with dismay.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is this really the way to run a presidential campaign?''
McCain said when he first found out. ``You would think this was for
county sheriff.''
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, he was even sharper, for fear voters would believe he
is uncaring about cancer: ``Governor Bush, get out of the gutter.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-02-00 1950EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000302.0324 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-02 19:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4956 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-BBN-ROCKER-SCENE03-CO     03-02 0673
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-ROCKER-SCENE03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A start, but closure's not close
 &HT;    By Steve Hummer
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   KISSIMMEE, Fla. _ As John Rocker slipped onto Disney property
Thursday morning, he, like everyone else, was greeted at the gate
by the likenesses of the Magic Kingdom's cartoon elite.
</P>
<P>
   Bigger than life, there they are, a mouse of color and a duck
with a speech impediment. Even here, a lesson in diversity. There
is nowhere to escape from life's delicious differences, a truth
being jackhammered home to the Braves' raked-over reliever.
</P>
<P>
   We interrupt the odes to spring to bring you the latest in the
saga of a baseball player turned pariah. About 150 media types and
half as many Braves invitees were here to witness Rocker's return.
It was no great honor to be part of the former group, as we staked
out the parking lot by the light of dawn in hopes of glimpsing his
first steps toward redemption. As if his every movement was of
presidential importance. On top of that, we missed him, Rocker
already showing a gift for finding the side entrance that will
serve him well this season.
</P>
<P>
   This day would have been so much better spent celebrating the
start of spring games, the Georgia Bulldogs in to get some
snapshots and take their annual beating. A fine and beautiful day
in which the Braves' phenom in training, Rafael Furcal, went deep
his first at-bat.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Rocker came down out of that deer stand where Sports
Illustrated left him, exchanged the camouflage for his Braves
blues, and commenced trying to get right with his team. No longer a
symbol, now a flesh and blood presence.
</P>
<P>
   It would be wonderful to report that Thursday was the merciful
end of the Rocker ordeal. It also would be wrong. Call this, at
best, the beginning of the end. Or, at least, the end of the
beginning.
</P>
<P>
   First came the meeting with his teammates, and by most reports,
it went swimmingly. They seem to be putting more effort into the
reconciliation than Rocker himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``Actually, it was much better than I thought it would be,''
Rocker said about the reception.
</P>
<P>
   The making over of Rocker has gone so far that Brian Jordon, one
of his sternest critics after the offensive SI story, was moved to
say, ``The guy's gone through a lot. I feel sorry for him.'' It's
but a short leap from there to martyrdom.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the closer did find some closure.
</P>
<P>
   His initial meeting with the gathered media was less successful.
The last event staged in the Disney field house was a
cheer-and-dance competition. Then came Rocker, for something
completely different. He didn't even try to tap dance. He simply
read another statement, with all the feeling of a man ordering off
a cafeteria menu.
</P>
<P>
   We still await the first signs of unscripted contrition. On the
other hand, keeping his mouth shut is not such a terrible idea.
</P>
<P>
   Forget the shortened suspension. Rocker's punishment began this
day. As he left the news conference, he was shadowed by mini-cams.
As he retreated to the bullpen, cameramen scrambled to the high
ground of the right field seats to shoot down on his sanctuary. A
beefy Disney security man tried to keep microphones away while
Rocker signed autographs. Peace will come grudgingly.
</P>
<P>
   The voice of the people seemed with him. He was cheered as he
made his first appearance, warming up with friend Rudy Seanez in
the outfield. Making his way back to the clubhouse after the
morning labors, he could hear, ``Way to go, Rocker!'' and ``First
Amendment!'' and ``We love you, John!''
</P>
<P>
   Only one dissenter, his Big Apple roots obvious in his accent,
said, ``You'll like the reception in New York.'' Hardly the worst
Rocker will hear this season.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday only started a long process. There's an evolution going
on. ``It's John's turn to be humble,'' Chipper Jones said. ``We'll
see how humble he is.''
</P>
<P>
   And what better time and place for him to get the message that
it's a small world after all.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
