<DOCNO> NYT20000302.0327 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-02 19:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4963 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-MEXICO-WHALES-0303-CO     03-02 0705
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-WHALES-0303-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    MEXICAN GOVERNMENT, MITSUBISHI SCRAP PLANS FOR SALT MINE
 &HT;    By SUSAN FERRISS 
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN DIEGO, Calif. _ After a five-year battle, the Mexican
government and Japan's Mitsubishi Corp. pulled the plug Thursday on
an industrial project critics said would have harmed one of the
last pristine gray whale breeding grounds in the world.
</P>
<P>
   The project would have created one of the world's largest salt
mining industries inside Mexico's Viscaino Biosphere Reserve, on
the Pacific Coast of Baja California Sur.
</P>
<P>
   An existing salt factory _ Exportadora del Sal (ESSA) _ is 51
percent-owned by the Mexican government and 49 percent-owned by
Mitsubishi. Since 1994, a plan to build the second plant on the
nearby Laguna San Ignacio has drawn international criticism from
environmental groups.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're ecstatic,'' said Jared Blumenfeld, habitat director of
the International Fund for Animal Welfare (IFAW). `` We're proud to
have protected one of the world's true natural treasures.''
</P>
<P>
   Even though Mitsubishi and Mexico government believed that
scientific evidence supported their claim that the factory would
not harm the whales' breeding ground, on Thursday they acknowledged
mounting public pressure against the project and agreed that it
would have an adverse impact on the landscape near the lagoon.
</P>
<P>
   ``We became more and more aware of the need to preserve the
environmental integrity of the area,'' said Mitsubishi
International executive vice president James Brumm, speaking at a
news conference in Mexico City. ``There was a lot of public
pressure, and we certainly felt the brunt of all that.''
</P>
<P>
   Environmentalists gathering in San Diego Thursday night for a
trip to Baja California Sur to see the whales said that their
journey will now be a celebration.
</P>
<P>
   Some whale experts argue that the existing salt factory on the
edge of another breeding area had not reduced the number of gray
whales that migrate there. Others argue that the salt factory has
contributed to degradation of the environment.
</P>
<P>
   Environmentalists opposed to the proposed salt works called
their five-year campaign one of the most important battles to
preserve the environment and bio-diversity. They argued that the
project would not only threaten the gray whales, but other
endangered species including black sea turtles and prong-horned
antelopes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Legally, there should never have been the possibility that
this would pass muster,'' said Mark Spalding, an international
environmental policy expert at the University of California at San
Diego and consultant to environmental groups. ``This is the largest
biosphere in all of Latin America. It is in the country that came
up with the concept of biospheres. And the precedent set would have
reverberated worldwide.''
</P>
<P>
   Blumenfeld said a massive grassroots campaign that targeted
Mitsubishi and its automobile dealerships with boycotts forced the
Japanese multinational to listen. Critics sent more than one
million letters to Mitsubishi urging them to stop the second plant.
Forty-three cities in California passed resolutions against the
project, and similar campaigns were underway in Europe, Mexico and
Japan.
</P>
<P>
   IFAW persuaded asset managers of 15 ``environmentally
sensitive'' mutual funds, representing some $14 billion in assets,
to not do business with Mitsubishi.
</P>
<P>
   Blumenfeld also said Mitsubishi dealerships and Union Bank of
California, in which Mitsubishi owns a majority stake, had come
under pressure from customers. The companies told environmentalists
they too wanted the project ``to go away,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The environmentalists' showed ``it's not enough to say this is a
beautiful place that deserves to be protected, you've got to hurt a
company's bottom line.''
</P>
<P>
   In remarks Thursday, Mexican President Ernesto Zedillo said the
``national and world importance and the uniqueness of the Viscaino
Biosphere Reserve'' was an overriding concern persuading the
government to scrap the proposed 116-square-mile project that ESSA
said would have created 200 much-needed jobs to the isolated
region.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
