<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-02 19:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4964 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w BC-CLINTON-AIDS-BOS &LR;      03-02 0838
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-AIDS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON OFFERS FIRMS $1B CREDIT IN SEARCH FOR CHEAP AIDS VACCINE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (w and f coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN DONNELLY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Hoping to spur a race for the discovery of vaccines
for the world's deadliest diseases, President Clinton Thursday
brought into the White House the heads of the four largest
pharmaceutical companies with an offer to create a guaranteed
market for new drugs in poor countries.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton announced legislation to create a $1 billion tax credit
over 10 years for pharmaceuticals that would cover the cost of an
economical vaccine for HIV/AIDS, tuberculosis or malaria in
developing nations.
</P>
<P>
   The meeting, remniscent of the gathering organized by White
House in 1996 when Clinton cajoled apparel and footwear companies
to end exploitation in sweatshops, was prompted by the unfolding
health pandemic in Africa, where 13 million children have lost one
or both parents to the AIDS virus.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said nothing at the beginning of the meeting in his
Cabinet Room, but listened for an hour to participants from
pharmaceutical and biotech companies, from public health advocates,
from philanthropic institutions and from those in his
administration. He spoke at the end, telling the group that dealing
the disease of those in poverty was a moral obligation, ``one very
much in our self interest as well,'' according to the notes of one
participant.
</P>
<P>
   ``He told us, `It was the right thing to do,' '' said Carol
Bellamy, executive director of UNICEF.
</P>
<P>
   The big question remains whether the pharmaceutical companies _
known as Big Pharma _ will calculate that the administration's
incentives, coupled with other publicly financed sweeteners, would
create a profitable market.
</P>
<P>
   There was some doubt Thursday. ``I think it's great the
president called this meeting, but what we've heard from the
industry in the past is that $1 billion is not nearly enough pull
to get Big Pharma interested in working on these vaccines,'' said
Jim Yong Kim, co-director of Harvard's Program in Infectious
Disease and Social Change.
</P>
<P>
   Michael R. Kremer, a Harvard economist whose research influenced
the president's proposal, said in an interview Thursday the plan
was ``a major step in the right direction, but I think more is
going to be needed.''
</P>
<P>
   Kremer, who estimated a need for $2.5 billion over 10 years in
incentives per vaccine to spark interest from the pharmaceuticals,
said he expected funds from the World Bank and European countries
to help bridge the gap.
</P>
<P>
   The administration plan, which in some respect parallels
legislation sponsored by Democratic Senator John Kerry of
Massachusetts and Republican Senator Bill Frist of Tennessee, also
calls for $50 million toward a vaccine purchase fund established by
the Global Alliance for Vaccines.
</P>
<P>
   The meeting Thursday almost fell through, according to Senate
and White House officials. In exchange for a presidential audience
and the ensuing free publicity, White House officials requested the
pharmaceutical companies donate large amounts of existing vaccines
and push ahead with clinical trials of drugs.
</P>
<P>
   At first, officials resisted, but later relented. Among the
announcements Thursday outside the Cabinet Room: Merck &AMP; Co.
donated 5 million doses of Recombivaz HB, a vaccine to prevent
hepititus B, a $100 million value; SmithKline Beecham agreed to
continue a second stage of clinical trial for a malaria vaccine;
American Home Products Corp. donated 10 million doses of
Haemophilus influenza type-B vaccine, helping protect 3 million
children; and Aventis Pharm gave 50 million doses of polio vaccine
to five war-ravaged African nations.
</P>
<P>
   The company heads said they were already committed to doing
research on vaccines. ``The key is once these drugs are discovered,
is to get access to them worldwide, particularly the developing
world,'' said Raymond V. Gilmartin, chairman, president and CEO of
Merck.
</P>
<P>
   Gilmartin described the White House initiative as a means of
`providing funding to the developing world to be able to develop
the infrastructure, the health-care delivery systems, as well as to
be able to finance health programs within each of these
countries.''
</P>
<P>
   Said William Gates Sr., co-president of the Bill and Melinda
Gates Foundation: ``There's a real prospect that we will change the
world in a very significant way in a matter of a very few years.''
</P>
<P>
   After the meeting, Nils Daulaire, president and CEO of Global
Health Council, a White River Junction, Vt.-based coalition of
international providers, said he was surprised at the support
expressed by the industry presidents.
</P>
<P>
   ``They see the opening being provided by the president's
policy,'' said Daulaire, a former administration health policy
adviser. ``One of the Big Pharma heads said vaccines account for
less than 2 percent of their overall budget. They could double
their investment and still not make a huge dent on their bottom
line.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
