<HEADER>
A4967 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-LEWIS-COP03-COX     03-02 0409
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEWIS-COP03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Lewis investigator faces probe over remark
 &HT;    By Lyda Longa
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The Atlanta policeman who arrested Baltimore Ravens
star Ray Lewis on murder charges is under investigation within his
own department for allegedly asking questions of a racial nature
that angered two potential witnesses in the case.
</P>
<P>
   The Atlanta Police Department's Office of Professional Standards
and Deputy Chief C.B. Jackson have confirmed that an inquiry has
begun to determine whether Lt. Mike Smith made a remark that
offended two men who are acquainted with Lewis. The men are
African-American.
</P>
<P>
   Tony Williams, one of the potential witnesses, had been with
Lewis on Jan. 29, while Lewis was signing autographs at the Sports
Authority in Duluth, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   But before police could learn what Williams knew about the three
knives purchased at the store that day, the interview turned sour.
</P>
<P>
   According to Williams, Smith immediately asked who, other than
Lewis, was at the Sports Authority.
</P>
<P>
   Williams said he told Smith he knew of only one other man, and
knew him only by nickname. Smith then asked Williams what his own
nickname was. Williams says that when he told Smith he didn't have
one, the officer responded: ``C'mon, you know all you
African-Americans have a nickname for each other.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams said he and the other witness left the room and refused
to continue the interview.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't believe I went up there to talk to them as a citizen
and I was treated like that,'' Williams said this week. ``When he
said that I told him, `I don't appreciate that kind of comment,'
and I walked out.''
</P>
<P>
   Investigator Ken Allen, the lead detective on the killings, ran
after Williams and apologized for Smith's remark, Williams said.
</P>
<P>
   Smith, a 26-year veteran of the force who was named commander of
the homicide unit in September, said the men misinterpreted his
comment.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said something that may have been taken the wrong way, but I
would never say anything of a racial nature,'' Smith said. ``I was
on Maynard Jackson's executive protection team. How could I be a
racist?''
</P>
<P>
   Jeffrey Norman, an associate city attorney, confirmed the Smith
investigation. The Office of Professional Standards investigates
every complaint lodged against a police officer. An investigation
could last several months
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
