<SLUG> BC-STABBINGS-DRUGTEST03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Lawyer seeks tests on stabbing victims
 &HT;    By Bill Torpy
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The attorney for one of the defendants in the
post-Super Bowl stabbing deaths in Atlanta asked the court Thursday
for the drug test results performed on the two men killed.
</P>
<P>
   The move is another indication that at least one of the three
defendants in the case will claim the killings were self-defense.
</P>
<P>
   Steven Sadow, attorney for murder suspect Joseph Sweeting, is
seeking tests performed on the bodies of Richard Lollar and Jacinth
Baker.
</P>
<P>
   He claims the tests ``will tend to show that one or both of the
decedents were aggressors.''
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Sadow filed a motion asking for the tests performed
on the gun he contends Lollar might have carried the night of the
killings.
</P>
<P>
   It is not clear if police even have the gun that was fired at
the scene. Friends of Lollar say he did not own a gun.
</P>
<P>
   Sweeting is a co-defendant with All Pro linebacker Ray Lewis and
Reginald Oakley.
</P>
<P>
   The three were rushed into a limousine when a fight broke out
near the Cobalt lounge in Buckhead, Atlanta's entertainment
district. The two men died of stab wounds to the chest.
</P>
<P>
   In other motions filed Thursday, Ray Lewis' attorneys asked to
opt in to the discovery process, meaning that the state must,
before trial, turn over evidence it uncovers in the case. By doing
so, the Lewis team must turn over their evidence to the state.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
