<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-02 19:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4969 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-TV-WALLS03-COX     03-02 0703
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-WALLS03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Redgrave a standout in HBO's special
 &HT;    By Phil Kloer
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   From the love that dare not speak its name to the love that gets
its own prime-time show, a new HBO special, ``If These Walls Could
Talk 2,'' traces the recent history of lesbianism.
</P>
<P>
   It does so with splashy stars (Sharon Stone, Vanessa Redgrave,
Ellen DeGeneres, Chloe Sevigny, Michelle Williams), flashes of
greatness, some nudity and sheet rumpling to lure the folks who
will tune in just for that, and several buckets of
diversity-seminar jawing about tolerance and acceptance. This is
not a debate, but a celebration.
</P>
<P>
   The first ``If These Walls Could Talk,'' in 1996, was about
abortion, and remains HBO's highest-ever rated ``movie.'' Both
``Walls'' are not really movies, though, but trilogies of stories,
each about a half-hour long. Both were produced, written and
directed entirely by women, and gay and straight women collaborated
on Sunday's offering. (``The Sopranos,'' incidentally, moves back
to 8 p.m. just for Sunday.)
</P>
<P>
   Like its predecessor, ``Walls'' links its stories closely, with
a single house in which the three stories take place. First it's
1961, with an elderly lesbian couple; then 1972, with a group of
college feminists; then 2000, with a thoroughly modern couple of
gals trying to have a baby.
</P>
<P>
   In 1961, as Doris Day's ``Que Sera, Sera'' plays in the
background, Redgrave stars as elderly Edith, whose lifetime
companion Abby is dying. Edith is denied visiting privileges at the
hospital because she isn't ``family'' and then must deal with
Abby's condescending relatives, who think they were just two old
spinsters sharing a house.
</P>
<P>
   There are scenes of unbearable sadness here, such as Redgrave
taking old framed photos off the walls that leave a brighter
wallpaper behind them. And Redgrave is beyond awesome in bringing
Edith to life. The story itself is really just a pro-tolerance
public service announcement, but Redgrave is so perfect she not
only transcends it, she makes the segment transcend its own
shortcomings.
</P>
<P>
   Cut to 1972 (``Share the Land'' by the Guess Who is playing),
and Williams (``Dawson's Creek'') is Linda, living with a group of
radical lesbian college students. One night they go to a ``dyke
bar'' (their words), and Linda is picked up by Amy (Sevigny, a best
supporting actress Oscar nominee for ``Boys Don't Cry''). Problem:
Amy is ultra-butch (short hair, necktie, motorcycle) and the other
lesbians are threatened by her persona, for reasons that are never
clear.
</P>
<P>
   But the chemistry between Williams and Sevigny is as potent as
can be (their long, wordless lovemaking scene will be what everyone
will be talking about Monday morning), and Sevigny's Amy is a
swaggering presence with a sweet core; along with Redgrave's Edith,
she's the only character who lingers after ``Walls'' is over.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, DeGeneres and Stone star in the contemporary episode as
a couple trying to get Stone pregnant through artificial
insemination. Unlike the first two, the tone here is goofy and
farcical (``Sisters Are Doin' It for Themselves'' in the background
couldn't be more tongue in cheek), with an undercurrent of
wistfulness.
</P>
<P>
   Stone is as loose as can be, but DeGeneres is mainly playing a
version of herself, and the fact that her companion, Anne Heche,
wrote and directed the segment, and the couple has talked publicly
about possibly having a child, make ``2000'' squirmy rather than
uplifting. And while the 1972 segment's love scene is the pivotal
plot point, the Stone-DeGeneres coupling is gratuitous even by HBO
standards.
</P>
<P>
   ``Walls'' ends up being too diffuse to sum up easily. There's
sex, sermonizing, a tone of political correctness that weighs
heavily, and Stone dancing giddily with a turkey baster. To crib
from the Indigo Girls, it's close, but could be even closer to
fine.
</P>
<P>
   ``If These Walls Could Talk 2''
</P>
<P>
   9 p.m. Sunday on HBO .
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: A mixed bag of strange bedfellows (and that's meant
figuratively, not literally).
</P>
<P>
   Phil Kloer writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
