<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WCW-UPDATE03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Ratings, talent roster among WCW's woes
 &HT;    By Lyle V. Harris
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Pro wrestling continues to ride a wave of popular interest on
TV, in toy stores, on T-shirts and in ticket sales.
</P>
<P>
   But in this time of plenty, the Atlanta-based WCW franchise has
run into its share of troubles, too.
</P>
<P>
   Lately, the WCW has become a popular target for lawsuits: Three
of its wrestlers are suing over alleged racial discrimination (see
article above), and last month Shane ``the Franchise'' Douglas sued
the WCW for firing him after he suffered a wrestling-related
injury. Last year, the legendary Ric ``Nature Boy'' Flair sued the
WCW over a contract dispute, then settled.
</P>
<P>
   Even more important to the WCW's bottom line is faltering TV
ratings. Although WCW shows such as ``Monday Nitro'' and
``Thunder'' consistently show up among the nation's top cable
programs, they have fallen to a distant second behind edgier fare
offered by the rival World Wrestling Federation. The ratings and a
roster of aging wrestlers earning six- and seven-figure salaries
probably led to the corporate decision to remove WCW President Eric
Bischoff last year.
</P>
<P>
   The WCW seemed to improve its fortunes recently by hiring Vince
Russo, a popular wrestling scriptwriter lured from the WWF. But the
coup was short-lived. Russo has been feuding lately with WCW
executives over creative differences, and four popular WCW
wrestlers have since defected to the WWF.
</P>
<P>
   With the talent exodus and the sense among fans that the WCW is
saddled with Golden Age stars like Flair and Hollywood Hogan, the
league is showing no signs of overtaking the WWF.
</P>
<P>
   Both leagues telecast their two-hour, marquee cable events on
Mondays: WCW's ``Nitro'' on TNT and WWF's ``Raw'' on USA. A year
ago the shows were a virtual dead heat. ``Raw'' now more than
doubles ``Nitro's'' ratings.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nitro'' had a chance to rebound Feb. 14 when ``Raw'' was
pre-empted to make room for USA's presentation of the Westminster
Kennel Club Dog Show. But the pooches narrowly beat the WCW
performers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now WCW is the underdog. We're David fighting Goliath,''
admits WCW spokesman Alan Sharp. But he says the troubles haven't
put the WCW on the ropes.
</P>
<P>
   ``WCW is focused on strengthening entertainment appeal of our
shows with compelling programs, larger-than-life personalities and
strong production. We will win the fan support one week at a
time.''
</P>
<P>
   Lyle V. Harris writes for the Atlanta Journal- Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
