<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-02 19:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4971 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-FASHION-PARIS03-COX     03-02 0624
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FASHION-PARIS03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Under Galliano, the D in Dior stands for daring
 &HT;    By A. Scott Walton
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ What a gal wants, and what a gal needs, aren't always
mutually inclusive of each other.
</P>
<P>
   Three of the best fall/winter collections presented this week
came from designers skilled enough to tread that fine line between
wardrobing necessities and desires while keeping firm toeholds on
their individual styles.
</P>
<P>
   Christian Dior
</P>
<P>
   Dior's iconoclastic new design chief, John Galliano, had the
gall to exorcise some demons publicly, instead of privately. He
showed clothes too racy not to make the label's old guard clients'
heads spin. But the devilishly clever collection also should fuel
new interest in the brand among younger women. His theme song _
whose refrain was ``I hate you so much right now!'' _ spoke
volumes. For his critics in the press, he produced coats, boots,
ultrasheer dresses and panties in a mocked-up ``Christian Dior
Daily'' newspaper print, with his own black-hatted photo placed
prominently amid tabloid headlines. For his employers pressuring
him to increase brand recognition, he augmented coats and pants
with belts that had clunky gold ``C'' and ``D'' buckles, and
splashed jeans and other separates with sequined Dior logos. To
show animal rights activists that they could not deter him, he
offered floor-length shearling coats in turquoise and purple. The
models' sassy strutting indicated how much they enjoyed wearing the
tie-dyed snakeskins, animal-print skirts with ragged and slinky
gowns that looked like they were made from strips of tissue.
Galliano emerged from backstage afterward wearing a tank top and
gold lame stretch jeans; confident that he'd flexed his creative
muscle to its fullest.
</P>
<P>
   Celine
</P>
<P>
   With the fanfare of the '80s nighttime soap ``Dynasty'' blaring
as his theme song, Celine design chief Michael Kors showed clothes
that juxtaposed the overindulged boarding schooler's style against
that of her manor-born mother. The looks were elitist, yet
electric: the suits _ in tweed or brown, blue and burgundy cashmere
and camel hair _ had a snug, sexy fit to them; skirts stopped at
the knee, but had a sultry swing to them; blazers were monogrammed
regally with Celine's logo; and jeans were trimmed extravagantly
with fur. As testament to Kors' mastery of textiles, even the
corduroy and paisley-print silk pieces seduced the eyes.
Eveningwear looks varied between crystal-encrusted, ruffle-skirted
gowns and ensembles composed of brilliant black-and-white pants
with shimmering blouses.
</P>
<P>
   Emanuel Ungaro
</P>
<P>
   Anyone who thinks a collection laden with pinstriped suits can't
be captivating hasn't seen the fall looks from Ungaro yet. The use
of color in this collection ranks among the season's most creative,
if only because Ungaro made divergent shades of blue, pink, green
and purple flow together flawlessly. He also offered innovative
twists on treadworn military styling: His broad-shouldered coats
and jackets had not only epaulets, but gold chains dangling
evocatively from them as well. His camouflage print separates came
in emboldened shades of turquoise, fuchsia, copper and cream.
Ungaro found endless ways to embellish garments with beads,
feathers, floral-appliques and sequins and tie-dying, and
patchworking gave his jeans and leathers added playfulness. His
vibrant chenille sweaters had a carefree quality. His coats swept
the floor. And his eveningwear consisted mainly of sassily short
dresses with asymmetrical hemlines and ruffles that danced in the
breeze.
</P>
<P>
   A. Scott Walton writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
