<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-02 19:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4972 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-PAULA-COLE03-COX     03-02 0641
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PAULA-COLE03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Don't be cross, Paula, but an award does not a career make
 &HT;    By Shane Harrison
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Grammys as arbiters of musical greatness are rather suspect.
Remember Milli Vanilli? Even artists whose contribution to their
own recordings is not in doubt aren't immune to a precipitous
decline in fortunes following a Grammy win.
</P>
<P>
   One artist who didn't receive quite the glowing response for the
follow-up to her heavily nominated album is in Atlanta this
weekend. (9 p.m. Saturday. $19 at Ticketmaster. The Roxy, 3110
Roswell Road N.E. 404-249-6400 or 404-233-7699). Like Christopher
Cross in 1980, Paula Cole's 1997 Grammy win didn't guarantee that
anyone would stick around for the sequel. Of course, everyone loves
a comeback (just ask Carlos Santana), so you can't count Cole out
yet.
</P>
<P>
   Herewith, a comparison of these two former darlings of the
National Academy of Recording Arts and Sciences.
</P>
<P>
   LINK COLE/CROSS
</P>
<P>
   Grammy
</P>
<P>
   nominations
</P>
<P>
   Seven
</P>
<P>
   7 in 1997
</P>
<P>
   CROSS
</P>
<P>
   5 in 1980; 1 in 1981
</P>
<P>
   Grammy
</P>
<P>
   wins
</P>
<P>
   Cole:
</P>
<P>
   1 (best new artist)
</P>
<P>
   Cross:
</P>
<P>
   4 (including album, record and song of the year)
</P>
<P>
   Album that
</P>
<P>
   made them
</P>
<P>
   Cole:
</P>
<P>
   The slickly produced Warner Bros. release ``This Fire''
</P>
<P>
   Cross:
</P>
<P>
   The slickly produced Warner Bros. release ``Christopher Cross''
</P>
<P>
   Song that made them
</P>
<P>
   Cole:
</P>
<P>
   ``Where Have All the Cowboys Gone''
</P>
<P>
   Cross:
</P>
<P>
   ``Sailing''
</P>
<P>
   Follow-up album that couldn't
</P>
<P>
   Cole:
</P>
<P>
   ``Amen,'' which received mixed reviews and peaked at No. 97 on
the Billboard 200. In an online review of the album at US Music
Vault Online (www.usmusicvault.com), critic Matt Portenoy writes,
``I can always accept the fact that a record is bad, but what I
cannot comprehend is how any one person can be as pretentious, as
utterly self-righteous as Paula Cole.''
</P>
<P>
   Cross:
</P>
<P>
   1983's ``Another Page,'' which shipped in huge quantities, but
clogged cutout bins for years afterward. Nearly a year after the
album's release, the track ``Think of Laura'' was used on the soap
opera ``General Hospital,'' helping propel the syrupy ballad into
the Top 10 in December 1983. It would be Cross' last Top 40 hit to
date.
</P>
<P>
   Teen tie-in
</P>
<P>
   Cole:
</P>
<P>
   A weekly presence in teen land with ``I Don't Want to Wait,''
the theme song of the WB's teen drama ``Dawson's Creek,'' starring
James Van Der Beek (right).
</P>
<P>
   Cross:
</P>
<P>
   Performed his biggest hit, ``Sailing,'' with teen pop phenoms 'N
Sync at last summer's Blockbuster Entertainment awards.
</P>
<P>
   Friends
</P>
<P>
   in high(ish) places
</P>
<P>
   Cole:
</P>
<P>
   Lilith Fair mastermind Sarah McLachlan (left), who included Cole
in her traveling gyno-centric music festival.
</P>
<P>
   Cross:
</P>
<P>
   Former Doobie Brother Michael McDonald, who contributed backing
vocals for Cross' first hit, ``Ride Like the Wind.''
</P>
<P>
   Where they are now
</P>
<P>
   Cole:
</P>
<P>
   Touring in support of ``Amen,'' her third album.
</P>
<P>
   Cross:
</P>
<P>
   At a tribute concert for Michael McDonald on Feb. 4 in Los
Angeles. Late in 1999, CMC International released ``Greatest Hits
Live,'' with plans for the future U.S. release of a studio album
that's already available in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Who they beat out for best new artist trophy
</P>
<P>
   Cole:
</P>
<P>
   Fiona Apple, Erykah Badu, Puff Daddy (left), Hanson
</P>
<P>
   Cross:
</P>
<P>
   Irene Cara, Robbie Dupree, Amy Holland, the Pretenders (below)
</P>
<P>
   A whiff of
</P>
<P>
   controversy
</P>
<P>
   Cole:
</P>
<P>
   Was incensed when her hirsute armpits were airbrushed out of a
photo in Entertainment Weekly in February 1998. It then obligingly
printed the unretouched image.
</P>
<P>
   Cross:
</P>
<P>
   Nothing very hairy, aside from besting such legends as Barbra
Streisand and Frank Sinatra at the 1980
</P>
<P>
   Grammys.
</P>
<P>
   Shane Harrison writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
