<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MAINE-COMPUTERS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COST FACTOR CITED IN PROPOSAL TO GIVE STUDENTS COMPUTERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID ABEL  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   If Mayor Boston Thomas M. Menino had the cash, he wouldn't
hesitate to supply every student with city-subsidized computers.
</P>
<P>
   Both Senators Edward M. Kennedy and John F. Kerry would also do
as much as possible to bridge the so-called digital divide, they
said.
</P>
<P>
   And a spokesman for Governor Paul Cellucci called furnishing
students across Massachusetts with their own computers ``a very
interesting idea.''
</P>
<P>
   Maine Governor Angus King's proposal Thursday to provide all
seventh-graders in his state with government-issued laptops has
captured the attention of politicians and educators across the
country.
</P>
<P>
   King proposed spending $50 million from a state surplus to buy
the first installment of 17,000 for every student entering the 7th
grade in 2002, and establish a $75 million income-producing private
endowment to buy computers for successive classes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're heading into an age when computer literacy is essential.
It's going to be as important as knowing how to read or write,''
King told a small audience of students and teachers at press
conference in Gardiner, Maine, Thursday. ``This isn't a frill. This
is essential ... this is where the country's going.''
</P>
<P>
   But the utopian idea scrapes against the reality of legislators
with competing views of how a state's money should be spent _ even
in an era flush with mounting surpluses.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I had the resources, I would love to give all the kids free
computers,'' Menino said from in a phone interview from San Jose,
Calif., where where he was attending a conference on how to help
lower-income families access the Internet and use computers.
President Bill Clinton is scheduled to address the conference
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Governor King's goal of providing laptop computers for all
Seventh graders demonstrates both long-term thinking and an
understanding of the paramount importance of equipping all our
students with the knowledge and skills to succeed in an information
economy,'' Kerry said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is encouraging that the digital divide is becoming such an
important policy issue at both the state and federal level,''
Kennedy said.
</P>
<P>
   And while Cellucci spokesman Jason Kauppi said the governor
supports using technology to improve education, he bridled at the
hundreds of millions of dollars it would surely cost to supply
students computers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's something that would have to be looked at for
feasibility,'' Kauppi said. ``It's interesting; but the hurdle is
the cost.''
</P>
<P>
   That's a similar reaction to King's proposal among many Maine
legislators.
</P>
<P>
   While many state lawmakers initially expressed interest in the
proposal, they quickly raised the issue of whether the state could
afford such a program before paying for needy school repairs and
other pressing obligations.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be a tough sell,'' said Dennis Bailey, King's
press secretary. ``We have a lot of work to do. There are always a
1,000 ways to spend money.''
</P>
<P>
   Educators, however, have lauded King's proposal as a bold and
novel approach to reducing the digital divide, the growing gap in
access to computers and the Internet along racial and economic
lines. According to a US Commerce Department study in July,
households with incomes greater than $75,000 are 20 times as likely
to have computers as those with lower incomes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a very exciting idea, and it makes sense in today's
technological world,'' said Linda Roberts, director of the US
Department of Education's Office of Educational Technology. ``But
this is a major investment. The goals have to be tied to the way
students use the technology.''
</P>
<P>
   In similar experiments around the country, where students have
been provided with free computers, researchers found the gifts also
must accompany close supervision and training, Roberts said.
``Where there has been no clear focus, and lack of teacher
training, the kids are just playing games,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Even if teachers and students are trained to use the computers,
some educators argue it's better for students to focus on the
basics of such elemental skills as reading and writing before
spending too much time on things such as surfing the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Boston University Chancellor John Silber said school districts
across Massachusetts have already wasted lots of money on ensuring
kindergarteners and first graders had access to computers. ``There
hands weren't even large enough to fit the keyboard,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Silber argued against further state investments in computers,
saying many students already have their own computers and the prime
beneficiaries would be the computer industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a great school system in Massachusetts before computers
were invented,'' he said. ``Three to four years of high school is
plenty of time to become expert on computers.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet those school districts that have actually issued students
computers say the positives far outweigh the negatives. At
Milwaukee Public School District, about 250 summer school students
have been given their own computers. And according to
administrators, attendance and class participation dramatically
increased.
</P>
<P>
   ``There really weren't any negatives,'' said Robert Shleck,
assistant director of technology for Milwaukee Public School,
adding only one computer had been lost and one damaged. ``And in
the end, the kids didn't want to return the computers.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
