<HEADER>
A4977 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-HOLYFIELD-PREACHER03-     03-02 0232
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOLYFIELD-PREACHER03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Appeals keep Atlanta reverend out of jail
 &HT;    By Ralph Ellis
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The Fayette County Sheriff's Department has stopped
looking for the Rev. Creflo Dollar.
</P>
<P>
   Dollar's attorney has filed new appeals with the Georgia Supreme
Court. That means the leader of World Changers Ministries won't be
arrested for contempt of court until the appeals are heard, said
his attorney, Lecora Bowen.
</P>
<P>
   Fayette County Judge Ben Miller found the leader of the
20,000-member church in contempt last December because Dollar
refuses to give a deposition in boxer Evander Holyfield's divorce
case.
</P>
<P>
   Dollar appealed the contempt citation, but the Georgia Supreme
Court dismissed it Feb. 25, saying the proper appeals procedures
were not followed.
</P>
<P>
   In domestic cases, lawyers seek permission to file an appeal
before the actual appeal is filed, according to the Georgia
attorney general's office. Bowen had appealed directly to the high
court.
</P>
<P>
   After the Supreme Court dismissal, Fayette deputies went to the
World Changers church in College Park looking for Dollar, but did
not take him into custody.
</P>
<P>
   Bowen then filed a motion asking the Supreme Court to reconsider
his appeal. Bowen argues the contempt citation was not a domestic
issue.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
