<P>
   HSIA-TRIAL (Washington) _ Maria Hsia, a longtime political
fund-raiser for Vice President Al Gore, is convicted of all five
felony counts against her for her role in arranging more than
$100,000 in illegal donations to the Democratic Party and its
candidates in 1996. By Neil A. Lewis. (Scheduled to move by 9 p.m.
ET in ``w'' news file.) 1,200 words.
</P>
<P>
   Off-lead story:
</P>
<P>
   CINDY-MCCAIN (Cincinnati) _ For months now, more than any other
presidential candidate's wife, Cindy McCain has been a regular on
the campaign trail. Through 14-hour work days, she is almost
constantly at her husband's elbow, smiling as she double-steps to
keep up with him in crowds and nodding at just the right moments
during the speech she has heard hundreds of times. A profile by
Melinda Henneberger. (Scheduled to move by 8:30 p.m. ET in ``p''
news file.) 2,000 words.
</P>
<P>
   Story runs under a 3-column photo; photos NYT2, 5.
</P>
<P>
   FOLD
</P>
<P>
   CHRISTIAN-RIGHT (Atlanta) _ It is hard to know how many Bob
Harrisons are out there. But each one is a nightmare for Sen. John
McCain. Harrison, a 60-year-old electrical engineer and a leader of
the choir at Atlanta's Mt. Paran Church of God, was once an
enthusiastic McCain supporter, but that all changed this week.
Harrison, who considers himself a Christian conservative voter, was
deeply offended by McCain's attacks on Pat Robertson and Jerry
Falwell, ``I think he was out of line,'' Harrison said, and now he
is leaning toward voting for Gov. George W. Bush in Tuesday's
Republican primary. By Kevin Sack. (Scheduled to move by 8:15 p.m.
ET in ``p'' news file.) 1,500 words.
</P>
<P>
   PALM-IPO (San Francisco) _ Continuing a wave of enthusiasm for
companies involved in the Internet and wireless communications,
investors snap up shares of Palm Inc., the maker of the popular
Palm Pilot handheld devices. Shares in Palm's parent, 3Com Corp.,
declined, although 3Com still holds 94 percent of Palm after the
offering. By Lawrence M. Fisher. (Scheduled to move by 8:30 p.m. ET
in ``f'' news file.) 1,200 words.
</P>
<P>
   BOTTOM
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-LEBANON (Dlaat Outpost, Lebanon) _ A debate has been
raging in Israel about what many have termed the senselessness of
the chronic fighting in southern Lebanon. But in the nine-mile-deep
``security zone'' that Israel occupies here, the war is still on
against the Hezbollah, or Party of God, guerrillas, who see
themselves as trying to liberate a swath of Lebanon from Israeli
control. And the political conversation has to be tuned out for
survival's sake. By Deborah Sontag. (The story has moved in ``i''
news file.) 1,800 words.
</P>
<P>
   With photo, map.
</P>
<P>
   AUSTRIA-HAIDER (Bad Kleinkircheim, Austria) _ To his supporters,
Joerg Haider's message has less to do with Nazi revisionism or
anti-immigrant vitriol than with market reform. It is about
deregulation. Sweeping privatizations. Reduced bureaucracy. An end
to the division of the spoils in Austria among members of the
long-dominant Social Democratic and conservative People's parties.
This is a popular view in Austria. About one-third of the support
that took Haider's Freedom Party into national government in
February for the first time comes from entrepreneurs, particularly
in the small companies that dominate the Austrian economy. By Roger
Cohen. (The story has moved in ``i'' news file.) 1,500 words.
</P>
