 LEG INJURIES SLOW WETTELAND, GREER (For
use by NYTimes News Service clients) By T.R. SULLIVAN c.2000 Fort
Worth Star-Telegram
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORT CHARLOTTE, Fla. _ Rangers pitcher John Wetteland and
outfielder Rusty Greer spent part of last night undergoing
magnetic-resonance-imaging exams on their lower right legs.
</P>
<P>
   Wetteland has a slight strain of his calf muscle, and Greer has
inflammation in his ankle. The results are expected today, but
neither injury is expected to be serious.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been told not to be too concerned,'' Rangers manager
Johnny Oates said. ``Until I'm told differently ... march on.''
</P>
<P>
   Wetteland said he experienced a ``twinge'' in the calf area in
the first inning of yesterday's scrimmage and decided it was too
early in spring training to push it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can deal with not throwing for a few days,'' Wetteland said.
``Not being able to work out like I'm used to is disappointing. I
don't want to spend all my time in the training room.''
</P>
<P>
   Greer did not play in yesterday's scrimmage and has been
scratched from today's exhibition opener against the Minnesota
Twins. But the Rangers expect him back early next week.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we skip John two days, it's no big deal,'' Oates said. ``If
Rusty misses three or four days, he won't miss a beat.''
\Nsubheds:Mateo's outlook Ruben Mateo's teammates suggest he is
cocky, but the Rangers' rookie center fielder insisted yesterday
he's a little uncomfortable with the high expectations being placed
on him.
</P>
<P>
   Rangers manager Johnny Oates, after meeting with Mateo on
Wednesday, said it's up to Mateo whether he wants to be an average
$3 million player or a $10 million star putting up big numbers.
</P>
<P>
   But Mateo said yesterday: ``I don't like hearing about those
things. My goal is to play 162 games. After that, I want to help my
team make the playoffs and the World Series.''
</P>
<P>
   Oates said Mateo needs to be pushed a little more this year. But
Mateo said he understands the manager's point about staying
focused.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel different than last year,'' Mateo said. ``Last year,
somebody else was playing center field. This year I'm the center
fielder. It's a good feeling. But the one thing I need to do is
play hard every day.'' \Nsubheds:Thompson throws Pitcher Justin
Thompson took another step toward coming back from last year's
surgery on his left shoulder by throwing 25 pitches off the mound
at a distance of 50 feet yesterday. Thompson said he experienced no
problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll do this a couple, three times more, raising the effort
and frequency slowly,'' pitching coach Dick Bosman said.
</P>
<P>
   Bosman was impressed that Thompson has corrected some of the
mechanical problems that caused the torn labrum in his shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   ``His mechanics look good,'' Bosman said. ``There is nothing
wrong with his mechanics.'' \Nsubheds:No Griffey, Sanders The
Cincinnati Reds won't be bringing their two most-glamorous players
to Port Charlotte tomorrow for their exhibition game against the
Rangers. The Reds informed the Rangers yesterday that Ken Griffey
Jr. and Deion Sanders won't be making the 45-minute trip from
Sarasota.
</P>
</TEXT>
