<HEADER>
A4986 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-BKC-JONES-REPORT-TEXM     03-02 1679
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-JONES-REPORT-TEX </SLUG>
 MIHM NEEDS ANOTHER SEASON AT TEXAS (For use
by NYTimes News Service clients) By MIKE JONES c.2000 Fort Worth
Star-Telegram
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Will they or won't they?
</P>
<P>
   The subplot to March madness may continue on into April and May
for hoops fans at Texas and Iowa State as they anxiously await the
decisions of Chris Mihm and Marcus Fizer regarding their respective
future mailing addresses.
</P>
<P>
   Will they return for a senior season? If the answer is yes, both
teams will catapult into serious consideration for 2000-2001
preseason Top 10 lists and the Big 12 will receive an attendant
boost in national prestige. If both opt for the riches of the NBA,
then the league will take a hit when their defections are coupled
with the loss of seniors Desmond Mason of Oklahoma State and
Eduardo Najera of Oklahoma.
</P>
<P>
   My semi-educated guess? Fizer is more likely to go, Mihm more
likely to stay.
</P>
<P>
   Both say they've yet to make a decision and how they say it
rings true. I hope both stay for the simple reason that a
conference that boasts national player-of-the-year candidates is a
more attractive beat. On an even more personal note, I like Mihm
and don't believe that he is ready for the rigors of the NBA,
either physically or mentally. Though he hedges on the question, I
sense Longhorns coach Rick Barnes feels the same way.
</P>
<P>
   As much progress as Mihm has made in the past calendar year, his
game is not at the level I suspect he would like it to be for entry
into the play-for-pay arena. I just can't imagine him going
one-on-one with Shaquille O'Neal and surviving without injury to
his psyche. And Mihm doesn't want to be a journeyman player. He
wants to be one of the best and I think that factor will weigh
heavily when he determines his immediate future.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's crazy,'' Mihm said in a recent conversation. ``Even my
friends are asking me about it. And it's only a month away until
the Big Dance is over with. I have so many things to look at and
it's going to take time. Right now, I have so many things on my
plate that I don't have time to think about it. When the time
comes, I'll sit down with my family and loved ones and coach Barnes
and discuss it. But ultimately, I'll make the decision.''
</P>
<P>
   If Mihm makes the decision based strictly on what he feels in
his gut, I believe we'll see him in a Texas uniform next season _
no matter what happens on the court during March.
</P>
<P>
   Chris has told me time and time again over the last year that he
really enjoys going to college, and why shouldn't he? I just can't
imagine that he would give that up for the bottom-line life in the
NBA. That's one good reason why he should stay. Another reason has
been sitting on Texas' bench this season _ transfer Maurice Evans,
a 6-foot-5 forward who ranked ninth nationally last year with a
22-point scoring average at Wichita State. Despite the loss of
seniors Gabe Muoneke, Ivan Wagner and Will Clay, Evans could be the
missing link in Barnes' stated goal of making a run at the national
championship. Evans alone could dampen other teams' desires to
double- and triple-team the Longhorns' 7-foot center.
</P>
<P>
   The prospect of Mihm suffering a career-ending injury next
season? Possible, but unlikely. His family doesn't need the money.
Both Texas and the Big 12 need him. But he needs to do what he
thinks is best for him and him alone. Ultimately, I think he'll
decide what is best is another year in Austin. Could that be so
bad?
Spotlight on ...
Player that few wanted proves a steal for Tech Rayford Young will
finish his career as one of only three players in Texas Tech
history to score more than 1,000 points (currently 1,470) and pass
out more than 400 assists (404). With 36 points and seven assists,
he almost single-handedly led the Red Raiders to the brink of an
upset against Iowa State in the final home game of his career.
</P>
<P>
   Not bad for a kid that few wanted, even though he led Pampa to a
state championship his senior year in high school. He wanted to go
to Texas. Former coach Tom Penders took Anthony Goode instead. But
a lot of other coaches passed, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's why I can't begin to tell you how much I appreciate
playing for coach \RJames\S Dickey,'' Young said. ``He was one of
the few coaches who was willing to give me a chance even though I
was on a team that went 33-3 and won state.''
</P>
<P>
   A class act on and off the court, Young will be remembered as
one of Tech's best ever, though he played during one of the most
difficult times in Raiders history. Recall that at the end of
Young's freshman season, academic certification problems surfaced
that led to NCAA penalties. Tech (19-8) pulled itself from NCAA
Tournament consideration and shortly thereafter, center Tony Battie
opted for the NBA rather than come back for a senior season when
Tech would have been one of the Big 12's top teams.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think about that all the time,'' Young said. ``All that
changed the whole profile of the program. It's still hard to
swallow. I thought a lot about transferring, but I think I still
made the right decision to stay.''
</P>
<P>
   The 5-footl-11 (on tiptoes) point guard still dreams of the NBA.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know I'm going to have to prove I can play with the big guys
in one of the \RNBA\S camps,'' Young said. ``But that's nothing
new. Everything in my life has come hard.''
</P>
<P>
   In the lane \Nsubhed:We remember From the October memory bank.
Nebraska coach Paul Sanderford questioning the Big 12 women's
coaches' poll.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't bet,'' Sanderford qualified. ``But Texas Tech fifth?
Just remember what I said at the end of the year.''
</P>
<P>
   Yep, he told us so. And so the No. 7 Lady Raiders (24-3, 13-3)
stand once again in the nation's Top 10, sharing a third
consecutive conference championship after starting league play 0-2.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it always feels better the third time around,'' Tech
senior forward Keitha Dickerson said. ``This is special. No one
expected us to win and we did. It's the greatest feeling.''
</P>
<P>
   Coach Marsha Sharp admitted, ``After we started 0-2, we thought
we were dead in the water, that we just had to go play hard and
hope to get one of the top four \RBig 12\S seeds and get a decent
seed in the NCAA Tournament.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe that was good, because it took some pressure off. The
last couple of years there has been a bull's-eye on our backs and
we operated under a lot of self-imposed pressure to live up to
expectations. So \R(winning this share\S has been fun. And the
thing that has made this so rewarding is that this is the best
conference race we've ever been involved in.'' \NSubhed:You foul,
you run It's no accident that Iowa State has made more free throws
(502 of 724) than its opponents have shot (258 of 354). Not
coincidentally, 1999 regular-season champion Texas did the same
thing in conference games (287 made to 286 for opponents' shots),
but nowhere near what the Cyclones have accomplished this season.
</P>
<P>
   The motivation? Fear and loathing of the dreaded wind-sprint.
</P>
<P>
   ``We spend a lot of time in practice paying penalties for
fouling in practice,'' coach Larry Eustachy said. ``We sometimes
play a two-basket game and if a coach thinks a player has fouled an
opponent, it's an automatic basket and the losers run.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we play five-on-five, if we see a foul we call it. Then,
we stop and run as a group, the whole team. We put a lot of time
and emphasis into it.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cyclones, who have clinched the No. 1 seed, attempt to win
it all tomorrow at Baylor. ISU fans have chartered a plane for the
game.
\Nsubhed:Nobody told me Missouri rookie coach Quin Snyder admits he
has been through the wringer this season and is looking forward to
a long nap.
</P>
<P>
   ``The physical toll of the season is something I had not
anticipated,'' he said. ``The psychological and emotional grind of
the season is very different from being an assistant. As an
assistant, there are times and places you can slide away for a
respite every now and then. But every minute of every day is on the
line as a head coach.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's something I was aware of, but until you feel the weight
of the responsibility you're not aware how fatiguing that can be.
You need to be so regimented in your daily routine. I forget to
eat. I don't sleep. The result is that if you're not careful, it
can make you less effective in the short run. It's something I
clearly need to modify.''
Free Throws
</P>
<P>
   If winning a share of the women's championship isn't evidence
enough, Oklahoma coach Sherri Coale clearly demonstrated she has
learned a thing or two after Wednesday's clinching 77-68 victory
over Oklahoma State when asked if she had a retort for fellow
coaches who picked the Sooners sixth in preseason.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have words for \Rthe title tie\S even though I planned
for it,'' she said. ``I didn't know at the time we would tie for
first, but I thought we could be in the top three. But no, I don't
have any bulletin-board material for them.''
</P>
<P>
   Texas women's coach Jody Conradt paid senior Edwina Brown the
ultimate compliment this week.
</P>
<P>
   ``The best thing I can say about her is she would be on our
all-Texas team, which puts her in some pretty elite company. I
don't think our fans will see a more versatile player in a Texas
uniform for a long time.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Women's Basketball News'' named Edwina Brown and OU's
Phyleshia Whaley to their 10-player All-America team, Iowa State's
Stacy Frese and Kansas' Lynn Pride to the second group. ESPN.com
picks Sherri Coale as national coach of the year.
</P>
<P>
   Quin Snyder's Tigers (17-10, 10-5) may need another `W' next
week in Kansas City to cement an NCAA invitation, but he appears to
feel good about Missouri's chances after a must-win over Nebraska
on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this team has made a pretty strong statement this year
about being in the Tournament,'' he said. ``And that's the first
time I've said that.''
</P>
<P>
   Put Columbia, Mo., on the top of my list for favorite old Big
Eight towns, Booche's pool hall hamburgers (order two) as a
favorite local delicacy and the Katy Trail as the best place to
walk 'em off.
nn
</P>
