<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHRISTIAN-RIGHT-1,070(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
 
(ATTN: Ga., Va., N.C., Miss., Ohio, Fla.)  
 REMARKS UNITE CHRISTIAN RIGHT AGAINST McCAIN 
 (rk) 
 By KEVIN SACK   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ It is hard to know how many Bob Harrisons are out
there. But each one is a nightmare for Sen. John McCain.
</P>
<P>
   Harrison, a 60-year-old electrical engineer and a leader of the
choir at Atlanta's Mount Paran Church of God, was once an
enthusiastic McCain supporter. He liked the Arizona senator's
heroic military background. He liked his positions on education and
health care. And he liked his penchant for straight talk. ``I was
really pulling for him,'' Harrison said. ``He was the guy.''
</P>
<P>
   That all changed this week. Harrison, who considers himself a
Christian conservative voter, was deeply offended by McCain's
attacks on Pat Robertson and Jerry Falwell, whom he described in a
speech on Monday as ``agents of intolerance'' comparable to Louis
Farrakhan and Al Sharpton.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he was out of line,'' Harrison said, pausing on
Wednesday night between dinner in the church fellowship hall and
choir practice. ``It's almost like a John Rocker episode. I don't
agree with everything Robertson and Falwell say, but McCain was
attacking the faithful.''
</P>
<P>
   Now Harrison is leaning toward voting for Gov. George W. Bush of
Texas in Tuesday's Republican primary in Georgia. And if McCain
happens to win the party's nomination, Harrison may stay home in
November rather than casting his traditional Republican vote. ``I
just haven't gotten over this,'' he said, ``and I probably won't.''
</P>
<P>
   In dozens of interviews this week, both the leaders and the rank
and file of the religious conservative movement said that McCain
may succeed in accomplishing what Robertson and Falwell could not.
By unleashing an offensive against the movement's two most visible
spokesmen, in a strategic appeal to moderate Republicans and
independents, McCain seems to have energized Christian conservative
support for Bush.
</P>
<P>
   In the Virginia primary on Tuesday, held the day after McCain
made his widely publicized remarks, Bush won the votes of nearly 80
percent of those who considered themselves part of the religious
right, a significantly higher percentage than in previous
primaries.
</P>
<P>
   Not only may McCain have miscalculated by alienating voters like
Harrison and by rousing those who leaned ambivalently toward Bush,
he also may have created for himself a formidable repair job should
he win his party's nomination. Seventeen percent of voters in the
presidential elections of 1992 and 1996 were white Christians who
identified with the religious right, and nearly two-thirds of them
voted for the Republican nominee, according to exit polls.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mr. McCain's remarks are irresponsible,'' said Dr. Paige
Patterson, the president of the Southern Baptist Convention, the
country's largest Protestant denomination, with 14 million members.
``And I would say if he wins the primary, they are the remarks of a
man who apparently doesn't want to be president of the United
States, because it's difficult for me to believe that a Republican
can win the election while deliberately abusing a considerable
segment of the Republican Party.''
</P>
<P>
   Can McCain win back Christian conservative voters? ``I'd say
it'd be pretty difficult,'' said Patterson, a North Carolinian who
supports Bush. ``I hope evangelical Christians are always willing
to forgive. But I've certainly not seen any disposition on the part
of Mr. McCain to do anything other than critique people of
evangelical faith.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain only deepened his problems with evangelicals by telling
reporters on Tuesday that Robertson and Falwell exerted an ``evil
influence'' on the Republican Party. Those comments followed nearly
two weeks of heavy criticism by McCain of Bush's decision to speak
at Bob Jones University on Feb. 2 without renouncing the
fundamentalist school's ban on interracial dating and the
anti-Catholic views of its leaders. While many Christian
conservatives, including many of the movement's leaders, also
object to the university's practices, they were made uncomfortable
by McCain's intense focus on a Christian college.
</P>
<P>
   McCain apologized on Wednesday, but only for the ``evil
influence'' comment, which he characterized as a ``flip remark.''
Gary Bauer, a Christian conservative leader who endorsed McCain
after withdrawing from the Republican race, issued a statement on
Wednesday repudiating McCain's ``unwarranted, ill-advised and
divisive attacks on certain religious leaders.''
</P>
<P>
   Until McCain's speech, the Christian conservative movement had
been riven this year by a debate over its place in American
politics.
</P>
<P>
   Some religious conservatives, disillusioned by President
Clinton's political survival and the failure of the
Republican-controlled Congress to change national policy on
abortion, school prayer and gay rights, have advocated a retreat
into the life of the church and the family. That, they say, is the
most effective way to bolster the country's moral standing. Others
insist that Christians must continue to fight for political
influence, while developing the sophistication to understand that
politics is a game of compromise and endurance.
</P>
<P>
   Among those who encourage continued political activism, Bush has
been a clear preference over McCain. But the level of fervor for
Bush, a United Methodist, has not approached that enjoyed by Ronald
Reagan or Robertson in their presidential campaigns, according to
movement leaders and academic authorities.
</P>
<P>
   Despite Bush's occasional references to his own conversion
experience and to his admiration for Jesus Christ, some religious
leaders question his level of commitment to their causes. For
instance, Bush favors a constitutional amendment to ban abortion
but supports exceptions in the case of rape, incest and danger to
the life of the mother.
</P>
<P>
   But McCain's comments, which were incited by Robertson's
campaigning against him in South Carolina and Michigan, may at
least temporarily unify the movement.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think in the short run it could be counterproductive and
mobilize the faithful to rally against McCain as much as rally for
Bush,'' said Charles Reagan Wilson, the director of the Center for
the Study of Southern Culture at the University of Mississippi and
the author of a book on religion in the South.
</P>
<P>
   John C. Green, a professor at the University of Akron who
studies religion and politics, speculated that McCain's attacks
might even prolong the life of Robertson's Christian Coalition.
``They really thrive on adversity,'' he said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   In his speech on Monday, delivered in Robertson's home town of
Virginia Beach, Va., McCain strove to draw distinctions between
Robertson and Falwell on one hand and other evangelical leaders who
he said were ``changing America for the better.'' By contrast, he
said that Robertson and Falwell ``have turned good causes into
businesses.''
</P>
<P>
   But that nuance seems to have been lost on many Christian
conservatives. While many do not agree with either the political
views or tactics embraced by Robertson and Falwell, they often
admire their record in winning converts to Christ. And already
sensitive to what they see as a media caricature of them as
zealots, they clearly view McCain's attack on Robertson and Falwell
as a broad assault on all evangelicals.
</P>
<P>
   ``I rather liked McCain for a while,'' said Marion J. Fisher, a
70-year-old retired secretary who was interviewed during the
Wednesday night fellowship at Southside Baptist Church in Lakeland,
Fla. ``But lately, talk about hate-mongering. I mean, the religious
right, quote unquote, gets a lot of flak about promoting hate. To
me, that's what he's doing now, throwing mud and bad-mouthing
people who have faith and beliefs.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps most grating to many Christian conservatives is their
feeling that McCain pandered to their detractors by playing on the
stereotype that they are a homogeneous collection of intolerant
extremists.
</P>
<P>
   ``That stuff plays well with people whose conception of a
fundamentalist Christian is that they're not smart enough to be
enlightened,'' said Ron L. Plemmons, the 37-year-old pastor at
Southside Baptist Church in Lakeland. ``What bothers me about it is
that you paint with such a broad stroke of the brush. And what's
amazing to me is that Ronald Reagan was elected to two terms by
embracing the pro-life, pro-conservative religious movement. And
here's someone, John McCain, who claims to be a Reagan Republican
yet tries to run against the very same people.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
