<DOCNO> NYT20000302.0349 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-02 20:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4992 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-STEINBERG-NORRIS-COLU     03-02 0617
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STEINBERG-NORRIS-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAUL STEINBERG: A MODEL FOR TODAY'S INTERNET BARONS 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By FLOYD NORRIS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Hot stocks traded for hundreds of times their earnings, if they
had any. Companies with concepts that caught the eye of eager
investors could acquire companies many times their size. Public
enthusiasm for stocks was higher than at any time since the 1920s.
</P>
<P>
   The late 1960s, memorably termed the Go-Go Years by the great
financial writer John Brooks, are largely forgotten now. They
shouldn't be.
</P>
<P>
   No man better exemplified that era than Saul P. Steinberg. He
was the survivor, a man wise enough in his youth to come up with a
concept that would captivate investors and then to realize that the
riches bestowed upon him would be ephemeral if he did not use his
ridiculously overvalued stock to buy something that had real value.
</P>
<P>
   Steinberg, now just 60 years old, announced this week that he
was stepping down as chief executive of Reliance Group Holdings,
the insurance company that he took over in 1968, although he is
staying on as chairman.
</P>
<P>
   His departure is not exactly being mourned, for Reliance is in
dreadful shape, with its stock trading as if its remaining
insurance operations were worth less than nothing. He did far
better for himself, taking generous salaries and bonuses, than he
did for Reliance's public shareholders. He was much better at
identifying values than he was at running companies.
</P>
<P>
   But it is not for what he did lately that Steinberg will be best
remembered. It was in 1961, at the tender age of 22, that he
pioneered the computer leasing business. IBM, which made the
computers, was not interested in offering long-term leases, and
Steinberg saw a niche. Whether or not that business would be
profitable in the long run depended on how well old computers would
hold their value, but with the right accounting assumptions his
company, named Leasco, could and did show instant profits. It went
public in 1965 and the stock zoomed. Three years later, that hot
stock enabled Leasco to take over Reliance, a dull but prosperous
insurance company that was nearly 10 times its size.
</P>
<P>
   Leasco, it turned out, was not worth anything close to what Wall
Street thought it was. But Reliance was a real asset, and Steinberg
had an operation that would keep him in business even when that era
vanished.
</P>
<P>
   The beginning of the end of the Go-Go Years may, in fact, be
dated to Steinberg's disastrous 1969 attempt to have Leasco take
over Chemical Bank of New York, then the sixth-largest bank in the
United States. Suddenly Leasco's inflated stock came under attack,
and Steinberg had to withdraw his offer as Leasco's share price
withered. ``I always knew there was an Establishment,'' he said
later. ``I just used to think I was part of it.'' Within a few
years the country was in recession, the stock market had collapsed,
and the public had lost interest in stocks.
</P>
<P>
   In later years, Steinberg tried more raids, but the really big
targets, like Disney before Michael Eisner turned it around, eluded
him. He took his empire private in 1982, when stock prices were
very low, and then sold stock in Reliance to the public in 1986,
when the bull was roaring.
</P>
<P>
   It is not easy for a company with a sizzling stock to go against
the Wall Street grain and use those shares to buy an unloved
company. Some America Online owners are outraged that its Internet
operations will be diluted by boring assets, and AOL is down 24
percent since it agreed to buy Time Warner. But the people running
many a hot Internet company now would do well to ponder Saul
Steinberg's staying power, and to follow his example.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
