<HEADER>
A4995 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-EUROPE-RATES-NYT &LR;      03-02 0832
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EUROPE-RATES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EUROPEAN CENTRAL BANK POSTPONES INTEREST RATE RISE  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By EDMUND L. ANDREWS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   FRANKFURT, Germany _ Despite worries about inflation and the
euro's slump to a record low this week, the European Central Bank
decided Thursday not to raise interest rates, while warning that it
would probably do so soon.
</P>
<P>
   ``The risks are increasing,'' said Wim Duisenberg, the president
of the central bank, after a meeting here of the board of
governors. ``There can be no doubt in anybody's mind about the
direction of monetary policy.''
</P>
<P>
   Duisenberg acknowledged that he was concerned about the euro,
the single currency adopted a year ago by 11 European countries.
Though conceived in part as a rival to the U.S. dollar, the value
of the euro has tumbled from $1.18 at its debut to 96.63 cents
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, the euro dropped to nearly 94 cents before recovering
a bit amid speculation _ apparently wrong _ that the central bank
had intervened on its behalf.
</P>
<P>
   European leaders insist that they have no intention of propping
up the euro through direct intervention, and Duisenberg explicitly
denied that the central bank had moved into currency markets on
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   But the persistent decline of the new currency has been
disheartening, and Duisenberg said he was troubled by it on two
counts.
</P>
<P>
   The first concern, he said, is that the currency weakness will
generate inflationary pressures by increasing the prices of
imported goods. A second concern, he continued, is about ``possible
psychological effects'' on the credibility of the currency itself.
</P>
<P>
   The main reason for the decline against the dollar, most
economists agree, is that the U.S. economy is growing so much
faster than that of Europe.
</P>
<P>
   On top of that, the U.S. Federal Reserve has raised U.S.
interest rates more rapidly in recent months than the European
Central Bank.
</P>
<P>
   Duisenberg is now caught at one of the trickiest junctures he
has faced since the introduction of the euro on Jan. 1, 1999.
</P>
<P>
   The anemic growth in Europe's biggest economies has finally
improved, and conditions are among the best they have been in
years. At the same time, however, inflationary pressures are
clearly building. Across the 11 euro nations, consumer prices
climbed at an annual rate of 2 percent in January. That is right at
the limit of what the European Central Bank considers acceptable.
</P>
<P>
   Prices are climbing considerably faster than that in Europe's
smaller but faster growing countries. Inflation is running at 4.4
percent a year in Ireland, while in Spain the rate is 2.9 percent.
Italy, one of Europe's biggest yet weakest economies, has a rate of
about 2.2 percent. Much of that reflects the surge in oil prices.
</P>
<P>
   The European Central Bank has come under increasing criticism
for sending mixed signals about its priorities. Until recently,
many economists were convinced that it would raise interest rates
Thursday in another pre-emptive strike against rising prices.
</P>
<P>
   Part of that expectation came from hawkish statements in the
most recent monthly bulletin of the central bank. In a newspaper
interview published Monday, the bank's vice president, Christian
Noyer, cautioned that people were reading too much into its
bulletin and hinted that the bank was not yet ready to become more
tightfisted.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems like they are aiming at a broad consensus of all the
members of the governing board,'' said Elga Bartsch, an economist
with Morgan Stanley Dean Witter in London.
</P>
<P>
   In the 14 months since it assumed control of monetary policy for
the euro countries, the European Central Bank has struggled to
maintain its credibility in global markets even as it has watched
the euro decline steadily the entire time.
</P>
<P>
   Initially determined to run a hard-nosed policy aimed at
preventing inflation above all else, it was forced to open its
spigots last year, when European growth stalled as a result of
financial crises in Asia, Russia and Latin America.
</P>
<P>
   Last November it swung back to a hard-line stance, raising
interest rates by half a percentage point, to 3 percent. In
January, it followed up with a second increase, to 3.25 percent.
</P>
<P>
   That still leaves baseline interest rates in Europe well below
those in the United States, though its inflation rate is slightly
lower as well.
</P>
<P>
   At the moment, all signs point to a strong rebound in European
growth. Germany, Europe's biggest economy but also its most
sluggish, is growing at an annual rate of more than 2.5 percent _ a
big improvement from 1999, when it grew a total of 1.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
   For the euro zone as a whole, economists predict that growth
will average about 3 percent in 2000, and perhaps slightly more.
</P>
<P>
   ``Economic conditions and perspectives in the euro area appear
to be better at present than at any time in the past decade,''
Duisenberg said Thursday, a signal that he is not worried that a
tougher monetary policy will put Europe back into a tailspin.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
