<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRADLEY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRADLEY SUPPORTERS SEEM RESIGNED TO POSSIBLE END OF CAMPAIGN 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By DAVID W. CHEN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Patricia Simpson was waiting for Bill Bradley inside
the Gray's Papaya hot dog joint in Greenwich Village on Thursday
afternoon, hoping for a word with the candidate and a chance to
show off her ``Bill Bradley for President'' sticker. But she would
also have been content, frankly, if the sticker had read ``Bill
Bradley for Vice President'' or ``Bill Bradley for U.N.
Ambassador.''
</P>
<P>
   After all, she said that while she liked Bradley's liberal
positions, particularly on abortion, she also said that she had
nothing against Vice President Al Gore. In fact, she said she would
probably vote for Gore in Tuesday's crucial Democratic primary in
New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like Bradley, and I think he's a very fine man,'' said
Simpson, 66, a retired speech pathologist. ``I just feel badly for
him because the spotlight has been on McCain.''
</P>
<P>
   With five days to go before the do-or-die Super Tuesday
primaries, Bradley's campaign has, for some supporters, taken on
the aura of a noble but silver-medal effort, as his poll numbers
have collapsed and his campaign continues to be overshadowed by the
more dramatic Republican race.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley remained upbeat on Thursday, from the event at Gray's
Papaya to later events in Connecticut, but many supporters seemed
almost philosophical and wistful about what they said was a race
that appeared to be over, barring a miracle. So they populated
their thoughts with sentiments ranging from encouragement to
gratitude.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even though I really don't see him winning, I want to thank
him because, if anything, he's pushed Al Gore to address issues he
wouldn't have addressed,'' said Jason Greenfield, 20, a student at
New York University majoring in political science. ``I think he
would be a great V.P.''
</P>
<P>
   Bradley, though, continued to talk the good fight. Looking
somewhat fatigued after his debate in Los Angeles on Wednesday
night with Gore, Bradley donned the strawberry-colored uniform of
Gray's Papaya, wolfed down part of a hot dog _ with sauerkraut _
and worked the modest crowd with smiles and handshakes. It all took
15 minutes, tops.
</P>
<P>
   The Gore camp is eager to appear sensitive to Bradley's
situation and wants to avoid alienating him and his supporters at
this delicate stage, Gore aides said. So when Gore visited P.S. 163
on the Upper West Side of Manhattan on Thursday, he seemed content
to read ``A Friend for Little Bear'' to children. Later, he read
``Green Eggs and Ham'' to children at the Francis Scott Key school
in District Heights, Md.
</P>
<P>
   Later, in Connecticut, Bradley reacted strongly to a decision by
the South Carolina Legislature on Thursday to reject recognition of
Martin Luther King's Birthday and to keep the Confederate battle
flag flying over the state Capitol. ``Yet again, South Carolina
sticks the finger in the eye of a country that recognizes that
diversity is a strength, not a weakness.''
</P>
<P>
   And he tried to sound positive in a five-minute television
advertisement that was broadcast nationally on Thursday night,
offering not an attack on Gore _ as he has done in previous weeks _
but a variation of his stump speech. But he did acknowledge that
his task was difficult.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew when I got into this race that it wouldn't be easy,''
he said. ``Anything worth fighting for in life rarely is. But my
convictions of where we are as a country and where we can go are so
deep that I made the decision to take on the establishment and
run.''
</P>
<P>
   Then, in Connecticut late on Thursday, he offered an underdog
pitch that he is expected to repeat throughout the Northeast the
next few days. In an interview with an NBC affiliate in Hartford,
he said: ``Don't listen to the pollsters and the pundits. Vote your
heart. Vote your conscience. Vote for a new politics.''
</P>
<P>
   It remains to be seen, though, whether Bradley has enough time
to climb back into the race. On Thursday, in Greenwich Village,
even his most ardent supporters admitted that the odds did not look
good.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel bad for him because I don't think he'll get elected,''
said Matt Rosenberg, a retired teacher. ``He's a real decent human
being.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
