<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-02 20:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5006 &Cx1f; tad-z
u r BC-CAR-LABONTE03-COX     03-02 0758
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-LABONTE03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bobby Labonte finds success, teamwork
 &HT;    By Al Levine
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Bobby Labonte learned the benefits of a two-car team last
season. He also learned some of the risks, such as protecting the
ego and sharing the spotlight in the same garage.
</P>
<P>
   Now Labonte is taking lessons learned in the 1999 season and is
using them to his advantage in 2000. The driver of the No. 18
Pontiac is off to a good start, winning Sunday's Dura Lube/Kmart
400 at North Carolina Speedway.
</P>
<P>
   With the victory, Labonte moved to second in the points
standings, which is where he finished last season.
</P>
<P>
   The gap between Labonte and the Winston Cup championship last
year was 201 points. In an otherwise splendid year _ five
victories, five poles _ Labonte looks back and sees opportunities
missed.
</P>
<P>
   ``The one thing that comes to my mind is Sears Point, trying to
go for fourth place. Maybe I should have stuck with fifth instead
of wrecking,'' Labonte said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was just a major screwup. I lost a lot of momentum that
day, points-wise, because we were ahead of Dale Jarrett and never
could gain it back. You wish you could have five mistakes
throughout the year and survive. That was one mistake I really
couldn't overcome.''
</P>
<P>
   Labonte had to deal with a number of freaky things last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can start off at Daytona,'' Labonte recalls. ``We had a
piece that fell out of the manifold. Freak deal. We've got to
address that problem. At Bristol, when you're running third or
fourth and somebody spins out in front of you, sometimes you can't
avoid that. When a piece of metal comes off the race track and
knocks the rear-end belt off and catches on fire, there's not a
whole lot I could've done about that one.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wrecking at Sears Point and Watkins Glen, yeah, I could have
done something big about that. In a nutshell, we've got to fix
those little things, and I've got to make sure I don't do the wrong
thing. Just try to be better everywhere. We ran good when we didn't
have a problem _ we were up front. But Dale Jarrett just had less
problems than we did.''
</P>
<P>
   Crew chief Jimmy Makar said he thinks this is the year Labonte
can make the move to the championship.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why did we finish second instead of first? Basically, it
boiled down to 10 races that we had problems in,'' Makar said.
``Twice we had debris knock belts off the car. We had a few motor
problems. Bobby had some mistakes on the race track and we were in
the wrong place at the wrong time on the race track. Those are the
areas that we have to try to work on to make the jump from second
to first.''
</P>
<P>
   Labonte emerged as a championship contender last year at the
same time that teammate Tony Stewart rewrote the standards for a
Winston Cup rookie.
</P>
<P>
   ``For Tony,'' Labonte said, ``the hardest thing probably was
knowing where the race tracks were, not what to do inside the
tracks.''
</P>
<P>
   But at times, Labonte had to wonder whose side Stewart was on.
In the next-to-last race of the season, the teammates were in a
side-by-side battle for the lead at Homestead, Fla., with laps
running out.
</P>
<P>
   Stewart tapped his No. 20 Pontiac into the side of Labonte's No.
18 Pontiac, took the lead away and went on to win his third race of
the season. Labonte fought to keep from sliding into the wall.
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, Stewart apologized to his boss and his teammate. He
said his car got loose on the apron where Labonte had pushed it
going into turn 3. ``I would never take Bobby Labonte out,''
Stewart said.
</P>
<P>
   The two seem to define the meaning of two teammates pushing each
other. Labonte believes it can only help the Joe Gibbs entries.
</P>
<P>
   ``If one's off one day, we try to help out,'' Labonte said.
``We're two different drivers with two different styles. We've got
to make sure we don't try to talk one of us into something that
really isn't good for him. We've got to drive our own race, but yet
we can still communicate about what the track's doing, what the
tire's doing, what the car is doing, about other people or
whatever.''
</P>
<P>
   Labonte's easy disposition is also helping make the Gibbs team
the most potent in Winston Cup racing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tony's an excellent driver,'' Labonte said. ``He came on board
and helped the program. We helped his program. The team that Jimmy
Makar has put together for the 18 car, and the 20 car, Greg
Zipadelli and all those guys, the communication's there. We're just
making a lot better decisions.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
