<HEADER>
A5007 &Cx1f; tad-z
u r BC-CAR-NASCAR-NOTES03-CO     03-02 1362
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-NASCAR-NOTES03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    NASCAR NOTES
 &HT;    By Michael Carvell
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _
</P>
<P>
   Power Index
</P>
<P>
   A look at some of the hottest NASCAR teams
</P>
<P>
   1.Robert Yates Racing: What is the highest honor for a driver
after the season's first two races? To have his 2000 Taurus
confiscated by NASCAR. That's what has happened with the
highest-finishing cars of each manufacturer after races at Daytona
and Rockingham. The cars were taken for a wind-tunnel examination
at Lockheed in Atlanta. Dale Jarrett has had the No. 88 Ford
confiscated two weeks in a row.
</P>
<P>
   2.Joe Gibbs Racing: This team might overtake the No. 1 ranking
from Yates after the next two events. Bobby Labonte miraculously
finished sixth at Daytona, despite a 15-second penalty in the pits.
He was the dominant driver at Rockingham. Teammate Tony Stewart,
who had a miserable experience at Daytona, returned to his rookie
form with a fourth-place finish Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   3. Richard Childress Racing: With 10 or 15 extra laps, Sunday's
Dura-Lube/Kmart 400 might have had a different winner.
</P>
<P>
   Many people thought that Dale Earnhardt, who finished second,
had the best car at the end of the race. Earnhardt has looked
superb in both races of the 2000 season.
</P>
<P>
   4.Penske Racing: Very quietly, the team of Rusty Wallace and
Jeremy Mayfield is starting to cause concerns in the garage area.
Wallace won the pole at Rockingham and was a force during the early
part of the race. Mayfield, after a disappointing sophomore season,
has shown signs of life. Mayfield, who finished seventh at
Rockingham, might soon reclaim his reputation as one of the
circuit's up-and-comers.
</P>
<P>
   5.Bill Davis Racing: After the first two races, Ward Burton has
surpassed the team's expectations and claimed the third spot in the
Winston Cup point standings behind Dale Jarrett and Bobby Labonte.
Only Labonte was stronger at Rockingham; Burton led four times for
100 laps. The only disappointment for the multi-car team was the
failure of Dave Blaney to qualify for the event. Blaney is a
Winston Cup rookie.
</P>
<P>
   ON THE RISE
</P>
<P>
   Some strong performances by drivers who appear to be on the fast
track from the back of the pack.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Dale Jarrett, No. 88 Ford: Mr. Consistency is up to his old
tricks again this year. He placed first at Daytona and fifth at
Rockingham. It's the same formula that the team used last year to
capture the Winston Cup title. Jarrett has been atop the Winston
Cup standings for 26 races in a row.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Johnny Benson, No. 10 Pontiac: Benson has been on the rampage
ever since he bought out his contract with Roush Racing for a
six-figure amount last year. Benson nearly came away with a miracle
victory in the Daytona 500 before being ganged up on by the Ford
fleet. He turned in a top-15 performance at Rockingham.
</P>
<P>
   FREE-FALLIN'
</P>
<P>
   Some weak performances from drivers who appear to be on the fast
track to the back of the pack.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Darrell Waltrip, No. 66 Ford: Waltrip had the racing community
excited after posting the 10th-fastest qualifying time at
Rockingham. He then reverted to form and dropped to last place nine
laps into the race. Can Waltrip win in his final year, the
``Victory Tour 2000''?
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The Rookies: The heralded eight-man rookie class won rave
reviews at Daytona but earned a thumbs down at Rockingham. Three
rookies, including Scott Pruett, failed to qualify. Dale Earnhardt
Jr. and Matt Kenseth started in the top 10 but were nowhere in
sight at the end.
</P>
<P>
   _ Michael Carvell
</P>
<P>
   MAKING HEADLINES
</P>
<P>
   Our take on the sport's top stories.
</P>
<P>
   LOOKING BACK
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Pit-crew members in danger zone: The track seems like a
children's playground compared with pit row. Several pit-crew
members from different teams have been seriously injured since the
season began. Mark Martin accidentally struck one of his crew
members in the Bud Shootout and quit the race immediately. Tony
Stewart accidentally hit a No. 20 crew member after he was trying
to grab a stray tire from another team. A member of Wally
Dallenback's crew suffered burns on his face at North Carolina
Speedway. NASCAR should take steps to improve safety in the pits.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Rockingham sees rocky future with spring race: At least 10,000
people were no-shows for Sunday's race at ``The Rock,'' which does
not bode well for the track's chances of maintaining two races per
season in future years. The weather forecast was sketchy, but a
better turnout was expected with big names such as Dale Earnhardt,
Bill Elliott and Darrell Waltrip starting in the top 10.
</P>
<P>
   LOOKING AHEAD
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  NASCAR hopes for more exciting racing: When will the boredom
end? Fans loudly complained about the boredom at the Daytona 500,
which is supposed to be the biggest race of the season. Rockingham
was much more exciting until the yawns began appearing with 40 laps
remaining. Can Las Vegas bring back the excitement? NASCAR needs
more thrilling finishes such as last year's Goody's 500 at Bristol,
Tenn., in which Dale Earnhardt bumped Terry Labonte to win the
race.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Eyes on the skies: After a week of sunny skies and
temperatures in the lower 70s, Atlanta Motor Speedway officials are
holding their breath that good weather can last for another week.
The spring race at Atlanta has a history of bad weather.
</P>
<P>
   BROTHERLY LOVE?
</P>
<P>
   At last year's Las Vegas 400, Jeff Burton, driving No. 99 Exide
Batteries Ford, outraced brother Ward to the finish line.
</P>
<P>
   It was the first 1-2 finish by brothers since Terry Labonte beat
Bobby in 1997 in Talladega, Ala.
</P>
<P>
   NASCAR Q&AMP;A
</P>
<P>
   Rookie Matt Kenseth, driver of the No. 17 Ford, has a top 10 in
a race and a top 10 in qualifying after two events. Here he talks
with Cox News Service reporter Rick Minter about his first few
weeks in Winston Cup.
</P>
<P>
   Q: How would you define a successful rookie season?
</P>
<P>
   A: It's hard to say what I'll feel good about after the season
ends. We want to improve from race to race _ make better pit stops,
qualify better and run better. Obviously, I'd like to win rookie of
the year. Winning a race, I don't really think about that. It's
pretty far-fetched at this point.
</P>
<P>
   Q: How much help have you gotten from your teammates at Roush
Racing?
</P>
<P>
   A: Mark Martin and Jeff Burton have been especially helpful to
me, giving me hints here and there. Their crew chiefs are giving us
a baseline chassis set-up so we'll have something to work with each
week. It's an advantage to be with guys with that much experience.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Are you taking a conservative approach with your set-up and
with your driving until you learn the cars and the tracks?
</P>
<P>
   A: No, I'm running as hard as I can run. That's my style. I've
never been smart enough to figure out how to lay back and still be
up front at the end of the race. If the opportunity is there to win
a race, we'll run as hard as we can. But it would be boastful to
say we can win a race. You can't go from running in the top-10 a
couple of times to all of the sudden winning a race.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What differences have you found between running the Winston
Cup and Grand National divisions?
</P>
<P>
   A: It doesn't seem that much different. The cars drive a little
different, and it's different getting in and out of the pits, but
on the track, passing cars and getting passed is about the same.
</P>
<P>
   Q: How is your relationship with Dale Earnhardt Jr., whom you
battled for the Grand National championship for the past two
seasons?
</P>
<P>
   A: Right now we are getting along better than ever. We spent a
lot of time together at Daytona hanging out, talking about
different things and watching TV in the motorhome at night. We talk
about other things besides racing more than ever now.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Are the demands on your time from sponsors, fans and the
media becoming a burden?
</P>
<P>
   A: It gets a little busier as we go along, but I'm young,
enthusiastic and fired up about doing this, so whatever else I have
to do, I don't complain about it. That's part of the job, and I
want to meet as many fans as I can and try to build a fan base.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
