<SLUG> BC-TOBACCO-REGULATE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PHILIP MORRIS OFFICIAL SAYS IT COULD ACCEPT SOME TOBACCO
REGULATION 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By BARRY MEIER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In a striking admission, a top executive of Philip Morris Cos.,
the nation's largest cigarette maker, referred to nicotine as a
``drug'' on Thursday and said the company could accept some
regulation of tobacco by the Food and Drug Administration.
</P>
<P>
   That executive, Steven Parrish, a senior vice president of
Philip Morris, also said the company was prepared to see cigarette
sales drop and invest assets now spent on tobacco n other
businesses. Additionally, he left the door open to discussing with
lawmakers whether the legal age for buying cigarettes should be
raised to 21 from 18.
</P>
<P>
   Parrish's comments are the latest he has made during a watershed
week for the giant cigarette maker. On Monday, he said that the
company was no longer opposed to some regulation by the federal
government. As expected, he expanded on those comments on Thursday
at a meeting of smoking and health experts held at the Ronald
Reagan Library in Simi Valley, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   The issue of whether nicotine should be classified as a drug is
at the center of federal efforts to exert some regulatory control
over tobacco companies. If nicotine is officially considered a
drug, the sale of tobacco products which contain it might be
regulated by the FDA.
</P>
<P>
   At Thursday's meeting, Parrish reiterated that Philip Morris
opposed having the FDA regulate nicotine as a drug or a cigarette
as a drug-delivery device. He said that nicotine was an addictive
drug but added that Philip Morris believed it did not fall under
the definition of that term by the federal Food, Drug and Cosmetic
Act.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think that it is a drug as that is defined by the act
but I do think that nicotine is a drug,'' said Parrish, according
to a transcript of his remarks.
</P>
<P>
   Apart from that, he said that Philip Morris could accept broad
regulation by the FDA in a number of areas. He said the company
wanted to develop a ``sensible, comprehensive regulatory approach
for this product that will keep it out of the hands of kids.''
</P>
<P>
   He also said the company wanted the industry and government to
work together to reduce the ``demand'' for cigarettes and to help
develop potentially less hazardous products.
</P>
<P>
   Parrish said Philip Morris, whose other divisions include Miller
Brewing and Kraft Foods, knew that efforts to deter youth smoking,
if successful, would lead to an erosion of cigarette sales.
</P>
<P>
   ``If no adults smoke as a result of cracking down on youth
smoking, we are prepared to invest our assets elsewhere,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In a brief interview, Parrish said that the company believed
there would always be adults who choose to smoke. He also said that
raising the legal age for cigarette sales in the immediate future
would prove difficult because significant numbers of people between
18 to 21 were already smokers.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. David Kessler, the former head of the FDA, appeared Thursday
on the same panel as Parrish and said that he applauded his
commitment to change.
</P>
<P>
   The new stance by Philip Morris come as a number of currents
swirl around the tobacco industry.
</P>
<P>
   A Miami jury is about to render a verdict in a case that could
financially devastate some cigarette producers. The Supreme Court
is set to decide this spring whether the FDA has regulatory
authority over tobacco. And a scientific panel is reviewing whether
it is possible to produce a less hazardous cigarette, a decision
critical to the industry's future marketing plans.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
