u s BC-BOX-TRINIDAD-REID-BOS     03-02 0589
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-TRINIDAD-REID-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOUT PUTS UNDEFEATED RECORDS ON THE LINE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAS VEGAS _ One thing is sure about Friday night's World Boxing
Association junior middleweight title fight between Felix Trinidad
and David Reid. Somebody's 0 has got to go.
</P>
<P>
   Reid is the undefeated former Olympic gold medalist who won the
WBA title in only his 12th professional fight and has since
defended it twice. Seldom does a fighter become a world champion
after 12 fights, and even less often does he put it all on the line
in his 15th one, against a longtime champion in his prime like the
undefeated Trinidad.
</P>
<P>
   At 36-0, Trinidad is the only man to defeat Oscar De La Hoya,
and he holds both the International Boxing Federation and World
Boxing Council welterweight titles. Friday night he is putting
neither at risk, but if he wins he must decide what titles he wants
to hold. If he does not conquer the calmly confident Reid, it is a
moot point, and he returns to a world of 147-pounders in which
pursuit of De La Hoya will again become his goal.
</P>
<P>
   In Reid's opinion, Trinidad will have only that option by late
Friday night. Supremely confident without being cocky, the kid from
the streets of Philadelphia who stunned the world when he won a
gold medal with a last-second knockout of a heavily favored Cuban
(Alfredo Duvergel) in the 1996 Olympics in Atlanta believes this is
his moment, not Trinidad's, just as that moment in 1996 was his and
not the Cuban's.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the biggest fight of my career,'' said Reid (14-0, 7
KOs). ``All the marbles are in the basket. It's a winnable fight.
It's a fight I have to win to go on to bigger and better things.
</P>
<P>
   ``From the beginning I have to make him respect my power. I have
to make him back up. That's the question. We both come forward.
Who's going to back up first?''
</P>
<P>
   Trinidad has confidently predicted a knockout and his father and
trainer, Felix Sr., has gone so far as to call the fourth round as
their moment. Reid didn't disagree with that timing, just who was
going down.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want it to end in four, too,'' Reid said. ``Who is going to
get hit on the chin first? I know it's not going to be me. I'm
going to start off fast. Trinidad is going to have to catch up to
me.''
</P>
<P>
   Even Trinidad's father concedes Reid is the faster fighter, both
in terms of foot speed and hand speed. He concedes, too, that while
Reid has only 15 fights, he is an Olympic gold medalist, the third
straight his son is facing. To the Trinidads, an Olympic gold medal
counts for much more than a lengthy string of professional
victories over nonentities, and so they view young Reid with
perhaps more respect than the bookmakers, who have made him an 8-5
underdog.
</P>
<P>
   They do not argue Reid's advantages, they concede them. Then
they simply contend that, in the end, none of them will matter.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, he is faster than my son,'' Felix Sr. said. ``But what
does it matter? When he gets hit, he will slow down.''
</P>
<P>
   Certainly that is what the Tinidads are counting on. David Reid
is counting on what he has in his heart and in his head.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Trinidad is going to have trouble with my speed and my
movement,'' he said. ``I do not stay in one spot . . . and he's
going to have trouble with my punching power.''
</P>
<P>
   In the end, somebody seems certain to find trouble before this
night is over. When he does his O will go. And, for 10 seconds or
so, he's likely to go out with it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-02-00 2039EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
