<HEADER>
A5013 &Cx1f; tta-z
u p BC-CINDY-MCCAIN-ART-2TAK     03-02 1022
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CINDY-MCCAIN-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
  
 CINDY McCAIN: A SURPRISING ASSET TO HER HUSBAND'S CAMPAIGN  
(ART ADV: Photos NYT21 and 22 are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
(bl) 
 By MELINDA HENNEBERGER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   CLEVELAND _ At every campaign stop, Sen. John McCain introduces
his wife, Cindy McCain, as ``the one who everyone says, `Why isn't
she the candidate?''' But until a few months ago, no one, including
either of the McCains, saw her as someone who could take on so much
as a supporting role in a national campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Even some friends considered her not only disinterested, but
simply too fragile _ and in the rough calculus of political life,
probably a liability. Her life in Arizona, where her husband has
joined her on weekends and holidays throughout his Senate career,
had always revolved around their children and her parents, who live
across the street. Politics was a subject the McCains rarely
discussed, she said.
</P>
<P>
   And if the public had heard of her at all, it was probably as a
result of the 1994 headlines about a federal investigation into her
theft of painkillers from a medical charity she ran. Or because of
the Keating Five savings and loan scandal a few years earlier,
which she was drawn into as well. Today, drug-free since 1993, she
looks back on that time in their lives as a moment that ``nearly
destroyed both of us.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, in contrast, news reports about Mrs. McCain have been
uniformly positive. Crowds like her, the camera loves her, and, not
insignificantly, her husband seems to have noticed, too: ``She's
really blossomed,'' he said. Those who know the couple say it is a
profound relief for Mrs. McCain to find that she is widely
perceived as a political asset to him.
</P>
<P>
   And in this new role, at age 45, she seems to be seeing not Sen.
McCain but herself in another light: ``It's overwhelming,'' she
said, ``how much interest there is in the partner.''
</P>
<P>
   For months now, more than any other presidential candidate's
wife, she has been a regular on the campaign trail. Through 14-hour
work days, she is almost constantly at her husband's elbow, smiling
as she double-steps to keep up with him in crowds, and nodding at
just the right moments during the speech she has heard hundreds of
times.
</P>
<P>
   Getting on the Straight Talk Express again one morning last
week, she said she had expected to hate campaigning, and planned to
avoid it as much as possible. And no one was more surprised than
she was, she says, that she has instead really taken to life on the
road: ``For most of the 20 years we've been married, he's been in
Washington all week while I'm in Arizona with the kids,'' she
explained. ``I've never spent this much time with my husband.''
</P>
<P>
   The campaign trail, of course, does not offer much quality time
for the candidate and his wife, either. But she says she is mostly
here to help, and she certainly does: She smoothes her husband's
hair and helps him with his jacket _ the injuries he suffered as a
prisoner of war prevent him from raising his arms over his head _
and watches his diet, too, though often in vain.
</P>
<P>
   Intensely protective, she also gives a pretty good stiff arm to
photographers who try to get too close _ not to her, but to her
husband.
</P>
<P>
   And she tries to see that he sleeps. During the flap about his
Republican rival, Gov. George W. Bush, carrying his own feather
pillow on the road, someone asked Sen. McCain whether, he, too, had
brought a pillow from home. Yeah, he said, and gestured towards his
wife.
</P>
<P>
   She is a quiet presence on the bus, and by far its best turned
out passenger, in her St. John knit suits and patent leather pumps,
with a soft-spoken femininity that does recall her role model,
Jackie Kennedy.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the hip haircut that an aide insists is sweeping
Washington, she carries herself in a way that is distinctly
unmodern: Years of dance training have endowed her with perfect
posture, and she usually stands with one foot forward, in the
fourth position.
</P>
<P>
   Often, she sits up front reading magazines and fielding calls
from her kids while her husband holds forth with reporters in back.
But when he does bring her into the conversation by teasing her, as
he did one day in New Hampshire _ when he referred to ``a certain
dyed blond'' and she pretended to throw something at him _ she
beams, and basks in the attention.
</P>
<P>
   She seems always to have revered her war hero husband, 18 years
her senior, whom she met when she was only 25: ``I see the crowds
and their faces and they're looking at him with hope and it's nice
people agree with me. He's a real inspiration.'' Then she stopped
and added, ``I guess anyone would say that about their husband.''
</P>
<P>
   Last week, seeing that her husband needed a day off, she pinch
hit for him while he took a break in Arizona. ``She did a very
stoic thing, while we all went to the cabin and grilled chicken and
drank beer and slept for 12 hours,'' said his longtime aide Mark
Salter.
</P>
<P>
   Usually, Mrs. McCain doesn't speak much to voters, but does make
a striking appearance, and her husband's admirers frequently tell
him they are wowed by her looks: ``I like your taste in women,''
one woman told him last weekend as Mrs. McCain sat at his side. A
supporter in San Diego last week waved a sign that said, ``Cindy is
a Babe.''
</P>
<P>
   Her assistant says that the number one question she gets is how
she manages to look at all moments as though she just returned from
a week at a spa. When asked that question yet again, she blushed
and said, ``I don't do anything special. I just love being with my
husband.''
</P>
<P>
   Far less flattering questions get a similarly positive response.
When asked whether she ever worried about how her addiction to
painkillers had affected her children, the oldest of whom was 7 at
the time she was dependent on Percocet and Vicodin, she said, ``No.
It was more for me that I missed a
</P>
<P>
   great deal. I missed a lot of what went on. But I'm a better
person and a better parent for having gone through that.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   And she went through quite a bit. In 1991, her husband was
rebuked by the Senate Ethics Committee for exercising poor judgment
in meeting with federal regulators who were investigating Charles
Keating Jr., the owner of a failing savings and loan who was also a
friend and donor. Mrs. McCain was involved in the matter as well
because she had helped keep her husband's books and could not find
receipts showing that they had reimbursed Keating for flying on his
corporate jet to his vacation home in the Bahamas.
</P>
<P>
   It was under pressure of that scandal, and after back surgery,
that she became addicted to painkillers. And though her drug
problem went on for a couple of years, her husband never noticed.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, it was not McCain but his wife's parents who became
worried by her erratic behavior and confronted her. More than a
year later, when federal authorities began investigating reports
that she had stolen drugs from the charity, the senator finally
learned of his wife's addiction _ just before her troubles, too,
hit the front page.
</P>
<P>
   Now, though, news of Mrs. McCain tends to focus on her constant
cell phone conversations with her children. And one of her closest
friends, Sharon Harper, said that she is enjoying every minute of
her moment: ``She does really well so there's a lot of
reinforcement, a lot of validation and reassurance along the way.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. McCain herself suggests that as a stay-at-home mom, the
little gold stars were harder to come by: ``There have been times,
particularly in Washington, when they shake your hand and look over
your head _ ``Where's John?'' _ but I don't really care what they
think.''
</P>
<P>
   The only child of a wealthy Phoenix beer distributor, Jim
Hensley, she was a little lonely growing up, she said, and always
knew she wanted children.
</P>
<P>
   After college and graduate school at the University of Southern
California _- an institution her husband refers to as the
University of Spoiled Children _ she shunned a major role in the
family business and taught for a few months as a special education
teacher.
</P>
<P>
   When she met McCain, and they ``fell in love at first sight,''
as she said, he was still married and living with his first wife.
But she was so shy, so obviously not the initiator, his first
wife's friends have said, that even then, no one blamed her.
</P>
<P>
   After years as ``a background spouse,'' as Salter referred to
her, McCain only got her to go along with his presidential plans by
promising that she would never have to set foot in Iowa or New
Hampshire.
</P>
<P>
   But then, over the course of the campaign, she began to feel
needed.
</P>
<P>
   At a town hall meeting in Peterborough, New Hampshire, last
October, someone in the audience asked about Mrs. McCain's agenda.
``Her special project? It would be keeping me under control,'' her
husband said, winking at the audience before handing the microphone
over to her.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's right,'' she began, ``my first concern is to keep him
under control, but I'm a stay-at-home mother. If our family is
running well and our home is running well that enables my husband
to do his job better. I don't like labels, but if there's a label
for me, it would be traditional, and I'm very proud to be
traditional,'' she said, to huge applause.
</P>
<P>
   Her issues as first lady, she says, would be adoption and foster
care.
</P>
<P>
   Despite her years in Narcotics Anonymous, Mrs. McCain doesn't
mention drug treatment as a principle focus, and in fact advocates
a return to Nancy Reagan's `Just Say No' anti-drug philosophy.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, even as her husband's most loyal supporter, how does
she appear ever rapt during the stump speech _ and filled with
delight at every retelling of his jokes? She laughed. ``Let's just
say it's very exciting when there's a new joke.''
</P>
<P>
   A couple of times, she has cried in full view of reporters, most
recently on the day of the South Carolina primary. ``Losing is not
what bothered me,'' she explained. ``It was how we lost. When they
criticized me for having an adopted child of color, that capped it.
That was despicable.''
</P>
<P>
   She was referring to reports, disputed by the Bush camp, that
there were campaign leaflets characterizing Mrs. McCain as a drug
addict who had adopted a black baby; her 8-year-old daughter
Bridget was born in Bangladesh, and Mrs. McCain brought her here
for medical care. She decided to adopt her on the flight back,
before talking to her husband, and at the airport, told him, ``Meet
your daughter.''
</P>
<P>
   In an interview on his campaign plane, McCain referred to that
display of emotion as ``the only time I saw her slip during this
whole thing'' and called her ``very emotional'' and ``not a
political sophisticate.''
</P>
<P>
   And when, at the end of yet another long day during which Mrs.
McCain spent virtually every moment supporting him, the senator was
asked to describe his marriage to her, he rubbed his hands over his
face before answering.
</P>
<P>
   ``Like most marriages,'' he said, sitting next to her on the
plane, ``it has a lot of revolving around our kids.''
</P>
<P>
   If these are not exactly the words every wife is longing to
hear, however, Mrs. McCain did not protest, or register any
reaction at all.
</P>
<P>
   Asked how he would describe his wife to a friend who did not
know her, the senator said, ``as a very kind person, committed to
her children, and never before this campaign politically involved.
She's really blossomed.''
</P>
<P>
   A few minutes later, she pulled a blanket over him and watched
as he drifted off to sleep.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
