<SLUG> BC-ZIMBABWE-POLITICS-480&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ZIMBABWE WILL REPORTEDLY CONTINUE EFFORT TO SEIZE WHITE-OWNED
LAND 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 By HENRI E. CAUVIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   JOHANNESBURG, South Africa _ The Zimbabwean government Thursday
sent the clearest signal yet that it plans to press ahead with its
effort to change the constitution to allow the state to seize
white-owned land without compensation.
</P>
<P>
   In a front-page article, the state-controlled Herald newspaper
reported that the government plans to put forward a constitutional
amendment that would grant the government the power to take land
from white farmers, resettle landless blacks and pay nothing.
</P>
<P>
   In February, a similarly worded proposal was defeated in a
referendum on a new constitution. But a constitutional amendment
could be adopted with the support of two-thirds of the 150-member
Parliament, which is dominated by President Robert Mugabe's
governing party, the newspaper said.
</P>
<P>
   Approval could come as early as April, before the country's
parliamentary elections.
</P>
<P>
   The voters' rejection of the constitutional referendum 16 days
ago delivered a stunning rebuke to Mugabe, who has led Zimbabwe
since its independence from Britain in 1980. But the rejection had
more to do with the country's crumbling economy than with the
constitution itself or with any widespread concern for the fate of
white farmers.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, two decades after the black majority wrested control
from whites, land reform and redistribution remains a volatile
political issue, particularly among people in the countryside.
Whites, who number about 70,000 in this nation of 12.5 million
people, are estimated to control more than half of the country's
most fertile land, while most blacks are crowded onto land with
little or no agricultural value.
</P>
<P>
   In a sign of just how inflammatory an issue land remains,
thousands of veterans of the guerrilla war against white rule
stormed farms around the country this week in what they said was
retribution for the vote against the constitutional revision.
</P>
<P>
   The mobs intimidated and threatened land owners, and in at least
a couple of cases, forced them off their land, said Jerry Grant,
deputy director of the Commercial Farmers' Union, which represents
about 4,000 large-scale farmers, most of them white.
</P>
<P>
   Police did little to halt the raids at first, and the national
police commissioner told the state newspaper that the actions
against the farmers were a ``political issue'' and that his
officers could do nothing to stop them.
</P>
<P>
   Home Affairs Minister Dumiso Dabengwa said Thursday that the
raiders could not be denied their ``democratic right to
demonstrate'' but added that if they did not withdraw by Saturday,
the police would intervene.
</P>
<P>
   With parliamentary elections set for April, the amendment
appears to be a play for the support of rural voters, whose
homesteads were in many cases stolen decades ago by white settlers
during Britain's colonial rule in the former Rhodesia and who
remain frustrated by the slow pace of redistribution.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Mugabe and his party were apparently counting on that anger to
propel the proposed new constitution in February, but they
underestimated the depth of discontent in the country over
inflation, unemployment and government corruption and
mismanagement.
</P>
<P>
   Arguing that the new constitution would only have strengthened
the president and was more about grabbing power than grabbing land,
opponents of the referendum were able to defeat Mugabe, the
liberation leader who has been all but invincible during his two
decades in power.
</P>
<P>
   Chastened by his surprising loss at the polls, Mugabe, 76, was
uncharacteristically diplomatic in his speech after the vote. But
since then, his government has been giving every indication that
the land question is far from settled.
</P>
<P>
   Only a couple of years ago, Zimbabwe appeared ready to make land
reform a reality. An agreement with several donor countries,
including Britain, called for Zimbabwe to cover the costs of
acquiring the land, while the donor nations would pay the
considerably higher costs of redeveloping and resettling the land.
</P>
<P>
   But the plan, hampered in part by the government's desperate
shortage of money, has yet to move off the drawing board. With
little to show for all the chatter about land reform, Mugabe has
frequently resorted to talk of simply taking the land and leaving
Britain with the responsibility for paying out any compensation.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, like the failed draft constitution, the new draft
amendment would codify Britain's responsibility for compensation.
Such a threat, empty as it is, has only served to harden attitudes
on both sides.
</P>
<P>
   Such standoffs, along with the government's willingness to stand
by and watch the farm raids happen, suggest that the divide between
the government and its critics _ at home and abroad _ is only
deepening, said Sam Moyo, a land reform expert and the director of
the Southern Africa Institute for Policy Research in Harare,
Zimbabwe's capital.
</P>
<P>
   ``People have dug in their heels,'' Moyo said in a telephone
interview. ``What we're seeing is a reflection of the polarization
that has developed on both sides.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
