<TEXT>
<P>
   The Seattle Post-Intelligencer plans to move the following
stories for clients of the NYTimes News Service for editions of
Friday, March 3, and thereafter. If you have any questions, please
call Bob Schenet on the national-foreign desk at (206) 448-8037.
</P>
<P>
   FILM-MAP (Undated) _ Alice (Sigourney Weaver), the
heroine-narrator of the film version of Jane Hamilton's 1994 novel,
``A Map of the World,'' tells us in its opening moments that we are
about to witness a woman's descent into a living hell. The boast
turns out to be no exaggeration.
</P>
<P>
   By William Arnold. (Story has moved in the ``e'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   FILM-THING (Undated) _ At some point, Madonna is going to have
to face the hard fact that her particular stardom just doesn't
translate well to feature-length, narrative-based motion pictures.
When she tries to play a normal, everyday human being _ as she does
in her latest splashy star vehicle, ``The Next Best Thing'' _ she's
fairly hopeless.
</P>
<P>
   By William Arnold. (Story has moved in the ``e'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   FILM-AGNES (Undated) _ Anjelica Huston's big-screen directorial
debut, ``Agnes Browne,'' is a chronicle of an imperiled Irish
family that could almost be described as a benevolent, feel-good
version of ``Angela's Ashes.''
</P>
<P>
   By William Arnold. (Story has moved in the ``e'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   FILM-PLANET (Undated) _ Garry Shandling is reportedly the best
friend of Hollywood power-couple Warren Beatty and Annette Bening,
which explains what A-level star Bening is doing in Shandling's
D-level wannabe star vehicle, ``What Planet Are You From?'' But
what the heck is Mike Nichols' name doing in the producer and
director's credits of this ghastly unfunny misfire?
</P>
<P>
   By William Arnold. (Story has moved in the ``e'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   FILM-SKIP (Undated) _ ``My Dog Skip'' has its lapses, but it
kept a preview audience in tears. As a family film about a boy and
his dog, it brings back memories of ``Old Yeller,'' ``Big Red'' and
``The Incredible Journey,'' which also taught kids about life, its
hardships and joys, and how important that first beloved pet can
be. And it works because it never tries to be more than the very
personal memory piece it is.
</P>
<P>
   By Paula Nechak. (Story has moved in the ``e'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   FILM-MONA (Undated) _ More and more nasty comedies have been
vying to topple Bobby and Peter Farrelly's ``Kingpin'' and
``There's Something About Mary'' from the top of the bad-taste
throne. The latest entry, ``Drowning Mona,'' scores high on
nastiness, but it has as many surprisingly funny moments as
offensive ones.
</P>
<P>
   By Paula Nechak. (Story has moved in the ``e'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   FILM-PEOPLE (Undated) _ Yugoslav director Jasmin Dizdar's
colorful first feature, ``Beautiful People,'' opens in a burst of
energy and never lets up. It's about melting-pot London and a group
of residents whose lives run parallel and perpendicular, no matter
what their ethnicity.
</P>
<P>
   By Paula Nechak. (Story has moved in the ``e'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   TV-COVERME (Undated) _ ``Cover Me,'' premiering Sunday on USA
Network, brings us Danny Arno: FBI agent, lounge singer, devoted
father. OK, unconventional father. It's one of the more enjoyable
new shows of this or any season.
</P>
<P>
   By John Levesque. (Story has moved in the ``e'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   TV-WALLS (Undated) _ If only the people who hate homosexuals _
excuse me, who hate homosexuality _ were forced to watch ``If These
Walls Could Talk 2,'' maybe they'd realize they really have nothing
to fear from homosexuals. And, consequently, one thing less to
hate.
</P>
<P>
   BKN-SONICS (Miami) _ Seattle SuperSonics at Miami.
</P>
<P>
   By Ronald Tillery. (Story will move in the ``s'' category.)
</P>
