<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMF-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STRAW POLL FAILS TO DESIGNATE NEW IMF CHIEF 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By JOSEPH KAHN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Directors of the International Monetary Fund failed
Thursday to rally around any of the people who want to lead the
world financial institution, and expectations rose that Europe
would search for a new candidate to keep its half-century lock on
the job.
</P>
<P>
   The European, American and Japanese contenders for the fund's
top post all fell short of a majority of the votes in a straw poll.
No further poll was scheduled, and people involved in the selection
process said it could now take weeks to choose a replacement for
Michel Camdessus, the Frenchman who recently retired as managing
director.
</P>
<P>
   The vote result, which was not a surprise, confirmed that
Germany had misjudged its chances of rallying support for Caio
Koch-Weser, a deputy finance minister whom German Chancellor
Gerhard Schroeder aggressively pushed for the job during a
four-month campaign. Germany backed Koch-Weser despite public
opposition from the United States and a lukewarm endorsement by
European allies.
</P>
<P>
   Koch-Weser garnered 43 percent of the votes in the straw poll,
people involved in the process said. That was a modest margin over
the nearly 37 percent of the votes that the European Union
controls. Stanley Fischer, the American candidate nominated by a
coalition of African and Arab countries, placed a distant second
with 12 percent. The Japanese favorite, Eisuke Sakakibara, a former
Finance Ministry official, got 9 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The United States abstained, as did many other countries, and 36
percent of the votes were not cast for any candidate.
</P>
<P>
   European Union officials expressed hopes that Germany would
admit defeat and allow the 15-nation European Union, which had
formally endorsed Koch-Weser earlier this week, to search for a new
candidate. Romano Prodi, the European Commission president, told
European reporters Thursday that Koch-Weser's candidacy was
effectively dead and that Europe should find someone the United
States could support.
</P>
<P>
   German officials sent no clear signals about their next move.
European and American participants in the process speculated that
Germany, which has surprised people with the tenacity of its
campaign so far, could try to force a second vote.
</P>
<P>
   At the least, these people said, Germany could seek to extract
diplomatic concessions from European partners before agreeing to
clear the way for a new IMF candidate. The fear was that such
maneuvering could take weeks, leaving the IMF leadership in limbo.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, attention quickly turned to other possible European
candidates. Clinton administration officials have said that they
intend to back a European for the job, a tradition that dates to
the founding of the monetary fund just after World War II.
Americans have historically run the IMF's sister institution, the
World Bank.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton, speaking before the vote, reiterated that
line Thursday. ``I am completely committed to having a European
head of the IMF,'' he said. In an apparent attempt to soothe
wounded German pride after the United States rejected Koch-Weser,
Clinton also said he would like see other German candidates.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like to see Germany play a bigger role in all these
international institutions,'' the president said.
</P>
<P>
   While there are no other publicly declared candidates in Europe,
speculation has focused mainly on five people. Gordon Brown,
Britain's chancellor of the exchequer, is considered a possibility
if he is willing to put aside ambitions to succeed Tony Blair as
prime minister. Andrew Crockett, a Briton who currently heads the
Bank for International Settlements in Switzerland, has a solid
reputation in international financial circles. There is some
question whether Germany could accept him, however, because he is
not viewed as having substantially greater political stature than
Koch-Weser.
</P>
<P>
   The French have a potential heavyweight candidate in Jean-Claude
Trichet, the head of the Bank of France. But Trichet would have to
sacrifice his ambitions of heading the European Central Bank to
take the IMF post. Two Italians, Treasury Minister Giuliano Amato
and Mario Draghi, a senior Italian Treasury official, are both seen
as experienced in finance and likely to be interested in the IMF
job.
</P>
<P>
   Aside from Germany, the big losers in the process were the 20
African and Arab countries that on their own decided to nominate
Fischer, the popular deputy director of the fund, risking Germany's
contempt for failing to support its choice. Delegates of those
countries had clearly hoped that their bid would sooner or later
attract the support of the United States. Fischer, a former
professor at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology, is highly
regarded by the Treasury Department.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton appeared to rule Fischer out on Thursday. He
said that while he admires Fischer, he will not turn away from
Europe. ``I will not support an American candidate even though I
have enormous respect for Mr. Fischer,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, some people involved said there was a set of
circumstances in which Fischer could get the job. In this case,
Europe would decide that it needed more time to settle on a
qualified candidate and would agree to throw its weight behind
Fischer, perhaps for an interim term of two years.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
