<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-02 20:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5022 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BBN-BRAVES-ROCKER-ART     03-02 1198
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES-ROCKER-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN ROCKER'S RETURN, THE REACTION IS POLITE
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photos NYT 6-8 are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
(Eds.: See also Cox News Service sports budget, SPORTS-BJT03-COX,
or call CoxNet at 404-526-5456.) (rk) 
 By JACK CURRY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   KISSIMMEE, Fla. _ After John Rocker was sneaked into the Atlanta
Braves spring training complex around 8 a.m. Thursday, he walked
through the doors of an anxious and awaiting clubhouse. Rocker wore
a smile, perhaps a nervous one, as he returned to the place where
some teammates once said he would never be wanted again.
</P>
<P>
   But Rocker was back because his suspension from baseball had
been reduced by an arbitrator on Wednesday. After shaking hands
with some teammates and introducing himself to new members of the
Braves, Rocker sat beside his locker on the left side of the room
and pulled on his uniform.
</P>
<P>
   There was a clock on the wall, but Rocker already knew what time
it would soon be.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, perhaps an hour after Rocker arrived, manager Bobby Cox
spoke to the Braves about Rocker's return and told them that the
reliever wanted to address the club. That is when Rocker, with
teammates and coaches sitting in a circle around him, began
apologizing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Please, guys, let me play,'' teammates said Rocker told them
at one point. ``I want to play for the Braves.''
</P>
<P>
   The Braves cautiously welcomed Rocker, with his teammates saying
they would give him a chance to prove he is different from the
person who made critical comments about foreigners, gays and New
Yorkers to Sports Illustrated in December.
</P>
<P>
   Later in the day, Rocker was adamant about not answering
questions from reporters. However, after he did one television
interview, he grudgingly agreed to speak with representatives of
the Atlanta news media and a pool reporter representing the
national news media.
</P>
<P>
   In Rocker's first interview with a group of journalists since
the article appeared, the Braves' closer talked about an encounter
with African-American construction workers in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   ``A black guy who is the foreman at a construction site right
next to my apartment complex stopped me two days ago when I was
pulling out and wanted me to come and talk to all his construction
workers,'' Rocker said. ``I stopped for 15 minutes and signed all
their hard hats, for about 30 guys. Probably 12 or 13 of them were
black guys and they shook my hand and were like, `Man, we hope you
stay with Atlanta.' It's been like that for the last two months.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Rocker wanted the anecdote to validate that he is not a
racist, it sounded awkward and mistimed. He had earlier read a
statement in which he said that minor league teammates from
different ethnic groups had stayed at his family's house in Macon,
Ga., and said that his best friend is of Lebanese heritage, a
person whose grandfather came to Ellis Island about 60 years ago.
Once again, Rocker's stories seemed clumsy.
</P>
<P>
   ``As you can see, my actions do not support this racist label,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   But Rocker probably cared less about his public statements than
what he told the Braves in the clubhouse meeting earlier.
</P>
<P>
   He spoke to his teammates for 10 minutes, telling them he was
sorry and claiming he did not intend to be malicious. When Rocker
was finished, six players and one coach spoke after Cox to counsel
the pitcher, ask him questions or lecture him. Players said the
meeting fluctuated between being serious and tense, and that Rocker
got teary-eyed at one point.
</P>
<P>
   Terry Mulholland advised him to show the organization respect.
John Smoltz and Tom Glavine talked to him about the critical
comments he made about Cox and reminded teammates that they have
probably been forgiven for something in the past. Brian Jordan and
Reggie Sanders told Rocker it was important for him to admit his
mistakes and move on.
</P>
<P>
   Randall Simon, the unidentified player Rocker had called a ``fat
monkey'' in the article, asked the left-handed closer how he felt
about Latin Americans, and Rocker told Simon that he lived with
Latinos in the minors and had nothing against any groups.
</P>
<P>
   ``He told me that he didn't mean what he said and he apologized
for it if he hurt me,'' said Simon, who is from Curacao. ``I felt
really good about what he said. I think I deserved that.''
</P>
<P>
   Players described Ned Yost, the third-base coach, as the most
passionate during his discussion with Rocker. Yost has been with
the Braves for 10 years and he scolded Rocker for being
disrespectful to so many people and causing such distress to an
organization that tries to be classy. Both Jordan and Eddie Perez
said that Rocker almost wept as he tried to apologize to Yost.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told John flat out that some of the things that he said
embarrassed me terribly and embarrassed my ideals about the
Braves,'' Yost said. ``He knew that and he was sorry about that and
he apologized to everyone for that.''
</P>
<P>
   Relieved that the meeting was finally over, Rocker later said,
``It was actually much better than I thought it would be.''
</P>
<P>
   Publicly, all the players said they would forgive Rocker.
Chipper Jones said Rocker has to use his second chance wisely.
Ozzie Guillen, whose fielding was criticized in the article, said
that he does not need an apology from Rocker, and that Rocker just
needs to win games.
</P>
<P>
   General manager John Schuerholz will monitor trade possibilities
and how Rocker's return influences the team.
</P>
<P>
   ``In here, it's not going to go away today,'' Glavine said.
``Our clubhouse is no different than society. There are cross
sections he offended in here a lot more than other cross sections.
The important thing was for him to do what he did. Now it's
important for him to figure out what guys he offended more than
others and maybe go around and have conversations there. It's going
to take a while to be totally normal here.''
</P>
<P>
   After Rocker's session with his teammates, he walked through the
spring training facility to get to a field house that was crowded
with 100 reporters. As Rocker strode along purposefully, camera
operators trailing him, he looked alone. It took him 102 seconds to
read a two-page statement that was similar to a statement that
appeared Thursday in The Atlanta Journal-Constitution. He
apologized to AIDS patients, members of minority groups, Cox and
the Braves. He also apologized for not being a role model.
</P>
<P>
   When Rocker sauntered onto the field for the first time this
morning, a fan yelled, ``We still love you, John,'' while another
shouted, ``First Amendment.'' The 25-year-old reliever tossed a
ball along the right-field line with Rudy Seanez, his best friend
on the team, and watched as the Braves defeated the University of
Georgia. It was Rocker's first day back, a day when he admitted he
has been immature and when the Braves admitted that this saga is
hardly over.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just turned 25 a couple of months ago and I think people are
expecting me to be mature way beyond my years because of the
position that I'm in,'' Rocker said. ``Got just a little bit of
growing up left.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
