<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-02 20:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5023 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-DOUBLECLICK-AD-COLUMN     03-02 0986
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOUBLECLICK-AD-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADVERTISING: DOUBLECLICK PUTS OFF PLAN FOR WIDER USE OF CONSUMER
INFORMATION
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By BOB TEDESCHI   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Yielding to pressure from privacy advocates and Wall Street,
DoubleClick Inc., the nation's largest online advertising company,
said Thursday that it would put a hold on its plan to link personal
information to anonymous data it collects about consumers on the
Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ``I made a big mistake,'' said Kevin O'Connor, DoubleClick's
chief executive. ``It was wrong to try to match that information in
the absence of government or industry standards, so until there's
agreement on it, we will not.''
</P>
<P>
   The move was applauded by privacy groups, which began
criticizing DoubleClick late last year, after it completed its $1.7
billion purchase of the Abacus Direct Corp., which compiles
off-line information on the buying habits of millions of consumers.
</P>
<P>
   The company's share price had fallen in recent weeks as protests
grew over DoubleClick's use of detailed personal data from multiple
sources to select consumers for advertisements that fit their
lifestyle and buying habits.
</P>
<P>
   DoubleClick had announced plans to take the Abacus information
and combine it with data it already gathers about consumers as they
travel within the company's network of 1,500 sites. These include
Web giants like Alta Vista and Autobytel.com. When users visit
those sites and view DoubleClick ads, DoubleClick places a tiny
file called a ``cookie'' on their hard drives. The cookie contains
an identifying number that enables DoubleClick to track consumers
and their behavior as they make their way around the Web.
</P>
<P>
   While some privacy advocates have criticized even the cookie
data, it is somewhat anonymous in that it is associated with the
user's computer, not with an actual name or address. But by
combining that data with the Abacus information, the company could
provide advertisers with consumers' identities and detailed
personal information that would tie an individual to his or her
Internet use and buying habits.
</P>
<P>
   DoubleClick also places traceable ads on more than 11,000 other
sites, including The New York Times on the Web, which are not part
of the DoubleClick network but use the company to serve some of the
banner ads on their Web pages.
</P>
<P>
   DoubleClick's Abacus policy also drew anxious inquiries from
legislators and state attorneys general. As privacy groups like the
Center for Democracy and Technology and the Electronic Privacy
Information Center increased the intensity of their attacks against
the company last month, the Federal Trade Commission opened an
investigation into the company's tracking practices.
</P>
<P>
   Investors also fled. DoubleClick's stock dropped more than $30
in the last two weeks in February, settling into the low $80 range.
They gained $2.875 on Thursday's announcement, closing at $83.4375.
</P>
<P>
   ``It became very clear that the overwhelming point of contention
was under what circumstances could a name be associated with
anonymous Web activity,'' O'Connor said. ``Now we're just happy to
get this behind us and move on.''
</P>
<P>
   Daniel MacKeigan, an analyst with Friedman, Billings, Ramsay, an
investment firm, said after the announcement: ``What DoubleClick is
trying to do is take the bull's-eye off their chest. The first side
of the hurricane hit them, and while it may have quieted down a
little, the back side of the storm was coming. It's a smart move.''
</P>
<P>
   Tara Long, an analyst with CE Unterberg Towbin, an investment
firm, said DoubleClick's new strategy was sound. ``It shows the
flexibility in their business model,'' she said. ``They recognized
they made a mistake, they maybe moved too early, and that they need
to have the consumers' buy in to make this work.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Is the Abacus acquisition as valuable now? Probably not, but
it's not a total waste,'' Long said. ``They didn't spend $1 billion
on nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   For example, she said, DoubleClick could still use the Abacus
data to aim ads at people based on their offline buying habits if
they wanted: ``For example, they could still target soccer moms _
women of a certain age, who might not have a job and might drive a
minivan.''
</P>
<P>
   She said the company was simply agreeing not to combine that
data with information about Internet sites this woman had visited.
</P>
<P>
   Privacy advocates expressed relief.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're pleased, and in fairness to DoubleClick, the fact that
they reversed themselves was the right thing to do,'' said Marc
Rotenberg, executive director of the Electronic Privacy Information
Center. Nevertheless, he added: ``That said, I don't think the
issue of online profiling goes away now. They just have to do it in
a way that maintains the user's privacy going forward.''
</P>
<P>
   But Evan Hendricks, editor of Privacy Times, a Washington
newsletter, said he feared that DoubleClick's move could actually
stall the effort to establish privacy standards. ``It's like `Darn,
we won!''' he said. ``By backing down now and doing the right
thing, they take a little air out of the balloon, and unfortunately
that could slow things down.''
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said that until February, the industry's
self-regulation effort was moving just slowly enough to maintain
the status quo, but quickly enough to satisfy Congress and the FTC,
each of which had threatened to propose privacy laws specific to
the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   However, since DoubleClick became the focal point of the online
privacy debate, the industry groups have accelerated their efforts.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really had a galvanizing effect,'' said Rich LeFurgy,
chairman of the Internet Advertising Bureau, one of several
industry trade groups developing privacy standards. ``We know the
FTC is looking closer and closer at it and potential legislation is
being reviewed, so we know we're reaching a critical point. I doubt
this will slow things down one iota.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-02-00 2053EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
