<DOCNO> NYT20000302.0367 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-02 20:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5024 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-BELLSOUTH-TAKEOVER03-     03-02 1558
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BELLSOUTH-TAKEOVER03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    BellSouth could be part of global deals
 &HT;    By Michael E. Kanell
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Deutsche Telekom is apparently in talks to buy Qwest
Communications, just as the Denver-based company is poised to merge
with US West.
</P>
<P>
   Such a purchase by the German phone company, the largest
telecommunications concern in Europe, would continue the wave of
consolidation that has roiled the industry during the past four
years. The acquisition would be the first by an overseas player to
purchase a U.S. company _ and probably not the last.
</P>
<P>
   For months, speculation has floated through the industry that
Deutsche Telekom is considering a bid for Atlanta-based BellSouth.
Word that Deutsche Telekom is now focused on Denver-based Qwest
drops an intriguing set of options at BellSouth's door _ assuming
BellSouth isn't already involved in the negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   BellSouth has mostly sat out the flurry of mergers and
acquisitions. Yet last year, BellSouth bought 10 percent of Qwest,
with the notion that the investment could lead to an acquisition _
especially once BellSouth is permitted into the long-distance
market in its nine-state region.
</P>
<P>
   And while BellSouth has been conservative _ zealously guarding
earnings from dilution by large investments _ the company has
proven that it can gamble big. With MCI WorldCom about to forge a
deal to buy Sprint last fall, BellSouth rushed in with a stunning,
eleventh-hour bid. MCI WorldCom quickly topped that $100 billion
package, but BellSouth had shown that it could move _ and quickly.
</P>
<P>
   This week, the possibility of an SBC-BellSouth alliance emerged
with news that the companies have been talking about joining to
form a nearly national wireless network. That kind of asset is one
that any major player is expected to build _ or buy.
</P>
<P>
   ALLIANCE MAY HELP BELLSOUTH
</P>
<P>
   Like MCI WorldCom, Deutsche Telekom has the firepower to win a
bidding war. But _ perhaps even without bidding _ BellSouth could
come away with an alliance that would help both companies.
</P>
<P>
   And the two might be natural allies, if only because BellSouth
recently earned the enmity of Deutsche Telekom's main rival, France
Telecom. Late last year, BellSouth headed off France Telecom's
purchase of a German wireless company. Perhaps by forging a deal
with Deutsche Telekom now, BellSouth might become more competitive
_ and maintain its independence, too.
</P>
<P>
   Other European telecom companies _ especially British Telecom
and France Telecom _ are also interested in establishing a U.S.
beachhead. And Deutsche Telekom is negotiating toward a purchase of
Global Crossing, the Bermuda-based provider of high-speed services,
according to Bloomberg News.
</P>
<P>
   ``If any of them did some kind of investment, it wouldn't
surprise me,'' said Elliott Hamilton, vice president with the
Strategis Group. ``If anything, it's surprising that they have
waited so long.''
</P>
<P>
   None of the companies involved would comment Thursday. And
Deutsche Telekom's French rival airily dismissed the whole notion
as a bad bargain.
</P>
<P>
   ``I see nothing in the valuation of Qwest that would justify
France Telecom being interested in it,'' said Michel Bon, chief
executive of France Telecom.
</P>
<P>
   But analysts said the logic of a deal makes sense, even if there
is some quibbling about the price. Qwest could give Deutsche
Telekom a 16,000 mile network of high-speed fiber lines in the
United States, as well as a sizeable long-distance company.
Deutsche Telekom is reportedly willing to pay at least $70 a share
for Qwest, setting the purchase price north of $52.4 billion.
Complicating any negotiations would be Qwest's $35 billion purchase
of US West, a compact embraced by shareholders and awaiting only
regulatory approval.
</P>
<P>
   US West, although the smallest of the regional Bells, is still a
large, stable, profitable company with dominance in local phone
service throughout its 14-state region. US West, while often
criticized for poor customer service, does seem to have a lead on
other phone companies in delivering high-speed services for video
and Internet. But it would be expensive.
</P>
<P>
   If Deutsche Telekom only wants Qwest, it would have to break up
the merger. In addition to facing a multi-billion dollar breakup
fee, that move would likely provoke a fight from US West, whose
shareholders expected to be paid a healthy premium as part of the
merger. Even an attempt to pay less than Qwest had agreed to pay
might spark resistance.
</P>
<P>
   With stock worth about $290 billion at the close of trading
Thursday, Deutsche Telekom certainly should be able to afford
either or both companies. But even two huge acquisitions would
hardly be the end of the game.
</P>
<P>
   SHIFT TOWARD GLOBAL
</P>
<P>
   Analysts believe the industry is in the midst of an inexorable
shift toward a global marketplace in which ``mega-carriers'' will
offer all manner of telecom services from local phones to Internet
access. No company known has that reach.
</P>
<P>
   ``Could it ultimately be Deutsche Telekom, Qwest, US West and
BellSouth together? Sure. Why not?,'' said analyst Marc Bacurin at
JC Bradford. ``We are moving to a world where there will be only
five or six global carriers. For BellSouth, it will mean becoming
part of some larger company, whether as an acquirer or being
acquired.''
</P>
<P>
   If BellSouth has not already maneuvered itself into the thinking
of Deutsche Telekom, it probably should, he said. ``BellSouth has
probably been making calls to make sure they are not left at the
altar.''
</P>
<P>
   At the least, BellSouth's stake in Qwest has risen along with
the speculation about Deutsche Telekom. BellSouth's 10 percent now
represents $4.4 billion, up more than 100 percent this year.
BellSouth's stock too has bounced _ jumping about 25 percent in the
past week to close Thursday at $44.875 a share.
</P>
<P>
   Consolidation talk has spurred a number of stocks in the
long-lagging sector. For example, AT&AMP;T added $6.31 1/4 a share to
close at $54.12 1/2, after some upbeat comments from Goldman Sachs.
SBC Communications gained $2.50 to $44.50 a share.
</P>
<P>
   Deutsche Telekom is Europe's largest telecommunications company,
but its presence in the United States has thus far been minimal.
</P>
<P>
   The company has seven offices in North America, with a U.S.
headquarters in New York that is mostly concerned with serving the
needs of German companies doing business here. Acting chief
executive of the unit is Don Hassenbein, a veteran of 23 years in
the U.S. Air Force and a decade with AT&AMP;T.
</P>
<P>
   In the Southeast, Deutsche Telekom has a site only in Atlanta.
Those offices are just across the street from BellSouth's corporate
headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   ``This (report) highlights the fact that Deutsche Telekom has a
gaping hole in its strategy,'' said London-based Bob House, vice
president of the consulting company Renaissance Worldwide. ``What
they need to do is make a play for someone who has built or is
building a high-speed network. There are not many of those around,
and Qwest is one.''
</P>
<P>
   Among those who have staked a claim at mega-carrier status are
AT&AMP;T, MCI WorldCom and Bell Atlantic, all of which have substantial
international interests. But Deutsche Telekom cannot vault to that
status without a large U.S. presence. Deutsche Telekom hadn't
entered the U.S. market at least partly because until recently it
was part of a three-way European venture with France Telecom and
Sprint. That arrangement, never entirely harmonious, fell apart and
France Telecom bought the others out.
</P>
<P>
   The Wall Street Journal reported Thursday that the instigator
behind the deal is Phlip Anschutz, chairman of Qwest who owns 39
percent of the company. Anschutz reportedly met with Deutsche
Telekom Chairman Ron Sommer on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Qwest Chief Executive Joseph Nacchio, a hard-charging veteran of
AT&AMP;T, has clearly been angling to make a major player out of Qwest,
whose sales last year were still shy of $4 billion. His ambitious
and independent nature has been widely viewed as a potential
obstacle to a deal with some larger company. And earlier this week,
US West's chief executive, Solomon Trujillo, announced his
resignation, citing a failure to reach accord on management in the
merged company.
</P>
<P>
   To buy US West, Nacchio and Qwest had to out-battle Global
Crossing, led by another aggressive ex-AT&AMP;T executive who had to
settle for purchase of Frontier Communications. If all the current
speculation is true, they could all be owned by Deutsche Telekom.
</P>
<P>
   And there are yet other entanglements. For instance, BellSouth's
main partner in Europe _ Dutch-based KPN Telecom _ has a joint
venture with Qwest that gives KPN the right to become sole owner if
Qwest is sold. BellSouth and KPN are seen as possible merger
partners.
</P>
<P>
   Yet for the talk of logic and lucrative global markets, the deal
may prove tough to consummate.
</P>
<P>
   Consultant Bob House of said that Qwest's top brass ought to be
enticed somehow into staying, perhaps through something less than
an acquisition, perhaps through granting them more independence.
``This is really not consistent with the way that Deutsche Telekom
thinks,'' House said. ``But unless they show some flexibility, they
stand the chance of losing management that makes Qwest a success.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
