<DOCNO> NYT20000302.0369 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-02 21:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5026 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w BC-CLINTON-GUNS-1STLD-WR     03-02 0812
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-GUNS-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON URGES CONGRESS TO BREAK LOGJAM ON GUN CONTROL 
</HEADLINE>
  (Adds Feinstein quote in 8th graf, Schumer comment and quotes in
12th and 13th grafs, deletes NRA spokesman's quote and adds
background on gun legislation offered last term in Congress in last
2 grafs of story) 
(jt) 
 By MARC LACEY and ERIC SCHMITT    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Responding to two high-profile incidents of gun
violence this week, President Clinton said Thursday that he would
invite legislative leaders to the White House next week to try to
``break the logjam'' on gun control legislation.
</P>
<P>
   But the prospect of Congress' approving a far-reaching gun
control bill remains bleak. Frustrated Senate Democrats vowed
Thursday to break off pieces of the legislation that has been tied
up since last summer and add them as amendments to other bills. In
the House, Speaker J. Dennis Hastert, R-Ill., called Democratic
leaders the obstructionist ones and suggested alternatives of his
own.
</P>
<P>
   The House and Senate approved different gun control bills after
contentious debates last year. But lawmakers in the two chambers
are deeply divided on the restrictions and have yet to reconcile
them in conference.
</P>
<P>
   In convening a session at the White House on Tuesday, Clinton
sought Thursday to bring the issue of gun control to the forefront
following heightened public concern after the shooting death of a
six-year-old girl in Michigan by a classmate, as well as a
Pennsylvania man's rampage that left two men dead and three others
wounded.
</P>
<P>
   ``These two incidents were very troubling, and they have
individual causes and explanations, and doubtless will require
individual responses,'' Clinton said. ``But they do remind us that
there is still too much danger in this country and that for more
than eight months now, Congress has been sitting on the
common-sense gun safety legislation.''
</P>
<P>
   The impasse over the legislation is becoming a powerful issue in
this election year and each sides blames the other for the delay.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats have explained lawmakers' inaction on gun control as
the result of a Congress held captive by the National Rifle
Association, especially the House.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's gotten so mired in politics that members are afraid of
their own shadows when it comes to these gun groups,'' said Sen.
Dianne Feinstein, a California Democrat who supports tougher
restrictions.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans accuse Democrats of refusing to compromise to have a
campaign issue to run on.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope the House Democratic leadership drops its
obstructionist tactics and agrees to work with us to pass
common-sense gun legislation,'' said Hastert, who suggested
legislation dealing with the prosecution of gun felonies, cracking
down on illegal drugs and addressing ``cultural problems which
encourage some of our youth to do evil things.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said that if a trigger lock had been installed on the
gun used by the Michigan boy, as the legislation in both chambers
calls for, the incident might not have happened. Child-safety
trigger locks are one part of the legislation with broad bipartisan
support. Other measures with wide backing include a ban on
large-capacity ammunition clips.
</P>
<P>
   But with legislation unlikely to move, Sen. Charles E. Schumer,
D-N.Y., said gun control supporters would seek to add gun
restrictions to unrelated bills in the next month.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't expect Republicans to be on board,'' Schumer said,
``but we'll take whatever steps we can.''
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, many Republicans rejected the Democrats' piecemeal
approach, and pressed House and Senate negotiators to break up the
impasse. ``I want a juvenile justice bill to be completed, and
that's the way we should do it,'' said Sen. Don Nickles of
Oklahoma, the assistant majority leader.
</P>
<P>
   The disagreements are not strictly partisan; a main opponent of
tighter gun restrictions is a Democrat, Rep. John D. Dingell of
Michigan.
</P>
<P>
   A compromise is not likely anytime soon, lawmakers in both
parties said. The popular gun control measures, as well as scores
of other measures intended to reduce youth crime, are imperiled
because of an impasse between House and Senate negotiators over
regulating gun shows.
</P>
<P>
   A provision that was endorsed by most Democrats and that was
approved by the Senate last May required all vendors at gun shows
to conduct mandatory background checks on customers and gave
vendors up to three days to perform those checks. Currently, only
licensed dealers must conduct background checks, while hobbyists
and collectors are exempt.
</P>
<P>
   The House bill technically has no gun show provisions, although
a majority of the House last year approved a measure that gave
dealers only 24 hours to conduct the checks. Since most gun shows
are held on weekends, critics said many checks would not be
completed in time.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
