<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-02 21:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5027 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-BUSH-CAMPAIGNER-2TAKE     03-02 0854
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-CAMPAIGNER-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
  
 BUSH SHOWS GROWING STRENGTH AS CAMPAIGNER IN BATTLE WITH McCAIN  
(sw) 
 By NICHOLAS D. KRISTOF   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   These days, Gov. George W. Bush shows roughly the same affection
for Sen. John McCain as he might for a particularly large and
repulsive cockroach. But if Bush becomes president in January, he
might want to use his White House stationery to send a thank you
note to McCain.
</P>
<P>
   For all the divisiveness that the Arizona senator has injected
into the Republican presidential primaries, and despite some harm
that he may have done to Bush's prospects in November, McCain has
helped Bush in one critical respect: he has made him a far better
campaigner.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of being frightened stiff by the McCain challenge, Bush
has been frightened loose. These days, as the Texas governor
barnstorms through Georgia, Ohio and other states that vote in the
March 7 Super Tuesday primaries, he comes across as a more relaxed,
more energetic and less scripted campaigner than he was just a
month ago, and his audiences are responding.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm completely mesmerized,'' said Gay Hartman, a mortgage
banker in Seattle who had just heard Bush speak in a crowded high
school gymnasium. Halfway across the country, in Cincinnati, after
a thunderous Bush rally that virtually had the ambience of a rock
concert, a nurse, Rose Anne Bertram, still had confetti in her hair
as she raved about Bush's speech, exclaiming, ``He seemed so down
to earth _ not at all like an Ivy Leaguer!''
</P>
<P>
   Yet, as a presidential candidate Bush still seems a bit quirky,
a work in progress, far more adept at dealing with voters than with
policies. He appears congenial, witty and charming, tremendously
capable of energizing audiences and glad-handing voters, yet weak
on policy details and foreign affairs and often wary of taking
strong stands.
</P>
<P>
   Surprisingly, he also appears squeamish about political
rough-housing. Unlike either McCain or Vice President Al Gore, who
seem to relish a brawl, Bush comes across as thin-skinned and
uncomfortable with the politics of insult _ and not very good at
it.
</P>
<P>
   When McCain used the slur ``gooks'' to refer to his North
Vietnamese guards when he was a prisoner of war (McCain later
apologized), Bush had a perfect opportunity to criticize his
opponent. But when the issue arose at Bush's daily press
conference, this was the exchange:
</P>
<P>
   Q. ``Is that appropriate language for someone running for
president?''
</P>
<P>
   A. ``That is going to have to be up to the people. You know,
it's amazing. I haven't seen that in the press yet. I appreciate
you bringing that up.''
</P>
<P>
   Q. (inaudible)
</P>
<P>
   A. ``I better not say anything about it, lest I be accused of
negative campaigning.''
</P>
<P>
   Q. ``Do you have an obligation as a leader to take a stand on
that kind of language?''
</P>
<P>
   A. ``He has an obligation as a potential leader to explain what
he meant.''
</P>
<P>
   Searching for news, the press corps daily lobs gentle pitches to
Bush in search of some condemnation that sounds like news. Bush
gamely swings at each lob, but he often takes a few tries before he
manages a hit worthy of the evening news.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, a television reporter asked Bush if he thought
McCain should apologize for a phone campaign that Bush says
portrays him as ``an anti-Catholic bigot.'' Bush answered awkwardly
without using the word ``apology,'' so the reporter tried again.
And again. The third time, Bush finally said, yes, McCain should
apologize. And MSNBC reported this with an on-screen headline,
``Bush demands apology.''
</P>
<P>
   While Bush has tacked right and left in his campaign to
outmaneuver his rivals, it is striking how little he panders to
audiences. Speaking to workers who worry about imports, he warmly
recounts the benefits of free trade. Addressing wealthy Republicans
decked out in pearls, he speaks sympathetically about Mexican
immigrants and asserts that a single mother has ``the hardest job
in America.''
</P>
<P>
   Before lily-white audiences that might favor English as the
nation's official language, Bush occasionally drops a phrase in
Spanish. The audiences stare back in puzzled silence.
</P>
<P>
   In some ways Bush comes across as the opposite of his father,
President George Bush, a cerebral, worldly man of great experience
who knew everything except how to be folksy. The younger Bush once
confessed that his greatest weakness is his lack of interest in
long books, especially those about policy, and that the only
statistics he seems to know involve baseball.
</P>
<P>
   The exception is education policy, on which the governor speaks
with passion and confidence. In other areas he is being
home-schooled by experts, engaging in at least one conference call
a week with his foreign policy advisers and plowing through
briefing papers on major issues in states he will be visiting.
</P>
<P>
   Bush also regularly reads The New York Times and two Texas
newspapers, plus clippings that his staff assemble from other
newspapers. But the contrast with Gore, who can recite statistics
about programs that Bush has probably barely heard of, is huge.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, Bush is a natural politician _ far more so
than the vice president _ with a down-home, one-of-the-guys charm
that puts people at ease. He loves the crowds, relishes the
limelight and invariably comes across to audiences as likable,
funny, sincere and decent.
</P>
<P>
   ``On TV, he used to come across as kind of stern,'' said Ken
DeWeber, a retired insurance agent who attended a Bush rally in
Pasco, Wash. ``But here he came across as the kind of guy you'd sit
on the river bank fishing with.''
</P>
<P>
   Before his loss to McCain in the New Hampshire primary, Bush
sometimes came across as cocky, lightweight and over-rehearsed.
Presidential campaigns are all a kind of theater, carefully
produced and directed in a frantic effort to seem as if they are
not, but Bush's appearances were particularly stage-managed, and
voters chafed at that.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, McCain's success has led Bush to redefine his
campaign themes _ sometimes appropriating McCain's, so that the
blue banner Bush now speaks in front of repeats the word
``reformer'' 43 times.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Jennifer Dunn of Washington state, who is co-chairwoman of
Bush's campaign in that state, said the primary battle was
ultimately helping Bush.
</P>
<P>
   ''All this has a good bottom line,'' Dunn said. ``He's much
crisper and much better schooled on all the issues he's asked
about. This primary scuffle is good for him.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush speaks without notes and often without much of a point,
telling audiences a bit about himself and his family in a folksy
way and raising a few issues like education, taxes and national
security. More than Gore, he knows how to be brief.
</P>
<P>
   After a rally in Ohio, a salesman named Bill Bertram said he
liked Bush's speech very much. Why? ``It was pretty short,''
Bertram replied enthusiastically. ``He just gave us the
highlights.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush's early appearances were complicated by what his friends
described as a smile but what others saw as a smirk. Since then,
the smirk seems to have been surgically removed.
</P>
<P>
   These days he frowns, smiles, laughs and even scowls, but he
does not normally smirk _ although occasionally he forgets himself
when he is in a good mood and it creeps back, only to be replaced
by a frown as soon as he notices it.
</P>
<P>
   Stung by journalists' praise for McCain as an accessible
candidate and envious of McCain's good relations with the news
media, Bush has begun his own charm offensive. Although he
sometimes gives the impression that he would prefer to pitch the
national press out of his campaign plane at 30,000 feet, he now
regularly puts on a smile _ not a smirk _ and comes to the back of
the plane to chat with journalists in an effort to win their hearts
and minds.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it is fair to say that thanks to a contested
nomination,'' said Ari Fleischer, an aide to Bush, ``the governor
is going to be much stronger running against Al Gore in November.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-02-00 2104EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000302.0372 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-02 21:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5029 &Cx1f; tab-z
r k BC-ALLENDE-ON-PINOCHET-N     03-02 1585
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ALLENDE-ON-PINOCHET-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PINOCHET WITHOUT HATRED 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (We are re-releasing this article due to its timeliness. A
longer version previously moved to clients of the Centerpiece
package. To publish it as a ``separate buy,'' it must be purchased
_ the rate is not prohibitive _ from one of these New York Times
Syndicate sales representatives: 
 &HT;    (--U.S. and Canada: DEBRA WEYDERT in New Jersey at
1-732-390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697. 
 &HT;    (--Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942. 
 &HT;    (--Latin America: ANA PENA in New York, 310-798-0970; fax,
310-798-7338.) 
 &HT;    
 By ISABEL ALLENDE  
 FROM: The New York Times Magazine  
 c.2000 Isabel Allende  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   Many years ago, I was asked whether I planned someday to write a
novel about Pinochet. No, I said, because as a character he was
insignificant.
</P>
<P>
   I need to retract that statement: One can say anything about him
except that he is insignificant. Pinochet held Chile in his grip
for 25 years. A decade after he stepped down from the presidency,
the old dictator still held the democratic government hostage.
</P>
<P>
   But by now, even if Pinochet never faces a tribunal, justice has
been done. By pursuing the general, assembling a strong legal case
and issuing the request for his extradition to Spain, the Spanish
magistrate, Baltasar Garzon, achieved the salutary result of
Pinochet's moral ruin. A man who had the gall to pose as his
nation's savior will now take his place alongside Caligula and Idi
Amin.
</P>
<P>
   Before 1973, no one could have imagined a dictatorship in Chile,
a nation so proud of its democratic institutions that we Chileans
called ourselves ``the English'' of our continent. How, then, did
this soldier, never characterized by intelligence, culture or
courage, come to hold absolute power?
</P>
<P>
   Just as at a critical moment Adolf Hitler embodied the
frustrations and aspirations of millions of Germans, Pinochet led
Chile along a path that many wanted. Neither Hitler nor Pinochet
could have existed without the tacit or explicit consent of
millions of citizens.
</P>
<P>
   Pinochet has long stood as a symbol of brutality for the simple
reason that he was and always will be linked to Salvador Allende,
an icon of social justice in the early 1970s. Allende was the first
Marxist politician in the world to win the presidency of a country
in a free election.
</P>
<P>
   Allende was my father's cousin; in a Latin family, that made him
my uncle. I knew him well and loved him with a mixture of
admiration and anxiety. Although he was a kind man with a good
sense of humor, I always felt it was impossible to live up to his
standards and expectations.
</P>
<P>
   Trained as a physician, he was well acquainted with the needs of
the poor. He was a founder of the Socialist Party, and was
appointed secretary of health at a young age.
</P>
<P>
   In 1970, after three failed attempts, Allende finally won the
presidency of Chile in a sharply divided election. He was a
minority president, having received only 36 percent of the vote.
</P>
<P>
   But that wasn't his biggest problem. Immediately after the
election results were in, the CIA and the Chilean right began a
campaign of terror to prevent him from assuming his post as
president.
</P>
<P>
   On Sept. 11, the military coup took place that would leave a
profound mark on Chile's soul.
</P>
<P>
   That morning I had left my home early. The streets were
practically empty, but I saw military vehicles, tanks and groups of
heavily armed soldiers. I didn't have a radio and went to the house
of a friend nearby to listen to the news.
</P>
<P>
   She was very distressed. Her husband, a teacher, had gone to the
school where he taught and she had not heard from him. By then all
the radio stations, except one, had been silenced by the military.
</P>
<P>
   On the way downtown to pick up her husband, I witnessed the
bombing of La Moneda palace. I heard Allende's last words on my
friend's portable radio. She and I held hands crying as my uncle
calmly addressed the country with a historic speech that later
would be broadcast and published all over the world.
</P>
<P>
   Having declared that he would never resign his office, he
refused to flee the country in a plane offered by the generals. It
was the right choice _ and not only because his heroic death
confirmed his place in history.
</P>
<P>
   Had he accepted their offer to go into exile, we now know,
Pinochet would have murdered him during the flight. Instead,
Allende took his own life in the burning presidential palace.
</P>
<P>
   Until just before the coup, Pinochet was an obscure Chilean army
general. He had been elevated to the rank of commander in chief of
the armed forces by Allende himself only three weeks before.
Pinochet had been recommended to Allende as a loyal soldier who
could be trusted to uphold the Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   The military junta Pinochet would soon command abolished the
Chilean Congress, muzzled the press, suspended constitutional
guarantees and began the systematic elimination of the left. The
right toasted with Champagne while leftists ran for their lives and
the rest of the population was dumbfounded.
</P>
<P>
   Pinochet persecuted labor and student leaders, politicians,
intellectuals, artists and journalists, as well as all those who
were a part of the Allende government. The worst repression was
carried out against the lower classes, long viewed by the military
as a prime breeding ground for Marxism.
</P>
<P>
   Thousands of Chileans were arrested. Others found asylum in
embassies or escaped across the border, while many simply
disappeared. Torture centers and concentration camps were set up
throughout the country. Hundreds of prisoners were thrown from
planes into the sea _ after their bellies were slit open to make
sure that they would sink _ or blown to bits or plowed under by
bulldozers. Fear became a way of life.
</P>
<P>
   Voices of protest were raised in most of the world, because the
socialist experiment of Allende had aroused great sympathy, but
Washington supported the dictatorship of Pinochet.
</P>
<P>
   The general changed Chile's Constitution to designate himself
president. In early photographs he is wearing dark glasses, his
arms folded across his chest and his jaw thrust forward in a
caricature of the Latin American dictator. Later he modified his
image, wearing impeccable suits and shedding the sinister dark
glasses.
</P>
<P>
   There is even a Pinochet Foundation, dedicated to assuring his
place in history as the Chilean Napoleon who ``saved the country
from communism,'' a task that some ``pinochetistas'' claim was
assigned to him directly by God.
</P>
<P>
   Pinochet is characterized by his cunning. (When a mass grave was
discovered with two bodies in each coffin, he said it was a good
way of saving nails.) He surrounded himself with the most
intelligent ideologues of the right. He transformed the economy of
Chile, moving from social democracy to the capitalism of Milton
Friedman, but with little of the freedom promised by the Chicago
School.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to Pinochet, entrepreneurs and investors were in
paradise. They enjoyed the benefits of the free market but did not
have to deal with unions; workers were plentiful, cheap and
submissive. The state still intervened in the economy, but always
in favor of the capitalists. Greed became the new religion. Almost
everything was privatized, even hospitals and public schools.
</P>
<P>
   Taken together, this created an economic boom and the basis for
sustained progress, which is the main argument of those who defend
Pinochet. But they can't disregard the social costs.
</P>
<P>
   Pinochet's savage capitalist revolution came out of the hides of
the poor, who were supposed to be satisfied with the crumbs
trickling down from the wealthy. For the poorest of the poor, the
trickle-down never did occur. A third of Chile's 15 million
inhabitants still live in poverty.
</P>
<P>
   Pinochet's supporters explain the torture, assassinations and
disappearances during his regime as a necessary evil in preventing
a civil war in 1973. That is preposterous. He remained as commander
in chief of the armed forces until 1998, when he had himself
declared senator for life. A law of amnesty granted him impunity
for all crimes committed during his tenure.
</P>
<P>
   I feel no hatred for Pinochet. Hatred is a very heavy burden,
one I shook off many years ago, when I started writing. Writing has
allowed me to exorcise most of my demons and transform my pain into
strength. I would like to see Pinochet face a trial, so that the
truth about his crimes is fully exposed.
</P>
<P>
   But I wouldn't want the general to rot in prison, as so many of
his victims did. He has already suffered an undeniable defeat that
nothing can turn into victory. Even without a trial, in the eyes of
the world he is an alleged criminal, and moral censure can be worse
than prison.
</P>
<P>
   I merely wish that in the winter of his life the general would
ask forgiveness of all those whose lives he destroyed, the families
of the dead and disappeared, the exiled and tortured; that he would
reveal where the bodies of his victims can be found.
</P>
<P>
   Only then, with the recognition of past errors, will a true
reconciliation among Chileans begin.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; c.2000 Isabel Allende &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Isabel Allende is the author of ``The House of the Spirits''
and numerous other novels.) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   _______
</P>
