<HEADER>
A5032 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-MOZAMBIQUE-U.S.-ART-N     03-02 0450
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOZAMBIQUE-U.S.-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. SENDS EMERGENCY WORKERS AND SUPPLIES TO MOZAMBIQUE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Germany ,  South Africa )  (ART ADV: A map is being sent. Nonsubscribers can purchase by
calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The United States began sending search-and-rescue
teams and additional emergency supplies to Mozambique Thursday to
help deal with ravages caused by weeks of severe flooding in
southern Africa.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. aid is expected to include about 500 people, five MH-53
cargo helicopters and five C-130 transport planes, according to
Capt. Bob Pritchard, a spokesman for the U.S. European Command in
Stuttgart, Germany.
</P>
<P>
   Ten military specialists from Europe are en route to Mozambique
to join a dozen others already there to determine the requirements
of the mission and the best way to carry it out, Pritchard said.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton said in a statement, ``All Americans have been
deeply moved by the tragic events in southern Africa,'' and he
applauded the governments in the region for working together to
address the situation.
</P>
<P>
   The United States had already pledged $12.8 million for the
flood relief effort, including money for a special 14-member team
from the Miami-Dade Fire and Rescue Department to travel to
Mozambique. The team will be taking three inflatable rescue boats
and three small trucks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our primary mission will be rescuing people from the high
areas and taking them to the shelters,'' said Lt. Louie Fernandez,
a rescue team spokesman in Miami.
</P>
<P>
   The MH-53 helicopters, which can carry about 38 people and have
infrared systems for operating at night, are suited for search and
rescue, said Pentagon spokesman Kenneth Bacon.
</P>
<P>
   The C-130 aircraft will be responsible for the in-flight
refueling of the helicopters, enabling them to travel much greater
distances, Bacon said. Most of the flood zone can be reached only
by helicopter.
</P>
<P>
   About 2,400 blankets, 6,000 water cans and 160 rolls of plastic
sheeting to build emergency shelters have already been flown into
Mozambique by a U.S. C-17 aircraft. Those supplies, provided by the
U.S. Agency for International Development agency, were to be
distributed by the United Nations, the government of Mozambique and
the South African military.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. aid package also consists of $7 million in food, as
well as sandbags, shovels and wheelbarrows.
</P>
<P>
   The crisis is the result of several weeks of torrential rains
and floods that have killed more than 150 people in Mozambique,
South Africa, Zimbabwe, Swaziland and Botswana. Relief agencies
estimate that more than 1 million people have lost their homes or
livelihoods.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
