<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HACKER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
N.H. YOUTH ARRESTED IN ALLEGED WEB HACKING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROSS KERBER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Authorities raided the home of a Wolfeboro, N.H., youth who they
said admitted to intrusions on several Web sites in recent months
including one operated by RSA Security of Inc.
</P>
<P>
   The raid was disclosed Thursday by the Los Angeles Police
Department, which said officers entered the home several weeks ago
as part of an investigation following attacks on a Web site
operated by the anti-drug organization DARE America in Inglewood,
Calif.
</P>
<P>
   A Los Angeles police spokesman said officers had arrested a
17-year-old male during the raid and that he had admitted to
defacing sites operated by DARE and a military organization, and to
interrupting service to a site operated by RSA.
</P>
<P>
   But federal law enforcement officials later said there had been
no arrests in connection with the incident, and the Los Angeles
police said they planned to issue a revised statement this morning.
They declined further comment.
</P>
<P>
   Federal authorities also indicated that the youth, who used the
online screen name of ``coolio,'' was not considered a prime
suspect in an ongoing investigation of attacks on major
electronic-commerce companies last month.
</P>
<P>
   In those attacks, major sites _ including those operated by
Yahoo Inc., ETrade Inc. and Amazon.com _ were knocked off-line for
hours after receiving a string of messages simultaneously from
thousands of other computers via the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Federal officials are looking into the incidents but have made
no arrests so far. Los Angeles police said the FBI's field office
there assisted in its investigation of coolio, but FBI spokeswoman
Laura Bosley also said the New Hampshire youth didn't appear
connected to the broader attacks on e-commerce companies. ``We do
not anticipate filing any federal charges against this
individual,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   She and other officials, who declined to name the youth, would
not say if he would face any other charges.
</P>
<P>
   He was sought after DARE filed a complaint in November after its
antidrug Web site was twice defaced with pornographic images and
text supporting the legalization of certain drugs. In Bedford,
Mass., RSA also complained that traffic to its own Web site was
being diverted for a period last month to a ``spoof'' site that
parodied the company's statements.
</P>
<P>
   The Wolfeboro police referred questions to the FBI and to Paul
Gagnon, US attorney in New Hampshire, whose office didn't return
calls seeking comment.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-02-00 2108EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000302.0377 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-02 21:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5034 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w BC-PATIENT-RIGHTS-NYT &LR;      03-02 0908
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PATIENT-RIGHTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BIPARTISAN AGREEMENT ON PATIENTS RIGHTS COULD BE REACHED BY
EASTER  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Okla., Mich., Ga., Pa.)   By ROBERT PEAR   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Negotiators from the House and the Senate, meeting
for the first time, said Thursday that they were optimistic about
their chances of cutting a deal on legislation that would establish
a wide range of new rights for patients and new duties for health
insurance companies.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton urged members of the conference committee to
reach a bipartisan agreement. Sen. Don Nickles of Oklahoma, the
assistant Republican leader, said he hoped to do just that by the
end of this month.
</P>
<P>
   The effort to define patients' rights is already a hot political
issue, and will become hotter as this fall's elections approach. In
their meeting Thursday, Republicans and Democrats alike stressed
the areas of potential agreement, as if to defy skeptics who have
for months been predicting a stalemate.
</P>
<P>
   Moments after being elected chairman of the conference
committee, Nickles said, ``My objective is to complete this
conference this month and have a bill passed by both houses of
Congress by Easter. We have a much better chance of passing good
legislation that's not so partisan, not so political, if we work
sooner rather than later.''
</P>
<P>
   In a pep rally Thursday at the White House, with a handful of
Republican members of Congress, Clinton said opinion polls showed
that ``well over 70 percent of all Americans, without regard to
their political party, support a strong, enforceable patient's bill
of rights.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said that the House bill, drafted by Reps. Charlie
Norwood, a Georgia Republican, and John D. Dingell, a Michigan
Democrat, was his benchmark for acceptable legislation.
</P>
<P>
   The House passed the Norwood-Dingell bill by a vote of 275 to
151 on Oct. 7, as 68 Republicans defied their party leaders and
supported it. The Senate passed its version, which provides
protection to fewer people, on July 15 by a vote of 53-47. All 45
Democratic senators voted against that version of the legislation,
saying it was largely a sham because many of its protections would
apply to fewer than one-third of the 161 million people covered by
the House bill.
</P>
<P>
   Norwood, a dentist, is not a member of the conference committee.
He stood in a corner, watching the committee as it met. He said he
believed a ``reasonable compromise'' could be achieved.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats said they felt they were in a strong negotiating
position, because the House bill, unlike the Senate bill, had
bipartisan support. Moreover, Democratic conferees said they were
pleased that Republicans were now talking to them about the
substance of the legislation. In the last five years, many
important bills have been written behind closed doors by
Republicans, with a minimal role for Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   After Thursday's session, an aide to a Democratic member of
Congress said, ``This has the feel of a real conference, such as we
haven't had around here in a long time.''
</P>
<P>
   The conferees appear to have devised an ingenious way of
proceeding. First, they will seek agreement on the substance of
proposed new rights for patients. Then they will discuss the more
difficult questions of who should have those rights _ the ``scope''
of the bill _ and how the rights should be enforced.
</P>
<P>
   Nickles said the conferees were ``very close to agreement'' on
guaranteeing coverage for emergency medical care and allowing
patients to visit pediatricians, obstetricians and gynecologists
without getting a referral from another doctor.
</P>
<P>
   Nickles said the House and Senate bills were also similar in
that they would guarantee timely access to certain specialists;
allow doctors to discuss all treatment options with patients; allow
patients to continue receiving care from a doctor dropped from
their health plan; and give cancer patients greater access to
clinical trials of promising new treatments.
</P>
<P>
   However, Sen. Edward M. Kennedy, D-Mass., said the protections
provided by the Senate bill were, in nearly all cases, weaker than
the comparable provisions of the House bill, which he strongly
prefers. ``The Senate bill excludes more than two-thirds of
privately insured Americans from most of its protections, and it
leaves out almost every citizen who belongs to a health maintenance
organization,'' Kennedy said.
</P>
<P>
   The House bill, unlike the Senate bill, would expand the right
of patients to sue HMOs and other health plans for injuries caused
by the delay or denial of care. Democrats see such a provision as
essential, and in recent weeks, Republican leaders of the House and
the Senate have expressed a new willingness to consider the idea,
as a way to make health insurers more accountable.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Arlen Specter, R-Pa., who was at the White House on
Thursday, said the question of liability was ``the key point'' that
must be resolved. ``It's very unpopular to advocate letting people
go to court, but you have to do that,'' he said in an interview.
</P>
<P>
   The House and Senate bills would both require HMOs to establish
appeal procedures, so patients could appeal the denial of benefits
to an independent panel of medical experts.
</P>
<P>
   Senate Republicans said they had limited the scope of their bill
because they did not want to usurp the states' authority to
regulate health insurance. In general, they said, states have done
a good job of regulating.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-02-00 2110EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
