<DOCNO> NYT20000302.0378 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-02 21:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5035 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-AETNA-ART-NYT &LR;      03-02 0603
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AETNA-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RIVAL BIDS FOR AETNA UNLIKELY, ANALYSTS SAY 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By MILT FREUDENHEIM   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Investors bought up shares of Aetna Inc. again Thursday, but the
buying spree slowed as it became apparent that rival bidders were
unlikely to emerge to a $9.9 billion purchase offer Aetna announced
this week.
</P>
<P>
   Aetna said it had received the purchase offer from ING America
Insurance Holdings, a financial services company, and WellPoint
Health Networks, a California-based national managed care company.
</P>
<P>
   Wall Street analysts said the bid of about $44 a share in cash
and $26 a share in WellPoint stock was not supposed to leak to the
public and posed considerable risk for Aetna shareholders.
</P>
<P>
   Unless there are other bidders, Aetna will have to choose
between negotiations with WellPoint and ING, a unit of ING Group,
and trying to solve its formidable problems internally.
</P>
<P>
   ``All WellPoint wants is an opportunity to look,'' said Todd
Richter, an analyst at Banc of America Securities. ``If Aetna's
business looks worse than they expected, and they decide to back
off from the price, it could be devastating for Aetna
shareholders.''
</P>
<P>
   WellPoint has grown through careful acquisitions of businesses
like the health care units of Massachusetts Mutual and John Hancock
life insurance companies. Usually WellPoint negotiates prices that
analysts say are on the low side.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of Aetna rose $2.8125, or 5.3 percent, to $55.8125
Thursday. Earlier, the stock peaked at $61.875 _ briefly a 50
percent gain in two days. WellPoint, which dropped $5.625 on
Tuesday, fell Thursday by $1.125, to $60.75.
</P>
<P>
   William McKeever, an analyst at PaineWebber Securities, said
there was only a remote chance that another bidder would emerge.
The other big, financially solid health insurance companies, United
Healthcare and Cigna, do not seem interested.
</P>
<P>
   Cigna has shown little interest in big acquisitions, and a
merger with Aetna would immediately raise antitrust issues, Richter
added. And United has been investing in lines of business that do
not entail taking the risk for delivering care at an agreed price
as health maintenance organizations do.
</P>
<P>
   More than a third of the 21 million people covered by Aetna are
in HMOs. Most of the rest have access to physician and hospital
discount networks that are paid on a fee-for-service basis, or else
they have traditional insurance with few restrictions.
</P>
<P>
   WellPoint, a medium-size insurer with 7.3 million subscribers,
has also emphasized these less risky networks. WellPoint's strategy
is ``giving consumers what they want: choice in the selection of
their health plans,'' Leonard Schaeffer, chief executive of
WellPoint, said last month.
</P>
<P>
   Schaeffer, who made his reputation by turning around Blue Cross
of California when it had heavy losses, ``really understands how
the business operates,'' said Helen Darling, a managed care expert
at the Watson Wyatt consulting firm.
</P>
<P>
   More than three years after its purchase of U.S. Healthcare,
Aetna still has not fully integrated that unit with its other
health-care lines, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ING, a worldwide financial services and insurance company based
in Amsterdam, the Netherlands, has said it was ready to spend
heavily to increase its presence in the United States. As outlined
in the offer, it would take Aetna's profitable pension and group
life insurance units, and WellPoint would get the health care
units.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-02-00 2110EST &QL; 
