<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-02 21:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5040 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-HMO-BAILOUT-BOS &LR;      03-02 1127
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HMO-BAILOUT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HMO'S WOES EASING, REGULATORS TAKE HANDS-OFF APPROACH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LIZ KOWALCZYK AND RICHARD A. KNOX  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Rejecting all proposals from outside investors because
they came with too many strings attatched, state regulators said
they will rely on clever accounting and faith to keep Harvard
Pilgrim Health Care an independent nonprofit organization.
</P>
<P>
   Just two months after forcing the state's largest HMO into state
receivership and touching off a regional healthcare crisis,
Attorney General Thomas F. Reilly said Thursday that the Harvard
Pilgrim's financial condition had improved dramatically in January
and February, infusing the HMO with $200 million in available cash.
</P>
<P>
   The unexpected turnaround, coupled with the fact that potential
investors and buyers were demanding unappetizing conditions,
convinced regulators that Harvard Pilgrim is a ``going concern''
that can continue to operate without new cash, a taxpayer bailout,
or court oversight, Reilly said.
</P>
<P>
   Reilly and Insurance Commissioner Linda Ruthardt next week will
ask the Supreme Judicial Court to take the HMO out of receivership
and approve a long-term rehabilitation plan.
</P>
<P>
   A key component of the rehabilitation plan are a pair of
accounting maneuvers that, if approved after a public hearing, will
allow receivers to instantly increase Harvard Pilgrim's net worth
from a negative $88 million to $178 million in the black.
</P>
<P>
   They will do this by bringing up to market value the plan's 14
health centers, much the way homeowners reassess their property,
and by subordinating the HMO's bond debt _ in other words taking it
off the books as a liability. A new law passed by the legislature
in November gives HMO receivers the power to restructure debt in
this way.
</P>
<P>
   Reilly said they are working out other details of the plan, but
that he and Ruthardt would continue to monitor Harvard Pilgrim's
operations under a more lenient term than receivership called ``
``administrative order.''
</P>
<P>
   The sudden confidence on Harvard Pilgrim's future prompted some
to ask whether receivership was every necessary or was brought on
by panic. Reilly said without the receivership, Harvard Pilgrim
would not have been able to ward off creditors, stop hospitals and
doctors from breaking contracts and regulators could not have
subordinated the debt.
</P>
<P>
   Reilly announced the unexpected plan, which he said
``crystallized'' for him over the weekend, in a private meeting
with hospital executives, patient representatives and officials
from the managed care industry; he then released details in a press
conference called by Governor Paul Cellucci, who has faced
criticism for not taking a public role in guiding the state through
the Harvard Pilgrim crisis.
</P>
<P>
   ``The turnaround plan is working; Harvard Pilgrim's financial
situation is turning around,'' said Cellucci, who partly credited
loyal subscribers. ``I can't emphasize enough how important it was
that people did not panic. This will take Harvard Pilgrim off the
critical list.``
</P>
<P>
   After the announcement, it was difficult to find even one critic
of Reilly's new plan, which at least for now will save Harvard
Pilgrim and its 1.1 million members from the disruption caused by
liquidation or purchase by a large out-of-state insurance company.
</P>
<P>
   But the crucial test will come in April, when the next wave of
Massachusetts employers will decide whether to stick by Harvard
Pilgrim or switch their employees to other health plans.
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether employers will remain faithful to the state's
largest HMO, Rick Lord of the Associated Industries of
Massachusetts, said ``I think so, yeah, I do.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt comfortable with the explanation I heard,'' said Lord,
who represents a trade group of manufacturers. ``In January and
February HP was actually making money. That's a very positive
signal that this is a viable entity going forward. There's a sense
of relief out there among the employers I talked to.''
</P>
<P>
   Reilly said that the other options were just too worrisome.
</P>
<P>
   Hospitals had considered lending Harvard Pilgrim money through a
mechanism called ``surplus notes'' but regulators feared that
option would unduly burden hospitals, many of which are already
losing money. Hospitals also demanded that the state guarantee the
loans in case Harvard Pilgrim ultimately failed, a precedent that
Reilly called bad public policy.
</P>
<P>
   Harvard University also insisted that the state guarantee its
investment in the HMO and rejected a request by regulators to
itself guarantee investments made by other parties.
</P>
<P>
   ``Harvard was adamant, they were not going to participate
without state guarantees,'' he said. ``Well, that's a deal-breaker,
we weren't going to give it to them...End of story.''
</P>
<P>
   Reilly complimented Ross Perot, owner of Perot Systems, the
company that is rebuilding Harvard Pilgrim's computer system, who
agreed to lend Harvard $75 million without a state guarantee.
</P>
<P>
   Reilly said that several for-profit companies showed
considerable interest, but that he feared those companies would
hurt small hospitals and doctors' groups by slashing rates and that
they would not honor debt owed by Harvard to bond holders.
</P>
<P>
   He said he also had a legal requirement to tell the court that
there was no viable nonprofit option before selling Harvard Pilgrim
to a stock-based company.
</P>
<P>
   While negotiations with the hospitals, Harvard University and
Perot were going on, ``we got better information on (Harvard
Pilgrim's) performance and more lengthy information on the cash
status and we realized, `Wait a minute, we don't have to cave in
and we don't have to give away the store. We have another option
presenting itself.'
</P>
<P>
   He said that the team of regulators and advisors had been
thinking about giving Harvard Pilgrim more time to recover, when
two professors from Harvard School of Public Health and Boston
University School of Public Health suggested that approach at an
advisory committee meeting last Friday. Reilly said ``we needed
hard data and analysis and we got that (Thursday).''
</P>
<P>
   The analysis revealed that Harvard Pilgrim is paying bills to
hospitals and doctors, that it has set aside $200 million in cash
since Jan. 1 because it raised premiums and closed down
money-losing operations in Rhode Island, and that it has paid $200
million in pre-receivership debt to hospitals.
</P>
<P>
   He predicts Harvard Pilgrim will be profitable next year.
</P>
<P>
   Reilly said he does not know when regulators will lift the
administrative order. ``It certainly would not be lifted until HPHC
is fully restored to financial health,'' he said. ``That would
include profitability and financial reserves.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
