<HEADER>
A5045 &Cx1f; tab-z
r k BC-PINOCHET-ETHICS-CASE-     03-02 0889
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PINOCHET-ETHICS-CASE-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHAT WE CAN THANK PINOCHET FOR 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (Because of its timeliness, we are re-releasing this article.
To publish it as a ``separate buy,'' please contact one of these
New York Times Syndicate sales representatives: 
 &HT;    (--U.S., Canada and the Pacific: CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at
1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448, or fax her at 816-822-1444. 
 &HT;    (--Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942. 
 &HT;    (--Latin America: ANA PENA in New York, 310-996-0075; fax,
310-996-0089. 
 &HT;    
 By JORGE G. CASTANEDA  
 c.2000 New York Times Special Features  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The arrest and detention of Augusto Pinochet served a purpose,
far beyond warming the hearts of the thousands of friends,
relatives and colleagues of his victims _ men and women who had
waited nearly a quarter of a century for justice and solace.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond its ethical and legal implications, the dictator's
detention revealed many of the contradictions and deeper truths
about how societies move from authoritarian to democratic rule, and
how they settle scores with a past that never should have existed.
</P>
<P>
   Both in general and in specific reference to Chile, Pinochet's
predicament raised far more questions than answers _ questions that
years ago should have been asked in Chile and Latin America, and in
countries as dissimilar as Mexico and South Africa.
</P>
<P>
   The so-called transitions to democracy in Latin America during
the 1980s, in eastern Europe in the late '80s and early '90s, as
well as in Asia and Africa, all rested on a few basic premises that
at the time seemed self-evident.
</P>
<P>
   Dictatorships do not just fade away; military rulers do not
simply walk into the sun when they get bored or tired. Achieving
their departure and the overall dismantling of their regimes, as of
one-party systems, implied providing them with a way out: a safe
departure, to a safe haven, for a safe future.
</P>
<P>
   On some occasions, the political golden handshake of amnesty or
tacitly letting bygones be bygones was accompanied by a desire to
know, if not to punish. Truth Commissions, Never Again Commissions,
White Books and the like were created and supported.
</P>
<P>
   But the understanding always was that the personal safety and
financial integrity of the dictators remain protected and that
details of their policies _ economic in some cases, geopolitical in
others _ be preserved by their democratic successors.
</P>
<P>
   This was the deal in Chile, in Argentina, in Uruguay, in a
certain sense initially in Nicaragua, in South Korea, South Africa
and even in some places in eastern Europe. It was formal and
institutionalized in some cases, de facto in others, but it made
democracy possible. It seemed a small price to pay, a pill not too
bitter to swallow, a necessary and sufficient condition for moving
on.
</P>
<P>
   But too many questions simply went unanswered. Who made the
deals? With whom did the political leaders consult? How freely did
the leaders and the led consent to the agreements and how well
informed were the countries' citizens?
</P>
<P>
   Would the arrangements withstand international and historical
scrutiny, particularly of a passionate and critical nature? Would
the amnesties resist the test of time, further investigations and
new revelations?
</P>
<P>
   In Chile and elsewhere, many had believed, sincerely, that the
best solution was to bury the past, to leave the dead where they
were and the fat bank accounts unexposed _ and move forward. Others
felt that some degree of accountability and punishment was
indispensable to ensure that impunity cease being a leitmotif of
routine political life.
</P>
<P>
   But who really knows the cost of either option: whether
forgiving and forgetting is possible, or if burrowing into the past
is unavoidable.
</P>
<P>
   For a decade, the conventional wisdom about Chile was simple. At
last, moderation and sensibility had prevailed, national
reconciliation had been achieved, successful economic policies had
been pursued. The past decades of revolutionary turmoil and bloody
repression had come to an end.
</P>
<P>
   Today we know that while Chile is a more prosperous nation than
before, it is as unequal in wealth and income distribution as ever,
and the polarization of its society is as acute as 30 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   For the country's left, and center, and sympathizers and allies,
as well as for much of international public opinion, Pinochet is
the personification of evil: The man with the dark glasses is as
bad as they come. Yet for a large minority of the population, he
remains the saviour of a nation threatened by heathen communism and
inflationary socialism.
</P>
<P>
   It is probably preferable for Chileans to have uncovered this
split of opinion, and for the rest of the world to grasp that
dealing with the past is a very complicated matter, and that easy
solutions, as brisk and painless as they may seem, generally do not
work.
</P>
<P>
   We can thank the dictator for this, but for nothing else.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Jorge G. Castaneda, Latin America's leading political
scientist, is the author of the best-selling ``Companero: The Life
and Death of Che Guevara.'' Castaneda lives in New York and Mexico
City and teaches at New York University.) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ------------------- &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
