<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000302.0385 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-02 21:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5046 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-BBN-ROCKER-MAIN03-COX     03-02 0777
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-ROCKER-MAIN03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A day of healing for Rocker
 &HT;    By Carroll Rogers
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   KISSIMMEE, Fla. _ John Rocker's locker was back where it's been
the past two years in the Braves clubhouse at Disney, beside that
of fellow reliever Rudy Seanez. Rocker played a little long toss in
the outfield, threw a side session in the bullpen, then worked out
in the weight room afterward.
</P>
<P>
   But his day was anything but usual.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves' 25-year-old closer, who alienated himself from
several segments of society _ and his own clubhouse _ with hateful
comments in a Sports Illustrated story, faced his teammates as a
group for the first time Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Rocker was given permission a day earlier by baseball arbitrator
Shyam Das to rejoin the team. Das reduced his suspension to 12
games and slashed his fine to $500. By Thursday, Rocker was trying
to mend his relationships with teammates.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was really good,'' Rocker said about a 30-minute,
closed-door team meeting. ``It was actually much better than I
thought it would be. This is my third year ... and I've always had
good relationships with 95 percent of the guys. Those guys treated
me just like they always have, and it went really well. My buddies
like Rudy (Seanez) and Mike Remlinger, Javy (Lopez) and Eddie
(Perez) _ it was the same greeting I got when I walked in the
clubhouse, say, last August.''
</P>
<P>
   Rocker apologized to Randall Simon, whom he referred to as a
``fat monkey'' in the article; Ozzie Guillen, whom he criticized
for not making a play behind him in the National League
Championship Series; and Brian Jordan, who after the story came out
initially called for Rocker to be traded.
</P>
<P>
   Rocker asked Simon to go to lunch after the game Thursday, which
Simon said he planned to do, with his wife, Jadira.
</P>
<P>
   ``I looked at him in the face, and he showed me that he really
meant that he regretted what he said,'' Simon said. ``I saw right
in his eyes (that) it was sad to be standing in front of him
because of what he said about me. ... I really accepted his
apology. I forgive him for what he said.''
</P>
<P>
   Guillen said he interrupted Rocker's apology. ``He thought he
hurt my feelings,'' Guillen said. ``I said, `I've heard worse
before.' I told him to be the same guy he's always been. He's my
teammate, and I support him 100 percent.''
</P>
<P>
   In the meeting, Rocker took the floor first. He was followed by
Bobby Cox, Tom Glavine, Jordan, Simon, newcomer Reggie Sanders and
third base coach Ned Yost.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're giving John Rocker the greatest opportunity in the
world to turn this around,'' Cox said. ``They were terrific.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the most poignant questions was posed by Yost, who asked
Rocker, ``Are you going to change or are you just going to stay the
same?''
</P>
<P>
   Players said privately they were upset that Rocker had decided
not to answer questions in his morning news conference. He chose
instead to read his statement, which had been published in The
Atlanta Constitution on Thursday. By the afternoon, Rocker had
agreed to meet a smaller number of reporters, who conducted a
five-minute interview in the clubhouse after he kept them waiting
for 90 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan, who met with Rocker privately and said he plans to
again, said he encouraged Rocker to face the situation head on.
</P>
<P>
   ``He showed some remorse,'' Jordan said. ``It was almost like he
might tear up a little bit. He's trying to be strong about it. ...
I feel sorry for him. I know he was really sincere as far as
feeling sorry about the pain and attention he's brought to the
team. It's a lesson he has to learn.''
</P>
<P>
   Chipper Jones said: ``All you guys want to see him break down
and cry and show all this emotion. That's not John. For those of us
who know John the way we do, we know he was a little more humble
when he walked in the clubhouse today. ... I think we all came away
satisfied for the time being.''
</P>
<P>
   Jordan went so far as to say that it ``would be cowardly act''
for the Braves to trade Rocker.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan and his teammates do expect some changes in Rocker,
something Rocker said he accepts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will have to grow up a little bit and find different ways to
deal with frustration from not being perfect all the time,'' Rocker
said. ``I just turned 25 a couple months ago. I think people are
expecting me to be more mature way beyond my years just because of
the position I'm in. I've just got a little bit of growing up to
do. I don't think it'll be a problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta Journal-Constitution staff writer Thomas Stinson
contributed to this article.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
