<HEADLINE>
THE PERFECTION OF PIANO-PLAYING?
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds: This story also moved in the ``a'' national news file)  
 By LEAH GARCHIK  
 c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   Three hundred years ago,  &UR; Bartolomeo Cristofori &LR;  introduced the
pianoforte in Florence, Italy. In keeping with that anniversary,
the latest issue of Smithsonian magazine tackles the challenge of
modern performance. (It's apparently a theme whose time has come,
also raised dramatically in ACT's current production, ``2 Pianos, 4
Hands.'')
</P>
<P>
   After watching a piano competition in Brussels last year,
essayist  &UR; Rudolph Chelminski &LR;  observes that despite the ``abundance
of fine pianists'' competing, ``most of these performers will be
obliged to make their livings in entirely different lines of
work.''
</P>
<P>
   The author quotes the late music festival impresario  &UR; Andre &LR; 
 &UR; Borocz  &LR; on changes in standards for what is considered good
playing. ``The difference between the 19th and the 20th centuries
is that technique has been projected to a previously
unheard-of-perfection,'' he says. ``I would pardon any number of
bad notes to hear a little emotion in the playing today.''
</P>
<P>
   Perfection is demanded, said pianist &UR; Claude Frank &LR; , because
``everybody fixes,'' that is, uses recording equipment to
substitute perfect passages for ones that contained wrong notes.
``Most of us are ashamed of fixing but admit it. And I'm one of
them. ... I think there's too much emphasis today on musical and
technical cleanliness. If we play too literally it can become
sterile, but now we compete with recordings, even sometimes with
our own.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; A &AMP; Q &LR;
</P>
<P>
   A (as presented in a story in Harper's Bazaar): ``If you are
young, you need this certainly more than anyone. You live in the
future. You are meeting more and more people; many don't share your
language. There isn't the time or the medium in which to convey the
clarity of your wit, the purity of your intentions or the depth of
your soul.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: Why would a young person spend $4,000 on an Hermes handbag?
</P>
