<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHILD-SHOT-(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AT SLAIN GIRL'S SCHOOL, REASSURANCE AND QUESTIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By DAVID BARBOZA   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOUNT MORRIS TOWNSHIP, Mich. _ Two days after a 6-year-old boy
brought a gun to first grade and killed a classmate, school
officials in this working-class district just north of Flint on
Thursday tried to reassure parents that it was safe to send their
children to school.
</P>
<P>
   ``I view the events that took place as an aberration, something
that was highly, highly, highly unusual,'' Ira Rutherford, the
superintendent of Beecher public schools, said at a news conference
Thursday morning.
</P>
<P>
   Rutherford said he ``was proud'' of the way the staff handled
the shooting of 6-year-old Kayla Renee Rolland at the Theo J. Buell
Elementary School on Tuesday. But he would say little about how the
school had handled a boy it recognized as troubled.
</P>
<P>
   The boy, who had been singled out as needing help by a school
program that identifies children with problems, had been assigned
to a social worker and had undergone counseling, Rutherford said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do have a number of support mechanisms in place to assist
youngsters that would be defined as high risk or have problems,
especially for an elementary school,'' Rutherford said. But he
would not give any details about the boy or how he was being
treated.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can only say we were aware that there were some problems
with him,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The boy, whose father is in jail and whose mother sent him and a
brother to live with an uncle in what the authorities say was a
drug-ridden crack house after she was evicted, will not be charged,
the authorities said. He told detectives he only meant to scare
Kayla with the gun.
</P>
<P>
   But Thursday, a 19-year-old man who lived in the house and who
police say left the stolen, .32-caliber semiautomatic gun that was
used in the shooting under blankets in a bedroom there, was charged
with involuntary manslaughter.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were not looking for scapegoats in this case; we're looking
for justice for Kayla,'' the Genesee County prosecutor, Arthur
Busch, said of the charge against the man, Jamelle Andre James.
</P>
<P>
   ``This definitely was grossly negligent in allowing the boy to
get a loaded pistol,'' Busch said.
</P>
<P>
   The school remained closed Thursday for classes, but was open
for counseling services. The district has sent teachers and
counselors to the homes of the 20 other first-grade classmates,
including five children who witnessed the shooting.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday night, more than 100 angry parents showed up at a
board of education meeting here, demanding action. They petitioned
the school system to install metal detectors and security cameras.
</P>
<P>
   Rutherford said the district was considering more security
measures. There are no guards currently assigned to the school.
</P>
<P>
   ``They need to put security guards _ not even security guards,
cops,'' June Hensley, whose five grandchildren attend Buell, said
in an interview Thursday. One of her grandsons witnessed the
shooting, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was raised here; I went to those schools and it's nothing
like when I went,'' Hensley added. ``You see people in the streets
trying to sell crack all the time.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   No charges have yet been filed in Kayla's death against the
boy's uncle, Sir Marcus Winfrey, who was taken into custody
Wednesday on unrelated charges, or the boy's mother, Tamarla Owens.
Owens and her 5-year-old daughter had been living with another
relative.
</P>
<P>
   The state of Michigan moved to gain custody of the boy and his
two siblings Wednesday, saying Owens and the boy's father, Dedric
Owens, 28, were unfit parents.
</P>
<P>
   The state said that Owens had physically abused her 8-year-old
son in the past year and that she had exposed the children to
drunkenness, criminality and drugs.
</P>
<P>
   Dedric Owens has apologized for the shooting. He told the
authorities he did not know where his children were living, but
knew that the boys' uncle lived in a crack house. The authorities
say they found a gram and a half of crack cocaine, a stolen shotgun
and ammunition in the house.
</P>
<P>
   A probate judge has placed the children with a maternal aunt,
pending a hearing.
</P>
<P>
   Douglas Theodoroff, the children's court-appointed lawyer, said
he had visited with them Wednesday and that they seemed unaware of
the impact of the shooting.
</P>
<P>
   ``The three of them were acting pretty age-appropriate,''
Theodoroff said. ``The little girl was spinning in her chair and
the kids were just kind of slapping at each other. I don't think
the 6-year-old has any concept of what's happened.''
</P>
<P>
   At Buell, people continued to mourn for Kayla, who loved Barbie
dolls and often prayed before lunch. A large makeshift memorial is
mushrooming hourly as a steady stream of visitors place candles,
cards, teddy bears and candy in the school's entrance.
</P>
<P>
   A candlelight vigil was held on Wednesday night, and a memorial
service is scheduled for Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, Geoffrey Fieger, a former candidate for governor of
Michigan and lawyer for Dr. Jack Kevorkian, who assisted in more
than 130 suicides, said he was retained by Ricky Rolland, Kayla's
father. Fieger also said he was investigating reports that Buell
elementary had acted improperly in guarding the children's safety
from a community awash in guns and drugs.
</P>
<P>
   ``They can pay lip service all they want,'' he said. ``You go
out to the school and you'll see the reality.''
</P>
<P>
   Hensley, whose grandson Christopher witnessed the shooting, says
her family is trying to decide whether the children should return
to Buell. Christopher is distraught, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He'll talk about it and then say he doesn't want to talk about
it anymore,'' she said. ``My daughter's taking him to counseling.
He doesn't want to go back to school. He's afraid that next time it
could be him.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-02-00 2125EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
