u p BC-MCCAIN03-COX     03-02 1008
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCCAIN03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    McCain, Christian right spat, but agree on essentials
 &HT;    By Mark Sherman
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Lost for the moment in John McCain's public fight
with Pat Robertson and the Rev. Jerry Falwell is one salient fact _
he agrees with them more often than not.
</P>
<P>
   On a range of social issues that include abortion rights, school
vouchers and gay rights, McCain holds views that come close to, and
sometimes match, the bench marks established by social
conservatives.
</P>
<P>
   He opposes abortion rights in all but limited circumstances,
even favoring a constitutional amendment to outlaw abortion.
</P>
<P>
   McCain supports voluntary school prayer.
</P>
<P>
   He would use public money for private schooling, although he
would begin with a test program of school vouchers in the nation's
poorest school districts.
</P>
<P>
   McCain opposes legal recognition of marriages between gays or
lesbians.
</P>
<P>
   He opposes allowing gays and lesbians to adopt children.
</P>
<P>
   McCain has at several points expressed astonishment at the
vehemence with which he has been attacked from his right.
</P>
<P>
   This reinforces his view that abortion and other issues have
little to do with it. McCain attributes the opposition to his
support for campaign finance reform.
</P>
<P>
   McCain's attack Monday on Falwell and Robertson, in their home
state of Virginia, was a moment of high drama, and it raised
another question.
</P>
<P>
   Why did McCain go public with such severe criticism of two men
who have significant influence among social conservatives?
</P>
<P>
   One possibility is that McCain was simply angry at attacks on
him and Warren Rudman, his campaign chairman, who has famously
feuded with Robertson's Christian Coalition.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Bauer, the former presidential candidate who has endorsed
McCain, said a nasty personal dispute with Robertson motivated
McCain's comments.
</P>
<P>
   Another possibility is that the attack was a calculated effort
to draw moderate Republicans to McCain's side. In this view, McCain
had little to risk since he already has lost the bulk of social
conservative support in this campaign.
</P>
<P>
   What he needed is a dramatic way to distinguish himself from
George W. Bush, portraying Bush as a captive of the religious
conservatives and McCain as a uniter, not a divider, to borrow a
phrase from Bush.
</P>
<P>
   McCain paints the issue simpy as a matter of conscience for
himself and his party. ``This is a defining moment,'' he said again
Thursday, as he continued to mention Robertson and Falwell at his
rallies and in sessions with reporters.
</P>
<P>
   Robertson and Falwell have pulled the party too far to the right
in national elections, forcing moderate voters into the Democratic
camp, he said.
</P>
<P>
   But even before McCain's attacks on Robertson and Falwell, Bush
had the overwhelming backing of social conservatives, despite the
fact that McCain's positions on many social issues are
indistinguishable from Bush's.
</P>
<P>
   Some conservatives suspect that McCain somehow harbors beliefs
more moderate than his voting record and platform would indicate.
</P>
<P>
   Rusty Paul, former chairman of the Georgia Republican Party,
said McCain damaged himself in the eyes of social conservatives in
January by suggesting he would consider allowing his daughter to
have an abortion if she became pregnant.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know that he intended to send that signal, but it was
received,'' said Paul, who worked for Steve Forbes's presidential
campaign. ``He would apply one standard for women in America and
another for his daughter.''
</P>
<P>
   It is true that McCain cloaks his positions in the rhetoric of
inclusion. This has never been more true than this week, when he
proclaimed that Falwell and Robertson ``practice the politics of
division.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain said he, on the other hand, favors ``the politics of
addition.''
</P>
<P>
   He urges people who disagree with him on a specific issue not to
let it determine their vote. On abortion, for instance, McCain says
he wants people on both sides of the issue to work together to make
adoption easier.
</P>
<P>
   That view misses the point, say abortion rights supporters. ``He
wants to take away a woman's reproductive freedom. That's the
bottom line,'' said Kate Michelman, executive director of the
National Abortion and Reproductive Rights Action League, which has
endorsed Vice President Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
   But the adoption issue also exposes a harder line in McCain's
views.
</P>
<P>
   As he traveled between campaign stops in California this week,
McCain was describing how he and his wife, Cindy, came to adopt
Bridget, their 8-year-old daughter.
</P>
<P>
   He told how his wife brought Bridget and another baby home from
Mother Teresa's orphanage in Bangladesh. Both babies had health
problems and, in McCain's view, probably would have died had they
remained at the orphanage.
</P>
<P>
   ``You just couldn't resist,'' he said warmly, recalling how his
wife surprised him by showing up at the airport in Phoenix with
their new daughter.
</P>
<P>
   But then he was asked why he would deny other babies similar
loving environments if the prospective parents are gay.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just don't think it's appropriate,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Why not?
</P>
<P>
   ``I just don't think it's appropriate,'' he repeated.
</P>
<P>
   He was pressed again and gave the same answer. The normally
voluble candidate refused to elaborate.
</P>
<P>
   To complicate the issue even more, McCain believes that ``what
people do with their private lives is their business.''
</P>
<P>
   But he would not give legal blessing to a union of gay men or
women.
</P>
<P>
   Still, McCain has attracted some support from gay Republicans.
Mike Flickinger is a gay Republican in Cleveland, where he is a
local GOP chairman.
</P>
<P>
   ``This guy met with the Log Cabin Republicans,'' a group of gay
Republicans, Flickinger said. ``Bush wouldn't do that. Bush went to
Bob Jones University. Which one of those guys would you choose?''
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists, visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
