r s BC-BBN-REEVES-ROCKER-TEX     03-02 0880
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-REEVES-ROCKER-TEX </SLUG>
 ROCKER NEEDS BRAVERY TO LIVE IN A NEW
WORLD (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) By JIM REEVES
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORT CHARLOTTE, Fla. _ Climb into John Rocker's head for a
moment _ there's plenty of room _ and take a look at the world
today through his eyes.
</P>
<P>
   A little frightening, isn't it?
</P>
<P>
   This is the universe you've made for yourself, J.R.
</P>
<P>
   It is full of strangers, many of them of different colors and
nationalities, of different cultures and languages and persuasions.
It is full of No. 7 trains, doomed, like some haunted subway car
from the ``Twilight Zone,'' to make the same dismal run, day after
miserable day, night after lonely night.
</P>
<P>
   Welcome aboard, John Rocker. Hope you enjoy the trip.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, you've just successfully manipulated the system to
effectively emasculate your baseball-inflicted punishment and bring
it down to a much more manageable two weeks and 500 bucks.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, and that sensitivity training you're required to complete?
You'll blow through that with your eyes closed. Literally.
</P>
<P>
   But what you are just beginning to understand is that no
arbitrator's decision can get you off the hook for the incredibly
inane and devastatingly insensitive remarks you so blithely made in
that ``Sports Illustrated'' article a couple of months ago.
</P>
<P>
   While you were so profusely and sincerely apologizing to your
teammates and reading your brief ``mea culpa'' statement to the
media at the Braves' spring headquarters in Orlando yesterday,
Rangers' first baseman Rafael Palmeiro was succinctly laying out
the harsh realities of your future existence at Texas' camp in Port
Charlotte.
</P>
<P>
   Welcome to perdition.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way he's going to pay for this is how he gets treated when
he goes out on the road,'' Palmeiro pointed out. ``People know who
he is now, and it's not just going to be waiting for him at the
ballpark. It's going to follow him everywhere.
</P>
<P>
   ``When he goes out to a restaurant or anywhere in public, people
are going to recognize him, and there'll always be some guy with a
smart mouth.''
</P>
<P>
   Some guy, in other words, who's not willing to let you off as
easy as arbitrator Shyam (rhymes with shame) Das did when he
ignored commissioner Bud Selig's attempts to finally get a player
suspension right.
</P>
<P>
   And you, better than anyone, know that anger control isn't
exactly your strong suit.
</P>
<P>
   Don't think for a minute that Palmeiro is blowing things out of
proportion, either. He was there to see the hell that Roberto
Alomar went through in Baltimore after the spitting incident with
umpire John Hirschbeck a few years back. And that's not even close
to what you're about to face.
</P>
<P>
   ``He \RAlomar\S went from being a guy everybody cheered and
loved to a guy everybody booed and hated,'' Palmeiro remembered.
``It just about killed him.''
</P>
<P>
   Unlike Alomar, however, nobody particularly liked you much in
the first place, which is why few players around baseball,
including your own teammates, have risen to your defense (an
impossible task anyway).
</P>
<P>
   ``The union had to go through with this appeal process, but what
I'd have liked to have seen him do is stand up and take the union
out of it by saying he accepted the suspension as punishment for
saying stupid \Rstuff\S,'' Rangers' reliever Tim Crabtree said.
``It wouldn't have hurt me to see him serve the entire
suspension.''
</P>
<P>
   You might have skipped out on that, John, but that doesn't mean
you won't pay. The bill is just beginning to come due.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has to answer to the media, to the fans and to other
players,'' Palmeiro said. ``His teammates may get past it, but
everybody won't be so forgiving.
</P>
<P>
   ``Me? I'd rather have had the year's suspension.''
</P>
<P>
   The real shame of it is that while you personally are a walking
cesspool of racism and intolerance and prejudice, you've managed to
paint all of baseball with the same brush. That is extremely unfair
because this is a sport where finally, every player really is
created equal as far as skin color and ethnic background.
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone can throw 95 miles per hour, but if you can, or if
you're left-handed, it wouldn't matter if you were purple and spoke
Martian, some team will happily sign you up and throw millions of
dollars at your webbed feet.
</P>
<P>
   Baseball is exploring the world in its search for talent, from
Caribbean hot spots such as the Dominican Republic and Venezuela,
to Far East locales such as Japan, Taiwan and South Korea.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thinking back, I can't remember the last time there was some
sort of racial incident in baseball,'' Rangers general manager Doug
Melvin said. ``As a player, it's just not an issue. When I was in
the minors in New Haven, Conn., I shared a house with five
Dominican pitchers. It just wasn't a big deal for any of us.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, we won't kid ourselves that you're the only one of your
kind out there. You're not the first close-minded bigot in
baseball, and you almost certainly won't be the last.
</P>
<P>
   Most are smart enough to hide it, though, which might make them
even more dangerous.
</P>
<P>
   We know who are you now, John. We know where you work and where
we can find you.
</P>
<P>
   You've earned yourself a lifetime pass on the No. 7 train, and
it's jam-packed with all your new ``friends.'' Enjoy the ride.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
