<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GALLOWAY-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HICKS CAN BALANCE BOOKS BY WINNING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY GALLOWAY 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ If you've been keeping up with the business
page this week, companies owned by Tom Hicks have been involved in
one transaction for $2-plus billion and another for $3-plus
billion.
</P>
<P>
   ``And don't forget our deal for Hong Kong Telecom,'' said Hicks,
almost meekly. ``I think that one gives us control of the Asian
market.''
</P>
<P>
   I forgot to ask how many more billions were involved in putting
this hammerlock on Asia, but for Hicks this kind of stuff is just
another day at the office. Frankly, he'd rather talk sports.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not that many people read the business page,'' Hicks added.
(Note to ``Star-Telegram'' Business Section employees _ he said
that, I didn't.) ``I told Mark Cuban early on that no matter how
great a company he had built, no one knew who he was. It was the
same with me. Buy a professional sports team, however, and all that
changes instantly, as Mark has found out.''
</P>
<P>
   Buy two, as Hicks did with the Rangers and Stars, and you become
the local sports mogul. Except the combined price of his baseball
and hockey clubs was around $325 million. On the business page,
that's considered tip money.
</P>
<P>
   ``The difference is that in sports, I'm dealing mainly with my
personal capital,'' Hicks said.''In business, it involves my
company, my company's investors, plus third-party investors. But
what makes it all work is I have to have a great team in position
from the top down. In sports, that's your president and your
general manager. It doesn't happen in either place without the team
effort. Fortunately, we have that in both areas.''
</P>
<P>
   But at some point, there's always a fork in the road, a roadway
that is littered with brilliant businessmen who buy a sports team,
become intoxicated with the instant notoriety, and drive right off
into the deep end of the ditch.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sports is so different,'' agreed Hicks, laughing.
</P>
<P>
   But after four years of Stars ownership and two years with the
Rangers, Hicks has been successful in trying to maintain the proper
balance.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Mark \RCuban\S bought the Mavericks, the media asked him
the same thing they asked me,'' Hicks said. ``Would he be like
Jerry Jones? My answer was I'd be like Tom Hicks. I'd say the
answer on Mark is he'll be like Mark Cuban.''
</P>
<P>
   At the moment, that means either unpredictable or loose cannon.
But Cuban is still learning, now that he's ventured outside his
dot-com-geek environment.
</P>
<P>
   Does the sports world operate like the business world? ``No,''
said Hicks, firmly. ``It should, but it doesn't.''
</P>
<P>
   Is that mainly because of ego? ``Yes,'' Hicks said.
</P>
<P>
   The almost automatic local answer is that Cuban should pattern
his ownership regime with the Mavericks after the Hicks model, as
opposed to the Jones version at Valley Ranch. Yet ...
</P>
<P>
   Who says Bob Gainey or Ken Hitchcock wanted Brett Hull two years
ago? Wasn't it Hicks who won out in pushing the Stars to sign Hull
as a free agent? And that was Hicks, right, who orchestrated the
trade attempt for pitcher Roger Clemens a year ago? The same Hicks,
by the way, who decided the Rangers were short a pitcher this
winter, so why not sign Darren Oliver?
</P>
<P>
   For those of us who label Jones a meddling owner, Hicks is not
even close to Jerry's hands-on grip of the Cowboys. But he can have
strong opinions and push for those. When Hicks pushes hard enough,
he obviously won't meet much resistance.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a very strong desire to win, to be successful,'' Hicks
said. ``At the same time, I never lose sight of the bottom line.
</P>
<P>
   ``For one thing, I know I didn't make myself clear enough after
the \RRangers'\S season was over last October. I said we were going
to cut payroll. But the Yankees had just swept us in the playoffs.
We didn't win with a high-dollar payroll. I wanted to cut that, but
only in terms of creating the financial flexibility to re-do the
team.''
</P>
<P>
   Hicks was in Port Charlotte last week, and will return to spring
training this weekend. ``What I love is the different mix of
players for this season,'' he said. ``The team attitude is the best
I've seen. Doug \RMelvin, the general manager\S has a payroll of
about $65 million, some $10 million less than last season. But that
gives us all this flexibility to add what we have to add. And we
will, if necessary.''
</P>
<P>
   As the Stars approach the NHL playoffs for another Stanley Cup
run, the Rangers approach the start of the American League season.
``I'm very pleased with how both teams are positioned,'' said
Hicks. ``I know there are those who don't agree with me on the
Rangers, but that's why we play the season.''
</P>
<P>
   And that's also why Hicks goes out and buys half of Hong Kong.
If you win, you're right. If you're right, you cash.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
