<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-02 21:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5063 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-BBA-RANGERS-TEXZIMMER     03-02 0545
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-RANGERS-TEX </SLUG>
 ZIMMERMAN UNHAPPY WITH CONTRACT (For use by
NYTimes News Service clients) By T.R. SULLIVAN c.2000 Fort Worth
Star-Telegram
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORT CHARLOTTE, Fla. _ Sticking to their strict pay structure
for younger players, the Rangers automatically renewed reliever
Jeff Zimmerman's contract for a salary of $250,000 yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   The All-Star reliever was not happy.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a little bit frustrating,'' Zimmerman said. ``I can see
from a business side their thought process; I just don't agree with
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Rangers general manager Doug Melvin said the Rangers have a
strict salary scale for players with less than three years'
experience. Players with zero to one year of experience get paid
from $200,000 to $250,000 based on service time and playing time.
</P>
<P>
   Zimmerman got the maximum amount for a one-year player under the
Rangers' system, and the team added a $10,000 bonus because he made
the All-Star team last year. Braves reliever Kerry Ligtenberg
signed for $255,000 last year after recording 38 saves as a rookie
the year before.
</P>
<P>
   But Zimmerman's contract is less than half of the $600,000 Kerry
Wood received last year after his terrific rookie season.
</P>
<P>
   ``We tell the players, for the first two years and 100 days \Rof
service time\S we have control,'' Rangers general manager Doug
Melvin said. ``The rest of the player's career comes arbitration
and free agency. Those years are affected by what other clubs pay
their players. We're not trying to be hard-line. It's a matter of
keeping salaries under control while we have the chance.
</P>
<P>
   ``It comes down to the system. If they have a problem with the
system, they should talk to the union. I have a problem with
arbitration.''
</P>
<P>
   Zimmerman's contract is in line with most other top rookies.
Reds reliever Scott Williamson, the National League Rookie of the
Year last year, had his contract recently renewed at $300,000.
Oakland's Ben Grieve got a $300,000 contract a year ago after being
American League Rookie of the Year. Oakland recently renewed Tim
Hudson for $250,000 after Hudson went 11-2 with a 3.23 earned-run
average as a rookie.
</P>
<P>
   Zimmerman and Mike Venafro, who was automatically renewed
yesterday at $245,000, don't like the fact the system is based on
how much they played and not how well they did.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were looking for something based more on performance
criteria and theirs is on service time,'' Venafro said.
</P>
<P>
   Zimmerman was 9-3 with a 2.36 ERA in 65 appearances and 872/3
innings last year. Venafro was 3-2 with a 3.29 ERA in 65 games and
681/3 innings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could have pitched the same number of innings, gone 0-20
with a 12 ERA and gotten the same amount of money,'' Zimmerman
said. ``Which is very frustrating. But I'm just glad to get it
behind me. It's all about pitching for a team with a chance to win
the World Series; it's not about money.''
</P>
<P>
   Melvin said if the salary structure was based on performance,
``then it's all arbitrary, who performed well and who didn't
perform well. Somebody has to make the decision. I told him, your
goal is to get to arbitration and free agency. But for two years
and 100 days, we're going to be tight.''
</P>
<P>
   Pitcher Danny Kolb was renewed at $200,000, and Matt Perisho
agreed to a one-year deal worth $230,000.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
