<HEADLINE>
WORLD NEWS IN BRIEF 
</HEADLINE>
  (pr) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EUROPE
</P>
<P>
   GERMANY: KOHL'S NEW FUND RAISING
</P>
<P>
   Former Chancellor Helmut Kohl said he has been collecting cash
among business friends to help his conservative Christian
Democratic Union pay fines imposed for its illegal campaign
financing during his years in power. News media reports said he had
raised $3 million, enough to cover the financial damage resulting
from his admission that he accepted $1 million in undeclared
donations. Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder's Social Democrats called
Kohl's activity ``incredibly embarrassing.''
</P>
<P>
   ITALY: SCHOOL COMPROMISE
</P>
<P>
   After a 50-year political battle, Parliament passed a law
granting private schools the same status as public schools, and
guaranteeing subsidies to poor families who choose private
schooling. The Catholic Church, which runs 90 percent of private
schools, had lobbied for full state funding. Parliament's
compromise failed to satisfy Catholic bishops, who called the new
law ``incomplete and ambiguous.''
</P>
<P>
   TURKEY: NEW CLASH WITH KURDS
</P>
<P>
   Three soldiers and six Kurdish rebels have been killed in two
clashes, the first casualties between the two sides in six weeks.
Fighting had all but ended in the Kurdish region since the captured
guerrilla leader Abdullah Ocalan called on his followers to press
their demands by peaceful means.
</P>
<P>
   YUGOSLAVIA: PAPER SEIZED
</P>
<P>
   A Serbian state publisher seized control of a popular daily,
Vecernje Novosti, which had recently begun to criticize the
government of President Slobodan Milosevic. The state publisher,
Borba, took over the newspaper's publishing company by government
order, Tanjug, the state news agency reported. The move is the most
serious of recent government efforts to curb independent and
critical news media.
</P>
<P>
   FRANCE: DUMAS TRIAL DATE
</P>
<P>
   June 19 has been set for the opening of the trial on corruption
charges of Roland Dumas, former president of France's highest
judicial body. Dumas is accused of getting his mistress a job with
the Elf oil group and benefiting from commissions she received
worth some $10 million. Dumas, 77, a friend of former President
Francois Mitterrand, was foreign minister at the time of the
reported scandal.
</P>
<P>
   THE AMERICAS
</P>
<P>
   CANADA: CUBAN ENVOY LEAVES
</P>
<P>
   Jose Imperatori, the Cuban diplomat expelled last week from the
United States, left Canada after overstaying his Canadian transit
visa by almost three days. In a negotiated departure, Imperatori
left the Cuban Embassy in Ottawa with a Mountie escort, and then
boarded a Cubana Airlines jet sent to take him back to Havana.
</P>
<P>
   PERU: EMERGENCY MOVE EASED
</P>
<P>
   President Alberto Fujimori revoked the powers of the security
forces to detain anyone at will in so-called emergency zones
covering about 6 percent of the country, where terrorism has been
seen as a grave threat for 17 years. The action appeared to be
intended to soften Fujimori's image 40 days before he stands for
election to a third term.
</P>
<P>
   ASIA
</P>
<P>
   AFGHANISTAN: TALIBAN'S NEW BATTLES
</P>
<P>
   Fierce combat has broken out again between the Taliban and
opposition forces in the Shomali Plains just north of Kabul. At the
same time, there has been fighting between the two armies near the
border with Tajikistan. The Taliban, which controls about 90
percent of the country, say they have captured the town of Sher
Khan Bandar along a key supply route.
</P>
<P>
   JAPAN: CULT'S DENIAL
</P>
<P>
   Aum Shinrikyo said it does not have access to sensitive
information on government and corporate computer networks, although
companies affiliated with the religious cult developed software for
many of those systems. Fumihiro Joyu, the cult's senior member,
said the activities of the Aum-related computer companies were
``merely economic and not based on malicious intent.''
</P>
<P>
   MIDDLE EAST
</P>
<P>
   IRAQ: U.N. HAJJ PLAN REJECTED
</P>
<P>
   Baghdad rejected a United Nations plan to give Iraqi pilgrims
going to Mecca for the hajj $2,000 each to pay for expenses. The
money, drawn from United Nations-controlled deposits from oil
sales, would have been part in cash and part in travelers' checks
to be cashed only outside Iraq. Iraq demands that the $49.4 million
to cover 24,700 pilgrims be turned over to the Iraqi central bank.
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL: U.N. HOPES RAISED
</P>
<P>
   Israel hopes the tide has turned in a long battle to persuade
Europe to admit it to the ``Western Europe and others'' group in
the United Nations. Spain has dropped its public opposition to
Israel's membership, now under discussion at several levels in the
European Union. Israel has never been admitted to any regional
group, through which committee positions and rotating Security
Council seats are filled.
</P>
</TEXT>
