<HEADLINE>
SHORT ITEMS ON PERSONAL BUSINESS  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MARCH 5) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Affluence of Youth, Thanks to Mom and Dad &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It is no wonder that teenagers are such targets for marketers:
they have a lot of money under their control. A study estimates
that 9.8 million American teenagers receive cash from their
parents, to the tune of $1.05 billion a week.
</P>
<P>
   During 1997 and 1998, researchers from Ohio State University
randomly selected 8,984 youths, ages 12 to 17, and asked, among
other questions, how much money they received from their parents.
</P>
<P>
   Included in the count were regular weekly allowances for chores,
lunches or transportation, along with other discretionary cash
doled out during the week for things like movies or clothing
purchases.
</P>
<P>
   Almost half the teenagers said they received a regular sum from
their parents; the median was $50 a week.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was very surprised at the amount,'' said Dr. Jay Zagorsky, a
research scientist at the university's Center for Human Resource
Research. ``My two sons aren't quite teens yet, but they don't get
anywhere near that much.''
</P>
<P>
   The statistics come from the latest National Longitudinal Survey
of Youth, conducted by Ohio State for the Bureau of Labor
Statistics. This was the first time the survey asked about money.
</P>
<P>
   As might be expected, teenagers from wealthier families received
the highest dollar amounts. For children from families with an
annual household income of at least $100,000, the median was $175 a
week. That compares with $12 to $14 a week for teenagers in
households with annual income of less than $20,000.
</P>
<P>
   Parents were more generous if they had fewer children, the
researchers found.
</P>
<P>
   Zagorsky noted that half the teenagers interviewed didn't
receive any cash. But, he said, the study suggests that ``there is
still a significant number of teens who aregetting a fair amount
of money'' over the course of a week.
</P>
<P>
   Another interesting finding _ and one that oddly echoes the
adult working world: boys in the study received more money than
girls did. ``I have no idea why,'' Zagorsky said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _Susan J. Wells &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   What About Last Year's Refund? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Refund checks for 1998 are still due to 100,000 taxpayers. The
checks, totaling $72 million, were returned to the IRS by the
Postal Service. More information is available by calling l
(800)829-1040. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _Jan M. Rosen
</P>
