<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PALM-PALM </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 Palm Stock Hits IPO Heights  &HT;     By Verne Kopytoff 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
In one of the hottest initial public offerings of the year, shares
of Palm, the handheld organizer manufacturer, soared nearly 150
percent yesterday in their first day of trading.
<P>
   After being priced at $38 per share late Wednesday, the shares
opened at a staggering $145, soared as high as $165, but then
dropped back to close at $95.06.
</P>
<P>
   The increase gave Palm a market value of $53 billion _ almost
twice that of its parent, 3Com Corp., the giant Santa Clara
computer networking company. Although 3Com still owns almost 95
percent of Palm's shares, worth $50 billion, and is a far bigger
company, 3Com's market value yesterday was only $28 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Some investors are betting that even though 3Com is bigger, Palm
will grow much faster. And unlike most recent high-tech IPOs, Palm
is actually making money.
</P>
<P>
   ``The interest in Palm is tremendous,'' said Peter Lieu, an
independent analyst in Boston. ``It has all the parameters of a
great growth stock.''
</P>
<P>
   Palm's $53 billion market value exceeded that of Ford Motors,
General Motors, Philip Morris and Chevron, each of which are worth
about $50 billion.
</P>
<P>
   One reason Palm's stock price soared is that very few shares
were sold in the IPO. 3Com offered only 23 million Palm shares _
less than 5 percent of Palm's 561 million outstanding shares. It
plans to distribute the remaining Palm shares to 3Com shareholders
in about six months.
</P>
<P>
   With more Palm shares on the market, the price could suffer,
which also could explain the wide disparity between Palm's and
3Com's market values.
</P>
<P>
   Palm is the world's largest producer of handheld computer
organizers, increasingly powerful devices that allow users to store
years' worth of appointments and thousands of telephone numbers.
These organizers feature liquid crystal screens, snap-in
accessories like digital cameras, and, in the case of the Palm VII,
a wireless Internet connection.
</P>
<P>
   According to International Data Corp., Palm controlled 68.4
percent of the handheld computer organizer market in the United
States during the first half of 1999. Most analysts believe that
the company is poised to dominate in the future.
</P>
<P>
   Palm also makes a relatively small amount of money by licensing
its organizer software to other organizer manufacturers. But some
analysts think that this market could grow tremendously if
organizers are integrated with cellular telephones, as many
companies are trying to do.
</P>
<P>
   Palm faces stiff competition, however, from companies including
Casio, Handspring and Hewlett-Packard.
</P>
<P>
   3Com decided to make Palm independent so it could concentrate on
its network business, which has been suffering lately.
</P>
<P>
   For example, 3Com's sales in the quarter ended Nov. 26, 1999,
declined 4.3 percent to $1.47 billion from the same period a year
earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Palm's sales increased 76 percent to $259 million during the
same period.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an exciting day for Palm,'' Alan Kessler, Palm's chief
operating officer, said in an interview. ``It's going to allow us
to move to the next level and invest in some young companies that
are in the Palm economy,'' he said, referring to firms that make
add-on products for the Palm.
</P>
<P>
   While Palm's stock took off yesterday, 3Com's declined
dramatically. Though 3Com's shares had quadrupled in value since it
announced the Palm spin-off in September, its price yesterday
declined $22.31, to $81.81.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts were divided on which company _ 3Com or Palm _ is the
better investment at this point.
</P>
<P>
   Gerry Purdy, president of Mobile Insights, a market research
company, preferred Palm. He said it will likely continue to grow
for years to come by adding sophisticated new features to its
organizers, essentially transforming them into portable personal
computers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Palm represents a computer company of the 21st century,''
Purdy said. ``It's going to be about personalized information _
where you need it and when you need it.''
</P>
<P>
   Purdy was less enthusiastic about 3Com, which he said must
reorganize and refocus on its computer networking business. Only
then, he said, will 3Com, the nation's second-largest maker of
networking equipment, be able to even consider overtaking No.1
Cisco Systems.
</P>
<P>
   Patrick Houghton, an analyst with Sutro Group, the investment
firm, thinks 3Com's stock is a steal considering that its market
value is half of Palm's, while it still owns about 95 percent of
Palm.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the market is efficient, those two prices are going to
converge over the next six months,'' Houghton said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &LR; id  &LR; E-mail Verne Kopytoff at verne &LR; sfgate.com.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
