<SLUG> BC-BIZ-SENIORITY-$ADV05-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A READY CONSTITUENCY AWAITING RECOGNITION  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MARCH 5) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.Y., Colo.)   (af)  
 By FRED BROCK   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Amid all the fighting over Confederate flags and Christianity,
none of the presidential candidates have tried very hard to connect
with an important constituency: older Americans.
</P>
<P>
   That is not to say that the contenders have ignored issues that
affect seniors, like Social Security and Medicare. And Vice
President Al Gore's recent trips to Florida have hardly been to
visit college students.
</P>
<P>
   But no candidate has tried to go beyond a handful of hot-trigger
issues and to forge an empathetic bond with older people, to become
(italics)their(end italics) champion, as President Clinton has with
blacks over the last seven years, as Sen. John McCain has with
fellow veterans or as Gore has with organized labor.
</P>
<P>
   Older Americans, of course, are a very diverse lot, making them
more difficult to appeal to than, say, an ethnic minority group
with a shared history.
</P>
<P>
   But Bill Zinke, a consultant for corporations on hiring and
retaining older workers, thinks the time is ripe for a leader to
tap into this important voter pool.
</P>
<P>
   ``A candidate who can show that he really understands the needs
of older Americans could certainly swing important votes in his
direction,'' Zinke said. ``And I don't mean just in terms of
entitlement programs or more laws.''
</P>
<P>
   In other words, he is not asking candidates to pander to
seniors' pocketbooks. Rather, he wants to hear them talking about
what older Americans have to contribute.
</P>
<P>
   The comments from House members in the wake of last week's
unanimous vote to lift earnings restrictions on Social Security
beneficiaries aged 65 to 69 indicate that, at least on the
congressional level, some politicians are catching on.
</P>
<P>
   Although Zinke has no formal expertise in politics, he argues
from the numbers. Some 58 million Americans are 55 or older, a
figure that will bulge as the baby boomers enter retirement. And
older people go to the polls. In the 1996 presidential election, 77
percent of Americans over 65 voted, compared with just 49 percent
of the overall voting-age population.
</P>
<P>
   Henry J. Aaron, an economist at the Brookings Institution in
Washington and an expert on aging and demographics, argues that
older people are too diverse to be captured as a core constituency.
He agrees, however, that their growing numbers and high voting rate
_ combined with ``ennui among younger voters'' _ could make them
fertile ground for a candidate able to forge an ``emotional
connection.''
</P>
<P>
   Zinke wants to see political leadership that will change what he
calls the ``national mind-set'' about older Americans. ``Jawboning
is as good a term as any to describe what I think is needed,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The general attitude is that when you reach a certain age,
you're over the hill. You should go somewhere and enjoy the `golden
years.'''
</P>
<P>
   He cited a 1999 Harris Poll showing that there were 3.7 million
people over 55 who were out of the work force but who would like to
keep working. ``Because of ageism and the national mind-set about
older people, they think there are no jobs for them or they are not
wanted,'' he said. ``In a tight job market, this is a valuable
resource pool.''
</P>
<P>
   So why doesn't one of the candidates start beating this drum?
``I think they and their advisers are just plain missing the
boat,'' Zinke said.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Murphy, a democratic political consultant in Washington,
thinks there may well be an opening for a candidate with such a
message. But he said national office seekers had to be careful of
too many segmented appeals. ``You need an overarching appeal to
build a majority,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Such an approach, he added, could have traction as a subtext of
a campaign, because values are important in this year's elections.
``Equal opportunity and respect for elders are important values,''
he said. ``Also, building credibility with older voters is
important, because traditional means of reaching them are becoming
less effective. They don't respond well to pandering.''
</P>
<P>
   Zinke, a former corporate and criminal lawyer in New York, runs
his own consulting company, Human Resource Services in Boulder,
Colo. He is organizing a conference in Washington in June on the
importance of older workers in meeting employment needs. Sponsors
include AARP, Chase Manhattan, GTE, Nortel Networks, Pitney-Bowes,
Young &AMP; Rubicam and AXA Equitable.
</P>
<P>
   Zinke is an example of what he preaches. He will be 73 this
month, and he has no plans to retire.
</P>
<P>
   ``We should not see aging and our increased longevity in a
negative light,'' he said. ``Instead of worrying about the graying
of America, we should be looking forward to the benefits and
opportunities of this demographic change.'' After all, he said,
``an older population is also a wiser and more skilled
population.''
</P>
</TEXT>
