<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PUC-PUC </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 New PUC Rules Try to Cut Off Phone Cramming  &HT;     By Todd Wallack 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
 &LR;   &LR; After nearly three years of discussions, state regulators
yesterday enacted rules to help consumers fight fraudulent charges
on their telephone bills.
<P>
   The California Public Utilities Commission unanimously barred
local phone companies from cutting off customers' local service
when they refuse to pay their long-distance bills.
</P>
<P>
   The commissioners said many customers mistakenly thought they
had to pay phony long-distance charges to prevent their phones from
being disconnected.
</P>
<P>
   ``The commission did the right thing,'' said Paul Stein, an
attorney for The Utility Reform Network, a San Francisco consumer
group that lobbied for the change.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you pay your local phone bill, you should get to keep your
local phone service.''
</P>
<P>
   Although complaints about overcharging have been falling,
regulators say it is still a sore spot for consumers. Pacific Bell
said it received as many as 1,200 complaints a month during a peak
in March 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``We must do more,'' Commissioner Josiah Neeper said in
introducing the rules. Neeper said he recalled that one consumer
called his office in a panic after receiving a bill with nearly
$800 in phony charges.
</P>
<P>
   Under the rules, long-distance long distance  &LR; companies must
identify themselves on bills by their legal name or the name
registered with regulators to make it easier to resolve complaints
and crack down on companies ``cramming'' unauthorized charges on
customers' bills.
</P>
<P>
   Regulators also issued new voluntarily guidelines outlining how
local phone companies can better track complaints against billing
companies, so they can sever ties with firms that pass along phony
charges.
</P>
<P>
   Commissioners quickly approved the new measures with little
debate. Commissioner Carl Wood, who recently proposed creating a
bill of rights for telephone customers, said the new measures
provide a good basis for a broad set of rules to protect consumers.
</P>
<P>
   Still, it took nearly three years for the PUC to approve the
rules, in part because of strong opposition from telephone
companies.
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T spokesman James Peterson said many companies have been
concerned about the rules because they could encourage some
freeloaders to refuse to pay legitimate charges, forcing phone
companies to raise their rates.
</P>
<P>
   Pacific Bell, which fought some of the measures when they were
being hammered out, hailed the vote yesterday. ``This will give us
some more enforcement tools'' to fight cramming, said spokesman
John Britton. He said the phone company has also refused to do
business with roughly 70 firms suspected of passing along
fraudulent charges.
</P>
<P>
   Fassil Fenikile, an aide to Neeper, said the rules took time to
work out because they involved several revisions. He also said the
commission had to wait for related action in the state Legislature
and Federal Communications Commission.
</P>
<P>
   The PUC ordered Pacific Bell and other local phone companies to
notify consumers about the new rules.
</P>
<P>
   Separately, the PUC approved the merger of Bell Atlantic and
GTE. However, the commissioners rejected a proposal to divert $64
million of merger-related savings to help provide
telecommunications infrastructure to poor communities. Two
commissioners said more hearings are needed to decide how to spend
that money.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
E-mail Todd Wallack at todd &LR; sfgate.com.
</P>
