u s BC-BBN-ARATON-COLUMN-NYT     03-02 0793
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-ARATON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: ROCKER FACES TOUGHEST CRITICS IN BRAVES TEAMMATES
</HEADLINE>
   (With BBN-BRAVES-ROCKER) 
(rk) 
 By HARVEY ARATON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   KISSIMMEE, Fla. _ John Rocker's de facto judgment began Thursday
morning when he took what must have seemed like a very long walk
from his dressing stall over to Randall Simon's a few feet away.
</P>
<P>
   With a room full of stone-faced Atlanta Braves watching for a
first act of contrition, Rocker tapped Simon on the shoulder, and
then waited out the most agonizing heartbeats of his 25 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to apologize to you,'' Rocker said, when Simon turned
to face him.
</P>
<P>
   More reflexively than deliberately, Simon's hand reached out to
meet the pitcher who had disparaged so many in the process of
disgracing himself. And at this very moment, Randall Simon applied
the lessons of a loving disciplinarian, a mother who had a way of
immediately recognizing deception disguised as truth.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because of the way my mother was, I've always been able to
look somebody in the eye and know if he means what he says,'' Simon
said.
</P>
<P>
   He studied the gaze of the man who had publicly labeled him ``a
fat monkey,'' and said he saw remorse. He said he saw pain.
</P>
<P>
   If Rocker's apology was just a song worthy of a Grammy, Simon
said he and his wife, Gidara, would surely catch on by the time the
three of them finished dinner Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
   So forget the arbitrary suspension and the arbitrator's decision
to reduce it. Forget the protesters and the shrill cries for
baseball to ban Rocker or for the Braves to cast him off to a
less-righteous bullpen. Forget those sound bites from the No. 7
train. The opinions that matter most, or at all, are going to be
those in the clubhouse, the jury of John Rocker's peers.
</P>
<P>
   Only the Braves can make the definitive call on whether Rocker
is, in his heart and mind, what he sounded like in the pages of
Sports Illustrated, or if he is just another wayward product of our
shock culture, a Frankenstein news media creation, Goofy gone
Daffy.
</P>
<P>
   It is somewhat of a coincidence that the Braves train on the
expansive Disney campus, in a complex called the Wide World of
Sports, as Rocker's xenophobic commentary staggered fundamental
logic, given the certainty he would be confronting one of those
``foreigners'' every time he looked in for the sign.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I first heard about it, I thought it was no big deal,
just more of what he was saying at the World Series,'' said one of
the catchers, Javy Lopez, out of Ponce, P.R. ``Then I read the
article and I thought it was a setup. I just couldn't believe it.''
</P>
<P>
   Lopez, in Atlanta at the time, said his phone began ringing,
calls from relatives and friends.
</P>
<P>
   ``They hated him right away, absolutely hated him,'' Lopez said.
``But I kept saying, `I've known Rocker for three years and he's
never, ever acted racist around me, or anyone I know.'''
</P>
<P>
   The other catcher, Eddie Perez of Cuidad Ojeda, Venezuela,
echoed those thoughts, following the team meeting during which
Rocker was said to have come close to tears and begged his
teammates, ``Please, let me play.'' Perez said Simon, one of
several Braves to stand up and speak, demanded that Rocker come
clean with the Hispanic players.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said that he had been in the minor leagues with Latin guys,
had lived with them, never had any problems and you can ask them,''
Perez said. ``That, I agree with him. Me and him have been good
friends.''
</P>
<P>
   Commissioner Bud Selig didn't have to make diversity training
part of Rocker's so-called punishment; he just had to return him to
the Braves, to the clubhouse, where Rocker can't hide anymore, if,
in fact, he was hiding there before.
</P>
<P>
   Fans may boo him, but Rocker has been booed before, even if it
was just for being the provocateur. The news media may hiss and
holler every time he uses awkward phrasing _ as he did Thursday in
relating a recent engagement with a bunch of African-American
construction workers _ but Tom Glavine was right when he said that
Rocker's real trial didn't begin until he walked through the
clubhouse door.
</P>
<P>
   The players will decide where they go from here. By late
morning, after manager Bobby Cox concluded the group therapy
session with a more sporting refrain _ ``Let's play some ball'' _
Rocker and Lopez could be seen on the warning track in right field,
chatting amicably.
</P>
<P>
   After the way the Braves' organization had shamefully tried to
close the clubhouse, it was if Rocker's teammates were saying, ``Oh
no, this is going to be out in the open where it belongs.''
</P>
<P>
   It was encouraging to hear them speak so candidly, straight from
the heart. If there is hatred in Rocker's, the Braves are the ones
to find out.
</P>
</TEXT>
