<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-02 21:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5072 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-LAWYER-LAWYER_SFCHRON     03-02 1214
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LAWYER-LAWYER </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 Lawyers Paid Well to Stay  &HT;     By Verne Kopytoff 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
Heather M. Shane was resigned to renting an apartment in San
Francisco because her $95,000 salary and $5,000 bonus weren't  &LR; 
 &LR; enough to buy one of the homes for sale that she visits for fun.
Now, the lawyer is thinking that buying a flat is within reach.
<P>
   In December, Shane's Menlo Park law firm, Gunderson Dettmer,
announced dramatic raises for its associates. Though Shane, who
graduated from law school 10 months ago, did not ask for more
money, her pay was increased to $125,000, with up to $25,000 more
in bonuses.
</P>
<P>
   ``Frankly, it just seemed astounding to me that I was making so
much money even before the raises,'' Shane said. ``Instead of
looking for a cheaper apartment, I'm looking for something that
possibly is in my range.''
</P>
<P>
   She's house-hunting in a market where the median price of a
condo was $435,000 in January, according to Acxiom Dataquick, a
real estate information firm in San Diego. Shane is the beneficiary
of a big increase in lawyer salaries in the Bay Area during the
past few months. In an effort to compete for attorneys with the
growing Internet and technology industries, many law firms now
offer salaries so generous that some normally stoic lawyers yell
and applaud when their raises are announced.
</P>
<P>
   The salary increases for Bay Area lawyers are being imitated at
corporate law offices across the country, noted Paula Patton,
executive director of the National Association for Law Placement,
which tracks hiring in the legal profession. That's unusual, she
said, because law firms in New York and Chicago dictate national
salary levels, not San Francisco and Santa Clara.
</P>
<P>
   It's too soon to say whether these increases are keeping lawyers
from leaving. Law firms say they expect to know in six months to a
year.
</P>
<P>
   Attorneys specializing in corporate law and intellectual
property are the primary beneficiaries of the salary increases.
Though costly, law firms say the raises are necessary to keep
attorneys from quitting to join Silicon Valley startups, many of
which offer shorter working days and stock options that are
potentially worth millions of dollars.
</P>
<P>
   Gunderson Dettmer was the first law firm in the Bay Area to
announce a salary windfall. Within a month, most of the other large
corporate law firms in the area instituted similar raises for
associates that are usually between 25 and 50 percent higher than
what they were paid before.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are losing a number of our most talented lawyers to our
clients,'' said Tower C. Snow Jr., chairman of Brobeck, Phleger &AMP;
Harrison, a law firm in San Francisco that works with companies
like Cisco and E-Trade. ``We wanted to make it as painful as
possible to leave.''
</P>
<P>
   In January, Snow's firm increased first-year lawyer salaries to
$125,000 from a base of $100,000. It is too soon, he said, to know
whether the raises will keep employees from leaving.
</P>
<P>
   Attrition at the firm had been increasing prior to the raise.
Nearly 22 percent of the firm's associates left in 1999, compared
with 12 percent in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   The cost of lawyer turnover can be high. Snow said that each
departing lawyer can mean a reduction in client billing time and a
loss of $200,000 in recruiting and training costs for the firm to
hire a replacement.
</P>
<P>
   One of the lawyers who left Snow's firm last year is Kirsten
Mellor. She now works as a director of legal affairs for
Egreetings.com, the digital greeting card and gift Web site in San
Francisco. Mellor said she left the law firm for several reasons,
including the opportunity to get away from the constant pressure of
law-firm deadlines and the inconvenience of frequently working on
weekends and past midnight.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes as a lawyer at a firm, your work can be dry with so
many documents,'' Mellor said. ``Working at a company like
Egreetings is fun.''
</P>
<P>
   According to Mellor, money was not an issue in the move. The
salaries were comparable, she said, though the stock options tipped
the balance in Egreetings' favor.
</P>
<P>
   Attorney salaries in the Bay Area are among the highest in the
country, according to a survey taken in February by
Emplawyernet.com, a Los Angeles legal job listing Web site. based &LR; 
in Los Angeles.  &LR; The median salary for all lawyers in the Bay Area
is $85,000, compared with to  &LR; $72,000 nationally, according to the
survey.
</P>
<P>
   Salaries are even higher for lawyers who specialize in
intellectual property, an area of expertise that is particularly
sought after in Silicon Valley. Those specialists earn a median
salary of $105,000 in the Bay Area, compared with $90,000
nationally, the Emplawyernet survey said.
</P>
<P>
   Craig Jacoby, a corporate lawyer at Cooley Godward, a Palo Alto
law firm that raised first-year salaries to $125,000 from $95,000,
plus bonuses, has so far resisted the lure of working at a startup.
However, he gets several calls a week from recruiters who try to
break down his defenses with promises of a ``great opportunity.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm pretty happy with my job,'' Jacoby said, conceding that
the extra pay is nonetheless appreciated. ``My wife works at a
dot-com, so that coal is already in the fire.''
</P>
<P>
   Jacoby, who plans to save most of the raise to help buy a house
and perhaps go to restaurants a little more often, added that
joining a startup &LR;   &LR; can be risky. Some companies prosper, while
others do not do well, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``When all the companies turned into gold at the outset, leaving
was easier,'' Jacoby said. ``There are now a lot more
counterexamples to look at.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to promoting an air of giddiness in law firms, the
salary increases have generated a lot of job applications. Since
the raises were announced, several Bay Area firms have received far
more resumes in the mail than usual.
</P>
<P>
   However, the premium pay attorneys are getting these days does
not necessarily extend to the entire legal profession. Criminal
defense attorneys, for example, have been mostly left out of the
raises so far, law firms say.
</P>
<P>
   There's some question whether the salary raises can be
sustained. Maurice Salter, chief executive officer for
Emplawyernet.com, said attorneys who earn high salaries may be
fired when times are not so prosperous, just as they were in the
1980s during an economic slowdown.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are getting to the point where lawyers are not worth what
they are paid, when you compare it to the amount of money they're
bringing in to a firm through their clients,'' Salter said. ``When
the economy contracts, they may have to release these people who
they paid so much for.''
</P>
<P>
   Jason Schultz, a law student at the University of California at
Berkeley who will earn $125,000 a year plus bonuses when he starts
work in a year at Fish &AMP; Richardson, a law firm in Menlo Park, had
other reservations.
</P>
<P>
   He wondered whether firms would offset the big salaries by
charging clients more or pressuring lawyers to work longer hours, a
practice that Fish &AMP; Richardson told him would not be the case.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was concerned that, obviously, if the firms are are paying
more, they have to find the money somewhere,'' Schultz said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
E-mail Verne Kopytoff at verne &LR; sfgate.com.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
