u s BC-AMERICA'S-CUP-NYT &LR;      03-02 0799
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AMERICA'S-CUP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE KIWIS LET LOOSE AFTER PRADA IS SUBDUED 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By HERB McCORMICK   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUCKLAND, New Zealand _ On Thursday afternoon, the America's Cup
went for a spin.
</P>
<P>
   An estimated 70,000 people descended on the Cup Village at the
Viaduct Basin to bask in the national glow in the moments after
Team New Zealand's mighty black sloop had put the finishing touches
on a 5-0 pasting of Italy's Prada Challenge. The Kiwis' victory was
the first successful defense of the cup outside American shores.
</P>
<P>
   The scene was absolute mayhem.
</P>
<P>
   A sea of humanity craned outward from every available space on
the waterfront, and thousands of revelers manned perches atop
apartment buildings and from balconies. Hundreds more took up
station on the bows and fly bridges of the dozens of superyachts
ringing the harbor. Percussive Champagne corks popped in the
breeze.
</P>
<P>
   If there was a theme color to the proceedings, it was the one
worn by all of New Zealand's national teams: basic black. A large
homemade sign was scrawled with the message, ``Black Is
Beautiful.'' A gigantic black flag emblazoned with a silver fern, a
Kiwi symbol for unity, streamed off a passing helicopter.
</P>
<P>
   Speakers pounded out that old Rolling Stones classic: ``Paint It
Black.'' Prada's Luna Rossa was the first boat to be towed into the
maritime maw, sporting a huge banner from its masthead which read,
``Arrividerci New Zealand.'' But the Italians will not be gone for
long, for immediately following their defeat they issued a
challenge to the Royal New Zealand Yacht Squadron for the next cup
match, to be sailed in the summer of 2002-3.
</P>
<P>
   In so doing, Italy's Yacht Club Punta Ala became the challenger
of record for the 31st competition for the cup. The most
significant apparent change in the regatta will be a modified
format for the challenger's selection tournament.
</P>
<P>
   Following two initial round-robins, two-thirds of the
challengers, with a maximum number of 10, will advance to a seeded
semifinal round. The final details of the series have yet to be
determined.
</P>
<P>
   But that is in the future. Thursday, the Italians arrived to
wild cheers at the temporary barges docked in the center of the
viaduct, to which the cup had been transported from its regular
quarters at the yacht squadron. But it was nothing compared with
the arrival of the Kiwi boat, lined from stem to stern with the
several dozen members of the sailing and shore team that comprise
Team New Zealand.
</P>
<P>
   A cacophony of unleashed air horns, blaring rock music, singing,
applause and cheers filled the early evening air. The unflappable
Kiwi tactician, Brad Butterworth, blinking Champagne spray from his
eyes and bellowing commands into a handheld radio against the din,
had the unenviable job of steering NZL 60 alongside.
</P>
<P>
   Once there, the New Zealanders took turns passing the cup around
and pressing it overhead, like Wimbledon champions. On the bow of
the winning yacht, the Kiwi supermodel Rachel Hunter, the pop
singer Rod Stewart's former wife, kicked up her heels in a victory
dance.
</P>
<P>
   At the opposite end of the boat, there was a more touching
scene.
</P>
<P>
   Clambering with difficulty from an inflatable dinghy to the
transom of NZL 60, the Kiwi skipper Russell Coutts' elderly father,
Allan, scrambled aboard and embraced his son. Coutts is known and
sometimes criticized for his restrained persona, but now his
unguarded sudden emotion was heart-wrenching.
</P>
<P>
   Although Coutts had elected not to sail the deciding race _ he
instead handed the wheel to the 26-year-old backup helmsman, Dean
Barker _ it was still very much his day. For in the grand gesture
of turning over command to his understudy, Coutts had underscored
his mantra that Team New Zealand was a well-rounded team. More
importantly, perhaps, he cemented his role as the squad's
undisputed, unselfish leader.
</P>
<P>
   Later, Coutts said: ``We want to hold this cup for a long time.
How long? Well, last night someone said 25 years, and that's not a
bad target.''
</P>
<P>
   If the Kiwis are to hold the cup for an extended spell, they
will need to cultivate young talent, which is why Barker was thrust
into the limelight for the final contest. And Barker was also at
the center of one of Thursday's signature moments, when he
liberated the cup for a long boat ride around the perimeter of the
basin, exhibiting the trophy to the gathered masses beyond the
viewpoint of the central barge.
</P>
<P>
   Barker could barely contain his pure, unabashed joy. Nor, in
return, could his countrymen. All wearing smiles, they were secure
in their knowledge that, for the foreseeable future, their
cup-holding nation remains the center of the yacht-racing world.
The cup was then escorted home, but the party raged into the night.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
