<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-02 21:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5078 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-BIZ-WORLD-INDIA-$ADV0     03-02 1063
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZ-WORLD-INDIA-$ADV05-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MODESTLY, INDIA GOES FOR A PUBLIC SWIM  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MARCH 5) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By CELIA W. DUGGER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOMBAY, India _ With its acres of artificial rivers and cement
oceans painted swimming-pool blue, Water Kingdom could almost pass
for a theme park in Florida, if it weren't for the men in turbans
who are bobbing in the wave pools and the women sailing down the
water slide in pants and long-sleeved shirts.
</P>
<P>
   But Bombay is a long way from Orlando. The water park here was
built for people who don't know how to swim; it rents swimsuits to
women who have never worn one before. Sarabjit Kaur, dressed in a
bathing costume of long black stretch pants and a loose T-shirt,
shuddered at the thought of a one-piece, never mind a bikini.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our culture doesn't allow us,'' she said shyly. Her husband,
Tanjendar Singh Sodhi, a well-traveled banker, explained: ``Things
are changing. She wouldn't have even worn this five years back. Now
she is.''
</P>
<P>
   Water amusement parks are springing up all over India, in New
Delhi and Bombay, in Madras and Hyderabad, in Ahmedabad and Indore
_ signs of change in a country where tens of millions of people
have benefited from an increasingly open, market-driven economy
over the past decade. They have money to spend on luxuries that
their parents could never have afforded, or even imagined.
</P>
<P>
   India may still conjure up exotic images of snake charmers,
leprous beggars and bejeweled maharajas, but there is a new middle
class rising here, and its members are busily doing the consumerist
things that the middle classes do everywhere: shopping for
refrigerators, chatting on the phone, watching cable television _
and looking for fun.
</P>
<P>
   ``Leisure is on the boom here,'' said Rajen Shah, general
secretary of the Indian Association of Amusement Parks and
Industries. ``One Sunday, people will go to a bowling alley or a
pool parlor. The next Sunday, they'll go to a water park.''
</P>
<P>
   Gautam and Madhauri Varik are just such a couple. He owns a
small workshop that assembles electronic gadgets using circuits
from Singapore. She sells chemicals to biotechnology laboratories.
Each has a master's degree, and together they earn roughly $4,000 a
year, about five times the national average, putting them in the
upper middle class.
</P>
<P>
   They have a far higher standard of living than their parents
did. Varik grew up in a one-room house with three other family
members. He and his wife, who have no children, live in a two-room
apartment with a kitchen and a host of appliances, including a
refrigerator, washing machine, television, VCR, CD player and
telephone.
</P>
<P>
   They enjoy their prosperity, but their lives are more hectic
than those of their parents. Neither of their mothers had jobs, but
Varik works and travels almost as intensively as her husband.
``They had more free time than us,'' she said, a bit wistfully, of
her parents' generation. ``We are working too hard.''
</P>
<P>
   So the Variks look for convenient places to relax. They enjoy
going out to play billiards, and on a recent Sunday they tried
Water Kingdom for the first time. ``One of my friends took his wife
here,'' Varik said, as he sat next to a wading pool. ``He insisted
this was the best place to spend a weekend. And it is fantastic.''
</P>
<P>
   Economists caution that being in the middle of the Indian income
range doesn't yield anything like the buying power of a
middle-class income in western Europe or North America. Iswar
Natarajan, chief economist at the National Council of Applied
Economic Research in New Delhi, thinks a better term for this group
might be the consuming class.
</P>
<P>
   Using survey data, he estimates that the number of households in
this class, with incomes of $1,200 to $6,000 a year, has almost
doubled in the past decade, to about 39 million. That translates to
220 million of India's one billion people. Most still cannot afford
a big-ticket item like a car, but they still find themselves with
growing amounts of disposable income.
</P>
<P>
   Ashok Goel's family owns the 22-acre Water Kingdom park, which
had more than half a million customers last year. Goel said a
typical visitor to the park spent about $5 over all, including
admission, suit and locker rentals and snacks; at a water park in
the United States, $5 might not even cover parking. Prices are kept
affordable at Indian parks by low labor costs and the fact that
there is no off season _ the weather is warm all year round in most
of the country.
</P>
<P>
   Parks like Water Kingdom adapt to the needs of local customers
in ways besides price. Almost all the pools are shallow, because
few Indians can swim, Goel said. Women, most of whom rent their
bathing gear, can choose among styles that reveal as much or as
little skin as they want.
</P>
<P>
   ``The swimming gear has been tailor-made for the Indian
psyche,'' Goel said. ``You can cover from wrist to ankle. We have
all the kinds. But the two-piece does not exist.''
</P>
<P>
   There are now about 80 water parks, large and small, in India,
most of them opened in the last few years, said Shah, who besides
heading the trade association is also managing director of the
Arihant Industrial Corp., which manufactured the water slides and
wave pools used at about 60 of the parks.
</P>
<P>
   On a recent Sunday, Water Kingdom was full of playful scenes.
There were young lovebirds floating in inner tubes down Drifting
River; lumpy, out-of-shape people lined up to buy french fries and
a Coke at an on-site McDonald's, and families riding the waves in
Wetlantic.
</P>
<P>
   Meenaxi Patel, a homemaker, sat astride a large inflatable
crocodile in the wading pool at Goofers Lagoon with a group of
other women from her apartment building.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have come, all the ladies and kids, no gents,'' she said.
``My husband is very sporting. If I go out with the kids, he feels
good. He's at home relaxing. My mother-in-law is also there,
resting.''
</P>
<P>
   Like others in the park, Patel spoke of freedom and fun as the
parks' big draws. Wearing her own colorful swimming costume, a
style that covered her thighs and upper arms but that was gaily
splashed with fuchsia flowers, she said she and her friends had
left all their worries behind.
</P>
<P>
   ``It used to be that women stayed at home,'' she said. ``They
wouldn't wear these costumes and come out. But times have changed.
We want to enjoy.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
