NEW YORK TIMES CORRECTIONS FOR FRIDAY, MARCH 3
</HEADLINE>
 Eds.: These corrections will appear in The New York Times on
Friday. Days and dates refer to the original article's transmission
by the New York Times News Service, and may need to be adjusted by
NYT clients.)  
(gc) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BC-HEALTHCARE-ONLINE-NYT (moved on Sunday, Feb. 26)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Sunday, Feb. 26,
about the business plans of Healtheon/WebMD, an online health care
information company, misspelled the surname of an executive who
supervises software programmers and computer engineers. He is Pavan
Nigam, not Nigram.
</P>
<P>
   BC-SCI-VITAL-SIGNS-NYT (moved on Monday, Feb. 27)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Monday, Feb. 27,
about undue optimism and the terminally ill misstated the degree to
which most doctors in a study overestimated the remaining lifetimes
of patients who had been referred to hospices. It was by a factor
of 5.3, not by 5.3 percent.
</P>
<P>
   BC-COOPER-NOVEL-NYT (moved on Wednesday, March 1)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Wednesday, March
1, about the novelist Dennis Cooper, subject of a symposium at New
York University in Fales Library, which houses his archives,
misidentified two scheduled participants in a reading of his work
tonight. Thurston Moore is the guitarist of the rock band Sonic
Youth, not its bassist; Robert Gober is a sculptor, not a painter.
</P>
<P>
   BC-CIR-GEEK-NOTES-NYT (moved on Wednesday, March 1)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Wednesday, March
1, about the Sony Vaio Music Clip, a personal audio player,
referred incorrectly to the digital audio files it can play. It
accepts any MP3 file, not just those that have been converted to
the Antrac3 format.
</P>
</TEXT>
