<DOCNO> NYT20000302.0414 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-02 21:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5081 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-BIZ-CHARM-ART-$ADV05-     03-02 1207
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZ-CHARM-ART-$ADV05-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FINE POINTS ON FINDING MR. PERFECT  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MARCH 5)
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Graphic of dos and don'ts for women to snag a husband is
being sent to NYT graphic clients. Nonsubscribers can make
individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(af) 
 By ABBY ELLIN  
c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Cheryl Marks has a good job and close friends. She travels
often. She's healthy. What's missing? A relationship. And though
she never defined herself by her marital status, after turning 31
last year, she decided to take action.
</P>
<P>
   So Marks, director of treasury and cash management for the
Children's Television Workshop, did what so many other New Yorkers
do: She signed up for a class, in this case one taught by Marilyn
Graman, a psychotherapist, on how to land a husband.
</P>
<P>
   While feminists might bridle at the course objective and the
curriculum, Marks found herself studying alongside Wall Street
brokers, advertising executives, physicians, computer experts _
women who have a firm handle on the career thing but need a little
help on the home front.
</P>
<P>
   ``Women in the corporate world confuse softness and tenderness
with weakness,'' said Graman, 53, a widow. ``My goal is to teach
softness as power.'' She half-jokingly refers to her program as the
Marilyn Graman Finishing School for Feminists.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Graman began her latest class, ``Marriage Works,'' a
six-month, 276-hour course intended to lead businesswomen down the
aisle. The cost is $9,600.
</P>
<P>
   Part therapy session, part personal pep rally, the course is
broken down into modules about aspects of the mating game: 40 hours
to study why participants might have a ``relationship block''; 26
hours to talk with a ``guidess,'' a paid relationship coach cum
cheerleader who has already reaped the fruits of a Graman course;
and 11 hours to discuss color, furniture placement and feng shui,
the Asian art of energy flow.
</P>
<P>
   The course also devotes 9 hours to learning to move gracefully,
8 to wardrobe and 3.5 to the art of gracious gift receiving.
</P>
<P>
   The finale is a field trip to a bridal shop, where women try on
dresses and visualize their wedding day. ``If you see it, you can
have it,'' said Graman, who leads similar workshops in Dallas and
San Francisco. So far, eight women, ages 25 to 65, have signed up
for the Manhattan course.
</P>
<P>
   You can just about guess what the editor of Ms. magazine thinks
of all this. ``I worry when women say women have to be soft
again,'' said Gloria Jacobs, the editor. ``Women are different from
men, but does that mean we're all soft and nurturing? That's
ridiculous. The goal is to have the freedom to be who you are.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Jacobs finds the whole concept of Graman's finishing
school rather annoying. ``Everyone wants relationships; that's
human nature,'' she said. `But what I don't get is the idea that
you can buy a relationship, or that if you spend enough money
you'll be able to communicate with another human being if you have
the right clothes or the right furniture.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why aren't men being encouraged to do this?'' Jacobs asked.
``Why does marriage have to be the end result here?''
</P>
<P>
   On a snowy afternoon in mid-February, Marks is in her
600-square-foot Upper West Side apartment with Graman, Robin
Lennon, an interior designer, and Debra Cox, an image consultant.
Today's lesson: making your home more man-friendly.
</P>
<P>
   ``What kind of thoughts do you want him to have when he walks in
the door?'' Graman asked. ``This is a Rorschach test. When a man
walks into a woman's house, he wants to feel that he has a space in
her world. That he belongs.''
</P>
<P>
   Gazing at her penguin collection, photographs of herself in
exotic locales, a Nordic Track and the bicycle leaning against her
sofa, Marks replied, ``I want to be comfortable here, and I want a
man to be, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``I work a lot, but I don't want to give that impression,'' she
said. ``I want playfulness in the apartment. I also don't want it
to look like a college dorm.''
</P>
<P>
   Walking from room to room, Lennon deconstructed the apartment
with a firm but gentle hand. Too many tchotchkes. Not enough light.
Dump the boom box. Scatter pillows on the bed. Spritz perfume on
the sheets. Get rid of clutter; it keeps men at bay. Paint the
walls in soft, sexy colors: salmon or peach or rose.
</P>
<P>
   And the bike? ``Do you use it?'' Lennon asked.
</P>
<P>
   Not in months, Marks said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you want someone to think you're athletic, it's good,''
Lennon said. ``Otherwise, could we put it in storage?'' Marks
nodded meekly.
</P>
<P>
   Next, the wardrobe. Since November, Marks had been out with 23
different men whom she met online and through dating services.
Mostly, they met after work when she was still in professional
garb.
</P>
<P>
   ``You need to have clothes that reflect all the sides of you,''
Cox said as she went through Marks's closet, which was filled with
corporate suits but lacking less formal attire. ``You want to be
professional, approachable, and feminine. You don't want men to
think you're a man.''
</P>
<P>
   She held up a dark blue wool skirt and jacket. ``This is fine
for the work world, but in the dating arena you want something a
little more approachable and feminine,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``A dark suit says, `I'm one of the guys,''' Graman added. ``A
buttoned-up jacket screams `I'm unapproachable.'''
</P>
<P>
   Cox then plucked a silk lavender suit from the closet. Her face
brightened.
</P>
<P>
   ``What a difference!'' she said. ``You look sexy and young.''
</P>
<P>
   Marks admired her reflection in the mirror. She clipped on a
pair of dangly silver earrings she had borrowed from Graman. The
women oohed and aahed. Marks smiled. Then she scribbled in a little
notebook. There was a lot to remember.
</P>
<P>
   If all this all seems a little dated, a little Cosmo, no one is
forcing women to enroll. According to Marks, her office colleagues
constantly ask for relationship advice and want her to conduct a
seminar based on her newfound knowledge.
</P>
<P>
   Graman said the women in her course must first be happy with
themselves; she lives by the motto ``the rose is itself and the bee
comes.'' She does not advise women to change themselves or to
deceive their men.
</P>
<P>
   In the '70s, she said, she was the stereotypical angry feminist.
But ``there was a softness that was missing in me,'' she said. ``I
wasn't getting everything I wanted that way, and it was time to
stop being angry at others.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course, the feminist movement needed to happen. In order to
make change, you need to go far to the other side. Women had to
stop being like women in order to be successful, and now we're
coming somewhere in the center. We're learning how powerful it can
be to be soft and tender.''
</P>
<P>
   Some women have worked with her and discovered that they do not
want to be married. Others have ended bad relationships. And
contrary to popular perception, she stressed, Manhattan is teeming
with men who are eager to tie the knot.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're not the enemy,'' she said. ``I see a lot of men in
business who are longing for a wife, for someone by their side.
When the house is empty, they feel lonely. That's why I have no
doubt that I can help a woman find a man, because I know there are
men out there that want to find her.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-02-00 2145EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000302.0415 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-02 21:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5082 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-DINNER-THEATER-REVIEW     03-02 0805
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DINNER-THEATER-REVIEW-ART-3TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`DINNER WITH FRIENDS': AT THE JUNCTION OF LIFE AND ART 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photos NYT3 and 4 are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
(bl) 
 By ROBIN POGREBIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In that first scene in a Connecticut kitchen _ with
its country table and canisters of beans, Trix cereal and tricolor
pasta on the counter _ you can almost smell the decaf brewing,
taste the lemon almond polenta cake Beth devours down to the last
crumb and ache with her as she confesses to her closest friends,
Karen and Gabe, that her husband, Tom, is leaving her for another
woman.
</P>
<P>
   And so it goes through the next six scenes of ``Dinner With
Friends,'' from the bedroom strewn with Beth's crumpled tissues,
where she and Tom ruthlessly confront each other later that
evening; to Karen and Gabe's well-appointed living room, where they
lounge on their couch mulling over Beth's news; to a rustic house
on Martha's Vineyard, where Karen chops garlic for a marinade and
Gabe slices limes for margaritas as they prepare to introduce Beth
to Tom more than a decade earlier; to Karen's sunny patio where,
over fruit salad, she and Beth painfully delve into their
differences; to a Manhattan bar, where the men do the same over
Pellegrino; and finally back to the Vineyard, where Karen and Gabe
slip between their crisp summer sheets and talk about what it takes
to tend a marriage.
</P>
<P>
   One wonders what it's like to perform the same play, night after
night, week after week, perhaps month after month or more. Does it
reach into the actors' private lives? Cause them to rethink values
or priorities? Perhaps even aggravate troubles in their personal
relationships?
</P>
<P>
   Given its delicate subject matter _ issues that cut so close to
the bone _ ``Dinner With Friends'' would seem to be an especially
challenging acting assignment. The play, written by Donald
Margulies (45, married for 13 years, with one child) and directed
by Daniel Sullivan (59, divorced three times) tackles thorny yet
elemental topics like how the pragmatic minutiae of a marriage _
``having kids ... having to pay the mortgage ... making the
deadline ... marinating the snapper,'' in Gabe's words _ can
eclipse the passion. It also explores what happens to friendships
when they are tested by change and time and whether even the
strongest ties can survive the truth.
</P>
<P>
   While all of this might be easily dismissed as the stuff of
daytime drama or just so much middle-class, middle-aged angst,
``Dinner With Friends'' appears to have proved itself a play for
our time. The universality of its perspective has clearly resonated
with audiences of varied ages. Largely on word of mouth, the play,
which cost $660,000 to mount at the Variety Arts Theater, has been
selling $20,000 worth of tickets a day, which is high for
off-Broadway. And Mitchell Maxwell, one of its producers, said he
expected to break even by the end of March. Postshow discussions
have been lively, indicating that ``Dinner With Friends'' strikes a
nerve and sends people into the street arguing about what they've
seen. Reviewing the play, Peter Marks wrote in The New York Times:
``It is wry and keenly observed and bathed in the unspoken sorrow
that can sneak up on you in middle age.''
</P>
<P>
   And the play, originally commissioned by the Actors Theater of
Louisville, is a hit in Paris, where it has been produced in
translation. The play had its world premiere in the 1998 Humana
Festival of New American Plays; a revised version was produced
later that year by South Coast Repertory in California.
</P>
<P>
   The dead-on realism of ``Dinner With Friends'' _ its familiar
dynamics and resonant details _ makes the play both compelling and
unsettling. The playwright said he once saw a man in the audience
pull on his coat at intermission and say to his companions, ``I'll
meet you after the show; this is just too close to home.''
</P>
<P>
   So if sitting through ``Dinner With Friends'' can be disquieting
for the audience, what, then, can living through it be like for the
actors? In interviews, each of the four performers in the
well-oiled ensemble talked about the experience of performing the
play over a long time. Carolyn McCormick is the only cast member
who has not been with the production since it opened in New York on
Nov. 4; she replaced Julie White as Beth on Jan. 4.
</P>
<P>
   The actors all touched on how ``Dinner With Friends'' has made
them look with new eyes at their own marriages and friendships,
along with those of their parents, colleagues and friends. They
said the play had made them examine the degree to which they
resemble the characters they play, relate to them, pity them,
admire them, judge them and forgive them.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Kilner (Tom)
</P>
<P>
   To watch Kevin Kilner play Tom is to believe that he must be
just like him in real life, so completely does he seem to inhabit
the role of a handsome corporate lawyer in midlife crisis who talks
about his emotional needs yet seems to lack emotional depth. But to
sit with Kilner, 41, over bowls of oatmeal and bananas is to
realize that Kilner plays Tom as thoroughly as he does precisely
because he has perspective on him. The actor has clearly given
considerable thought to what prompts Tom to make the choices he
does, to leave a wife and two children for a travel agent.
</P>
<P>
   ``While he may be able to function as a lawyer, he is
immature,'' Kilner said. ``He lacks the emotional vocabulary that
would enable him to be a good husband or father.''
</P>
<P>
   Just as there is no black and white in Margulies' play, Kilner's
response to his character is more complex than merely critical. In
fact, Kilner said, he has grown to respect Tom's decision to come
clean about his discontent and to try to do something about it.
``He's the first in the group of four to hold his hand up and say,
`I'm not happy,''' Kilner said. ``And the bottom line of anyone's
life is, `I should be happy.'''
</P>
<P>
   Kilner's response to his character wasn't always so nuanced. At
first, he said, he doubted his ability to pull off the part and
shared his misgivings with his wife, Jordan Baker, also an actress,
who was working in California at the time. ``I was calling her in
San Diego saying: `I don't know if I can do this guy. I don't
understand him in so many ways,''' Kilner said. ``It's hard to play
someone who's so unconscious when you've become conscious yourself
_ even hyper-conscious. It was hard for me to go back and play
someone who was irresponsible.''
</P>
<P>
   Kilner said that his role tended to elicit the most visceral _
even vocal _ reactions from the audience and that there had been
performances in which people burst out with such disparaging
responses to Tom's lines as, ``Oh, please, get over yourself'' and
``Tsk, tsk, tsk.''
</P>
<P>
   But Kilner said the words of one audience member made him feel
as if he had at least succeeded at making Tom more than a
one-dimensional adulterer, ``I hated you in the first act, but I
understood you in the second.''
</P>
<P>
   It was precisely to ensure that this insight into Tom would be
possible, Kilner said, that he spoke up on the third day of
rehearsal. ``I said, `I have to talk about something that's
bothering me,''' he recalled. ` ``I don't mention my children at
all, and I have no defense of why I did what I do.''' In response,
Kilner said, Margulies agreed to write additional lines for the bar
scene between Tom and Gabe that helped shed some light on Tom's
upbringing and how it might have shaped him.
</P>
<P>
   GABE: Marriages all go through a kind of base-line wretchedness
from time to time, but we do what we can to ride those patches out.
</P>
<P>
   TOM: Like my parents did? Like your parents? They ``rode it
out'' for 50 years! Is that what you'd want me to do? Is it? What
kind of example would that be setting for my kids? That we're all
powerless to change our lives? You make a mistake, too bad, you
just have to live with it?
</P>
<P>
   ``If you get some glimpse of what his childhood was _ that he
was emotionally malformed,'' Kilner said, ``you can hate that _
especially if you have had a bad experience with it _ but then you
have to accept it as a truth.''
</P>
<P>
   Kilner had been married just a year when he went into rehearsal
for ``Dinner With Friends,'' which he said created an odd
juxtaposition between beginning to build a marriage in real life
even as his marriage in the play was unraveling. ``It was weird to
be so unhappy when I was so happy,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Kilner's last performance will be on March 12; he said he would
then head for Los Angeles to try to earn more money in movies or
television. And while he feels he has no choice financially but to
leave, he said, he will forever be affected by ``Dinner With
Friends.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This play is really about how do you choose to live your life:
each individual person alone has to face this, has to make choices
and live with them,'' he said. ``It has powerful implications in
the arguments between all of them. They continually discover and
define for themselves what they will live with and not live with.
</P>
<P>
   Carolyn McCormick (Beth)
</P>
<P>
   All four actors in ``Dinner With Friends'' are married to other
actors; all but Kilner have children, and all described their
relationships with their spouses as self-aware and communicative.
</P>
<P>
   McCormick, who is in her late 30s, said the play prompted her to
think about her own marriage (to Byron Jennings) in relation to
that of her parents, who divorced when she was 24. ``It made me
continue to, with great vigilance, not take anything for granted,''
she said over coffee. ``It reaffirmed to me how delicate marriages
are and how much work and how worth it.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, all the actors spoke of marriage as something that takes
attentiveness and effort, given that long-term unions often suffer
from neglect. McCormick seemed to have a particularly relaxed
attitude toward cycles, believing that relationships' cool or tense
periods eventually pass.
</P>
<P>
   ``They can always be recharged,'' she said. ``Relationships are
not linear.''
</P>
<P>
   Because she is more circumspect than Beth in her own life and
tends to play controlling characters, McCormick said, she relishes
the out-there quality of her current role. ``I just love this
character,' McCormick said. ``I like her openness and her
accessibility. She just calls it like she sees it.
</P>
<P>
   ``She is such a great juxtaposition to Karen. Because she
doesn't try to control anything. She's a spewer.''
</P>
<P>
   The actress said the toughest spewing for her occurs in Act II
when she talks to Karen over lunch about how it feels to be in love
again after separating from Tom, and comes up against Karen's
obvious disapproval.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   BETH: You know what I think? I think you love it when I'm a
mess.
</P>
<P>
   KAREN: What?!
</P>
<P>
   BETH: You do. You love it when I'm all over the place, flailing
about. I finally find someone who's like a _ like an anchor and you
don't want to hear about it!
</P>
<P>
   KAREN: That is not true.
</P>
<P>
   BETH: As long as I'm artsy and incompetent, everything is fine.
The minute I show any signs of being on equal footing with you,
forget it; you can't deal with it, you have to knock me over!
</P>
<P>
   McCormick said different things influenced her performance,
including the audience. ``When I know someone is in the house, I'll
hear things through their ears,'' she said. ``If I have a friend
out there who's going through divorce or someone who has had a
husband say some of those things. So every night it's a little
different, because different things are coursing through my mind.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You do think a lot about your life,'' added McCormick, who
gave birth to her second son four months ago. (Her first is 3.)
``You think about the kids' reality of a father leaving and just
how truly tragic that is. I still can't help feel a great
sadness.''
</P>
<P>
   Matthew Arkin (Gabe)
</P>
<P>
   If the roles of Tom and Beth are something of a stretch for
Kilner and McCormick, Matthew Arkin says he was born to play Gabe.
He almost failed to land the part, he said, and told his agent to
tell the director he would ``crawl through glass'' to get it. After
several call-backs, he succeeded.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe what it says about marriage, about what it takes to
make that commitment work,'' the 39-year-old actor said over a bowl
of Chinese noodles. ``That it's hard, back-breaking work for the
best reward you can possibly get, but if you don't pay attention to
it, it can stall.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always had that philosophy. But this play sharpened it, or
said it in a way that says it better than I ever could.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet he is not entirely Gabe, Arkin said: ``I'm a little bit
better at confrontation than Gabe is. I'm a little bit better about
getting in there and talking about the hard stuff with my wife. I
go to therapy; Gabe doesn't. I think if Gabe did, he'd be just like
me in a few years.''
</P>
<P>
   Even though he is already very much in sync with his character,
Arkin said, playing the role, along with growing older and being a
parent (he and his wife, Pamela Newkirk-Arkin, have a 2-year-old
son), has changed him in certain ways. ``It's made me be a little
bit more forgiving,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In particular, Arkin said he had come to realize that Gabe has
little right to feel betrayed by Tom's betrayal of his wife. ``Your
best friend doesn't promise to stay married so you can grow old
together,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   There are moments in the play, Arkin said, when he is supposed
to cry and can't, as in the final bedroom scene, and moments when
he can't help it, as in the bar scene. ``It's very upsetting to me,
the loss of that friendship,'' he said. ``When I get to the part,
`We had a vow . . .'''
</P>
<P>
   GABE: We had a vow, too, you know. Not a marriage, but something
like it.
</P>
<P>
   TOM: Yeah?
</P>
<P>
   GABE: We were supposed to get old and fat together, the four of
us, and watch each other's kids grow up, and cry together at their
weddings . . .
</P>
<P>
   TOM: It's not like I'm dead, you know . . .
</P>
<P>
   GABE: I guess I mean, I thought we were in this together. You
know? For life.
</P>
<P>
   Arkin said the final scene with Emery, in which Gabe and Karen
talk about ``when practical matters begin to outweigh . . .
abandon,'' is also loaded with emotion for him _ particularly
because he is the child of divorced parents and his father, the
actor Alan Arkin, recently divorced his second wife after 34 years
of marriage.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm so much in the middle of that now,'' Arkin said. ``What my
wife and I are battling _ how do you keep all that stuff that got
you going in the beginning alive?
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm still scared because of what my parents went through,'' he
continued. ``I worry that there are all these hidden land mines I
don't know anything about. I sometimes say, `Who am I to think I'm
going to make it?'''
</P>
<P>
   Lisa Emery (Karen)
</P>
<P>
   The backstage set changes in ``Dinner With Friends'' amount to
something of a show all their own, particularly given how ambitious
they are for a tight off-Broadway house.
</P>
<P>
   On a revolving stage that is within inches of a wall, with the
requisite rapid-fire speed and muscular grace, seven crew members
manage to transform the play's highly specific environments,
designed by Neil Patel, seven times, down to the most specific
details, from the Chex mix on the bar to the toy dinosaurs on the
sisal rug in Karen and Gabe's living room to the square ceramic
plate on a bureau containing odd items that could have been dumped
from Beth's purse or Tom's pocket: a match box, a pencil, a stray
Tootsie Roll, loose change.
</P>
<P>
   Depending on who's remembering, building the Martha's Vineyard
house for the top of Act II initially took 50 to 90 minutes in
technical rehearsals before the show opened out of town in
Stamford, Conn. Now the crew does it during the 20-minute
intermission, down to the many household items itemized on the prop
list: ginger grater, shallot, paring knife, four carrot sticks.
</P>
<P>
   Lisa Emery, along with her fellow actors, said that those
physical details helped ground her performance, that actually
making a marinade _ she considered jarring it to take home but gave
up on the idea _ made the experience of the play much more real,
even though her hands end up smelling of garlic and scallions for
the rest of the evening.
</P>
<P>
   The final scene in a Martha's Vineyard bedroom seems perhaps the
most spare and pristine, from the still unpacked open suitcase
containing fresh linens and an alarm clock, suggesting Karen and
Gabe's recent arrival, to the books on the warmly lighted bedside
tables _ for her ``In Nonna's Kitchen: Recipes and Traditions From
Italy's Grandmothers,'' for him ``State of the Union'' (with folded
reading glasses on top).
</P>
<P>
   With a wicker chest at the foot of the bed and two photos on the
walls, the room becomes a tranquil beach home on a soft summer
evening. One can almost hear the crickets and feel the night's
coolness through the sheer white curtain over the doorway.
</P>
<P>
   At one recent performance, out of sight of the audience, Emery
came in and lay down on her back on the bed before the scene began.
She said later that the scene was the most difficult one to do
because of the part when Gabe says, ``Boo.''
</P>
<P>
   The boo recalls a joke the couple shared when they were young;
Gabe would pretend to scare Karen, and the boo that followed would
lead to lovemaking. ``It was hard at the beginning because I wasn't
sure what was the right approach,'' Emery said over a maple scone.
``I think what we've arrived at is, you see two people who are
still connected, although they don't think that little game is
going to fix anything. But you see them trying.''
</P>
<P>
   Emery, who is in her 40's, said being in a play that is so
familiar felt both simpler and more complicated than other
projects. ``In some ways it's easier,'' she said. ``You don't have
to go in and put on tight foundation garments and high heels.
You're comfortable. You're in your own home, it's just like life,
there's no time tripping.
</P>
<P>
   ``On the other hand, that's what makes it hard. You live your
life with your husband and your kid, and you go into the theater
and live your life with your husband and your kids.''
</P>
<P>
   Emery said she and her husband, Josh Pais, already had the kind
of frankness that Karen and Gabe are fumbling toward. ``We're
always stock-taking and kind of assessing our marriage and where it
is,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, she said, ``Dinner With Friends'' prompted a
deeper level of introspection, as well as an even more profound
appreciation for her husband, their 6-year-old son and what they
have built together.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't dive that deeply into a play without its having an
effect on your life,'' she said. ``It permeates your life. Just the
way your life permeates a play.''
</P>
<P>
   WHEN AND WHERE
</P>
<P>
   ``Dinner With Friends'' is at the Variety Arts Theater, 110
Third Ave., at 13th Street, East Village, (212) 239-6200.
Performances are Tuesdays through Fridays at 8 p.m., Saturdays at 3
and 8 p.m. and Sundays at 3 and 7:30 p.m. Tickets are $30 and $55.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
