<HEADLINE>
PINOCHET, RELEASED FROM BRITAIN, FACES A BATTLE AT HOME 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also PINOCHET) 
(sw) 
 By CLIFFORD KRAUSS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SANTIAGO, Chile _ Britain abruptly dropped extradition
proceedings on Thursday against Gen. Augusto Pinochet, who then
headed home to Chile where his political opponents were waiting,
intent on making him face months, if not years, of additional court
proceedings.
</P>
<P>
   After 16 months of house arrest in distant London, where he
waited out excruciating legal twists and turns, Pinochet was told
by Britain's home secretary, Jack Straw, early on Thursday that
because of his failing health he did not have to stand trial in
Spain on charges of gross human rights violations.
</P>
<P>
   Although Straw's ruling ended Pinochet's plight in Europe, his
case is expected to have far-reaching implications in international
law governing human rights violations.
</P>
<P>
   The 84-year-old former dictator was accused of abducting,
torturing and executing thousands of political prisoners during his
17-year authoritarian rule in Chile. As the case now shifts to his
homeland, it will undoubtedly have an important political impact on
the new civilian government and the still-powerful armed forces.
</P>
<P>
   President-elect Ricardo Lagos, a Socialist who takes office in
nine days, has promised to let justice run its course. But the
departing government of President Eduardo Frei is quietly pushing a
constitutional reform that would allow Pinochet to give up his
current position in the Senate and retain parliamentary immunity
from prosecution.
</P>
<P>
   About 50 people who had family members disappear during
Pinochet's years in power sat up most of the night holding hands
and singing folk songs while waiting for Straw's decision at the
headquarters of a human rights group. When news arrived that
Pinochet was free, they broke into sobs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Until the last minute we thought Jack Straw would allow the
extradition,'' said Viviana Diaz, president of Family Members of
the Disappeared, ``but we always had to take into account the
enormous political effort our government made toward Britain,
Spain, France and Belgium to free Pinochet.'' But despite her
disappointment, she added, ``Pinochet left Chile as the king of the
world, and he returns a criminal condemned morally by the world.''
</P>
<P>
   By the afternoon, Diaz and other activists were in court filing
a petition to revoke Pinochet's senatorial immunity, which was
granted along with his status as a senator for life under a
Constitution written while he was still in power.
</P>
<P>
   Removal of his immunity would be necessary before an indictment
could go forward in a case alleging his involvement with a military
death squad known as the Caravan of Death, which removed scores of
political prisoners from police and army jails for execution the
month after the 1973 coup that overthrew President Salvador
Allende, a Socialist.
</P>
<P>
   Across Santiago, a hundred supporters of Pinochet celebrated at
the offices of the Pinochet Foundation with patriotic chants and
songs. But while expressing relief that the former dictator was
returning home, they said Chile's sovereignty had been sullied and
their leader had been humiliated.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one won, everyone lost,'' said Luis Cortes Villa, a retired
general who is executive director of the foundation, a private
group that promotes the former dictator's image. ``There is really
nothing to celebrate when an ex-president is arrested arbitrarily
and unfairly.''
</P>
<P>
   The government and armed forces are going out of their way to
ensure that Pinochet's arrival on Friday morning will be as
uneventful as possible. He is scheduled to land in a northern
desert town before finally arriving in Santiago, where family
members, military commanders and leaders of the Pinochet Foundation
will give him a ceremonial welcome that will not be open to the
public.
</P>
<P>
   The former dictator will then be taken to the Military Hospital
for a medical checkup that will last at least two days. Officials
said he could remain there under tight security for several weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Judge Juan Guzman Tapia of the Santiago Appeals Court, who is
investigating 60 criminal complaints against the former dictator,
has requested a battery of other medical tests be done by doctors
chosen by the courts in preparation for a possible trial. Under
Chilean law, findings of dementia or mental impairment _ though not
physical ill health _ would protect Pinochet from legal
proceedings. Last month, two newspapers in Spain quoted British
medical reports as saying that he had suffered brain damage during
two minor strokes in recent months.
</P>
<P>
   For more than a year Chilean officials argued that Spain's
request to have Pinochet sent to Madrid to stand trial on torture
charges was unnecessary because the justice system here could try
him. Now that claim will be put to the test, with the armed forces
and the first Socialist president since Allende watching the case
closely.
</P>
<P>
   Guzman has been engaged in an aggressive investigation into
Pinochet's possible connection to more than 2,000 political deaths
and tens of thousands of tortures. And his ruling last year that an
amnesty decree that covered the years between 1973 and 1978 did not
cover disappearances of people who remain missing has opened the
way for the arrests of about 50 retired military and police
officers.
</P>
<P>
   But to prosecute Pinochet, Guzman must first request that the
Santiago Appeals Court lift the parliamentary immunity that
accompanies his position as a senator for life. That process could
take months or years, including appeals to the Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   In a candlelight vigil on Thursday night in front of La Moneda,
the presidential palace, 500 protesters chanted ``No to the
amnesty, no to immunity, the blood of the dead is not negotiable.''
</P>
<P>
   Apparently in an effort to nudge Pinochet out of his Senate
position, Frei and a coalition of moderate and conservative
legislators have proposed a new constitutional provision that would
allow him to retire from the Congress but retain his senatorial
privileges, including salary and legal immunity.
</P>
<P>
   Human rights advocates say that the measure, which appears
headed for passage at the end of the month, would give Pinochet
extra protection because there would be no provision in the law to
strip immunity from a former president who is no longer serving in
the Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Lagos has not spoken on the proposed constitutional measure
publicly. But while attending the presidential inauguration of
Jorge Batlle in Uruguay on Wednesday, he said: ``The conditions
exist to judge Senator-for-Life Augusto Pinochet. If that were not
the case, it would be as if to say we have a castrated democracy.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   For Socialists like Lagos who have served in the current
Christian Democratic-Socialist coalition government, working for
Pinochet's release has been a bitter experience forced by their
need to get along with the powerful military and defend the
country's sovereignty.
</P>
<P>
   That explains why at the moment of a long-sought diplomatic
victory, Foreign Minister Juan Gabriel Valdes' reaction to the news
from London was so distraught. ``This has been a disgraceful affair
that has damaged the image of Chile throughout the world,'' said
Valdes, a Socialist. ``And the principal person responsible for
that is General Pinochet himself.''
</P>
<P>
   The coming judicial deliberations in Chile are bound to be
complex.
</P>
<P>
   Human rights lawyers are likely to argue against any
parliamentary immunity defenses and against the 1973-1978 amnesty
decree as contrary to new precedents in international law that
invalidate amnesties and statutes of limitations in cases of crimes
against humanity such as torture. The Supreme Court would most
likely have to rule on this point before lower courts could judge
the former dictator.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Pinochet's lawyers are expected to argue that Guzman
does not have grounds to investigate alleged crimes committed on
military premises or during acts of military service and that any
case against the former dictator should be decided before a
military tribunal. In the past, civilian courts have given military
tribunals wide authority in cases involving military personnel.
Again, the Supreme Court would have to decide.
</P>
</TEXT>
