<SLUG> BC-NY-DIALLO-590&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DIALLO FAMILY MEETS WITH JUSTICE OFFICIALS TO SEEK U.S.
PROSECUTIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By AMY WALDMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The family of Amadou Diallo met with Justice
Department officials Thursday to press for federal prosecution of
the four police officers who were acquitted last week in the death
of Diallo, as hundreds of supporters rallied outside to express
their continuing outrage over the verdict.
</P>
<P>
   Deputy Attorney General Eric Holder, the Justice Department's
second-ranking official, released a statement after the meeting
saying that the department was reviewing all information related to
the shooting to determine whether federal civil rights laws were
violated.
</P>
<P>
   Mary Jo White, the U.S. attorney in Manhattan, opened the
federal investigation into the shooting soon after Diallo, an
unarmed African immigrant, was killed in a hail of 41 bullets on
Feb. 4, 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Holder's statement read in part: ``While I explained that the
standard to proceed in federal court is high, I indicated that the
review is a priority, that we have not ruled anything out and that
it will be conducted as thoroughly and expeditiously as possible.''
</P>
<P>
   That review will begin with the case's paper record: pulling
together all documents, from the trial transcript and videotape to
everything collected during the investigation. The officers'
testimony is likely to be examined closely, since it was the first
time they had publicly spoken about the case. If holes are found in
the investigation, federal officials may then undertake further
investigation of their own in an effort to uncover additional
evidence.
</P>
<P>
   Diallo's parents, Kadiatou and Saikou, and their daughter,
Laura, were accompanied by an entourage that included the Rev. Al
Sharpton; their lawyers; former Mayor David Dinkins; eight members
of Congress; Kwesi Mfume, the president of the National Association
for the Advancement of Colored People; and the Rev. Jesse Jackson's
wife, Jacqueline.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have hope,'' said Kadiatou Diallo, Diallo's mother, after
the meeting. Sharpton said Holder told the family that the review
was a priority not only for him, but for the president and the
attorney general.
</P>
<P>
   Still, federal officials seem to be trying to make sure the
family's hopes are not too high. At his morning briefing, Holder
reiterated that ``these are difficult cases to prosecute,'' and
said the federal government took on only about two such cases a
year.
</P>
<P>
   To undertake a second, or dual, prosecution of the officers,
there must be a substantial federal interest in the case and the
government must determine that that interest was ``unvindicated''
by the state prosecution.
</P>
<P>
   To find that its interest was not vindicated, the federal
government would have to find, for example, that the prosecution in
the state trial was incompetent _ an argument that the Diallos and
their lawyers have been making with increasing stridency _ or that
there was ``jury nullification,'' when a jury ignores the evidence
before it.
</P>
<P>
   Anthony Gair, one of Mrs. Diallo's lawyers, said he believed the
judge's legal instructions to the jury, which were generally
considered favorable to the defense, effectively nullified the
jury's function.
</P>
<P>
   But in the end, federal officials are likely to bring charges
only if they believe they have a case in which they could obtain a
conviction.
</P>
<P>
   That depends on whether existing evidence or evidence that was
not known at trial shows the officers had a willful intent to use
more force than was reasonably necessary.
</P>
<P>
   All of those guidelines were explained to the Diallos in the
meeting, which lasted nearly two hours.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Afterward, the Diallos and Sharpton emerged to rally the
protesters gathered outside. ``We do not want this decision to be
used to justify and acquit some other officers who might do the
same thing,'' Mrs. Diallo said.
</P>
<P>
   Laura Diallo, the 21-year-old sister of Amadou Diallo, made her
first public appearance, telling the crowd, ``I cannot explain what
I go through every night when I see my mother break down in front
of me or when my two brothers tell me they miss my brother.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Diallo has made a concerted effort to keep her three
remaining children _ Laura and her brothers, Ibrahima and Abdul,
who are 17 and 16 _ out of the spotlight.
</P>
<P>
   As the meeting went on inside, a variety of speakers denounced
police conduct in minority communities. Among them was the former
mayor of Washington, Marion Barry, who told the crowd, ``We must do
all we can to stop these mad dog cops.''
</P>
<P>
   The presence of the crowd, which came from up and down the East
Coast, suggested that anger over the killing and the verdict showed
no sign of abating.
</P>
<P>
   Linda Cox, a 42-year-old postal worker from Paterson, N.J, came
down with two busloads of people from New Jersey. ``When you're
passionate about something you have to show your support,'' she
said. Melody Cooper came from Hastings, N.Y., with her father and
two young children, and said she would keep protesting until she
felt justice had been done. ``Race does matter,'' she said. ``Race
is the very crux of the issue.''
</P>
<P>
   When Sharpton emerged after the meeting, he announced that he
would lead the crowd around the Justice Department seven times,
until ``the blue walls of silence'' came down. So enthusiastic was
the crowd that they marched around the building more than a dozen
times.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
