<SLUG> BC-FBC-COWBOYS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COWBOYS SIGN CORNERBACK MCNEIL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CHAREAN WILLIAMS 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING _ Ryan McNeil concedes he is not Deion Sanders, but then,
who else is?
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys have not officially bid farewell to Sanders, but
McNeil arrived at Valley Ranch yesterday looking a lot like
Sanders' replacement at right cornerback. McNeil, who led the
league with nine interceptions in 1997, became the first
unrestricted free agent from another team to sign with the Cowboys,
agreeing to a five-year contract worth up to $18 million. The deal
can be voided by either side after one season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't look at it as replacing him,'' said McNeil, who spent
last season with the Cleveland Browns. ``I look at it as coming in
and doing what I can do and what I've been doing. I don't think
anything's going to change about that. I think I'm pretty good at
what I do. If I wasn't, I wouldn't be here.''
</P>
<P>
   Sanders remains a member of the Cowboys in name.
</P>
<P>
   Sanders, who is in spring training with the Cincinnati Reds, has
said his five-year career with the Cowboys is over. On June 2, the
Cowboys are expected to void his contract, which would count $12.7
million against their salary cap next season.
</P>
<P>
   But owner Jerry Jones is not yet prepared to write off Sanders
as an ex-Cowboy despite McNeil's signing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think we should,'' Jones said. ``We're spending some
money \Ron McNeil\S, but I don't want to go there.''
</P>
<P>
   McNeil, who has 20 interceptions and 396 tackles in his career,
chose the Cowboys over the New York Giants and the San Francisco
49ers for the chance to ``get a ring.'' The Cowboys chose McNeil
over New York Giants cornerback Phillippi Sparks because of
McNeil's size and durability.
</P>
<P>
   McNeil, who is 6-foot-2, 192 pounds, has played in 110 of a
possible 112 games during his seven-year career, including 89 as a
starter. He has a streak of 86 consecutive games played.
</P>
<P>
   ``We looked at him a year ago and thought he was one of the top
guys out there,'' Cowboys defensive coordinator Mike Zimmer said.
``He has an advantage, because of his size and his long arms. We
think he can play bump-and-run against some of the bigger receivers
in our division.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys are the fourth team for McNeil since the Detroit
Lions drafted him 33rd overall in 1993. Free agency also took
McNeil to stops in St. Louis and Cleveland.
</P>
<P>
   He has played for six defensive coordinators in seven seasons,
and he has had a series of one-year contracts. He left more than
$10 million on the table from the Rams in 1998 and instead settled
for a one-year deal.
</P>
<P>
   Last season, he signed a one-year, $1.5 million deal with the
Browns on July 31, a week after training camp had begun.
</P>
<P>
   McNeil has a multiyear contract for the first time in five
years, although it is structured like a one-year deal that will pay
him slightly more than he made last season in base salary.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a good opportunity for us because of the circumstances
that he's had in St. Louis and in Cleveland,'' Jones said.
``Because of his contract negotiations, he's missed some minicamps,
some training camps. I buy into that. Given an off-season where he
doesn't have his contract on his mind, that'll help him get to
where he's physically capable of being as a corner.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones said the Cowboys' next move will come in finding a backup
quarterback for Troy Aikman. The Cowboys are in the process of
scheduling a visit for Scott Mitchell, a 10-year veteran who spent
last season with the Baltimore Ravens.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
