<SLUG> BC-RAC-PRICE-REPORT-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW ORLEANS SHOWS LUKAS THE MONEY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TIM PRICE 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Trainer D. Wayne Lukas is fibbing. He is, if
you believe he's in the racehorse business because of the money.
</P>
<P>
   OK. So that's a big reason.
</P>
<P>
   But Lukas would have you believe that he isn't always after the
quick buck. With that consideration, maybe he's not kidding when he
says he doesn't hold Exchange Rate with more regard than High
Yield. They appear to be the best colts he has pointed toward the
Kentucky Derby.
</P>
<P>
   Here's the situation: While High Yield is training toward the
Derby in Florida, Exchange Rate is based in New Orleans. In our
``Show me the money!'' generation, there's a huge difference
between the two.
</P>
<P>
   The operators at the Fair Grounds in New Orleans are offering a
$500,000 bonus to any horse that wins the Louisiana Derby on March
12 and the Kentucky Derby on May 6. There is no bonus for High
Yield or any horse at Gulfstream Park in Florida.
</P>
<P>
   Lukas admits, or boasts, this much: ``We've won more
million-dollar bonuses than anybody.''
</P>
<P>
   But he won't admit this: Exchange Rate is a better horse than
High Yield.
</P>
<P>
   It looks that way, at least according to the quick-buck litmus
test. Since there is a bonus for sweeping the Louisiana Derby and
Kentucky Derby, wouldn't Lukas have his best horse chasing it?
</P>
<P>
   ``The bonus never enters into our thinking,'' Lukas said. ``It's
great to have it laying out there. Yet, that is not the underlying
thing when we make our plans.''
</P>
<P>
   Hardee har-har. But wait before you laugh. Lukas' plans may
balance in other places besides the accountant's ledger.
</P>
<P>
   It's logical to send High Yield to Gulfstream. He ran a
competitive race there in the Breeders' Cup Juvenile, leading with
about a half-mile to go before he wilted under Anees' big run.
</P>
<P>
   High Yield's running style is laced with early speed. And early
speed works at Gulfstream, even if it didn't that one race in the
Breeders' Cup. It did when he shot immediately to the front and won
the Fountain of Youth Stakes two weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   Fair Grounds, on the other hand, has a track configuration with
a longer stretch run. It blunts the advantage of early speed.
</P>
<P>
   And it's widely regarded to have a racing surface that's kind to
a horse's legs. That's what Exchange Rate needs. His 2-year-old
season was cut short when he suffered a condylar] fracture in an
ankle.
</P>
<P>
   He's mended. His victory in the $125,000 Risen Star Stakes two
weeks ago at Fair Grounds offers proof.
</P>
<P>
   But if Lukas isn't running for the quick buck, it looks as if]
the rest of the training community is. Right now, the
bonus-attached Louisiana Derby is shaping up stronger _ way
stronger _ than the Florida Derby. It's usually the other way
around.
</P>
<P>
   When High Yield enters the starting gate for the Florida Derby,
it's likely the field of eight or 10 horses will include only one
other horse that's won a major stakes race. And that's Greenwood
Lake, but he hasn't finished in the top three of a race this year
after winning the Champagne and the Remsen Stakes last year.
</P>
<P>
   Here are a few of the horses Exchange Rate is expected to face
in the Louisiana Derby: Captain Steve, More Than Ready, Mighty and
Country Only. More than seven major stakes wins among them, and
three horses (Captain Steve, More Than Ready and Mighty) have won a
stakes race at the Derby site of Churchill Downs.
</P>
<P>
   If Lukas wants someone to show him the money, it's up to
Exchange Rate to get everyone else out of Lukas' view.
</P>
<P>
   Hurley now takes shot at the horse business
Bobby Hurley may no longer be a point guard, his glory days with
back-to-back national championship teams at Duke long behind him.
But he certainly isn't down on his luck.
</P>
<P>
   Hurley is now 28 and was cut from the NBA's Vancouver Grizzlies
more than a year ago. But he showed up at the Fasig-Tipton Calder
Selected 2-Year-Olds In-Training Sale in Miami on Tuesday and spent
$1 million on a horse.
</P>
<P>
   Hurley grew up in New Jersey and followed horse racing at area
tracks with his father and other family friends. He was Duke's
starting point guard when the Blue Devils won national
championships in 1991 and '92.
</P>
<P>
   Hurley's horse is one of four in the sale that brought more than
$1 million. The sale-topper was a $1.95 million colt bought by
Monte Carlo-based wagering book operator Michael Tabor.
</P>
<P>
   The colt Hurley purchased is by former 2-year-old champion
Unbridled's Song and out of a mare who has produced two stakes
winners who have earned more than $375,000.
</P>
<P>
   The colt is scheduled to be trained by John Dowd. But that may
be Hurley's only public relations problem in this deal.
</P>
<P>
   Dowd has been hit with a 180-day suspension from stewards at
Aqueduct Racetrack in New York because three of his horses tested
positive for a banned medication. The medication is known as
ergonovine, which use is permitted up to a week away from a race
but not on race day. In humans it's used to help migraine
headaches, but in horses it is designed to restrict bleeding in the
breathing passage. Dowd has appealed the ruling.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-02-00 2152EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000302.0423 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-02 21:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5094 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-SOTHEBY-EARNINGS-NYT &LR;      03-02 0776
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOTHEBY-EARNINGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOTHEBY'S REPORTS EARNINGS UNDER CLOUD OF INVESTIGATION 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Conn.)   (af)  
 By REED ABELSON and CAROL VOGEL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Sotheby's Holdings could do little to dispel
investors' concerns over the outcome of a federal antitrust
investigation Thursday as it discussed its Internet prospects and
fourth-quarter results.
</P>
<P>
   While Sotheby's earnings were slightly better than Wall Street
had expected, the company said it would eliminate its first-quarter
dividend because of ``significant cash needs'' from its online
forays and uncertainty surrounding the investigation.
</P>
<P>
   While William F. Ruprecht, the company's new chief executive,
spoke optimistically about Sotheby's future in holding auctions
over the Internet, he acknowledged the fierce competition for
blockbuster works of art and the challenges of proceeding in the
face of a criminal investigation and the threat to its reputation.
</P>
<P>
   The stock closed Thursday at $22, down $1.0625.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, the company's chairman, A. Alfred Taubman, and its
president and chief executive, Diana D. Brooks, stunned the art
world by abruptly resigning. Their departure came as the company
and its archrival, Christie's, were accused of colluding to fix the
commissions charged buyers and sellers. Both companies face tens of
millions of dollars in damages from class-action lawsuits, and
Sotheby's faces lawsuits from its shareholders.
</P>
<P>
   After becoming Sotheby's president in 1987, Brooks was the face
and voice of Sotheby's and played a vital role in deal-making and
client relations for the company. Ruprecht, who had run Sotheby's
operations in North and South America and is an auction house
veteran, has not been as closely involved with some of the
company's most important and richest clients.
</P>
<P>
   Although Brooks resigned her post, she and Taubman still remain
on the company's board, and she continues to play a role at the
company. During his discussion with analysts and investors,
Ruprecht described Brooks' role as helping the company ``on a
transitional basis with a number of client relationships.''
</P>
<P>
   When asked in an interview later about how long the two would
remain on the board, Ruprecht said he did not know but that the
board would next meet formally in April in London.
</P>
<P>
   Since her resignation, Brooks no longer has an office at the
newly expanded York Avenue headquarters in Manhattan. Nor has she
been in the building, according to a spokesman. But Ruprecht said
Brooks was still on the company's payroll and was attempting to
redirect long-standing client relationships to other executives
within Sotheby's.
</P>
<P>
   Ruprecht, a burly, outgoing man, clearly has a different
management style from the famously micromanaging Brooks. ``I'm
going to be much more a ringmaster than a star of the show,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   But Ruprecht shed little light on the progress of the Justice
Department's investigation. He said the company had recently met
with the department to discuss the investigation's ``prompt and
appropriate resolution'' but refused to predict the course of those
discussions.
</P>
<P>
   Despite repeated questions by analysts, the company also
remained silent about whether it was likely to reach a settlement
anytime soon and whether depositions were complete.
</P>
<P>
   Sotheby's has acknowledged that the impact of the matters could
be material, and the company announced Thursday that it had
eliminated its first-quarter dividend of 10 cents a share, partly
as a result of the potential damages.
</P>
<P>
   But the company also faces significant costs for its Internet
sites, Sothebys.Amazon.com and Sothebys.com. The company spent $42
million in 1999 and said it expected to spend another $60 million,
mostly in marketing costs, this year. Sotheby's projected as much
as $100 million in auction sales might take place online in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   While investors have focused on the Internet as the company's
future, Sotheby's also acknowledged that the high end of its
business was getting even more competitive and less profitable. The
company also said it did not expect its important spring sales of
Impressionist, modern and contemporary art to be as strong as they
were last year.
</P>
<P>
   In its results, Sotheby's said it earned $34.4 million, or 57
cents a diluted share, on revenue of $188 million in the fourth
quarter. Analysts had expected the company to earn 55 cents a
share.
</P>
<P>
   But some analysts say a lot is still up in the air. ``I think it
is going to take a lot of time to resolve,'' said Jeanne T. Hanley,
the president of Capital Reflections Inc., an independent research
firm in North Granby, Conn. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
