<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (pr) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Shares of Palm Pilot Maker Soar on First Day of Trading
</P>
<P>
   Continuing a wave of enthusiasm for companies involved in the
Internet and wireless communications, investors snapped up shares
of Palm, the maker of the Palm Pilot handheld devices. The shares
traded as high as $165, more than four times the offering price of
$38, before retreating to slightly more than $95. At that price,
the market is valuing Palm at $53.3 billion, far more than the
value of its parent, 3Com, which still owns most of the company.
Palm's market value is higher than that of many far larger
companies, including Ford, General Motors and Chevron.
</P>
<P>
   Inquiry Clouds Sotheby's Report
</P>
<P>
   Sotheby's Holdings could do little to dispel investors' concerns
over the outcome of a federal antitrust investigation as it
discussed its Internet prospects and posted better-than-expected
fourth-quarter results. While William F. Ruprecht, the company's
new chief executive, spoke optimistically about Sotheby's future in
holding auctions over the Internet, he acknowledged fierce
competition and the challenges of proceeding in the face of a
criminal investigation and the threat to its reputation. Last week,
the company's chairman, A. Alfred Taubman, and its president and
chief executive, Diana D. Brooks, abruptly resigned as the company
and its archrival, Christie's, were accused of colluding to fix
commissions.
</P>
<P>
   DoubleClick Backs Off Data Plan
</P>
<P>
   Yielding to pressure from privacy advocates and Wall Street,
DoubleClick, the Internet advertising company, said that it would
put a hold on its plan to link personal information to anonymous
data it collects about consumers on the Internet. By combining the
two, the company would be able to offer advertisers consumer's
identities and detailed personal information that tied people to
their Internet use and buying habits.
</P>
<P>
   Dow Edges Up, but Nasdaq Declines
</P>
<P>
   Blue-chip stocks moved higher while the Nasdaq market sagged.
The Dow Jones industrial average rose 26.99 points, or 0.27
percent, to 10,164.92. The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index edged
up 2.57 points, or 0.19 percent, to 1,381.76, while the Nasdaq
composite index lost 29.57 points, or 0.62 percent, to 4,754.51.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of Aetna Increase 5.3 Percent
</P>
<P>
   Investors bought up shares of Aetna again, but the buying spree
slowed as it became apparent that rival bidders were unlikely to
emerge to a $9.9 billion takeover offer from ING America Insurance
Holdings and WellPoint Health Networks. Shares of Aetna rose
$2.8125, or 5.3 percent, to $55.8125.
</P>
<P>
   February Retail Sales Rose 5.1 Percent
</P>
<P>
   Despite rising interest rates and oil prices, consumers
continued their spending spree in stores and on the Internet, two
reports showed. Retail sales rose 5.1 percent in February, while a
separate survey found that $5.3 billion worth of goods and services
were sold online in the fourth quarter of 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Jeanne Jackson, the Gap executive who is credited with building
the Banana Republic division into a retail powerhouse and who
started the Gap's online store, has resigned to become the new head
of Wal-Mart.com.
</P>
<P>
   3 Oil Ministers Back Rise in Output
</P>
<P>
   With the high cost of oil spreading alarm through Western
economies, oil ministers from Saudi Arabia, Venezuela and Mexico _
some of the world's major exporters _ agreed that production should
be increased to stabilize prices, but they declined to make firm
commitments on the timing or the amount.
</P>
</TEXT>
