<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-02 22:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5100 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-GUASTAVINO-CEILING-AR     03-02 1305
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GUASTAVINO-CEILING-ART-2TAKES(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENSUOUS CURVES ASCEND ABOVE THE HARD-EDGED CITY 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: A 125-word information box about a free guidebook appears at
end of story.) &HT;    (ART ADV: A photo is being sent. Nonsubscribers can purchase by
calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
 By DAVID W. DUNLAP  
(DW) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In a Guastavino tile ceiling, the sum of a thousand
right angles is a curve worthy of nature.
</P>
<P>
   True, the ceilings bespeak meticulous craftsmanship with their
intricate coursing, usually in a telltale basket-weave or
herringbone pattern. True, they evoke the architecture of
Catalonia, where the tradition grew of spanning large spaces with
thin, multilayered tile-and-mortar vaults.
</P>
<P>
   But what is most appealing about the ceilings produced in New
York in the early 20th century by the Spanish architect Rafael
Guastavino y Moreno and his son, Rafael Guastavino y Esposito, is
their sublime defiance of the rectilinear city.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM.)
</P>
<P>
   As New York is hard-edged and mechanistic, the ceilings are
sensuously organic; as it is tightly vertical, they are broadly
expansive; as it is brooding, they are joyous.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM.)
</P>
<P>
   What is astonishing about these great curving forms _ the
largest being the 135-foot-diameter dome of the Cathedral Church of
St. John the Divine _ is that they are made up of relentlessly
orthogonal building blocks: flat clay tiles, typically 6 inches by
12 inches.
</P>
<P>
   Today New York has a chance to fall in love again with
Guastavino.
</P>
<P>
   The opening this winter of the Bridgemarket development under
the Queensboro Bridge has focused the civic spotlight on a splendid
array of newly restored cream-colored Guastavino vaults in which
the project is set. It is also a reminder of how many such
treasures endure.
</P>
<P>
   A couple of Guastavino spaces are already postcard-familiar,
like the Registry Room at Ellis Island and the Oyster Bar at Grand
Central Terminal, both of which were restored in the 1990s. (But
most New Yorkers probably do not know that the large vault outside
the Oyster Bar works as a whispering gallery. Someone facing the
wall at one corner, speaking very softly, can be heard clearly by
another person facing the wall in the diagonally opposite corner,
40 feet away.)
</P>
<P>
   Other great Guastavino ceilings in Manhattan are in buildings
that may not be widely known but that amply repay a visit, like St.
Paul's Chapel at Columbia University, Holy Trinity Roman Catholic
Church at 213 West 82nd Street, and Recreation Center 54 East at
348 East 54th Street, with a gymnasium ceiling that rivals those of
the churches.
</P>
<P>
   Still others are in landmarks not commonly associated with the
Guastavinos: St. Patrick's Cathedral, Riverside Church, St.
Bartholomew's Church, the Bronx Zoo, the Municipal Building and the
Federal Reserve Bank. In the 38th Street side entrance of Lord &AMP;
Taylor, for example, is a small ceiling of Guastavino tiles
inscribed with a gold-edged fret pattern.
</P>
<P>
   Then there are Guastavino spaces whose existence is almost a
matter of archaeological interest. They are under the traffic
circle at Riverside Drive and 79th Street. A small colony of
basket-weave vaults can be found in an unused arcade near the
southern end of the downtown platform at the 34th
Street-Pennsylvania Station stop on the No. 1 and 9 lines.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM.)
</P>
<P>
   An entire subway station made of Guastavino vaults and arches
lies directly under City Hall Park, closed since the 1940s. A
garage ramp crowned by basket-weave tiles can be spotted on East
44th Street, between Madison and Vanderbilt Avenues, at the base of
an office building reconstructed from the Biltmore Hotel.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM.)
</P>
<P>
   By far the best behind-the-scenes view of the Guastavino
engineering system can be had every other Saturday at the Cathedral
of St. John the Divine as part of the aptly named vertical tour,
which involves a 12-story ascent through spiral staircases up the
south side of the nave.
</P>
<P>
   At the top of the clerestory, about 105 feet above the floor,
visitors are treated to a breathtaking vista of the vaulted ceiling
from a small bridge across an interior buttress, framed by the
cusps of a multifoil rosette more than 10 feet in diameter.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM.)
</P>
<P>
   (Obviously this tour is not for acrophobes.)
</P>
<P>
   The ceiling surface is not in the customary basket-weave
pattern. Instead the courses vary in height and the tiles vary in
width. ``He wanted to give the illusion of a stone vault,''
explained Andrea Yost, director of public education at the
cathedral.
</P>
<P>
   The illusion is broken at the next stop on the tour: a vast
attic chamber almost 40 feet high between the top of the nave
ceiling and the peak of the gabled cathedral roof.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM.)
</P>
<P>
   Visitors emerge on a slender catwalk where they can begin to
discern the outlines of the 225-foot-long nave ceiling at their
feet as their eyes grow accustomed to the dim light. With its
curves and peaks and folds and protrusions and scales, the ceiling
resembles a gigantic dormant dragon. On closer inspection, though,
one realizes that the scales are actually Guastavino tiles, reddish
brown in color, with a distinctive surface striation. This vantage
affords the chance to appreciate the engineering of a Guastavino
vault, which is self-supporting, made up of layer after layer of
thin tile and thick mortar.
</P>
<P>
   Testament to the durability of a Guastavino vault is the dome
over the cathedral crossing, which was supposed to be only a
temporary covering when it was built 91 years ago. Elsewhere in the
cathedral one can see the familiar basket-weave pattern in the
ceilings of the ambulatory aisle and in two exquisite corkscrew
staircases spiraling to the organ loft.
</P>
<P>
   Another curving Guastavino staircase is on view just inside the
entrance of St. Paul's Chapel at Columbia, completed in 1907. Here
the tiles are close enough to touch, and one can appreciate at this
intimate range another distinctive feature of the Guastavino
system: the raised mortar joints, which extend about one-quarter
inch beyond the tile surface.
</P>
<P>
   St. Paul's is a riot of Guastavino handiwork, from the
48-foot-diameter dome to the apse and even the undersides of the
galleries, all in a rich earth-tone palette of cinnamon, wheat,
chocolate and burnt orange.
</P>
<P>
   An even larger Guastavino dome, some 66 feet in diameter,
ornaments Holy Trinity, which was finished in 1912. Always
majestic, the dome is more glorious since the installation a year
and a half ago of new fixtures at the base of the ceiling that
bathe it in light.
</P>
<P>
   How are the acoustics? ``Magnificent!'' declared the pastor,
Msgr. Thomas P. Leonard, clapping smartly as he said so, allowing
the long return to impress itself on a visitor.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a miniature Hagia Sophia,'' Leonard said, explaining that
the founding pastor of Holy Trinity, Michael J. Considine, returned
from a trip to the Middle East with the idea of emulating the
Byzantine cathedral of Constantinople. The Guastavino system was
ideally suited for the task of reproducing a broad, shallow dome
like that of Hagia Sophia.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the cohesive strength and the relatively light weight
of tile courses compared with stone, greater spans with a very low
rise were possible, wrote Janet Parks and Alan G. Neumann in ``The
Old World Builds the New,'' the catalog of a Guastavino exhibition
at Columbia University in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a perfect Manhattan solution: you could get this
structure in a building for relatively little money, and it took up
so little room,'' said Parks, curator of drawings at the Avery
Architectural and Fine Arts Library at Columbia, where the
Guastavino company archives are kept.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The older Guastavino was born in Valencia, Spain, in 1842. He
moved to New York in 1881, bringing with him an adaptation of a
centuries-old building technique known as the boveda catalana, or
Catalan vault, that he had perfected as an architect in Barcelona.
The Guastavino Fireproof Construction Co. was incorporated in 1889.
On the death of the founder in 1908, his son took over the business
``so smoothly that many are unaware of the existence of two Rafael
Guastavinos,'' Angela Giral wrote in ``The Old World Builds the
New.''
</P>
<P>
   The younger Guastavino lived until 1950, and the company
survived until 1963, when it was liquidated after the completion of
its last big project, the National Shrine of the Immaculate
Conception in Washington. Its archives were transferred to Columbia
at the behest of Prof. George R. Collins, an authority on the work
of the pre-eminent Catalan architect, Antonio Gaudi.
</P>
<P>
   Gaudi comes easily to mind when one stands at the base of the
Municipal Building, across from City Hall. Although it looks like a
Beaux-Arts wedding cake on the skyline, its open-air Guastavino
arcade is a marvel of organic complexity. Billowing curves seem to
bump into one another like giant amoeba in an upside-down petri
dish.
</P>
<P>
   Far more regimented are the vaults under the Queensboro Bridge,
marching four abreast from First Avenue, where they leap across the
street in a 90-foot arc and proceed eastward for another nine bays
that once served as a farmers' market hall for produce coming in
from Long Island.
</P>
<P>
   The vaults are typically 30 feet square and rise eight feet from
the top of the columns on which they sit. They are made of one
layer of ``face tile'' _ that is, the cream-colored tile visible
from below _ and four layers of backing tile. (The layering
technique is clearly visible in the edges of the ribs between
vaults.)
</P>
<P>
   In December 1996 the city Transportation Department began a $3
million restoration of the Guastavino tile work as part of a much
larger renovation of the bridge. The contractor was Grow-Perini,
and the masonry restoration subcontractor was the Graciano Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Vollmer, the project manager for Graciano's New York
division, recalled conditions under the Queensboro three years ago.
``You'd be walking around and whap! a tile would come down,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Each vault has more than 1,600 face tiles. They were all tested.
``If it gives a firm sound, the mortar is sufficient,'' said Peter
E. Johe, the director of design and construction at the
Transportation Department for the East River bridges. ``If it
sounds hollow, that probably means there's a void behind it.''
</P>
<P>
   About half the face tiles had to be replaced with new ones made
by Boston Valley Terra Cotta, near Buffalo. Except for the new
tiles' slightly higher sheen, their presence is almost
undetectable.
</P>
<P>
   Engineers were impressed that tile failures in the 86-year-old
vaults were randomly dispersed. ``There were no real high-stress
points that we saw,'' said James P. Cusack, engineer in charge of
the Queensboro Bridge reconstruction project at the Transportation
Department. ``That's testimony to how good structurally these
arches are.''
</P>
<P>
   The easternmost bay, however, had to be rebuilt from scratch to
isolate it from steel girders that vibrate heavily with overhead
traffic.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the first rebuild of a Guastavino vault in the United
States,'' said Gino Marchese of Graciano, who supervised a team
from the Bricklayers and Allied Craftworkers union, using skills he
began acquiring as a boy from his grandfather, Americo J. Gonano,
who was a stonemason.
</P>
<P>
   Six bays of the Bridgemarket hall are a Food Emporium. Three
bays have been turned into Guastavino's restaurant, operated by Sir
Terence Conran and Joel Kissin.
</P>
<P>
   It was designed by Conran &AMP; Partners and Hardy Holzman Pfeiffer
Associates. But not too much. ``A space like this is so phenomenal
that the least intervention is the best,'' said the architect Hugh
Hardy.
</P>
<P>
   In picking a name, Kissin said, Guastavino's seemed a good
choice because it established a connection with the site and also
resonated with Quaglino's, the name of a Conran restaurant in
London. ``The one question was whether people would think it's
Italian,'' Kissin said. ``The funny thing, of course, is that he's
Spanish.''
</P>
<P>
   At a recent meeting under the vaults it seemed only fair that as
Kissin talked about architecture, Pamela Loeffelman of Hardy
Holzman Pfeiffer could make a suggestion about cuisine.
</P>
<P>
   ``You'll have to have tilefish,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
LIFE IS LOOKING UP &QC;
</P>
<P>
   A free map of 233 Manhattan buildings on which the Guastavinos
worked can be obtained by sending a self-addressed business-size
envelope, with 55 cents postage, to: Department of Drawings and
Archives, Avery Architectural Library, 1172 Amsterdam Avenue, MC
0301, Columbia University, New York, N.Y. 10027. Call Furthermore,
the publication program of the J.M. Kaplan Fund, (518) 828-8900.
</P>
<P>
   ``Vertical tours'' are given on the first and third Saturday of
every month at noon and 2 P.M. at the Cathedral of St. John the
Divine. The cost is $10. Reservations are required, and can be made
by calling (212) 932-7347. Comfortable shoes are a good idea; you
will be climbing 124 feet.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
