u f BC-GAP-RESIGN-NYT &LR;      03-02 0394
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GAP-RESIGN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KEY OFFICER AT GAP RESIGNS TO BE CHIEF OF WAL-MART.COM  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By LESLIE KAUFMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Jeanne Jackson, the Gap executive who is credited with building
the Banana Republic division into a retail powerhouse and who
started the Gap's online store, has resigned to become the new head
of Wal-Mart.com.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement of her departure was made after the market
closed on Wednesday. Shares of Gap declined $3.625 Thursday, or 7.6
percent, to $44.25, in part on the news of Jackson's departure but
also on a report that Gap's sales in stores open at least a year
were up 4 percent, at the low end of expectations.
</P>
<P>
   More significant, sales at the Gap division, which have been
lackluster, fell 1 percent to 3 percent; the consensus among
analysts had been for an increase of 3 percent to 4 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson is widely seen as a talented executive who helped define
Banana Republic as a leading seller of sleek urban apparel. During
her five years leading the division, sales grew to $1.8 billion a
year from $650 million, according to Dana Cohen, an analyst at
Donaldson, Lufkin &AMP; Jenrette. ``Over the time period she ran the
business, it had a dramatic turnaround and became an important
leading-edge fashion business and sales and margins increased
substantially,'' Cohen said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the Gap is such a well-run organization that several
stock analysts argued that Jackson was replaceable. ``The way the
Gap works, Mickey is the king of vision,'' said Richard Baum, a
retail analyst at Credit Suisse First Boston, referring to Millard
Drexler, the Gap's highly regarded chief executive. ``The people
running the businesses are still today executing his vision. He is
keeper of the brands.''
</P>
<P>
   By her own account, Jackson has spent about 50 percent of her
time over the last year building up Gap Inc. Direct, the division
that handles Gap's Internet store and the Banana Republic catalog.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, Jackson will have her hands full in developing
Wal-Mart.com. Although Wal-Mart Stores Inc. is perhaps the most
efficient competitor in the business on land, its Web site has been
criticized as cumbersome.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't even begin to give you the to-do list; I am not
there,'' Jackson said in an interview. But she acknowledged, ``I
know as a shopper I could wish for easier navigation.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
