<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-02 22:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5118 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-AT-THE-MOVIES-NYT &LR;      03-02 1154
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AT-THE-MOVIES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEWS OF THE SILVER SCREEN 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By RICK LYMAN    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; The Urge To Branch Out &LR;
</P>
<P>
   HOLLYWOOD _ Albert Brooks is on the sidewalk outside a bright
green house in West Hollywood, staring between the bars of a metal
gate toward a middle-aged woman with a broom. ``I can't see your
eyes, Albert,'' shouts his director, Christine Lahti, from her seat
behind the video monitor.
</P>
<P>
   The way the camera is placed, Brooks has to obscure his face
behind the bars to be looking into the eyes of the actress with the
broom. Lahti, who is making her feature-film directing debut with
the project, ``My First Mister'' (after winning an Oscar for the
first short film she directed,``Lieberman in Love,'' in 1995),
tries to decide what to do. Should the camera be moved? A lot of
time and trouble. Perhaps Brooks should move slightly to the left.
He takes a step. No, not enough. He takes another step. Oops, a
little too far. He inches back. ``Perfect,'' Lahti says.
</P>
<P>
   The problem is, Brooks is now staring at metal bars and can no
longer see the face of the actress opposite him. Can he finish out
the scene performing to a pair of metal bars? ``OK,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Lahti smiles. ``Albert, you're a trouper!'' she calls out, then
shakes her head. ``I wouldn't do it,'' she says. ``I can't act to
metal. I need two eyes.''
</P>
<P>
   People in Hollywood are often simultaneously maintaining an
image and reinventing themselves. And that was part of what was
happening on this scraggly residential street off Melrose Avenue.
Brooks, largely known as the star of his own quirky films, would
very much like audiences and studio executives to realize that he
is more versatile than that, that his critically praised supporting
role in Steven Soderbergh's ``Out of Sight'' was no fluke. And
Lahti, a veteran actress who has distinguished herself on Broadway,
in films that include Bill Forsyth's ``Housekeeping'' (1987) and on
television series like ``Chicago Hope,'' would like to be seen as a
director of feature films.
</P>
<P>
   ``My First Mister'' is the story of a 49-year-old clothing store
owner (played by Brooks) who crosses paths with a young Melrose
Avenue hipster (Leelee Sobieski). They overcome their differences
and are drawn together by the loneliness they have in common.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been trying for a long time to act more,'' Brooks said.
``I'd like to be able to dig my teeth into something. I'd like to
play a lot of things. Whatever. The villain. The crazy person who
cuts people's heads off. I can do that. I really can. I think what
I need is two or three good roles, one right after the other, to
make people see that. With luck, this will be the first step.''
</P>
<P>
   A short while later, Lahti was working her way through a salad
in her trailer. ``I knew this was going to be challenging,'' she
said. ``But I guess I didn't realize quite how fulfilling it would
be.''
</P>
<P>
   Lahti said she had looked through dozens of feature-length
scripts right after winning the Oscar but couldn't find anything
she wanted to direct. ``Fortunately, I'm in a position where I
don't have to do something; I can afford not to,'' she said. ``And
I am married to a director, so I know how difficult and
all-consuming the job can be. I didn't want to take that much time
unless it was a story that I had to tell.'' (Her husband, Thomas
Schlamme, has directed dozens of television episodes, including,
recently, the pilot of ``The West Wing.'')
</P>
<P>
   Finally this script, which is by Jill Franklyn, came to her, and
the film was shot at various Los Angeles locations in 29 days.
Next, Lahti said, she would like to go back to Broadway, although
she hasn't found the right play yet. And then maybe direct again,
if she can find something.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to be a director for hire,'' she said. ``But if
another good script were to come along ... ''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Nine-Yard Formula &LR;
</P>
<P>
   The No. 1 movie in America for two weeks in a row has been a
modestly budgeted gangster comedy called ``The Whole Nine Yards.''
Since the film stars Bruce Willis and is being released widely by
one of the major studios, Warner Brothers, with a prominent
director, Jonathan Lynn (``My Cousin Vinny''), many people may not
realize what a relative shoestring operation it was.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was not at all an expensive movie to make, and we were able
to shoot it in 35 days,'' Lynn said. ``This was possible only
because we rehearsed it quite thoroughly before we began
shooting.''
</P>
<P>
   What is also not readily apparent to audiences is that despite
the Warner logo, the film was actually fully financed by a new
company called Franchise Pictures, whose chairman, Elie Samaha, has
burst on the Hollywood scene in the last year and carved out deals
with some of the biggest names in Hollywood, including Willis, John
Travolta and Sylvester Stallone. Franchise's ambitious slate of
pictures, most of which are to be distributed through Warner
Brothers, are only now beginning to hit theaters.
</P>
<P>
   Travolta will be seen in one Franchise project this summer,
``Battlefield Earth,'' and Stallone will be seen in another, ``Get
Carter.'' It is Franchise's plan to hire top names, offer them
lower-than-normal salaries but potentially lucrative profit-sharing
deals, and then make the movies economically. If all the films do
as well as ``The Whole Nine Yards,'' it is a model others will soon
be copying.
</P>
<P>
   ``With this film, there was a budget and a shooting schedule,
and we were all very clear that this was never going to change,''
Lynn said. ``I didn't mind that. It made everyone very intense and
concentrated. It was actually very fun.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; A Kung Fu Fan &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Forest Whitaker will be one of the alien villains in
``Battlefield Earth,'' but before that he is starring as a
samurai-obsessed hit man in Jim Jarmusch's ``Ghost Dog: The Way of
the Samurai,'' which he discussed over a plate of pancakes and
vegetarian sausage at a health food restaurant in West Hollywood.
</P>
<P>
   ``I started studying martial arts when I was a kid, growing up
in South Central L.A.,'' Whitaker said. ``I used to carry around
this beat-up paperback called `The Wisdom of Kung Fu.' Even before
that, when I was really young, in East Texas, I remember seeing
some of those early kung fu movies at the local drive-in.''
</P>
<P>
   So he had some definite ideas for ``Ghost Dog,'' he said. For
one thing, there had to be at least one really good kung fu scene.
</P>
<P>
   Whitaker, whose Spirit Dance Productions employs 14 people in
West Hollywood (and is about to open a new office in London) and
has projects in the works for television series and feature films,
met Jarmusch when he went to pick up some film stock at a technical
house. The two agreed that they would like to work together
someday. It's the kind of thing people say all the time. ``But he
called in about a year and said he had this idea,'' Whitaker said.
``And it was perfect.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
