<HEADLINE>
PLANS FOR MEXICAN SALT PLANT ARE CANCELED  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ Yielding to pressure from environmental groups,
the government and Mitsubishi of Japan canceled plans Thursday to
build a giant salt factory at a pristine Pacific Coast lagoon.
</P>
<P>
   The campaign to block the proposed plant at Laguna San Ignacio,
a spawning ground for the gray whale set in a breathtaking Baja
California desert, galvanized an unusually broad coalition of
environmental groups, generating petitions by prominent scientists
and a boycott against Mitsubishi products.
</P>
<P>
   President Ernesto Zedillo said he had decided not to go forward
with the $100 million project even though an environmental study
released Thursday by the salt company, owned jointly by the Mexican
government and Mitsubishi, showed that the plant would not harm the
whales.
</P>
<P>
   Zedillo said there was a risk that the project, which would have
paved the desert around the lagoon with huge evaporating pools,
could ``alter the landscape'' that Mexico wanted to preserve.
</P>
<P>
   A Mitsubishi executive, James E. Brumm, said the company was
convinced that it could not predict the plant's effects on the
surroundings.
</P>
</TEXT>
