A5125 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-THEATER-REVIEW-NYT &LR;      03-02 0691
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THEATER-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`SUENO': WHEN LIFE IS NOT A DREAM BUT AN UNENDING NIGHTMARE  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By D.J.R. BRUCKNER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In ``Sueno'' (Dream), Jose Rivera stands on its head
a Spanish theatrical masterpiece about the traps sprung on a person
plodding through the complexities of life as if in a dream. In
Rivera's play _ produced by the MCC Theater under Lisa Peterson's
direction _ the audience is caught in the dream, in which a parade
of bondage, rape, torture, mutilation, murder, treason and civil
war, accompanied by the music and rhythms of flamenco, arouses the
uneasy laughter of confusion.
</P>
<P>
   Rivera calls his work a translation and adaptation of ``La Vida
Es Sueno'' (Life Is a Dream), written by Pedro Calderon de la Barca
around 1638. In Calderon's story a king, warned by astrologers that
his son will be a raging maniac, imprisons the baby in a tower,
with but one human contact, an old guardian (Yusef Bulos, whose
sure grip on a complicated character often seems to hold this play
together). After 25 years he frees the captive, only to find that
he may have made his son the monster he feared. A subplot brings in
a woman in armor seeking vengeance on her unknown father, who
abandoned her mother before she herself was born.
</P>
<P>
   Calderon, a superb poet with deep psychological insights,
explored astonishingly modern concerns: an intellectual elite
manipulating nature, determinism undermining free will, child abuse
producing criminality, men subjugating women. His play should
translate easily into captivating present-day theater. That does
not happen here. It is as though Rivera was hesitant about the
Calderon play, unwilling to simply translate it (heroic labor in
itself), or send it up, or lift it into modern times in a modern
voice.
</P>
<P>
   Instead we get the old play with distracting moments of odd
comedy and with characters wise-cracking in current cliches that
make them seem singularly vacant. At the climax, when the king's
son (John Ortiz, a formidable presence who never fuses the untamed
savage and the awakening world citizen that are combined in this
character) realizes that his liberty gives him the moral freedom to
be just rather than vengeful, he says, ``I've won a great victory
over myself today.'' No wonder viewers giggle nervously. Another
character calls ``Sueno'' ``this tortured soap opera.'' At least
someone is awake.
</P>
<P>
   In the end the comic moments, most of them supplied by three
people, deserve their applause even when they seem out of place.
David Greenspan as the cowardly companion of the female knight
makes high camp the way of wisdom, albeit shatteringly shrill
wisdom. James Urbaniak as a witless duke who wants to usurp the
throne turns the movements of a dancer and the eye of a mime into
body language that makes every remark a tickling lie.
</P>
<P>
   The face of Rebecca Wisocky, as the duke's greedy sister, lets
you see her mind turn 180 degrees away from comprehension of her
lines even as she speaks them. When she wants to express deep
emotion she can turn her spine into something like an accordion, a
trick that produces equal gasps of laughter and disbelief _ perhaps
the best response to ``Sueno.''  &QL; 
PRODUCTION NOTES: &QL; 
`SUENO'  &QL; 
By Jose Rivera; directed by Lisa Peterson; sets by Riccardo
Hernandez; costumes by Anita Yavich; lighting by Christopher
Akerlind; original music/sound design by Fabian Obispo; flamenco
instructor, Gloria Marina; fight director, Rick Sordelet; original
guitar music by Aaron Gilmartin; production manager, Rob Conover;
production stage manager, Lisa Gavaletz. Presented by MCC Theater,
Robert LuPone and Bernard Telsey, artistic directors; William
Cantler, associate artistic director. By special arrangement with
the Hartford Stage Co. in Manhattan. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   With: Geno Silva (Basilio), Yusef Bulos (Clotaldo), Ken Parker
(Servant), Michi Barall (Rosaura), David Greenspan (Clarin), John
Ortiz (Segismundo), James Urbaniak (Astolfo), Rebecca Wisocky
(Estrella), Sam Wellington (1st soldier), Lorenzo Gregorio, Parker,
Jeremy J.H. Seymour and Wellington (guards, servants, soldiers and
rebels).  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-02-00 2216EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
