<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-02 22:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5142 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-REPUBS-ADS-2TAKES(TRI     03-02 1164
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REPUBS-ADS-2TAKES(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GATHER STEAM
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.Y., Ohio, Calif., Va., Texas) 
BUSH AND McCAIN TRADE BITTER CRITICISM AS CAMPAIGNS IN NEW YORK (rk) 
 By ADAM NAGOURNEY and RICHARD PEREZ-PENA   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   John McCain and George W. Bush head into New York Friday to
begin personally campaigning in a state whose primary seems likely
to help determine their fate, after setting a bitter stage Thursday
with a harsh round of exchanges about the way each man is trying to
win the White House.
</P>
<P>
   McCain, in particular, seemed angered over a tough new round of
attacks Bush and his New York supporters launched this week in
anticipation of next Tuesday's primaries. They portrayed the
Arizona senator as anti-New York and as an opponent of breast
cancer research.
</P>
<P>
   ``My message is, Governor Bush, get out of the gutter,'' McCain
said in Los Angeles. ``Let's stop this kind of campaign.`
</P>
<P>
   McCain campaign aides were also infuriated by a political
commercial that popped up on television stations in New York, Ohio
and California. The ad labels its sponsor as ``Republicans for
Clean Air,'' _ a group that the McCain campaign contended was a
front for Bush, which would violate campaign finance laws.
</P>
<P>
   In a news conference and later on his campaign bus, McCain
returned repeatedly to what he described as the negative nature of
the Bush campaign, and asserted that he would risk getting pulled
into a back-and-forth argument about campaign tactics.
</P>
<P>
   At one point on the bus, McCain cited one of his campaign
strategists, Mike Murphy, declaring, ``There's a famous Murphy
saying, which he stole from somebody: `When you wrestle with a pig,
you both get dirty and the pig likes it.'''
</P>
<P>
   Bush, in his own brief meeting with reporters, raised questions
about the temperament of his opponent, repeatedly using the word
``angry'' to describe McCain. ``Mr. McCain is running an angry
campaign,'' Bush said. ``And I'm going to talk about how to make
the education system better.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush's press secretary, Karen Hughes, dismissed McCain's
suggestion that the Bush campaign had resorted to low-road tactics.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a habit in this campaign,'' she said. ``Every time
someone disagrees with Senator McCain on a substantive policy issue
he vilifies, he begins calling them names.''
</P>
<P>
   As the two main Republican contenders quarreled in California,
Bush's two main New York supporters _ Mayor Rudolph Giuliani and
Gov. George Pataki _ turned on each other in an ever-more-public
quarrel over how Bush should take on McCain's challenge. Pataki and
his advisers have counseled Bush to run an aggressive campaign, and
as his surrogates, they have attacked McCain over votes he has
taken in Congress that might hurt him with New York voters.
</P>
<P>
   But Giuliani, who has shown no shyness during his political
career over such attacks, including in his current race for Senate
against Hillary Rodham Clinton, has demurred in this case, refusing
to participate Thursday in a news conference attacking McCain. His
campaign manager, Bruce J. Teitelbaum, said the mayor would avoid
these kind of events and criticized the governor's tactics.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't comprehend why it's so difficult for some people to
understand that the mayor has made a principled decision not to
engage in negative attacks against John McCain,'' Teitelbaum said.
</P>
<P>
   Zenia Mucha, Pataki's chief political adviser, responded: `I am
puzzled about how the Giuliani administration could perceive that a
senator's voting record isn't something that should be looked at
and carefully examined.''
</P>
<P>
   The atmosphere that was evident as the candidates prepared for
the final weekend of campaigning before next Tuesday's vote was
charged by the orchestrated attacks Bush made on McCain's voting
record, in radio advertisements, a television commercial and
mailings.
</P>
<P>
   And it was heightened by the purchase of air time in New York,
Ohio and California by the clean-air group, which McCain's campaign
said was a ``shadow organization'' operating with the approval of
Bush's campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's advisers denied the contention, although records show
that the firm that bought the television time in New York,
Multi-Media Services Corp. of Virginia, has a long record of
working with Pataki.
</P>
<P>
   In placing the advertisements, Republicans for Clean Air
provided a post office box in Virginia as its address. That box is
also the address of a political action committee led by Rep. Henry
Bonilla of Texas, a close Bush ally. Lydia Meuret, the executive
director of Bonilla's committee, said Thursday that she owned the
box and that she was a consultant to Republicans for Clean Air. But
she said there was no connection between Bonilla and the group that
bought the ad.
</P>
<P>
   The commercial, which praises Bush's record on clean air while
criticizing McCain's, prompted irate responses from
environmentalists who said it distorted the truth.
</P>
<P>
   At one point the commercial says that as governor of Texas, Bush
``led one of the first states in America to clamp down on old
coal-burning electric power plants.'' But environmentalists said
the program was voluntary and ultimately ineffective.
</P>
<P>
   Larry Rockefeller, a prominent Republican environmentalist in
New York, said, `` George W. Bush has probably one of the worst
environmental records of any governor in the nation.''
</P>
<P>
   Republicans for Clean Air was unknown to the Federal Elections
Commission and to political professionals in both parties. It has
no telephone listing in New York state or Washington and has no Web
site.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Rick Davis, McCain's campaign manager, said the commercial
violated federal rules requiring disclosure of who is behind
political advertising, and he suggested collusion between the
sponsors and the Bush campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are questions of whether this is being done in
connection with the Bush campaign,'' Davis said, ``I call upon the
Bush campaign to explain what relationship they have with this
group and what they may have done in coordination with this
group.''
</P>
<P>
   Davis said the sponsors had bought $1.5 million worth of air
time for the ad in New York _ a large amount for a single week _
and more than $400,000 for similar commercials in California and
Ohio, which also hold their primaries on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Ari Fleischer, spokesman for Bush, said that neither the
governor nor his campaign aides knew who was behind the group.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have nothing to do with these ads, and the governor will
continue to run a campaign that unites our party and nation without
vilifying those who disagree with him,'' he said. ``The senator
keeps hurting himself by going too far on just about everything. He
keeps going on the attack against just about everything that moves.
He's only hurting himself, so we're happy to let his attack speak
for itself.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Mucha, a spokesman for Pataki, said that she and the governor
also had no knowledge of the group or its advertisements.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to two television spots touting Bush's record, there
is a radio ad, being broadcast in the New York area, attacking
McCain over breast cancer, an often hot political issue.
</P>
<P>
   The radio commercial features Geri Barish, a leader of One in
Nine, a breast cancer patients and survivors group, chastising
McCain for opposing funding for several breast cancer research and
treatment projects in New York state.
</P>
<P>
   The raw material for the ads came from McCain's own campaign Web
site, where he lists hundreds of items that he says he would cut
from the current federal budget. The site calls the projects
``wasteful, unnecessary and low-priority spending.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We're talking about what's on his Web page,'' Bush told
reporters Thursday after appearing at a charter school in Chula
Vista, Calif. ``He put on his Web page that these programs, he was
going to cut back on these programs. This is something John McCain
laid out.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain declined to discuss the charges and countercharges. ``I'm
going to do everything in my power not to get down into those
weeds,'' he said in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   The breast cancer ad is part of a strategy that Bush's New York
supporters have turned to in their efforts to stop McCain. They
contend that he has voted against spending in areas like breast
cancer research, mass transit, home heating oil subsidies and solar
energy, that are of particular interest here.
</P>
<P>
   McCain's aides countered that in many of those votes, he did not
object to the projects themselves, but the way they were approved
without being considered in committee and competing with other
projects on their merits. Instead, the items were usually inserted
into bills just before floor votes at the behest of powerful
sponsors.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-02-00 2236EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000302.0457 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-02 22:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5146 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-OIL-PRICES-1STLD-WRIT     03-02 1018
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OIL-PRICES-1STLD-WRITETHRU-540&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OIL MINISTERS AGREE PRODUCTION SHOULD INCREASE
</HEADLINE>
  (CORRECTS name to ``Ali al-Naimi'' in 6th graf; ADDS quote from
French industry minister   in 1st graf of optional trim) 
 (rk) 
 By ALAN COWELL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ With the high cost of oil and gasoline spreading alarm
through western economies, oil ministers from Saudi Arabia,
Venezuela and Mexico _ all among the world's major exporters _ met
here Thursday and agreed that production should be increased to
stabilize prices, but they declined to make firm commitments on the
timing or the amount.
</P>
<P>
   Oil market traders interpreted the absence of such commitments
as an indication that producers may not meet demands by the United
States and other oil-consuming nations for a substantial increase
in output.
</P>
<P>
   Oil prices, which have risen to nine-year highs in recent weeks
and jumped 4 percent on Wednesday, ended little changed Thursday on
the vague outcome of the oil ministers' meeting in London.The
London price of Brent crude for April delivery rose to $29.47 a
barrel before settling back to $29.22, up 10 cents. In New York,
oil for April delivery briefly rose to $32.15 a barrel before
retreating to settle at $31.69, down 8 cents.
</P>
<P>
   The Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries is to meet in
Vienna on March 27 to decide whether to increase production or to
maintain the present reduced output, as some exporters led by Iran,
Libya and Algeria are demanding.
</P>
<P>
   ``OPEC still has moderates and still has price hawks,'' said
Peter Gignoux, an oil analyst with Salomon Smith Barney here. ``We
still need to get a consensus'' for the Vienna meeting, he said.
``I think we are looking at high oil prices for a bit to come.''
</P>
<P>
   The Saudi oil minister, Ali al-Naimi, acknowledged Thursday that
``there is need for additional production. The issue is when and
how much.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Uppermost in our minds is to maintain stability in the
market,'' he said, but he refused to specify the likely scope of a
production increase. ``I think the number will be put forward when
we finish our consultation with all other members,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you are seeking the number, you are not going to get it
today,'' he told reporters. He also declined to say whether he was
aiming at a specific price level and would not comment on
suggestions that producers want oil prices in the United States to
sink below $25 a barrel. ``We are going to leave that up to the
market for now,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Delegates at the discussions here have said privately they
expect production to be increased next month by 1 million or 1.2
million barrels a day. The United States would like to see
production increase by 2 million to 3 million barrels a day.
</P>
<P>
   World oil consumption runs at around 77 million barrels per day
but, since OPEC agreed deep production cuts last March, production
has dropped to 75 million barrels a day. The shortfall of 2 million
barrels a day has tripled oil prices since December 1998, when they
had fallen to $10, the lowest in 12 years.
</P>
<P>
   Retail gasoline prices have reached an average of $1.421 per
gallon in the United States, the world's biggest oil-consumer, and
there is some expectation they will reach $2 by the summer driving
season, when demand is highest.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. energy secretary, Bill Richardson, who has just
returned to Washington after a visit to major oil producers has
called the rising prices and dwindling supplies a threat to global
economic growth.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Those views were echoed Thursday by the French industry
minister, Christian Pierret, who also warned producers that high
prices would strangle their own markets in the West. ``As far as
France is concerned, the persistence of high prices could affect
world economic growth and weigh on the inflationary pressures that
might appear,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   OPEC's production cuts are set to expire on March 31.
Historically, however, demand for oil falls in the second three
months of the year with the arrival of spring in the Northern
Hemisphere, and prices tend to weaken. That cyclical shift has
provided OPEC's hawks with the argument against increased
production.
</P>
<P>
   ``I accept that oil prices are high at the moment, but they will
fall in the second quarter when we expect demand to drop by 2.8
million barrels per day,'' said Hossein Kazempour Ardebili, an
Iranian oil ministry official. ``If we increase output while demand
is falling it will be detrimental to prices.''
</P>
<P>
   Iran has previously called for the OPEC production cuts to be
maintained through September and the official's remarks seemed to
signal continued deep division within OPEC about raising production
levels.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's clearly no decision taken yet,'' said Frederic
Lassere, an analyst at Societe Generale in Paris, who argued that
of the three oil-producers meeting here, Mexico was probably under
greatest pressure from the United States to increase output.
</P>
<P>
   Mexico is not a member of OPEC, which accounts for around one
third of worldwide oil production, but has agreed to cooperate with
the group's decision at its Vienna meeting later this month. ``An
increase in production is warranted'' because of a dramatic
increase in demand, the Mexican oil minister, Luis Tellez, said
Thursday. ``We believe there is a need for more oil in the
market,'' he said, but indicated that Mexico would prefer not to
break ranks while OPEC was seeking a broad agreement among its
members. ``We will wait to see this consensus before making our
independent decision,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The move to raise oil production won further cautious support
Thursday when Norway, another non-OPEC country that joined in last
year's production cuts, indicated that it backed a return to less
volatile prices. ``It is a goal that we should reach long-term
stability that is fair to both producing and consuming countries.
There is a danger when the price is very low and when it gets very
high,'' Marit Arnstad, the Norwegian oil minister, said in Paris
Thursday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-02-00 2240EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000302.0458 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-02 22:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5147 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-NY-MCCAIN-RURAL-2TAKE     03-02 0934
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-MCCAIN-RURAL-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
  
 McCAIN'S NEW YORK REBELS MAKE THEIR STAND IN UNPRETENTIOUS PLACES  
 (bl)  
 By DAN BARRY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   JAVA CENTER, N.Y. _ Travelers driving through the wintry brown
hills of western New York state might miss this place, technically
considered a town. Its center comprises little more than a railroad
crossing, a Roman Catholic church and the Sad Dog Saloon.
</P>
<P>
   The saloon is a roadside place, a place with a portrait gallery
of poker-playing dogs, fish-fry dinners on Fridays and a police
scanner to serenade the regulars. But lately, the Sad Dog has
become a cell of rebellion, where people hope to rattle the state
Republican leadership in Albany, 300 miles to the east, by plotting
against its chosen one, George W. Bush, in the state party's
presidential primary Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Let the word go forth: the Sad Dog is for the other guy, John
McCain. And if you need lapel stickers or want to make a round of
calls for the cause, go see that man behind the Coors Light, Thomas
Moran, a retired railroad worker, Sad Dog habitue and the 27th
Congressional District coordinator for the McCain campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``How many stickers you need?'' he shouted to one of the bar's
elder statesmen, who was immersed in his daily game of euchre.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gimme five,'' creaked the answer from behind a handful of
cards. ``My sister might want one.''
</P>
<P>
   In a way, Moran's territory _ a rural stretch of dairy farms,
vineyards and small towns south of Buffalo and west of Rochester _
seems as far removed as one can get from the Bush-McCain fight for
the state's Republican delegates. New York City and Albany, yes.
But Java Center? Where the town name is pronounced JAY-va Center,
as if to thwart confusion with some smug Manhattan cafe? Where CB
radio can disrupt the reception of the Sad Dog's television?
</P>
<P>
   But each of the state's 31 congressional districts has three
delegates and three alternate delegates for the candidates to win.
In a way, that makes the district's small towns of Arcade, Clarence
and Java Center just as important to the state Republican Party as
White Plains or Mineola. As Dan Allen, a state party spokesman,
said, ``It's like 31 special elections across the state.''
</P>
<P>
   They are especially vital to the Sad Dog candidate, that senator
from Arizona. Having lost primaries to Bush in Virginia, Washington
and North Dakota this week, McCain desperately needs to come
roaring back in the Super Tuesday primaries in 13 states, including
California, Ohio, Massachusetts _ and New York. A loss may very
well transform that McCain poster, hanging beneath the Coors Light
mirror, from statement to novelty.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all Tuesday,'' said Moran, 51, whose loss in a state
Assembly race two years ago gave him a taste of what he describes
as big-time politics. ``Tuesday's it.''
</P>
<P>
   Moran is one in a cadre of Republican rebels and newcomers who
have helped to turn next week's Bush-McCain matchup into the first
contested primary since Alfonse D'Amato challenged Sen. Jacob
Javits in 1980. There are Michael O'Sullivan, a travel agent and a
political neophyte, coordinating the effort in Rockland County, and
Seth Arluck, a lumberyard owner, working in Orange County.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Bob McNeil, the St. Lawrence County treasurer and a
normally obedient Republican, is fielding dozens of e-mails from
McCain supporters near the Canadian border.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout, the state campaign has been based in what Gerry
O'Brien, the state's political director, calls ``a ramshackle
series of offices in the St. George section of Staten Island, with
a scenic view of the ferry terminal.'' But O'Brien _ a political
consultant who worked on Larry Rockefeller's ill-fated run for the
Senate in 1992 _ said that room was recently made for a group of
advisers from McCain's national headquarters in Alexandria, Va.
</P>
<P>
   ``We call them the cavalry,'' he said, ``and are we delighted to
see them.''
</P>
<P>
   Several McCain coordinators said the David-and-Goliath feel to
the McCain-Bush fight fills them with bravado and dread. They
rejoiced when state Republican leaders gave in to charges of
bossism and granted McCain access to the ballot. But the ballot's
structure is intended, they said, to skew the contest in favor of
Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Here is why. The names of proposed delegates will appear in
large type, while the names of presidential candidates will appear
immediately below, but in small type. Since the Republican
leadership supports Bush, the familiar names of prominent party
members _ county chairmen, state senators, members of Congress _
will essentially be shouted as Bush delegates on the ballot, while
those of lesser Republican lights will be whispered as McCain
delegates.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the really big challenge for Senator McCain,'' McNeil
said. ``The delegates for Bush are generally really big names.''
</P>
<P>
   The 27th District is a case in point. The three Bush delegates
are Robert E. Davis, the Erie County Republican chairman, and two
state senators, Michael F. Nozzolio and Mary Lou Rath. Of the three
McCain delegates, Moran might be the best known because he was Java
Center's part-time supervisor and was once the chairman of Wyoming
County's board of supervisors.
</P>
<P>
   Allen, the spokesman for the state Republican Party, disputed
that contention, saying the candidates' names are easy to find. As
for having big-name delegates pitted against little-known
delegates, he said, ``It's a matter of having a message that
resonates with Republican leaders across the state, and that's why
Mr. Bush got their support.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Still, the faint whiff of droit du seigneur _ along with having
read McCain's autobiography _ drove Moran from dutifully endorsing
Governor Bush of Texas to embracing the underdog. With some words
sent in an e-mail to the McCain campaign's Web site,
www.McCain2000.com, followed by a few conversations with officials
on Staten Island, he wound up being Big John's man in the 27th.
</P>
<P>
   So empowered, Moran unilaterally declared the Sad Dog to be
district headquarters. He then invited volunteers to come today to
meet him, pick up lists of get-out-the-vote phone calls to make,
and maybe even have a beer.
</P>
<P>
   It was more of a charming offer than a serious edict. Java
Center, after all, does not even have a stoplight; it is 8 miles
from the nearest supermarket, in Arcade, and 11 miles from the
nearest movie theater, in East Aurora.
</P>
<P>
   Moran, a short, white-haired man who could pass as McCain's
younger brother, fanned out some bumper stickers and placards on a
table, ordered his usual and waited. The police scanner squawked, a
couple of regulars debated the finer points of car motors, and the
owner, Dave Hackett _ whose ever-forlorn visage gave name to his
saloon _ hovered.
</P>
<P>
   After a while, Doug Berwanger, a dairy farmer and the town
supervisor of Arcade, and Jim Schlick, the Republican commissioner
for the county board of elections, walked in and ordered beers.
Berwanger is an alternate delegate for McCain; he shoved the Arcade
phone list into a pocket of his maroon blazer. Schlick professed
neutrality, but agreed to take the Attica phone list for his wife,
an avid McCain supporter.
</P>
<P>
   Time passed. The owner scolded Moran for putting campaign
literature on a table reserved for the daily euchre game.
</P>
<P>
   Then four seniors from Clarence High School, more than an hour
away, walked in. They said their interest in the McCain campaign
stemmed from a class on government and politics. Now, they said,
they could not wait to wave signs and make calls for their
candidate. Two of them will vote on Tuesday; the other two will
turn 18 in time to vote in the general election in November.
</P>
<P>
   Moran handed them lists with a total of 1,400 phone calls to
make in Clarence, and offered some advice: ``You say something
like, `Hello, I'm Kristina, and I'm for John McCain, and I hope
you'll support us on Tuesday.'''
</P>
<P>
   ``That's easy!'' chirped one of the students, Kristina Hartzell.
Soon she and her friends were out the door, arms laden with bumper
stickers and placards.
</P>
<P>
   More time passed. Outside, a heavy rain turned the dirt parking
lot to mud. Inside, snippets of bar talk provided distraction.
Someone asked a man at the end of the bar whether he supported
Hillary. ``I'm not familiar with the man,'' he said earnestly.
</P>
<P>
   After a while, Doug Hill, 38, an elementary school teacher,
stopped by to pick up a phone list of 450 names; he had driven 40
miles from Le Roy to participate in his first campaign. Then came
Jeremiah Thompson, 21, the campaign's coordinator at the State
University at Geneseo.
</P>
<P>
   Thompson said he was devoted to a candidate who had caught his
fancy with a stint on the Comedy Central cable network.
</P>
<P>
   The beer lights in the Sad Dog now glowed all the brighter,
which meant that darkness had come. But progress had been made. The
bar owner, a bartender, two customers, and one of the euchre
players were all wearing McCain stickers.
</P>
<P>
   McCain's man in Java Center was ready to call it a night. He
ordered another beer.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
