<HEADLINE>
CHARGES EXPECTED IN ATTACK ON A WEB SITE  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By MATT RICHTEL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The FBI seized a computer two weeks ago from a
17-year-old New Hampshire resident who the Los Angeles Police
Department said Thursday night would be charged in connection with
attacks on the Web site of an antidrug organization.
</P>
<P>
   But a federal law enforcement official who asked not to be
identified said Thursday night that the teen-age hacker, who goes
by the nickname Coolio, was not a suspect in last month's attacks
on Yahoo, eBay and other major e-commerce Web sites.
</P>
<P>
   Sgt. John Pasquariello, a spokesman for the Los Angeles Police
Department, said Thursday night that Coolio, whose real name was
not released because he is a juvenile, was under investigation for
defacements on Nov. 14 and Nov. 17 of the Web site of the antidrug
organization DARE America.
</P>
<P>
   Pasquariello said that the Los Angeles district attorney's
office was preparing charges and that the teen-ager would probably
be arrested next week in connection with the DARE attack. The
organization is based in Inglewood, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   Charlie Parsons, executive director for DARE, which stands for
Drug Abuse Resistance Education, said that a person who attacked
the site on Nov. 14 and Nov. 17 left a profane message glorifying
drugs. He said the vandal signed both attacks ``Coolio,'' in the
second case writing, ``Craftily owned by Coolio..D.''
</P>
<P>
   Parsons said he had reported both attacks to the Los Angeles
police, the FBI and the Secret Service.
</P>
<P>
   A federal law enforcement official said Coolio had admitted in
writing to having been responsible for several attacks, but the
official did not specify whether the DARE attack was among them.
</P>
<P>
   The official said, however, that Coolio was not a suspect in the
attacks last month on Yahoo, eBay and Amazon.com, among others.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't think he's good for the others,'' the official said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
