<HEADLINE>
CAMPAIGN NEWS IN BRIEF 
</HEADLINE>
 (rk) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   THE DEMOCRATS
</P>
<P>
   BRADLEY'S WIFE CAMPAIGNS: In a sign of spousal and female unity,
Bill Bradley's wife, Ernestine, is expected to tour upstate New
York starting Friday with the wives of Sen. Daniel Patrick Moynihan
and the Los Angeles Lakers coach Phil Jackson. Mrs. Bradley will
visit Rochester, Buffalo and Albany with Elizabeth Moynihan and
June Jackson.
</P>
<P>
   GORE DAUGHTER RAISES MONEY: Karenna Gore Schiff, the oldest
daughter of Vice President Al Gore, raised $40,000 for her father's
presidential campaign last night at Cities, a Washington
restaurant, packing in 150 young professional Gen-Xers like
herself. She said that her generation tried to ``cultivate an
ironic detachment'' but she urged her listeners to overcome their
cynicism and support her father.
</P>
<P>
   THE SOUTH
</P>
<P>
   BUSH LEADS IN GEORGIA: Though making only one appearance in
Georgia in recent weeks, Gov. George W. Bush is well ahead of Sen.
John McCain in the state, which holds Tuesday's only Southern
primary. An American Research Group poll, conducted on Monday and
Tuesday, found Bush had the support of 62 percent of likely primary
voters and McCain had 23 percent. McCain led among Democrats and
independents, but the state will have its own Democratic primary
that day, in which Vice President Al Gore is considered a heavy
favorite over Bill Bradley.
</P>
<P>
   THE WEST
</P>
<P>
   PRIMARY CLEARED IN CALIFORNIA: The California Supreme Court
denied a request for an injunction to bar election officials from
reporting party votes in next week's presidential primary here.
That means the state's unusual two-tiered election, in which all
candidates will appear on the same ballot but only votes cast by
registered party members will apply in selecting convention
delegates, can proceed as planned. The separate partisan tally was
enacted under a law that amended a 1996 voter initiative that set
up the so-called blanket primary. Barry Keene, a former state
senator, contended that the law was unconstitutional, because it
amended a ballot initiative without voter approval.
</P>
<P>
   THE MIDWEST
</P>
<P>
   POSSIBLE RACE FOR KANSAS: Lawmakers in Kansas, who earlier this
year canceled the Republican primary in the face of a tight state
budget and what looked like a cakewalk for George W. Bush, are now
considering whether to reinstate it. The state is doing better and
the race is more competitive. ``Now we have money, and this primary
might matter,'' said Mark Parkinson, the state party chairman.
</P>
<P>
   THURSDAY'S SCHEDULES
</P>
<P>
   BILL BRADLEY: Hartford, Portland, Me., and Providence, R.I.
</P>
<P>
   GEORGE W. BUSH: Stony Brook, N.Y., and Buffalo.
</P>
<P>
   AL GORE: Jacksonville, Fla., Atlanta, Boston.
</P>
<P>
   JOHN McCAIN: New York City and Fairfield, Conn.
</P>
</TEXT>
