<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-O`LEARY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JAMES J. O'LEARY, AN ECONOMIST AND BANK EXECUTIVE, DIES AT 85  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Conn., N.C.)  By NICK RAVO   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   James J. O'Leary, an economist and a former vice chairman of the
U.S. Trust Corp., died Monday at his home in Westport, Conn. He was
85.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. O'Leary was vice chairman of U.S. Trust, a money management
company based in New York, from 1970 until 1980.
</P>
<P>
   He also served on the board of the National Bureau of Economic
Research and was its chairman from 1976 to 1980.
</P>
<P>
   Born in Manchester, Conn., on May 7, 1914, O'Leary graduated
from Wesleyan University, where he also earned a master's degree.
He received his doctorate from Duke University.
</P>
<P>
   During World War II, he taught at Wesleyan and at the Air
Navigation Flight Preparatory School in Middletown, Conn.
</P>
<P>
   After the war, O'Leary became a consultant for the Connecticut
General Life Insurance Co., taught briefly at Duke and served in
various positions with the Life Insurance Association of America.
</P>
<P>
   He was also chairman and chief economist at Lionel D. Edie &AMP; Co.
from 1967 to 1969, the year he joined U.S. Trust as an executive
vice president and economist. After his 10 years with U.S. trust,
he was an economic consultant.
</P>
<P>
   In 1992, O'Leary published the book, ``Stagnation or Healthy
Growth?: The Challenge to the United States in the '90s''
(University Press of America).
</P>
<P>
   His wife, Rita, died in 1997. He is survived by three sons,
James P., of Goshen, Conn.; Paul H., of Fairport, N.Y.; and Mark
E., of Montauk, N.Y.; a daughter, Martha E. O'Leary of Garden City,
N.Y.; and five grandchildren. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-02-00 2250EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000302.0466 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-02 22:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5160 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-CT-PATRIOTS-STADIUM-N     03-02 0633
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CT-PATRIOTS-STADIUM-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN LIEU OF PATRIOTS, HARTFORD GETS A $2.4 MILLION SETTLEMENT ON
STADIUM DEAL 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Mass.) (Eds: Story is also being filed in `s' category.) 
(DW) 
 By PAUL ZIELBAUER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   HARTFORD _ Ten months after the
New England Patriots backed out of a $375 million deal that would
have made Hartford a star in the National Football League's
constellation of football cities, Connecticut finally got some
payback Thursday.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Exactly $2,399,060.66.
</P>
<P>
   That is the amount the league wired to Connecticut Thursday
afternoon to settle an embarrassing episode for the state and Gov.
John G. Rowland, the foremost champion of the deal that evaporated
almost overnight last April. It called for the state to finance a
new stadium for the Patriots in exchange for a 30-year lease.
</P>
<P>
   The money compensates the state for costs incurred during the
preliminary stages of negotiations with Robert K. Kraft, the team's
owner, Rowland said. The amount includes $667,000 that the state
paid to study the environmental impact of a new stadium on a slice
of downtown envisioned as the site of a sweeping redevelopment
known as Adriaen's Landing.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's finality to this; the check has even been sent
directly to us,'' Rowland told reporters during a news conference
outside the governor's mansion Thursday. ``As far as I'm concerned,
this chapter of all of our lives is concluded.''
</P>
<P>
   None too soon for the governor, who suffered one of the worst
defeats of his career last April after Kraft decided to try to keep
his team in Massachusetts after all but promising to relocate to
Hartford. Kraft made his decision just three days after
Massachusetts legislators offered him a $70 million subsidy to help
build a new stadium at the team's home in Foxboro, south of Boston.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we made the best of a situation that perhaps many of
us wished might have been different, but I think it does bring
closure,'' said the state attorney general, Richard Blumenthal, one
of three Connecticut officials to sign the agreement with the NFL.
</P>
<P>
   In the 10 months since the deal collapsed, Blumenthal had been
looking into the possibility of suing the team or the league for
essentially using Hartford as leverage in Massachusetts. But any
legal action, Blumenthal said, would have been ``very costly,
time-consuming, difficult and uncertain,'' and the agreement signed
Thursday prevents the state from seeking any further remedy in
court.
</P>
<P>
   Calls to the Patriots organization were referred to the league,
which declined to discuss details of the settlement. ``We
appreciate the state's participation in the good-faith negotiations
that achieved a fair compromise of the interests of all
concerned,'' Paul Tagliabue, the league's commissioner, said in a
two-paragraph printed statement.
</P>
<P>
   One of the sticking points in the months of negotiations between
the state and the NFL was whether Kraft would be responsible for
paying any part of a settlement cost. Thursday's agreement makes no
reference to any amount the team might pay, though Blumenthal said
some of the $2.4 million settlement would probably be paid back to
the league by the team.
</P>
<P>
   Rowland noted the ``coincidental'' nature of Thursday's
announcement, coming one day before he is to introduce the state's
plans to turn the Adriaen's Landing site, still occupied by an
aging steam plant, into a shopping and entertainment mall.
</P>
<P>
   But . Rowland played down the betrayal he and many state
lawmakers felt in the weeks after their bid for the Patriots
collapsed. ``It was a risk worth taking,'' he said. ``We knew from
Day One that maybe we're being played against other states.'' Asked
if he was still angry, Rowland shrugged. ``No,'' he responded,
``and I never really was.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
