<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BELTRE TALKS DRAG ON
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   VERO BEACH, Fla. -- The progress in the Adrian Beltre
negotiations continued at a snail's pace Thursday, but both sides
agreed the finish line is, at most, probably a week away.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Boras, Beltre's agent, and Dodgers managing general
partner and CEO Bob Daly both said it was unlikely they sides would
talk about a three-year deal after the mandatory March 11 signing
date for players with less than three years experience. But during
the latest two-hour meeting, financial terms were discussed for the
first time.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we don't get this thing done by (the mandatory renewal
date), I don't think it will be done,'' Boras said. ``If it's not
completed by then, I think we have to look at this as a point of
litigation.''
</P>
<P>
   So they have nine days to negotiate a deal before major league
rules man dates the Dodgers sign Beltre. But after the fourth day
of meetings, the parties aren't expected to have significant talks
again until Monday, and a deal is not considered imminent despite
lengthy negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   Boras and Daly have met for 10 1/2 hours this week. Both
parties, considered top-flight negotiators well versed in patience,
remain optimistic. And while neither side talked about the
financial particulars of the case, Boras continues to compare
Beltre favorably to many major league players making at least $5
million.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to give the impression that we're inches away
from a deal ,'' said Daly, who's returning to Los Angeles on Sunday
night. ``We are discussing concepts, exploring new concepts. We're
not going to renew the player, we're going to wait until the
appropriate time, and hopefully by that point, we will either know
we can make a deal or we won't.''
</P>
<P>
   There is also the impending hearing of the grievance filed on
Beltre's behalf by the players association. Arbitrator Shyam Das,
who just ruled on the John Rocker case, could set a hearing date
next week. But Boras said it was unlikely Beltre's case would be
ruled on before opening day, which would create an enormous
headache for both sides.
</P>
<P>
   ``None of our discussions, in any way, have been arguing with
each other ,'' Daly said. ``There's never a date you set to stop
negotiating until the arbitrator rules. As a practical matter, I
think we should try to set (March 11) as a date we should try to
get this done.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Grapefruit League play begins today and Beltre is
expected to play third base -- without a contract. If he's injured,
Beltre is protected under the collective bargaining agreement.
Boras added that Beltre has a disability policy to guard against
injury.
</P>
<P>
   Beltre, 20, batted .275 with 15 homers and 67 RBI last season.
He's seeking free agency because the Dodgers violated baseball
rules by signing him at the age of 15.
</P>
<P>
   ``For this deal to get done you're going to have to believe
Adrian Beltre is going to be a superstar player,'' Boras said.
``The thing is, they have said he is. ...That's one major
philosophical point that allows this element to continue. When they
say that, I believe them. The question is to what level?''
</P>
<P>
   Grading Grudzielanek: After a winter of working out, converted
shortstop Mark Grudzielanek gets his first shot to play second base
under game conditions when the Dodgers begin Grapefruit League play
today. And while manager Davey Johnson said Grudzielanek could
start the season now, he's glad there's a month until the season
opener.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I was going to give him a grade over there so far, it would
be B+,' ' Johnson said. ``I was probably more proud of the work and
the effort from start to finish of him than anyone on the club last
year.''
</P>
<P>
   Odds and ends: The Dodgers signed catcher Angel Pena to a
one-year deal. He will make $210,000 with the big league club and
$82,500 if he plays in the minor leagues. ...One difference
Grudzielanek's noticed in playing second is a change in throwing
motion, and he's been icing his right arm because of tenderness.
</P>
</TEXT>
