CAMPUS-BREADTH-1-BOS -- Courses available at Harvard University are
emblematic of the variety and popularity of what's being taught at
area colleges at any given time. Robert Levin taught a class on the
Swing Era at Harvard's Saunders Theater. ``I want students to get a
real insight into the aesthetics of swing, the way they'd view a
painting in a fine arts course or read a poem in a literature
class,'' he told his audience. (Bill Greene/The Boston Globe)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT15) KINGSTON, Mass. -- March 2, 2000 --
BEEKEEPING-HOBBYISTS-BOS -- Interest in beekeeping seems to be
growing across the country. Howard Scott, who runs the Kingston bee
school, has published a small volume called ``Bee Lessons,''
describing ``the poetical wonder of bees.'' He's seen folks who
``are tired of the rat race'' discover the meditative, Zen-like
quality of this hobby rooted in nature and the outdoors. (David L
Ryan/The Boston Globe)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) NEW YORK -- March 2, 2000 -- GUASTAVINO-CEILING-2 --
Throughout New York City, Guastavino tile ceilings bespeak
meticulous craftsmanship with their intricate coursing, usually in
a telltale basket-weave or herringbone pattern. A good place to
view a Guastavino tile ceiling is above the Oyster Bar at Grand
Central Terminal. (Fred R. Conrad/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) UNDATED -- March 2, 2000 -- GUASTAVINO-CEILING-1 -- What
is most appealing about the ceilings produced in New York in the
early 20th century by the Spanish architect Rafael Guastavino y
Moreno and his son, Rafael Guastavino y Esposito, is their sublime
defiance of the rectilinear city. The tiled vaults of the new
Guastavino's restaurant, left, were built into three Queensboro
Bridge bays; a tiled staircase at St. Paul's Chapel at Columbia
University, right. (Fred R. Conrad/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) BUENOS AIRES, Argentina -- March 2, 2000 --
BUENOS-AIRES-EXHIBIT-2-B&AMP;W -- Incorporating more than 500
photographs, drawings, maps and miscellaneous ephemera, ``Buenos
Aires 1910: Memories of the World to Come,'' documents one of the
20th century's most dramatic stories of urban growth. A 1913
photograph of the Nicolas Avellaneda Bridge under construction and,
below, ``Buenos Aires in the Year 2010,'' a 1910 drawing by Arturo
Eusevi, both appear in the show at the World Financial Center.
(International Institute of Environment and Development - Latin
America/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) BUENOS AIRES, Argentina -- March 2, 2000 --
BUENOS-AIRES-EXHIBIT-1-B&AMP;W -- Incorporating more than 500
photographs, drawings, maps and miscellaneous ephemera, ``Buenos
Aires 1910: Memories of the World to Come,'' documents one of the
20th century's most dramatic stories of urban growth. A photograph,
``The Dance of the Closing of the Lorea Market,'' appears in the
show at the World Financial Center. (International Institute of
Environment and Development - Latin America/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) UNDATED -- March 2, 2000 -- AUTOS-REVIEW-2-BOS -- The
2000 Hyundai Tiburon comes with a base price tag of $13,999 and a
10-year, 100,000-mile warranty (five years bumper-to-bumper and
rust perforation). The square headlight coverage pattern, left, was
unique and offered outstanding night vision; the interior was neat,
but not luxurious. (Paul Drake/The Boston Globe)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) UNDATED -- March 2, 2000 -- AUTOS-REVIEW-1-BOS -- The
2000 Hyundai Tiburon comes with a base price tag of $13,999 and a
10-year, 100,000-mile warranty (five years bumper-to-bumper and
rust perforation). It offers unique styling, surprisingly good
handling, a neat-but-not-luxurious interior, and plenty of oomph
from the 140 horsepower produced by its 2.0-liter, 4-cylinder
engine. (Paul Drake/The Boston Globe)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) KISSEMME, Fla. -- March 2, 2000 -- BBN-ROCKER-COX-3 --
Atlanta Braves pitcher John Rocker during workouts with his team,
Thursday. Rocker arrived for spring training Thursday and began the
process of patching up his strained relationship with his coaches
and teammates. Rocker met with his teammates Thursday for a
half-hour after his suspension was reduced by baseball arbitrator
Shyam Das on Wednesday. Afterward, he addressed the media for three
minutes, reading a copy of his apology that ran in Thursday's
Atlanta Journal-Constitution. (Marlene Karas/Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) KISSEMME, Fla. -- March 2, 2000 -- BBN-ROCKER-COX-2 --
