<P>
   (NYT38) LAGUNA NIGUEL, Calif. -- March 2, 2000 -- RICH&AMP;RICHER-2
-- In a world of instant windfalls where companies go public
without ever earning a profit, two distinct classes among the rich
have emerged - the haves and the have s'mores. Dave Welsh, senior
director for corporate development at Portal Software, said he has
a stock option package worth tens of millions of dollars, but that
still doesn't place him in the filthy richest air that some of his
colleagues breath. (Marissa Roth/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT37) NEW YORK -- March 2, 2000 -- RICH&AMP;RICHER-1 -- Keeping up
with the Joneses used to mean buying a vacation home, a BMW,
perhaps, or first-class airplane tickets. But your own fleet of
planes? These days, though, even the superrich are finding that the
rules of the game are being rewritten with each stock market move.
Nelson Peltz made much of his $890 million in the '80s. ``You see
these young guys worth $3 billion to $4 billion, and you think to
yourself, 'What have I done wrong?' `` he wondered. (Ruth
Fremson/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT36) WASHINGTON -- March 2, 2000 -- PATIENT-RIGHTS --
Negotiators from the House and the Senate, meeting for the first
time, said Thursday that they were optimistic about their chances
of cutting a deal on legislation that would establish a wide range
of new rights for patients and new duties for health insurance
companies. President Clinton helped Rep. John D. Dingell take a
seat Thursday at a bipartisan rally in favor of the bill. (Shana
Raab/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT35) NEW YORK -- March 2, 2000 -- BRADLEY-2 -- With five days
to go before the do-or-die Super Tuesday primaries, Bill Bradley's
campaign has, for some supporters, taken on the aura of a noble but
silver-medal effort. Vice President Al Gore's camp is eager to
appear sensitive to Bradley's situation and wants to avoid
alienating him and his supporters at this delicate stage, Gore
aides said. Gore read ``A Friend for Little Bear'' to children at
PS 163 in Manhattan on Thursday. (Paul Hosefros/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT34) NEW YORK -- March 2, 2000 -- BRADLEY-1 -- With five days
to go before the do-or-die Super Tuesday primaries, Bill Bradley's
campaign has, for some supporters, taken on the aura of a noble but
silver-medal effort, as his poll numbers have collapsed and his
campaign continues to be overshadowed by the more dramatic
Republican race. Bradley donned a uniform and grabbed a hot dog at
Gray's Papaya in Greenwich Village on Thursday. (Nicole
Bengiveno/The New York Times) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT33) BOSTON -- March 2, 2000 -- BKN-HOLLEY-COLUMN-BOS -- By
next season, Vince Carter (at left, beating the Boston Celtics on
Wednesday with a last second three point shot) will certainly be
among the NBA's top three players. And by next season, Boston coach
Rick Pitino (at right, whose huge contract is a stark counterpoint
to his team's weak record of 78-111 over nearly three seasons) will
certainly crumble under the weight of what he calls negativity.
(David L. Ryan/The Boston Globe)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT32) DLAAT OUTPOST, Lebanon -- March 2, 2000 --
ISRAEL-LEBANON-2 -- In Israel, a debate has been raging about what
many have termed the senselessness of the chronic fighting in
southern Lebanon. Referring to ``the tragedy'' of Israel's
18-year-old involvement, Prime Minister Ehud Barak has set a
deadline of July to withdraw the troops in the context of a peace
agreement with Syria. Ori Rosenstein, 19, in the bunkroom of the
Israeli Army outpost at Dlaat, said, ``The sooner we leave, the
better.'' (Deborah Sontag/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT31) INDIANAPOLIS -- March 2, 2000 -- IND-CHURCH-TAX-2 --
Pastor Gregory J. Dixon's Indianapolis Baptist Temple is on a
collision course with the IRS, one of a small but growing number of
New Testament churches that say they are not subject to federal tax
laws requiring employers to withhold income, Social Security and
Medicare taxes from workers. Dixon, 67, said the people who work at
the church are not employees and called the money they receive
``love gifts.'' (Mary Ann Carter/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT30) INDIANAPOLIS -- March 2, 2000 -- IND-CHURCH-TAX-1 --
Facing foreclosure in a tax dispute, the Indianapolis Baptist
Temple is trying to establish what it says are its rights by
forcing the IRS to act. On Saturday, the church plans a
demonstration in downtown Indianapolis to protest the ruling, and
says it expects as many as 2,000 members and supporters to march.
(Mary Ann Carter/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT29) RIVERSIDE, Calif. -- March 2, 2000 -- CINDY-MCCAIN-3 --
Cindy McCain, at a campaign event in Riverside, Calif., on
Wednesday, is a regular on the campaign trail. Through 14-hour work
days, she is almost constantly at her husband's elbow, smiling as
she double-steps to keep up with him in crowds, and nodding at just
the right moments during the speech she has heard hundreds of
times. (Ruth Fremson/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT28) DLAAT OUTPOST, Lebanon -- March 2, 2000 --
ISRAEL-LEBANON -- In Israel, a debate has been raging about what
many have termed the senselessness of the chronic fighting in
southern Lebanon. Referring to ``the tragedy'' of Israel's
18-year-old involvement, Prime Minister Ehud Barak has set a
deadline of July to withdraw the troops in the context of a peace
agreement with Syria. An Israeli soldier rested at the Dlaat
outpost in Israel's ``security zone'' in Lebanon on Thursday. ``We
still have a mission here,'' an army spokesman insisted. (Deborah
Sontag/The New York Times) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT27) UNDATED -- March 2, 2000 -- TV-WEEKEND -- Vanessa
Redgrave in ``If These Walls Could Talk 2,'' to be broadcast
Sunday. Matchless performances soar above the movie's predictable,
agitprop writing and self-satisfied attitude. The film, about three
lesbian couples, is a sequel to HBO's 1996 trilogy about abortion,
which was far more powerful dramatically (and remains its
highest-rated original movie). (Marie W. Wallace/HBO)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT26) NEW YORK -- March 2, 2000 -- ANTIQUES-COLUMN -- It took
John James Audubon 11 years, from 1827 to 1838, to publish the 435
hand-colored, etched and aquatinted plates that were needed to
produce the four giant volumes of ``Birds of America,'' which had
been in a Scottish house since 1909 before being consigned to
Christie's. An american pelican from the leather-bound set displays
vibrant color with little deterioration. (Christie's/The New York
Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT25) WASHINGTON -- March 2, 2000 -- ART-NOTES -- Last month
the National Gallery of Art in Washington announced that it would
exhibit works from the collection of Barney A. and Pam Ebsworth,
St. Louis collectors of American art. So it comes as no surprise
that this week the gallery has received three more works from
Ebsworth's collection: Charles Sheeler's ``Classic Landscape''
(1931), is one of them. (National Gallery of Art/The New York
Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT24) GHANIKHEL, Afghanistan -- March 2, 2000 --
AFGHANISTAN-PRICES-2 -- Abdul Wahab, an opium merchant, in the
bazaar in Ghanikhel earlier this week. The Taliban militia seem to
be putting limits on the drug trade and local merchants are feeling
the effects in lower prices. (Barry Bearak/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT23) GHANIKHEL, Afghanistan -- March 2, 2000 --
AFGHANISTAN-PRICES --Khyber Gul works on his poppy field earlier
this week. The Taliban militia seem to be putting limits on the
drug trade. Afghanistan's crop of raw opium amounted to a record
5,070 tons, about 75 percent of the global yield. (Barry Bearak/The
New York Times) LITE
