<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-02 23:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5299 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-BAXTER-DEBATE03-COX     03-02 0580
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BAXTER-DEBATE03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Thrill is gone, it appears from latest debates
 &HT;    By Tom Baxter
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ For the past couple of nights the stage for the
nation's presidential debate has been one that resembles one of
those new millionaire shows, bespeaking the fact that the race has
arrived in California, and the big time.
</P>
<P>
   If politics worked the way quiz shows do, the Democratic and
Republican debates sponsored by the Los Angeles Times and CNN would
have packed the most punch of any so far.
</P>
<P>
   The enormous trove of convention delegates that will be decided
in Tuesday's primaries and caucuses across the country are by far
the biggest payoff of the nominating season.
</P>
<P>
   But much of the suspense has drained away from both races, and
these two nights lacked the electricity of the last Republican
debate before the South Carolina primary, or the Democrats' meeting
at the Apollo Theater in Harlem.
</P>
<P>
   On the Republican side, much of the debate had to do with who
had to be there. Gov. George W. Bush complained during his visit to
Atlanta that he changed plans to be in Los Angeles for the forum,
only to find that McCain would be beamed in from St. Louis.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, in the first question, was called on to give the strategic
rationale of why he is more electable than McCain, if his rival has
greater appeal to independents and Democrats. McCain, in turn, was
called on to explain how a Republican can win without the support
of religious conservatives.
</P>
<P>
   Both gave serviceable answers: Bush said there was time to win
over non-Republicans after the Republican primaries, and McCain
argued it was Jerry Falwell and Pat Robertson he attacked in his
speech Monday.
</P>
<P>
   But the passion seems to have gone out of the argument, in the
wake of Tuesday's results in Virginia, North Dakota and Washington
state.
</P>
<P>
   It was nearly an hour before there was any genuine flash of
controversy, and then the catalyst was the third man onstage: Alan
Keyes, who announced he couldn't vote for McCain because he doesn't
consider him pro-life, and then launched into a denunciation of his
views on campaign finance reform. At best, however, this just
seemed a fast-forward replay of how earlier GOP debates have gone.
</P>
<P>
   For reasons not at all clear, the Democratic debate the night
before was 30 minutes longer than the Republican forum, even though
there was one less candidate and a whole lot less to argue about.
</P>
<P>
   With no realistic hope of overtaking Vice President Al Gore,
former New Jersey Sen. Bill Bradley took the stage Wednesday, it
seemed, to give himself a graceful way out of a race that has had
its bruising moments.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast to their exchange at the Apollo, the Democrats found
little to differ on, and as the 90 minutes wore on, the list of
things they basically agree on grew long: hate crimes, racial
profiling, Al Sharpton, China and Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley seemed unable at times to resist a weary sigh at some of
Gore's chipper answers, but only in the last few minutes were the
two opponents coaxed into an argument over whether Gore ever voted
to give tax-exempt status to Bob Jones University.
</P>
<P>
   Which is a very un-California subject, anyway, and better left
for the other party to fight over.
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists, visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
