<SLUG> BC-GRITZ-KIDNAP-TRIAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MILITIA LEADER ON TRIAL OVER A CUSTODY CASE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Conn., Idaho, Texas)   (bl)  
 By DAVID M. HERSZENHORN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ENFIELD, Conn. _ On this point, at least, the prosecution and
the defense agree: On the afternoon of Sept. 30, 1996, Bo Gritz, a
former Green Beret commando and a leader of the far-right militia
movement, was sitting in a car in the parking lot of McAlister
Middle School in Suffield, Conn., a small town on the Massachusetts
border far from his favored stomping grounds in the Idaho hills.
</P>
<P>
   But in closing arguments in state Superior Court here Thursday,
the opposing lawyers offered starkly different explanations of what
exactly he was doing in the parking lot.
</P>
<P>
   According to the prosecution, he was waiting to snatch one of
two young boys he believed had been unjustly taken from their
mother in a custody dispute. Gritz (pronounced GRITES) is charged
with attempted kidnapping, conspiracy, custodial interference and
loitering.
</P>
<P>
   According to the defense, Gritz was merely trying to investigate
the situation and to use his celebrity as a syndicated radio
talk-show host and an elder in the far-right Patriot movement to
draw attention to a grave injustice: the awarding of the boys'
custody to their father, who has been accused by their mother,
Gritz and others of sexually abusing the boys.
</P>
<P>
   Bo Gritz, whose full name is James G. Gritz, and his son, James
R. Gritz, were arrested that afternoon in 1996 while sitting in a
car owned by Linda M. Wiegand, the boys' mother. She had recently
appeared on the elder Gritz's radio program. In the car, police
found photographs of the boys, a school floor plan, a class
schedule, two-way radios and other documents.
</P>
<P>
   ``Did Gritz just happen to show up at the school in the mother's
car at precisely the time school was to let out?'' the assistant
state's attorney, John H. Malone, asked the jury in his closing
argument Thursday morning. ``You can reasonably draw the inference
that what was going to happen was the crime of kidnapping.'' Malone
accused Gritz of wanting to carry out ``a rescue mission.''
</P>
<P>
   Gritz's lawyer, David Kritzman, said that the police officer who
arrested his client had been sitting in a marked cruiser, clearly
visible in the school parking lot. ``It did not make sense that my
client would try to kidnap that boy,'' Kritzman said. ``It makes no
sense whatsoever.''
</P>
<P>
   The closing arguments wrapped up a two-month trial in which
Gritz has been tried along with a co-defendant, Sheldon Robinson.
The younger Gritz will be tried separately. Robinson, a Texas
businessman and an associate of Gritz's, was charged as an
accomplice and accused of all the same crimes, except for
loitering, because he did not go to the parking lot.
</P>
<P>
   The prosecution charged that Robinson was in Suffield with Gritz
in 1996 and planned to use a private plane to get the boys out of
Connecticut. Robinson's lawyer, Wendy Doolittle, told the jury
Thursday that he had not acted secretly but had rented cars and
hotel rooms using his own name and credit card. ``This was a
businessman on a business trip,'' she said. ``He did nothing out of
the ordinary.''
</P>
</TEXT>
