r s BC-HKN-STARS-TEX     03-02 0746
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-STARS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROENICK IS WELL-HATED, UNKNOWN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JENNIFER FLOYD 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ For somebody whom nobody knows, everybody seems to
have an opinion.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of them are the same,'' Roenick said. ``They don't like
me.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah,'' Stars captain Derian Hatcher said. ``I'd say that's
accurate.''
</P>
<P>
   Phoenix's Roenick is an enigma wrapped in a riddle awash with
contradictions.
</P>
<P>
   He could score 100 points this season, yet he plays with a 1970s
Broad Street Bullies-like style.
</P>
<P>
   He exudes cockiness, brashness and machismo during games, yet
he's quite unassuming one-on-one.
</P>
<P>
   He counts the Stars' Mike Modano and Chicago's Tony Amonte among
his friends in the NHL, yet he has gone after both of them with,
let's just say, less-than-clean hits in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   ``If my mother was out there, I think I'd do the same thing,''
Roenick said. ``When you are on the ice, you have to play to win.
You can't play to make sure your buddies don't get hurt.''
</P>
<P>
   Good 'ol J.R. Just when you think you have him all figured out,
he says something that makes you realize you don't.
</P>
<P>
   Like the whole jaw-breaking thing. Roenick has to hate Hatcher,
right? Hatcher did, after all, shatter Roenick's jaw with a hit
last spring, causing him to miss the first six games of Phoenix's
first-round playoff series with St. Louis. He returned for Game 7
only to watch his team be eliminated by the Blues. He then spent
his summer vacation sipping dinner through a straw.
</P>
<P>
   So he hates Hatcher, right? Well, not exactly.
</P>
<P>
   In the first game between the Stars and Coyotes at Reunion Arena
this season, Roenick skated up to Hatcher and said, ``Stay away
from me.'' He then skated away chuckling with a huge grin on his
face.
</P>
<P>
   Hatcher said he felt awkward. Not Roenick. He loved it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do,'' Roenick admitted. ``What do you play sports for? You
play sports for rivalries. You play sports to get the better of the
better teams and players. Sometimes, you break a jaw. Sometimes,
you get your jaw broken.''
</P>
<P>
   He has had his it's-just-part-of-the-game mentality since
breaking into the league 11 seasons ago with the Chicago
Blackhawks. One time, he took a crosscheck to the face by a St.
Louis player. There was no penalty called on the play, but after
the whistle Roenick calmly skated up to the referee, spit into his
hand and extended his palm. There sat his teeth.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what scares you about him,'' Stars coach Ken Hitchcock
said. ``When the player we play against is focused, he's very hard
to play against. He seems to be able to do pretty much anything on
the ice he wants to. He's been a hard guy this year for us to play
against, very difficult.''
</P>
<P>
   The Coyotes certainly haven't been a walk in the park for the
Stars. They're in second place in the Pacific Division, five points
behind the Stars coming into tonight's game. It wasn't too long ago
that the Coyotes held the division lead, and Roenick is a big
reason why. He has a team-leading 30 goals and 38 assists in 58
games.
</P>
<P>
   So why then don't people around the league like him?
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure there are a lot of guys in this league who don't like
my style or my yapping or my crankiness,'' Roenick said. ``When I'm
done, I don't want other teams or players to say `Oh, I liked
playing against Jeremy Roenick.' You know why? That probably means
they beat me a lot. Those are the guys who are fun to play
against.''
</P>
<P>
   The Stars can say a lot of things about Roenick, and usually do.
</P>
<P>
   But nobody says he's fun to play against. They just don't like
him.
</P>
<P>
   ``To be honest, I wouldn't know him from a hole in the ground,''
Stars winger Mike Keane said. `` I just know what I've heard.''
</P>
<P>
   What's to hear? Well, let's just say that at the All-Star game,
where the unwritten rule is nobody hits anybody, Roenick was hit
three times.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the perception of Jeremy is he's a loose cannon and
he's living in the fast lane,'' Coyotes coach Bob Francis said.
``Everybody has made mistakes. It's how you come through those
mistakes. ... The perception of Jeremy isn't what he is.''
</P>
<P>
   Which is all well and good, except for the fact that Roenick
sounds like a man who doesn't really care.
</P>
<P>
   He won't exactly say it, but he kind of likes the fact that
nobody understands him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not afraid of what people really think of me,'' Roenick
said. ``What's good for Jeremy Roenick is good for Jeremy
Roenick.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
