u p BC-REPUBS-DEBATE-ART-NYT     03-02 0912
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REPUBS-DEBATE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
  
 BUSH AND McCAIN TRADE CHARGES OVER RELIGION AND POLITICS 
 (sw) 
 By TODD S. PURDUM and ALISON MITCHELL  
 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The setting was surreal Thursday night, with Gov.
George W. Bush standing at a lectern and his main opponent, Sen.
John McCain, beaming from a television monitor a few feet away. Yet
all of the bitterness of the Republican presidential race was on
full display as the rivals rehashed mutual recriminations in a
debate four days before a round of critical primaries across the
country.
</P>
<P>
   Capping weeks of acrimony, McCain stood by the phone calls that
his campaign made to Roman Catholic voters, alerting them to Bush's
appearance at Bob Jones University, while Bush once more protested
about being characterized as anti-Catholic.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted to tell people exactly what Governor Bush had
done,'' McCain said, arguing that he had not accused Bush of
``being an anti-Catholic bigot'' but simply pointed out that Bush
had waited weeks to repudiate the anti-Catholic teachings of Bob
Jones. That, he said, was ``a factual statement and one that I
stand by.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush quickly shot back, ``Yeah. I appreciate that. If you don't
think those phone calls labeled me an anti-Catholic bigot, then you
weren't paying attention to what your campaign was putting out.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The clear message,'' he added, ``was I was an anti-Catholic
bigot.''
</P>
<P>
   The charge and countercharge came even though each man started
out trying to stand above the fray and present a positive case for
himself in a debate that ranged across foreign policy, education,
gun control and abortion.
</P>
<P>
   Bush called himself ``somebody who's been a proven leader,
someone who has set an agenda, somebody who has risen above
politics.'' And McCain, who participated by way of a satellite
link-up from a studio in St. Louis, turned a question about his
characterization of leaders of the religious right as ``agents of
intolerance'' into a statement that ``ours is a message of
inclusion.''
</P>
<P>
   Alan Keyes, the third candidate, made his most pointed remarks
when he accused McCain of not vigorously opposing abortion, and
said he could never support his candidacy.
</P>
<P>
   But the testiest moments in the one-hour debate belonged to the
ongoing battle between Bush and McCain over religion and politics.
Bush once again said he regretted that he had not spoken out
against the teachings of Bob Jones University when he visited the
institution while campaigning in South Carolina last month.
</P>
<P>
   ``I talked about bringing people together,'' he said, ``so
America can achieve its greatness. I talked about lifting the
spirit and the soul of this country. I regret I did not speak out
against that school's anti-Catholic bias. I missed an opportunity.
I make no excuses. I make no excuses.''
</P>
<P>
   But then he turned on McCain and said, ``What I regret is the
politics of smearing somebody's reputation. That's what I regret.
And I don't appreciate it one bit.''
</P>
<P>
   When McCain asked for time to respond, Bush said, ``I didn't
attack Senator McCain.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain on Thursday night gave his most detailed explanation for
his sharp attacks on the Rev. Jerry Falwell and Pat Robertson by
describing how they differed with him in their views of President
Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``I voted to impeach President Clinton,'' McCain said. ``I don't
believe he's a murderer. Falwell believes that he's a murderer.
Robertson has espoused some cockamamie theories about the
Freemasons. I believe they have led some very good and wonderful
people in a message of intolerance.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain and Bush each seemed uncomfortable at times on issues of
domestic policy. Asked what he had accomplished on education across
18 years in Congress, McCain had to reach back to his years in the
House to cite his service on the House Education Committee and
spoke vaguely of ``being involved in the effort in my state for
reform in many ways.''
</P>
<P>
   The answer was so vague that the Bush campaign promptly put out
a statement mocking the answer.
</P>
<P>
   Bush seemed equally uncomfortable on gun control. Asked about
whether trigger locks on guns should be mandatory, he said, ``Ask
about education, will you?''
</P>
<P>
   Then he said that while he did not mind trigger locks, ``the
question is how do we enforce it. Are we going to have trigger lock
police knocking on peoples' doors, saying, `Show me your trigger
lock?'''
</P>
<P>
   The face-off came four days before the critical Super Tuesday
primaries in a dozen states including the powerhouses of New York
and California. All together, nearly 60 percent of the delegates
needed to win the Republican nomination will be chosen then.
</P>
<P>
   With polls showing Bush leading by nearly 2-1 among Republicans
in California and McCain pinning more of his hopes on New York, the
Republican race has become increasingly acrimonious and the debate
itself _ sponsored by CNN and The Los Angeles Times _ almost became
the victim of the rancor.
</P>
<P>
   In a week of feints and parries, McCain said he would not debate
because he had a planned a campaign schedule in New York and New
England when Bush had refused to commit. Then the senator abruptly
changed his mind and agreed to participate by satellite.
</P>
<P>
   That led Bush too to threaten to debate by satellite. But then
on the heels of his sweeping victories in Virginia, North Dakota,
and Washington on Tuesday, he said he would attend in person to
showcase his commitment to California.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
