<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-GUNS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: POSITIVE OVERTURES ON GUN CONTROL 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Friday, March 3:
</P>
<P>
   Some encouraging things are being said about the need for
stronger gun control laws in the wake of this week's fatal shooting
in Michigan of a first-grader by a 6-year-old classmate and the
rampage at two fast-food restaurants in Pittsburgh. Republican
congressional leaders, who bear responsibility for the legislative
logjam on gun control, need to listen hard. So for that matter do
the Republican presidential contenders, Gov. George W. Bush and
Sen. John McCain, who have budged little from their reflexive
anti-gun-control records.
</P>
<P>
   During the Democrats' debate Wednesday night, both candidates
expressed dismay at the incidents and reiterated support for much
tougher gun control plans than the rather modest set of measures
now stalled in a House-Senate conference committee. Former Sen.
Bill Bradley restated the bold gun control agenda that may well
turn out to be a major legacy of his campaign. Bradley has broken
an old political taboo by daring to recommend that guns be licensed
and registered, and he did so again. Vice President Al Gore, while
stopping short of Bradley's call for universal gun registration,
reaffirmed his support for a new system of photo licensing and
testing for handgun purchasers, a ban on junk Saturday night
specials and reinstatement of the three-day waiting period for all
gun purchases, which expired two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton added his voice when he appeared on the
``Today'' show on Thursday morning. He noted that despite having a
higher percentage of people in jail than other advanced countries,
America has a much higher gun death rate. ``That's because they
don't have an NRA in their country,'' Clinton explained, ``and they
take sensible steps to protect children and society as a whole.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether the Republicans who run Congress sense the public's
hunger for stricter gun laws may be known next week, when Clinton
will invite lawmakers to the White House to try to win agreement on
the package stalemated in committee. That package includes a
minimal child trigger-lock provision and a provision requiring
background checks on prospective purchasers at gun shows that the
National Rifle Association wants to weaken. Clinton will also seek
funding to speed development of personalized guns, which can be
fired only by the authorized owner. By approving this package,
Republicans can begin to show that it was not just the Democrats
who heard this week's gunshots.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-02-00 2325EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000302.0480 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-02 23:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5312 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a BC-CARDINALS-AZR &LR;      03-02 1085
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CARDINALS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STADIUM BILL HUNTS LEGISLATIVE SUPPORT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 BY NENA BAKER  
 c.2000 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
(PHOENIX) - It's third and long for a proposal that outlines
funding for a new $341 million Cardinals stadium, with time running
out in the Legislature.
</P>
<P>
   All week long, powerful lobbyists have put an NFL-style blitz on
Arizona lawmakers in hopes of winning support for a package that
includes money for tourism and Cactus League activities.
</P>
<P>
   But the plan's chances remain as iffy as the Cardinals'
late-season offense, with political obstacles littering the playing
field like a stack of downed linemen.
</P>
<P>
   As of Thursday, March 2, supporters had yet to find a sponsor,
nor had they finalized the bill's language. It's been changing day
by day as lobbyists tweak the bill in an effort to enlist votes.
</P>
<P>
   ``The largest obstacle is the perception this is just a stadium
bill, which is no longer the case,'' said Steve Betts, the
Cardinals' chief lobbyist. ``As we get around and talk to
individual legislators and explain the breadth of the package . . .
there appears to be broad support.''
</P>
<P>
   Betts, apparently, is not talking about Senate Majority Leader
Russell ``Rusty'' Bowers, R-Mesa, who takes a different view.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope it dies,'' Bowers said. ``I don't support public
financing for these big businesses. These kind of deals just rankle
people.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals and the NFL have pledged $75 million toward a
78,000-seat facility with a retractable roof. The Fiesta Bowl,
which says it needs the new facility to maintain its position in
college football's Bowl Championship Series, and other users are
expected to come up with an additional $20 million.
</P>
<P>
   But legislators are leery the stadium package could be perceived
as corporate welfare by tax-averse voters. And inside the
statehouse, Senate President Brenda Burns, R-Glendale, who has the
procedural power to block any package, is adamant that no public
money should be used to build professional sports facilities.
</P>
<P>
   The ground has gotten so rocky that Gov. Jane Hull, who started
things in November by forming a stadium task force, has distanced
herself from the plan.
</P>
<P>
   Stadium proponents must convince lawmakers _ and ultimately
Maricopa County voters, who would decide the matter in November if
it made it through the Legislature _ that the benefits of a new
stadium outweigh the plan's costs.
</P>
<P>
   To make it as attractive as possible, the package includes money
for expanding the Cactus League, with the intention of luring the
Los Angeles Dodgers and the Texas Rangers. At the same time,
tourism promotion money, earmarked for Maricopa County, would
immediately be doubled. There also is about $2 million a year set
aside for amateur and youth sports facilities.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we started on this, I never thought we would have a
proposal that benefited so many stakeholders,'' said Mike Bidwill,
Cardinals vice president and general counsel. ``With that as a
backdrop, the more people hear about it, the more they like it.''
</P>
<P>
   To pay for the package, the plan would:
</P>
<P>
   Increase hotel taxes by 1 percent in Maricopa County.
</P>
<P>
   Establish a 3.25 percent surcharge on vehicles rented in
Maricopa County by non-residents.
</P>
<P>
   Dedicate state income taxes from NFL salaries and
stadium-generated sales taxes toward the project.
</P>
<P>
   A legislative hearing on the proposal is expected; supporters
are aiming for as early as Monday. Detailed financial projections
should then be available, said Ted Ferris, Hull's chief deputy.
</P>
<P>
   He described the package as having ``very minimal'' impact on
state residents, amounting to an annual incremental cost of less
than $1 million per year over 30 years of financing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of the $341 million cost of the stadium, just $18 million is
paid by Arizona taxpayers,'' Ferris said. ``This amounts to less
than a quarter per person, per year. If you don't attend a game,
rent a hotel room or car, then you don't pay a cent.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals, with a 27-39 record over the past four seasons,
have shared ASU's Sun Devil Stadium in Tempe since moving to the
Phoenix area in 1988. They are the only NFL team playing in a
college stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Team officials say the Cards are in desperate need of their own
stadium to help them stay competitive with other NFL franchises
that increased their revenue in new facilities.
</P>
<P>
   But the team's last attempt to win approval for a new stadium
was defeated in May when Mesa voters soundly rejected a
quarter-cent sales tax to help fund a combined stadium/convention
center project. And lawmakers still are stinging from criticism
over a general sales tax increase that was used to help fund Bank
One Ballpark, the home of the Diamondbacks, which opened two years
ago.
</P>
<P>
   Stadium supporters have already backed away from a statewide
hotel and rental-car tax increase in favor of a regional tax in an
effort to make the plan more palatable _ the theory being that the
areas that would benefit economically from the stadium should foot
the bill.
</P>
<P>
   They also point out that a state Tourism and Stadium Authority
would choose the site and own the facility, even though the Cards
would retain the prized stadium-naming rights.
</P>
<P>
   Lobbyists have used a list of talking points to play up the
project's benefits, including economic benefits of $300 million a
year from events held at the new facility, and $200 million a year
from a beefed-up Cactus League.
</P>
<P>
   But such figures fail to impress Bowers, who describes the
stadium plan as ``a big burrito that's always got to be wrapped in
something.''
</P>
<P>
   ``First it was a convention center, now it's tourism, and next
it will be teacher salaries and education. The point is: Just do a
straight-up stadium,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of the proposed plan, Bowers said he'd rather slow down
a scheduled 1 percent repeal in the corporate income tax rate and
earmark the money for a stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the corporations want this baby,'' he said, ``maybe we
should have them pay for it.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
Reach the reporter at Nena.Baker(at)Arizona &QL; 
Republic.com or (602) 444-8256. &QL; 
 &QL; 
All week long, powerful lobbyists have put an NFL-style blitz on
Arizona lawmakers in hopes of winning support for legislation that
outlines financing for a new $341 million Cardinals stadium in the
Phoenix area. But the plan's chances remain as iffy as the
Cardinals' late-season offense, with political obstacles littering
the playing field like a stack of downed linemen. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
