<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-BREDAHL-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BREDAHL IS BRIMMING WITH CONFIDENCE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHN STURBIN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAS VEGAS _ Like any first-time, foreign visitor to Las Vegas,
Johnny Bredahl's weekend is slightly overbooked.
</P>
<P>
   Tomorrow night, Bredahl claims he will end the reign of World
Boxing Association bantamweight champion Paulie Ayala of Fort
Worth.
</P>
<P>
   And then Sunday, Bredahl and his wife plan to restate their vows
in one of the city's many quaint marriage chapels. Just like any
starry-eyed tourist couple from Copenhagen, Denmark.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our wedding was so perfect that we're going to take it one
more time over here,'' said Bredahl, who was married to Jacqueline
in December 1997. ``And I told my wife that I will remarry her with
my \Rtitle\S belt on.''
</P>
<P>
   A 61/2-1 betting underdog heading into the scheduled 12-rounder
at the Mandalay Bay Events Center, Bredahl was brimming with
confidence during and after the final news conference for ``Bring
on Heat. Caliente!'' yesterday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just open your eyes and open your ears, know what I mean?''
said Bredahl, 31, the European champion at 118 pounds. ``This is my
fight. This is not for Europe or nobody else. This is for me. And
I'm going to do it for me.''
</P>
<P>
   As challenger, Bredahl spoke before Ayala during the formal
portion of the Top Rank news conference and said this pay-per-view
fight was the culmination of a 12-year dream. Bredahl also reported
that he and Ayala met for the first time Wednesday night in the
resort's spa.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went down to get some tan, and he was coming out of the
steam room,'' said Bredahl, the WBA's No. 4-ranked contender. ``I
asked him if he's got some problem with the scales \Rmaking
weight\S. We just laughed. And it was just, how are you doing? We
were talking and I said, `Let's settle this in the fight. There's
no need to be enemies.'
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a nice guy. No doubt about that. But he knows after this
talk we had, he knows he's going to lose. If you have doubts, you
know it in the heart. Deep inside. I can't feel that. And then when
I saw him that night ... goosebumps. It's there. I knew it in my
heart. I am ``soooo'' confident.''
</P>
<P>
   Bredahl has claimed a number of lesser-recognized alphabet
bantamweight belts _ International Boxing Organization,
International Boxing Council, World Boxing Union _ since suffering
his only professional setback in December 1995. Bredahl was stopped
in the eighth round by Wayne McCullough in their bout for the World
Boxing Council bantamweight title, an outcome Bredahl contends was
orchestrated in favor of a popular champion.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was stopped so he could get ready for his next fight,''
said Bredahl, 45-1 with 23 knockouts. ``There was no reason, and
that's a problem in my heart. The referee just stopped the fight _
no warning, nothing at all. They took my chance away from me.''
</P>
<P>
   Staged before McCullough's rabid fans in Belfast, Northern
Ireland, the fight was the first of only two Bredahl has contested
outside of Denmark as a pro. Since losing against McCullough,
Bredahl has won 19 consecutive fights, 14 by either technical
knockout or knockout. That run of power, Bredahl said, has
coincided with his reunion with trainer Kjeld Krough, who tutored
him and older brother/retired world champion Jimmi Bredahl from
1988 to 1994.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since I got him back, it was knockout after knockout after
knockout,'' said Bredahl, whose brother is a former World Boxing
Organization junior lightweight (130 pounds) champion.
</P>
<P>
   With a family boxing background that goes back 25 years, Johnny
Bredahl said there is little he has not experienced inside the
ring. Bredahl acknowledged that Ayala has been on a roll since
scoring a 12-round decision against the formerly unbeaten Johnny
Tapia here to win the WBA title in June. That fight was selected by
``The Ring'' magazine as Fight of the Year, and Ayala was voted
Fighter of the Year for his 12-round slugfests against Tapia and
former No. 1-ranked contender Saohin Srithai Condo of Thailand in
Fort Worth in October.
</P>
<P>
   But at 5-foot-8-inches tall, Bredahl will enjoy a three-inch
height and a five-inch reach advantage against Ayala.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got two arms, two legs, just like me,'' said Bredahl.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
