<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-02 23:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5314 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-GOP-DEBATE03-COX     03-02 1247
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOP-DEBATE03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    GOP candidates break little new ground in debate
 &HT;    By Ken Herman and Mark Sherman
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ With Super Tuesday's crucial set of 13 primaries
and caucuses just four days away, Thursday night's televised debate
among the three Republican presidential candidates probably did
little to change the overall picture. There were plenty of clashes,
but no one seemed to deliver any death blows. Nor did anyone
falter.
</P>
<P>
   So after 60 minutes of tough grilling by three reporters and
accusations and countercharges by the three candidates, the
political terrain appeared unchanged: Texas Gov. George W. Bush
remains the front-runner after his stunning victories in two
primaries and a caucus this week. Arizona Sen. John McCain still
needs a strong showing Tuesday to keep his insurgent race alive.
And radio commentator Alan Keyes is an impressive orator but trails
the other two by so much that he's really not a factor.
</P>
<P>
   The debate format was unusual, with Bush and Keyes on stage in
an auditorium in the Los Angeles Times building in California, and
McCain joining by satellite from a studio in St. Louis. Bush, Keyes
and the audience watched and heard the Arizona senator on a large
screen television positioned where a third podium would have been.
</P>
<P>
   That was close enough for Bush, who after two weeks of
long-distance finger-pointing, confronted McCain about campaign
phone calls that Bush say branded him as an ``anti-Catholic
bigot.''
</P>
<P>
   Picking up on the most persistent theme of recent weeks, Bush
said he regrets not speaking out against Bob Jones University's
anti-Catholic policies when he appeared at the South Carolina
school last month. But he said McCain has misconstrued the visit in
telephone calls to voters.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I regret is the politics of smearing somebody's
reputation, and I don't appreciate it one bit,'' Bush said, ``and
the good news is: Catholics around the country are coming to my
defense.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain defended the phone calls, labeled as a ``Catholic voter
alert,'' as fair and accurate.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was straight talk because we wanted to tell people exactly
what Governor Bush had done. It did not accuse him of being an
anti-Catholic bigot, it did not say anything except that he was (at
Bob Jones University) and waited three weeks before he repudiated
it,'' McCain said. ``The fact is that was a factual and fair
statement and one that I stand by, unlike many of the phone calls
and the negative ads that are being broadcast all over
television.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush told his opponent: ``If you don't think those phone calls
labeled me an anti-Catholic bigot, then you weren't paying
attention to what your campaign was putting out, I guess, because
the clear message was I was an anti-Catholic bigot.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That's why people all over the country were wondering about my
heart for awhile. The good news is that Americans reject that kind
of politics,'' Bush said. ``The good news is we put that behind us
in 1960 with John Fitzgerald Kennedy, and Catholic leaders all
across the country are coming to my defense.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain, Bush and Keyes compete Tuesday in 13 primaries and
caucuses around the nation that will award 613 delegates, almost 60
percent of the 1,034 needed for nomination.
</P>
<P>
   Keyes provided some fire in a debate that remained civil. Asked
why his campaign wasn't catching on, he blamed a ``media blackout''
and suggested that the major broadcast networks were ignoring him
because he is black.
</P>
<P>
   ``You guys play the game, put the mask over the eyes of the
people and then ask why they don't see me,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He also said he could not support McCain, who earlier in the
campaign said it would be his daughter's decision on whether to
have an abortion if she got pregnant. Keyes said he could not
support a candidate who is not pro-life and that McCain's answer
proves he supports abortion.
</P>
<P>
   Near the end of the debate, McCain and Bush clashed on campaign
finance reform.
</P>
<P>
   Bush said he supports unlimited contributions from individuals,
with instant disclosure.
</P>
<P>
   ``The best reform policy is to say individuals can give and we
ought to have instant disclosure on the Internet,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   A few minutes after that, McCain said Bush's ``description of
campaign finance reform is one of the most bizarre that I have
experienced.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain also questioned the practice of allowing some of Bush's
big contributors, his ``pioneers,'' to spend the night in the
Governor's Mansion in Austin, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   But Bush responded that the people who have spent the night have
been his longtime friends, and in some cases, his relatives.
</P>
<P>
   Then Bush went on the attack suggesting that McCain's pledge to
reduce the influence of special interests by breaking the so-called
iron triangle of lobbyists, big money and legislation does not
square with his own campaign fund-raising practices.
</P>
<P>
   ``You talk about the iron triangle and you're ringing it like a
dinner bell with all those fund-raisers in Washington, D.C.'' Bush
said.
</P>
<P>
   Given another chance to respond, McCain said, ``If' I'm ringing
the dinner bell, you've got both feet in the trough because you've
raised five times the amount of money in Washington that I have.''
</P>
<P>
   At earlier debates, Bush and McCain frequently talked of each
other as friends. Now, as they trade negative ads, the friendship
has definitely cooled. Thursday's war of words began before Bush
and McCain hooked up for the evening event.
</P>
<P>
   McCain is hot about a Bush radio ad, airing in New York, noting
that he opposed two breast-cancer research projects as ``garden
variety pork.'' The ad features a New York woman who has had breast
cancer and says she will not vote for McCain because ``we deserve a
candidate with a record on women's issues we can trust.''
</P>
<P>
   ``My message is, Governor Bush get out of the gutter,'' said
McCain. ``I have strongly supported breast cancer research.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he opposed cancer research money when it was tacked onto
military spending bills he believed lacked sufficient pay hikes for
military personnel.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are literally taking bread out of the mouth of military
families. We've got 12,000 enlisted people on food stamps. We need
to take care of them,'' McCain said. ``The funding for breast
cancer research obviously should come out of the appropriations for
health and human services.''
</P>
<P>
   But McCain said he does not plan to respond in kind to Bush's
aggressive ad.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to do everything in my power not to get down into
those weeds,'' McCain said. ``When you wrestle with a pig, you both
get dirty and the pig likes it.''
</P>
<P>
   In Chula Vista, Calif., where he spoke at a charter school, Bush
defended the ad as accurate, though it does not mention McCain's
support for other breast-cancer measures.
</P>
<P>
   ``It sounds like Senator McCain is becoming increasingly angry
as the campaign goes on,'' said Bush. ``We're talking about what's
on his Web page.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain's campaign Web page includes the breast cancer programs
among ``garden variety pork'' projects he has opposed.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's schedule seems to indicate he has no plans to drop the
issue. He will stage a ``leadership forum on breast cancer
awareness'' today in Stony Brook, New York.
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists, visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
