<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCCAIN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MCCAIN CAM PAIGN STRUGGLES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 BY KRIS MAYES  
 c.2000 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
LOS ANGELES _ John McCain tried to get his Straight Talk Express
back on the high road Thursday, March 2, amid complaints that his
campaign has become bogged down in its preoccupation with tactics
and by McCain's criticism of religious conservatives.
</P>
<P>
   McCain, who is fighting for his political life in the days
remaining before the Super Tuesday primaries, tried to absorb the
blame for three rocky days that resulted from statements he made
against leaders of the Religious Right.
</P>
<P>
   He has also had to handle internal bickering over his decision
to stay out of or to attend Thursday's, March 2, debate that nearly
led to the resignation of one of his top lieutenants.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday afternoon, McCain remained steadfast in his criticism
of certain leaders of the Religious Right but admitted he had
allowed the campaign to momentarily spin out of his control.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've made a lot of mistakes in this campaign primarily
because we haven't got the most brilliant candidate. But one of the
things we are going to try to do is keep it on the issues,'' McCain
told reporters at a press conference in East Los Angeles. ``I am
going to try to keep it on the issues and not get bogged down in
this tit-for-tat kind of thing.''
</P>
<P>
   It has been a trying week for McCain, beginning with his speech
on Monday, Feb. 28, lacerating Christian religious leaders Pat
Robertson and Jerry Fallwell as divisive and intolerant.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, Feb. 29, McCain made comments aboard his campaign
bus suggesting that certain elements of the religious conservative
movement were ``evil.'' That prompted a McCain supporter, former
presidential candidate Gary Bauer, to ask for an apology from
McCain for his remarks and touched off a fusillade of questions
from reporters.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, McCain was forced to put down rumors that his
national communications director, Dan Schnur, was resigning over
McCain's original decision to forgo the California debate. And to
top it off, McCain's team was reeling from Tuesday's shutout in the
Washington, North Dakota and Virginia contests.
</P>
<P>
   McCain said that if the campaign has sagged in recent days, it
``might be because we have gotten too involved in the process,
about who is doing what commercials.''
</P>
<P>
   But McCain stood defiantly behind his comments about religious
conservatives.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to make a strong statement about the direction of the
party,'' McCain said. ``Are we going to be reformist, inclusionary,
expansionist? Or are we going to be less inclusionary, to say the
least, and suffer electoral defeats? That statement needed to be
made.''
</P>
<P>
   One top aide to McCain said that the recent turbulence in the
campaign was a temporary condition and that the operation has been
righted.
</P>
<P>
   ``Campaigns are like this,'' said Ken Kachigian, McCain's top
adviser in California. ``You have to take each day at a time.
Sometimes, the dialogue in the campaign is a little different than
you would like it to be.''
</P>
<P>
   But with the campaign headed back to the Northeast, where McCain
will stump in New York, Massachusetts and Connecticut, Kachigian
said the campaign is ``back on track.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got five days until election day, and we're headed in
the right direction,'' Kachigian said.
</P>
<P>
   McCain did his best to return to the issue that has been the
cornerstone of his campaign by reminding a group of largely Latino
voters in East Los Angeles that he favors setting aside much of the
projected budget surplus to keep Social Security afloat and to pay
down the debt.
</P>
<P>
   But two new ads attacking McCain, one by the campaign of Texas
Gov. George W. Bush and another by an independent environmental
group, made it difficult for McCain to stay on message. Even at the
press conference where he insisted he was back to issues, McCain
lashed out at his opponents' ads.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unfortunately, Governor Bush has decided to again take the low
road on the issue of breast-cancer research, alleging that I am
opposed to it. I voted many, many times in favor of breast-cancer
research,'' McCain said.
</P>
<P>
   He was referring to the Bush ad running in New York that
criticizes McCain for including breast-cancer research money on a
$13 billion list of ``pork barrel'' spending. &QL; 
 &QL; 
John McCain tried to get his campaign back on track Thursday after
a difficult three days in which he was frequently on the
defensive. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
