<HEADLINE>
CAP DEAL SAVES STATE $700 MIL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 BY SHAUN MCKINNON  
 c.2000 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
(PHOENIX) - Arizona ended a seven-year legal battle with the
federal government Thursday, March 2, over how much the state owes
for construction of the $4.7 billion Central Arizona Project.
</P>
<P>
   The Central Arizona Water Conservation Board voted, 12-1, to
approve a settlement with the U.S. Bureau of Reclamation that over
the next 50 years will reduce the state's CAP debt and save Arizona
taxpayers as much as $700 million.
</P>
<P>
   The landmark decision lays the groundwork for final resolution
of a host of other critical water issues, too.
</P>
<P>
   The state will give up 200,000 acre-feet of CAP water, 13
percent of the canal's total annual capacity. The federal
government will use that water to help settle longstanding disputes
with several Indian tribes. The tribes, in turn, could lease the
water to some of Arizona's fastest-growing cities.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement also signals a change in the way the state
allocates its most precious natural resource. Farmers will slowly
lose the cheap and abundant water the CAP has offered for more than
a decade as the state moves to ensure long-term supplies for its
urban areas.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have had a mammoth financial dispute with the federal
government, and that's a scary thing,'' said board member Grady
Gammage, one of the settlement's architects. &QL; 
 &QL; 
The Central Arizona Water Conservation Board voted, 12-1, Thursday,
March2, to approve a settlement with the U.S. Bureau of Reclamation
that over the next 50 years will reduce the state's CAP debt and
save Arizona taxpayers as much as $700 million. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
