<DOCNO> NYT20000302.0486 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-02 23:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5321 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w BC-GUN-CONTROL-HNS &LR;      03-02 0954
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GUN-CONTROL-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GUN-CONTROL BID TO BE RESURRECTED 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JOHN C. HENRY 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Outraged by deadly shootings this week, President
Clinton and congressional leaders agreed Thursday to meet next week
to revive gun-control legislation lying dormant in Congress for
almost eight months.
</P>
<P>
   While still sharply divided over restricting weapons sales at
gun shows, congressional Republicans and Democrats indicated
agreement was likely on requiring trigger locks for guns in the
wake of the shooting death of a Michigan first-grader Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Apparently the child who was killed was killed by another with
a stolen gun,'' Clinton told reporters in the Oval Office. ``If we
had child trigger locks on all guns, it wouldn't have happened.''
</P>
<P>
   The meeting, set for Tuesday, is aimed at raising public
discussion about guns in the United States, Clinton said. Twice
this week, Clinton has interrupted speeches on other topics to
complain about lack of action by Congress and opposition to the
legislation by the National Rifle Association.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe this tragic death will help,'' the president said
Thursday, referring to the shooting death of a 6-year-old girl by a
classmate using a stolen .32-caliber semiautomatic pistol.
</P>
<P>
   The president's call for action, and talk of compromise on
Capitol Hill, was fed by public outrage over the killing of Kayla
Rolland, who was shot while in class at Mount Morris Township,
Mich. The next day, a gunman fatally shot two men and wounded three
others at fast-food restaurants near Pittsburgh.
</P>
<P>
   ``What are we waiting for, more of these deaths?'' said Sen.
Barbara Boxer, D-Calif.
</P>
<P>
   Wrapped inside a bill to crack down on juvenile crime, the
stalled gun-control measure would require background checks on all
gun show sales, prohibit violent juvenile offenders from ever
owning guns, ban high-capacity ammunition clips and require that
all guns be sold with childproof trigger locks.
</P>
<P>
   Although the White House is pushing for the legislation to pass
intact, sentiment was growing among Democrats and Republicans to
separate the child safety lock issue and schedule a quick vote.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll take whatever we can get _ gun shows, clips, safety
locks,'' said Senate Minority Leader Tom Daschle, a South Dakota
Democrat. ``We have sat paralyzed now for a year.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Anything's possible. I'm open to compromise,'' said Rep. Henry
Hyde, an Illinois Republican who chairs the House Judiciary
Committee.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's an old saying: `If you can't get dinner, get a
sandwich','' Hyde said, adding: ``Our challenge is to navigate
between the two extremes on this issue and the gun show provision
in particular.''
</P>
<P>
   The Senate last year included the gun provisions in a juvenile
justice bill, but the House stripped the gun-control measures from
the legislation. The last meeting between House and Senate members
trying to reach a compromise was in early August.
</P>
<P>
   Hyde said new laws will not prevent gun deaths.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were 17 federal laws and, I think, 16 state laws that
were violated at Columbine and they didn't stop that,'' Hyde said,
referring to the April 20 attack by two armed students at Columbine
High School in Littleton, Colo. Fifteen people, most of them
students, were shot to death.
</P>
<P>
   Republican House Speaker Dennis Hastert blamed Democrats for the
lack of action on gun control, saying they walked away from
negotiations. Republicans in August agreed to legislation that
included child safety locks and other restrictions but did not go
as far as Clinton wanted in background checks at gun shows.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope the House Democrat leadership drops its obstructionist
tactics and agrees to work with us to pass common-sense gun
legislation,'' said Hastert, R-Ill.
</P>
<P>
   Regarding gun show sales, Republicans agreed to a 24-hour delay
in obtaining a gun to give authorities time to do a background
check on the purchaser, with an additional two days if the
``instant'' check raises questions.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats are pushing for a three-day waiting period, which
would end most gun show sales. Gun shows normally are held on
weekends and are only one- or two-day events.
</P>
<P>
   The president, who also wants gun buyers to be licensed, blamed
the impasse on the pro-gun lobby, headed by the National Rifle
Association.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think most Americans have any idea what a stranglehold
the NRA has had on this Congress,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview on the NBC ``Today`` show Thursday, Clinton said
13 children are killed with guns every day in America, a rate nine
times higher than the world's 24 largest countries combined.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's because they don't have an NRA in their country and
they take sensible steps to protect children and society as a whole
from people having guns who shouldn't have them, doing things they
shouldn't do with them,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   NRA spokesman Bill Powers said the group supported the GOP
compromise that would have required safety locks, instant gun-show
checks and other provisions. But, he said, Clinton insisted on
restrictions that even some key Democrats revolted against.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president's comments are simply not true,'' Powers said.
</P>
<P>
   Wayne LaPierre, NRA executive vice president, said Clinton and
most congressional Democrats are pushing the legislation ``as a
safety-lock bill and gun-show-check bill when actually what it is
is a phone-book volume of federal regulation that only hits the
law-abiding, not the criminal.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all just politics,'' LaPierre told The Associated Press.
``It has nothing, in my opinion, to do with making America safer
and that's sad.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY XXXX &QL; 
$$$
</P>
</TEXT>
