<HEADLINE>
REPRIEVE FOR HOUSTON TV STATION 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By   BILL CARTER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Lee P. Brown, the mayor of Houston, stepped in to prevent a
scheduled shutdown of the ABC television station Thursday by
announcing that he had won an agreement from ABC and Time Warner's
cable unit to extend their contract in Houston for seven days.
</P>
<P>
   The two companies have been locked in a bitter dispute over the
transmission rights to the station. Brown said he had won an
agreement for a seven-day ``cooling off period'' during which he
hoped serious new negotiations could take place.
</P>
<P>
   ABC has demanded concessions to allow Time Warner's cable
systems to continue carrying ABC-owned stations. The concessions
included a fee of 70 cents a subscriber for the Disney Channel, as
well as the addition of two other Disney-owned channels, the Soap
Opera Channel and Toon Disney, to Time Warner's system.
</P>
<P>
   ABC had charged Time Warner with refusing to negotiate. Time
Warner accused ABC of reneging on a previous deal.
</P>
<P>
   ABC had already extended its deals with Time Warner by a month
in other locations, like New York City, but had said it would
terminate the transmission rights in Houston as of Thursday night
at midnight. That would have removed the ABC station, KTRK, in
about 650,000 homes in Houston. ABC had started offering to pay for
some viewers to install satellite dishes to receive the station.
</P>
<P>
   Time Warner executives have accused ABC and its parent, Walt
Disney Co., of trying to extort an agreement that would cost Time
Warner $100 million.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
