<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-METEORITE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: THE STORY OF A METEORITE 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Friday, March 3:
</P>
<P>
   In the history of the Willamette Meteorite, there are at least
two memorable photos. The first shows the meteorite in Oregon,
resting on a rough sledge made of logs, its inertia almost
palpable. The second shows the meteorite chained to a heavy dray,
about to be unloaded at the American Museum of Natural History in
1906. Somehow, it looks even heavier in New York. Since 1935 the
Willamette Meteorite, the largest ever found in the United States,
has been housed in the Hayden Planetarium. Now it is mounted
beneath the Hayden Sphere in the new Rose Center for Earth and
Space.
</P>
<P>
   But last week, just as the Rose Center first opened, the
Confederated Tribes of the Grand Ronde Community in Oregon asked
the museum to turn the meteorite over to them. They say that when
it still lay in the hills southeast of modern Portland, the
meteorite was an important object of tribal culture. They argue
that it falls under the Native American Graves Repatriation and
Protection Act, which is designed to restore historic Native
American artifacts in museums to the tribes themselves.
</P>
<P>
   The Museum of Natural History has gone to court to legally
establish its ownership of the meteorite based on a clear
succession of title back to 1855, when the land on which the
meteorite rested was obtained by treaty. In 1905 the Oregon Supreme
Court settled the question of ownership in favor of Oregon Iron and
Steel, which sold it to the Museum of Natural History.
</P>
<P>
   It is easy to sympathize with the members of the Grand Ronde.
But the museum has a very strong legal case, based largely on the
clear descent of ownership and some important limitations in the
Native American Graves Repatriation and Protection Act that protect
rightfully established owners. The museum also has a very strong
ethical case. The Willamette Meteorite is a celestial object with a
history that includes all of us _ the Grand Ronde as well as the 50
million people who have seen it since it first came to New York.
Because it was once part of a planet and embodies a record of
violent forces in the universe, the Willamette Meteorite still has
much to contribute to science, especially now in a new era of
planetary discovery. It belongs to us all, and is best left in the
custody of the museum. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-02-00 2350EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000302.0491 </DOCNO>
