<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERS-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAKERS HAVE PLENTY IN RESERVE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The Lakers didn't just reclaim their place as the
NBA's top team this week. They gave the league another four reasons
to worry that they are on top for good.
</P>
<P>
   Those reasons are Robert Horry, Derek Fisher, Rick Fox and Brian
Shaw.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers - no longer just the Shaq, Kobe and Rice show - are
winning games on bench strength. Over the last five games of their
13-game winning streak, the Lakers have gotten an average of 31
points per game from their reserves.
</P>
<P>
   It was the bench that put away Vancouver on Wednesday, beat the
vaunted reserves of Portland on Tuesday and carried the Lakers
through a victory at Cleveland last week. Against the Grizzlies and
Cavaliers, the reserves played a huge role when Shaquille O'Neal
sat with foul trouble.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a shared trust and confidence that players get with
coaches and teams have with each other,'' said coach Phil Jackson,
``and I think the confidence level that they have, operating in a
system and being able to take on a game on their own is a trial
basis. And we have two examples of ourselves having to play without
Shaq in the lineup, in Cleveland and last night (against Vancouver)
for short periods of time, not extended periods of time, but we
responded very well.''
</P>
<P>
   It's a strength they'll need come playoff series time, and even
tonight, when the Indiana Pacers come to Staples Center.
</P>
<P>
   The Pacers, who lead the East, have one of the league's best
bench corps, led by Austin Croshere, Travis Best, Chris Mullin and
Sam Perkins. Croshere and Best led the fourth-quarter surge that
beat the Lakers in January.
</P>
<P>
   Horry, who is averaging 9.0 points over the last five games,
said the bench surge is a product of ``being more aggressive.... We
just have to shoot the ball. Shaq's so big down there, if we miss
it, five times out of 10 he's going to get the offensive board, so
we just try to be more aggressive and shoot the rock.''
</P>
<P>
   Streakers: Last time the Lakers played Indiana, the Pacers
snapped their winning streak at 16 games. Now they carry a 13-game
streak into tonight's game against the Pacers, but their odds of
continuing the string are better this time.
</P>
<P>
   The Pacers are a league-best 26-2 at home but under .500 on the
road.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it says something about their new building (Conseco
Fieldhouse), their fans - they have fans that are very intense and
very dedicated to their home team,'' Jackson said.
</P>
<P>
   He also speculated that aging Reggie Miller is no longer as
effective on the road, and ``they've got younger players that have
to perform on the road. That's not as easy.''
</P>
<P>
   Ouch report: Shaw is day to day after spraining his left ankle
Wednesday night. The Lakers held only a light practice, but Shaw
would have been held out of any full-speed drills.
</P>
<P>
   Fisher suffered a bruised right forearm Wednesday but is not
expected to miss any playing time.
</P>
<P>
   LAKERS vs. INDIANA
</P>
<P>
   Tipoff: 7:30 p.m., Staples Center.
</P>
<P>
   TV/Radio: Fox Sports Net; KLAC-AM (570).
</P>
<P>
   Lakers (47-11) update: No team has swept the Lakers in a series
this season, but the Pacers have a shot after beating them in
Indiana in January. The Lakers, winners of seven straight home
games, are 20-2 against the Eastern Conference.
</P>
<P>
   Pacers (39-17) update: They had won nine of their last 10 games
heading into this road trip, which began Thursday in Phoenix. Dale
Davis has a pulled left hamstring and is listed as day to day.
Austin Croshere has been starting in his place.
</P>
<P>
   - Howard Beck
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
