<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-TRINIDAD-REID-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRINIDAD-REID BOUT LACKS A PROMOTIONAL PUNCH
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By TIMOTHY W. SMITH   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAS VEGAS _ Felix Trinidad thinks he is the man. He talks as if
he is the man. He is the man in Puerto Rico. But to everyone else
he remains an enigma _ an insular figure who stays on his estate in
Cupey Alto, P.R., when he is not boxing.
</P>
<P>
   Trinidad (36-0), the WBC and the IBF welterweight champion, will
meet David Reid (14-0), the WBA superwelterweight champion, in a
12-round title bout at Caesars Palace Friday night. Both fighters
weighed in Thursday at 153 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   The fight, which will be broadcast on pay-per-view by Showtime
Event Television, should be a sold-out ratings grabber, matching
two undefeated champions in their prime.
</P>
<P>
   But the promotion has suffered. The promoter Don King alleges
sabotage from his rival, Bob Arum, who has predicted everything
from an outright cancellation to rain and sleet for the fight at
the 10,000-seat outdoor arena.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the problem with the promotion lies with the fighters.
Trinidad, 27, is not an engaging personality, and Reid, a gold
medal winner at the 1996 Olympic Games, is not a household name.
</P>
<P>
   Despite Reid's limited experience (14 fights overall and three
world championship bouts), many are saying the 26-year-old will
win.
</P>
<P>
   ``For all the writers that have participated in the poll they
know Tito is a champion, an excellent welterweight champion and he
does not need to demonstrate anything more than he already has,''
said Felix Trinidad Sr., Trinidad's father and manager.
</P>
<P>
   The fact that Trinidad and his father only speak Spanish and
must rely on an English translator has contributed to the fighter's
image not catching up to his abundant talents. Some argue that
great champions like Roberto Duran of Panama, and Julio Cesar
Chavez of Mexico, never spoke English and it did not hurt their
careers with American boxing fans.
</P>
<P>
   But Duran and Chavez emitted a fire and passion that burned down
language barriers. Trinidad lacks the magnetism of Duran and
Chavez. Trinidad's demeanor is that of a humble, young family man,
who boxes for a living. There is nothing wrong with that, but it
will never lift him to the matinee-idol status of Oscar De La Hoya,
or put him in the same financial strata.
</P>
<P>
   Trinidad, however, believes that his victory over De La Hoya
makes him the superior fighter. It is an attitude he has retained
in the negotiations for a rematch.
</P>
<P>
   ``I fought him, I beat him,'' Trinidad said. ``If he wants to
fight he must come to me and fight on my terms. It can't be the way
he wants it. It has to be the way that I want it.''
</P>
<P>
   Trinidad said last January that he was ready to make a rematch
with De La Hoya. He said a meeting was set up in New York at the
HBO offices, but De La Hoya never showed up. Lou DiBella, HBO's
senior vice president of programming for HBO/TVKO, said De La Hoya
was not supposed to be at the meeting.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he had shown up, I would have made the fight at 147
pounds,'' Trinidad said. ``The money didn't matter. I was ready to
sign. It would have been my last fight at 147 pounds. But now, it
can only be made on my terms.''
</P>
<P>
   The deal-breaker for Trinidad is the weight limit of 152 pounds.
De La Hoya does not want to fight Trinidad over 150 pounds. The
fight may never happen. De La Hoya has agreed to fight Shane Mosley
at 147 pounds on either June 10 or June 17.
</P>
<P>
   Trinidad says he is also prepared to move on. He said he does
not have anything to prove by fighting De La Hoya again. He wants
to unify the 154-pound titles, which will mean fights against
Fernando Vargas and Javier Castillejo of Spain. But first he has to
get past Reid, who lacks experience, but has incredibly fast hands
and a devastating right hand. It promises to be a great fight,
better than De La Hoya's mismatch against Derrell Coley at Madison
Square Garden last week.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know Reid and I will deal with his right hand and every
other punch he throws,'' Trinidad said. ``I hope the press
carefully observes my fight and that they watch me very closely. I
have worked very, very hard and I am going to demonstrate how great
a champion I am and how great a WBA 154-pound champion I will be.''
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
