<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-02 23:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5339 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u p BC-GOP-DEBATE-HNS &LR;      03-02 1487
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOP-DEBATE-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 
BUSH, McCAIN TRADE BARBS OVER RELIGION 
 
By CRAGG HINES 
and R.G. RATCLIFFE 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &UR; LOS ANGELES _ George W. Bush and John McCain dueled anew
Thursday night about support from conservative Christians and Roman
Catholics _ and the effect both critical constituencies may have in
the glut of primaries next week as well as the national election
this fall. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   In a nationally televised debate, Bush said McCain's attacks on
him for visiting Bob Jones University in South Carolina, a school
with strongly anti-Roman Catholic views, had backfired.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, governor of Texas, said Catholic leaders around the
country were rallying to his defense after he repudiated the
school's stance.
</P>
<P>
   McCain pilloried the visit once again by exclaiming, ``I want
the party of Abraham Lincoln, not the party of Bob Jones.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain, a senator from Arizona, also refused to back off his
caustic assessment of Pat Robertson and Jerry Falwell, two leaders
of the religious right, but he argued that their followers would
still support him in the general election if he is the Republican
nominee.
</P>
<P>
   The debate was the candidates' final joint encounter before the
glut of primaries Tuesday, the richest day of the nominating
season, in which 613 delegates _ or about 30 percent of the total _
are at stake.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Because the most important contests Tuesday are open only to
registered Republicans, McCain took pains to rule out bolting the
party if he should win more popular votes than his delegate count
reflects.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a loyal Republican,'' McCain said, promising: ``No matter
who the nominee it, I will support that nominee.'' &LR;
</P>
<P>
   McCain defended his campaign's calls to voters in some states
pointing out Bush's visit to Bob Jones University.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it was straight talk,'' McCain said, but ``it did not
accuse (Bush) of being an anti-Catholic bigot. It did not say
anything except that he was there and waited three weeks before he
repudiated'' the school's anti-Catholic views.
</P>
<P>
   Bush shot back, questioning McCain's sincerity and command of
his insurgent campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you don't think those phone calls labeled me an
anti-Catholic bigot, then you weren't paying attention to what your
campaign was putting out, because the clear message was I was an
anti-Catholic bigot,'' Bush said. ``That's why people all over the
country were wondering about my heart for a while.
</P>
<P>
   ``The good news,'' Bush said, ``is that America rejects that
kind of politics. The good news is that we put that behind us in
1960 with John Fitzgerald Kennedy, and Catholic leaders across the
country are coming to my defense.''
</P>
<P>
   Former Reagan administration official Alan Keyes, who has had
little practical political impact on the campaign and is not
expected to figure prominently in Tuesday's voting, also
participated in the debate.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Keyes, a fundamentalist conservative, asserted that he was
``the sentimental favorite'' of a majority of Republicans and
deserved votes as well as vocal plaudits. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   The Republicans' spirited exchanges were a contrast to the
largely agreeable debate Wednesday night between the Democratic
front-runner, Vice President Al Gore, and former Sen. Bill Bradley,
who seemed to be acknowledging with his low-key performance that
the prize had almost certainly eluded him.
</P>
<P>
   The debate was beamed by CNN from the headquarters of the Los
Angeles Times. McCain, who had initially backed out of the
face-off, participated by satellite hookup from St. Louis.
</P>
<P>
   Bush leads McCain in delegates, 170 to 105, with Keyes holding
five, according to The Associated Press count. The senator
acknowledged the possibly decisive nature of the voting next week.
``I think we're going to find out everything next Tuesday,'' McCain
told reporters on his campaign bus before the debate.
</P>
<P>
   Bush leads handily in California and several other states voting
Tuesday, including Ohio, according to recent polls. McCain leads in
New England. The two leading contenders are in a dead heat in New
York.
</P>
<P>
   The debate was most important for McCain, who was battling back
from a triple loss to Bush on Tuesday in North Dakota, Virginia and
Washington state as well as the fallout from his attack on
conservative religious leaders Robertson and Falwell as ``forces of
evil.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain, who has a reputation for a sharp tongue and easily
aroused temper, tried to back off the remark Wednesday, calling it
a poor attempt at humor.
</P>
<P>
   McCain said in the debate that although he had publicly
``regretted the leadership'' of Robertson and Falwell, he had
confidence he could rally their supporters if he is the nominee.
``I share their values and their goals,'' McCain said of adherents
of the religious right.
</P>
<P>
   ``They will desert, I hope, the intolerance and wrongheadedness
of Jerry Falwell and Pat Robertson,'' McCain said, accusing the men
of leading ``our party in the wrong direction.``
</P>
<P>
   McCain excoriated Falwell for arguing that President Clinton is
a murderer and Robertson for ``some cockamamie theories'' about
Freemasonry.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; In the reference to Falwell, McCain was talking about
videotapes that the evangelist sold implicating Clinton in the
death of former White House deputy counsel Vince Foster. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Bush again defended his support for the death penalty and the
record number of executions in Texas during his terms.  &UR; Bush
expressed certainty that the men and women executed during his
tenure were guilty of the crime for which they were convicted and
had been afforded full legal review of their trial and death
sentence. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Bush said he was concerned about Wednesday's federal court
order in Texas that a man held on death row for 16 years be
released. The U.S. District judge noted that the attorney for the
man, Calvin Burdine, had dozed during the trial and that the state
had missed a Jan. 27 deadline to retry him for capital murder. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Bush, indicating he believed the man was already free, said:
``I`m sorry he's out. He's a really violent man.'' He called for
the man to face a new trial quickly.
</P>
<P>
   Prison officials were given five days to release Burdine, enough
time for the 5th Circuit Court of Appeals to rule on an emergency
request for a stay the state filed Wednesday. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; On the issue of campaign finance, Bush said free-speech rights
means there should be no limits on how much money individuals can
give to political parties. But McCain said $1 million in
contributions from one individual in 1996 to the Democratic Party
resulted in questionable transfers of technology to China.
</P>
<P>
   ``Governor Bush just said he wants unlimited contributions from
individuals. Maybe that explains why there have been sleep-overs at
the Governor's Mansion in Austin by the Pioneers,'' McCain said,
referring to reports that eight of Bush's top presidential
fund-raisers have spent the night at the mansion.
</P>
<P>
   Bush retorted that those individuals were longtime friends and
relatives before they were campaign fund-raisers. He blasted McCain
for breaking his own promise to destroy the ``iron triangle'' of
money, lobbyists and legislation by holding Washington fund-raising
events.
</P>
<P>
   ``You talk about the iron triangle, but you're ringing it like a
dinner bell with all those fund-raisers in Washington, D.C.,'' Bush
told McCain.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I'm ringing it like a dinner bell, you've got both feet in
the trough because you've raised five times as much money in
Washington as I have,'' McCain replied.
</P>
<P>
   In a warm-up for the debate, Bush and McCain traded charges
earlier in the day about a new Bush commercial suggesting McCain
opposes breast cancer research.
</P>
<P>
   ``Get out of the gutter,'' McCain said. ``I have strongly
supported breast cancer research.``
</P>
<P>
   ``It sounds like Senator McCain is becoming increasingly angry
as the campaign goes on,'' Bush shot back.
</P>
<P>
   The governor said his commercial was based on an item on
McCain's campaign Web site in which the research program was part
of one cited as an example of ``everyday, garden-variety pork''
which the senator has pledged to eliminate if he reaches the White
House. ``The list includes funds for breast cancer research,'' said
Bush spokeswoman Karen Hughes.
</P>
<P>
   ``He can't have it both ways,`` McCain also complained about
commercials being sponsored by a group called Republicans for Clean
Air that attack his environmental record and laud Bush's.
</P>
<P>
   McCain suggested the group was a Bush front, but he offered no
substantiation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Praising Governor Bush's record on the environment is like
praising Bill Clinton for honesty and candor,'' said McCain
campaign manager Rick Davis.
</P>
<P>
   McCain also visited the heavily Hispanic neighborhood of East
Los Angeles to announce the endorsement of Sheriff Lee Baca, Los
Angeles County's top-ranking Republican elected official.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY XXXX &QL; 
